<HEADLINE>
LASORDA: SOSA IS MVP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ On the day the St. Louis Cardinals' Mark McGwire tied
Roger Maris' all-time single-season record with 61 home runs,
Dodgers GM Tom Lasorda cast his unofficial MVP vote for the Chicago
Cubs' Sammy Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got to be Sosa,'' Lasorda said. ``Look what Sosa has
meant to his team this season. The reward is for the most (ital)
valuable (off) player. It is the guys who is most valuable to his
team. That's what it is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   MVP voting, which is done by writers covering major league
baseball and based only on regular season contribution, is largely
subjective. But it usually is given to the player who has most
helped his team.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, the Cardinals' Lou Brock was named National League
Player of the Year by The Sporting News after stealing a then major
league record 118 bases. But the Dodgers Steve Garvey was named MVP
after taking the club to the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Colorado's Larry Walker was named NL MVP after
winning batting and RBI titles. Mike Piazza batted .362 with 40
homers, 124 RBI and a .360 average with runners in scoring
position. He also kept the Dodgers in the NL West race until the
final weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, who has 58 homers, has been critical to the Cubs' climb
from a last-place team (68-94) a year ago, to a 80-64 record and a
tie with the New York Mets for the NL wild card spot.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, who hit No. 61 in the first inning of Monday's 3-2
victory over the Cubs, has electrified the country with his pursuit
of Maris' record. But the Cardinals, pre-season favorites to win
the NL Central, have gone 70-73, 20 1/2 games behind
division-leading Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you take Sosa off that team,'' Lasorda said, ``where would
they be.''
</P>
<P>
   Park to Japan:Dodgers right-hander Chan Ho Park has agreed to
participate in the annual eight-game All-Star series in Japan
beginning Nov. 1 against a collection of all-stars from the
Japanese leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Park, who spends much of the winter in his native Korea, flies
to Orlando, Fla. on Oct. 27 for a two-day workout. He then heads to
Japan for the opening game against the world famous Yomiuri Giants.
Park will earn $83,000.
</P>
<P>
   Park also is being recruited by Korea to play for the national
team in the Asian Games, which begin Dec. 15 in Bankok, Thailand.
The Dodgers have yet to grant him permission to play.
</P>
<P>
   Quick Hits:Raul Mondesi missed his third consecutive game with
lower back soreness, but he did accompany the team to Arizona and
hopes to play tonight.
</P>
<P>
   When he returns, Mondesi will be back in right field, where he
played until the May 15 acquistion of Gary Sheffield. With
Sheffield gone for the season (sprained left ankle), manager Glenn
Hoffman decided to move Mondesi to take added strain off the back.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi also has said recently he thinks the responsibilities of
playing center have hurt his offensive production.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot to think about out there,'' Hoffman said. ``He
is still our centerfielder, no question. But I think the transition
during the season has been a drain on him. When he gets to spring
training he'll have a better idea of the responsibilities of the
position.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
