<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-BOX-OFFICE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MARY' SPURTS UP TO TOP OF BOX OFFICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Surprise hit ``There's Something About Mary''
edged ``Blade'' to post its first victory at the nation's box
office with an estimated $10.9 million at 2,555 theaters during the
Friday-Monday Labor Day weekend, studio sources said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mary,'' in a reflection of the strong word-of-mouth it
received after opening in mid-July, became the only film ever to
lead the weekend box office for the first time after eight weeks in
nationwide release. The goofy romantic comedy has grossed $130.2
million overall, and its weekend-to-weekend improvement was an
impressive 31 percent, far better than any rival.
</P>
<P>
   ``The performance by `Something About Mary' has been just
incredible,'' said Robert Bucksbaum, president of the Reel Source
tracking service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mary'' carries an estimated $24 million price tag, by far the
lowest budget among successful summer movies, and could top $175
million for 20th Century Fox by the end of its domestic run,
Bucksbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Mary' should do very well for a while since there's really
nothing out there against it,'' he said. ``Fall is the king of
dramas and thrillers.''
</P>
<P>
   Also performing impressively on the final weekend of Hollywood's
summer season was two-time box office leader ``Blade'' with $10.7
million at 2,375 theaters to move its 18-day total to $49.5 million
for New Line. Bucksbaum said the studio showed savvy in scheduling
``Blade,'' starring Wesley Snipes as a part-vampire crime-fighter,
late in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``New Line was really smart to wait until all the other summer
popcorn movies were played out,'' he said. ``It's one of the few
films right now for teen-agers and young adults.''
</P>
<P>
   DreamWorks SKG's seventh weekend of ``Saving Private Ryan''
continued its solid performance with $8.6 million at 2,807
locations to move its overall gross to $166.6 million. Bucksbaum
said the studio is certain to make a major push for ``Ryan'' during
the Academy Awards campaign season this winter, ensuring the D-Day
epic will finish well above $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Private Ryan'' is the 45th-highest domestic grosser of
all time behind ``Three Men and a Baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Sony's opening of ``Knock Off,'' starring Jean-Claude Van Damme
battling terrorists in Hong Kong, performed adequately in fourth,
with $5.7 million at 1,800 theaters. The studio acquired rights to
the action-adventure at relatively low cost and expects to generate
a profit on the project, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's sixth weekend of ``Ever After'' finished a solid fifth
with $4.3 million at 2,001 sites to push its overall take past $54
million. The ``Cinderella'' remake easily beat a pair of
disappointments in their second weekends _ Miramax's ``54'' with
$3.5 million and Warner Bros.' ``Why Do Fools Fall in Love'' with
$3.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the top 10 were Paramount's fifth weekend of
``Snake Eyes'' with $3.3 million at 1,912 sites, Fox's fourth
weekend of ``How Stella Got Her Groove Back'' with $3 million at
1,339 locations and Disney's sixth weekend of ``The Parent Trap''
with $2.8 million at 2,045 theaters. Disney's 10th weekend of
``Armageddon,'' with $2.7 million, may have also cracked the top
10.
</P>
<P>
   ``Armageddon'' has reached $192 million and ranks 26th on the
all-time domestic list after ``Indiana Jones and the Last
Crusade.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney's limited opening of ``Firelight,'' a costume drama with
Sophie Marceau as a governess seeking her out-of-wedlock child,
debuted impressively with $125,000 at 10 theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Year-to-date business is nearing $4.7 billion and is 13 percent
ahead of the same period last year. Summer business, from Memorial
Day weekend to Labor Day, topped $2.5 billion, or 12 percent up
from last summer with nine films taking in more than $100 million,
including ``Saving Private Ryan,'' ``Deep Impact,'' ``Dr.
Dolittle,'' ``Godzilla,'' ``There's Something About Mary,''
``Lethal Weapon 4,'' ``The Truman Show'' and ``Mulan.''
</P>
<P>
   Paramount's ``Titanic,'' despite having been in video stores
since last Tuesday, drew $190,000 at 447 theaters in its 38th
weekend to push its overall domestic total to $600.7 million, or
$140 million more than its closest rival. About 80 percent of
``Titanic's'' total total came during 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's Something About Mary,'' ``Blade'' and ``Saving Private
Ryan'' face competition next weekend from Miramax's opening of
``Rounders,'' starring Matt Damon as a card shark, and Disney's
family drama ``Simon Burch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
