A3030 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-REDS-HNS &LR;      09-08 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-REDS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
The Cincinnati Reds came closer to scoring off Randy Johnson than
any of the teams Johnson had shut out in his three previous starts
in the Astrodome.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But the scoreboard still reads all zeros.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson pitched a six-hitter for his fourth straight shutout at
home as the Astros labored to a 1-0 victory over the Reds before a
crowd of 42,787 on Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Astros' fourth straight win at home and their 13th in
the last 16 games at the Dome as they pulled within one game of
Atlanta for the best record in the National League. Since Johnson
was acquired, the Astros are 26-9.
</P>
<P>
   While the Astros' offense showed the effects of a long, late
haul back from Arizona following a 10-run outburst Sunday night,
Johnson was fresh and ready. He struck out 14 while extending his
scoreless-innings streak at home to 36.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a struggle. Johnson (7-1) escaped his own mistake in
the eighth inning when Brook Fordyce led off with a double and
pinch runner Pat Watkins took third when Johnson threw wildly to
first base on an appeal play.
</P>
<P>
   The stage set, Johnson took care of the next three batters _
pinch hitter Melvin Nieves, Reggie Sanders and Chris Stynes _ on
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's a close ballgame, you realize that you don't have a
lot of leeway to be giving up base hits and making big innings
happen, because that one run had to hold up,'' Johnson said. ``To
go that far and hold a quality team down like that, and then just
about throw the ballgame away _ or at least let them back in it _
it was big to get out of the inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Derek Bell provided the offense with his 19th home run, a
sixth-inning shot off Reds righthander Steve Parris (4-4).
</P>
<P>
   In four starts at the Astrodome since being acquired from
Seattle on July 31, Johnson is 4-0 with 51 strikeouts and four
walks. He has 85 strikeouts in eight starts overall. He is
responsible for the Astros' top four strikeout totals this season.
</P>
<P>
   His NL ERA is 1.00.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like his fastball went up 2 to 3 miles per hour and
his slider got sharper (in the eighth),'' first baseman Jeff
Bagwell said. ``That's what the great pitchers do.
</P>
<P>
   ``As people who have been around and seen Nolan (Ryan) and Mike
(Scott know), it doesn't matter if there is a guy at third base
with no outs. He can strike out three straight guys. That's as
impressive an eighth inning as I've ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have liked to score a few more runs and make Randy's
job a little easier. We didn't swing the bats well all day. We
didn't mount much. He made a one-run lead hold up.''
</P>
<P>
   In earlier Astrodome starts, Johnson had a pair of five-hitters
against Philadelphia and Milwaukee and a seven-hitter against
Pittsburgh. After eight NL starts, Johnson's four shutouts rank
second only to Atlanta's Greg Maddux, who has five _ in 30 starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hate to face the Big Unit. You've got to throw extremely
well when you face him,'' Parris said. ``If you give up one run or
more, there's a good chance you're going to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   After a Barry Larkin single in the first inning, Johnson retired
nine straight batters. Since Larkin was caught stealing, the Reds
sent the minimum 12 hitters to the plate through four innings.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth, Dmitri Young singled to lead off. Following
strikeouts to Jeffrey Hammonds and Bret Boone, the Reds loaded the
bases when Aaron Boone doubled and Fordyce was intentionally
walked. Parris struck out to end the threat.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Astros couldn't manage much against Parris, who
allowed four hits in seven innings and struck out seven. Parris,
who entered with a three-game winning streak, had a two-hitter
until Bell homered.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you think of the Astros, you think of Moises Alou, Jeff
Bagwell and Craig Biggio,'' Bell said. ``I just sneak in from
behind, like always.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, some people look at the scoreboard and see my numbers
and say, `Wow, this guy is swinging the bat pretty good.' I like to
sneak up because nobody pays attention to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reds were too busy paying attention to Johnson, who threw
the first 1-0 shutout against the Reds since Maddux did it Aug. 15,
1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``We normally figure if you hold a team to one run we're going
to win, but not with Randy Johnson on the mound,'' Reds manager
Jack McKeon said. ``He's at the top of his game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
