<SLUG> BC-BBO-CHASE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CHASE ENERGIZES CARDINALS
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Just like Mark McGwire, his St. Louis Cardinals
teammates have been living with the Great Home Run Chase since
spring training. They've been thrilled by the spectacle but are
relieved it's almost over.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to break this thing so he can settle down,'' catcher
Tom Lampkin said. ``It's so exciting, everybody wants him to get it
so bad. But we want to get it over with so we can get on with
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Lampkin watched the historic home run from the Cardinals' bench
and said he had thoughts of running the bases with McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is the same burst of energy for No. 62 as there was
for 61, I might jump over that (dugout) fence,'' Lampkin said.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Bobby Witt watched the home run from the bullpen and
didn't get to participate in the mob scene near the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he hits one (Tuesday), I'm coming out of the bullpen,
that's for sure,'' Witt said. ``Every one he's hit since breaking
the National League record, I get goosebumps up my arms. Today was
no exception.'' LUCKY FAN HAD FREE TICKETS
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis fan Mike Davidson's brother-in-law has two Cardinals
season tickets in the left-field bleachers. But Mike Izo gave them
to Davidson on Monday, and the 28-year-old catering manager got the
thrill of his life.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's record-tying home run caromed off the front of the
second deck Monday and fell into the bleachers where Davidson was
sitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bounced off five people's hands and rolled underneath my
seat,'' Davidson said. ``I picked it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Davidson, caught up in the generous spirit of the home run
chase, said he was giving the ball back to McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have talked about it at work, joking around what we would
want for it and everything,'' Davidson said. ``But I always figured
I would give it back to McGwire.'' EX-ATHLETICS GET HUGS
</P>
<P>
   McGwire sought out manager Tony La Russa and trainer Barry
Weinberg for special hugs. Both have been with McGwire for many
years, dating to when they were all members of the Oakland
Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   La Russa managed McGwire in Oakland from 1987-95 before being
hired by the Cardinals. Weinberg was in Oakland until last season,
then was hired by the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it, Tony gave me my start,'' McGwire said. ``I
wasn't supposed to make the team back in 1987. He decided to stay
with me and I remember the night _ it was April 1 in Anaheim _ and
he stuck with me and the next thing you know I hit 49 home runs. He
stuck with me through the year of 1991 when I hit .201.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barry and I have gone through so much through my back
injuries, through my foot injuries, the only time Barry and I have
been apart is just the two months when I was traded over here last
year. Those two guys have backed me, supported me, just been with
me since Day One in Oakland and here in St. Louis.'' McGWIRE MEETS
MARIS FAMILY
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Maris, the widow of Roger Maris, was still recovering
from heart complications experienced Friday, and did not attend
Monday's game. But McGwire did meet with her four sons after the
game: Roger Jr. 39, Kevin, 38, Randy, 37, and Rich, 34.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all thanked me and gave me a hug and I'm sure if we were
more private, it would have been a little bit more emotional,''
McGwire said. ``I said I would love to meet with them some day when
this is all over and to talk to them and basically tell them what
their father was going through at that time because it is an
amazing story.'' HOME RUN GREETING
</P>
<P>
   McGwire has hit so many home runs he has become an expert at
post-blast greetings. In Oakland, he and Jose Canseco came up with
the forearm bash, which led to the Bash Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   The current ``handshake'' in St. Louis is double high-fists
followed by an exchange of playful punches in the stomach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just started doing it,'' McGwire said. ``Everybody, you
know, is doing a fist or high-five. For some reason I just started
hitting our guys in the stomach and it's like they've got pretty
good stomachs. But we just started doing that and I don't know, it
just carried on and it's just something that people are watching
right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
