<SLUG> BC-BBO-SOSA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT PRESSURE? SOSA'S JUST HAVING FUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST.LOUIS _ Roger Maris lost his hair in clumps. Mark McGwire
confessed, only half-jokingly, he can't wait until the end of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Sammy Sosa, on the other hand, has said he's on one long
holiday, combining his pursuit of baseball's home run record with a
one-man comedy act that plays to standing room only crowds at every
stop. Even McGwire can't help but enjoy playing straight man to
Sosa's zingers.
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter spotted Androstenedione in McGwire's locker and
made it a national story last month, Sosa responded by putting a
bottle of Flintstones vitamins in his locker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure they work,'' Sosa said with that smile seen
coast-to-coast nightly on ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa arrived in St. Louis on Monday to meet McGwire head-to-head
in the home-run chase and the two actually had some fun in a joint
pregame news conference. But Sosa led the way, refusing to get
flustered even when asked if the high number of home runs hit this
year cheapened the record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish for the rest of the year I hit one cheap one every
day,'' Sosa said.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa was asked if he had ever envisioned as a child that he
would be in this position. Doing his best ``Saturday Night Live''
imitation, Sosa, again breaking into a smile, said, ``Not really
but I have to say ... `Baseball being very very good to me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But Sosa's sense of humor and easy graciousness during the
home-run chase have also made him a big hit in the United States.
Albert Belle he is not.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps in tribute to that, Monday's crowd of 50,530 at Busch
Stadium gave Sosa a standing ovation when he came to bat in the
first inning. Sosa, reveling in the moment, stepped out of the
batter's box, tipped his batting helmet and waved.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire said before Monday's game, ``Wouldn't it be great if we
ended up tied? I think it would be beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Sosa, ``What number?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Seventy is a good one,''McGwire said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will take it,'' Sosa said.
</P>
<P>
   At one point during the news conference, McGwire was talking
about all the trouble Roger Maris went through in 1961 and said,
``Hopefully the day that I die I can, after seeing the Lord, I can
see him and Babe Ruth and talk to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa broke in and said, ``Don't forget about me.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire laughed and said, ``I think you're a little younger than
me. You might come a couple years later.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire was also asked Monday what advice he would give to
children who want to be big league ballplayers. His answer seemed
to sum up what Sosa has done this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just have fun,'' McGwire said. ``Just have fun. That is all
you can do is have fun ... because it's serious enough when you get
up here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
