<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0008 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3038 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-H     09-08 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
By FRAN BLINEBURY
<TEXT>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
FARGO, N.D. _ Bill Weaver remembers those magical nights back in
the summer of 1961 when he and Rudy Maris used to sit in front of
the ticker-tape machine in his office and wait for the infernal
thing to tap out messages one letter at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Rudy was the father of Roger Maris, who was making his run back
then at Babe Ruth's home-run record, and Weaver, now retired, was a
radio and TV broadcaster who worked for the local NBC affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, it was nothing like it is today,'' Weaver said.
``You didn't have constant coverage on the radio and TV. There
weren't satellites or anything like that where you could tune in
and see the games live.
</P>
<P>
   ``Naturally, this was the biggest sports story to ever hit
Fargo, probably all of North and South Dakota. Roger was one of our
boys, and so it was the kind of thing where everybody in town
couldn't wait to get the latest news on what he did each day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the way through the season, when it was pretty clear
that Roger was going to have a chance at Ruth, I had the
ticker-tape machine installed in my office. It was our fastest link
to what was happening with the Yankees. But by today's standards,
of course, it was slow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day or night, when the Yankees were playing, Rudy and I
would sit in the office and just watch that machine go, `tick . . .
tick . . . tick' and type out when something happened or at the end
of each inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd have our chairs up there real close to the machine, and
we'd see it start to go, `tick . . . tick . . . tick . . . HR . . .
tick . . . tick . . . tick . . . NYY . . . tick . . . M . . . tick
. . . A,' and we'd be going crazy with anticipation, waiting to see
if the next letter was an R or an N. Maris or (Mickey) Mantle, you
know.''
</P>
<P>
   As soon as Rudy Maris and Weaver knew, so would all of Fargo.
Because Weaver would run from his office right into the studio, and
the TV station would break into the middle of any programming for
an update.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had made up slides to show on camera,'' Weaver said. ``You
know, 57, 58, 59, 60, 61. And we'd cut right into whatever was on
TV at the time. It didn't matter if it was an NBC network show.
Roger knocked it right off the air in Fargo. It was the most
exciting time of my 28-year career.''
</P>
<P>
   Weaver, like a lot of old fighter pilots, has trouble with his
hearing. To talk to him on the telephone, you have to play a game
of tag and use his wife as an intermediary.
</P>
<P>
   But get him warmed up on the subject of Maris, and the words
come out in spitfire fashion, like the rat-a-tat-tat of the
tailguns from those missions he flew in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver had come home from the war and settled into his radio and
TV job when he first came across the young Maris while doing
play-by-play work for the Shanley High football and basketball
teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roger was a real good athlete in both of those sports,''
Weaver said. ``He was tall enough to be a good basketball player,
and he could really run with the football. I know there are a lot
of the stories about how he might have been a great football
player. I don't know. Bud Wilkinson did offer him a scholarship to
Oklahoma. But he lasted only two weeks down there. Got a little
homesick. I don't know if he could have been a great one at the top
level of college football.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there was never much doubt when he started playing pro
baseball. I really got to know Roger in his first year in the
Northern League (with the Fargo-Moorhead Twins). He was the MVP,
and they won the league title. Not much of a doubt he'd make it
after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Little doubt, too, in the minds of longtime friends like Weaver,
that Maris was never appreciated for simply being down-to-earth and
uninterested in playing the role of an icon like Mantle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as humble as any human being I've ever met,'' Weaver
said. ``He never talked about breaking the record and was always a
great friend.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a phone call in October of 1960.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roger wanted me to come to the World Series in New York,''
Weaver remembered. ``I told him I only worked at a tiny TV station,
and I didn't think that kind of money was in the budget. He told me
there would be two plane tickets waiting for me and my wife, and
they were on him. So we spent four nights in the Manhattan Hotel,
where the Yankees were staying during the Series, and had a great
time. Then I went to pay the bill for the room and our meals, and
the desk clerk said, `You don't owe anything. It was all paid by
Mr. Maris.'''
</P>
<P>
   There was a time earlier this summer when Weaver taped an
interview with ESPN and said, ``If anybody around here told me they
wanted to see Roger's record broken, I'd have to take them in the
back alley.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the relentless charge of Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa has
turned the improbable into the inevitable, Weaver and others close
to Maris have mellowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like they say, all records are made to be broken,'' he said.
``If the record has to fall, then I'm just glad it's going to go to
McGwire or to Sosa. They are both very classy. They have both held
Roger and Babe Ruth in great respect all season long.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it goes, then the positive thing to come out of all this is
that for the past year Roger's name has been back in the headlines
in newspapers from all over the country. Instead of Fargo being
forgotten, it's like we've all been rediscovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe this will help Roger get into the Hall of Fame. There's
a new member of the veterans committee, you know. It's Yogi Berra.
So I think we have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The old fighter pilot-turned-broadcaster paused.
</P>
<P>
   ``This season has actually been a lot of fun,'' he said.
``Looking back at that year. Remembering Roger. Picturing that
perfect swing.''
</P>
<P>
   And the nights with Rudy Maris in front of that machine.
</P>
<P>
   Tick . . . tick . . . tick . . . HR . . . NYY . . . M . . . tick
. . . A . . . tick . . . R . . .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
