<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3039 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-08 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ST. LOUIS _ He pointed to the sky. He pointed to the Roger Maris
family. He pointed to his heart.
</P>
<P>
   And with that, even though it was only the first inning of a
game that was supposed to feature so many home runs, so many
records, so many cheers, there would be no more.
</P>
<P>
   It would be only No. 61 on this day. It would be only Mark
McGwire and Roger Maris, joined together for one day. It would be a
booming shot by the Cardinals slugger in the first inning and the
cheers that Maris never heard wafting down on his family and making
them feel that, yes, if the record is to be broken, it should be
done by this man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I truly believe Roger Maris is with me right now,'' McGwire
would say of the former Yankees great, who often walked alone as he
chased the record McGwire now seems sure to break. ``He's been with
me through all this. He's walking with me through this right now.''
</P>
<P>
   It was supposed to be a day when the Cubs' Sammy Sosa would
march toward history with McGwire, two sluggers hammering baseballs
into oblivion, carving a double-edged legend.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire was supposed to hit maybe one home run on this day,
maybe two, maybe three. Smash the record. Step right past Maris.
And Sosa, who has been linked at the adjective with McGwire since
early in the season _ great, super, remarkable _ would follow suit.
It was supposed to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty times already, one of these baseball giants has hit a
home run in a game, only to see the other match or better the shot
on the same day. In a game between their teams at Chicago's Wrigley
Field last month, Sosa passed McGwire in the home-run chase, only
to see Big Mac slam a pair of homers later in the afternoon to
regain the edge.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa entered Monday's game with 58 home runs, McGwire 60. Sosa
had nine homers in his previous 14 games, McGwire 13 in his
previous 19. It was McGwire and Sosa, Sosa and McGwire, a
double-edged legend in the making.
</P>
<P>
   But for one day, McGwire shared the stage not with Sosa, not
with Babe Ruth, not with anyone but Maris. McGwire seemed honored,
if not divinely touched.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really feel for what Roger Maris went through, all the
negative stuff that was going on in his life when he broke the
record,'' McGwire said. ``I wish it hadn't happened to him.''
</P>
<P>
   But it did, beginning with the misguided edict from
then-commissioner Ford Frick, who announced that unless Maris broke
Ruth's magical mark of 60 homers in 154 games or fewer, an asterisk
would be placed by his name in the record book. It was a slap in
the face. How could Maris be blamed for the extension of the season
from 154 games to 162?
</P>
<P>
   Coupled with the public's love for the legendary Ruth, Maris'
march to history consequently was not hailed and revered like
McGwire's and Sosa's, but questioned.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 1, 1961, when Maris finally hit No. 61, barely 23,000
fans attended the game at Yankee Stadium. The cheers were cordial
but not warm.
</P>
<P>
   Maris remained proud of the mark until he died of cancer in
1985, but he was a reticent, mistreated hero, a reluctant North
Dakota man who never heard the kind of cheers McGwire heard Monday,
the kind of cheers McGwire tried to share with Maris.
</P>
<P>
   ``Breaking the record never really was a fond memory for my dad
at all,'' Roger Maris Jr. said. ``That's what was disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps that is why there might be something to that special
feeling McGwire said he felt Monday, that feeling that Maris was
there with him, finally trotting around the bases to the thunder of
sincere applause.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that always bothered Maris, according to his son, was
that no one on the opposing Boston Red Sox ever congratulated Maris
when he hit No. 61 _ not when he trotted around the bases, not
after the game, not ever.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Cubs first baseman Mark Grace slapped McGwire's hand
as he trotted around; third baseman Gary Gaetti shook his hand;
Sosa, in right field, shook his fist in the air and began
applauding into his glove. Between innings, Cubs second baseman
Mickey Morandini congratulated McGwire, and after the game several
Cubs players did the same. And this on a day when Chicago's one-run
loss dropped it out of sole possession of the National League
wild-card lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a feeling of awe,'' McGwire said.
</P>
<P>
   It was a day for McGwire and Maris. As he floated toward the
dugout amid the madness after slamming the record-tying shot,
McGwire paused and looked toward the seats where Roger Maris Jr.
and his brothers and sisters sat. He pointed to the sky. He pointed
to the Maris family. He pointed to his heart.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, McGwire walked up to Roger Jr. and hugged him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roger is in my heart,'' McGwire told Roger Jr. ``I know he's
with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Maris Jr. nodded his head and bit his bottom lip.
</P>
<P>
   The only man who really knows what it is like to hit 61 home
runs in a single season, to endure the road, the scrutiny, finally
gave Maris what he deserved. He shared the day with him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
