<HEADER>
A3047 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-     09-08 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
 
THREE EX-PLAYERS TALK ABOUT McGWIRE  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Mark McGwire caught Roger Maris Monday in his Labor Day
showdown against Sammy Sosa, I decided to consult three Long Beach,
Calif., natives, Bob Bailey, Bobby Grich and Jeff Burroughs, on the
home run duel that has, blessedly, developed into a greater
national obsession than Clinton's fib about Monica.
</P>
<P>
   This trio has more than a passing interest on the subject,
inasmuch as they all had lengthy major league careers and they all
hit with power as evidenced by their aggregate total of 653 home
runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what McGwire and Sosa are doing has been phenomenal,''
said Bailey from his residence in Las Vegas. ``It's just been great
for the game. The whole country is talking baseball, and when was
the last time you can remember that happening?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just been fantastic. ... I don't think anyone has
realized that the football season has started,'' said Grich from
his home in Coto de Caza near Mission Viejo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, this has been just great for baseball,'' said
Burroughs, who still resides in Long Beach. ``I've noticed even
some of the newscasts leading off with it. It's resulted in great
publicity for the sport.''
</P>
<P>
   The three men have their theories for the recent upsurge of home
runs in their sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt the pitching is down because of expansion,'' said
Bailey, a 1961 Wilson High graduate who hit 189 home runs in his
17-year career, with a high of 28 in 1970 with the Montreal Expos.
``But in all fairness, the strike zone is a joke. The umps don't
call high strikes anymore, or inside strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can think of four reasons for the eruption in home runs,''
said Grich, a 1967 Wilson High graduate who hit 224 home runs in
his 17-year career, with a high of 30 in 1979 for the Angels.
``One, I think years of work in the weight room are paying
dividends for the players. Two, the ball is livelier. Three, the
parks are now smaller. And, four, the pitching talent is smaller.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt that the pitching is thinner,'' said
Burroughs, a 1969 Wilson High graduate who hit 240 home runs in his
16-year career, including a high of 41 in 1978 for the Atlanta
Braves. ``But I think the biggest difference is the ball. They're
now using a much livelier one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember they brought some balls over from Japan once in
spring training it was either in 1974 or 1975 and everyone was
hitting home runs. We had a game in Ft. Meyers, and a shortstop
named Eddie Brinkman, who hit about two or three home runs a year,
hit one about 475 feet over the light standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``At an Old Timer's game I participated in at the Sky Dome in
Toronto, we used juiced-up balls in batting practice, and I hit
several into the upper deck in left field.''
</P>
<P>
   So what's a juiced-up ball?
</P>
<P>
   ``The strings inside are wound much tighter,'' said Burroughs.
``The ball's just much harder, and explodes off the bat. And goes a
lot farther.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Bailey, Bobby Grich and Jeff Burroughs all marvel at the
distance so many of the home runs travel these days, including most
of the ones deposited by McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the days when I played, it was a big deal when someone
would hit a home run to the opposite field,'' said Bailey. ``Willie
Mays was the only one who did it consistently, and he was forced to
because the wind blew out to right and right centerfield at
Candlestick Park, and blew in from leftfield. Now I see little
second basemen swing late, and hit the ball into the stands in the
opposite field.
</P>
<P>
   ``The farthest I've ever seen a ball hit came at old Forbes
Field in Pittsburgh when Hank Aaron hit one over the iron gate in
rightcenterfield that was about 457 feet away. The farthest I ever
hit one was at the Houston Astrodome. I hit it into the yellow
seats in left field, about 450 feet away. A garden variety home run
for McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I played in Baltimore, center field at our stadium was
about 405 feet, and I only saw five balls make it over it,''
related Grich. ``I remember seeing Frank Robinson, Boog Powell and
Frank Howard clearing it, but that's about all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The longest ball I've ever saw hit came at old Comiskey Park
in Chicago when Dick Allen put one of Mike Cuellar's screwballs
over the roof and out of the park in left field. It had to travel
at least 475 feet. The longest ball I ever hit came at the Oakland
Coliseum. I hit it into the left field stands about 430 feet
away.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm totally amazed by the distances guys hit the baseballs
today,'' said Burroughs. ``I'm sure when a guy doesn't hit a home
run more than 400 feet now, he probably doesn't even think he hit
it well. When I played, guys just hit the ball over the fence and
that was it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, you'd see a long one once in a while. I'll never forget
the longest one I saw when Frank Howard reached the upper deck at
RFK Stadium in Washington, D.C. It was about 480 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   ``The longest ball I ever hit came at Arlington Stadium when I
was with the Texas Rangers. It came against Rollie Fingers, and
traveled about 450 feet. I got all of it. Mark McGwire seems to do
that 10 or 12 times a day in batting practice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
