<HEADLINE>
HELLING'S THREE-HIT SHUTOUT LIFTS RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON _ Manager Johnny Oates does not know whether his Texas
Rangers will be involved in either of the American League's
best-of-five, divisional playoff series. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oates, though, hinted Monday that Rick Helling likely will be
the Rangers' starting pitcher for Game 1 of that series should the
Rangers capture the AL West title and not need the right-hander for
their final regular-season game Sept. 27 in Seattle. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Helling demonstrated why during the Rangers' 6-0 victory against
the Minnesota Twins Monday at The Ballpark in Arlington. The
27-year-old became the league's fourth 18-game winner with a
three-hit, complete-game effort that ended the Rangers' two-game
losing streak. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The victory moved the Rangers within three games of the idle
Angels in the AL West and alleviated the sting of defeats Saturday
and Sunday. The Rangers entered the eighth inning of both those
games with a two-run advantage, and Oates wondered before Monday's
game which reliever would be summoned to pitch the eighth inning if
needed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess Rick Helling answered that question in big style,''
Oates said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Helling (18-7) threw a string of zeroes at the Twins until the
Rangers took advantage of two seventh-inning errors for their first
run against right-hander LaTroy Hawkins (7-14). Third baseman Luis
Alicea and center fielder Tom Goodwin later delivered run-scoring
singles in the inning, and second baseman Mark McLemore and right
fielder Juan Gonzalez capped the six-run outburst with home runs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Helling allowed six baserunners, only two of whom reached second
base, and recorded eight strikeouts during his economical,
115-pitch appearance on an afternoon in which the thermometer
registered 94 degrees at game time. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been outstanding all year,'' said first baseman Lee
Stevens, who opened the seventh inning with a leadoff double and
scored the game's first run. ``He always seems to pick us up on
days when we need it. He also kept us off the field and out of the
heat.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The heat of this title race prompted Oates to alter his rotation
to ensure that Helling and right-hander Aaron Sele pitch every
fifth day the remainder of the season. Oates finalized the plan
Wednesday in Detroit. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This is perfect,'' Oates recalled telling himself after
formulating the rotation's course for the remainder of the season.
``Helling gets an extra start, and he gets to pitch against the
Angels twice. He's also available to pitch on the final day of the
regular season if we need him. If we don't need him, he can have
the first playoff game. This is too good to be true.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Helling continues to demonstrate that he deserves to be
considered the Rangers' big-game pitcher. Helling beat the Mariners
and their former ace, left-hander Randy Johnson, in May. He beat
the Angels and their ace, left-hander Chuck Finley, twice in June.
It did not stop there. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Helling beat the Red Sox and right-hander Pedro Martinez in
August, and Monday's performance prevented a three-game losing
streak after agonizing defeats the previous two evenings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we're going to win the division,'' Oates said.
``I don't have that crystal ball, but I think today showed that
this group plays with character and integrity in spite of the
doubters and naysayers, and there are a lot of them around here.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Helling hushed such discussions at least for one September
afternoon. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Something I've prided myself on is that I've always been
healthy and durable,'' Helling said after the Rangers won for the
22nd time in his 30 starts. ``I've always had better second halves
than first halves.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers will call upon that at least three and maybe four
more times this month and perhaps again during Game 1 of a playoff
series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
