<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE COWBOYS ARE BACK? CHECK BACK IN 16 WEEKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ It was only one game.
</P>
<P>
   Such was the feeling Monday at the Dallas Cowboys' Valley Ranch
headquarters regarding the 38-10 season-opening drubbing of the
Arizona Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the rout ushered in the Chan Gailey era on a positive note
and ended the Cowboys' five-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   But as guard Nate Newton said, ``we are not going to go jump off
a building.''
</P>
<P>
   Newton cited Sunday's upcoming game against the defending Super
Bowl-champion Denver Broncos and last season's experience of
opening with a 37-7 rout of Pittsburgh only to follow with a loss
to the Cardinals en route to a 6-10 record. This time, he said, the
Cowboys are keeping everything in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just one game,'' Newton said. ``That's just one win. We
got to play an even tougher team this week. And what happened last
year should keep us humble.''
</P>
<P>
   Several players pointed to last season after Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   And, in case the message didn't get across, Gailey, who was on
the Steelers' sideline last year, also brought up 1997's turn of
events.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just one of 16,'' Gailey said. ``One game doesn't make
or break a season. I'm sure they remembered last year. But I talked
about it anyway. One win is great, but it's only one game.''
</P>
<P>
   Also helping temper the Cowboys' enthusiasm is the fact that
they did not play a mistake-free game, which included 10 penalties
against Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the offensive totals _ the 38 points were the most in
the regular season for the Cowboys since a 42-31 victory against
Green Bay in 1994, and the 444 yards were the most since they
totaled 482 against Miami in 1996 _ Gailey said the team has a long
way to go in learning his offense.
</P>
<P>
   All he had to do was point to the Cowboys' first five
possessions. The first three ended with punts after a total of 11
plays. The next two were halted by an interception and a fumble.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said the offense turned it around because the players
were persistent. Though the first quarter looked a lot like the
Cowboys' preseason struggles, the offense got a chance to work
through the mistakes on field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believed the offense could put it together,'' said Gailey,
who said the Cowboys used only 30 percent of the new offense
against the Cardinals. ``The defense played good long enough to
allow the offense to get a comfort level. The game worked out where
we could be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Troy Aikman said the performance helps the team's
confidence but cautioned that ``we still got a lot of work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said the area needing the most work is the inside running
game, despite the big day from running back Emmitt Smith (29
carries, 124 yards).
</P>
<P>
   Of Smith's 29 carries, 14 netted 3 yards or less, and most of
his success came on outside runs.
</P>
<P>
   Newton said it was no coincidence that the Cowboys did better on
the ground after Cardinals defensive tackle Eric Swann was ejected
in the first quarter for fighting with Cowboys tackle Erik
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said the Cowboys made up for their slow start on the
ground with big plays, but said ``in order for us to be a solid
offense, we have to be more consistent'' running the ball.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
