<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 08:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3292 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN09-CO     09-08 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Bureaucracy is going nuttty
 &HT;    (For release Wednesday, Sept. 9, 1998)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWS ITEM: The U.S. Department of Transportation has ordered
airlines to create peanut-free buffer zones on flights when a
person with an allergy to peanuts is aboard _ one row in front of
the allergic person, one row behind and, of course, the row the
allergic person is sitting in.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Department of Transportation: I'd like to speak with you
about perfume _ perfume in airplanes, specifically the row in front
of me, the row in back of me and, of course, the row I'm sitting
in. And, if your powers also embrace elevators, I'd like to talk
with you about perfume in those closed-in mechanisms, and where may
I write about perfume in restaurants; would that be the Food and
Drug Administration?
</P>
<P>
   Oh, brother, where do we draw the line?
</P>
<P>
   As a person with allergies, I have empathy for people who are
allergic to peanuts. Studies show that all of us opening our
pressurized peanut packs within a limited time frame sends the
allergen coursing throughout the plane's ventilation system.
</P>
<P>
   While peanuts do not bother me, my throat closes when I inhale
someone's perfume. Perfume has long been identified by health
organizations as a frequent trigger of asthma attacks.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure there are other people who are adversely affected by
the odor of Parmesan cheese they sprinkle on that dreadful airline
pasta. And I know my wife can't stand the smell of beer, so let's
create another rule about that stuff on airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   I loathe echoing Republican populist battle cries, but
government is getting a bit too heavy on my back with the peanut
edict. Never mind that peanut farmers are in a rage _ this never
would have happened under Jimmy Carter's presidency _ the problem
is how far we are going these days.
</P>
<P>
   People are allergic to peanuts, to perfume, to millions of other
things, including all that dust that gathers on airline seats. But
a ban solely on peanuts? Is someone in a very high place allergic
to peanuts?
</P>
<P>
   And what a rule! If a person with documentation that he or she
is allergic to peanuts calls in advance, the airline must provide a
peanut-free zone. Well, I want to do the same about perfume. I've
been on plenty of flights where I was gasping for air because a
perfume-wearer was nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Just the other night, I was sandwiched between two tables in a
trendy restaurant where the fragrance of perfume coming from others
was ruining my dinner. Anybody for a law? Of course not! None of
this _ peanuts or perfume _ is as prevalent as the problem of
second-hand smoke. That's where the line should have been drawn.
</P>
<P>
   Allergy sufferers _ and I am one _ have to come to grips with
reality. We can't make rules for everything.
</P>
<P>
   I am reminded of a flight I took from Budapest to Moscow about
eight years ago. I had requested seats in the non-smoking section.
As soon as we departed on the Marev Hungarian Airlines flight,
three men across the aisle lit up, not just any cigarettes but
those strong, doubly smelly Russian types.
</P>
<P>
   Choking, I called for the stewardess and, through broken
English, hand signals and heavy smoke, the conversation went
approximately this way:
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked for non-smoking.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is non-smoking.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But they're smoking over there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, this side of the plane is for non-smoking, the other side
is for smoking.''
</P>
<P>
   You just can't make annoyance rules that will satisfy everyone.
I can do without the peanuts, but that's not the idea. Will someone
else do without the perfume? Or the beer? Or the screaming child?
Or the hair spray?
</P>
<P>
   Where does it end?
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
