<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOW I SPENT MY BALTIC VACATION: Just look at those Latvian Alps
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   What I didn't know about the Baltics until I got here:
</P>
<P>
   _ Latvia somehow has become known as the Switzerland of the
Baltics. Never mind that one-tenth of the country is below sea
level.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reassuring item from a tourist magazine: ``Chances are you
won't die on the spot if you drink water straight from the tap.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Popcorn comes flavored with your choice of either salt or
sugar.
</P>
<P>
   _ The farther south you go, from Estonia to Latvia to Lithuania,
the more picturesque the Baltics become. The farther north you go,
from Lithuania to Latvia to Estonia, the more prosperous the
Baltics become.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lithuanian cafes serve fried pig ears that are the size of a
platter.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Vilnius, the capital of Lithuania, cabdrivers have to pay
kickbacks to crime organizations for the privilege of parking in
prime business areas, such as the train station.
</P>
<P>
   _ Family tradition is strong in the Baltics, as illustrated by
the lyrics of this love song: ``I need just you ...'' the woman
sings to her man. She pauses and then adds, ``... and my daughter
and my mother.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The gender symbols on restroom doors can be confusing for U.S.
visitors. A circle above a triangle is for women; a circle above an
inverted triangle is for men. The idea is this: Women are larger at
the bottom, men are larger at the top.
</P>
<P>
   _ The languages of Estonians, Latvians and Lithuanians have this
much in common: Each is well colored with Russian curse words.
</P>
<P>
   _ A new Robin Hood television series for the U.S. was filmed
this summer in the forests of Lithuania. It's a matter of
economics: Extras can be hired for $11 a day, and with bright
sunlight from 7 a.m. until 7 p.m., the workday is 12 hours long.
</P>
<P>
   _ But in winter, anyone working 8-5 in an office never sees the
sun. It rises at 9 a.m. and sets at 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _ People from Finland come here to drink. Their own country has
stringent liquor laws, the Baltics do not.
</P>
<P>
   _ A welcome sign for a homesick American at an Estonia hotel:
``Rotary International Meets Here.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Latvia wants to ban the display of Nazi and Communist symbols,
such are the strong feelings that still exist in the Baltics.
</P>
<P>
   _ Vilnius has a statue of Frank Zappa, the late American
rock-'n'-roll legend who enjoys cult status in the Baltics, thanks
to his anti-establishment lyrics, which were considered
anti-Communist as well.
</P>
<P>
   _ An American tourist tells this story as an example of how
little the U.S. knows about the Baltics: When he asked at an
America Express office in New York City to exchange dollars for
Latvian currency, he was told they had never heard of the place.
``Latvia?'' he was asked. ``Where's that _ in Africa?''
</P>
<P>
   _ You can learn more about the Baltics by checking the web site
maintained by ``City Paper _ The Baltic States,'' an excellent
English-language magazine, http://www.balticsww.com/.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
AWEW18A(at)prodigy.com; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
