<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 11:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3417 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EQUIFAX-CEO09-COX     09-08 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EQUIFAX-CEO09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sales-oriented CEO energizes Equifax
 &HT;    By David McNaughton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A lot has changed since Thomas F. Chapman ran into a brick wall
when he went looking for help from Equifax.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Chapman was at First National Bank of Atlanta, and
his ``passion was to sell a lot of stuff.'' He asked Equifax if
there was a way to cross-check data for leads.
</P>
<P>
   The best Equifax could do then was to simply suggest it might
give the bank a discount on credit reports, Chapman said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Equifax offers the kind of information Chapman needed. And
Chapman is president _ since August 1997 _ and chief executive
officer _ since January _ of the Atlanta-based credit reporting and
information services company.
</P>
<P>
   What has not changed is Chapman the salesman, which is a plus
for Equifax, according to analyst Kevin R. Gruneich of Bear,
Stearns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom is the right person to take (Equifax) forward,'' Gruneich
said. He has ``a sales orientation, and I think that is
important.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a great marketer,'' added John Rougeou, who retired as
executive vice president of Equifax's North American operations in
February.
</P>
<P>
   Some longtime Atlantans might recall the hoopla Chapman set off
in 1982 with a teaser promotion rate of 18.65 percent on money
market deposit accounts at First National.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was his marketing program,'' said D. Raymond Riddle,
Chapman's boss at First National and a director of Equifax since
1989. ``It kind of shocked the banking community. It set off a
price war, but being first, the bank was able to capitalize and get
a nice deposit base.''
</P>
<P>
   Chapman was one of the early outsiders that C.B. ``Jack'' Rogers
Jr., now chairman of Equifax, hired after he joined the company
from IBM. Chapman, who in 1988 left what was then Wachovia, was
hired by Rogers in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack felt he needed someone to energize Equifax,'' said
Riddle, a former chairman and chief executive of National Service
Industries.
</P>
<P>
   What he got was ``no shrinking violet,'' by Chapman's own
admission. ``Emotional'' is another way that Chapman describes
himself, as do others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't sit back like a guy ats ... a funeral home,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chapman can be animated, boisterous, funny and _ based on his
own telling and that of others _ demanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``He strives for perfection not only of others, but for
himself,'' Rougeou said.
</P>
<P>
   Chapman recounted how he recently dropped a travel book on
someone's desk, with a note that he thought the recipient's little
girls would enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't make me a good guy. It just means there is some
compassion there,'' Chapman said. ``And,'' he added in explanation
of the gift, ``a couple of weeks ago I near killed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the things I learned from Raymond Riddle (is)
that he had this great knack of not letting the day close, if you
sort of crossed horns with someone, without going and making it OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't mean `I forgive you for costing us $10 million.'
It's just, `You're OK with me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The chief executive's job is OK, too, even if there are
``moments,'' as Chapman said he told a group of Equifax employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `This is not a very fun job sometimes. Every day you
have to be driven by the stock price, and things happen to your
market and you don't know why. You're supposed to have answers to
questions (and) sometimes there are no answers to them.' ``
</P>
<P>
   ``So, by and large, this is a pretty difficult job. But I love
this job. It's a great job, but there are days when I'd love for
somebody else to have it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
