<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Equifax has expanded into global information service
 &HT;    By David McNaughton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The strategy for Equifax was set with the arrival in 1987 of
C.B. ``Jack'' Rogers Jr. as president and chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   His job was to use technology to transform Equifax's products
into more useful and valuable offerings.
</P>
<P>
   That's still the idea: selling information rather than raw data.
And it continues under Thomas F. Chapman, the current president and
chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Chapman took the company further along that route
with the acquisition of Decisioneering Group, a firm that brings a
new business _ customer loyalty consulting _ to Equifax.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to help companies find a way to develop customers
for life, as well as be more efficient in attracting those
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of our customers say, `OK, how do we take this customer
and multiply the relationship in order to keep them?' It takes a
whole new set of tools,'' said Chapman.
</P>
<P>
   Buying a new set of tools is part of the acquisition strategy at
Equifax, which looks for companies that will bring it better
technology, new products, or geographic expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Equifax announced its biggest deal since 1990, one
that gets it into the Brazilian market. For $200 million in cash,
Equifax bought 80 percent of Seguranca ao Credito e Informacoes,
which sells business and consumer credit information and other
data.
</P>
<P>
   The transition from a credit reporting company to what Equifax
is today has not gone unnoticed on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Early last month, Salomon Smith Barney started coverage of the
company with a ``buy'' rating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Equifax is best known as one of the three dominant providers
of consumer credit reports in the U.S. (with the others being
Experian and Trans Union), but we believe this description is too
narrow and that it misses key parts of (Equifax's) growth story,''
analysts at Salomon Smith Barney wrote. ``The company is actually a
diversified global information and payment services company with a
significant opportunity to expand both the services offered as well
as the geographic markets covered.''
</P>
<P>
   The price of Equifax stock is down since that report was issued,
but still faring better than the broader market. It closed Friday
at $37.37 1/2, down from a 52-week high of $44.12 1/2 hit Aug. 2,
but up 5.5 percent this year against a 0.36 percent gain for the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
