 &HT;    Backup quarterbacks enter the spotlight
 &HT;    By Randy Riggs
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Timing is everything in life, it's said, so who are Matt Tittle,
Patrick Fletcher and Eric Crouch to disagree?
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, who are they, period?
</P>
<P>
   Before the football season, they weren't exactly household
names, except perhaps in their own households. Before Saturday,
Sept. 5, they were seldom-used backup quarterbacks and, for two of
them, no change in that status seemed in imminent.
</P>
<P>
   Only Nebraska's Crouch knew Sept. 5 would be a big day for him,
since he already had been pencil ed in to start for injured Bobby
Newcombe against Alabama-Birmingham. But it also turned into a big
day for Texas Tech's Tittle and Oklahoma's Fletcher as all three
played improbable roles in leading their teams to season-opening
victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to have to go with a backup quarterback, the
first game probably is the best time to do it before people get
into a flow as the season goes along,'' Baylor Coach Dave Roberts
said. ``But I don't know if there is a good time, really.''
</P>
<P>
   Tittle, a fifth-year senior who had played in a grand total of
two previous games at Tech, was thrust into the Raiders' game
against Texas-El Paso early in the second quarter when Rob Peters
went down with a s
</P>
