<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-MAKEUP09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Scratch 'n' slather: Mag prints samples with story on makeup
 &HT;    By Loretta Grantham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Palm Beach Post
<TEXT>
<P>
   Turn to page 156 in this month's Allure, and play
paint-by-number _ on your face!
</P>
<P>
   The magazine is the first to feature real makeup samples with a
story, this one about fall colors. You not only see a photo of
Revlon's Bold Berry lipstick and Frederic Fekkai's Clove eye
shadow, but you also get to dab some on.
</P>
<P>
   There are eight wee flaps with directions such as ``try this,''
``touch this powder'' and ``burst this blob.'' Think pop-up book.
Or beauty advent calendar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Readers are telling us that they're trying makeup they never
would've tried,'' says Allure Editor in Chief Linda Wells. ``And
not to sound touchy-feely, but this brings back the playfulness of
it. Makeup's supposed to be fun, not rocket science.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a science _ plus an astronomical production cost _ to
slathering goo behind a trap door on glossy paper that's reproduced
800,000 times. But the technology, developed by Arcade (the company
that created perfume ScentStrips), is top-secret. And so is the
bill, which was paid by Allure, not by companies whose items are
featured.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a panel sample lots of products and pick the best ones
like we always do,'' Wells says. ``We wanted to be sure the story
didn't look like an ad, so we didn't design the samples to look
like a lipstick tube or blush compact.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, you're shown a model's made-up face and given
instructions: ``For this look, try lipstick 1 and eye shadow 6.''
</P>
<P>
   The best news is, if Chanel's Nightlight Bronze shadow makes you
look like Frankenstein's betrothed, you're not out $25.
</P>
<P>
   Just $2.50, horoscope included.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
