<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hacking was inside job to promote MTV awards
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MTV's Web site seems a prime candidate for teenage hackers who
like to mess with big-time sites. For a while last week, it looked
as if MTV had indeed been hacked. As it turns out, the defaced
start page was actually created by MTV itself as a promotion for
Thursday's ``MTV Video Music Awards.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Silicon Alley Reporter's editor, Jason McCabe Calacanis,
extracted a gleeful confession from MTV Tuesday, designers and
programmers who flood the mailing list of the World Wide Web
Artists Consortium were divided on the possibility the MTV site
could be hacked.
</P>
<P>
   In place of MTV's slick black Web pages was a bright yellow
message reading ``I'm in! I TOLD YOU GUYS I'D DO IT! Shoutouts to
milw0rm, vaporRub and Dave D. in Secacus! By the way, I've got
something serious planned for this Wednesday, so you better come
by. J.F.'' There was also faux spray paint across the MTV logo with
the words ``J.F. was here.'' (For those of you who missed it, the
altered home page is preserved at (http://www.nocturna.com
</P>
<P>
   /hacked.html).
</P>
<P>
   For the uninitiated, real hacking involves gaining illegal
access to a site's server and altering the code that makes the site
look the way it does. The designers and programmers on the WWWAC
list were nostalgically hoping it was a couple of kids from New
Jersey busting into the site, but most suspected MTV was behind the
hack. And if MTV was trying to sell something, they said, this was
a lame way to do it.
</P>
<P>
   MTV spokeswoman Caroline Mockridge said the J.F. stands for
Johnny Fame, a new MTV personality who will be covering the MTV
awards exclusively online. ``We wanted to present this personality
to our audience in a dramatic and media-appropriate way,'' she
said. ``You'll be surprised how his presence will manifest itself
between now and the awards show.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the most jaded Web denizen has to admit it's pretty clever
to make your own Web site look as if it had been hacked to generate
a buzz among your target audience _ high school and college kids
who routinely surf the Web, and the aging artsy/hipster types who
still watch MTV and frequent Internet mailing lists where
journalists tend to troll for information. As Magnavox used to say
in its TV ads, ``Smart. Very smart.''
</P>
<P>
   But most Net regulars did not believe the site had actually been
hacked. It's fairly easy to see why. Back in the dark ages of the
Internet _ about four or five years ago _ ``hacking'' or illegally
breaking into a Web site was something of a hobby. The fabled two
kids in a garage so integral to mythology of the Internet would
spend endless hours surrounded by computers, monitors and a pile of
blue, black, green and gray ``hacker'' boxes. Eventually, they'd
find their way into a site or a database and change billing records
or grade reports, look for stored credit card numbers or maybe
alter a few pages of text. Like graffiti artists, hackers had their
own ``signatures,'' as many on the WWWAC list pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1998, we live in an age of browsers that provide
encryption standards so powerful that users must verify the fact
they are U.S. citizens before even downloading either the Netscape
or Microsoft browser. With the recent boomlet in electronic
commerce, sites such as ESPN SportZone (which was hacked by an
employee last summer trying to prove how shoddy SportsZone's
security was) have more elaborate gatekeeping devices to keep
information from being hacked by outsiders than ever before. Online
banking services such as First Union won't even deliver banking
information unless its customers have the strongest encryption
technology available.
</P>
<P>
   Web sites must now go to great pains to prove their sites are
more secure than Fort Knox. A couple of kids from Secaucus, N.J.,
breaking into the MTV server and redesigning a couple of pages
would be a good laugh at corporate America's expense. But in the
new age of encryption, hacking a major Web site would have to be an
inside job _ just like the one at MTV.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
