<TEXT>
<P>
   In print
</P>
<P>
   In this age of the Internet and 24-hour news television, anyone
can become a celebrity overnight. Which also means you can just as
quickly become a target for public scrutiny. ``Spin,'' a new book
by spin doctor Michael S. Sitrick and journalist Allan Mayer, talks
about this modern phenomenon and how you can make it work for you.
Among the famous cases Sitrick was involved in were the bankruptcy
of Orange County, Calif., and Food Lion's suit against ABC News.
</P>
<P>
   On CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   Interactive Magic is offering a new wrinkle in the growing list
of flight simulators. Called ``Carrier Strike Fighter,'' this game
lets you land and take off on a U.S. aircraft carrier. The game is
modeled on real aircraft carriers. It also includes video and sound
effects from the USS Abraham Lincoln. ``Carrier Strike'' retails
for about $40 and is available only for Windows PCs.
</P>
<P>
   First it was deer. Now its waterfowl and big game. The success
of WizardWorks' original ``Deer Hunter'' has prompted the company
to release a series of add-on games. Two of the latest are ``Bird
Hunter'' and ``Trophy Hunter.'' You need the original game to play
these new scenarios. The add-ons work only with Windows 95 or
higher PC operating systems. They retail for about $20.
</P>
<P>
   Online
</P>
<P>
   With summer ending, golfers eventually will be moving inside.
But that's no excuse to give up following the game. Now you can do
it on the Internet. There are plenty of sites, and one of the best
is maintained by Links magazine. This site offers a look at some of
the best and most famous courses in the world. There's also a look
at the game's big personalities. You'll find the site at
http://www.linksmagazine.com.
</P>
