<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't blame the Internet for the failings of humanity
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The big news in technology this past week came from Carnegie
Mellon University in Pittsburgh, where researchers discovered that
people who spent hours and hours on the Internet each night didn't
have time left to have any real human relationships.
</P>
<P>
   And because of that, these cyber-junkies spent a lot of time
being depressed.
</P>
<P>
   What a surprise that was. It is roughly equivalent to
discovering that people who walk in the rain get wet and then long
to be dry.
</P>
<P>
   Here we have the research subjects, a hundred or so people in
Pittsburgh who _ instead of taking walks and hugging _ sit in front
of a computer monitor all night. And lo and behold, they have lousy
personal lives, lose touch with their families and feel terrible.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes researchers at fancy universities are so danged smart
they overlook the obvious.
</P>
<P>
   I think those Ph.D.s confused a symptom for the disease. Imagine
what they would have found if they surveyed people who spent almost
all their spare time playing golf, or dancing or watching TV. Do
you think their personal relationships would be any better? Would
the day magically have more hours in it?
</P>
<P>
   I'm the last person in the world to defend the sort of shallow
relationships spawned in the Internet's chat groups. I'd much
rather talk to someone I can see. And my guess is that most of the
friendships and the romances that develop there have the life span
of a fly. But I also think it is likely the same people would find
shallow and short-lived relationships in the real world. I'm saying
that it's not the Internet's doing; it's the people.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, some of these people with friendships and romances that
exist only in cyberspace are doing the best they can. People who
are shy or socially inept in real life sometimes become bold and
witty in the pretend world of the chat groups. My guess is that
many of them wouldn't have any relationships at all if not for the
Internet. I'm thinking that any human contact _ no matter how
flawed _ is better than none at all. So it's hard to judge.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing surprising about the fact new technology is seen
as magical, with exaggerated notions of how good it is or how evil
it is. That's a human reaction that dates all the way back to
primitive man. In the very earliest days, even fire was seen as a
spirit. When the first cameras came along, people were afraid the
images they took would capture our souls.
</P>
<P>
   In the Golden Age of Television, some social critics saw it as a
demonic force that would destroy civilization; others thought it
would automatically change tastes and make opera and theater lovers
out of the masses. Civilization may be a little battered, but it's
still around. And instead of being a nation of theater lovers, we
watch MTV.
</P>
<P>
   It's strange how little the human thinking process has changed.
We use different words and terms than medieval people, but we still
think new technology has magical powers. Instead of seeing the
Internet as the particularly complex and efficient delivery system
for data that it is _ a neutral pipeline that doesn't care what it
carries _ we believe the pipeline itself has a personality of its
own and powers far beyond what you'd expect from a bunch of wires
and fiber-optic cable.
</P>
<P>
   For what it's worth, I think people should worry more about
spending time with those they love than in trying to find witches
hiding in the Internet. It's a lot easier to blame technology than
ourselves for our failings. But when we do that, the problem
becomes unsolvable. We can't fix the technology; we can only fix
ourselves. Either that or move out of Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: tecbud(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Bill Husted appreciates hearing from you but can not respond to
all e-mail. Personal home page:
http://www.mindspring.com/(tilde)bhusted/bills.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
