<SLUG> BC-BRAIN-SIDE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Where did I park the car?
 &HT;    By Carolyn Susman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are some tips on improving your recall ability:
</P>
<P>
   Recalling names: Conjure up a mental picture or association to
remember names. Repeat the name in conversation and ask how to
spell it.
</P>
<P>
   Absent-mindedness: Block out distractions. When you run upstairs
to get your checkbook, think about nothing else until the item is
in your hand. If you're interrupted, cue yourself by turning a
watch or ring inward as a reminder that you were in the middle of
doing something.
</P>
<P>
   On the tip of your tongue: Anxiety is a mental block, which is
why wracking your brain for a word usually doesn't work. The
thought will likely pop into your head later when the mind has more
time to scan its reserves. Sometimes, running through letters in
the alphabet can trigger the sound of the word you're searching
for.
</P>
<P>
   Losing things: Select a permanent place for frequently misplaced
items such as keys. Say out loud for reinforcement, ``I'm leaving
the keys on the hallway table.'' To find a missing item, retrace
your steps and recall as many details as possible. One recollection
can trigger others.
</P>
<P>
   Where's the car? Before you walk away from your parked car,
pretend that your mind is a camera and record a snapshot
perspective of your car's location. At the mall, be attentive to
landmarks such as banners or storefronts. Better yet, try parking
in the same area each time.
</P>
<P>
   WAYS TO KEEP YOUR BRAIN SHARP
</P>
<P>
   _ Get plenty of sleep and exercise.
</P>
<P>
   _ Read books and newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Enroll in an adult education course.
</P>
<P>
   _ Learn a new hobby or skill.
</P>
<P>
   _ Attend lectures.
</P>
<P>
   _ Engage in debates; have serious conversations.
</P>
<P>
   _ Do crossword puzzles; play word games.
</P>
<P>
   _ Do volunteer work.
</P>
<P>
   _ Avoid passive activities like watching television.
</P>
<P>
   _ Avoid substances known to damage the brain: alcohol, drugs,
tobacco, excess fatty foods and cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: Drs. Larry Eisner and Rodrigo Kuljis
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
