<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EYMAN-ON-BOOKS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Cats of Lamu' is an informal study of an old culture
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The island of Lamu is off the coast of Kenya. The renowned
wildlife photographer Jack Couffer _ ``Born Free, Out of Africa'' _
discovered it more than 20 years ago, and has been going back ever
since.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cats of Lamu'' (Lyons Press, $24.95) is his fascinating,
semi-anthropological look at the indigenous population of the
island's semi-feral cats.
</P>
<P>
   Couffer initially became fascinated because the Lamu cats are
clearly genetic twins of the cats of ancient Egypt, which were
thought to have evolved out of existence _ skinny, fine-boned, with
very long tails. On balance, inherently aristocratic and quite
beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   The Lamu cats live only about five years on the average, despite
the fact that the native population takes good care of them as a
sort of religious duty; Couffer's book features delightful pictures
of about 50 of the cats residing in a local school, where the
teacher dutifully feeds them, and the cats spend the day resting
among the children.
</P>
<P>
   Although the cats are largely wild, some of them have a liking
for people and allow themselves to be petted, although their
generosity rarely extends so far as to be picked up.
</P>
<P>
   Couffer's method is similar to Jane Goodall's; he separates the
population into prides, adopts several animals in each pride, names
them, then tracks them and becomes as intimate as possible with
them in order to discover their habits and traits. Along the way,
he becomes one with a remote culture.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly a picture book _ although the photos are excellent;
not exactly scientifically painstaking _ Couffer is a good,
spritely writer _ ``The Cats of Lamu'' is like a cat: simply
itself, something to be cherished.
</P>
<P>
   THAR SHE BLOWS! . . . The success of ``The Perfect Storm'' has
publishers looking for other books to fill the same niche. Viking
has paid around $1 million for ``In the Heart of the Sea: The
Tragedy of the Whaleship Essex,'' the story of a 19th-century
shipwreck brought on by one very hostile sperm whale. It's the
story that inspired Melville to write ``Moby Dick.''
</P>
<P>
   Author Nathaniel Philbrick told ``Perfect Storm'' author
Sebastian Junger about his book when Junger spoke at Philbrick's
Marine Institute in Nantucket. Junger clued in his agent, and
voila!
</P>
<P>
   Nobody's saying whether Junger gets a piece of Philbrick's
action for being a good Samaritan.
</P>
<P>
   GREAT FIRST PARAGRAPHS. . . ``It was almost quitting time when
Toddy met the man with no chin and the talking dog. Almost three in
the afternoon.'' _ from Jim Thompson's ``The Golden Gizmo,''
published by Vintage
</P>
<P>
   QUOTE UNQUOTE . . . ``To love another: the riskiest, most
profound choice . . . obviously the ground of all real ethics, the
most terrifying, the one that demands the most commitment and
energy, the most potentially annihilating, the most demanding of
both identity and non-identity.'' _ C.K. Williams
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
