<HEADER>
A3431 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KABAT-COLUMN09-COX     09-08 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KABAT-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With a single squeak
 &HT;    By Vicki Marsh Kabat
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are many good reasons behind my return to the workforce
fulltime, but I didn't note one of the best until recently.
</P>
<P>
   The boys are back in school, and one is taking band for the
first time. Last spring, when we discussed which instrument he
should choose, the clarinet seemed a natural. For one thing, it
would be easy to carry to school, unlike a tuba or baritone. Also,
my husband was an ace clarinetist during his high school days, and
he could give some expert pointers to our son.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, as we made our decision, swinging melodies from the
likes of Pete Fountain and Benny Goodman danced in my head.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, I visited with a friend who is a band instructor at
a local school and told him of our son's instrument choice. He took
me aside and looked solemnly into my eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``A word of advice: Lay in a supply of earplugs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, it can't be that bad,'' I laughed merrily, remembering our
sons' first days on the piano.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me try to describe what your son's clarinet will sound
like in those first weeks,'' he continued. ``Think of a cat being
sucked through the engine of a jet airplane. That's close.''
</P>
<P>
   I swallowed hard.
</P>
<P>
   The first day our son came home with his instrument is forever
etched in my memory. His father and I were thrilled at his
excitement as he took the clarinet out of its case. We oohed and
aahed as he showed us how to assemble it and moisten the reed. We
admired his music stand and beginner's book.
</P>
<P>
   And then he blew.
</P>
<P>
   Instantly, I had a flashback to the sounds I emitted in the
final throes of childbirth. My husband's eyes rolled up into his
head in painful recollection. In fact, I'm not sure there are words
in the English language to describe the sound that emanated from
the end of that harmless-looking instrument.
</P>
<P>
   Our dogs bolted from their slumber. There was howling and
quivering and ducking under the furniture. Actually, that was us,
not the dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Another son came running from his bedroom in great
consternation.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was that? Is everyone all right?''
</P>
<P>
   My husband and I looked at each other and then at our budding
musician, who stood there proudly, cheeks puffed wide, still
blowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my!'' I exclaimed. ``What sound you're getting!''
</P>
<P>
   Mothers know how to say volumes without hurting tender feelings.
My husband even took a turn, and after a 25-year layoff, was able
to coax a few high C's from the clarinet while our son watched in
awe.
</P>
<P>
   It was a long 30 minutes of practice, but I'm proud to say we
sat stoically through it. We encouraged our son every time he
stopped to catch his breath, opportunities we hastily took to
engage him in long periods of conversation.
</P>
<P>
   My ears rang for days, but it only took me a few moments to plan
my next step.
</P>
<P>
   When my son finished his practice that first day, I sat him down
and gave him an earnest talk about the importance of daily
practice. We discussed the need to set up a routine and stick to
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's what I want you to do,'' I told him. ``When you get
home from school each day, take 30 minutes to relax and have a
snack. Then, immediately practice your clarinet. You can do any
other homework later, but always practice your clarinet first.''
</P>
<P>
   Just to make sure, I call home before I leave the office. I
think he can squeak by without me on this one.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Marsh Kabat writes for the Waco (Texas) Tribune-Herald.
She can be reached online at VMKabataol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
