<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `I don't care' what they say; don't call me
 &HT;    By Emily J. Minor
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The other day between 3 and 5 p.m., the phone in my kitchen rang
seven times and in those hours, that special time of day when
homework and hunger make young children insane, I _ woman _ was
able to accomplish many things.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you heard me roar.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, what I did was this: Refuse the following, politely.
</P>
<P>
   Aluminum siding on our stucco house, new exterior paint,
refinancing, carpet cleaning and another refinancing.
</P>
<P>
   I also listened to a computerized political advertisement for a
school board candidate who would go on to lose, and took a moment
of personal time _ excuse me for being so greedy _ to call my
husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honey, please,'' I said. ``Can you pick up a pizza for dinner?
I'm too busy answering the telephone to cook.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, this might not annoy you. Indeed, you might not even be
home at these hours. But I have to tell you, this telephone
solicitation business has gotten out of hand. Indeed, everything to
do with the telephone is out of control, including last week's
decision by Florida utility officials that some guy from Texas can
name his phone company ``I Don't Care.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong. I like the telephone. I like to pick it up
and call my friend in Colorado and my mother in Ohio and my sister
on the other coast of Florida. I like a clear line with no crackle.
I like a bill under $150.
</P>
<P>
   But I do not appreciate it when the phone company puts little
voices in my head, the likes of which I heard just the other day
when I placed a called - between solicitations - to area code 303.
</P>
<P>
   It is 4:22 p.m. in the time zone you are calling, the chipper
voice said.
</P>
<P>
   Well, gee, thanks. But I think I can figure out what time it is
in Denver without the help of my long distance provider.
</P>
<P>
   These phone company people have tried to dupe me in other ways,
too, but I can be a strong, cautious sort. In fact, I am proud to
announce right here and now that I have never, ever, paid the
telephone company 50 cents to automatically dial a number I got
from a 411 operator, although I've considered it a few thousands
times.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, I am sure that one day _ weak, hormonal and insane from
the constant ringing of the kitchen telephone _ I'll probably cave
in on that one too. Damn them.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings me to today's gripe, mainly, the fine folks at the
Florida Public Service Commission. See, they told Dennis Dees,
founder of KTNT (say it out loud. Sound anything like AT&AMP;T to you?)
that he can name his telephone companies ``I Don't Care'' and ``It
Doesn't Matter.'' Believe me, I am not some crazed carpet cleaner
making all this up.
</P>
<P>
   From what I'm told, this means if someone calls and asks which
phone company I want to do business with and I say, ``I Don't
Care,'' I'll soon be getting a bill from Mr. KTNT in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about invasive.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about annoying.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about somebody missing the boat.
</P>
<P>
   Because if those aluminum siding guys were really on the ball,
they'd go ahead and name their company ``Don't you dare call me
between 3 and 5 again.'' In fact, I just might be on to something.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
