<HEADER>
A3433 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SORORITY-HOWTO09-COX     09-08 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SORORITY-HOWTO09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How to pledge a sorority
 &HT;    Sidebar to SORORITY-SECRETS
 &HT;    By Cara Anna
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spring, senior year of high school
</P>
<P>
   Girls who have been admitted to the University of Florida
receive a brochure describing the sorority selection process, which
takes place during ``Rush Week.'' ``A sorority is more than just a
chapter or a house,'' the brochure says. ``It is lifelong friends
who will be there to laugh, cry, celebrate and graduate with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Summer
</P>
<P>
   Girls who are interested register for Rush Week, sending UF's
Panhellenic Council 18 copies of their registration and $45. The
money is nonrefundable.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 16
</P>
<P>
   Rush Week officially begins with a mandatory Rushee Forum in the
university auditorium. The ``rushees'' receive identical white
T-shirts to wear for Round One.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 17-18
</P>
<P>
   Round One: Rushees split into 16 groups of about 80 people, led
by rush counselors. (The counselors are sorority members who cannot
reveal which sorority they belong to until the week is over. They
wear orange pith helmets to stand out.) The groups visit eight
sorority houses a day for parties that last 30 minutes each. This
is for getting-to-know-you chatting, but attendance is mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 19
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary Preference: Each rushee chooses up to 10 favorite
sororities, while each sorority chooses who it will invite to the
second round of parties. (Each sorority has a certain number of
openings to fill, depending on how many members left the year
before.) Even if a girl lists a sorority as her favorite, she
cannot attend its party if she is not invited. If a girl doesn't
get any invitations, a rush counselor calls and tells her not to
show up any more. This year, only one girl had to be called.
Another 55 girls dropped out voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 19-20
</P>
<P>
   Round Two, the ``philanthropy round'': The rushees attend five
40-minute parties each day. Those who aren't invited to a party
wait together in the ``rushee lounge'' in a nearby auditorium. In
these parties, the rushees make items _ centerpieces, IV bag covers
_ that can be donated to community groups.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 21
</P>
<P>
   Round Three, the ``video round'': Each rushee chooses her top
six sororities while each sorority prepares invitations. Four girls
were called to be told they had no invitations. Another 113 dropped
voluntarily. The rushees attend six 40-minute parties in the
afternoon. In these parties, the sororities show videos of their
activities and explain their meaning of sisterhood.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 22
</P>
<P>
   Final Preference: Each rushee picks her top three sorority
choices while sororities prepare invitations. The rushees attend
three 50-minute parties in the evening. Dress is formal or
semi-formal. Each rushee again ranks her three favorites.
Meanwhile, each sorority prepares three lists of girls they want to
invite. That night, a computer program matches the remaining girls
to sororities, according to the rankings. This year, 928 remained.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 23
</P>
<P>
   Bid Day: Rush counselors call girls who were not invited by a
sorority and tell them not to come. The rest walk to a nearby
field, where each rushee is given an envelope with her invitation
inside. They open the envelopes all at once and run to their new
sorority sisters, who are waiting outside their sorority houses
with balloons and cheers. Rush counselors now can reveal which
sorority they are in.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 23-Oct. 31
</P>
<P>
   New Member Education Program: The new girls take part in all
sorority activities except chapter meetings. This is the time when
those who don't like it drop out. The rest pay their dues. (New
member and initiation fees are estimated at $275, dues are $135,
meals are $650 a semester and housing, which is optional, is $725.)
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 1
</P>
<P>
   Initiation. For sorority members only. The new girls go through
the sorority's rituals and take an oath. Some sororities teach the
secret words that have meaning only to sorority members. Some have
secret handshakes or secret knocks for entering sorority meetings.
The initiation can last from one to six hours.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
