</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0055 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 11:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3434 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SORORITY-SECRETS09-CO     09-08 2085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SORORITY-SECRETS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What a rush!
 &HT;    Has sidebar: SORORITY-HOWTO
 &HT;    Photos available
 &HT;    By Cara Anna
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ They are not supposed to touch the girls.
</P>
<P>
   They may greet them and take their bag and walk them into the
sorority house. They may get them a glass of water. They may chat.
But they may not hug or hold hands or do anything that would say,
``We want you, more than we want that girl next to you.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, they may not even say, ``We hope to see you again.'' It
is against the rules.
</P>
<P>
   They may say, ``We are so very happy you decided to come back.''
They may kneel in front of the sitting girls and talk to them, to
keep better eye contact.
</P>
<P>
   They may, later in the week, dim the lights and give the girls
ribbons or flowers or pearls to wish on _ a sorority tradition _
and silently hope that wish will be, ``Please let them choose me.''
</P>
<P>
   And they may sing, and wipe their eyes, and gather in the foyer
of the sorority house in white dresses and say goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   This is the time of year that sororities across America open
their houses to strangers. They call it Rush Week. By the end of
that week, the strangers _ mostly freshmen _ are met, looked over,
sorted, chosen (or not chosen) and welcomed as sisters. During that
week, they are called rushees.
</P>
<P>
   A rushee's job is to go to parties. At the University of
Florida, that means as many as 35 in six days. Each lasts less than
an hour. If you want to be invited back to the next round of
parties, a good first impression is key. There is lots of smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, UF had the largest sorority rush in the nation, with
976 girls making it through the week and into one of the 16
sororities affiliated with the National Panhellenic Conference.
(UF's four historically black sororities conduct their own rush.)
</P>
<P>
   This year's Rush Week started with 1,225 rushees. Some quit
along the way. Others were called after one of the four rounds of
parties and told not to come back, because no sorority had invited
them. Some received invitations to sororities, only they weren't
the right sororities, and they cried.
</P>
<P>
   Little things are stressful. ``You have girls who might trip
walking out of a sorority house and freak out,'' says Michelle
Peitz, a senior from Stuart who is president of Zeta Tau Alpha.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the week, 928 girls made it through.
</P>
<P>
   The rushees stop chattering when the door to the Chi Omega house
opens. Along the street, doors are opening to the other sorority
houses. Each sorority president has a stopwatch, and they are
synchronized. One by one, rushees are escorted inside.
</P>
<P>
   The Chi Omega interior is pink. Pink carpeting in the main room,
pink walls. No chairs. Rushees and sorority girls stand in pairs.
The room is full of noise. ``What's your name?'' ``Where are you
from?'' Every few minutes, the pairs shift. ``Let me introduce you
to . . .'' It is like a dance.
</P>
<P>
   The Chi Omega girls are wearing white hose and pastel-colored,
floral dresses. ``Obviously, someone had to tell them to dress like
this,'' whispers Annie Grodin, an Orlando senior and president of
the UF Panhellenic Council. ``It will be a violation.''
</P>
<P>
   A violation for dressing alike? Less than a decade ago, dressing
alike was a plus. Even rushees wore nice dresses and hose all week.
Some girls were paying $300 for clothes alone, says Mike Farley,
assistant dean.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, the National Panhellenic Conference said sororities
should quit the special outfits, catered meals and elaborate
``Broadway'' skits. A spending cap was suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were saying, get to know the women and quit entertaining,''
says Lissa Bradford, conference chair. ``The rush that had
developed in the '80s gave the public the impression that
sororities were very shallow _ just rah-rah songs and skits.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, the University of Florida dropped skits and let
rushees wear casual clothes _ shirts and shorts _ for the first two
rounds of parties. It set a $3,500 spending cap for each sorority,
money that pays for balloons and finger foods and flowers.
</P>
<P>
   So Chi Omega might end up paying $100 to the Panhellenic Council
for dressing alike, Annie says. And they may have to have their
outfits screened before next year's rush.
</P>
<P>
   Conversations over, the Chi Omega girls move on to another new
Rush Week feature, the video. They stand in a semi-circle around
the seated rushees, who watch clips of girls waving, hugging,
playing flag football. There is little narration; the songs are
``Walking on Sunshine,'' ``These Are The Days,'' ``Forever Young.''
</P>
<P>
   The video ends and the Chi Omega girls link arms and sing the
theme song from ``The Golden Girls.'' ``Thank you for being a
friend . . .'' Even Annie sniffles.
</P>
<P>
   The rushees file out of the house. ``I feel like such an
idiot,'' one says. ``I don't even know these girls and I'm
crying!'' _ _
</P>
<P>
   A.J. Siccardi is a senior from Boca Raton. He is a guy, but he
can watch a rush party because he is the president of the UF's
Interfraternity Council. Sororities have started inviting
fraternity presidents to parties to show they are no longer sitting
around in white gloves drinking tea _ which is what A.J. had
imagined.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he's shocked at the ``pristine order'' of things. The
group photos with the tiny hearts taped over the faces of the rush
counselors, who have to hide their sorority affiliation this week
while they work with rushees. Conversations stopping when a little
bell rings.
</P>
<P>
   The guys just have food and bands, he said. No one has to go to
a party and no one has to dress up.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Delta Gamma house on Friday, the girls giggle. One
rushee and her Delta Gamma escort are wearing the same J. Crew
dress. Both girls are from Boca Raton. They had never met. ``I was
like, `Cool dress!' '' said Kim Rosemurgy, the rushee. ``It helped
the conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   (Later, Kim was accepted to Delta Gamma, her first choice.
``It's like you have automatic friends!'') _ _
</P>
<P>
   By Friday, round three, the rushees have moved from 16 parties
to 10 to six. Girls who aren't invited to a party have to wait it
out in the rushee lounge, an auditorium nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Courtney Kraft, a sophomore from Lake Worth, has been here for
four parties straight today.
</P>
<P>
   Her only party is at Phi Mu, which rushees say is one of the
least selective sororities. Kraft says she had good conversations
at some houses, ``but I'm not 5-9 and a size three,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft thinks she's figured out this sorority business. ``AEPhi
and DPhiE have dark hair and are from New York or New Jersey. Zeta
are tall, model types. ChiO and ADPi are more Southern charm _
pearls and immaculate. Tri-Delt is the popular one, that and Zeta
and ADPi and Kappa Delta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kappa Delta look like girls who would be in Gap ads. I can't
see girls from Zeta going for a hike in the woods. Sigma Kappas are
kind of the nerdy ones.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday morning she gets the phone call from a sympathetic
rush counselor. Phi Mu, her only hope, dropped her. She cries. She
tells friends she feels like there's something wrong with her.
</P>
<P>
   (On Sunday morning, another call. Two sororities had not met
their quota of 58 people and now want her. She chooses Phi Mu. ``I
just joined the girls like nothing ever happened.'') _ _
</P>
<P>
   It is Saturday. Today, rushees will go through the final round
of parties, visiting up to three houses. For the sororities, this
is their last chance to impress; for the rushees, it is the last
chance to sell themselves. Once the final party is over, all
rushees walk to a classroom and rank the three sororities they want
to join. From the time they leave their last party until the lists
are made, there is no talking, so they cannot influence each other.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the sororities make their decisions. Some choose
girls they had never met until that week; others they have had
their eye on since reading the Rush Week applications (GPA?
Extracurricular activities?) or letters of recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   Some rushees may want sororities that do not want them. For
these girls, there is always next year.
</P>
<P>
   But some may be wanted by more than one sorority. It is for
these girls that the Delta Delta Delta sisters _ known as Tri-Delts
_ are stringing white Christmas lights in the foyer. They are also
waiting on the specially ordered potted trees and moving the piano
into place.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, they will bring the rushees into their meeting room.
The window panes are taped over, blocking any view from outside.
Everything is white. The rushees will sit in a circle with one row
of sorority girls kneeling in front of them and another standing
behind them, singing. Each kneeling girl hands a rushee a pearl to
wish on. The rushee does not keep the pearl.
</P>
<P>
   This is what the Tri-Delts will sing softly as the rushees leave
the house: ``Tri-Delt/I'm hoping for Tri-Delt/For a long time I've
felt/It's where I belong . . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Amy Freeman, a senior from North Palm Beach, is the sorority
president. She is nervous about her speech tonight. ``We don't want
you to come here and be like us,'' she will tell them. ``We want
you to come here and be like you.''
</P>
<P>
   And she is nervous about seeing her sister, Kate, a rushee. She
will escort Kate herself and for the first time in two weeks, they
will be allowed to talk about rush.
</P>
<P>
   Amy has heard all sorts of questions from other rushees. ``Girls
have asked, `I heard to be in Delta Delta Delta you have to have a
lot of money.' `I heard you guys drive BMWs.' `I heard you have to
have blond hair to be in Zeta.' '' She shakes her head.
Stereotypes, she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, what else are they going to talk about, sitting under
the tent?'' _ _
</P>
<P>
   That afternoon in their dorm room, Kate Freeman and Kim Seager,
a freshman from Wellington, put on semi-formal dresses and heels.
``Ready to go?'' ``No, are you?'' ``Don't forget your name tag.''
Roommate Kim Balestrieri, who is not rushing, unloads college-sized
groceries. A five-pound jar of peanut butter. A six-pack of mac and
cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Another rushee runs in, wearing a short blue dress and silver
heels. She's nervous. ``This dress or black?'' They consult. Kim B.
watches, then goes into her room. (``It's not like I hate it or
anything,'' she says. ``It's just not for me.'')
</P>
<P>
   They're ready. Backpacks with a change of clothes for post-party
wear are the last touch. ``This is bizarre,'' Kate says. ``Walking
across campus like this _ `Hey, the first day of school!' ''
</P>
<P>
   (Kim is invited to Chi Omega; Kate joins her sister at
Tri-Delt.) _ _
</P>
<P>
   That evening, girls walk between the rushee lounge and their
next party. Three guys pass, then start talking in girly voices.
``Oh, I've got a stain on my shirt, I've got to change it!''
``Mine's wrinkled, I'll never get in!'' They are not, it turns out,
fraternity boys.
</P>
<P>
   Don Epperson is with campus parking patrol. He has stood on the
same corner during 14 Rush Weeks. ``In the old days, trucks would
drive by with guys out back, yelling,'' he says. ``Well, you've got
over 1,000 pretty girls in one spot. Everyone just wants to come
look.''
</P>
<P>
   His corner is next to the Chi Omega house, a big two-story brick
house with white trim. These girls are his favorite. He likes their
Southern style, he says. ``The balcony helps, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The girls have Rush Week down to a science, he says. He watches
as doors up and down the street open and rushees leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``See that?'' he says. ``They're giving the pledges white
carnations! It's a nice touch.'' _ _
</P>
<P>
   These days, the girls are no longer rushees. They are new
members, and are busy now with ``announcing'': dressing in black
and visiting the fraternity houses during dinner. They sing to the
guys. ``Your Chi-O Girl'' set to Brown-Eyed Girl. Something called
Flamin' Zeta.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Christmas caroling,'' says Megan Lake of Delray
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   They have to wear their pledge pins every day. Wednesdays, they
wear their sorority shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Courtney says her sorority told them to look good when guys are
around, and if they go to the gym looking ``ratty-tatty'' they
shouldn't wear anything that says Phi Mu.
</P>
<P>
   ``And this might sound bad, but I'm trying to conform to the
house,'' she says. ``I'm trying to fit in. It's not very hard, but
I wear more makeup than usual.''
</P>
<P>
   She likes it. ``You definitely get more attention than just a
regular person.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
