<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 11:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3435 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WIGGINS-COLUMN09-COX     09-08 0512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIGGINS-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Get with the (TV) program: We're entering a golden age of
decency
 &HT;    By Ron Wiggins
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nellie and I are news blurter-outers at the breakfast table.
It's almost an agreement that whoever sees something interesting
has to blurt it out to the other so we can discuss it right that
second.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey,'' I blurted the other morning, ``did you see this about
Bud Paxson's 24-hour family channel? Wholesome programming as far
as the eye can see.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about time,'' my wife said. ``I hope this doesn't turn
out to be Paxson's Folly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nope. It's for real,'' I insisted. ``Decency is in and
all-family programming makes it official.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you sure about this decency trend?'' Nellie asked.
``Because I seem to recall sitting through a movie about a guy who
gets his thingy caught in his zipper.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a difference between gross humor and indecency,'' I
pontificated, ``even if I can't define it. `There's Something About
Mary' is a vulgar movie about a guy so throughly decent that he
drives 1,500 miles to find his first love even after he's told
she's grossly overweight and uses a wheelchair.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll need a better example.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure. Amadeus was a decent movie with a few vulgar scenes.
`Lolita' may not have clean language and zero nudity, but the very
idea of a man and a 12-year-old girl is indecent.''
</P>
<P>
   Nellie shrugged and went back to her section of the paper.
</P>
<P>
   She wasn't convinced. I maintain that there are signs and
portents of a Golden Age of Decency in the offing:
</P>
<P>
   _ Fox's ``King of the Hill'' is funny, endearing and chock full
of wholesome values.
</P>
<P>
   _ Long stay dead ``Married . . . With Children,'' and long live
``Ally McBeal,'' quirkily confronting us with the issues of the
day. Is discrimination ever just? Are wattles sexy?
</P>
<P>
   _ Every hospital drama puts us through an ethical workout that
would exhaust a saint.
</P>
<P>
   _ Could anything be more wholesome and good-natured than ``Win
Ben Stein's Money?'' Will everyone who has even paused on ``Wildcat
Bob's Big Ass Show'' please vigorously self-administer a noogie?
</P>
<P>
   OK, so in our long trek to decency we lost a step when ``Nothing
Sacred'' bit the wafer and Soul Man wasn't picked up for the fall.
But ``Touched by an Angel'' soars and, thanks to Bud Paxson, ``Dr.
Quinn, Medicine Woman'' is out of intensive care and will be
receiving visitors soon.
</P>
<P>
   If Resurgent Decency is not the theme of the New Millennium,
explain to me why we're putting up with someone as annoying as Dr.
Laura? How is it that two of the smartest radio talk show hosts in
the nation _ Jack Cole and Rush Limbaugh _ while political polar
opposites, hammer on the same themes of decency and integrity?
</P>
<P>
   I salute Bud Paxson and his all-day all-family television
network, and lift a glass of O'Doul's to his success. May the
critics one day look back and say, ``If Bud Paxson didn't exist, we
would have had to invent him.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
