<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHARLES-MOTT09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eccentric Mott kept costs down
 &HT;    By Jennifer Peltz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charles Stewart Mott once, the story goes, changed a 30-watt
refrigerator bulb to 15 watts to save electricity.
</P>
<P>
   That might not have been unusual for someone who'd endured the
Great Depression. But Mott, creator of what became the country's
15th-largest charitable foundation, was then considered one of the
richest men in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he prized simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   He had left his father's cider business in 1900 to make one of
America's legendary automotive fortunes. But he made his own home a
working farm _ and insisted his family eat all the homegrown
produce before buying any.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this house wants yellow tomato juice, it had better make it
during the season,'' he once decreed, according to a family history
published by the University of Michigan at Flint.
</P>
<P>
   But C.S. Mott was as generous as he was thrifty _ and, perhaps
not surprising, thrifty about the business of being generous.
During his time, the Charles Stewart Mott Foundation roosted in an
office with obviously patched carpet; the office manager had to buy
his own air conditioner.
</P>
<P>
   Along with a fortune valued at $300 millionchecking with jen,
main says $500 million at last count, C.S. Mott left his family a
commitment to charity. His widow, his six children and several of
his grandchildren themselves became philanthropists.
</P>
<P>
   Their interests range but have common themes _ like promoting
peace and revitalizing Flint, said William White, C.S. Mott's
grandson-in-law and the current head of the Charles Stewart Mott
Foundation. It remains the largest of the family's philanthropies.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the best known of C.S. Mott's descendants is son
Stewart Rawlings Mott. He considers himself the family's ``black
sheep, maverick, whatever you want to call it'' for his liberal
politics and flamboyant style. But in some ways, he didn't fall far
from the Mott family tree.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart Mott has given away half his income for decades, but
he's been known to do it from an apartment with peeling paint and
rundown furniture. It was a Park Avenue penthouse, yes, but he grew
his own vegetables and raised his own chickens on the roof (to the
dismay of his neighbors, who eventually had a court order him to
stick to his own terrace. He moved.)
</P>
<P>
   His plunges into politics are not surprising for the son of a
three-time Flint mayor. But father and son were more than six
decades apart in age and just as far in politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I talked to (C.S. Mott), the veteran of the
Spanish-American War, about laying down our nuclear weapons with
the enemy, he thought I was wacko,'' Stewart Mott said. ``My father
just found me too argumentative.''
</P>
<P>
   So much so, he said, that he wasn't welcome at his father's
foundation. So he carved out his own brand of philanthropy: part
giving money, part raising it; part politics; and part just plain
party.
</P>
<P>
   He gave hefty donations to the presidential campaigns of Eugene
McCarthy, George McGovern and later, John Anderson. His $400,000
contribution made him McGovern's most generous supporter and earned
him a spot on the Nixon White House's enemies list. He mounted his
own campaign to stop the Vietnam War from Washington to the General
Motors Corp. boardroom, where he criticized the company that made
his fortune for not speaking out against the war.
</P>
<P>
   But ``I wasn't crusading against my father,'' Stewart Mott said.
``No way. I was just going a different path.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides high-profile work, there was high-profile play, like his
40th birthday party in New York in 1977, which he still talks
about. The former Columbia drama student asked his 680 guests to
dress in Medieval garb and staged his own script of a King Arthur
legend.
</P>
<P>
   For a 1983 party to celebrate his work in Washington, he urged
guests to ride an elephant on the sidewalk and wear gold sashes
emblazoned with a French saying that means, roughly, ``Shame on
those who think badly of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Now 61 and living mostly in North Salem, N.Y., Stewart Mott has
stayed largely out of the limelight in recent years. But he said he
still gives $750,000 to $800,000 a year to organizations promoting
peace, population control, government reform and civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
