<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WATER-RESCUE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rescue training for swift waters proves valuable
 &HT;    By Ralph K.M. Haurwitz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Jesse Tarin learned the importance of
swift-water rescue training the hard way more than 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, he was a ranger at Enchanted Rock State Park near
Fredericksburg. Flooding in Crabapple Creek in Llano County had
swept a car from a low-water crossing. Fearing that the driver was
still inside, Tarin tied a rope around himself and waded in without
a life jacket. Floating debris snagged the rope and nearly pulled
him under.
</P>
<P>
   Tarin did everything wrong _ and for nothing. The driver already
had been swept two miles downstream and crawled out safely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was risking myself for no reason at all,'' Tarin said.
``That was my lesson. About a third of the drowning victims in the
United States are would-be rescuers.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, as director of public safety for parks at the Texas Parks
and Wildlife Department, Tarin is a believer in swift-water rescue
training and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The basic skills and tools are fairly low-tech. A life jacket
will help keep the rescuer alive. Victims can be hauled ashore with
a ``throw bag'' _ a small bag that measures about a foot long and 6
inches in diameter, with a 50- to 75-foot rope stuffed inside. The
rope is made of a buoyant material, such as polypropylene.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a little practice, you can pitch that rope out 50 to 60
feet,'' Tarin said. ``Hopefully it reaches the victim, and you can
pull him to shore. The last thing you want to do is get in the
water and swim after someone. That's a high-risk option.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty to 40 percent of state park workers in flood-prone areas
have received swift-water rescue training, Tarin said. Newly hired
game wardens also receive training.
</P>
<P>
   For a nationally ranked team of swift-water rescuers, look no
further than the City of Austin. Each city firefighter and medic
has received basic training, and many have undergone advanced
training, said Casey Ping, commander of special operations for
Austin's Emergency Medical Services.
</P>
<P>
   All city fire and medical trucks are equipped with life jackets,
throw bags and special helmets that drain water.
</P>
<P>
   Austin EMS workers received a program-development award this
year from the Swiftwater Rescue Committee of the National
Association for Search and Rescue.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
