<SLUG> BC-COMMENTARY-BJT09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE WEDNESDAY COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Wednesday, September 9, 1998, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ I can think of few prospects less appealing than
being treated to a recitation of Dan Burton's sleepovers. If we are
on the verge of an unwelcome contest in sexual gotcha, the larger
push for it will come from within the press itself than from any
White House pressure. There's precedent. (Teepen, Cox News Service)
MOVED FRIDAY 9/4.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ NEWS ITEM: The U.S. Department of
Transportation has ordered airlines to create peanut-free buffer
zones on flights when a person with an allergy to peanuts is aboard
_ one row in front of the allergic person, one row behind and, of
course, the row the allergic person is sitting in. Dear Department
of Transportation: I'd like to speak with you about perfume. Howard
Kleinberg is a former editor of the Miami News. (Kleinberg, Cox
News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MURRAY-COLUMN08 _ RIGA, Latvia _ If you're a tall, blond,
beautiful woman who is tired of standing out in the crowd, come to
Riga. It's like a pretty woman parade all day and into the night,
long-legged women in short skirts and high-heel shoes. None of
them, alas, was wearing her dancing shoes. (Murray, Cox News
Service) MOVED FRIDAY 9/4.
</P>
<P>
   MURRAY-COLUMN09 _ What I didn't know about the Baltics until I
got here: Latvia somehow has become known as the Switzerland of the
Baltics. Never mind that one-tenth of the country is below sea
level. And other fun facts. (Murray, Cox News Service) MOVED
TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ On the airline, we called it
``Smile School'' _ a derogatory term for the mandatory six weeks of
training all newly hired flight attendants were required to endure.
Schooling was occasionally ludicrous, sometimes interesting, and
frequently boring, but it came with the territory. (Schuett, Cox
News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KABAT-COLUMN _ There are many good reasons behind my return to
the workforce fulltime, but I didn't note one of the best until
recently. ``Here's what I want you to do,'' I told my son. ``When
you get home from school, immediately practice your clarinet. You
can do any other homework later, but always practice your clarinet
first.'' Just to make sure, I call home before I leave the office.
I think he can squeak by without me on this one. (Kabat, Waco
Tribune Herald) MOVED.
</P>
