<HEADER>
A3448 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEN-STILLER-INTERVIEW     09-08 1327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEN-STILLER-INTERVIEW-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STILLER LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from W magazine _
the rate is not prohibitive _ contact one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    (_ U.S. and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
 &HT;    (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at (310)
996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     (-----They also have information on how to subscribe to ``HIGH
STYLE AND MORE,'' a complete lifestyle and entertainment package
composed of stories _ with accompanying B&AMP;W and color art _ from
numerous publications issued by Fairchild Publications.-----) 
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``e'' entertainment news files.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: One color slide is available.)  
 &HT;    
 By MERLE GINSBERG 
 c.1998 Fairchild Publications  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   For a guy with a reputation for brains, Ben Stiller has managed
to upstage _ and ultimately degrade _ himself with other body parts
recently.
</P>
<P>
   In this summer's ``There's Something About Mary,'' he was the
high-school geek who got his privates caught in his zipper on the
hottest date of his life _ only to have it become suburban legend.
</P>
<P>
   In the upcoming ``Permanent Midnight,'' based on TV writer Jerry
Stahl's memoirs of his addiction to drugs, he shoots up anywhere he
can find a vein _ even in his neck.
</P>
<P>
   And in ``Your Friends and Neighbors,'' director Neil LaBute's
dark follow-up to last year's ``In the Company of Men,'' Stiller
has several graphic semi-nude sex scenes _ in which he fails to
perform.
</P>
<P>
   Sure it takes a lot of guts to play a loser. But Stiller's not
quite ready to see it that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, after these three movies,'' the 32-year-old actormuses thoughtfully over a lobster salad lunch at Da Silvano in New
York, ``I did have to stop and wonder _ why did they see me in
these roles? People wind up believing you are the characters you
play. What does it say about me that I played three dysfunctional
guys in a row, who do hugely embarrassing things?''
</P>
<P>
   He stops to laugh at little at his own expense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully,'' he adds, ``those movies say I like to push
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   They'd be telling the truth. The man who launched his career
with the critically acclaimed comedy program the ``Ben Stiller
Show'' is serious and intensely motivated, a hard worker hellbent
on success on his own terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ben's not a guy driven by ego,'' LaBute explains. ``He
displayed a lot of fearlessness. I think when he was doing those
sex scenes, he was totally in the moment, totally there. He did it
and didn't think too much. But later on, when we screened the
movie, he was terrified to watch them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's weird,'' Stiller says, ``because the things I did on
screen this year are things in my life I'm so not open about _ at
all. I don't really talk about sex _ it's not my thing. But ever
since I did `Flirting With Disaster,' which also dealt with sexual
situations, I keep getting scripts like this. Stuff comes up in
your life and your work that you kind of need to deal with. Nothing
like having to work it out in public!''
</P>
<P>
   Since he began working on ``Permanent Midnight,'' Stiller became
close friends with Stahl (best known for his writing on '80s hits
like``Moonlighting'' and ``Thirtysomething''), who served as his
technical _ and spiritual _ adviser. The media's already dubbed
them ``the new Ben &AMP; Jerry.'' The pair got along so well, they
wrote an adaptation together of Budd Schulberg's 1941 classic
Hollywood novel, ``What Makes Sammy Run'' that they're pushing to
have produced.
</P>
<P>
   During filming, Stiller was recovering from his breakup with
long-term girlfriend Jeanne Tripplehorn, which may have helped him
lose the 28 pounds to bring him to junkie weight, but also made him
focus even harder on work. So after wrapping ``Midnight'' _ and
finally being able to eat again _ he got the script for the equally
dark ``Your Friends and Neighbors'' and decided to jump into it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd just seen `In the Company of Men,''' he says, ``and Jason
Patric, who was producing the movie, called and asked me if I'd
meet Neil LaBute. It was one of those things, like getting a call
from Albert Brooks, where I wouldn't even have to look at a script
_ I knew I'd just do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stiller had been itching to break into drama after years of
stand-up comedy, parody and satire.
</P>
<P>
   ``It freaked out my agent,'' he says. ``None of the characters
in this movie is redeemable.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the acting part of his year has wound down, the Los
Angeles-based Stiller has rented a New York apartment where he can
concentrate on writing. He just produced a movie called ``The
Suburbans'' about a one-hit-wonder '80s band and is developing a
movie about the Hardy men _ a grown-up version of the Hardy Boys.
</P>
<P>
   He's also readying the updated version of ``Sammy'' (and plans
to write more with Stahl), wants to collaborate with LaBute and is
developing a movie about Derrick, the brain-dead male supermodel
character he invented for the VH-1 Fashion Awards. Paramount
greenlighted it for a midsized budget without even seeing a script.
</P>
<P>
   ``That whole world is ripe for parody,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   It was Joel Gallen, the executive producer of the Fashion
Awards, who suggested turning the skit, which Stiller co-wrote with
``Newsradio'' writer Drake Saylor into a movie. But then there was
the problem of turning a two-minute sketch into a two-hour film.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we should take this character, who's really not that
smart, and put him into a sophisticated espionage thriller along
the lines of `The Day of the Jackal' or `Patriot Games.' So we came
up with this idea: Derrick is having a midlife crisis as he
approaches 30. He loses VH-1 Model of the Year after winning two
years in a row. He's crushed _ there's this other model named Hans
who's on the rise _ so he's having this dark night of the soul.
Meanwhile, he gets picked by a super-secret government agency to
assassinate a world leader. Turns out, in our movie, male models
are perfect assassins _ they don't really talk, and they have easy
access to world leaders. We show how every assassination in the
last 100 years was done by a male model. I want it to be incredibly
stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Stiller may be on a major roll, but he's worried it will drive
him to Workaholics Anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, acting, writing and directing fulfill the need I have
to get outside myself,'' he explains. ``Work numbs the pain. I saw
Elizabeth Shue recently; she just had a baby, and she was saying
her priorities are changing. She had this vision of all of us, her
friends, as workaholics _ becoming just a little stack of videos in
the video store, with no other lives. It's such cold comfort. But
unfortunately, the best work does come out of the most painful
times.''
</P>
<P>
   He admits, though, that there's a limit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely tired of playing those loser roles,'' he says,
then pauses. ``Unless,'' he adds, ``they're really, really
funny.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Merle Ginsberg is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
