dark ``Your Friends and Neighbors'' and decided to jump into it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd just seen `In the Company of Men,''' he says, ``and Jason
Patric, who was producing the movie, called and asked me if I'd
meet Neil LaBute. It was one of those things, like getting a call
from Albert Brooks, where I wouldn't even have to look at a script
_ I knew I'd just do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stiller had been itching to break into drama after years of
stand-up comedy, parody and satire.
</P>
<P>
   ``It freaked out my agent,'' he says. ``None of the characters
in this movie is redeemable.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the acting part of his year has wound down, the Los
Angeles-based Stiller has rented a New York apartment where he can
concentrate on writing. He just produced a movie called ``The
Suburbans'' about a one-hit-wonder '80s band and is developing a
movie about the Hardy men _ a grown-up version of the Hardy Boys.
</P>
<P>
   He's also readying the updated version of ``Sammy'' (and plans
to write more with Stahl), wants to collaborate with LaBute and is
developing a movie about Derrick, the brain-dead male supermodel
character he invented for the VH-1 Fashion Awards. Paramount
greenlighted it for a midsized budget without even seeing a script.
</P>
<P>
   ``That whole world is ripe for parody,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   It was Joel Gallen, the executive producer of the Fashion
Awards, who suggested turning the skit, which Stiller co-wrote with
``Newsradio'' writer Drake Saylor into a movie. But then there was
the problem of turning a two-minute sketch into a two-hour film.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we should take this character, who's really not that
smart, and put him into a sophisticated espionage thriller along
the lines of `The Day of the Jackal' or `Patriot Games.' So we came
up with this idea: Derrick is having a midlife crisis as he
approaches 30. He loses VH-1 Model of the Year after winning two
years in a row. He's crushed _ there's this other model named Hans
who's on the rise _ so he's having this dark night of the soul.
Meanwhile, he gets picked by a super-secret government agency to
assassinate a world leader. Turns out, in our movie, male models
are perfect assassins _ they don't really talk, and they have easy
access to world leaders. We show how every assassination in the
last 100 years was done by a male model. I want it to be incredibly
stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Stiller may be on a major roll, but he's worried it will drive
him to Workaholics Anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, acting, writing and directing fulfill the need I have
to get outside myself,'' he explains. ``Work numbs the pain. I saw
Elizabeth Shue recently; she just had a baby, and she was saying
her priorities are changing. She had this vision of all of us, her
friends, as workaholics _ becoming just a little stack of videos in
the video store, with no other lives. It's such cold comfort. But
unfortunately, the best work does come out of the most painful
times.''
</P>
<P>
   He admits, though, that there's a limit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely tired of playing those loser roles,'' he says,
then pauses. ``Unless,'' he adds, ``they're really, really
funny.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Merle Ginsberg is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
