r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN09-COX     09-08 0161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Smile, whether you're happy about it or not
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ On the airline, we called it ``Smile School''
_ a derogatory term for the mandatory six weeks of training all
newly hired flight attendants were required to endure. Schooling
was occasionally ludicrous, sometimes interesting, and frequently
boring, but it came with the territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smile!'' we were commanded. ``That passenger is paying your
salary.''
</P>
<P>
   And smile we did _ through delays, broken airplanes, canceled
flights, bomb threats, thunderstorms, cold casseroles, and
overflowing barf bags. Boy were we cheerful!
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't always easy. Like the time we were landing in
Louisville and the lady in 3A asked what time we were going to
arrive in Indianapolis. I SMILED, explaining we'd just come from
there, and our next stop would be Charlotte. The once cheerful
passenger was suddenly not
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 1115EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
