<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEATURES-BJT09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE WEDNESDAY FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories for release Wednesday, September 9, 1998,
are moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports, business and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. All stories have moved
except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e category)
</P>
<P>
   EYMAN-ON-BOOKS _ The island of Lamu is off the coast of Kenya.
The renowned wildlife photographer Jack Couffer _ ``Born Free, Out
of Africa'' _ discovered it more than 20 years ago, and has been
going back ever since. ``The Cats of Lamu'' (Lyons Press, $24.95)
is his fascinating, semi-anthropological look at the indigenous
population of the island's semi-feral cats. (Eyman, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WIGGINS-COLUMN _ Nellie and I are news blurter-outers at the
breakfast table. It's almost an agreement that whoever sees
something interesting has to blurt it out to the other so we can
discuss it right that second. ``Hey,'' I blurted the other morning,
``did you see this about Bud Paxson's 24-hour family channel?
Wholesome programming as far as the eye can see.'' (Wiggins, Palm
Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BRAIN-GAMES _ ``Most of us (after school) stop learning things
on a routine basis. If we stop learning, we stop remembering how to
learn,'' said Dr. Larry Eisner. But how do we continue that
learning process? If you really want to exercise your mental
capabilities, take courses, learn a new hobby or skill or
participate in lectures or ``serious'' discussion groups. Doing
puzzles, crosswords or playing games that involve memory will also
help. (Susman, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BRAIN-SIDE _ Here are some tips on improving your recall
ability: (list follows). (Susman, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MAGAZINE-MAKEUP _ Turn to page 156 in this month's Allure, and
play paint-by-number _ on your face! The magazine is the first to
feature real makeup samples with a story, this one about fall
colors. You not only see a photo of Revlon's Bold Berry lipstick
and Frederic Fekkai's Clove eye shadow, but you also get to dab
some on. (Grantham, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (l category)
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-ALABAMA _ Moundville Native Americal Festival Sept.
22-26 and also other University of Alabama museums, which include
Paul W. ``Bear'' Bryant Museum, Alabama Museum of Natural History
and 1829 Gorgas House. Also, fun things to see and do, places to
eat and shop and stay in Tuscaloosa and neighboring North Port.
(Thrasher, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-FESTIVALS _ Southern Happenings. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   SORORITY-SECRETS _ This is the time of year that sororities
across America open their houses to strangers. They call it Rush
Week. By the end of that week, the strangers _ mostly freshmen _
are met, looked over, sorted, chosen (or not chosen) and welcomed
as sisters. During that week, they are called rushees. (Anna, Palm
Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   SORORITY-HOWTO _ Timeline of sorority pledging. (Anna, Palm
Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WATER-RESCUE _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Jesse Tarin learned the
importance of swift-water rescue training the hard way more than 10
years ago. In a drowning incident, Tarin did everything wrong _ and
for nothing. Now, as director of public safety for parks at the
Texas Parks and Wildlife Department, Tarin is a believer in
swift-water rescue training and equipment. (Haurwitz, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   RESCUE-MISSION _ AUSTIN, Texas _ The state's newly formed urban
search and rescue team, which was dispatched to flood-stricken Del
Rio for its first mission, is not trained or equipped to work in
swiftly flowing water. The team, known as Texas Task Force 1, was
not called on to perform such rescues, but the situation has
prompted the agency overseeing the team to accelerate a plan to
upgrade training and buy life jackets, inflatable boats, helmets
and special ropes that float. (Haurwitz, Austin American-Statesman)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   REAL-LIFE _ The other day between 3 and 5 p.m., the phone in my
kitchen rang seven times and in those hours, that special time of
day when homework and hunger make young children insane, I _ woman
_ was able to accomplish many things. Maybe you heard me roar.
Basically, what I did was this: Refuse the following, politely.
(Minor, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE (a and/or l category)
</P>
<P>
   HMO-FLA _ Jupiter, Fla., resident Lise Greene's fight with her
HMO is nothing unusual in the insurance world. What is different is
a judge forced her managed-care insurance company, Well Care HMO,
to pay for her hyperbaric oxygen therapy for bladder damage. Well
Care argued that the procedure is experimental. It's the only known
injunction of its kind in Florida. (Warejcka, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
