<HEADER>
A3555 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN09-COX     09-08 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Smile, whether you're happy about it or not
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ On the airline, we called it ``Smile School''
_ a derogatory term for the mandatory six weeks of training all
newly hired flight attendants were required to endure. Schooling
was occasionally ludicrous, sometimes interesting, and frequently
boring, but it came with the territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smile!'' we were commanded. ``That passenger is paying your
salary.''
</P>
<P>
   And smile we did _ through delays, broken airplanes, canceled
flights, bomb threats, thunderstorms, cold casseroles, and
overflowing barf bags. Boy were we cheerful!
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't always easy. Like the time we were landing in
Louisville and the lady in 3A asked what time we were going to
arrive in Indianapolis. I SMILED, explaining we'd just come from
there, and our next stop would be Charlotte. The once cheerful
passenger was suddenly not happy, the agent at the gate wasn't
happy, the captain wasn't happy, and when I got back to Chicago two
days later, my chief flight attendant was REALLY unhappy. But I
kept on smiling _ it was my job.
</P>
<P>
   One night my concerned roommate forcefully shouldered her way
through the bi-fold bathroom door on a Constellation, landed
face-down on the scuffed green floor, and looked up at the startled
gentleman with his trousers around his ankles and a newspaper
covering his vitals. Turning on her most DAZZLING SMILE, she backed
out on all fours, apologizing: ``Oh sir, I'm so sorry. You've been
in here over an hour and when you didn't respond to my knocks, I
was afraid you'd had a heart attack.''
</P>
<P>
   I KEPT SMILING that stormy night, somewhere between Atlanta and
Nashville, as a line of thunderstorms tossed our airplane
every-which-way but up and a gentleman with an expensive briefcase
and an attitude to match demanded a chilled martini or my life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sir,'' I explained with what I hoped was a DISARMING SMILE as
I clung to the overhead for dear life, ``there is nothing I would
rather do at this moment than mix a shaker of martinis and sit down
and have one with you, but we have no liquor kit on this
airplane.'' I managed to squeeze out one more APOLOGETIC SMILE
before I lost my grip and went sprawling onto the heaving aisle
floor.
</P>
<P>
   The smile was a part of my job.
</P>
<P>
   My fellow flight attendants and I SMILED our way through
innumerable gagsters armed with insidious grins, raised eyebrows,
and the same boring line: ``Coffee, tea or me? Huh, honey?''
</P>
<P>
   One of my colleagues on a nightcoach from Chicago to San Juan
even mustered up a STARTLED SMILE the night she had to explain to a
young couple that if they insisted on flying ``United'' they
couldn't fly Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   And once in a while when a passenger got a little too friendly,
I'd remind him with as GRACIOUS a SMILE as I could muster that if
he didn't remove his offending hand from wherever it had come to
rest, no doubt accidentally, then I would have to call in my Uncle
Luigi, the notorious knee-cracker from the south side of Chicago,
to deal with the situation. It always worked. And everyone kept
SMILING.
</P>
<P>
   It was written in the Flight Manual, posted on the wall in
Operations, and always on the lips of our supervisors: SMILE. THAT
PASSENGER IS PAYING HIS WAY _ AND YOURS.
</P>
<P>
   That's why I'm having a hard time working up any sympathy for
the 12 Safeway employees (11 women and 1 man) in California who are
suing the store because the company thinks it's a good idea for its
employees to smile at the customers. One complains she has been
``hit on'' by men who think she is ``coming on'' to them.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Another frivolous lawsuit, another nail in the coffin of
independence and self-assurance.
</P>
<P>
   I've said it before but that won't stop me from saying it again:
We are fast becoming a nation of litigious wimps. Can't we just
grow up?
</P>
<P>
   (Elizabeth Schuett, a writer and teacher, writes for Cox News
Service. Her e-mail address: eschuett(at)nwonline.net.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
