<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR IN THE ERA OF EASY LIFTING 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HARRY ROSENFELD  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Labor Day was a fitting reminder that in this
technological age, heavy lifting isn't what it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   A strong back, physical dexterity and a stout heart are still
required for a variety of occupations. But human inventiveness has
created a multitude of machines to ease the burden for most who
toil, at home or at work. This helps to explain why Americans,
young, middle-aged and old, are tubbing up. Nowadays, instead of
relying on work to tire you out, you have to take yourself off to a
gym to raise a healthy sweat.
</P>
<P>
   We should be grateful, therefore, for having to cope in our
daily lives with another in the range of inventions intended to
improve our way of life. This is having to open all manner of
packaged goods. For our benefit or enjoyment, they are wrapped to
protect them against tampering and to give them a long shelf-life.
</P>
<P>
   The often-ingenious designs devised to fend off the undesired
impede, ineluctably, the quest of the customer to get his hands on
the actual items for which good money has been paid.
</P>
<P>
   Consider earphones just purchased, and eagerly brought home to
be connected to the stereo. You can see them, of course, alluring
and promising through their plastic wrapping. However, actually
touching them is another story. It cannot be done by using the mere
hands nature gave us. The two sides of a package, sealed with a
ferocity not to be easily overcome, will not give way no matter how
hard they're tugged.
</P>
<P>
   After several unsuccessful tries, a knife or scissors is
resorted to, and even then it takes concentration to puncture a
hole and begin to expose the earphones to the air. If, by that
time, you are not discouraged by the effort, you are disgusted by
the torn plastic strips heaped on the table.
</P>
<P>
   Plastic in its many variations is no doubt a godsend to this
upgraded lifestyle. In its thinnest guise, it is shrink-wrapped
around much desired merchandise, including compact discs. As with
the earphones, you just have to make up your mind that it will be a
while before you manage to listen to the music.
</P>
<P>
   It's not only hard goods that require special effort at
extrication. Take the ordinary milk carton, for example, something
we make use of every day.
</P>
<P>
   Who among us can boast of managing to pry open the top of a
carton of milk without tearing the edges? That carton top, properly
unfolded, is supposed to serve as a funnel through which to pour
the contents. But when torn open, it is a sorry excuse for a
funnel.
</P>
<P>
   Each new carton is a fresh challenge, time consuming and
intimidating, because we know how often in the past we have failed
to open it with the edges as straight as when they were sealed
shut. Even the greatest care is seldom rewarded with success, and
we wind up having to look at the mangled spout for as long as the
milk lasts.
</P>
<P>
   These experiences signal us, however subliminally, that we have
yet to master the varieties of benefits in which we are supposed to
revel. Dealing with these challenges is not exactly a moral
equivalent of work. For one thing, it doesn't provide the
satisfaction of real work, the sense of tangible accomplishment,
the feeling of a job forthrightly undertaken and well done.
</P>
<P>
   Our tactile skills are not up to our present availabilities,
much less possibilities yet to be devised. We are told the future
belongs to those with strong minds and lots of self-discipline. Yet
we frequently find ourselves in an environment in which we
comprehend little more than the surface of the technologies that we
are assured empower us.
</P>
<P>
   The new technologies have revolutionized how work is done and
life is lived. In an incessant accompaniment, they also provide a
background hum of low-level frustration, for understanding resides
more on the surface of these ``things.'' As a result, too often we
feel ourselves astray in this new world, a world perhaps brave but
surely inescapable.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Harry Rosenfeld is editor-at-large of the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
