A3594 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-COSTELLO-HNS &LR;      09-08 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-COSTELLO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`COSTELLO' REHASHES OLD IRISH STEREOTYPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In this era of political correctness that has virtually
paralyzed television, let's not forget that the two most abused
ethnicities are the Italians and the Irish. Always have been.
Because television thinks they are fair game and, well, neither
puts up much of a fight about it.
</P>
<P>
   Although both stereotypes will be represented this year,
consider this the Celtic comeback. There will be Irish shows, Irish
families and Irish characters spread across the channels as the
fall programming rolls out. In case you're Irish and think this is
a good thing, think again.
</P>
<P>
   You will get some fair play here and there, but for the most
part you get ``Costello'' (8:30 p.m. Tuesdays, check local
listings), the latest Fox program. Here's a show about Irish
Catholics who actually drink a lot, beat each other up, are
decidedly blue collar, have parents that are emotionless (unless
they're angry) and yell all the time.
</P>
<P>
   (If you're African American and you're thinking at this point,
``Thank God somebody else gets stereotyped this year,'' forget it _
there's an updated version of ``The Jeffersons'' just around the
corner).
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, blame part of this broad sweep on Sue Costello, who
apparently was famous enough as a stand-up comic in Boston to get
her own show even though virtually no one west of Brockton, Mass.,
had ever heard of her.
</P>
<P>
   Costello helped create what she says is an autobiographical
show. She plays Sue Murphy (why not just be Sue Costello, since
that's the show title?), a native of South Boston who just happens
to be a bartender in a ``Southie'' neighborhood. She is Irish
Catholic, the daughter of emotionally bankrupt parents, a big
drinker and someone who possesses ``a mouth on her'' that
invariably leads to yelling, arguments and fist-fighting.
</P>
<P>
   If they had just made this show about Elvis Costello, it would
be so much more enjoyable and, without question, more
groundbreaking.
</P>
<P>
   But no. This is Sue Costello's story and she's sticking to it.
Her Sue Murphy character is troubled. She's 27 and heading for
marriage to her high school sweetheart who has no ambition, so she
decides she wants to go to school and get smart. She's studying
lots of big words and she's gone to see a shrink, which makes her a
freak in the Southie neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Some people are going to flip for Costello. She's short and wiry
and mean as a weasel but also kind of endearing. ``Roseanne'' fans
are certainly the target market as this tough-but-tender approach
gets laid out.
</P>
<P>
   Others won't be able to stomach five minutes of ``Costello.''
It's as if the volume on your TV set got turned up all on its own.
When she opens her mouth its like a band saw cutting through a
particularly knot-filled piece of cherry wood. There may be subtle,
whispered moments in this show but you'd never know it. Mostly
there's yelling and swearing and a general attempt to try to get
away with murder in front of the network censors.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps if you can get past the voice and the constant
head-rattling yelling, you can find enough pieces to make this a
lovable working-class comedy. The pilot hints at this potential but
every time ``Costello'' looks to be getting ready to strike a true
chord, somebody feels the need to play up either the Irish
stereotypes or the Southie thing, which leads to predictable
cliches and makes for a mediocre pilot.
</P>
<P>
   There is an intangible here: Costello's drive. She somehow
managed to get her own show when scores of more famous stand-up
comics get passed over, so she certainly is motivated. And if this
truly is her life story and she got herself educated (Salem State
College, the University of Massachusetts) in the face of friends
and family who thought she was trying to be ``superior,'' then
maybe it's destiny. Maybe she's the next Roseanne.
</P>
<P>
   ``Costello'' benefits enormously from the ``King of the Hill''
lead-in. And maybe Hank Hill's down-home attitude _ even if he is a
cartoon _ meshes with Costello's. But there are some serious
question marks for survival here. Nobody knows if ``King of the
Hill'' can be the beachhead Tuesday show that Fox wants it to be,
and viewers are savvy enough to know that there are a lot of
half-hour sitcoms _ and good ones _ on that night, so they may opt
away from the annoying little blond buzz saw and steer toward
something funnier.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
