<HEADLINE>
ELWAY STILL VERY MUCH AT THE TOP OF HIS GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ All discussion of Monday night's 27-21 Patriots loss to
the Broncos must start and end with the fact that John Elway is
still at the top of the elite NFL quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Elway may be 38, but he dissected New England with his mind and,
yes, his 38-year-old body. That was enough to beat the Patriots,
even with Terrell Davis reduced to a nonfactor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elway may be the best that ever played,'' said Patriot
quarterback Drew Bledsoe, who, like his teammates, was not at the
best he ever played.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shot ourselves in the foot,'' was how Patriots safety
Willie Clay put it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept stopping ourselves,'' were the words of wide receiver
Shawn Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you come to Mile High to play the world champions,'' said
safety Lawyer Milloy, ``you have to have your complete package. We
didn't. We kept making too many mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Optimists can look to the fact that New England allowed the
Broncos to jump out to a 17-0 lead and didn't quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fought back,'' said Jefferson. ``There are no quitters on
this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Realists, though, can wonder why the Patriots committed a
worrisome number of bonehead plays _ jumping offsides on a punt,
calling two timeouts on the same series in the third quarter and
leaving themselves with a third and 19 and no timeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have penalties, they hurt you,'' said Bledsoe, ``but
the penalties we had hurt us more than they normally hurt you. We
had penalties on punts. They were not the kind of penalties where
you lose 5 yards and have to get back those 5 yards.''
</P>
<P>
   In sum, said Bledsoe, the Patriots ``could have made it a very
interesting ballgame if we hadn't made those mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his own performance, ``There were plays early in the game
that I could have made,'' said Bledsoe. ``There were a couple of
times early on that I could have gone in another direction than
where I did.''
</P>
<P>
   What might be equally unsettling to Patriots fans is that it was
the Denver defensive schemes that confused the Patriots _ and not
the Patriots defensive schemes that confused the Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a great defensive scheme,'' said Bledsoe. ``Their
defensive coordinator (Greg Robinson) and (Carroll) are great
friends. We knew the Broncos would have new things for us that we
weren't ready for; the stuff we were ready for I felt we did a
great job against it. But they gave us a great scheme, arguably the
best defensive scheme in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll, for his part, didn't hide his displeasure at Willie
McGinest, who was offsides on a Denver punt in the first half and
was called for roughing Elway in the second half. Denver scored TDs
on both of those revived drives, and the Patriot coach was terse in
his explanation for why McGinest was on the sidelines for a chunk
of the final quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had enough mistakes and he was cramping up,'' said Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   In summary, said the coach, ``We needed to play a terrific game
to win and we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Far from it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
