<SLUG> BC-BBN-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADMIRABLE RESTRAINT ON ESPN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ESPN's Jon Miller called Mark McGwire's 61st home run with
simple elegance Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That ball is gone if it's fair ... and it is ... a home run,
No. 61, ties Roger Maris,'' Miller announced as the Chicago Cubs'
Mike Morgan gave up the historic blast.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of waxing ad infinitum, Miller and analyst Joe Morgan
allowed the crowd to do the rest of the talking. The people at
Busch Stadium were on their feet, of course. Many wore red buttons
with ``62'' on them. They were screaming, cheering, deafeningly
appreciative of McGwire's achievement.
</P>
<P>
   No words could adequately capture the crowd's reaction. And
while the networks have milked the home run chase for as much as
they could, when it came time for this homer, less was more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I wanted to do was my job,'' Miller said.
``It's just like the opposing pitchers facing McGwire. We all have
jobs to do, no matter the situation. Mine is to deliver the most
relevant information in as timely a manner as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller knew immediately that McGwire's first-inning smash was
over the fence. The only question was whether it was fair. It was,
and for Miller, that home run replaced Cal Ripken breaking the
consecutive-games record as the biggest feat he has witnessed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing No. 60 was legendary,'' Miller said. ``But No. 61?
That's history.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan was equally impressed. The Hall of Fame second baseman
played in the game in which Hank Aaron tied Babe Ruth's career home
run record. Morgan said he was too caught up in that game to
appreciate Aaron's 714th homer, a feat Morgan considers the
greatest he's witnessed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember nodding my head at Aaron,'' Morgan said. ``But I
could not really celebrate because in reality my team had just
given up a run.''
</P>
<P>
   There was little reserve Monday. ESPN cameras caught Cubs first
baseman Mark Grace giving McGwire a high-five as the slugger
strolled around the bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, it was a tremendous achievement,'' Morgan said.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire appeared as relieved as he was excited in interviews
after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt very calm, very relaxed,'' he said. ``It all comes down
to getting a ball to hit. I'm just one swing away from breaking
it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
CBS A-OK
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CBS's ``NFL Today'' earned a respectable 3.1 rating Sunday
afternoon in the overnight ratings released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's pregame show earned a 3.7.
</P>
<P>
   CBS recently returned to the NFL after a four-year absence. And
though it came in second place, the solid performance was
encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   CBS's doubleheader coverage, which included the San Francisco
49ers' overtime victory over the New York Jets, received a slightly
higher rating than NBC's first-game coverage last year.
</P>
<P>
   CBS said Sunday's 1 p.m. game, Steelers-Ravens, pulled a 7.9
rating and 19 share, a 13 percent increase over NBC's 7.0 and 16
share last year.
</P>
<P>
   The network's 4 p.m. game, 49ers-Jets, pulled a 12.4 rating and
a 28 share, an increase of 19 percent from last year's 10.4 rating
and 24 share on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's 1 p.m. game, Packers-Lions, pulled a 11.7 rating and 28
share. One rating point equals 980,000 households.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's happy,'' said CBS spokeswoman Leslie Anne Wade.
</P>
</TEXT>
