<SLUG> BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2-YEAR-OLDS DID NOTHING TO DISTINGUISH THEMSELVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Both the handicap division, headed by Skip Away's six
consecutive wins, and the 3-year-olds, with Real Quiet, Victory
Gallop, and Coronado's Quest excelling, have produced plenty of
thrills this year. However, not much of interest has occurred with
the 2-year-olds. The $200,000 Hopeful Stakes at Saratoga often
points out the best 2-year-old in the East, but Saturday's running
of the most prestigious juvenile event at The Spa did not do so, as
Lucky Roberto, a New York-bred off at 9-1 ($20.20 to win), took the
race.
</P>
<P>
   A big loser in the Hopeful was trainer D. Wayne Lukas, who sent
out two promising colts in Tactical Cat, at 2-1, and Time Bandit,
at 5-2; but they could do no better than second and third,
respectively. Another loser was 9-5 favorite Prime Directive, the
winner of the Saratoga Special Aug. 19, who finished fifth in the
Hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky Roberto, trained by Frank Alexander and ridden by Robbie
Davis, wore down front-runner Tactical Cat, who was handled by
Jerry Bailey, in the stretch to prevail by a length in the time of
1:234/5 for 7 furlongs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The race set up just like I thought it would, and I wasn't
surprised at all that my horse won,'' said Alexander. ``This horse
has been doing very well and he has been doing everything right. I
told Robbie to just let him settle in and then let him do his own
running. I knew the distance was going to help him. He acts like he
can run all day.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been some excellent New York-breds, but it is highly
unlikely that Lucky Roberto, a son of Belong to Me, is going to
turn out to be the top juvenile in the East, even though he does
have a nice record of 4-2-1-0 that includes a second behind
Tactical Cat in the Tremont Stakes at Belmont July 4. More will be
known after the running of the $150,000 Belmont Futurity Sept. 20,
contested at a mile. That is where Lucky Roberto is scheduled to
run next, and Lukas expects to enter his top 2-year-old gun, Yes
It's True, who won the $200,000 Sapling Stakes at Monmouth Aug. 22
by more than 7 lengths.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would certainly say this is our best one at this point,''
said Lukas after the Sapling.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe the best 2-year-old in the East didn't run at Saratoga
at all.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
A quick spin
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the most accomplished 2-year-old to run at
Saratoga this season is the filly Things Change. A daughter of
Stalwart, Things Change captured the $200,000 Spinaway, the filly
version of the Hopeful, by more than 4 lengths under Jose Santos.
Off at 2-1 ($6 to win), Things Change closed strongly, negotiating
the seven panels in 1:244/5.
</P>
<P>
   Trained by Linda Rice, who is outstanding with 2-year-olds,
Things Change also took the Adirondack Aug. 17 and has won three of
four starts, her lone loss coming when she finished second in her
debut. The Spinaway gave Rice her first Grade I victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was concerned because I wanted to see her closer to the
lead,'' said Rice. ``Jose never panicked, though; he just let
things unfold. He let her settle in, and when he engaged her, she
responded. This race exhibits that the distances won't bother
her.''
</P>
<P>
   Next for Things Change will be the $400,000 Frizette Stakes, at
a mile and one-16th, on the Breeders' Cup Preview Day card at
Belmont Oct. 10.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Tough way to return
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lil's Lad, a top Triple Crown contender until he chipped his
left front ankle in the Blue Grass Stakes at Keeneland April 11,
returned to the races at Saratoga Saturday and ran fourth as the
1-2 favorite.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to know what choices were available to trainer
Neil Howard in the condition book, but he picked a bear of a
$50,000 allowance race against older horses for the return of Lil's
Lad. The three veterans who finished ahead of him in the 6
1/2-furlong dash, run in 1:153/5, were, respectively, Pyramid Peak,
Diligence, and Trafalger, all graded stakes winners.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Material from publicity departments at various racetracks was
used in this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
