<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY GORBY LOOKS GOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The midterm election campaign kicks off this week and
businesspeople, at least the businesspeople I know, are extremely
uneasy.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as a couple of weeks ago, the expectation was that
the Democrats would pick up a few seats nationally, cut the GOP's
11-vote majority, possibly even retake the House of
Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Such a shift would have set the stage for the Republicans to
retake the White House in 2000, without upsetting the checks and
balances of divided government.
</P>
<P>
   Now, some forecasters are expecting a Republican pickup _
perhaps as many as 10 or 15 seats.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the problem? Simply that the prospect of unchecked GOP
rule is profoundly unsettling to businessfolk.
</P>
<P>
   For last six years, it has been the Democrats who have been the
stewards of free trade and a growing international economy, while
the Republicans have shown themselves prone to capture by religious
and ideological factions.
</P>
<P>
   Today, even Mikhail Gorbachev is looking pretty good. He was
Russia's leader the last time a Republican occupant of the White
House had to make a difficult choice.
</P>
<P>
   George Bush bet on Boris Yeltsin _ but the strategy for Russian
reform has turned out to be a disasterous mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of sending in American corporations to work side-by-side
with Russia's bureaucratic ministeries to create giant corporations
susceptible to orderly devolution _ which was one logical response
to the end of the 50-year Cold War _ Bush bet that Yeltsin could
preside over an orderly ``big bang.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorbachev predicted that the attempt to privatize Russia's
assets without simultaneously maintaining a good deal of central
control would lead to massive corruption. And so it has.
</P>
<P>
   The idea that you can pop a macroeconomic system on a highly
developed command economy now has been discredited. The mess in
Russia was brought to you in part by the conservative Heritage
Foundation, whose trademark neckties Yeltsin used to sport.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it just Russia that has raised doubts about the wisdom of
the GOP strategic vision. Take the spectacle of Kenneth Starr's
pursuit of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   It was Bush who first placed Starr on the national stage, by
naming him soliciter general. The spectacle of the the Bush
administration's chief lawyer tormenting Clinton with questions
about the intimate details about his sex life, in the manner of
Torquemada, surely is highly embarrassing to the former president.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, too, must worry about his place in history _ and Starr has
turned out to be no better bet than Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   However it is the specter of a Republican Congress with a
veto-proof, even filibuster-proof majority that is really causing
big business political strategists to think hard about the future.
And I don't mean just the difference of opinion over how best to
structure future tax cuts _ say, eliminating the marriage penalty
in the personal income tax as opposed to stimulating capital
formation.
</P>
<P>
   The conservative leadership of the Republican Party that came to
power in 1980 was fresh, powerful, and had a few simple good ideas.
The second generation of that leadership is overripe. Populists,
protectionists, religious conservatives in the GOP vie with one
another to promote dubious ideas.
</P>
<P>
   They want to derail fast-track negotiating authority for trade
agreements, end well-established affirmative action programs in
governments and corporations, restrict immigration, tie
anti-abortion and school prayer measures to bills as unrelated as
trade with China and funding for the International Monetary
Authority. Big business is skeptical of it all.
</P>
<P>
   For 75 years, ever since Warren Harding swept into office on the
strength of promise to ``Return to Prosperity,'' America's business
culture has identified its interests with those of the Republican
Party. With the GOP increasingly dominated by ideologues, moralists
and sore losers, a historic reallignment looms.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Warsh writes about economics for the Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)nws.globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
