u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-08 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRUNK AND WHITE MEET THE CLASS OF '02 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Delivering a freshman to college last week, I wasn't surprised
to find that William Strunk Jr. and E.B. White's ``Elements of
Style'' _ relied upon by generations of students since Strunk's
solo version appeared in 1918 _ was still required reading, or at
least required buying, for aspiring writers. But I hadn't realized
that the book was as old as the freshmen are: The third edition,
apparently last revised in 1979, is the one on offer on bookstore
shelves.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen is not an advanced age, of course, either for people or
for books. S&AMP;W's reassuringly slim, no-nonsense volume still has
much good advice on the virtues of simplicity, the importance of
parallelism, and other basics of prose style. But its roots go much
further back than the '70s, and in some respects it is showing its
age. For example, S&AMP;W fret a good deal about wordiness and
pomposity, but teachers today seem less concerned with suppressing
bombast than with wringing any sustained writing effort from their
television-addled charges.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the chapter called ``Misused Words and Expressions''
that seems the most dated. Despite their graceful acknowledgment,
elsewhere in the book, that language is a living, changing
organism, S&AMP;W are firm, even dogmatic, in their denunciation of
certain usages _ some of which have been standard English since the
class of '02 babbled its first syllables.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the verb contact, much reviled by usage
authorities in the first half of the century, is still condemned as
``vague and self-important'' by S&AMP;W in 1979. ``Do not contact
anybody,'' they order; ``get in touch with him, or look him up,''
and so on.
</P>
<P>
   The adjectives ongoing and offputting are also ruled out of
order, although earlier words formed the same way _ oncoming,
outgoing _ are quite acceptable. But both ongoing and offputting
are standard today, if not equally widespread; ongoing has the
flavor of New World ambition _ shorten those words, sell those
trombones! _ while offputting has a British feel, perhaps because
Americans are less inclined to be merely ``put off'' by the
deficiencies of their neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   S&AMP;W's strictures, at any rate, are ongoing. Kind of and sort of,
they tell readers, are ``not to be used as a substitute for rather
or something like, but should be used only in a literal sense.''
Thus, when Ado Annie sings ``I only did the kinda things I orta _
sorta,'' the ``Oklahoma'' femme fatale is using kind of correctly
and sort of incorrectly. Feeling sort of confused? Sorry, that's
not allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Occupied with these battles, S&AMP;W did not foresee that baby
boomers would refuse to abandon their slang on schedule: ``By the
time this book sees print,'' they declared, ``uptight, ripoff, rap,
dude, vibes, copout, and funky will be the words of yesteryear.''
And so they are, but they also remain in daily use, though some
have new meanings and others have acquired a halo of irony with the
passing years.
</P>
<P>
   But there's something to be said for S&AMP;W's usage pronouncements:
They'll give students an instant history lesson, their very flaws
illuminating how quickly and unpredictably language can change.
Where else would a college freshman learn that you must not
personalize your stationery, since personalize is a vulgar
neologism? What you want to do, according to Strunk &AMP; White, is
``Get up a letterhead.'' They don't say when the expression was
current, but those are unmistakably the words of yesteryear.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Only last month I was noting the rapid spread of wax on as a
synonym for talk, chatter _ recently seen not only in the Globe but
in Newsweek and the Wall Street Journal (``Mr. Stone, a
surgical-equipment repairman, waxes on about how well his deck
matches his contemporary home.'') But wax on isn't the only meaning
shift making inroads this summer. There was the discussion on ``The
Connection'' last month in which Tovia Smith, speaking of President
Clinton's deposition in the Paula Jones case, observed, ``The
president did seem to couch his answers ... Is there a problem
there?''
</P>
<P>
   Couch, however, needs a prepositional phrase to complete it,
just as wax needs an adjective. He couched his language in vague
terms? in high-flown metaphors? in sports slang? Or is couch coming
to mean simply ``measured'' or ``weighed'' his words?
</P>
<P>
   Then there's this innovation from a recent Time magazine:
``Apple's low-cost Imac is a design statement bar none.'' Again,
there's a missing word: ``Imac is the best-designed computer, bar
none'' is the meaning here; bar none means ``excepting none,''
though Time's writer seems to think it's a synonym for
``extraordinaire.''
</P>
<P>
   These are not, I think, examples of one-time gaffes _ those are
easy to find, especially in television and radio, as when Joe
Mantegna, describing Dean Martin, referred to ``some kind of enigma
that he had.'' No, wax and pit, and possibly bar none, are language
in motion, for better or worse. Readers are invited to contribute
other examples of such slippage, whether to celebrate or to mourn;
like it or hate it, it's our language in search of its future self.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (What's the word? Write or e-mail yours to Jan Freeman at The
Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107-2378; freeman(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
