<SLUG> BC-FBN-QUATERBACKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL QUATERBACKS: OLD GUYS DO IT BEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GWEN KNAPP  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Who is the next great one, the quarterback of
the future?
</P>
<P>
   Everyone keeps asking, in print, on the air. Peyton Manning or
Ryan Leaf? Their contracts went platinum. Their hype went through
the ozone. Now what can we expect?
</P>
<P>
   Probably this: Steve DeBerg as the quarterback of the future.
</P>
<P>
   He is 44 and he is back, because behind center these days, you
can't keep a marginally competent old codger down. More to the
point, you can't keep sensationally talented, lavishly paid,
breathlessly anticipated young quarterbacks up.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Steve Young's goal of playing until 40 looks more and
more realistic all the time. He may turn creaky, but he can't turn
into an outrageously expensive young savior. He's been there. He's
done that. It was an overrated experience. But it's valuable now,
at a time when any experience constitutes an advantage, when creaky
trumps callow.
</P>
<P>
   The twentysomethings simply aren't challenging the elders. Brett
Favre and Mark Brunell are young superstars, and Drew Bledsoe has
certified credentials. But their peers aren't altogether reliable.
There doesn't seem to be a Jim McMahon or Phil Simms in the bunch.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Mirer and Heath Shuler, ostensibly sure things, can barely
hand off competently. Trent Dilfer survives in Tampa Bay only
because of his running backs and coach Tony Dungy's exceptional
patience.
</P>
<P>
   The three of them make a case for a new draft-day rule: Never
take a quarterback whose name ends in the letters ``er.'' If Jake
Plummer and Jim Druckenmiller both go belly-up, the rule should
become a commandment.
</P>
<P>
   Those two, however, didn't go in the top six picks of their
draft. Mirer, Shuler and Dilfer all did.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle thought Mirer was going to be the Bledsoe of the Pacific
Northwest. Five years after the Seahawks drafted him, Mirer has
been dumped by two teams, and Seattle is squeezing juice out of
Warren Moon's 41-year-old arm.
</P>
<P>
   Moon is another quarterback of the future, coming to us from
deep in the past. He can still outplay more than half of the
quarterbacks in the league. Where are the players who should be
forcing him out?
</P>
<P>
   It will be interesting to watch what happens in Buffalo, where
Doug Flutie could become the feel-good story of the season. Exiled
in the Canadian Football League for most of his career, dismissed
as too small for the National Football League, he just might take
over for Rob Johnson, the $25 Million Kid, at some point and fill
our bleak Sundays with wild scrambles and free-lance passes.
</P>
<P>
   He is 35, and his feet should have lost a spark or two. But if
Tom Watson can win a golf tournament at 48, if Tom Candiotti and
Danny Darwin can still find work in the major leagues, if Michael
can make 35 look like prime time, then maybe Flutie is just getting
started.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson may not relinquish the job, but he could also turn into
another Scott Mitchell, lured out of obscurity in Florida by
free-agency riches, only to flounder in the Rust Belt.
</P>
<P>
   It's a sign of the Bills' desperation that Johnson converted one
professional start into $25 million. And the Bills are not unique.
Most NFL teams are flailing about, trying to find the next Elway,
Marino, Kelly, Young, etc.
</P>
<P>
   All of these elders went through their own rough times. John
Elway and Steve Young were both, in their early days, seen as
symbols of decline in modern football. Elway manipulated the draft
by refusing to report to Baltimore, and Young signed a
budget-busting $40 million deal with the USFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the headlines,'' Young said. ``Everyone said it was
the end of sports.''
</P>
<P>
   They both persevered, and now, in their late 30s, they seem to
be in no hurry to depart. Elway talked about retirement after the
Super Bowl, but he couldn't let go of the game.
</P>
<P>
   And at 37 last year, he seemed younger and healthier than he had
in his early 30s. He underwent shoulder surgery and came out of it
with raves for the procedure. Not too many years ago, when a knife
went into a football player, his career might have been saved, but
it wasn't enhanced.
</P>
<P>
   Modern medicine allows the players to patch themselves up and
jump back into the fray in no time. Modern defensive schemes,
meanwhile, prevent younger players from immediately entrenching
themselves in starting jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Free agency may also be impeding the development of the next
generation of quarterbacks. Every year, teams must play musical
chairs with their rosters. Nowhere is that more disruptive than
along the offensive line. A new lineman throws off the rhythm of an
offense, and the quarterback is bound to fall out of synch.
</P>
<P>
   An old-timer can make adjustments more easily (assuming that he
survives the mind-altering collisions that come with disarray in
the trenches). A fledgling, no matter how talented, needs the
harmony of a stable lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Today's youngsters should have one advantage. In the last 10
years, most major colleges have started running pro-style offenses.
Yet the quarterbacks come to the NFL even less prepared than
before.
</P>
<P>
   Even those who thrive tend to retreat after a year or so. Some
of the floundering defies explanation. Jeff Blake seemed to have a
great future in Cincinnati, if anyone can be said to have a great
future in Cincinnati. Now his job is threatened by Neil O'Donnell,
whose continued presence in the NFL illustrates the shallowness of
the quarterbacking pool.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Collins flew high for Carolina in 1996, then came down
like an Icarus in shoulder pads last year. Collins may piece it all
together again. If not, Steve McNair, Elvis Grbac and Kordell
Stewart could stand up for their generation.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, the future belongs to the old men, not to the
Heaths, Ryans, Trents or Peytons. This is, for better or worse, the
Year of DeBerg.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
