<HEADLINE>
SUMMER FUN NOT OVER JUST YET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now, many travelers realize that September and beyond can be the
ideal time to head for the shore _ Jersey, Cape Cod, Maine, New
Hampshire _ you name it. The weather is fine, the water is still
warm, certainly crowds are fewer and smaller, prices are lower at
resorts and inns, and there are festivals galore.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Hampton Beach in New Hampshire waits until Labor
Day is over to hold its biggest and one of its best celebrations,
the annual Seafood Festival. There's no admission to the festival,
it's strictly a pay-as-you-eat affair, and you'll find more than 50
area restaurants cooking under colorful tents along Ocean
Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   You'll find favorites such as lobster, shrimp, clams _ steamed,
broiled, barbecued, or fried _ as well as non-seafood items. There
will be entertainment from two oceanside stages, a crafts fair,
children's activities, sidewalk sales, fireworks (Sept. 12 at 8
p.m.), and Louie the Lobster and friends will again sky-dive onto
Hampton Beach (Sept. 12 at 6 p.m.).
</P>
<P>
   Hampton Beach is just about an hour from Boston, so it's easy to
reach, but should you want to stay for the weekend, many lodgings
are offering off-season rates.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Ocean Boulevard will be closed for the festival, but
free shuttle service is available from area parking lots (regular
parking fees are in effect). Parking meters are in effect in the
area, and, sorry, but pets are not welcome, especially with Ted the
Cat, a Seacoast personality, joining street performers for the
festival. Just bring your appetite and enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   The festival is 11 a.m. to 8 p.m. Sept. 12, and 11 a.m. to 6
p.m. on the 13th. For more information, call the Hampton Beach Area
Chamber of Commerce at 603-926-8717.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton Beach is extending its summer season even one week more.
Sept. 18-20 will see the first annual Hampton Beach Seniors
Appreciation Days. The festival is mostly free, and will feature
lots of activities for seniors, including square dancing, bingo,
and antique autos. The Artie Shaw Orchestra will perform in the
legenday Casino Ballroom on Sept. 18 from 7 to 11 p.m. Tickets are
$15.50 a person and can be obtained by calling the Casino at
603-929-4100.
</P>
<P>
   And, should you be interested in the Jersey Shore and happenings
there, give a call to 800-JERSEY-7. The Miss America Pageant will
be held Sept. 15-19 in Atlantic City, and it's now just one of many
post-Labor Day events.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Chocolate heaven
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hotel Meridien in Boston will bring back its famed Chocolate
Bar for its 10th season beginning Sept. 12. The buffet features
more than 25 different chocolate desserts from mousses and ice
creams to cakes and the hotel's signature chocolate croissant
pudding. The bar is open every Saturday from 1 p.m. to 3 p.m.
through the end of May. The bar is $16.50 for adults, $7.75 for
those 13 and younger. For reservations, call 617-451-1900, ext.
7125.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Grape fest
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Have you ever wanted to jump into a barrel and stomp on grapes?
You can, at just one of the happenings at the first grape harvest
festival at Boyden Valley Winery in Cambridge, Vt. The farm, in the
same family for four generations, uses only organically grown fruit
from Vermont farms. From 2 p.m. until dusk on Sept. 12-13, the
winery will celebrate with live music, free winery tours and
tastings, a chance to watch craftspeople at work, and a hayride.
Boyden Valley Winery is near Smugglers' Notch and Mount Mansfield.
The farm is open for tastings Tuesday through Sunday through Dec.
31. For information, call 802-644-8151.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sabbath Trail
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Worshipers from around the country will gather Saturday (Sept.
12) at a tiny country church in New Hampshire to dedicate the
Sabbath Trail.
</P>
<P>
   It was 150 years ago that pioneer Seventh-day Adventists studied
the Bible together at the church in Washington (N.H.) and
determined that Saturday was the biblical day of worship.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabbath Trail will be dedicated at the site where Adventists
first observed the Saturday Sabbath. Forty granite markers with
biblical texts and historical descriptions of people who observed a
seventh-day Sabbath through history line the mile-long loop through
the forest. The day will include a worship service at 9:15 a.m.,
concert at 2 p.m., and dedication at 2:45 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The church is near Route 31 about 10 miles west of Hillsboro.
For information, call Merlin Knowles, pastor of the church, at
603-298-5757. Tourists wishing to visit the church when it is not
open (it is used only from May through October) and read the old
gravestones in the churchyard can get the key at the general store
in town, where they can also pick up a generous hot fudge sundae,
we're told.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Open a B&AMP;B?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you've ever been interested in opening a bed-and-breakfast or
operating a country inn, an upcoming one-day seminar might be just
what you need. The Sept. 19 seminar, co-sponsored by Country Inns
magazine, features a program led by experienced innkeepers who
promise to reveal ``the realities of what it takes to run a
bed-and-breakfast.'' The seminar at the Doubletree Guest Suites
Hotel in Waltham is $149 a person. For information, call
888-201-7602.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Good deals
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The French Railpass now comes with bonuses such as free entrance
to museums, discounts on a cruise, and more. Passes begin at $132
for three days' travel within a 30-day period. For information,
call Rail Europe at 888-382-7245.
</P>
<P>
   Holland America Line is offering two-for-one fares on cruises to
Asia, the Panama Canal, and across the Atlantic. The cruises are
for sailings beginning Oct. 20 through Dec. 3.
</P>
