<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A POWERFUL PRESENCE IN ST. LOUIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ST. LOUIS _ Mark McGwire is a very nice fit for the Cardinals.
In less than a season and a half, he has won the hearts of fans in
St. Louis, home to one of baseball's oldest and most traditional
franchises.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire has been elevated to a status in this city previously
reserved for Hall of Famers Stan Musial, Lou Brock, and Bob Gibson,
and soon-to-be Hall of Famer Ozzie Smith. In the long history of
the Cardinals, which goes back to 1892, there never has been
anything like McGwire's impact in so short a time.
</P>
<P>
   How has McGwire stood up under all this attention? Better than
you might think. While Roger Maris was hounded by fans and media in
his run to 61 home runs in 1961, McGwire practically has been on
cruise control in an era where media scrutiny has brought down many
sports heroes.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, who matched Maris with his 61st home run Monday,
undoubtedly is helped by the fact that he has dealt with the
spotlight since he was a rookie for Oakland. That year, 1987, he
hit 49 home runs, a record for a first-year player. He was a part
of four A's teams that won division titles and played in three
World Series, so he is no stranger to media attention. Along the
way he made a lot of friends who appreciate his frankness and
honesty under stressful conditions.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993 and '94, though, McGwire dropped out of sight when
recurrent back injuries limited him to 27 and 47 games,
respectively. When he returned, the A's were only a shadow of the
team that dominated in the late '80s, though he never gave up on
his own ability. McGwire batted .312 in 1996 and was hitting .284
when he was dealt to the Cardinals July 31, 1997 as part of a
rebuilding project in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis fans quickly learned what Oakland fans had known for
years. McGwire is not only talented but also very loyal. If the 24
home runs he hit in only 51 games last season didn't win over the
Cardinal faithful, his signing of a three-year contract worth 28.5
million did. McGwire, who could have gotten more money elsewhere as
a free agent, said that, among other things, he relished the sense
of tradition in St. Louis, something that was missing in Oakland.
He had no idea how much the St. Louis fans would enjoy having him.
</P>
<P>
   Largely because of McGwire, the Cardinals are projected to draw
a club-record 3.2 million fans this year, even though they are
under .500 and more than 20 games behind the Houston Astros in the
NL Central. McGwire reportedly has a clause in his contract that
earns him $1 a ticket for every seat sold beyond 2.8 million. Not a
bad return, and a bonus he surely has merited.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Making an impact
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the Cardinals decided for economic purposes to move
their Hall of Fame out of Busch Stadium. It now shares a facility
with the International Bowling Museum, across the street from the
park. Attendance at the new combined Hall has gone up 40 percent,
according to marketing director James F. Baer, and the reason is
clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We already have some of McGwire's things,'' said Baer. ``We'd
love to have home run ball No. 62 on the way to Cooperstown. But
that's up to Mark. We already have a Home Run Chase exhibit. Of
course, the complete Cardinal history is available.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's arrival in St. Louis has helped in other areas.
Downtown hotels and restaurants are thriving. Business has
improved. The Cardinals are at least as popular as the NFL's Rams
and NHL's Blues, both of whom have new downtown stadiums as
attractions. On Sunday, 65,000 watched the Rams in the Trans World
Dome, while 47,000 were at Busch to see the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people are saying is that Mark is a really great
Cardinal,'' said Baer. ``It's a real love affair. Sometimes you
find a guy who is breaking records and is a big jerk. Most people
who come here think Mark is really natural and down to earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he's not a guy you see off the field a lot, but we all
know about the time and money he puts into his Foundation for
Abused Children.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire not only knows how to handle the media demands, but he's
also able to defuse controversy like few other athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should I allow other things to derail me when I come to
the park?,'' said McGwire after hitting his 60th home run Saturday.
After going 0 for 3 Friday night, he did not grant any interviews,
but on Saturday, he spoke after the game for almost an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather do my normal things, and go about my business like
I am supposed to,'' he said. ``There really isn't much to talk
about prior to a game. If I don't hit a home run, I don't think I
have to come into the interview room to analyze every swing and
every pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Aiming to please
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McGwire says his schedule is only slightly different on the
road. Normally, he reserves all interviews for the first day of any
series. (Exceptions are made for national television outlets.) If
he hits a home run, he is always available.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's teammates love having him around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Day in and day out,'' said pitcher Kent Bottenfield, ``I've
never seen him worry about things. If he goes 0 for 3 or 3 for 3
and hits three line drives for singles, he's just the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tip my cap to Sammy. But if you make a perfect pitch to
Sammy he's going to make an out. With Mark, you never know. You
battle to get a hitter behind and get a pitch he can't swing at.
With Sammy you can do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that he's out there trying and we
appreciate this. Hitting 50 home runs three years in a row is a
hard thing to do. But sometimes he makes it look so easy that
people on the outside looking in wonder out loud.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 1316EDT &QL; 
