<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3621 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-HURRICANE-2TAKES-     09-08 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-HURRICANE-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPEAT OF THE '38 HURRICANE WOULD BE MORE DAMAGING, LESS DEADLY 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ Nobody knew it was coming. The morning of Wednesday,
Sept. 21, 1938, dawned to cloudy skies and a forecast of rain, but
nobody had the slightest clue that New England was about to get
walloped by a hurricane that for decades would rank as the most
damaging storm in the nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   In a few brief hours, some rivers reached record flood levels. A
gust of wind at the Blue Hill Observatory in Milton was measured at
186 m.p.h.; for decades it was the second-highest wind speed ever
recorded on this planet. Phone and electric lines _ 20,000 miles of
them _ were knocked down, leaving seven-eighths of New England's
homes without power. Nearly 100 bridges washed out, and almost
9,000 homes were destroyed. An estimated 275 million trees were
snapped or uprooted. And more than 600 people perished in the
blinding wind, rain, and waves.
</P>
<P>
   New Englanders abruptly learned the hard way that hurricanes
were not just a tropical concern.
</P>
<P>
   Largely as a result, the region was far better prepared during
large hurricanes that followed in the 40s and 50s, and today with
improved satellite systems and computer analysis there would be
enough warning to avert most of the loss of life from a similar
storm. But the vast increase in development along the coast could
make the physical damage even greater.
</P>
<P>
   Although the storm was considered unprecedented in 1938, it
turned out that New England had been hit before, and would be hit
many times again _ though not in the 60 years since with such
ferocity.
</P>
<P>
   Far more people _ an estimated 6,000 _ had died in the famous
Galveston flood of 1900, which was caused by a hurricane that
originated in the same area off the coast of Africa; and the
earthquake and fire that hit San Francisco in 1906 left more
memorable images of destruction and ruin; but nothing short of war
had ever caused as much devastation in this country as the
hurricane of '38. And no storm on record anywhere in the world, up
to that time, had caused so much damage.
</P>
<P>
   Most weather forecasters at the time believed that hurricanes
always veered out to sea before they could strike the New England
coast, so even though this storm was being tracked as it moved
rapidly northward _ much faster than most hurricanes do, sometimes
at speeds exceeding 50 m.p.h. _ the official forecast from the
National Weather Bureau, even that morning, made no mention of a
hurricane. It was just a run-of-the-mill storm warning.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Emanuel, professor of meteorology at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology and a specialist in hurricane modelling,
says ``there was one renegade forecaster in Washington who thought
it was going to hit New England, but nobody believed him.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Clark, acting chief of the Weather Bureau at the time,
later explained that the forecasters ``could hardly have given any
greater advance warning, for the tropical storm _ the worst in the
history of the Northeast _ was a freak; it did not follow the usual
pattern...''
</P>
<P>
   Later analysis of historical records made it clear that the
storm was not a freak. In fact, New England had suffered at least
two equally devastating hurricanes: One in 1815, and, earlier, in
1635, soon after the Mayflower colonists arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Governor William Bradford wrote about the storm of 1635, calling
it ``such a mighty storm of wind &AMP; raine, as none living in these
parts, either English or Indeans, ever saw.'' He described it,
quite accurately, as resembling the ``Haurricanes'' of the West
Indies. He wrote that it blew down many hundred thousands of trees,
and that ``the signs and marks of it will remaine this 100 years in
these parts where it was sorest.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  It was also described by Increase Mather as ``a most terrible
storm ... whereby we were in as much danger, as I think ever people
were.''
</P>
<P>
   The great hurricane of 1815 was of similar scale, and by then
the region had been substantially built up, so the damage was more
devastating. John Farrar, a professor from the University of
Cambridge, wrote that ``Our orchards and forests exhibited a scene
of desolation, which has never been witnessed before to such an
extent in this country.... A considerable proportion of the large
and beautiful trees in Boston mall (on the common) and in the
public walk near the grainery burying ground, several of which
measured from 8 to 12 feet in circumference, were torn up by the
roots and prostrated.... there seems to be no part of the coast of
New England which escaped its fury.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver Wendell Holmes lived through the 1815 hurricane as a boy
of seven, and later described his recollection of ``a mighty
howling, roaring, banging, and crashing, with much running about
... and battening down of everything that could flap or fly away.''
He wrote a poem about the storm, which included this description:
``Lord! How the ponds and rivers boiled!/ They seemed like bursting
craters,/ And oaks lay scattered on the ground/ As if they were
p'taters.''
</P>
<P>
   Those writings endured, but the passage of time erased the
memory of hurricanes from the consciousness of New Englanders, and
even of meteorologists. They were caught completely unprepared by
the howling wind, driving rain, and merciless surf of that
September day in 1938.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 1317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3623 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-HURRICANE-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     09-08 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-HURRICANE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... in 1938.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Things changed fast after that, however. Shaken into action
by the devastation, Congress approved funding for the creation of a
National Hurricane Center, and the US Army Corps of Engineers began
an ambitious program of flood-control projects that went on for
decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``That storm was the first of a series of wake-up calls'' that
brought about the changes, said Emanuel.
</P>
<P>
   The dams and storm barriers erected by the Corps of Engineers,
and the enormous improvements in forecasting brought about later by
satellites and better computer models of weather systems, have
combined to make coastal areas far better prepared for the next
raging hurricane that may strike this region. But that's not the
whole story.
</P>
<P>
   For at the same time, the population has grown, and the
development along vulnerable coastal areas has been especially
vigorous. Not only are there far more oceanfront houses, but they
are typically much larger and more expensive than the summer
cottages of earlier times. Researchers Roger Pielke of the National
Center for Climate Research and Christopher Landsea of the National
Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration have analyzed all the
recorded major storms of this century and calculated how much
property damage might result if the same storms struck today.
</P>
<P>
   By their reckoning, the hurricane of 1938 would now cause more
than $16 billion in damage _ more than all but three other US
storms since 1925, and all but five in this century. (The
recordholder would be an unnamed hurricane that struck Florida in
1926; they figure it would have topped $72 billion in damage today.
Hurricane Andrew, in 1992, ranks second at $33 billion.)
</P>
<P>
   The 1938 storm's unusually rapid motion was part of the reason
it caused so much damage _ and still would today. There would have
been little time to mount an evacuation, even if one had been
ordered, because the storm was barrelling along at more than 50
m &UR; . &LR; p &UR; . &LR; h &UR; . &LR;  Typically, hurricanes travel 10 to 20 m.p.h.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even today, it would be a challenge to get people in New
England to take it as seriously'' as people do in the Southeast,
where hurricanes are so much more frequent, said Rutherford Platt,
a University of Massachusetts/Amherst specialist in land use and
planning. ``It was such a fast moving storm ... if you had just 24
hours, it might take some doing to get people to leave their
beachfront communities.''
</P>
<P>
   The storm's forward speed added to its ferocity in another way
as well: Because hurricanes consist of a swirling mass of winds
circling counterclockwise around a calm center, the winds on the
east side of the hurricane's eye actually are amplified by the
forward motion. While the sustained winds around the eye were
clocked at around 90 m.p.h., when the storm hit, that velocity was
relative to the storm center. Measured on the ground, the winds to
the east roared with the speed of the storm itself added to that,
producing speeds of 140 m.p.h., in places _ and gusts even
stronger. Blue Hill measured sustained winds (averaged over five
minutes) of 121 m &UR; . &LR; p &UR; . &LR; h &UR; . &LR; , along with the record-setting gust of
186 _ and that was far from the storm's peak force, to the west
near the Connecticut river.
</P>
<P>
   Charles F. Brooks, who was director of the Blue Hill Observatory
at the time, wrote later that the hurricane of 1938 had ``rushed
northward to Long Island and New England with the speed of an
express train,'' building wind velocities to 120 m.p.h., on the
eastward part of its path. Striking the coast just at the time of
one of the year's highest tides, the storm's waves ``threw the sea
to such heights that demolition was general along the exposed
coast, and they came so suddenly that hundreds of persons, some of
them at the shore to watch the fine surf, were engulfed and
drowned.''
</P>
<P>
   Plants 20 miles inland were killed by the salt spray, Brooks
wrote, and traces of the salt could be found 50 miles from the
coast.
</P>
<P>
   Long Island and Connecticut bore the brunt of the storm, but
central Massachusetts took an unusually heavy pounding as well, as
the hurricane maintained its strength well into Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   Physical reminders of the 1938 hurricane _ and even of those of
1815 and 1635 _ are still preserved in some of New England's salt
marshes. Thompson Webb III, a professor of geology at Brown
University, has been studying the layers of sand blown across the
dunes and into the salt marshes by great hurricanes. Because sea
level has been rising steadily since the end of the last ice age,
these deposits form a layered sequence in which the history of the
region's storms lies indelibly written. Webb calls his research
``paleotempestology'' _ the study of ancient storms.
</P>
<P>
   Webb says four sand layers can be clearly distinguished in core
samples that span the last four centuries, taken from his principal
research site at Succotash salt marsh in Rhode Island: Those laid
down in 1635, 1815, and 1938 are the thickest; a thinner layer
marks the passage of Hurricane Carol in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to make absolute comparisons of the ferocity of
different storms from such layers, because there are so many
localized differences. But the 1938 hurricane, striking without
warning after several days of soaking rain had swelled the rivers,
was ``almost an ideally bad storm,'' says Emanuel. ``It came
barreling in unannounced on a high tide _ it couldn't have been
worse.''
</P>
<P>
   But it still could get worse. Some projections of global warming
suggest that sea level could rise by three feet over the next
century, and if that happens, another such storm ``would be a lot
more devastating,'' Emanuel says. ``That's something to be worried
about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
