<SLUG> BC-BBN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINAL SLUGGER HAD A BALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ He knew.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew today because it was a lot higher than Monday's, and as
soon as it left my bat I put my hands up,'' said Mark McGwire, who
now has had 448 career opportunities to assess the trajectory of a
home run, but only one chance to watch a record-tying 61st leave
the premises.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday afternoon in Busch Stadium, McGwire launched a missile
down the left-field line in the sixth inning. When it left the bat,
it was clearly going to be a matter of fair or foul _ there is
never any uncertainty about the length of a McGwire home run _ and
it wound up hooking foul by 7 or 8 feet, depending on which
``official'' estimate you believe.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire said he realized that one would wind up on the wrong
side of the foul pole. But he was equally sure that the 1-and-1
pitch he hit Monday off Cubs veteran Mike Morgan in the bottom of
the first would be the historic No. 61 that would tie him with
Roger Maris in only the 143d game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably hooked foul past the pole,'' McGwire said. ``But I
knew at that time, and what a feeling it was; I'll tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   The ball hit glass in front of the restaurant situated between
the lower and upper decks, just below something known as ``Big Mac
Land'' (a special section sponsored by You-Know-Who) and ricocheted
into the lower stands, where it was recovered by one Mike Davidson,
a 28-year-old St. Louis resident. The official distance estimate
was 430 feet. The actual distance through time and space was
infinite, because now he is linked with Roger Maris, at least until
he gets his first hacks against lefthander Steve Trachsel tonight.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire celebrated his record-tying blast in orderly fashion. As
he started his home run trot, he gave a restrained fist pump. He
was greeted both at first (Mark Grace) and third (Gary Gaetti). And
then, well, let him tell it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pointed to the man upstairs,'' McGwire recapitulated. ``Then
I pointed to my father. Said, `Happy birthday.' Then I saw my son.
I pointed to my father again, just in case he didn't hear me.''
</P>
<P>
   When he emerged from the dugout for the perfunctory curtain
call, he spied the Maris family seated in box seats to the left of
the Cardinals' dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pointed upstairs, pointed to my heart that Roger is with
me,'' McGwire continued. ``Blew him a kiss, pointed upstairs again.
I'd like to point to everybody in the world right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals won the game by a 3-2 score, a fact that mattered
a lot more to the losing Cubs, who are embroiled in a tight
wild-card battle with the Mets and Giants, than it did to anyone in
the stands. The only thing that matters around here are the four
times a night that Mark McGwire comes to the plate. As soon as he
is done, fans by the thousands head to the concession stands or
restrooms, or perhaps to call Mom and see if she's been watching.
</P>
<P>
   Now let the record show that in the matter of McGwire vs. Sosa,
as in Sammy, the season tally is 61-58 in favor of the
Brobdingnagian redhead. Sosa was 1 for 5 (an eighth-inning single),
and he struck out three times.
</P>
<P>
   The third K spoke eloquently to the business at hand.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs had Lance Johnson on third base, representing the tying
run, with two away in the ninth. St. Louis manager Tony La Russa
convened a conference at the mound. No one would have criticized
him on any technical basis had he decided to put Sosa on, even
though he represented the tying run. But La Russa elected to have
closer Juan Acevedo pitch to Sosa, and he struck him out on a
1-and-2 pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Grace said he, for one, wasn't surprised La Russa pitched to
Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really,'' reasoned the first baseman, ``because he was the
winning run, and if you put him on he has the ability to steal
second. You walk him, and it can turn into a double or triple.
That's the difference between Sammy and Mac. Mac's a base-clogger,
like me.''
</P>
<P>
   La Russa was well aware that Sosa could steal a base, but that
wasn't why he pitched to Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about it on the bench,'' explained La Russa. ``I
thought about it a lot, and I decided _ and I can't believe I'm
saying this _ that the moment was bigger than the game. In that
situation, you should make (on-deck hitter) Brad Brown beat you.
You've got to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought I'd say this, but in that situation those two
guys deserve to be bigger than the game. I yelped the whole second
half of the season about people not pitching to McGwire. What I
said was that if Grace flied out and Johnson stayed on second, we'd
walk him, because then he couldn't steal a base, but if Johnson got
to third (which he did, on Grace's tapper to the box), we'd pitch
to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Now you know how big this is. This is Tony ``The Mad
Manipulator'' La Russa talking. No one loves and respects the daily
ins and outs of the game more. No one sits around thinking up more
ways to tinker with lineups (he routinely bats his pitcher eighth,
remember). But now La Russa feels the weight of history. He told
his pitcher to go after Sosa because there he felt there was
something bigger at stake than he'd ever known in a regular-season
game.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire himself feels overcome by cosmic forces. He talked about
fate, and the fact that Monday was _ get this _ his father's 61st
birthday. He talked about his son's plane landing from California
45 minutes before game time and young Matthew arriving at the park
barely in time to see the milestone home run. He talked about the
bond he feels with Maris.
</P>
<P>
   There is one game left on this homestand and McGwire desperately
wants to break the record in front of the St. Louis fans, whose
folksy fervor during the final two months of the 1997 season
persuaded him to sign a long-term contract with the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been thinking about it since the 50 plateau, but you
think about it and you let it go right out of your mind because you
can't waste brain cells hours on hours thinking about it,'' he
said. ``Now we are one swing away, so we will have to wait and
see.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing is for certain: When it leaves the bat, Mark McGwire
will know.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
