<HEADLINE>
MURDOCH MOVES CAUSE CONCERN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nobody knows whether Rupert Murdoch intends to take over the
world. But he is making it clear that he wants to dominate world
sport.
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch's European Super League proposal has been resisted, so
he has decided to make a power play, bidding nearly $900 million
for Manchester United PLC, one of the world's most popular clubs.
Murdoch is offering $2.25 sterling for shares that were worth $1.59
sterling last week. He has reached an agreement with the main
shareholder, Martin Edwards, who had attempted to sell Manchester
United for about $30 million in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Murdoch has most bases covered. British government
officials have raised the alarm, but Murdoch is a strong supporter
of prime minister Tony Blair and will not likely confront political
problems. Murdoch could then lead an exodus from the English
Football Association, which was founded in 1863.
</P>
<P>
   Manchester United already has a huge payroll and an
international cast of players. But Murdoch would be prepared to
increase the stakes, tempting the Baggios and Ronaldos to compete
in England.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Murdoch has been like an annoying intruder into the
exclusive fiefdoms of baseball, ice hockey, and rugby. But he has
respected the balance of power there.
</P>
<P>
   There is no guarantee that will continue, though. If Murdoch and
the Media Partners group of Milan gain control of European soccer
from the governing bodies, checks and balances will be diluted.
Since their power is purely electronic media-driven, the
distinctions between entertainment and sport will be blurred
further.
</P>
<P>
   The first sporting principle to fall would be
promotion-relegation. The problem with soccer is that there is no
guarantee that the best, or strongest, team will win.
</P>
<P>
   Also, it is difficult to make a case for a Super League when the
structure for one already is in place, involving any and all teams.
Media Partners hopes to turn the league into an exclusive group,
with money being the sole requirement for entry. Next week, the
European Commission will rule on the antitrust aspects of the case
for the Super League.
</P>
<P>
   As the British fanzine When Saturday Comes noted: ``While laws
governing restraint of trade are intended to ensure as much
competition as possible, the clear aim of the would-be breakaway
clubs is to end any competition, in a purely footballing sense, by
setting up a cartel for clubs.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Euro 2000 kicks off
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From Champions du Monde to wrecks in Reykjavik.
</P>
<P>
   France might have been the best while playing at home, cheered
on by an entire nation this summer in the World Cup. But with only
10,000 Icelanders watching Saturday's opener of Euro 2000
qualifying at Laugardalsvollur National Stadium, the French could
only tie the hosts, 1-1, on a 36th-minute Christophe Dugarry goal.
</P>
<P>
   Riki Dadason, who attended college in the United States, took
advantage of an error by goalkeeper Fabian Barthez to score for
Iceland in the 33d minute. Robert Pires set up Yazid Zinedine
Zidane three minutes later, and Dugarry headed in the rebound.
</P>
<P>
   France, which is playing a more adventurous 4-3-3 scheme under
new coach Roger Lemerre, dominated the second half and nearly went
ahead when Youri Djorkaeff hit the crossbar. Instead of Aimee
Jacquet's conservative, single-striker attack, France used the
powerful Lilian Laslandes flanked by Dugarry and Pires.
</P>
<P>
   The French were missing Laurent Blanc and Marcel Desailly, who
were suspended during the World Cup, and Emmanuel Petit. Laslandes
was ineffective and could be replaced by either Stephane Guivarc'h
or David Trezeguet when France visits Russia Oct. 10.
</P>
<P>
   The top two teams from each group will qualifying for the finals
in Belgium and the Netherlands, and France remain favorites from
Group 4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 1321EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
