<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT WAS NO NEAR-MISS _ NOT EVEN CLOSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOOTBALL HADES, Colo. _ For those of you who collect old
newspapers, go up to the attic and pull out your Globe of Oct. 7,
1997, and take a look at it.
</P>
<P>
   Or read the one from Nov. 18, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Or the one dated Oct. 9, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Or any one you've got that tells you the tale of the Patriots
playing one of John Elway's Denver Bronco teams _ because nothing
changed last night.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be fooled by the score in today's newspaper, which reads:
Broncos 27, Patriots 21. Those numbers might lead you to believe
the Patriots came close to beating the Broncos at Mile High Stadium
for the first time since 1968 last night.
</P>
<P>
   They did not.
</P>
<P>
   They trailed the entire night, ominously blowing a 40-yard field
goal that would have tied the game on their first offensive series
and soon falling behind, 17-0. It was a race uphill after that,
and, as everyone kept saying last week, the air is thin in
Colorado. It is especially thin when you're climbing out of a deep
hole you helped dig for yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of doing the little things the elite teams do, the
Patriots did the deadly things the almost-elite do. They did the
things that get you beat.
</P>
<P>
   --They missed a 40-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   --They had another field goal blocked.
</P>
<P>
   --They committed special teams penalties that cost them at least
48 yards of field position, yards that will appear nowhere on the
stat sheet but cost them dearly on the field and, most likely, on
the scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   --They committed outrageously stupid penalties, like Willie
McGinest slamming Elway to the ground after a 9-yard completion,
thus turning it into a 19-yard completion. That moved the ball to
the 11 and set up the eventual clinching touchdown by pushing
Denver's lead to 27-14 in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   --They allowed Denver to convert on third down 53 percent of the
time, including on a third and 7 at the 8 that gave the Broncos
four downs to score from the 1 (they needed only one). They would
have had to settle for a field goal had New England held.
</P>
<P>
   --They burned up all their second-half timeouts with 6:16 left
to play in the third quarter because they couldn't get the right
offensive people on the field or into the right formations. Thus,
when the end came and they scored a late touchdown to bring
themselves within 6 points with just under two minutes to play,
they had to try a desperation onside kick. When they didn't get it,
they were left with no way to stop the clock and possibly squeeze
out one last chance at victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unusual to see these situations that we kept putting
ourselves in,'' Patriot head coach Pete Carroll said. ``We normally
handle them quite well but we didn't tonight. They were able to
capitalize on all of them. We missed opportunities by making too
many mistakes. They didn't make the ones that were critical. We
did.''
</P>
<P>
   In fairness, the Patriots played hard, especially on defense,
but they get paid a lot of money to play hard. There are no medals
for trying. Trying is the minimum. Effort is the minimum. You get
no points for effort in the NFL and you shouldn't think you deserve
any. You play hard, just like you work hard, because that's what
you're supposed to do.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness, the Patriots also refused to fold several times
after bad things happened and a blowout loomed.
</P>
<P>
   But, in the end, they were not good enough or smart enough to
beat the defending Super Bowl champions, and they were not truly
even within 6 points of them.
</P>
<P>
   So what does that tell us? Not much except what we already knew,
which is that Elway is unbeaten (now 10-0) against the Patriots and
the only way that streak will be broken is if they square off again
in January, once the playoffs begin, or he decides not to retire as
planned at the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   That's what they were talking about in the Patriot locker room.
They were talking about the next meeting, about wanting another
shot at the Broncos when everything will be on the line.
</P>
<P>
   It is a good sentiment and it may carry them a ways this season.
Nothing happened last night in Denver to hint that that is not a
strong possibility.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact is that losers talk about wanting another shot
because they're the ones who need one. The Broncos were not talking
about wanting another shot at the Patriots, although they probably
wouldn't mind it, considering that they're 11-0 in their last 11
meetings with them.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, nothing changed and nothing happened to indicate
that it would next time, either.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 1323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
