<HEADLINE>
NO QUESTION, SEOUL IS BUSY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's one thing everyone who has been to Seoul can agree upon:
It's a really busy place. On a typical day in the South Korean
capital (population 9.6 million), there are:
</P>
<P>
   _Two hundredtwenty-seven marriages and 45 divorces.
</P>
<P>
   _Four hundred sixty-three births and 108 deaths.
</P>
<P>
   _Three hundred five auto purchases, 1,272 new drivers' licenses,
and 5,684 traffic tickets.
</P>
<P>
   _Eight thousand three hundred fifty-two changes of residence.
</P>
<P>
   _Five million pieces of mail processed and 160,000 barrels of
oil consumed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Travel Trivia: &LR;  How well do you know our neighbor to the South?
Which city is not on the Gulf of Mexico: Veracruz, Tampico,
Manzanillo, or Ciudad del Carmen? (Answer at end of column.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; In a name: &LR;  Los Angeles's full name is ``El Pueblo de Nuestra
Senora la Reina de los Angeles de Porciuncula.'' &UR;  &LR; Its common
abbreviation, L.A., is just 3.63 percent of its size.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Quotable: &LR;  ``We cannot learn to love other tourists _ the laws of
nature forbid it.'' _ Agnes Repplier.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Today's fractured English lesson: &LR;  Two signs in a Majorcan shop
entrance: ``English Well Talking'' and ``Here Speeching American.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; They guessed it:  &LR; Add these names to the ones of those who
correctly guessed that our mystery photo of a giant hand was taken
in Venice: Richard Finch of Burlington and Nancy Carlson of
Nottingham, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; September song:  &LR; What finer month to travel than September? In so
many places, the weather is wonderful, the crowds of summer are
gone, and most attractions are still open. (Cape Cod, for instance,
is delightful in September. And Prince Edward Island publishes a
booklet listing an impressive 900 businesses that are open at least
till the end of September.) So what are you waiting for? If you
can, give September travel a try. We do whenever we can.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Tragedy tour: &LR;  How's this for morbidity? The Hotel Odeon in Paris
is offering tourists a drive over the last route Princess Diana
took, ending at the hospital where she was pronounced dead. The
hotel even offers tours in a black Mercedes, the kind of car Diana
crashed in nearly a year ago. The tour goes first to the Hotel
Ritz, where Diana got into the limousine with Dodi Fayed on Aug.
31, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Cutting ties in Texas:  &LR; Ties remain ``illegal'' on South Padre
Island at the tropical tip of Texas, and now socks have been added
to the list of ``outlawed'' clothing. Since June 1997, when
offensive neckwear was banned, Island police have issued verbal
warnings to tie-wearers, politely offering them a South Padre
Island T-shirt for the removal of their tie. More than 100 T-shirts
have been issued.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; A trip and a wedding:  &LR; One-fourth of 200,000 people who get married
in Las Vegas every year are from other countries.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; That's some trip! &LR;  It's called ``Around the World with 80 People.''
It lasts 23 days, takes in 10 countries and three continents, and
includes transportation by three celebrated trains and the
supersonic Concorde. And, oh yes, it costs $64,000. The trip,
limited to 80 people, begins April 5, 1999, from London and
concludes April 28 in Sydney, Australia, before a return to North
America. The adventure begins with a London palace tour, joins the
Venice Simplon-Orient Express for an overnight journey to Venice,
takes in the Eastern &AMP; Orient Express in Thailand, and, by
Concorde, links Venice, Dubai, Bangkok, and Cairns, Australia, for
the final inaugural celebration of the Great South Pacific Express,
Australia's new Orient-Express train. A few surprises are planned
along the way, too. For more information, call 800-524-2420.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Seaport ``store'':  &LR; So you're in Boston and find you need, say,
another shirt or pair of pantyhose. But you're in a rush and
haven't time to head to a store. Well, Boston's new Seaport Hotel
will bring the store to you. A selection from Filene's Basement is
available to guests. All they need do is fill out a card already in
their room, and the items, which are right in the hotel, will be
delivered to the room.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Sign of the times: &LR;  A sign on the grounds of the Atlantis Resort on
Paradise Island in the Bahamas says: Please Do Not Drop Your
Cigarette Butts On The Ground. The Fish Crawl Out At Night To Smoke
Them And We Are Trying To Get Them To Quit.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Freebie: &LR;  For a Quiklist kit containing tips for travelers to
Atlanta, Boston, Chicago, Los Angeles, New York City, San
Francisco, or Washignton, D.C., call 800-789-9887, or check out
www.quikbook.com. on the Web. The tips include information on
transportation, entertainment, and busy dates, as well as on-line
addresses for even more information about the city. The kit is
issued by Quikbook, a no-fee hotel discounting service.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Did you guess it? &LR;  Manzanillo is not on the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
