<HEADER>
A3635 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-LONGFELLOW-ART     09-08 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-LONGFELLOW-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTECTING LONGFELLOW HOUSE'S TREASURES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Most visitors to the Longfellow House don't
clamber up to the cramped servants' quarters in the attic or down
into the cellar's furnace room. But the voluminous history of 250
years is crammed there and elsewhere _ papers, artworks,
furnishings _ and to safeguard that history, the house will close
soon for at least a year.
</P>
<P>
   Renovations on the Longfellow House, scheduled to begin next
month, include installation of protective and security systems. A
major National Park Service construction effort for 1999, the $1.6
million project is now awaiting funding by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Guiding a visitor through the house on a late summer morning,
curator James Shea did not have to call attention to the lack of
any climate-control system; the stale, musty air did that.
</P>
<P>
   But again and again, whether in the mansion's overstuffed living
quarters or in the cluttered storage areas _ which include back
bedrooms turned into library stacks _ Shea did lament the lack of
sprinklers.
</P>
<P>
   Without those and other renovations, said Shea, the house itself
is at risk. It's the most stately of the Brattle Street ``Tory
Row'' mansions, built in the 1740s and home of the poet Henry
Wadsworth Longfellow from 1843 until his death in 1882.
</P>
<P>
   Also in jeopardy are the collections of a family that never
threw anything out. Besides Longfellow's personal library, there
are 635,000 artworks and furnishings; 600,000 letters, journals,
and other documents; and 10,000 19th-century photographs _ with
much still uncataloged.
</P>
<P>
   The vast collection is an extraordinary resource for scholars,
whether their interest is Colonial Cambridge, Georgian
architecture, the American Revolution (the house was General George
Washington's headquarters during the siege of Boston), 19th-century
society, or Longfellow and his esteemed literary circle.
</P>
<P>
   When the project is completed, there will be state-of-the-art
storage systems, and researchers will have something more for
office space than the folding tables pushed together in a corner of
the furnace room. As for the house itself, said Deputy Park Service
Superintendent John Maounis, ``We'll sharpen up the interior, but
maybe it will not look a whole lot different.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the house had a rather extraordinary life before
Longfellow rented rooms there as a young, recently widowed Harvard
professor (he acquired the house as a wedding present from the
Beacon Hill family of his second wife) the aura is all Longfellow.
Washington's association is so much an afterthought that a chair
believed to have been used by the ``Father of Our Country'' is
tucked away.
</P>
<P>
   Longfellow the poet is very much out of fashion these days, the
result, writes literary historian Lawrence Buell, of his being
viewed as too European in comparison with contemporaries (and
friends) Nathaniel Hawthorne and Ralph Waldo Emerson.
</P>
<P>
   Out-of-fashion older readers, at least, will recall from
childhood a line or two from ``Evangeline,'' ``The Song of
Hiawatha,'' ``The Courtship of Miles Standish,'' ``Paul Revere's
Ride,'' or ``The Wreck of the Hesperus'' _ epic poems that defined
the American experience, if in a European style.
</P>
<P>
   The Longfellow aura is a cosmopolitan one, and nowhere felt more
strongly than in the study off the front entrance hall, where the
dark Victorian furnishings set it off from the lighter Georgian
style of the other rooms. It is the ``castle'' he wrote of in ``The
Children's Hour,'' that beloved poem of childhood, describing his
three daughters _ ``Grave Alice, and laughing Allegra/And Edith
with golden hair'' _ making
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(begin poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A sudden rush from the stairway,
</P>
<P>
   A sudden raid from the hall!
</P>
<P>
   By three doors left unguarded
</P>
<P>
   They enter my castle wall!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dark, ornately carved bookcases contain Longfellow's collection
of Scandinavian literature (in the original languages, which he
knew) and the collected speeches of his close friend Charles
Sumner, the abolitionist senator. Arranged on two walls are a
crayon likeness of Sumner by Eastman Johnson, and portraits of
Hawthorne and Emerson.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the room from the hallway, the visitor finds his eye
drawn immediately to the armchair next to the fireplace. It was
carved from wood of ``the spreading chestnut tree'' celebrated in
his poem ``The Village Blacksmith'' after the tree was cut down
when the street was widened. Cambridge schoolchildren helped fund
the chair and presented it to him on his 72d birthday in 1879.
</P>
<P>
   Longfellow quickly wrote a poem in return:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(begin poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Only your love and your remembrance could
</P>
<P>
   Give life to this dead wood,
</P>
<P>
   And make these branches, lifeless now so long,
</P>
<P>
   Blossom again in song.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When children visited, he would give them a copy of the poem and
sit them in the chair.
</P>
<P>
   A door from the study leads into the music room, a light and
spacious room opening onto the formal gardens behind the house.
Originally the dining room of the Vassall family for whom the house
was built, it was a wardroom and officers' mess for members of
Washington's staff. It is the room that best preserves the house's
18th-century origins.
</P>
<P>
   The music room is also the scene of the second great tragedy of
Longfellow's life. His first wife had died in childbirth in
Germany. And in 1843, Longfellow married Boston heiress Frances
Appleton, known as Fanny. In the house _ the wedding present _ they
raised five children, two boys, and the three girls of ``The
Children's Hour.''
</P>
<P>
   But one afternoon in 1861, while Fanny Longfellow was seated in
the music room, her gown caught fire. She rushed into the study,
where Longfellow wrapped her in a carpet to smother the flames, but
she died of her burns the next day.
</P>
<P>
   The house is remarkably undervisited _ only some 20,000 come a
year _ and may be as much out of fashion as Longfellow's poetry.
But it remains an architectural and cultural treasure.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
IF YOU GO:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Longfellow National Historic Site, 105 Brattle St.,
Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Open Wednesdays through Sundays _ until Friday, October 23 _ 10
a.m. to 4:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   For information: 876-4492.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
