<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-HARDSHIPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUBLE'S FREEFALL BRINGS BACK EMPTY SHELVES, LONG LINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; MOSCOW _ The shiny new all-terrain vehicle, black with gold
trim and loaded with extras, roared up to the Kuntsevsky
Supermarket in western Moscow and a sharply dressed woman jumped
out, a slim new cellular phone pressed to her ear.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``You're sure it's here?'' the woman shouted into the phone as
she sprinted inside, rushing past the lines for meat, butter, and
dog food, to get in line just as the last box of dishwasher
detergent sold out. The woman uttered an oath, stomped off to her
vehicle and sped away, dialing a number on her phone.
</P>
<P>
   This scene epitomized the sudden collapse of Moscow's thriving
consumer economy that has accompanied the ruble's tailspin and the
meltdown of Russia's financial markets. Once again, this is a city
of empty shelves and rapidly climbing prices, lines, hoarding,
black marketeers, bank runs, and panic buying. And the overall
feeling is a sense of despair.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past six years, while Russia was lurching from one
period of pain and crisis to another, the one glimmer of hope that
this country might be ``turning the corner,'' as numerous pundits
have said, was Moscow's gradual transformation from the shoddy
capital of Soviet socialism to a modern city with high-paying jobs,
well-stocked stores, a burgeoning service sector and a confident
new middle class.
</P>
<P>
   In a matter of days, that transformation has been halted. Now,
like millions of their poorer and disenfranchised countrymen in the
outlying regions, Moscow's middle class is at a loss to explain
what is going on as the economy they thrived in disappears. Store
shelves have emptied as Muscovites frantically unload their rubles
and stock up on goods. Imported items, which make up 80 percent of
Moscow's food supply by most estimates, are at a premium, with
stores raising prices several times a day to keep up with the
falling ruble's exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
   Bank machines and credit cards, those universal tools of
middle-class consumption, no longer work. Savings have gone up in
smoke, or are trapped in banks that have closed down indefinitely.
The ruble has lost more than two-thirds of its value since Aug. 17
and looks ready to fall much, much more. Many shops and businesses
have closed down. Those that have stayed open are the scene of
quiet mayhem.
</P>
<P>
   ``What? How much for that coffee? I don't have that much,''
Svetlana Gavrilova said from the front of the long checkout line at
a trendy supermarket that opened not long ago, across the street
from President Boris N. Yeltsin's city residence. Gavrilova paid
for the goods she had already put on the conveyor belt, and pushed
her half-full cart away with disgust.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been like this all day,'' said Tatyana Dobrynina, a
cashier at the store. ``People don't know how much things cost.
Everyone wants to stock up while they can. No one can believe it
when I tell them.''
</P>
<P>
   No one at Super Siva, a Finnish-run supermarket, could believe
the cost of a package of diapers _ $65. At a nearby music store,
imported compact discs were marked up to more than $40 each. Once
unheard-of luxury items that Moscow residents have learned to love
_ like cat litter, or dog chow _ have disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   City officials say that Moscow has plenty of staple goods to
survive the winter, but buyers are stocking up anyway. Shopping
strategies not seen since the dying days of the Soviet Union _ if
you see a line, stand in it; if it's something you don't need, buy
it anyway _ have made a comeback. So have black market currency
traders, who reappeared on the street after banks stopped giving
out dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought I'd see this again, but here it is,'' said
Marina Volkova, a Moscow schoolteacher.
</P>
<P>
   Certain sites, to be sure, have never been seen here before. It
was intermission at the Lenkom theater the other night, and the
trendy Moscow drama house's upscale guests, as they always do,
reached into their dinner jackets and evening dresses for their
cellular phones. But their conversations were all about one thing _
where to buy what.
</P>
<P>
   If Muscovites were hoping for some encouraging news from their
leaders, they did not get it last night.
</P>
<P>
   Viktor Chernomyrdin, Yeltsin's prime minister designate whose
confirmation battle in Parliament has dragged into its second
deadlocked week, had little good news for his countrymen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The country has gone into such a tailspin that there are no
easy ways out,'' Chernomyrdin said on NTV television in a program
where the acting prime minister took phone calls from the public.
``It is painful, bitter, that we have to go back to the way things
were.''
</P>
<P>
   The acting premier, whom lawmakers voted down last Monday and
who is likely to be rejected again in a second vote today, has
proposed an emergency plan that has been panned by economists and
ordinary Russians alike. First Russia would print money, let the
ruble go into a free fall, allow high inflation, and pay off state
debts to workers and industry. Then, after Jan. 1, the country
would return to tight-spending ways, bankrupting insolvent firms,
and forcing everyone to pay taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Forgetting whether such a plan could work, no one expects things
to go as Chernomyrdin says now, because in Russia, no one believes
anything politicians say. Or, at the very least, most people are
convinced that bad things that happen to them are part of a
conspiracy to benefit the rich and powerful.
</P>
<P>
   ``What will happen to my deposit _ will it end up on the Canary
Islands like everything else?'' one caller asked, referring to a
move by the Central Bank to transfer people's individual deposits
from commercial banks to the state savings bank. At first, the
government had made it sound as if the transfer would protect
people's savings. But by the end of the week, after it became clear
that depositors would lose much of their money, and would not be
able to access their funds until November, the Central Bank
official who oversaw the scheme stepped down.
</P>
<P>
   The Moskovsky Komsomolets newspaper highlighted the popular
disgust with the banks on Saturday by printing an anecdote about a
man who enters a Russian bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to open an account in your bank, whom should I speak
to?'' the man asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``A psychologist,'' is the teller's answer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 1327EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
