<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAD ENOUGH OF IRRITAINMENT? TUNE IN TO JARGON WATCH
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   ``Irritainment: Entertainment and media spectacles that are
annoying, but you find yourself unable to stop watching them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Assmosis: The process by which some people seem to absorb
success and advancement by kissing up to the boss rather than
working hard.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Umfriend: A sexual relation of dubious standing. ``This is
Dale, my ... um ... friend ...''
</P>
<P>
   Each month Gareth Branwyn's Jargon Watch column in Wired
magazine offers a handful of new slang culled from a multitude of
submissions by jargonauts to jargon(at)wired.com. The September
issue has six terms, the best of which may be ``brain stain,''
defined as, ``inept, often irrelevant comments left by supervisors
on copies of memos and other documents.''
</P>
<P>
   The pick of Branwyn's previous columns can be found in a little
book _ and it's truly little, just 3 1/2-by-5 inches _ called
``Jargon Watch.'' There's a funny, useful word on every page. Many
entries have a Dilbertian edge because they emerge from the pods
(or ``cube farms'' or ``veal pens'') of disgruntled workers. For
example there's ``uninstalled,'' yet another euphemism for being
fired; ``interrupt-driven,'' used to describe someone who responds
to a series of interruptions rather than set work goals; ``voice
jail system,'' for a voice mail system that's too lengthy and
confusing.
</P>
<P>
   A few of the terms in ``Jargon Watch'' are by now pretty well
entrenched in the language. Facetime. Going postal. Stalkerazzi.
Road Rage. Tract mansion. Starter marriage. Begathon. But there are
many more clever inventions that deserve wider use.
``Permalancer.'' A permanent freelancer. ``YODA: Young, Opiniated,
Directionless Artiste.'' And one of my favorites (I wonder why?),
``stress puppy: A person who seems to thrive on being stressed out
and whiny.''
</P>
<P>
   A great many of the entries have, of course, emerged from
computer culture. ``Webbelganger,'' a person who comes up in an
on-line search but is not the person you're looking for. ``Eliza
Effect,'' the tendency to believe that a computer has personality
and intelligence. ``Ohnosecond,'' the fraction of time in which you
realize you've made a big mistake. ``Kubris: An extreme form of
arrogance found in multimedia auteurs who think they're Stanley
Kubrik.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Kubris, I also liked ``multimediocrity,'' defined
as, ``Boring, poorly-done CD-ROMS, multimedia Web sites, and the
like.'' It also could be used to describe certain persons in the
wonderful world of irritainment: ``Kathie Lee Gifford is a
multimediocrity.'' Although it can't be said she's covered with
``loser dust,'' a bit of Hollywood slang defined as ``the opposite
of fairy dust.''
</P>
<P>
   A few more favorites (of many):
</P>
<P>
   ``Generica.'' Parts of the American landscape (strip malls,
hotel chains, prefab housing) that are exactly the same no matter
where you go.
</P>
<P>
   ``SITCOMs.'' Single income, two children, oppressive mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Circling the drain.'' Medical slang for someone near death who
refuses to give up, used in other contexts, e.g., ``This idea has
been circling the drain for weeks ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why bother.'' Coffeehouse term for decaf with skim milk.
</P>
<P>
   Branwyn is always on the lookout for new slang. I may have found
a couple of possibilities the other day, in a British newspaper.
The first was ``Lycra lout,'' used to describe a reckless bicyclist
and doubtless inspired by the long-established ``lager lout,''
which is self-explanatory. The second term was ``poke,'' the street
name for Viagra. It's self-explanatory too, I suppose.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
