<SLUG> BC-WATER-LANDINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LANDINGS   ON WATER EXTREMELY RARE, RISKY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is part of virtually every pre-flight safety message: ``In
the unlikely event of a water landing, your seat cushion is
designed to float.''
</P>
<P>
   On overseas flights, the water precautions seem even more
comforting _ flight attendants tell you that life vests are under
your seat and laminated safety cards have pictures of passengers
floating in large circular life rafts.
</P>
<P>
   What neither the smiling flight attendant nor the safety card
will tell you is that ditchings, or water landings, are an act of
supreme desperation and any slim chance of survival depends on an
extraordinary confluence of luck and skill.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots admit they have no way of training for a water landing,
other than to review the steps called for in their flight
operations manual. And most of those instructions detail procedures
to prepare the cabin crew and notify the Coast Guard of the
aircraft's exact location, pilots say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not something that you can train for,'' says Robert
Flocke, a spokesman for the Air Line Pilots Association, the union
that represents most commercial airline pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the crew of Swissair Flight 111, which crashed in the
Atlantic on Wednesday while trying to land at Halifax, Nova Scotia,
was attempting to ditch is unknown. Passengers, however, had put on
life vests and pilot Urs Zimmermann had dumped fuel _ perhaps in an
effort to make the aircraft more buoyant in the event of a water
landing. The accident, however, certainly illustrates how
unforgiving a surface water can be.
</P>
<P>
   One item in the pre-flight safety message that is beyond debate
is that water landings are very rare indeed. Consider that the
National Transportation Safety Board database _ which covers the
31-year history of the agency _ has no entry of a US commercial
airliner ditching.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is difficult to find any precedents on which to rely,''
says Stuart Matthews, president of the Flight Safety Foundation, a
Virginia-based organization whose members include airline
executives and airplane manufacturers. ``And aircraft are not
designed, in the end, to land on water, although it is assumed they
will float.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Bradley, a spokeswoman for Boeing, the world's largest
commercial airline manufacturer, says the company uses a NASA study
from the 1960s to determine ditching characteristics of an
airplane. Bradley says that although the study is 30 years old, the
appearance of jet aircraft has not changed much in that time.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing also uses computer modeling to follow Federal Aviation
Administration regulations regarding buoyancy in ditching.
</P>
<P>
   But the regulations are not specific other than that a plane
should be buoyant enough to allow all passengers time to evacuate.
The regulations add that models can be used to determine ditching
characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   The regulations and all the engineering calculations make one
very large assumption: that the fuselage will remain intact.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent attempt of a pilot trying to land an airliner in
water occurred off the Indian Ocean islands of Comoros. A hijacked
Ethiopian Airlines Boeing 767 _ its fuel exhausted _ was coming in
for a daylight landing on relatively calm seas when a wing-tip
dipped, caught the water, and the plane cart-wheeled and broke into
several pieces. Of the 175 people on board, only 52 survived.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to that, in May 1970, a Dutch Antilles Airlines DC-9
ditched in the water off St. Croix after it ran out of fuel. That
crash had a much higher survival rate _ only 20 of the 63 people on
board died.
</P>
<P>
   The downing of Swissair Flight 111, which killed all 229 on
board, is only the most recent of crashes into water. Some of those
crashes have only served to spur debate about the best way to ditch
an airplane.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1978, a National Airlines Boeing 727 headed for
Pensacola, Fla., crashed in Escambia Bay, some 31/2 miles short of
the runway. The landing gear was down. Three passengers drowned in
the accident; 49 others, and all six crew, survived.
</P>
<P>
   While most manufacturers and airlines mandate that ditching be
done with gear up, some pilots point to Escambia Bay as a reason
why the gear should be down.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some interesting debate among pilots as to whether
gear up or down is better for ditching,'' said John J. Goglia, a
member of the National Transportation Safety Board.
</P>
<P>
   For obvious reasons, ditching cannot be practiced and airline
pilots interviewed say it is not part of training on simulators.
For the most part, the only water training pilots and flight
attendants receive is in dealing with the life rafts _ which are
stored in the ceiling of overseas aircraft _ and use of survival
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Matthews, for one, wonders why the rafts are even there. ``I'm
never going to advocate doing away with life jackets or a slide
that converts to a raft, but you have to question why those rafts
are in the ceiling. They have never been used in millions and
millions of flights.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps what is most frightening about water landings is they
assume a best case scenario _ daylight, calm seas, and lots of time
to prepare. Consider that under recent rule changes, most
twin-engine aircraft that now fly across the Atlantic have to be
within 180 minutes of an airfield. It took about 20 minutes for
Flight 111, a three-engine MD-11, to go from a normal
trans-Atlantic flight to a tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ditching is a very difficult thing to do well in the daytime,
when you have to judge where you are in relation to the water and
if there are big swells, you might try to come down on the back
side of one,'' said Eugene Covert, Massachusetts Institute of
Technology professor emeritus of aeronautics. ``At night,
everything is more difficult because you can't see.''
</P>
<P>
   Pilots say in attempting to ditch an airplane the preferred
method is to keep the engines running, approach the water at speeds
of around 150 miles per hour, with the nose of the plane slightly
higher than normal and have the tail strike first. With luck, the
plane would act somewhat like a skipping stone before settling
gently into the water.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to get the plane to stall, at 100 miles per hour, a few
feet above the ocean and pancake in may seem like a more reasonable
approach because the lower airspeed would probably reduce stress on
the fuselage. But it could result in a case like the Ethiopian
airliner, and a wingtip could catch a wave with disastrous results.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we have great confidence in doing something like this?
No,'' said one veteran airline pilot. ``It is new ground _ and that
is a bad word _ for everyone. Nobody has done it. We would do what
we are trained to do and what our airmanship skills provide. An
airliner is a marvelous piece of equipment, but it is not designed
to land in water.''
</P>
<P>
   The closest an US commercial jet ever came to ditching was in
May 1983, when an Eastern Airlines Lockheed L-1011 took off from
Miami for Nassau with 162 people on board. A half hour into the
flight, the pilot, Richard Boddy, was guiding the jumbo jet on a
descent through 15,000 feet when the tail engine lost oil pressure
and was shut down. Boddy told passengers he needed to return to
Miami, turned around, and climbed to 16,000 feet when one
under-wing engine flamed out. Three minutes later the only
remaining engine shut down.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers said they became very alarmed when the cockpit crew
called all the flight attendants into the cockpit. ``That made me
realize that there was something rotten in Denmark,'' passenger
Sandy Dix said at that time.
</P>
<P>
   As the plane passed through 10,000 feet, the flight crew
announced ``ditching is imminent.'' Passengers had trouble finding
and putting on life vests, the NTSB said.
</P>
<P>
   As the plane flew silently closer to the Atlantic, sobs and
prayers were heard throughout the cabin. At about 2,800 feet, Boddy
managed to restart the tail engine and the plane limped back to
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is,'' Dix said at the time, ``like God turned that one
flaming engine back on for a few minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   As those passengers still brave enough to fly waited for a new
aircraft to take them to Nassau, the airline provided them with
food and drinks that May morning. They consumed a total of 384
one-shot bottles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
