<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3648 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINN-MOTHER-BOS &LR;      09-08 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINN-MOTHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMUNITY LEFT GRIEVING BY DEATHS OF SIX CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PAUL, Minn. _ Khoua Her wore a traditional silk gown, her
black hair flowing over its blood-red hues, as she dialed 911 to
report that she had just killed her three sons and three daughters.
</P>
<P>
   To her elegant apparel, the 24-year-old woman, a mother since
she was 13, added a gruesome accessory, a length of cord wrapped
around her own neck, police sources said. The children had already
been strangled to death.
</P>
<P>
   By outfitting herself with the cord and the ceremonial garb more
normally reserved for weddings and New Year's festivities, Her sent
a message to the immigrant Hmong community, which was left groping
Saturdayto understand Thursday night's sextuple homicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our people, when they die, they have to wear their best. She
must have put it on to take her to God,'' said Robert Thou, a
relative of Her's, standing on a soccer field next to the housing
project where Her and her children lived.
</P>
<P>
   Her survived _ a police source said she apparently passed out
while trying to tighten the cord _ and was being held under guard
Saturday at nearby Regions Hospital. Her injuries were described as
not life-threatening. She has not been charged in the killings, but
a judge allowed authorities to hold her through Tuesday while the
investigation continues.
</P>
<P>
   One investigator said Saturday that Her would probably be
charged with six counts of second-degree murder at an arraignment
Tuesday afternoon in the deaths of the six children, whose last
name was Hang: boys Kouaeai, 11; Samson, two weeks shy of his 10th
birthday; and 7-year-old Tang Lung; and daughters Nali, 9; Aee, 6;
and Tung Ke, 5.
</P>
<P>
   Police refused to release the tape of the 911 call or discuss
the case in detail before the arraignment.
</P>
<P>
   However, the police supervisor who took the 911 call said in an
interview with the Globe Saturday that Her first said only that she
needed help, and initially he thought she was being threatened by
someone in the house. Then, ``she blurted out, `Suicide,''' said
Sergeant Tim McCarty. ``Five or six minutes into the call, she said
she didn't know why she killed her children.''
</P>
<P>
   By then, a rescue team was on its way, and Her added another
piece to the puzzle. ``She said she tried to hang herself,''
McCarty said. Her ``wasn't too lucid'' when she called, he added.
</P>
<P>
   No motive has been given for the killings, but police described
a combustible relationship between Her and her estranged
29-year-old husband, Kong ``Tou'' Hang. The couple had been brought
together by Hang's mother in an arranged marriage. They wed in a
refugee camp in Thailand when Her was just 13.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors said the two seemed happy at first but in recent years
had grown bitter and apart. One neighbor said they had received a
``Hmong divorce,'' but apparently had not dissolved the marriage in
a US court.
</P>
<P>
   Police records show officers were called to the home 17 times
since February 1996, and both husband and wife traded accusations
of abuse. One case in June 1997 included an allegation that she
threatened Hang with a shotgun; she said it was in self-defense.
Later, she received a restraining order against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got no sympathy for him, only for the children,'' said a
St. Paul police official close to the case.
</P>
<P>
   There had been no reports of abuse involving the children, who
ranged in age from 5 to 11, all of whom the Ramsey County medical
examiner said had been killed by ``ligature strangulation.''
</P>
<P>
   Their bodies, still warm when authorities arrived in response to
the 911 call, were found scattered through the home.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday morning, just 20 feet from the door of Unit G at 1541
Timberlake Road, six boys climbed on one of roughly a half-dozen
playground sets that punctuate the wide green spaces in the neat
1950s McDonough Homes housing project.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the three-bedroom, tan stucco townhouse where the
children died, mourners had left a small memorial. Six teddy bears
of various sizes _ the largest a foot-and-a-half tall and the
smallest just 3 inches, white with a tiny bowtie _ stood silent
guard. Above them a sign read: ``May God be with you all. Peace.''
Eight bouquets surrounded the bears, and someone had placed a
children's magazine and Christian comic books alongside.
</P>
<P>
   The door to the unit was sealed with police tape. The only
movement apparent was made by wind-blown curtains in an open
upstairs window.
</P>
<P>
   The boys on the jungle gym steered clear of the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their mom put bad medicine in their food, and they died,''
said a boy who identified himself as Chi, a 7-year-old who had
played with Her's children.
</P>
<P>
   On the nearby soccer field, Thou, a cousin of Her's by marriage,
stood watching a soccer tournament involving 20 teams, mostly from
the Twin Cities' 50,000-strong Hmong community. Nearby, men played
a Hmong game reminiscent of bowling, launching spinning tops into
the air to knock down stationary tops some 30 yards away. A flea
market ringed the playing fields, and men sold roasted meat while
women set up racks of colorful clothes to catch the eye of Hmong
soccer moms.
</P>
<P>
   But the festive atmosphere was a facade, as conversations kept
coming back to the six children killed not 48 hours earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Thou said he worked with Her at a computer disk-manufacturing
plant and described his distant relation as slim and pretty, ``a
very strong Christian.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She seemed like a happy person,'' he said. He added that she
told him Tang stayed home with the children while she worked and
that was fine with her.
</P>
<P>
   Hugging her 2 1/2-year-old son close, Julie Yang stood nearby
shaking her head. ``We are all shocked,'' Yang said. ``To me, I
think she was out of control and wanted to take her children with
her.''
</P>
<P>
   Across town at the headquarters of the Lao Community of
Minnesota Inc., men sat at a table making plans for the New Year's
celebration in November. By coincidence, they were all members of
the Her family, though none said they were close relatives of Khoua
Her or the children. Still, their eyes were ringed red, and there
was little talk of the big party planned with the ``Silent Thunder
Band.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing to say. It is too hard,'' said John Her.
</P>
<P>
   Others struggled to make sense of the tragedy. Some who have
studied infanticide said that by apparently trying to kill herself
as well, Her should be viewed at least to some small degree as a
victim.
</P>
<P>
   ``This might well be a case of a woman saying, `I can't protect
you, but I can't leave you behind,''' said Richard Gelles, who
holds the Joanne and Raymond Welsh chair in child welfare and
family violence at the University of Pennsylvania.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
