<HEADER>
A3655 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-HOMER-VARIABLES-B     09-08 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-HOMER-VARIABLES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE VARIABLES IN THE EQUATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The basic equation that explains whether a given hit will be a
home run is that of momentum, defined as mass (bat size), times
velocity (speed of the swing plus the speed of the ball). But those
are only two of the perhaps countless variables involved.
</P>
<P>
   It may seem counterintuitive, but a fast ball is more likely to
be swatted for a home run than a slower-moving curve, knuckleball,
or slider. The reason is a ball coming in at 90 m.p.h., has more
inherent kinetic energy that can be converted to moving it over the
fence than does a slower-moving pitch.
</P>
<P>
   In his 1990 book, ``The Physics of Baseball,'' physics professor
Robert K. Adair of Yale University showed that for a batter
swinging squarely at 70 m.p.h., a 60 m.p.h. pitch will travel only
360 feet, but a 95 m.p.h. fastball will carry more like 380 feet.
In many parks, that's the difference between a warning-track out
and an over-the-fence homer.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously the varying dimensions of ball parks make it easier to
hit homers in some than others.
</P>
<P>
   The trend towards building intimate ``bandbox'' arenas like
Baltimore's Camden Yards or Cleveland's Jacobs Field, many say, has
contributed to the slugging explosion of recent years. Five of the
13 top parks of 1995 for home runs were built after 1989, and at
least six stadiums _ including Mark McGwire's home field in St.
Louis _ have pulled in or lowered outfield fences since then.
</P>
<P>
   But those are just a few of the many factors that go into a home
run that are cited by Adair and other baseball-loving scientists:
</P>
<P>
   _Local weather. Depending on direction, a 10 m.p.h. wind can add
or subtract perhaps 35 feet from the ball's flight (particularly
noticeable at the San Francisco Giants' 3-Com Park, but a nonissue
at the Minnesota Twins' indoor Metrodome).
</P>
<P>
   Under identical circumstances, a given hit will travel about 12
feet farther on a 90-degree August afternoon than on a 50-degree
April or September evening, because the ball is bouncier and the
air is a tiny bit thinner. Likewise, 90 percent-plus humidity
thickening the air can take 30 feet off what would be a long ball
on an equally warm but drier day.
</P>
<P>
   Daily variations in the barometric pressure at a given stadium
could determine whether a given hit nicks the wall or passes just
over an outfielder's glove. The difference between a a reading of
29.0 inches and 30.5 inches on the barometer might account for 9
extra feet on a hit, as the less dense air on a low pressure day
provides less resistance.
</P>
<P>
   _Elevation. Because the air is thinner, it's slightly easier to
hit a given pitch farther at the Atlanta Braves' Turner Field,
about 1,000 feet up in the Piedmont, than at sea-level Fenway Park.
It's easier still at the Colorado Rockies' mile-high Coors Field,
where more homers are hit than at any other stadium. Denver's thin
air could allow a 400-foot shot at an East Coast stadium to travel
440 feet.
</P>
<P>
   _Point of impact: Studies by scientists such as Adair and James
A. Sherwood, who runs a bat research lab at the University of
Massachusetts at Lowell, show that a batted ball's potential
distance begins to fall dramatically as the impact moves more than
a few inches from the ``sweet spot'' near the end of the bat's
barrel.
</P>
<P>
   A 390-foot shot from the heart of the sweet spot, Adair
calculated, would dwindle to about a 340-foot fly-out if hit two
inches closer to, or four inches farther from, the batter's hands.
Three inches closer still to the grip, and the hit is a blooper.
</P>
<P>
   _Angle of impact: Only one-ninth of the perimeter of the bat,
according to Adair, can be used to hit a home run. Most balls that
take off at an angle less than 20 degrees above horizontal will be
line drives or grounders; most that leave the bat at an angle
greater than 40 degrees above horizontal will go up more than out,
and drop for long flies.
</P>
<P>
   Taking into account both the location of the sweet spot and the
fact that only a small sliver of the barrel's arc will propel the
ball at the correct angle, the average batter must make contact
with exactly the right 4 to 7 percent of the bat's surface to have
any hope for a home run. Some sluggers, like McGwire, are so strong
they can occasionally connect with the ball in close to their hands
or near the end of the bat and still hit it out.
</P>
<P>
   _Ball squishiness: Under major league standards, a ball's
``coefficient of restitution'' can vary about 6 percent from a
standard. That means one regulation ball might travel 10 feet
farther than another thrown and hit at the same speed.
</P>
</TEXT>
