<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY DO OWLS HOOT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Why do owls `whoo'? Why don't they `caw'?
</P>
<P>
   C.L.G.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Actually some owls don't ``whoo'' at all. Screech owls make a
noise that sounds like a whistling horse whinny. Barred owls hoot,
haw, and sometimes scream. Barn owls hiss. Only the great horned
owl, a common species in the area, really ``whoos.''
</P>
<P>
   Why do owls, or any bird, vocalize at all? Ron Rohrbaugh of the
Cornell University Laboratory of Ornithology says they're either
alerting fellow species members to danger, staying in touch with
members of their flock, or begging for food.
</P>
<P>
   But while all birds vocalize, Rohrbaugh says, with few
exceptions, only males sing _ to search out mates and defend their
territory. (Female cardinals do sing, and the mating ceremony of
the Carolina wren involves a male-female duet.)
</P>
<P>
   And why do some birds ``chick-a-dee-dee-dee'' and some
``quack-quack?'' So individual species can communicate only among
themselves. If you're a blue jay alerting fellow blue jays to
danger, you need a unique language that your jay pals alone will
recognize. If you're a fledgling house finch squawking for food,
you don't want a heron bringing you a fresh fish.
</P>
<P>
   Males of different species sing different songs for the same
reason, Rohrbaugh says. A wood thrush singing to attract a mate
doesn't want a great horned owl showing up.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  And if you're a house sparrow joining that great dawn chorus
of birds singing to let other house sparrows know that you survived
the night and are re-establishing your territory, you need a song
the other sparrows will recognize. You don't much care about
goldfinches or woodpeckers in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   And, you might ask, are birds born with a song in their hearts?
Researchers working with newly-hatched chicks isolated from all
bird sounds have found that some species do indeed know their music
from birth, and that some learn it. Some species learn to sing
another species' song if that's all they hear.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why do humans need the ability to taste sour and bitter
things?
</P>
<P>
   K.W. Peabody, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Sour and bitter tastes are probably warning you that what
you've got in your mouth isn't good for you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many compounds that taste bitter are toxic,'' says Dr. Paul
Breslin, a researcher at the Monell Chemical Senses Center in
Philadelphia. ``For example, most medicines taste bitter. All
medicines are toxic at high doses. If you were foraging and you bit
into something horribly nasty bitter in the wild, you'd probably be
better off not eating that stuff. You'd probably get sick.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may have evolved the rule of thumb that if it tastes nasty
bitter, don't eat it.''
</P>
<P>
   There are three theories on sour, based on the fact that sour
foods are acidic. And there are good reasons to avoid acids.
</P>
<P>
   1. Acid erodes your teeth and causes oral ulcers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; 2. Unripe fruit is acidic. Riper fruit is sweeter. We want
sugars in our food for the calories (unless we're on a diet); sour
steers us away from the unripe.
</P>
<P>
   3. In some foods, a sour taste is a warning that the food has
spoiled. Ever gulp a mouthful of spoiled milk? You'd be awfully
sick if that sour taste didn't prompt you to spit it out.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet and salt tastes, on the other hand, evolved not discourage
us from eating what's bad for us, but to encourage us to eat things
we need. We need the sweet for the calories, and salt to maintain
fundamental body chemistry. That probably explains why we have the
most sensation of sweet and salt in the front of our tongues, where
we sample things to see how they taste. Sour is more noticeable on
the sides, and bitter in the back, probably to make us gag and not
swallow a potential poison.
</P>
<P>
   But it's myth that you taste only certain tastes with certain
parts of your tongue. While tastes are concentrated in certain
areas, you can pick up any taste anywhere on your tongue, even on
the soft palate on the top of your mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a fifth taste you can throw in there,'' Breslin tells
us. ``Since the turn of the century, the Japanese have recognized
what they call `umami' (ooh-MOMMY).'' It's the taste of broth rich
in monosodium glutamate from foods like shitake mushrooms, sea
weed, or bonito (fish). Breslin says umami broths taste a little
like chicken soup. Western scientists are just starting to
recognize umami as an officialtaste.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write
to How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
