<HEADLINE>
WATCHING FALL TV: NEW SEASON, OLD FRIENDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It all depends on what you mean by ``new.'' We may be on the
verge of the 1998 fall season, the first batch of TV series since
the ``Seinfeld'' Four were sent up to syndication lockdown, but
most of the comedies and dramas the networks are ready to unveil
are about as new as jokes that end with ``yadda yadda yadda.''
</P>
<P>
   Seems as though TV executives think we can never watch too many
``Mary Tyler Moore Show''-style office sitcoms. And they just know
our lives would be less exciting without a couple of ``Ally
McBeal'' wannabes, or a medical drama begging for comparisons with
``ER,'' or, since ``The Love Boat'' was already dredged up last
season, a remake of that other late 1970s schlockfest, ``Fantasy
Island.'' They don't want us to feel vertigo, either, from seeing
too many unusual faces each week. That's why this season is thick
with TV alumni like Shannen Doherty, Ken Olin, Peter Horton, Faith
Ford, Linda Lavin, Christina Applegate, Jeremy Piven, the Olsen
twins, Brian Benben, and Jerry Stiller, all back in new vehicles.
Alas, Ted Danson and his newest sitcom, ``Becker,'' have been
postponed until midseason.
</P>
<P>
   Would we truly be shocked by the new? The irony of the network's
safe approach is that many of TV's best and biggest moments _
``Seinfeld'' and ``Ally McBeal,'' for example _ have been the
result of gambling, and not cloning. After all, nothing meaningful
came from those very many ``Friends'' copycats that arrived all
dolled up in cool haircuts, from ``The Single Guy'' to ``Union
Square.'' If the networks are feeling threatened by the cable
universe (and they should: This summer, cable channels actually won
better ratings than the networks over two consecutive weeks), then
they might want to reassess their battle plan. Viewers are growing
less intimidated by cable's kajillion channels, and more willing to
try less formulaic cable series on Lifetime, Comedy Central, and
VH1. And they don't seem exactly thrilled with the networks' notion
of series television _ of all the new shows that premiered on the
three majors last fall, only three have survived: ``Dharma &AMP;
Greg,'' ``Veronica's Closet,'' and ``Working.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, experimentation doesn't always equal creative
success, as evidenced by this season's most mindbendingly inane
show, ``The Secret Diary of Desmond Pfeiffer'' (Mondays at 9 on
UPN). It was imaginative, perhaps, to set a sitcom in Abraham
Lincoln's White House; but it was out-and-out absurd to use slavery
as a vehicle for humor, and to rely on jokes about stained dresses
and _ I kid you not _ toe cheese. It makes you long for ``Union
Square,'' almost.
</P>
<P>
   And anyway, ``Desmond Pfeiffer'' aside, the fall 1998 season
does not qualify as a disaster. It may be familiar, and bland, and
skewed on the young-and-pretty side, and it may offer up no
creative force prepared to dethrone David E. Kelley, the man
responsible for two of last year's finest shows _ ``Ally McBeal''
and ``The Practice.'' Still a few of the new harvest _
``Felicity,'' ``Will and Grace,'' ``Sports Night,'' ``Buddy Faro,''
``Maggie Winters,'' ``Jesse,'' ``Cupid'' _ show enough promise in
their pilot episodes to make up for insultingly infantile new fare
like Fox's ``Holding the Baby'' (Sundays at 7:30 on Fox). With some
tweaking, they stand a chance to last longer than Tom Selleck's
latest TV comeback.
</P>
<P>
   The best premiere of the season is on the up-and-coming WB
network, which is creating a solid youth-market niche with hits
like ``Dawson's Creek'' and ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer.'' It's a
drama called ``Felicity'' (Tuesdays at 9), but of course it's not
about blissfulness. Angst is the ticket, as a high school graduate
named Felicity goes against her controlling parents to chase a guy
to a New York university. She's like Claire Danes from ``My
So-Called Life'' in college, or Calista Flockhart from ``Ally
McBeal'' before law school, but she's also uniquely Felicity,
especially as played by talented newcomer Keri Russell. If
``Felicity'' were a movie, about a people-pleasing teenager who
hungers for real experience, it would be directed by Cameron Crowe.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the new shows split along gender lines, focusing either
on women trying to make it after all, or men in need of some heavy
bonding. The cosmetic and costume artists of ``Maggie Winters''
(Wednesdays at 8:30 on CBS) have worked hard to give star Faith
Ford that Ally McBeal bounce. But even as she spews high-strung
emotionality all over her supporting cast, the ``Murphy Brown''
alum makes an appealingly distinct impression. The show's concept,
like the Sandra Bullock movie ``Hope Floats,'' has Maggie moving
back home after a bad marriage, and reuniting with her high school
pals, who haven't changed since graduation. It's a charming sitcom
that argues we're all teenagers just below our adult surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of new comedies feature young blonde women waitressing in
bars and trying to exceed their blue-collar roots. ``Jesse''
(Thursdays at 8:30 on NBC) couldn't ask for a better time slot _
after ``Friends'' and before ``Frasier.'' But it may also succeed
on both the star quality of ``Married ... With Children'' alum
Christina Applegate, who plays a single mom hoping to become a
nurse, and a warm ensemble of men, including a slacker brother
who's taken a vow of silence. ``Costello'' (Tuesdays at 8:30 on
Fox) will have a rougher road, and not because it's set in a bar in
our own South Boston. With her loud delivery, stand-up comic Sue
Costello is more of an acquired taste than Applegate. She's like
one of Gilda Radner's wacky characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charmed'' (Wednesdays at 9 on WB) offers the irresistible
attraction of watching former ``Beverly Hills 90210'' brat Shannen
Doherty play a witch. In this girl-power drama of the supernatural,
Doherty and her two sisters fight ghouls without parental guidance
in picturesque San Francisco. It's ``Party of Five'' meets
``Buffy'' meets ``Sabrina.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as He TV goes, you can put away the Viagra. Most of these
guys are having pretty serious woman trouble. The most
disappointing of the boys club may be ``The Secret Lives of Men''
(Wednesdays at 9:30 on NBC), a sitcom about a trio of divorced
lunkheads who are burned by their exes and try to support one
another during and after golf games. Guys are people, too, you
know. Too bad Peter Gallagher is so wooden (and his accent is so
unnatural), and too bad the savvy about life after divorce doesn't
extend beyond lines like ``I'm finally able to take a nice,
peaceful dump.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports Night'' (Tuesdays at 9:30 on ABC) is better at
capturing a buddy chemistry, in large part thanks to the sure hand
of creator and executive producer Aaron Sorkin (he wrote ``A Few
Good Men'' and ``The American President''). The two leads, played
by Josh Charles and Peter Krause, are anchors of an ESPN-like
sports channel, and they deal with personal (divorce) and
professional (accuracy) conflicts. It's a state-of-the-art media
comedy, with influences from the movie ``Broadcast News'' and TV
series like ``The Larry Sanders Show'' and ``Lateline,'' with an
uncanny ability to slip dramatic moments into its newsroom frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   Two brothers form the dramatic center of ``Wind on Water''
(Saturdays at 8 on NBC), the season's most picturesque _ and most
turgid _ series. These dudes, Cole and Kelly, are expert surfers,
so the hour is filled with bloated wave sequences and oh-so-earthy
posing by their newly widowed mom, Bo Derek (no kidding). Sorry,
Bo, this show is a 1, not a 10. On the other hand, the pilot for
``Buddy Faro'' (Fridays at 9 pm CBS) is a wonderfully stylized hour
that bodes well for the crime series. Dennis Farina and Frank
Whaley are buddy private investigators in a garish, jazzy Los
Angeles that's just swimming with sharks.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of the fall guys are on their own. Poor ``Conrad
Bloom'' (Mondays at 8:30 on NBC) is surrounded by a whack pack of
needy women who keep him from finding true love. This sitcom stars
the easy-to-watch Mark Feuerstein, last seen on the un-dear
departed ``Fired Up,'' but it needs to find an identity. ``The
Brian Benben Show'' (Mondays at 9:30 on CBS) also gives us a hero
alone, a divorced news anchor demoted to features correspondent.
Benben, from ``Dream On,'' does his crazed shtick well enough, but
his vehicle needs to become something more than just a
run-of-the-mill media sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   On ``Brimstone'' (Tuesdays at 9 on Fox), Peter Horton is doomed
to be alone, since, of course, he is dead. No, it's not a sequel
series to ``thirtysomething,'' on which Horton passed unexpectedly
out of this world in a car crash. It's a hokey thriller about the
living dead doing battle on Earth. On ``Will and Grace'' (Mondays
at 9:30 on NBC), Will is probably doomed to remain single, since,
of course, he is a gay man on network TV. This sitcom version of
``My Best Friend's Wedding'' revolves around the love between a
willful straight woman and a graceful gay man. It's got a lot of
potential. And on the unexpectedly promising ``Cupid'' (Saturdays
at 10 on ABC), Jeremy Piven will probably remain unattached since,
of course, he is the god of love. He's been put on Earth (sans bow
and arrow) to match up 100 couples.
</P>
<P>
   The two best shots at strong drama are ``L.A. Doctors'' (Mondays
at 10 on CBS) and ``Trinity'' (Fridays at 9 on NBC). Ken Olin began
to turn slimy on ``thirtysomething,'' but on ``L.A. Doctors'' he
goes all the way as a publicity-hungry MD looking to make a million
in a managed-care environment. The show will need to work up some
new ethical quandaries if it wants to survive against ``ER'' and
``Chicago Hope.'' ``Trinity,'' on the other hand, has way too many
ethical challenges for its own good. What do you expect from a
family whose siblings include an avenging cop, a liberal priest, a
substance abuser, and a woman in love with a married man?
Simplification is in order on ``Trinity,'' especially since the
cast, including Tate Donovan, is first-rate.
</P>
<P>
   Last, and close to least, is the new ``Fantasy Island''
(Saturdays at 9 on ABC). Sure, executive producer Barry Sonnenfeld,
director of ``The Addams Family'' and ``Men in Black,'' has gussied
up this relic with some neat special effects and a sly Mr. Rourke
in the person of Malcolm McDowell. But the plots, in which
unsuspecting visitors learn big lessons on the island, are
painfully manipulative and moralistic. I think that kind of easy
answering was tired even back in the 1970s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
