<SLUG> BC-BOOK-KINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RUBE AND A SLICKER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whe Ethan Canin wowed critics with the beauty of his premiere
1988 story collection, ``Emperor of the Air,'' it was partly
because he was a kid with a Harvard medical degree _ a
well-marketed 27-year-old who had already survived a residency as
well as a debut in The New Yorker. That's the kind of transient
glory that publicists adore, but Canin had something far better to
offer. At its finest, his fiction is thick with longing: a
luminiscent ode to want and regret. Steeped in dreams but bound to
the ordinary covenants of a day, his characters are delivered to us
by way of the small humiliations and triumphs most people rarely
reveal but nearly always possess. In the presence of a Canin
epiphany, the morning light across a bank of trees may be enough to
bless a life, but not so that anyone else would notice.
</P>
<P>
   This depth of character is most successfully evoked in Canin's
short fiction, where the form requires inner impetus rather than
external range. Certainly the novel ``For Kings and Planets'' has
hints of it, particularly in the ocean-liner momentum of its
protagonist, an endearingly stalwart fellow named Orno Tarcher. But
Canin has returned here to a brooding filial theme _ it defined his
first novel, ``Blue River,'' as well as one of the novellas in
``The Palace Thief'' _ and written a far-flung work about two men
whose friendship is a study in contrasts. The result is uneven:
Some moments I loved ``For Kings and Planets''; at other times, I
wanted to send Canin back to class at the Iowa Writers' Workshop,
where he's now a teacher. With its impressive melancholy detail and
its cliched novelistic conceits, the book combines everything Canin
does right with some things he shouldn't be doing at all.
</P>
<P>
   The novel opens with that gravely retrospective phrase, ``Years
later,'' and so we know that Orno Tarcher, at least will survive to
remember the tale. When he arrives at Columbia University one
bright September day in 1974, he's a young man straight off the
farmland of Cook's Grange, Mo. _ upright and well-intentioned, both
terrified of and drawn to the inevitable expatriate's alienation
that awaits him. Within hours he has met Marshall Emerson, a
fatally ironic sophisticate with a probably-dark past who will show
Orno the world, then challenge him with it. Where Orno is solemn
and plodding, Marshall is capricious and brilliant; where the
Midwesterner is intent upon an education, perhaps in engineering,
Marshall, given his lifestyle habits, may well not make it through
the night. It's type cast against type, in other words, with Orno
playing the innocent rube from tractor country against Marshall's
Manhattan psychollectual: William Styron's Stingo to Nathan, say,
or a dozen other hayseed-cosmopolitan dyads of popular fiction.
</P>
<P>
   While Orno buries himself in chemistry texts, Marshall drinks
shots down at the neighborhood pseudo-literary bar and tries to
corrupt his friend; when Orno takes up with a Russian girlfriend,
Marshall charms her, then steals her away. The friendship between
the two men is a long, competitive, displaced seduction, sublimated
by women who don't matter and complicated by the one who does:
Marshall's little sister, who seems to have more sense than the
rest of the Emersons put together. When Marshall makes a feeble
suicide attempt and calls Orno, it's Simone Emerson, 17, who
accepts her brother's act for the performance it is, though she's
also fiercely loyal to him, even when his toxic manipulation
targets her. But then everyone is loyal to Marshall; he has the
force of a tornado. Not to mention the potential for destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Hints of Marshall's family pathology appear early on in ``For
Kings and Planets'': the unhappy contract of his intellectual
parents, both academics; the murderous footrace between father and
son for most-miserable status; the absent mother in Marshall's
first few years; the casual lying that hovers over his every
enchanting tale. He'll be the storm Orno has to define himself
against: a worthy adversary promising everything, presenting a
world that is beautiful but based on false gods. And it will be
Orno's predictable task to defy and transcend him. When the good
Midwestern boy applies to dental school, you sense that his awkward
acceptance of his lot will also be his saving.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, though, as familiar as this dark fraternal theme is, the
tempest between Orno and Marshall isn't the real problem with ``For
Kings and Planets''; it's a compelling formula, the way ``ER'' or
childhood fables are engagingly predictable. That can be one of the
pleasures of popular fiction, and while Canin has proved his mettle
at more literary and less compulsively readable pursuits, I don't
mean to undermine the straightforward narrative thrust this novel
accomplishes. More problematic, and ultimately annoying, is the way
Canin himself romanticizes Marshall, and thus undermines (and
thins) his character. What we have here is a near-sociopathic guy
with a suicidal streak as wide as Route 128 _ a fellow who
sabotages his family and friends, then shows up at 3 a.m. insisting
they join him in a glass of French Champagne. This isn't alluring;
it's pathetic. The tragic side of Marshall's personality is
eclipsed by his charisma rather than illuminated by it; drawn too
sympathetically, characters like this simply don't work anymore,
and haven't since Raymond Chandler.  &UR; ufspanish &LR; Oh, sure, he seems
darkly fabulous when he quotes Auden _ but that has more to do with
the beauty of ``Musee des Beaux Arts'' than with Marshall's eidetic
memory.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few errors in ``For Kings and Planets'' that a
writer of Canin's gifts shouldn't make: occasional tin-ear
dialogue, overuse of italics, internal inconsistences (the gender
of a cat keeps changing, for instance). But with Orno Tarcher _
lovable, earth-deep Orno _ Canin beautifully creates a character he
knows well. Like Abba Roth, the accountant-narrator of a novella in
``The Palace Thief,'' Orno is a steady man drawn with a slow hand;
the excruciating complexity of his feelings toward his father _ a
mix of familiarity and shame _ so precisely captures the
ambivalence of a son's love that it brings tears to one's eyes. We
love Orno for the same reasons Marshall loves him. He is the
essence of guilelessness and decency, and his generosity is as
natural to him as breathing.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps for his own reasons, Canin seems mesmerized by Marshall
but actually understands Orno better _ understands the gravitas and
tenacity that, in so many cases, collude to create a life. While
``For Kings and Planets'' is an easily gratifying story, full of
shadowy omens and potentially happy endings, I do hope Canin has
got the Cain-and-Abel thing out of his system. ``Nobody changes,''
Marshall tells Orno. ``They just reveal themselves.'' In this case,
the tortured anti-hero keeps turning up as the same unhappy fellow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
