<HEADLINE>
NEWSMAGAZINES DOMINATE NONFICTION TV 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't like TV newsmagazines? Then you'd better keep your channel
clicker handy this fall, because the television schedule will be
more crowded than ever with the progeny of ``60 Minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   By remaining relatively cheap to produce at a time when the cost
of sitcoms and dramas is skyrocketing, one-hour newsmagazines have
become the first resort of networks looking to plug holes in their
prime-time schedules.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, with their mixture of tearjerking stories,
exposes, and celebrity interviews, newsmagazines are emerging as a
force that could dominate the new television season.
</P>
<P>
   Not that they will have the field to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most anticipated programs is CNN's ``Cold War,'' a
24-part documentary hosted by Kenneth Branagh that is slated to
begin on Sept. 27. If you're in the mood for something less
weighty, A&AMP;E's ``Biography'' series this week launches a ``Can We
Talk?'' series of profiles of Regis Philbin, Merv Griffin, Don
Imus, Joan Rivers, and Geraldo Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, PBS has several significant projects on tap. On Sept.
21-23, PBS will broadcast ``The Farmer's Wife,'' a chronicle of the
ups and downs of a Nebraska farming family by Newton filmmaker
David Sutherland.
</P>
<P>
   The WGBH-Ch. 2 production of ``Africans in America,'' a
four-part documentary on the role played by Africans in the
founding of the United States, airs Oct. 19-22. The prodigious Ken
Burns is back on PBS Nov. 10-11 with ``Frank Lloyd Wright,'' a
documentary on the fabled architect.
</P>
<P>
   But on the commercial networks, newsmagazines will hold sway,
week in and week out.
</P>
<P>
   NBC has added an extra night of ``Dateline NBC,'' meaning the
newsmagazine _ which debuted on a single night in 1992 _ is now
spread across five nights of prime time: Sunday, Monday, Tuesday,
Wednesday, and Friday. That is a remarkable chunk of choice real
estate on the No. 1 network.
</P>
<P>
   At ABC, meanwhile, ``20-20'' is adding an extra show next week,
meaning the newsmagazine (into which ``PrimeTime Live'' will be
absorbed after this week) will now air three times a week: Sunday,
Wednesday, and Friday.
</P>
<P>
   CNN has plunged headfirst into the newsmagazine world with
``NewsStand'' (a Sunday show that repeats on Monday, plus new shows
on Wednesday and Thursday), and Fox News Channel recently launched
its own entrant, ``Fox Files,'' on Thursday nights.
</P>
<P>
   As for the granddaddy of them all, ``60 Minutes,'' the venerable
Sunday-night CBS franchise is expected to clone itself for a second
weekly edition by midseason, while ``48 Hours'' remains on the CBS
schedule as well, on Thursdays.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, not every newsmagazine is guaranteed success. CBS
dropped ``Public Eye With Bryant Gumbel'' from the fall schedule
(though there's an outside chance it could resurface at midseason).
But in general, newsmagazines have proven remarkably durable and
popular with viewers.
</P>
<P>
   That was especially evident this summer, when regular network
entertainment programming went into reruns, viewers shifted in
droves to newsmagazines. During one stretch, ``60 Minutes''
finished first in the ratings four times in five weeks. In late
July, six newsmagazines ranked in the Top 10; in the most recent
Nielsen ratings report, for the week of Aug. 24-30, eight of the
top 20 shows were newsmagazines.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason for the popularity of newsmagazines may be
that they feature some of the best-known anchors and reporters:
ABC's Barbara Walters and Diane Sawyer, NBC's Jane Pauley, CBS's
Mike Wallace, CNN's Bernard Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, newsmagazines such as ``Dateline'' are able to
broaden their horizons by discarding previously scheduled stories
at a moment's notice to pounce on breaking news developments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can do an expanded version of a news story in prime time,''
says ``Dateline'' spokesman Cory Shields, pointing to the show's
recent handling of Hurricane Bonnie and the stock-market plunge.
``People can tune in and get the major news story of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   That could be the wave of the future. As busy careers result in
fewer people getting home in time for the traditional early-evening
newscasts, networks may increasingly package miniature newscasts
into newsmagazines, which generally air between 9 and 11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows? If newsmagazines continue on their current roll,
maybe ``Dateline,'' rather than ``Seinfeld,'' will be rememberd as
the most-copied show of the 1990s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
