<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-VIDEOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PRIMARY COLORS' FADED; `WILD THINGS' WILD TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES:  &UR; ``Primary Colors''  &LR; _ Once again, history
outstrips fiction. Since President Clinton's confession, this
so-called satire has become as old-fashioned as Margaret Truman's
piano playing. While populated with terrific performances, this
Mike Nichols-directed political parody, based on Joe Klein's novel,
has already lost its punch.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Wild Things'' &LR;  _ John McNaughton directs the neo-noir set in
Florida with Bill Murray as sleazy, sex-mad Matt Dillon's nutty
attorney. Sometimes it's tough to follow all the twists and turns,
but one of the advantages of home video is that the slower thinkers
like myself can hit the rewind button to catch the stuff that
sneaked by the first time. Add Denise Richards and Neve Campbell as
a pair of diabolical nymphets and it makes for some wild times.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``John and Julie''  &LR; _ This odd little artifact focuses on two
children escaping to London to see the coronation of Queen
Elizabeth II. A bit slow, but the nonfiction footage of the queen's
ascension and an appearance by Peter Sellers make it more than just
a curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Elvis Meets Nixon''  &LR; _ This fanciful story surrounding the
meeting of Richard Nixon and Elvis Presley gives further proof that
the cable networks _ specifically HBO and Showtime _ provide a
great home for quirky ideas that don't fit Hollywood's
mega-marketing machine. Extremely entertaining and very smart.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``The Pentagon Wars'' &LR;  _ This HBO production, directed by
Richard Benjamin, stars Kelsey Grammer as an incompetent general
trying to cover up military miscalculations. Grammer is great as
the egotistical militarist and the script is very clever.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMING ATTRACTIONS:  &UR; Sept. 15:  &LR; ``Lady and the Tramp,'' ``He Got
Game,'' ``Deep Rising,'' ``Hush,'' ``Rhapsody in August,'' ``Eat
Drink Man Woman,'' ``Suicide Kings,'' ``Man With the Gun,'' ``To
Live.''  &UR; Sept. 22: `` &LR; Addams Family Reunion,'' ``Happy Together,''
``Nightwatch,'' ``Fallen Angels.''  &UR; Sept. 29:  &LR; ``The Object of My
Affection,'' ``The Song of Songs,'' ``The Trial,'' ``Milo,'' ``Two
Girls and a Guy,'' ``The Devil Is a Woman,'' ``Chinese Box,'' ``The
Flame of New Orleans,'' ``Paulie.''  &UR; Oct. 6 &LR; : ``Lost in Space,''
``Holiday Toons.''  &UR; Oct. 13: &LR;  ``The Big One,'' ``Black Dog,''
``It's a Gift,'' ``Million Dollar Legs,'' ``You Can't Cheat an
Honest Man,'' ``You're Telling Me,'' ``I Got the Hook Up.''  &UR; Oct.
20 &LR; : ``Chitty Chitty Bang Bang,'' ``Red Corner.''  &UR; Oct. 27:  &LR; ``The
Lion King II: Simba's Pride.''
</P>
