<HEADLINE>
GLOBE CRITICS RATE FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 ! poor, !! fair, !!! good, !!!! excellent  
 
 !!! ``Firelight''  Handsomely made by William Nicholson and
vibrantly acted by Sophie Marceau, this is a period drama with
impressive reach. An impoverished young woman agrees to serve as a
surrogate mother so a 19th-century English landowner will have an
heir; seven years later, she's hired as the child's governess, with
appropriately gothic consequences. (R)
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !! 1/2 &LR;   &UR; ``A Moment of Innocence'' &LR;  Iranian filmmaker Mohsen
Makhmalbaf's eclectic output includes intense social dramas and
absurdist comedies. This faux documentary has the director, who in
his youth was an anti-shah militant, re-create his stabbing of a
policeman 20 years earlier, with the collaboration of the
middle-aged ex-cop. The blend of deadpan comic tone with sentiment
doesn't ultimately work, though tension does escalate toward the
climax. The film's most successful aspect is its sense of place.
(Unrated) (Farsi; subtitles) (Betsy Sherman)
</P>
<P>
