<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-KINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARK STEVEN JOHNSON MAKES A JOHN IRVING-INSPIRED MOVIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Irving is one of the great writers of the past
quarter-century. He writes sprawling, enthralling books packed with
complicated and eccentric characters, whose lives are often marked
by stunning, sudden tragedy and violence. He takes common themes _
family, love, friendship, death _ and spins them into grand,
decades-spanning tales seasoned with humor and horror, pain and
poignancy.
</P>
<P>
   What John Irving doesn't do is write books easily made into
movies.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, some have tried. Director George Roy Hill, along with
stars Robin Williams, Glenn Close, and John Lithgow, wrestled with
``The World According to Garp,'' in 1982. The end result, while
watchable, was little more than the book's greatest hits _ a clip
job of quirky moments and characters that missed the book's charms.
Two years later, Tony Richardson had a go at ``The Hotel New
Hampshire,'' with Jodie Foster, Rob Lowe, and Beau Bridges, but
again the film never found the pulse of Irving's words.
</P>
<P>
   Even Irving himself has had difficulty turning his novels into
movies. For years, he tried unsuccessfully to write a screenplay
based on ``A Prayer for Owen Meany,'' his novel about an unlikely
friendship, Vietnam, and religion. So more than a few people
wondered aloud why Mark Steven Johnson, the young screenwriter best
known for the ``Grumpy Old Men'' films with Jack Lemmon and Walter
Matthau, would want to tackle Irving's 1989 book as his directorial
debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I finished the book, I put it down and thought, `This is
going to be a nightmare to try to make into a movie, and I'm not
quite sure how it can be done, but this will be the movie I
direct,'' Johnson said during a recent visit to Boston. ``But I
knew I had to do something so radical to it; in my estimation,
that's the only way it would work.''
</P>
<P>
   In Johnson's ``radical'' vision, Owen Meany became ``Simon
Birch,'' which opens Friday. Instead of spanning 15 years, it has
been streamlined into one extraordinary year in the lives of two
friends: Joe (Joseph Mazzello), the illegitimate son of an
independent-minded woman (Ashley Judd), and Simon (Ian Michael
Smith), a boy born small enough to fit in the palm of the doctor's
hand, who believes he is an instrument of the Lord. The film also
stars Oliver Platt and David Strathairn.
</P>
<P>
   In the film's credits, Johnson's screenplay is said to be
``suggested by'' Irving's novel, although Johnson believes
``inspired by'' is more accurate. (The Writers Guild wanted and got
``suggested by.'') The setting has moved from the 1950s to the
1960s, and the characters now live in Gravestown, Maine, instead of
Gravesend, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the changes, Johnson believes he is faithful to the
novel's spirit, keeping its opening, heard in voice-over by the
adult Joe, played in a cameo by Jim Carrey:
</P>
<P>
   (itals)``I am doomed to remember a boy with a wrecked voice _
not because of his voice, or because he was the smallest person I
ever knew, or even because he was the instrument of my mother's
death, but because he is the reason I believe in God.''(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   ``I like `inspired by' better,'' Johnson said. `Suggested by'
sounds strange, and it doesn't give enough credit to how much of
the novel really is in this movie, which is a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   For fans of the book, Johnson keeps the stuffed armadillo, and
the fatal foul ball. Of course, it might not be enough to satisfy
Irving devotees, which is why the author suggested a name change,
said Johnson, who came up with Simon Birch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `They need to know that if you're looking for a
faithful adaptation of `A Prayer for Owen Meany,' you're not going
to find it,''' Johnson said. ``You'll find a lot of the book, but
it's not a word-for-word adaptation.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite reports to the contrary, Johnson maintains Irving has
been supportive of the film. The two men, he said, have been in
constant contact about the script's development and its deviations
from Irving's book. The most-debated aspect, Johnson said, was his
decision to eliminate the Vietnam War, the setting of the book's
dramatic conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``John said, `My novel is about two things _ religion and
Vietnam. You want to take Vietnam out, and that's half the novel to
me,''' said Johnson, recalling Irving's conversation. ``I said to
John, `I don't know what else to say about Vietnam.' As far as
movies go, there've been so many Vietnam movies. At the end of the
day, it's really the same theme _ Vietnam was a mistake, war is
hell, the government lied to us. It's all true, but to me it wasn't
interesting anymore, and if I didn't have anything fresh to say
about it, I didn't want to say anything. He got that.''
</P>
<P>
   Another change also altered the story's dramatic structure.
Irving's book spans 1953 to 1968; Johnson instead concentrates on
1964, when Joe and Simon are 11 years old. He always knew he wanted
to center his film during the boys' childhood, but that idea became
especially clear when he found an actor to play Simon, ``the
smallest delivery ever recorded in the history of Gravestown
Memorial Hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson discovered Ian Michael Smith, now 12, shortly after the
boy lost a role in ``The Mighty,'' starring Sharon Stone, to Kieran
Culkin. In that film Culkin plays a boy with Morquio's syndrome,
which causes dwarfism; Smith was born with the same rare condition.
Casting directors familiar with the 3-foot-1-inch Smith soon
alerted Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, `This kid's amazing, you gotta meet him,''' Johnson
said. ``When I met him, my jaw dropped. I said, `That's him, that's
the guy, I just know it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Even as he tested others for the part, Johnson hired an acting
coach for Smith, who had no professional experience. He saw more
than 100 kids worldwide, but always knew Smith was Simon.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of them had what Ian had,'' Johnson said. ``When he
smiles, you smile. He just lights up the screen, and he breaks your
heart. I was afraid the studio would be worried because he's not
traditionally cute. He's not an adorable Disney tyke. But I just
thought he was beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Making a dramatic film, albeit one with comic moments, may seem
a departure for Johnson, 33, unless you're familiar with his own
loopy entry into Hollywood. Born in Minnesota, Johnson moved to Los
Angeles in his 20s to pursue a film career. He wound up as an
$8-an-hour secretary at Orion Pictures. Between sorting faxes and
answering phones, he wrote his first script. At a time when other
25-year-olds were working on their latest screed to 20-something
angst or imitating Quentin Tarantino, Johnson was writing about
cranky sexagenarians and ice fishing in his native Minnesota.
``Grumpy Old Men,'' and its sequel, ``Grumpier Old Men,'' went on
to make more than $150 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time everyone was writing `Die Hard' movies _ `Die
Hard' on a bus, `Die Hard' on a plane. I tried to do that but I
just didn't know how to write that kind of movie,'' Johnson said.
``I didn't have that many life experiences, so I wrote about my
grandfather, who the Jack Lemmon character was based on, and I
wrote it in four weeks. It was this goofy movie about old people
and ice fishing, and it made people laugh. I think that's why it
stood out.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife, who worked at a hospital, passed the script to a
co-worker whose cousin was a former agent _ an LA story, if ever
there was one. The success of the film made Johnson a hot property,
and emancipated him from Orion's secretarial pool.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's moved from the ranks of screenwriters to the director's
chair with ``Simon Birch,'' and has been spared doing ``Grumpy Old
Men: The Next Generation,'' he said. When he was pitching the
project, the hardest thing was describing ``Simon Birch'' as
something the high-concept Hollywood minds could grasp. He told
them it's the story of two friends, each on a personal quest _ Joe,
to discover his father's identity, and Simon, to understand his
place in God's plan _ and how their separate destinies intersect in
1964.
</P>
<P>
   Now if he can just sell that to audiences who've spent recent
months dodging asteroids and riled-up reptiles.
</P>
<P>
   Thinking of a new pitch, Johnson paused for a beat, then said,
``Just tell people it's a Jim Carrey movie. Let's just get all the
money we can on the opening weekend, then run like hell.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
