<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-SOLDIER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FICTIONAL DIARY DETAILS HELL IN CIVIL WAR PRISON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
A SOLDIER'S BOOK 
By Joanna Higgins 
Permanent Press, 191 pp., $24 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   During the Civil War, mainly during its final 18 months, more
than 56,000 men, pretty evenly divided between Union soldiers and
Confederates, died in prisoner-of-war camps. They died of cholera
and yellow fever, of starvation and untended injuries. They
represented roughly 14 percent of all those held in the camps, both
North and South. A young Michigan sergeant being held in the
Confederate prison at Andersonville, Ga., wrote in his diary on
June 27, 1864: ``The further advanced the summer, the death rate
increases, until they die off by scores. I walk around to see
friends of a few days ago and am told, Dead.''
</P>
<P>
   This passage from the diary of Sergeant John Ransom is quoted in
``Andersonville,'' MacKinlay Kantor's epic novel of 1955, one of
the few works of fiction to deal with the unremitting, inglorious
suffering of the prison camps. The diary form is adopted by Joanna
Higgins (author of a well-regarded story collection, ``The
Importance of High Places'') for her grim and gritty first novel,
``A Soldier's Book.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a literary journey ``farther and farther downward into the
valley of darkness'' _ to use a phrase that Higgins's fictional
diarist employs to describe his transportation to the prison camp.
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of problems inherent in presenting a
fictional diary as the complete text of a novel. Since the diarist
has little or no reason to tell himself about his past life, and
since a novelist who plays fair can't go much farther than the
diarist does, the reader is forced to supply much of the context.
</P>
<P>
   The Civil War does at least provide a general context familiar
to general readers. Nonetheless, ``A Soldier's Book'' sometimes
requires a quick look at a standard history _ or even at
``Andersonville'' (which almost inevitably becomes an extended
reading rather than a quick look). The military and political
issues of the prisoner-of-war exchanges, which occupy much of the
diarist's concern, is one such case. Another is the arrest, trial,
and hanging of a gang that had terrorized fellow Union prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   But more important than such background matters, the conventions
of the diary as novel require readers to stretch their imagination.
It is a tribute to Higgins's craft that, by and large, ``A
Soldier's Book'' works _ gradually so, as the diarist becomes a
fully realized character and the reader grows accustomed to his
point of view and his manner of writing.
</P>
<P>
   Higgins's diarist is Ira Cahill Stevens, a young apprentice
apothecary from northeastern Pennsylvania (where Higgins lives),
who was captured during the Battle of the Wilderness. The reader
learns little more about him, because it is his present condition
that is of overriding concern _ to the reader and the diarist.
</P>
<P>
   The diary entries cover some six months through the summer into
the fall of 1864, a period during which the humane practice of
routinely exchanging prisoners had been halted because Union
leaders realized that most exchanged Confederates were being sent
back to their regiments. Stuck with a growing number of internees,
both sides hastily threw up stockades in isolated locations.
Supplying the influx of prisoners with food or clothing, or
providing medical care, were afterthoughts at best.
</P>
<P>
   Still worse, the ending of exchanges deprived prisoners of hope;
speculation that they would be resumed are subjects of daily
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The words the 7th pass man to man with the greatest
reverence,'' Stevens writes one day in July. ``Exchanges to
commence on that day, we hear. ... It is hard to wait with hope.
But harder without it. Hardest of all is to be a battlefield, the
slashing and cutting all inside.''
</P>
<P>
   So hopeless does even survival appear that prisoners often
crawled across the ``dead line,'' into the forbidden territory near
the stockade, knowing that sentries would see them _ and shoot
them. ``Saw another fellow exchange himself at the dead line,''
Stevens writes. ``Didn't make a sound. It's like some ordinary
transaction. An exchange in fact.''
</P>
<P>
   The writing is plain and uncolored, as one would expect from a
diary, but no less vivid for that in its relating of incidents and
portrayal of comrades. And it is wonderfully compressed, as a diary
written under horrific conditions would be. The somewhat wooden
title is a reference to a pocket-size handbook published in
Cambridge in 1862 and intended for distribution to the young
Christian soldier going forth ``in defense of his country.''
</P>
<P>
   Civil War novels have most typically been a male thing, from
Stephen Crane to Charles Frazier. So Joanna Higgins joins a very
select company _ Margaret Mitchell, most famously, but also Mary
Johnston, the granddaughter of Confederate General Joseph E.
Johnston and author of two of the most vivid of all Civil War
novels, ``The Long Roll'' and ``Cease Firing.'' Here, it is a
soldier's hell that is made vivid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
