<SLUG> BC-FILMS-ASIANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASIAN AMERICANS SEEK BROADER ROLE IN HOLLYWOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE CHAO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ For decades, Asian Americans have been lobbying
Hollywood to include more Asian faces in movies and television
shows. Now it's finally happening, although the result is not what
they hoped for.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I come across Asians portrayed in the media these days,
it always has something to do with kung fu, or that stereotypical
evil mystique,'' said Nancy Hom, a San Francisco arts producer.
``We're either gambling or (taking) opium.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, little has changed in 20 years. And Hollywood's
recent fascination with the Hong Kong action genre has made some
feel that stereotyped characters have become even more prevalent.
``Lethal Action 4'' and ``Replacement Killers'' are two of the
latest films to feature Asian triad-types.
</P>
<P>
   Some Asian Americans are now talking about the best way to
counter negative portrayals. Strategies range from protesting every
objectionable incident to just ignoring them.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer Nakasako is a documentary filmmaker who works with
underprivileged teen-agers in San Francisco, mostly immigrants from
Southeast Asia. The teens have grown up watching actor Jet Li as
the good guy in numerous Hong Kong action flicks, but were crushed
when they saw him play a menacing Asian mobster in ``Lethal Weapon
4,'' his first American film.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a lot of the kids I work with were really disappointed
because they're used to Jet Li being a hero,'' he said. ``They're
like, `How come he's a bad guy?' For them, it didn't make any
sense.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end, Mel Gibson's character kills off Jet Li in a bloody,
brutal fight.
</P>
<P>
   Darrell Hamamoto, a professor of Asian-American studies at the
University of California at Davis, takes the criticism of ``Lethal
Weapon 4'' a step further.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we have everybody _ whites, blacks, Jews and feminists _
aligned against the yellow peril,'' he said, referring to
characters played by Gibson, Danny Glover, Joe Pesci and Rene
Russo.
</P>
<P>
   Warner Bros. did not return calls for comment on ``Lethal Weapon
4.''
</P>
<P>
   Hom said Hollywood should strive to portray Asian Americans as
three-dimensional people and noted that omitting them was just as
objectionable as vilifying them.
</P>
<P>
   Television shows such as ``Party of Five'' and ``Suddenly
Susan,'' Hom said, took place in San Francisco but had nary an
Asian character. The city's population is 34 percent Asian.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hardly see an Asian even walking in the background,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Producer Janet Yang disagrees that things are getting worse for
Asian Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Although the situation is far from ideal, ``the opportunities
for Asian-American actors are incredible. I have friends playing
doctors and lawyers and judges and teachers on major shows,'' said
Yang, who was Oliver Stone's production partner for seven years
before starting her own company two years ago with another partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go back 20 or 30 years,'' she said. ``There was nothing.
(Asian-American actors) back then were playing butlers and maids.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, more and more Asian Americans are studio executives,
and doing better than their black and Hispanic counterparts, said
Yang, a producer of ``The Joy Luck Club.''
</P>
<P>
   A smattering of Asian Americans have begun to appear on TV. But
they remain the exception rather than the norm. Berkeley-based film
consultant Gary Meyer believes non-stereotypical roles for Asian
Americans have increased only minimally.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems the larger push has been to get African Americans in
less stereotypical roles,'' Meyer said.
</P>
<P>
   As interest in Asian culture grows, some studios are responding.
Disney's summer blockbuster ``Mulan,'' set in ancient China, has
been well-received by audiences, but some Asian Americans still saw
cause for complaint.
</P>
<P>
   ``Must all sinister Chinese people have Fu Manchus?'' asked
columnist Emil Guillermo in a recent AsianWeek item criticizing the
movie.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles-based Media Action Network for Asian Americans
(MANAA) has been monitoring ethnic slurs and stereotypes in the
mass media since 1992. In its early days, the complaints it dealt
with were equally split between Korean and Japanese issues, said
spokesman Guy Aoki.
</P>
<P>
   This past year, every documented complaint was about use of the
word ``Chinaman.'' It appeared in numerous TV shows, radio
broadcasts and films, including ``U.S. Marshals'' and ``Seinfeld.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, you'd have it here and there over the years, but
not like this,'' Aoki said.
</P>
<P>
   He attributes it to the economic and political ascendance of
China, and media reports that commonly refer to it as the next
superpower.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, everything is China,'' he said. ``China is in the news.''
</P>
<P>
   MANAA has had mixed success in meeting with the appropriate
executives and getting a public apology or retraction. One show it
did reach a satisfactory conclusion with was ``Seinfeld.''
</P>
<P>
   In the April 9 episode, a character joked that opium was like a
``Chinaman's nightcap.'' After MANAA objected, NBC agreed it had
erred and agreed to delete the line from subsequent showings.
</P>
<P>
   But after years of complaining, some Asian Americans are
beginning to wonder how they can be more effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think too much emphasis is placed on what's politically
incorrect and not enough emphasis on what we're going to do about
it,'' said Jeff Adachi, a San Francisco public defender who also
chairs the Asian-American Arts Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   He believes Asian Americans should take out their wallets and
invest in the arts in the way African Americans have begun to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 70s, they had blaxploitation; we had Bruce Lee,'' he
said. ``It hasn't gone beyond that for Asians, whereas black cinema
has evolved.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 1354EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
