<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3686 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAGE-FOSSE-2TAKES-BO     09-08 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-FOSSE-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETURN OF THE FOSSE RAZZLE DAZZLE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; They're all in black, from their top hats to their toes.
Fingers splayed, arms bent at acute angles, they writhe, slither,
and slide. One minute, they wriggle, sinuous as snakes; the next,
they freeze, limbs locked at impossible angles. Here's a drumroll,
a tip of a hat, a tap of a cane.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's show time, folks!''
</P>
<P>
   Whenever they give 'em the old razzle-dazzle in that
distinctive, inimitable way, there can be no doubt that the guiding
spirit has to be the late choreographer Bob Fosse. ``Everybody
knows the Bob Fosse silhouette; you can spot it a mile away,'' says
director Richard Maltby Jr. But in this case, the Fosse oeuvre is
hardly miles away. More than a decade after his death, in 1987 at
age 60, the choreographer is enjoying a posthumous comeback, a
curtain call that is arguably as splashy as the death dance he
staged in his semi-autobiographical film, ``All That Jazz.''
Revivals of such Fosse signature shows as ``Chicago'' and ``Sweet
Charity'' have met with critical and box-office success, and
theaters in New York and beyond are restaging lesser-known works
like ``Redhead'' and ``Little Me.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's ``Fosse: A Celebration in Song and Dance,'' an
ambitious retrospective that premiered in Toronto in July and opens
a three-week run in Boston Tuesday before moving to Los Angeles and
then Broadway. A corps of 36 dancers performs one knock-'em-dead
show stopper after another, ranging from the warm folksiness of
``Shoeless Joe From Hannibal, Mo.'' to the balletic grace of
``Crunchy Granola'' to the cool come-on of ``Steam Heat'' to the
driving beat of ``I Gotcha.'' In three hours, the encyclopedic show
spans four decades, with dances culled from Fosse's work in
theater, television, and film.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of this work is dated,'' says Ann Rein-king, the dancer
who codirected the show with Maltby. ``It may come from a certain
era, but it's timeless.'' The retrospective is strictly dancing,
with no book or narration or any attempt to stage a Fosse
biography. (That's another story entirely.) It was initially
conceived a few years ago, when Fosse's onetime wife, dance legend
Gwen Verdon, and a Fosse dancer named Chet Walker started a
workshop in New York to teach the choreographer's style to young
hoofers. That informal effort led to the idea for a retrospective,
and the Toronto-based producing company Livent Inc. embraced the
idea.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the team brought in Maltby, who is best known for
his conception of ``Ain't Misbehavin','' the successful musical
tribute to Fats Waller. Maltby remembers traveling to Toronto
``basically to turn down the show,'' because he didn't want to
stage what he describes as ``a variation on an `And then I
choreographed ...' show, with narrative anecdotes and stuff.'' He
envisioned the celebration as an internally organized revue that
would capture the essence of Fosse without force-feeding the
audience biographical details and dates. Maltby shares conception
credit with Walker and Reinking, and Verdon is billed as artistic
adviser. ``I think of the show as a sort of aesthetic journey,''
Maltby says. ``It's certainly the journey of the heart of a man.''
</P>
<P>
   A complicated man, at that. Off stage, he was known as a
mercurial genius who could be both tender and tough,
self-deprecating and self-aggrandizing; his life has become the
stuff of backstage legend, particularly the stories about his
amorous adventures. In the studio, his work as a choreographer and
director is more often than not described as cool and detached,
sophisticated and sexy; in such works as ``Chicago'' and the film
version of ``Cabaret,'' he chronicled the seamy underside of
show-biz life, depicting the seductive yet destructive appeal of
glamour. He took a cold, calculated look at excess in the '70s and
'80s, long before such cynicism became fashionable.
</P>
<P>
   That cynicism is what some folks zoom in on when they think of
the Fosse ``style,'' associating the choreographer with a kind of
barren sexuality devoid of emotion. That infuriates his daughter
Nicole Fosse, who, along with her mother, Gwen Verdon, served as
consultant for the show. ``I want to clear up what hundreds of
people have been twisting around for years,'' she says. ``His work
explored relationships, politics, love, and sex, issues other
people didn't dare delve into at the time. But if nobody wanted to
see it, everything would have flopped, right? He was diving into
topics that made people tick, and that's what intrigued people
about his work.''
</P>
<P>
   A former dancer and mother of two (with a third child on the
way), Nicole Fosse alternately bristles and beams when she
discusses her father's work at a cast party immediately after the
opening in Toronto. ``I heard a woman at the performance today turn
to her husband and say, `Well, he certainly had a fixation on the
behind,''' she says, letting out a long whoop of a laugh. ``All
those dancers up there are actors. They're up there with political
ideas, with a life, with a story. They're complex human beings.
They're actors, and that's how Bob Fosse approached everything. It
was never just `Wiggle your behind' or `Shake bells on your
tush-ee.' If you really watch with an open-minded, intellectual
perspective, there is so much more up there. Am I being clear?''
</P>
<P>
   What's up there, Nicole Fosse, Reinking, and Maltby say, is the
spirit of a man who criticized society harshly but who embraced his
closest confidants tenderly. ``His work questions morality, big
time,'' says Reinking. ``He showed us the seduction of glamour and
how it can be a deadly thing.'' Reinking _ who lived with Fosse
after he and Verdon officially separated _ allows that the
choreographer did have a dark side, but insists that he also was
able to attain a certain lightness of being. ``He did have real
depression, and he did despair, but in spite of that, he couldn't
help coming up laughing and finding something that would touch him
dearly. And then he'd bounce back and go for it again.''
</P>
<P>
   The show aims to chronicle those times he went for it, to keep
the Fosse signature alive for generations to come. ``In the
theater, we're profligate with our artists,'' Maltby says. ``It's
not until about 10 years after a death that you realize what you've
lost. Fosse wasn't deified during his career. We got a Fosse show
every four or five years, which we could sneer at but privately
love. Now, we can feel his absence. There is a void, and this show
helps us realize what we have.'' The creators scoured film
libraries and archives to re-create works that had not been
documented, and part of the goal is to preserve the Fosse legacy.
``Dance is passed down person to person,'' Maltby says. The young
dancers will pass the tradition on, so that dancers who are only
toddlers today might look in the mirror someday in the future,
straighten their top hat, pull on their gloves, and say, ``It's
show time, folks!''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Louis Fosse was born in Chicago in 1927; his father, a
salesman who was also a vaudeville performer, prodded him onto the
stage. The young Fosse was working Chicago clubs by age 15 and he
stayed on stage until the day he died of a heart attack in 1987 on
a street in Washington, D.C., a few hours before his revival of
``Sweet Charity'' was set to open at the National Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 1358EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3689 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAGE-FOSSE-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     09-08 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-FOSSE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... National Theatre.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The choreographer had modest aspirations as a youth. ``All he
ever wanted to be was a nightclub performer,'' Maltby says. He did
a lot more than that over the years: He worked his way out of the
nightclubs and onto the Broadway stage, playing such roles as the
slick gigolo in ``Pal Joey'' and eventually turning to
choreography. The young hoofer who got his start in the clubs
eventually went on to win what show-biz folks refer to as the
triple crown: In 1973, he won the Oscar for ``Cabaret,'' the Tony
for ``Pippin,'' and the Emmy for the television special ``Liza With
a Z.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, of course, he developed that style. He once
claimed his distinctive look stemmed from an attempt to hide his
own deficiencies: ``I was getting pretty bald for a hoofer and felt
a hat would hide it. Canes became important to me when my hands
started trembling and seemed like a good way to distract the
audience.''
</P>
<P>
   In his 40-year career, he had a way of mixing modesty and
bravado. The 1979 film ``All That Jazz'' takes a scathing,
self-critical look at the life of an artist; his screen surrogate,
Joe Gideon, is a shameless womanizer who overdoes it when it comes
to work and women and overdoses when it comes to tobacco and drugs.
The character, whose only redeeming qualities are the brilliance of
his work and his fondness for his young daughter, literally drives
himself to death _ and then stages his own requiem, Broadway-style.
</P>
<P>
   Fosse, no doubt, took plenty of creative license with his own
life story. The film is utterly unforgiving of the Gideon
character, who maintains a working relationship with his dancer
wife while he lives with another dancer (played by Reinking). To
outsiders, it's astonishing that they all remained friends, but
they did and continue to work together to this day. Verdon and
Reinking are the closest of collaborators on ``Fosse.'' What about
normal human emotions, like jealousy and anger?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing to me,'' admits a perplexed Maltby. ``I haven't a
clue how they do it. They're all larger-than-life people who have
lived very complicated and fascinating lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Verdon scoffs at the public's fascination with those very
complicated lives. ``People are so in-trigued by sex, and I just
couldn't care less,'' she says. ``One person even said that Bob had
a voracious appetite, which makes him sound like a glutton. He
liked women. They're beautiful. But the women he knew, such as Ann
Reinking, were very bright women. They weren't just dumb dancers.''
</P>
<P>
   She dismisses published accounts that recount his love affairs
with the zealousness of, say, an independent prosecutor. As for
``All That Jazz,'' she says, ``A true biography would have been
very boring. He had to make it theatrical.'' The real Bob Fosse,
she says, was ``your ordinary, everyday 9-to-5 guy'' who loved
sports and puttered around the house.
</P>
<P>
   Nicole Fosse says her father once told her the only true
relationship in the film is the touching one between the Joe Gideon
character and his daughter. ``Everybody loves sensationalism,'' she
says. ``Everyone in the line at the grocery store peeks at the
tabloids; they don't buy them but they peek. I'm not going to say
Bob Fosse was perfect and he was an angel, but who was? Look at
Balanchine. Does he have a perfect reputation? Look at Jerry
(Jerome) Robbins. Does he? Nobody has a perfect reputation, so
what's the big deal?''
</P>
<P>
   The man she wants people to see in the retrospective is the
father who once introduced her to Vivaldi by comparing his music to
Pink Floyd. She wants people to get a feel for the father she
danced for when she was a preteen and lived with for the first time
after he and her mother separated. At the time, he was working on
``Dancin','' the Broadway valentine to dancers that he
choreographed and directed in 1978. ``All of a sudden, he had this
prepubescent, exuberant child in his home,'' she recalls. ``I
wasn't jaded yet. Do you remember when you're just about to start
falling in love, and you can't stop talking and can't contain
yourself? I was as pure as could be.''
</P>
<P>
   The choreographer told her a story about an old man who loves to
dance but can't do it anymore, and he asked her to dance with him
as he played the old man. The father shuffled gingerly while the
daughter did the ballet version behind him. ``We stayed up all
night; he would do little bell kicks while I did big assembles,''
she says. That all-nighter eventually became ``Mr. Bojangles,'' a
sentimental number about what a dancer does when he can't dance
anymore. It's in the retrospective, a quiet, contemplative moment
in an otherwise rock-'em-sock-'em display of powerhouse numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Nicole Fosse says ``Bojangles'' makes her eyes go fuzzy every
time she sees it. As for her parents' unusual relationship, she
says, ``They had a child together. They worked brilliantly
together. You don't split that up. They were very sophisticated and
very honest.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicole Fosse, in fact, was adamant that the retrospective be
produced now, while her mother, who is 73, could still be a part of
the creative process. ``I knew at some point somebody was going to
do it,'' she says. ``It was inevitable. And it would have been nuts
to do it without the deep consultation of Gwen Verdon. You have to
have worked closely with Bob Fosse to understand him, and if you
lived with him, even better. Gwen Verdon and Ann Reinking not only
worked with him many times, but they were also privy to his most
personal thoughts and feelings. He always used life as an integral
part of his work, and you can't separate the two. That's why you
cry. That's why you laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   So despite the unusual relationships of the collaborators, the
backstage drama associated with this show had nothing to do with
the Fosse family. The day after ``Fosse'' opened in Toronto, the
new management at Livent suspended its founders Garth Drabinsky and
Myron Gottlieb, citing ``ir-regularities'' in a financial audit.
Late last week, the company appointed Todd Haimes, currently
running New York's Roundabout Theatre Company, to the new position
of artistic director. Financial control of the prolific producing
company had been taken over by former Disney honcho Mike Ovitz and
investment banker Roy Furman in April.
</P>
<P>
   The departure of Drabinsky and Gottlieb had been expected in
theater circles, and Verdon, for one, says the change doesn't worry
her. ``The show is too good,'' she says. ``They could put a gorilla
in there, and it would still go on. And Ovitz and Furman are both
very bright men. They're very secure about dollars and cents, and
Annie (Reinking) and I are very secure about good theater.''
</P>
<P>
   They've both starred in Fosse creations; Rein-king staged the
recent acclaimed tour of ``Chicago'' that played the Colonial last
year. They know the moves: the shoulder shimmies, the forward
struts, the shuffles and slides. This time they're tipping their
hats to the master himself, adding a touch of reverence to the
words Joe Gideon said so ironically in ``All That Jazz.'' You know
the rap by now: It's show time, folks.
</P>
</TEXT>
