<HEADLINE>
MOISES KAUFMAN'S TOP-GROSSING AMERICAN DREAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Moises Kaufman grew up in a household where they
discussed Spinoza over dinner and threw in a little Aristotle for
dessert. As a child in Caracas, Venezuela, he remembers being
encouraged to philosophize _ Please pass the Plato _ and to
investigate matters of the mind.
</P>
<P>
   At 34, there's no doubt that Kaufman would make the ideal dinner
guest, entertaining companions with a probing intelligence that is
seasoned with a dry, almost mischievous wit. But for all his
conversational skills, he still couldn't talk anyone into producing
his play, ``Gross Indecency: The Three Trials of Oscar Wilde'' when
he shopped it around a few years ago. He says he approached 37
producers, and 37 producers turned him down. And then he simply
mounted the play himself.
</P>
<P>
   What happened next is the kind of story anyone who's ever
dreamed the impossible absolutely adores. Kaufman and his small
theater company, the Tectonic Theatre Project, scraped together
$15,000 to produce the play at a tiny theater in Greenwich Village.
With virtually no advertising, this play about the great Irish
dramatist by an unknown writer from Venezuela sold out every night.
Word spread. By the time the uptown critics heard of the production
(with the help of a clever letter that began, ``Pleading to Dear
Members of the Press''), Kaufman had proved all those producers
wrong. Since then, the New York production has moved twice to
larger houses, and it's still playing at the Minetta Lane Theater.
Another production is opening in London, and the play is making the
rounds on the regional theater circuit. The Huntington Theatre
Company production opens on Friday and runs through Oct. 11.
</P>
<P>
   Now everyone wants to say they discovered the play before it
became successful. ``I think it reinforces something very profound
about the belief in the American Dream,'' Kaufman says. ``We love
seeing people succeed. We love it when, all of a sudden, this
little struggling theater company makes this incredible stride in
the world, because it allows us all to believe that it's
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman himself had no idea that he would embody the mythical
American Dream when a friend gave him a book called ``The Wit and
Wisdom of Oscar Wilde'' a few years back. He had read the
dramatist's greatest hits _ ``The Importance of Being Earnest,''
``An Ideal Husband.'' He knew the Irish writer had been tried on
charges of homosexual acts in Victorian England, but he didn't
realize that the dramatist had founded the aesthetic movement, that
he had embraced art as the only pure form of expression in a
changing world. The little book of quotes included transcripts from
Wilde's trials: The writer at first sued his lover's father, the
marquess of Queensbury, for slander and then ended up being tried
twice himself and convicted of ``gross indecency'' in 1895.
</P>
<P>
   The man who grew up contemplating Spinoza set off on a research
binge. He expected to come up with a definitive version of the
story, but like any good historian, he discovered varying degrees
of truth. ``The formal problem became, `How can theater reconstruct
history?' And then, of course, that leads to the bigger question,
`What is history?''' Kaufman says, echoing the thought. ``What is
history?''
</P>
<P>
   Around that time, he happened to be talking to a friend who
teaches history to high school students in the Bronx. The
adolescents were quite apathetic, so Kaufman's friend pushed them
to define history before they even started their studies. ``They
came up with a definition: History is a story told by people in
power, in the vocabulary of people in power, mostly about other
people in power,'' Kaufman explains. ``I like that definition
because it involves this idea of versions, and it resembles theater
very much because theater deals with people telling stories. So how
do you create a theatrical event that encompasses all those
versions?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gross Indecency'' does exactly that. Nine male actors perform
in two playing areas. One is a platform that serves as the
courtroom, and the other is a table covered with research
materials. As the trials proceed, the actors read from the books
and articles, demonstrating the research process as the play is
performed. The audience gets to consider the various
interpretations from primary sources: Kaufman even writes himself
into the play, in a scene where the ``playwright'' discusses
Wilde's role as the first ``modern homosexual'' with a New York
University academic. ``That's because I'm an egomaniac,'' Kaufman
quips during a telephone interview, groaning as he hears the
computer keyboard constructing this sentence as he speaks. ``No, it
was a tongue-in-cheek thing. The play poses the question of how we
construct history, and the way we do that is the way we construct
identity and who we are in the larger context of the universe.
How's that for an answer?''
</P>
<P>
   The question of identity, of course, is at the core of
contemporary society, when hyphens and labels seem like inadequate
stand-ins for the larger issue of how we define ourselves in this
confusing, balkanized world. Kaufman has wrestled with that
question himself. The son of a Romanian-born father and a mother of
Ukrainian Jewish descent, he was raised in Venezuela speaking
Spanish, English, and Hebrew. But his confusion had nothing to do
with language. ``It had to do with growing up Jewish in a Catholic
country,'' he says. ``It had to do with growing up as a gay person
in a very heterosexual country. It had to do with having artistic
inclinations in a society that is very business-oriented. So there
was always the sense of being `The Other.' I've been an outsider
all of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   His father owned a food business, and his mother was
vice-president of a bank. Despite their business acumen, at home
they encouraged their three children to discuss the classics the
way other families contemplate the weather or neighborhood gossip.
``My dinner conversations were about Spinoza,'' Kaufman says,
laughing as he hears the keyboard click-clacking on the other end
of the line. ``I know, I know, I know, it sounds absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he explains that his father survived the Holocaust in
Romania and fled to Paris after World War II. He contracted
tuberculosis and ended up in a Parisian hospital for a year. ``He
asked the nurse to go to the library and bring him books, starting
with the letter A,'' Kaufman says. ``When he got out of the
hospital after a year, people couldn't believe the way he spoke, in
this beautifully florid literary manner, with all these references
to the obscurest of works by the most famous of writers. In a
sense, World War II made me an artist, because it gave him the
knowledge that instilled in me this intellectual rigor and
appetite. Growing up, there wasn't a lot of stimulation outside the
house, but inside, there was a very rich and fertile ground.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jewish family practiced religion inside the house, but
appeared secular in the outside world. ``It's funny, there's
something about Judaism that says you can be Jews at home but not
outside. Needless to say, that comes in very handy when you're
gay.'' A pause and a laugh. ``I should tell them that! Mom, Dad, I
can't thank you enough for teaching me to be in the closet!''
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman did have a coming out scene back home in Caracas, and he
came to terms with his sexuality when he moved to New York in 1987
to study directing at New York University. His voice does a sort of
verbal twitch when he recalls telling his family he is gay . ``I
got a range of reactions, from `It doesn't matter,' to `This is
going to be hard for me,' to cries and hugs and kisses,'' he says.
``It's very interesting that the one thing all gay people have in
common is a history of coming out. On a personal level, there is a
history of this event that we all share, and that is a beautiful
notion.''
</P>
<P>
   His subject, Oscar Wilde, shares that history, too. Kaufman is
particularly fond of a scene in ``Gross Indecency'' when Wilde
tells his friend and biographer, Frank Harris, that the charges
against him are true. Wilde asks his friend whether that revelation
matters, and Harris thinks about it before answering, ``No.
Curiously enough it has made no difference to me at all. I do not
know why... but it has no effect on my friendship, none upon my
resolve to help you.'' In a few short sentences, Harris moves from
dismay to tolerance. ``I always tell the actor playing that role
that between finding out until the minute he says, `No,' he has to
travel a hundred years,'' says Kaufman, who directed the original
production. ``He has to come to this part of the century where he
can make that discrimination: `It doesn't matter. I don't know why,
but it doesn't matter.'''
</P>
<P>
   It's a journey that Kaufman has traveled himself, from his own
coming out scene to the day he told his father he wanted to be an
artist, not a businessman. In Moises Kaufman's version of history,
it all worked out splendidly. His life has changed since three
dozen or so producers rejected his script. He's had offers to write
the film version of ``Gross Indecency.'' He's off to London to
direct the British premiere of the play. He's toiling away on his
next script: ``It's a secret. There has to be some mystery.''
</P>
<P>
   His ``little struggling theater company'' isn't struggling so
hard anymore. ``All of a sudden, we don't have to be thinking where
the next meal is coming from, and all of a sudden, this theater
company is talking to a much larger audience,'' he says. ``But you
want to hear what has been the best part of all? I have been able
to engage in dialogue with people I've admired for a long time. I
think of Paris at the turn of the century, where there were these
salons where... artists would get together and their views of the
changing world would collide and something would happen. Now, with
all this success and publicity, I'm able to talk with people I've
wanted to dialogue with forever.''
</P>
<P>
   It's as if he's back at that dinner table, talking about Spinoza
or whatever with colleagues like Tony Kushner, Larry Kramer or Mike
Nichols, to name a few. The success of the thinking man's play has
also reassured him that other like-minded people crave intelligent
discourse. ``It's a great revelation because it means to me that
people want to be talked to intelligently about things they care
about,'' Kaufman explains. ``And in a sense, that has made me feel
more of a part of the human race. I never felt that way before.''
He pauses and laughs at the weight of that statement. ``How's that
for an ending?''
</P>
</TEXT>
