 Tuesday, Sept. 8, 1998     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following
stories for Wednesday. If you have questions, please call Chuck
Lewis or Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in
all sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-POLL (Washington) _ A bipartisan poll shows the Monica
Lewinsky matter has taken its toll on President Clinton and
Democrats. Among the findings: ``Moral values'' are now up there
with crime and the economy as leading issues, Clinton's personal
approval has dropped 19 percentage points since the beginning of
the year, and Republicans are up 3 points over Democrats in
congressional races. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ When Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn,
condemned President Clinton's immoral behavior, he joined a small
band of senators who over the decades have shown the courage and
integrity to defy their party's leaders on a matter of principle.
It's a very small band indeed, but it includes Sens. Mark Hatfield,
Howard Baker, William Fulbright and Margaret Chase Smith, all
heroes worth remembering. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
</TEXT>
