<HEADLINE>
REPETITIVE STRESS DISORDERS AFFLICTING MORE STUDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 ABBY FUNG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON - Sewell Chan, 21, had dreamed of becoming a journalist
for as long as he could remember and was heartbroken this spring
when he had to turn down a summer internship at the Washington Post
because his wrists throbbed with pain whenever he tried to type.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, in his senior year at Harvard, Chan began feeling a
tingling sensation in his forearms every time he typed, took notes,
or edited the school paper. It turned out he had repetitive stress
injury, or RSI, a catch-all term covering tendinitis, carpal tunnel
syndrome, cubital tunnel syndrome, and more, in which muscles,
tendons, and nerves are damaged through excessive typing and bad
posture.
</P>
<P>
   Once an affliction mainly of veteran office workers, RSI is
quickly becoming more and more a problem for today's college
students, who grow up playing Atari and Nintendo, endlessly write
papers and theses on their home computers, and surf the Internet or
check their e-mail ``for relaxation.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no national statistics available, but a survey of
colleges reveals that RSI is afflicting students at an alarming
rate.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Diamond of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology
Medical Center said he has treated more than 1,500 RSI patients
over the past eight years, with each year's toll growing.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 350 RSI patients visited the MIT Medical Center. On
average, 200 students at the school seek help for the syndrome each
year. At a school with 8,000 students, 1 in 40, suffers from RSI,
Diamond said.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers are also high at Harvard University. Seven years
ago, there were only two cases of RSI, according to Louise Russell,
director of Harvard's student disabilities resources center. Last
year, more than 100 were reported. Russell said she has seen the
number shoot up dramatically in the past three years, due to
increased awareness and an ``increasingly competitive academic
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Richard Moore, student health physician at the University of
Virginia, said he sees two or three RSI patients per semester. Jane
Austin, a physical therapist at the University of Nebraska in
Lincoln, diagnoses two to three cases of RSI each month, and Alan
Hedge, a professor of ergonomics at Cornell University in Ithaca,
N.Y., said 1 in 5 students, out of 104 randomly selected
undergraduates, reported persistent wrist pain in an April survey.
Hedge said he plans to expand the survey to 1,000 students soon.
</P>
<P>
   Diamond said RSI used to afflict mainly middle-aged workers
``who do forceful repetitive motions with the wrist.'' But with the
proliferation of home computers, some members of the generation
born in the 1970s began typing practically as soon as they could
talk.
</P>
<P>
   Baratunde Thurston, 20, is a prime example. A self-described
``information freak,'' the Harvard senior says he began playing
with computers when he was 6 years old. ``The message you get is
that you have to be computer-literate when you're 6 years old or
you're going to be a bum when you grow up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Thurston can no longer scoop ice cream, hold dining
hall trays, or ride his bike (because gripping the handlebars has
become too painful), he still works as a computer user assistant,
helping students set up their computers and solve computer
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Allmon, a 21-year-old Harvard senior, sleeps with
wrist braces and has spent more than $500 on acupuncture,
chiropractic treatment, and massage.
</P>
<P>
   Universities have been forced to respond to the pleas for help
from students like Thurston and Allmon. Diamond, of MIT, said
booklets on how to prevent RSI fill the mailboxes of all incoming
freshmen, and posters about it pepper the campus kiosks. Russell,
of Harvard, said that mouse pads in the computer lab have been
redesigned to provide information on how to prevent RSI, and
adjustable chairs and keyboard trays are available in student
rooms.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, professor Hedge at Cornell has created a Web site
(http://ergo.human.cornell.edu) to teach students how to RSI-proof
their computer workstations.
</P>
<P>
   Some students say that's not enough. ``The desks are too high or
the chairs are too low,'' Thurston said of his dorm. ``But it would
cost way too much money for them to replace it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Thurston said, he warns classmates about RSI. ``People
really take typing and mousework for granted,'' he said. ``They
don't think they're going to injure themselves because they're just
typing, but they will.''
</P>
<P>
   To increase awareness of the problem, Thurston became part of a
group called RSI Action, which was formed at Harvard a few years
ago. The group takes credit for introducing RSI-preventive mouse
pads and for convincing computer labs to post warning signs about
RSI.
</P>
<P>
   Allmon says he has become a one-man warning network. ``I nag
everyone about posture and typing and taking breaks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Speech-recognition software companies are also responding to the
needs of the students.
</P>
<P>
   Renee Blodgett, manager of corporate communications at Dragon
Systems Inc. in Newton, is in charge of marketing Dragon Dictate
and Dragon Naturally Speaking, speech recognition software that
Thurston and Allmon use to ``write'' their papers. They speak into
a microphone, and the computer translates the words on-screen.
</P>
<P>
   The software is now marketed to doctors, lawyers, and business
executives, but Blodgett said college students with RSI represent
``an untapped market.'' Although she has no figures on the number
of RSI patients who purchase speech recognition software, Blodgett
said, ``There's a lot of people using it for that purpose.''
</P>
</TEXT>
