<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3715 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  AM-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      09-08 1225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR TUESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, Sept. 9:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Russia &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-MIDDLECLASS (Moscow) _ Layoffs, office closings and
budget cutbacks have hit the middle class of Moscow hard. By
Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS (Moscow) _ Day developments following
Chernomyrdin's second loss. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-U.S. (Washington) _ There are serious divisions within
the Clinton administration over what to do next with its
U.S.-Russia financial policy. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Other international &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-TERROR (Belfast) _ The Roman Catholic terrorist group
that killed 29 people in a bomb attack in the town of Omagh three
weeks ago says it has permanently ended its campaign of violence.
By James F. Clarity.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-TRUTH (Johannesburg) _ Testimony before the Truth
Commission focuses on crimes committed outside South Africa. By
Donald G. McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   CONGO-TALKS (Victoria Falls, Zimbabwe) _ Developments in the
Congo talks. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA-UNREST (Phnom Penh) _ Developments in the political and
military unrest in the capital. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ Developments in Kenneth Starr's
investigation of the president; folo on the bid by David E.
Kendall, Clinton's lawyer, to get an early look at the prosecutor's
report. By James Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SCHOOL (Silver Spring, Md.) _ The president visits a
school; some parents complain he is a flawed role model. By Francis
X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-FUNDRAISING (Washington) _ Majority Leader Lott
promises another campaign finance vote. By Lizette Alvarez. &UR; (BU) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   AFFIRM-IMPACT (Undated) _ A major new study of 45,000 graduates
of the nation's top colleges over 20 years concludes that
affirmative action at elite institutions has created the backbone
of a black middle class that has largely been responsible for
integrating the professional ranks of white America. With a rich
data base and carefully calibrated tone, the study is leading the
charge in a liberal counteroffensive to recast the debate over
affirmative action. By Ethan Bronner.
</P>
<P>
   MCDOUGAL-TRIAL (Santa Monica, Calif.) _ Five years after the
case was filed, Susan McDougal is set to stand trial on charges of
embezzling $150,000 from conductor Zubin Mehta and his wife. By
Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   PRIMARY-RDP (Boston) _ A roundup of primaries in Arizona, New
Hampshire, Vermont and Wisconsin. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SHOOTING (Aurora, Colo.) _ Two teen-agers are accused of
shooting four other teens and a woman to death in a rampage at two
homes in a wealthy suburb of Denver. One of the suspects is later
found dead in a field and the other was taken into custody. By
James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-RDP (Halifax, Nova Scotia) _ Developments: Investigators
are optimistic about getting useful information from the data
recorder. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks soar, lifted by Fed Chairman
Greenspan's comments. At 1:20 p.m., the industrial average was up
207 points. Overseas, prices gained 0.8 percent in Tokyo and 1.4
percent in Hong Kong. They rose 3.3 percent in Frankfurt and 0.4
percent in London. On the American debt market, the long bond was
down 28/32 point at midday, with the yield at 5.34 percent. By
Edward Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   With a separate:
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ Credit market developments. By Robert
Hurtado.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDMAN-IPO (New York) _ Goldman, Sachs says it will proceed
with its stock sale despite the market's ups and downs. By Joseph
Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   HMOS-ELDERLY (Undated) _ After aggressively recruiting the
elderly and the disabled into their Medicare plans, many of the
nation's large health maintenance organizations are now rapidly
retreating in the face of huge losses. By David J. Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-ECON (Rio de Janeiro) _ The Brazilian government
announces austerity steps. By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-SUN (San Jose, Calif.) _ Sun Microsystems squares off
in a federal courtroom against Microsoft. Sun accuses Microsoft of
scheming to pollute the Java technology that Sun hoped would loosen
Microsoft's influence over the computer industry.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Microsoft files its formal
response to the government brief last week that called on the judge
to ignore Microsoft's request that it be dismissed. By Joel
Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   IBM-DRIVE (Undated) _ IBM introduces a new disk drive. By John
Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-TOBACCO (London) _ British American Tobacco shares rise
as much as 15 percent on their first day of trading following the
split of BAT Industries' tobacco activities from its
financial-services interests. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column. By
Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The weekly travel column. By Edwin
McDowell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK Region &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NY-YOUTH-RALLY (New York) _ Developments in the aftermath of the
Harlem rally: The district attorney is considering charges against
the rally's organizer, Khallid Abdul Muhammad.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHEAST-STROM (Rahway, N.J.) _ Aftermath of the storms that
hit the Northeast on Monday, focusing on Rahway, N.J., but with
damage reports from all around. By Ronald Smothers.
</P>
<P>
   NJ-TEACHER-STRIKE (Freehold, N.J.) _ All-night negotiations
failed to produce a settlement in the teachers' strike in Monmouth
County. A contempt hearing this afternoon at which 800 teachers are
supposed to appear.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Dowd's ``Liberties''; details to come.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Rich is on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET _ A rundown of culture, lifestyle, sports, and
special section stories will move by 3:00 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   AM-PAGE1-NYT-CONSIDER _ A list of stories being considered by
New York Times editors for Page 1 will move at 4:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   AM-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT _ Stories scheduled for Page 1 will be
listed by 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   AM-FRONTPAGE-NYT _ A description of the front page layout of the
first edition of The New York Times will move at 7:30 p.m.
</P>
