A3724 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DINING-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      09-08 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DINING-NYT-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Food and dining stories in sight at this hour from The N.Y.
Times News Service for Wednesday, Sept. 9:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURES: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-CROWDED-RESTAURANTS (New York) _ Short of pointing a
telescope through your neighbor's window, few experiences offer
better access to the intimate details of strangers' lives than
dining in Manhattan restaurants. Who hasn't had the pleasure of
being squeezed onto a narrow banquette where the tables are too
close for comfort? Your mind may be on your companion across from
you, but you cannot avoid being distracted by the couples sitting
on either side. You overhear their conversations, you inhale their
perfume, you can almost taste their food. With rents soaring and
restaurants booming, restaurateurs feel justified squeezing in an
extra table or two _ even if it meansthe difference between
convivial and claustrophobic. A critic's notebook by Eric Asimov.
</P>
<P>
   TEQUILA (Tequila, Mexico) _ Was it a mirage? In the sultry
95-degree heat, the fields shimmered along the highway leading from
Guadalajara, as if the hazy blue sky had tumbled to the earth and
splashed over the hillsides. But the fields really were blue,
covered with acres of steely agave plants, the raw ingredient for
one of the world's most popular spirits _ tequila. By Florence
Fabricant.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-FAT (Louviers, France) _ A gray cloud is passing over the
traditional French dietary regimen: the French are gaining weight,
if statistics are to be believed. And if you ask anyone from the
country's top epidemiologists to starred chefs to the local grocer,
they all point to the west, the U.S.A., the country the French love
and hate the most. By Susan Herrmann Loomis.
</P>
<P>
   MADAME-CURRY (Undated) _ Madame Curry packaged Indian mixes are
what foods like Rice a Roni should be. The recipes are authentic,
the instructions are easy to follow, and the quality of the
ingredients is exceptional. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE-COOKING (Undated) _ The column: Crispy lamb shanks. By
Mark Bittman.
</P>
<P>
   With recipe.
</P>
<P>
   MASTER-CHEF (Undated) _ The column: Salad of oven-dried pear,
walnuts and blue cheese.
</P>
<P>
   With recipe.
</P>
<P>
   KITCHEN-WARES (Undated) _ The test kitchen column: Grill pans.
By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   BERNARDIN-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Florence Fabricant reviews
``Le Bernardin Cookbook.''
</P>
<P>
   With recipe.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TALK (UNdated) _ So you're a wine fanatic whose day is
incomplete if it doesn't include a bottle of some rare California
cabernet. Unfortunately, you have lots of incomplete days, because
most shops don't carry them and those that do are always sold out.
Help is at hand. First Sip, a new monthly wine newsletter, not only
identifies the wines, as do all the other newsletters, but goes the
extra mile and lists where to find them. By Frank J. Prial.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TASTINGS (Undated) _ A capsule review of McDowell Valley
Vineyards Marsanne 1997, Mendocino County, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-NOTES (Undated) _ News and notes on food.
</P>
<P>
   We expect to move all Living Section stories by early evening
with a ``d'' category code, unless otherwise indicated.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867. And be sure to look for other stories from our partners:
Bloomberg News, The Boston Globe, Cox News Service, Hearst
Newspapers, The Arizona Republic, Kansas City Star, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Los Angeles Daily News, San Francisco Chronicle and
Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
