<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERET-STOCKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET COMPANIES RIDE OUT STORMS WITH EYE TO FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ They're the Beanie Babies of the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Internet-based companies like Amazon.com, GeoCities and
Broadcast.com mimic the little stuffed toys in a key assumption:
They make money now only because enough people agree that they will
be a valued collectible down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sell the future,'' said Stuart Skorman, founder of
Reel.Com, a Berkeley-based video retailer that is expected to go
public soon. ``Internet companies don't make money. In fact,
they're expected to lose money.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Skorman and analysts who watch over this
hyperactive segment of the economy, Internet-based companies are
burning up investor dollars to become a familiar destination and
brand name when the big ``future'' hits: A marketing nirvana where
consumers make instant impulse buys from their couches while
sitting in the glow of their hybrid TV/computer information
appliance.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts say that last week's stock market turmoil means
there are some dangerous curves on the road to Tomorrowland.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a crisis comes, selling a piece of the future is not as
valuable as selling a piece of the present,'' said Paul
Sonderegger, a senior analyst at the Massachusetts-based Forrester
Research. ``Suddenly, reality sets in, and investors realize that
they can't put food on the table now with hopes for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a reality that can seriously disrupt an Internet company's
current march into this future.
</P>
<P>
   Internet companies, because they have little or no present
streams of revenues, depend upon investor dollars to pay the bills.
A company creates a serious mountain of cash when they put their
stocks up for sale on the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com, the Seattle-based on-line bookstore, generated $54
million with its initial public offering, or IPO.
</P>
<P>
   A company's fluctuating stock price doesn't affect that first
flush of money. But a company's stock market price is crucial to
the company's ability to exist in the future, enabling it to buy
other companies, offer incentives to current and future employees
and raise more to cover continued losses. All of which are at the
heart of the business plan of most Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The foundations of these companies are future investor
dollars, employee retention and company acquisitions,'' said Dave
Jones, an analyst with the California Technology Stock Newsletter.
``And a company's stock price is central to these foundations.''
</P>
<P>
   The quandary of Internet stocks is that they confound current
analysis. Traditionally, a stock's worth was derived by formulas
such as the price/earnings ratio.
</P>
<P>
   Such formulas collapse with an Internet company that has little
or no earnings. Analysts spend their days trying to determine what
an Internet company might make if the Internet itself eventually
takes off as a mass medium, and users embrace on-line shopping.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's assumption on assumption on assumption,'' Jones said.
``When you have one part of those formulas go out of whack, like a
stock's unusual drop, the whole thing can come caving in.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said sustained hits on an Internet company's stock price
can force it out of business.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got certain stock price numbers built into their
business plans,'' he said. ``And they're usually planning to go
back to the equities (stock market) for funding in the future. If
their prices are way down, that destroys their models. They have to
make it up somewhere else, or close their doors.''
</P>
<P>
   That is what makes Internet companies such a volatile
investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditional companies having hard times with their stocks can
always show investors recent sales numbers or things like that,''
Jones said. ``Right now, the only thing Internet companies have are
predictions. And the way things are going these days, predictions
aren't worth that much.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
