<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-MANLY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLEUTH PROBES BATTLE OF SEXES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Last Manly Man 
Sparkle Hayter (William Morrow and Co., $22) 
 
 By CHARLES KELLY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As modern fictional sleuths go, none is more fun to spend time
with than Robin Hudson, a reporter for the New York-based All News
Network whose life is just one damn thing after another.
</P>
<P>
   The creation of Sparkle Hayter, a former reporter for CNN who
also has done stand-up comedy, Robin has to solve murders while
evading the back-stabbing antics of co-workers, figuring out what
life is all about, mollifying stupid superiors, and securing her
share of physical romance without becoming a casualty in the battle
of the sexes.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Last Manly Man,'' Robin is again beset by complexities
that would test the resources of Indiana Jones or Brenda Starr.
</P>
<P>
   She's having a hard enough time trying to report a story on the
Man of the Future, a look at how far men (that's  &UR; men, not mankind)
have come and what they might evolve into.
</P>
<P>
   Then she gets caught up in the investigation of the kidnapping
of a bunch of bonobo chimpanzees and the efforts of a shadowy
organization of animal activists (who also want to save indigenous
peoples, rain forests, etc., etc.) to free the chimps.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of figuring out who's doing what to whom, Robin
has to deal with an animal-rights activist who spends most of his
time in drag, a laid-back marijuana dealer who's dating his
ex-wife, and her gun-toting downstairs neighbor, Mrs. Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   Robin, a divorced woman with a cat who once had a lucrative
career in cat-food commercials, is determinedly
non-politically-correct. She loves red meat, men and looking good.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly enough, her unrestrained personality makes it
possible for her to both poke fun at and sympathize with the
save-the-world types with whom she joins forces.
</P>
<P>
   In her previous adventures, Robin spent plenty of brain time
trying to make sense of the personal fascination and frustration
she feels in dealing with men. In ``The Last Manly Man,'' she
pushes her intellectual inquiry to a global level while continuing
to provide healthy doses of hell raising and hilarity.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to laugh your way to a better understanding of what
men and women are all about these days, you should spend some time
with ``The Last Manly Man.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 1430EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
