<HEADER>
A3754 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDSBOOKS-AZR &LR;      09-08 1193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDSBOOKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAGE-TURNERS ARE JUST WAITING FOR YOUTHFUL READERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BEVERLY MEDLYN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that school's back in session, it's time to hit the books.
</P>
<P>
   Creatures such as ants and spotted yellow frogs will entertain
preschoolers. A novel about two pen pals and an adventure story
about what it's like to climb Mount Everest will appeal to older
children. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; SPOTTED YELLOW FROGS &QL; 
 &UR; Matthew Van Fleet (Dial, $9.99)
</P>
<P>
   Wow! This book has it all: colors, patterns, animals and
three-dimensional shapes such as pyramids, cubes, cylinders, cones
and rings that usually are not taught in books for tykes. The
colorful patterns on one page are clues about which animal lurks
behind each geometric shape on the next fold-out page. When your
preschooler masters that game, fold out the final page, which asks
kids to identify the  &UR; wrong patterns on eight animals scampering
among dozens illustrated correctly. It'll keep your little one
plenty busy. For ages 2 to 4. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; WHERE DO I LIVE? &QL; 
 &UR; World Wildlife Fund (Cedco, $12.95)
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a Red Fox. I hunt for rodents, birds, and sometimes
frogs. I hide in dark, safe places. Where do I live?'' Across the
page is a portrait of an adorable fox. Lift the flap to reveal the
fox in its natural surroundings, along with the answer: a forest.
So goes this educational picture book, which also features a polar
bear, an angelfish, a gorilla, a zebra, a pelican, a sea star and
more.
</P>
<P>
   The World Wildlife Fund continues to publish breathtaking nature
photography for kids in its fall offerings. Other titles are ``Look
Who's Hatching!'', a compendium of eggs and baby animals, and
``Habitats: A Sticker Activity Book.'' For ages 2 to 5. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; HEY, LITTLE ANT &QL; 
 &UR; Phillip and Hannah Hoose; illustrated by Debbie Tilley (Tricycle
Press,
 &UR; $13.95)
</P>
<P>
   To squish or not to squish? That is the question posed in this
morality tale.
</P>
<P>
   It begins with a great big kid who's about to flatten an ant
with his tennis shoe. The ant, holding two shopping bags, takes on
human dimensions as it pleads for its life. It's got a home and a
family to feed, too. As the big kid's buddies urge him to squish, a
sudden role reversal occurs. The ant grows tall and the boy shrinks
to antlike size. After a turn in the ant's shoes, the kid thinks
again. What do you think he should do?
</P>
<P>
   Told in rhyme with amusing illustrations, this book from a
Buddhist publishing house is a good starting point for discussing
the value of life. For ages 3 to 5. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; COYOTE IN LOVE WITH A STAR &QL; 
 &UR; Marty Kreipe de Montano; illustrated by Tom Coffin (Abbeville
Press, $14.95)
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix artist Coffin, a Kansas native and member of the Prairie
Band Potawatomi and Creek tribes, pens the whimsical illustrations
in this tale about a coyote who moves from the plains to New York
City. In his VW bus, coyote negotiates the bustling urban streets
(lined with signs such as ``Cuban Chinese food'') and gets himself
a job as the rodent control officer for the World Trade Center.
There, he stargazes at night, eventually falling for a special star
that takes him on a wild dance to the edge of the sky. De Montano
put this modern spin on a traditional Native American story.
</P>
<P>
   The title is among several in the ``Tales of the People''
series, published in partnership with the Smithsonian's National
Museum of the American Indian. The picture books are written and
illustrated by Native Americans. For ages 4 to 8. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; HOME RUN: THE STORY OF BABE RUTH &QL; 
 &UR; Robert Burleigh; illustrated by Mike Wimmer (Harcourt Brace, $16)
</P>
<P>
   Babe Ruth died 50 years ago, but his legacy lives on in this
old-fashioned picture book about one of the greatest players who
ever lived. Wimmer's paintings, in the realistic style of Norman
Rockwell, capture the action of Babe at bat and his fans'
amazement.
</P>
<P>
   Burleigh writes in free verse, giving the game a poetic quality:
``He watches the pitcher lean. Rotate. Rock back and forth. The leg
wheels out. The arm whips over the head. Babe narrows his
hunter-like gaze and strides into the pitch that is now only a tiny
speck of whirling whiteness.'' Baseball cards on each page add
facts and figures that will interest older readers. For ages 4 to
8. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THE ENCHANTED TREE &QL; 
 &UR; Flavia and Lisa Weedn (Cedco Publishing, $12.95)
</P>
<P>
   Flavia, of inspirational greeting-card fame, and her daughter
have written and illustrated four children's books to be released
Sept. 15. The pictures are beautiful, and production is top-notch.
Story lines center on values of friendship, love, sharing and
kindness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Enchanted Tree'' is about a tall, pink giraffe that
doesn't care for its looks and wants to be like everyone else. It
leaves its village, and on its journey meets a wise tree that
teaches it that individuality is a gift and that each of us is
perfect just as we are. Other titles in the series are ``The
Elephant Prince,'' ``The Little Snow Bear'' and ``The Star Gift.''
For ages 4 to 8. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; P.S. LONGER LETTER LATER &QL; 
 &UR; Paula Danziger and Ann M. Martin (Scholastic, $15.95)
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth and TaraStarr (she uses a star in her name, of course)
are friends, like the writers who created them, Danziger (best
known as the creator of the Amber Brown novels) and Martin (of the
Baby-Sitters Club). When Tara moves away with her family, she and
Elizabeth continue their close relationship through correspondence
that reveals their contrasting personality traits, modeled on those
of the book's authors.
</P>
<P>
   The letter-writing exchange is a clever vehicle for covering the
concerns of pre-adolescence: peer-group acceptance, school
challenges, geeky parents and those awful but exciting parties.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth comes from monied parents who lose everything when
Dad's employment abruptly ends. (``Dad said something about a
package. Do they give going-away presents to people they fire?''
asks Elizabeth.) Tara writes condescendingly of her ``charents (my
CHildlike pARENTS),'' who are young and not so well off
financially. But she realizes how lucky she is to live in a loving
home. Great friends, fun book. For ages 8 to 12. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; WITHIN REACH: MY EVEREST STORY &QL; 
 &UR; Mark Pfetzer and Jack Galvin (Dutton, $16.95)
</P>
<P>
   Pfetzer was on Mount Everest just below the summit when a
terrible storm struck, causing one of the worst disasters in the
mountain's history. Eight people perished, and their ordeal became
the basis of the bestselling adult book ``Into Thin Air'' and an
IMAX film, ``Everest.'' What was a 16-year-old kid doing there, a
few steps from death?
</P>
<P>
   Pfetzer, the youngest person to attempt Everest, describes the
perilous night of May 10, 1996, and his nine other climbs of the
world's highest peaks. He also talks about becoming a karate black
belt at age 11, a certified emergency medical technician at age 17,
and his ambition to become a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   His determination will inspire children and dumbfound adults.
The first-person narrative is heavy on action but light on insight
about the forces driving Pfetzer's relentless climb to achieve. For
ages 10 and up. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Beverly Medlyn can be contacted at bevmedlyn(at)aol.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 1432EDT &QL; 
