<HEADER>
A3757 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDSBOOKHELP-AZR &LR;      09-08 0466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDSBOOKHELP-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPINIONATED DUO SERVE UP BEST SELECTIONS FOR YOUNG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BEVERLY MEDLYN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Buying a book for a child can be an intimidating process, with
an overwhelming number to choose from, uncertainties about what is
age-appropriate, and chagrin over price tags. Even choosing a free
library book can be a daunting experience.
</P>
<P>
   Help has arrived. Valerie V. Lewis and Walter M. Mayes have
narrowed the possibilities to a mere 2,000 titles in their new
``Valerie &AMP; Walter's Best Books for Children: A Lively, Opinionated
Guide,'' published by Avon Books for $15.
</P>
<P>
   Their selections neatly are cataloged for easy reference,
according to age and reading and listening levels. An index even
groups titles according to topics and themes, such as trains,
stepfamilies, emotions, fear of the dark and woodchucks.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a section called ``tricky situations and frequently
asked questions.'' Sidebars and inspirational tips on such subjects
as choosing a book, series fiction, exceptional authors and
literary classics are interspersed.
</P>
<P>
   The one-paragraph book summaries are done in an amusing style.
When Valerie and Walter agree that a book is the best of the best,
a star is printed next to the title. When they disagree, each one
weighs in with a few comments, a la Siskel and Ebert.
</P>
<P>
   Although the selections aren't included in the guide unless
Valerie and Walter believe in their merit, every now and then they
raise an eyebrow, as in this passage about H.A. Rey's ``Curious
George'':
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not wish to be curmudgeonly, but we need to say that
much of George's appeal is lost on us as adults. Oh, we read them
as children and later to our own children, and we acknowledge the
fact that they delight. But we are at a loss to explain why they
are popular. Is it just that George embodies curiosity so well? Is
it a nostalgia for simpler times, perhaps, when a man in a big
yellow hat taking a monkey from the jungle could be looked upon
fondly and not as a poacher? Or is it that George is simply
beloved, period, and we just don't get it? Do not let us stop you
from making up your own mind, as there is certainly plenty of
George to go around.''
</P>
<P>
   After a while, you feel like you know and trust the two
knowledgeable characters who tackled this massive project (their
original list of titles topped 8,000).
</P>
<P>
   Mayes, also known as Walter the Giant Storyteller, is a
book-sales representative who talks nationwide with parents and
kids about books. Lewis, owner of Hickelbee's children's bookstore
in San Jose, is children's book correspondent for ``CBS This
Morning.'' They've worked together since 1981, and their
comfortable writing style reflects the friendship. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 1433EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3758 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAMAICA-BIRDWATCHING-     09-08 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAMAICA-BIRDWATCHING-$ADV12-CO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IN JAMAICA, IT'S THE BIRDS, MON, NOT THE BEACH, THAT ATTRACT
ATTENTION
 &HT;    With JAMAICA-BOX-$ADV12.
 &HT;    With photos to be placed in the International and Travel
categories.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (t) Travel categories.
 &HT;    For Use Saturday, Sept. 12 and Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANCHOVY, Jamaica _ About 30 minutes into a bumpy drive along a
road with crater-sized potholes, you finally begin seeing signs.
They have no words, only pictures of birds and arrows leading
travelers atop a wooded hill 900 feet above the waters of Montego
Bay.
</P>
<P>
   That's where you find the Rocklands Feeding Station, one of the
Caribbean's most unusual attractions.
</P>
<P>
   At first, it looks like nothing but an unassuming stone house
with a green roof on a verdant plot of land.
</P>
<P>
   But off to the side, in the shade of a small terrace, a show is
about to begin, and hushed onlookers from all parts of the world
are ready to see it. Armed with cameras, they are perched on
rickety folding chairs.
</P>
<P>
   They don't wait long because soon a flock of greedy,
lightning-fast birds that include saffron finches and blue tanagers
descends on the terrace, ready for food.
</P>
<P>
   Birds with spectacular colors, but not such good manners, whiz
about the heads of visitors like miniature flying saucers.
</P>
<P>
   Most impressively, the hummingbirds drink from hand-held bottles
of sugar water, and the tiny finches flutter around outstretched
palms packed full of birdseed.
</P>
<P>
   Others just eat off the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just can't do the sun and the surf thing, so I do the bird
thing, and this is certainly the best place to be if you want to
interact with birds,'' said Janis Gaudy, a tourist from Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   A pleased Gaudy holds out some food and attracts a black
hummingbird with an iridescent emerald throat. Her reaction? That
she's made a new friend.
</P>
<P>
   Jamaica is the largest English-speaking country in the
Caribbean, 146 miles from east to west.
</P>
<P>
   Here, there are three main tourist destinations -- Montego Bay,
Ocho Rios and Negril -- all boasting a plethora of all-inclusive
resorts along stunning coasts.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone enjoys powdery sands, crystal-clear waters, and
acting out Jacques Cousteau fantasies.
</P>
<P>
   Off the beaten track are all sorts of other activities to keep
tourists busy and happy, everything from horseback riding to
mountain hiking to bicycle riding.
</P>
<P>
   And, most especially, birdwatching.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Salmon, a native Jamaican, opened the Rocklands Feeding
Station in 1958. Today, at age 94, Salmon still lives on the
property, although she's mostly confined to bed. The eccentric
proprietor never married and considers the birds to be her only
family.
</P>
<P>
   Her employees open the sanctuary each day from 2 p.m. to 5 p.m.,
and charges visitors $8 to feed the wild birds. The site is located
just a few miles from Montego Bay, on the northern coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lisa's the one who got the birds to start coming here,'' said
Daisy Morrison, who's worked at Rocklands for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``She would go day after day into the forest to try to feed the
birds,'' she said. ``She would bring the birds closer by feeding
them nearer to the house.''
</P>
<P>
   The sanctuary sits on about 2 1/4 acres of forested land and is
surrounded by virtual clouds of birds: grassquits, finches, and,
most importantly, hummingbirds. There's the mango, the
streamertail, and the vervain, the second-smallest bird on the
planet.
</P>
<P>
   Birds flit back and forth across the terrace, which is
pleasantly cluttered by ferns, and various tropical plants.
</P>
<P>
   They pause mid-flight, just momentarily, to take a sip of sugar
water from small bottles that hang on wires from the roof.
</P>
<P>
   The birds -- even wild canaries -- don't seem to be afraid of
anything, and certainly not a stranger's extended finger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really amazing how they will come to you,'' said Doreen
Mensink, a tourist from Holland. ``I've not seen anything quite
like this before.''
</P>
<P>
   But besides Rocklands, there are many other places to see birds
on the island.
</P>
<P>
   Also popular are the forest-blanketed Blue Mountains, a central
