<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 14:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3761 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KUWAIT-JOURNAL-$ADV10     09-08 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KUWAIT-JOURNAL-$ADV10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WHY WASN'T I BORN A KUWAITI? GULF STATE GOOD LIFE IS EASY TO GET
USED TO
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (k) Commentary
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Thursday, Sept. 10 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUWAIT CITY _ With candor and a little embarrassment, Kuwaitis
talk about taxi drivers with maids and middle-class families with
six or seven cars.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with their country, they readily admit, is that
Cadillacs came into favor and work went out of style.
</P>
<P>
   My recent trip to Kuwait started with the government insisting
that it would pay all my bills for lodging, meals and laundry. I
declined.
</P>
<P>
   It ended with a hotel official giving me a souvenir that
explained the comforts I'd seen -- a Plexiglas cube with a few
drops of shiny black oil swishing around in the center.
</P>
<P>
   Kuwait used to be poor. Now, it sits on about 10 percent of the
world's oil reserves.
</P>
<P>
   There are only 1.8 million people in Kuwait, and only about
700,000 are Kuwaitis. The rest are foreign workers, who do jobs
from housekeeping to car sales to stock brokering.
</P>
<P>
   You can spot Kuwaiti men by their red-and-white head scarfs and
flowing white robes. But mostly you see Indians, Sri Lankans,
Iranians and Filipinos.
</P>
<P>
   Kuwait's per capita income in 1995 ranked third in the world,
still behind the United States. But the oil has created what many
describe as a rich ``welfare state.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuwaitis pay no income tax. Education is free through college.
Utilities are heavily subsidized. Health-care is free. House loans
are low-interest. Land, in some areas, is free.
</P>
<P>
   Sulaiman(CQ) Mutawa, a former government minister and economist,
explained that words like ``unemployment'' and ``rich and poor'' do
not apply.
</P>
<P>
   ``If my income is $1,500 a month, but I can buy a Mercedes on
installments, what do you call me?'' he asked. ``Our existence is
based on subsidies.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuwaitis like big American cars _ a favorite is the Chevrolet
Caprice Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Neighborhoods are built on the desert sand. Large villas are
pushed close together and usually sprout two satellite dishes.
</P>
<P>
   There are no public bars or public consumption of alcohol in
this Muslim country, but I found a spotless bowling alley that
featured an Internet computer room. And Kuwaitis were happy to
invite me to their nightly salon discussions.
</P>
<P>
   There are, indeed, poor in Kuwait. Some foreign workers live in
crowded apartment blocks and there is an ethnic group of some
100,000 people claiming citizenship but not getting it and not
being allowed to work.
</P>
<P>
   Kuwait is also tough on women. They are not forced to wear head
scarves or prohibited from driving as in Saudi Arabia, but they
cannot vote.
</P>
<P>
   The limits on Kuwaiti democracy caused some to complain about
the U.S. efforts to liberate Kuwait from Iraqi leader Saddam
Hussein's 1990 invasion. Amnesty International says Kuwait holds
more than 100 political prisoners accused of collaborating with the
Iraqis.
</P>
<P>
   Kuwait does have a parliament, even if the ultimate decisions
are made by the royal family. It's what you might call a
semi-democracy.
</P>
<P>
   People discuss politics openly, as long as they do not criticize
the royal family directly, and the hospitable, soft-spoken Kuwaiti
nature is easy on a foreign traveler. They like, and in many ways,
resemble Americans.
</P>
<P>
   But, the good times might not last. Slumping oil prices have the
Kuwaiti government in deficit spending and there's talk about
cutting the subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   Some say they can already see the effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see the people here,'' said one young Kuwaiti man,
gesturing around a crowded mall that boasts stores by Laura Ashley,
Godiva and Gucci. ``How many people are carrying (shopping) bags?
They are just walking around!''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
