<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-PRICES-0909-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PRICES RISE, RUBLE SLIDES: A LOOK AT THE PLIGHT OF RUSSIAN
CONSUMERS
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-CONSUMERS-0909.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In the current economic crisis, Russians are watching
their spending power evaporate as the ruble tumbles in value and
prices rise.
</P>
<P>
   Inflation rose to 15 percent in August, up from 0.2 percent in
July, the government announced recently. Forecasters say the August
rate could triple or quadruple by the end of September.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at the problem:
</P>
<P>
   INCOME: The average monthly household income in June was 861
rubles, about $137. With the ruble's devaluation since Aug. 17, the
same income of 861 rubles withered to a value of about $40 on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   THE RUBLE'S FALL: Economic analysts say the ruble has fallen
farther and faster against the dollar than any other currency in
the world except for Indonesia's. In the past three weeks, the
ruble has fallen about 67 percent.
</P>
<P>
   COMPARED TO THE DOLLAR:
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 13 6.2
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 14 6.3
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 17 6.9 -- as government attempts controlled devaluation,
allowing ruble to slide to 9.5
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 24 7.1 -- street trading 8-9.5 rubles to the dollar
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 25 7.9 -- central bank concedes it cannot prevent ruble's
free-fall ruble rate reaches as low as 10 in street trading
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 27 12.0 -- bank and street trade takes over, official rate
of 7.9 becomes meaningless
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 28 12.9 -- black market reappears, trading at 14-15 to the
dollar
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 1 13.0 -- official ruble rate set at 10.3, beyond
government-imposed guidelines
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 2 15.0
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 4 17.0
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 7 20.0
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 8 22.0
</P>
<P>
   Sources: Russia Central Bank, Cox Newspapers survey of Moscow
exchange offices.
</P>
<P>
   From Aug. 13-25, list reflects official ruble-dollar rate.
</P>
<P>
   From Aug. 27, list reflects unofficial trade rate in banks and
on street.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------
</P>
<P>
   PRICES RISE: In Moscow, the cost of imported and Russian-made
foods-tuffs and household products has risen 100-500 percent in the
past three weeks. Among the best buys is a Big Mac, the cost of
which has actually dipped about $1 as McDonald's price increases
have not kept pace with the slide of the ruble.
</P>
<P>
   PRICES ON SOME CONSUMER ITEMS ....
</P>
<P>
   (in U.S. dollar equivalents)
</P>
<P>
   mid-August Now
</P>
<P>
   Milk (one liter) $0.52 $0.69
</P>
<P>
   Flour (two kilos) $1.29 $1.75
</P>
<P>
   Butter (250 grams) $0.40 $1.00
</P>
<P>
   Chicken (one kilo) $1.75 $3.00
</P>
<P>
   Fish (one piece) $0.83 $1.75
</P>
<P>
   Blackberries, imported (1 pint) $30.00 $45.00
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's Big Mac: $2.10 $1.10(CQ)
</P>
<P>
   Toilet paper (one roll) $0.16 $0.30
</P>
<P>
   Laundry detergent $0.98 $3.00
</P>
<P>
   Prices reflect spot checks of Moscow stores, Sept. 7-8. Dollar
values calculated using posted prices in rubles and calculated to
exchange rates of 6.2 rubles to the dollar on Aug. 13, and 20
rubles to the dollar on Sept. 7.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
