<TEXT>
<P>
   Entertainment and culture stories in sight at this hour from The
N.Y. Times News Service for Wednesday, Sept. 9.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867. And be sure to look for other entertainment stories from
our partners: Bloomberg News, The Boston Globe, Cox News Service,
Hearst Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle, The Arizona Republic,
Kansas City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles Daily News,
San Francisco Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
<P>
   GREECE-ARMENIA (Athens) _ The art of the past is forever being
reinterpreted in terms of the politics of the present. The most
distinctive Armenian sculptures, for example, are heavy stone
crosses called khatchkars. The Armenians, having been driven away
or massacred by the Seljuk Turks, the Turkomans, the Arabs and
others on and off since ancient times, developed khatchkars partly
as a way to leave their mark in the land. So khatchkars are
political symbols. Can they be interpreted in other ways as well?
Obviously, though politics seemed an inevitable issue in the
context of a big and excellent exhibition that was recently here.
By Michael Kimmelman.
</P>
<P>
   RECLAIMING-NAZI-ART (Undated) _ In the last six months there has
been a notable change in the art world. It has nothing to do with
exhibitions or acquisitions, but rather with the rhetoric
surrounding potential claims for art plundered during World War II
that later found its way, by various routes through dealers and
collectors, into American museums. A news analysis by Judith H.
Dobrzynski.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-FENNINGER (Berlin) _ This year Germany has been
celebrating the American artist Lyonel Feininger as one of its own,
with retrospectives of his watercolors and sketches in Hamburg and
Tubingen and, since July, a retrospective of 137 of his 540 oil
paintings at the Neue Nationalgalerie here. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   TV-NOTES (Undated) _ News and notes from television. By Bill
Carter and Lawrie Mifflin.
</P>
<P>
   CHILE-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Chile, Obstinate Memory and The
Battle of Chile, Part Two: The Coup D'Etat'': Patricio Guzman,
director. In Spanish, with English subtitles. Reviewed by Lawrence
Van Gelder.
</P>
<P>
   BORGES-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Collected Fictions,'' by Jorge
Luis Borges (Viking). Reviewed by Richard Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE-NOTES (Undated) _ Short items from the world of music
and the arts.
</P>
