<HEADER>
A3814 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAIN-GAMES09-COX     09-08 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAIN-GAMES09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Flex your mental muscle
 &HT;    By Carolyn Susman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The threat of going mad _ losing his mental capacity _ plagued
Associated Press Middle East correspondent Terry Anderson during
almost seven years in captivity.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson spent 2,455 days isolated from the world after Muslim
extremists abducted him in Lebanon in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   But Anderson knew instinctively what doctors swear by today: You
can combat mental decline by keeping your mind occupied.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson goaded fellow hostages into heated debates, badgered
one into teaching him a foreign language and created his own form
of sign language and tapping noises to communicate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Studying and learning new things are effective ways of keeping
your processes fresh and active,'' says Dr. Larry Eisner, medical
director of the Baumel-Eisner Neuromedical Institute in Boca Raton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us (after school) stop learning things on a routine
basis. If we stop learning, we stop remembering how to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   But how do we continue that learning process?
</P>
<P>
   Reading and casual conversation are good, but ``minor'' ways of
challenging the brain, Eisner says.
</P>
<P>
   If you really want to exercise your mental capabilities, take
courses, learn a new hobby or skill or participate in lectures or
``serious'' discussion groups. Doing puzzles, crosswords or playing
games that involve memory will also help.
</P>
<P>
   ``This keeps the brain in an active mode and doesn't allow it to
deteriorate based on disuse,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The distinction is the level of activity. Watching television _
even the History Channel _ is more passive than getting into a
rip-roaring debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need activities in an interactive fashion to engage your
intelligence,'' explains Dr. Rodrigo Kuljis, professor of neurology
and psychiatry at the University of Miami Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you spend weeks on end watching TV passively, you probably
won't do well. But people who pursue interests that are
intellectually challenging tend to preserve their intellectual
abilities.''
</P>
<P>
   And we can hone the sharpness of our minds well into old age.
Contrary to what was once thought, senility is not inevitable as
times passes. Twenty percent of mature adults experience no
discernible drop in their mental faculties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have people in their 90s who are remarkably sharp,'' Kuljis
says. ``And that's the reason we don't accept even subtle
complaints that (mental decline) is due to aging.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people tend to fall back into things that are
entertaining. You need things that require your participation, that
challenge you without being overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   There are three types of memory, each influenced differently by
age, explains Dr. Milton Alter, clinical professor of neurology at
Allegheny University of the Health Sciences in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Long-term memory enables you to remember things about your best
friend in grade school and is the least affected by advancing
years. Intermediate memory _ say, remembering an appointment _ may
wane a little more over time.
</P>
<P>
   Most vulnerable to age is short-term memory, says Dr. Alter, a
neuroepidemiologist. This is why you may be flabbergasted to find
you can't remember something you were discussing 10 minutes ago.
</P>
<P>
   Physical exercise is important to keeping the mind alert, also.
</P>
<P>
   ``The brain is an organ _ a functioning, living, breathing organ
_ and we want to maintain the blood flow and the connections
between nerve cells on a sound basis. We can keep them healthy and
operating at peak performance by being active and regularly
stimulated,'' Eisner adds.
</P>
<P>
   If you're worried about your memory or that of someone close to
you, talk to your primary care physician first. If needed, your
doctor can refer you to a specialist who can perform a complete
evaluation that would include a physical exam, personal interview
and screening tests that measure a range of cognitive skills,
including concentration and orientation.
</P>
<P>
   This report was supplemented by Post wire services.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
