<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 15:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3819 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-GOV-HNS &LR;      09-08 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GOV-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLL GIVES VALLONE NEW MUSCLE IN NEW YORK PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HARVY LIPMAN  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ New York City Council Speaker Peter Vallone has
leapfrogged into the lead in the race to be the Democratic
candidate for governor. But if he does win the party's Sept. 15
primary, it likely will be a hollow victory for Vallone _ giving
him the chance to go down in history as the man who lost one of the
biggest landslides ever seen in New York politics.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Gov. George Pataki leads not only Vallone, but
each of his four potential Democratic challengers by 40 percentage
points or more.
</P>
<P>
   While Pataki looks as close to unbeatable as a politician can
two months before an election, his fellow Republican incumbents
will be facing much tougher battles in the fall. U.S. Sen. Alfonse
D'Amato holds relatively small leads over the two top Democratic
challengers: Former Rep. and one-time vice presidential candidate
Geraldine Ferraro and Rep. Charles Schumer of Brooklyn. The battle
between the leading Democrats has heated up quite a bit over the
past three weeks, with Schumer cutting Ferraro's
14-percentage-point lead in half.
</P>
<P>
   In what could well end up as the closest of all the statewide
races this fall, Attorney General Dennis Vacco faces a formidable
political foe in former Manhattan assistant district attorney Eliot
Spitzer, who has pulled far ahead in the Democratic primary
contest.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the key findings of a poll of likely voters conducted
from Sept. 2-4 for the Albany Times Union and the Syracuse
Newspapers by Zogby International.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, Lt. Gov. Betsy McCaughey Ross led all Democratic
comers, with 24 percent of the vote to 13 percent for Vallone, 4
percent for Brooklyn District Attorney Charles J. Hynes and 3
percent for former state transportation commissioner James Larocca.
Since then her political fortunes have gone the way of the Titanic.
</P>
<P>
   While Vallone has flooded the airwaves with advertising,
McCaughey Ross' multimillionaire husband Wilbur Ross has pulled the
financial plug on her campaign _ leaving her unable to put together
a serious television campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a race turned upside down. Vallone now is being
backed by 27 percent of likely Democratic primary voters, while the
Republican-turned-Democrat lieutenant governor has dropped to 18
percent. Hynes and Larocca continue to lag far behind.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone and McCaughey Ross are running neck-and-neck in New York
City and upstate, but Vallone has a huge lead in the New York City
suburbs. Men support him by a better than 3-to-2 margin, while
women Democrats are split.
</P>
<P>
   ``Primary victories depend on good organization, advertising
money and passioned voters,'' noted pollster John Zogby. ``Vallone
is aided by having the best organization and the most money. He
also has a decent issue helping him with his support of keeping
Yankee Stadium in the Bronx.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning the primary, however, may not be the best thing that
ever happens to Vallone's political career. Pataki not only
overwhelms his challengers among all voters _ he even leads them
among likely Democratic voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gov. Pataki simply mops up against all possible Democratic
opponents,'' Zogby said. ``Perhaps the most interesting question is
how well the minor party candidates will do, and we find that
Reform Party candidate Tom Golisano's advertising blitz is
certainly paying off as he garners almost double digits.''
</P>
<P>
   Zogby also pointed out that if the current trends hold up, Green
Party candidate Al Lewis _ the actor who played Grandpa Munster on
TV and has been a long-time labor union activist _ may get the
50,000 votes the party needs to win an automatic spot on the ballot
next time around.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer, with millions in his campaign coffers being spent to
broadcast his face to TVs around the state, is eating into
Ferraro's once formidable lead in the race to be the Democratic
nominee for Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the ground he's making up is in New York City, where
he leads both Ferraro and New York City Public Advocate Mark Green.
The Brooklyn congressman continues to trail both his opponents in
the New York City suburbs. And Ferraro dominates upstate, with 55
percent supporting her to Schumer's 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Zogby, however, pointed out that in a Democratic primary, most
of the vote comes from New York City. ``The Senate primary looks to
be a squeaker,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So does the general election, whether it's Schumer or Ferraro
facing D'Amato. The critical factor there may be Schumer's presence
on the Liberal line, an endorsement he won in the spring. Even if
Ferraro wins the Democratic primary and Schumer decides to drop out
and support her, New York election law requires that his name
remain on the ballot. In a close race, a few thousand votes
siphoned off to Schumer could allow D'Amato to win with less than
half the vote _ something he's done two of the three times he's
been elected to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What was a tight primary contest in the race for attorney
general has been blown wide open by Spitzer. Two months ago he and
Evan Davis, who served as chief counsel to former Gov. Mario Cuomo,
were in a virtual tie, and state Sen. Catherine Abate from
Manhattan was well within reach of the lead. Now Spitzer, with 32
percent of the vote, has more support than Davis, Abate and former
Attorney General G. Oliver Koppell combined. He's ahead among every
demographic group.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other candidates have barely made a dent in the public
mind,'' Zogby said. ``He has the money, the organization and the
focused message to even further pull away.''
</P>
<P>
   Zogby added one cautionary note: ``The other candidates are only
now planning their advertising blitz.'' If it does end up being a
Spitzer-Vacco race in the fall, the incumbent attorney general
looks like he'll be in for a serious challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer, with far less name recognition than Vacco, is already
within 8 percentage points of him among likely voters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 1507EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
