   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CONSUMERS _ MOSCOW _ Their primary currency is worth only
half what it was three weeks ago. The price of a loaf of bread has
quadrupled. Many of them haven't been paid in months, having to use
a barter system to acquire the bare essentials. And the majority of
their banks are insolvent. Yet, the time-worn phrase you continue
to hear from Muscovites is, ``Oh well, what are you going to do?''
Are the 147 million people of this once-proud nation that at one
time challenged _ and even beat America _ in space, being pounded
into submission by a terrible economic crisis. How are they coping?
(Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With RUSSIA-DATA _ MOSCOW _ A box containing data on how prices
of consumer goods have changed over the last month or so. (Holmes,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-ANALYSIS _ The shadowy Kim Jong Il has been confirmed as
North Korea's all-powerful leader, completing the first dynastic
succession in a Communist state. But in a sense Kim is still
carrying his late father on his back. By Han Park, North Korean
expert and director of the Center for the Study of Global Issues at
the University of Georgia. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton showed Tuesday he
planned to hang tough in the face of an expected report on his
wrongdoing from Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr. He scheduled
meetings this week with congressional leaders to rally support and
deflect criticism and planned an event a day to press popular
issues. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-DELAY _ WASHINGTON _ As the House prepares whether to
consider impeachment of President Clinton, Majority Whip Tom DeLay,
R-Texas, has put together an elaborate team to provide members and
staff with information on every facet of the Clinton scandals.
(Harlan, Cox News Service).
