   &UR; DINING &LR;  (``d'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NY-CROWDED-RESTAURANTS (New York) _ Short of pointing a
telescope through your neighbor's window, few experiences offer
better access to the intimate details of strangers' lives than
dining in Manhattan restaurants. Who hasn't had the pleasure of
being squeezed onto a narrow banquette where the tables are too
close for comfort? Your mind may be on your companion across from
you, but you cannot avoid being distracted by the couples sitting
on either side. You overhear their conversations, you inhale their
perfume, you can almost taste their food. With rents soaring and
restaurants booming, restaurateurs feel justified squeezing in an
extra table or two _ even if it means the difference between
convivial and claustrophobic. A critic's notebook by Eric Asimov.
</P>
<P>
   TEQUILA (Tequila, Mexico) _ Was it a mirage? In the sultry
95-degree heat, the fields shimmered along the highway leading from
Guadalajara, as if the hazy blue sky had tumbled to the earth and
splashed over the hillsides. But the fields really were blue,
covered with acres of steely agave plants, the raw ingredient for
one of the world's most popular spirits _ tequila. By Florence
Fabricant.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-FAT (Louviers, France) _ A gray cloud is passing over the
traditional French dietary regimen: the French are gaining weight,
if statistics are to be believed. And if you ask anyone from the
country's top epidemiologists to starred chefs to the local grocer,
they all point to the west, the U.S.A., the country the French love
and hate the most. By Susan Herrmann Loomis.
</P>
<P>
   MADAME-CURRY (Undated) _ Madame Curry packaged Indian mixes are
what foods like Rice a Roni should be. The recipes are authentic,
the instructions are easy to follow, and the quality of the
ingredients is exceptional. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
