<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3835 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAPLAN-COLUMN09-COX     09-08 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPLAN-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Emergency contraception an ethical advance
 &HT;    By Arthur Caplan
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Americans have a very difficult time dealing with sex. Granted,
when the subject is the love life of a president, a British
princess or an underage prostitute on one of the TV tabloid shows,
we cannot shut up. But that is talk about strangers whose habits,
peccadilloes and moral failings have no immediate bearing on what
we do in our own bedrooms. When the conversation turns to our own
sex lives, to the sexuality of our spouses, children and siblings,
we have much less to say.
</P>
<P>
   Our national reticence about sex has made it impossible to
conduct reliable surveys about sexual behavior among adolescents
and to talk to one another frankly and honestly about sexually
transmitted diseases. A significant number of Americans do not
realize that fertilization does not take place at the moment of
sexual intercourse. We are so paralyzed about the topic of abortion
that all we can do is yell, picket or bomb.
</P>
<P>
   This inability to address sex and its consequences, other than
when it involves distant strangers, is why it has taken so long _
far too long _ to get a safe and effective form of emergency
contraception into the hands of our wives, sisters and daughters.
Emergency contraception, sometimes misleadingly called the
``morning-after pill'' because it works for up to three days after
sex, has long been available in many European nations. There have
been no serious side effects or complications.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, some doctors and clinics have used a
``home brew'' approach, giving high doses of birth control pills
and dealing with the consequences of rape or a failed condom or a
moment of passion where no contraception was used. But almost no
women know about emergency contraception.
</P>
<P>
   Even among women who have been raped and treated at hospitals,
many have no idea that medicine had anything to help them not
become pregnant. Most women think the only thing medicine has to
offer is RU-486, the so-called abortion pill, and for some that is
not an option. The lack of frankness about sex and about what can
be done to prevent unintended pregnancy has left American women
without the best treatment that medicine has to offer.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the Food and Drug Administration has approved an
emergency contraception kit, using the same pills now used for
birth control. The kit _ marketed by Gynetics Inc., of Somerville,
N.J. _ has a pregnancy test that a woman must use first since, if
she is already pregnant, emergency contraception will do nothing to
change that. But if she is not yet pregnant, emergency
contraception will cut the chance of becoming pregnant after
unprotected sexual intercourse from 8 percent to 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency contraception is no substitute for ongoing birth
control. Condoms, ordinary birth control and other methods work
more effectively. And emergency contraception offers no protection
against sexually transmitted disease.
</P>
<P>
   Still, having emergency contraception available at every
student-health or family-planning clinic, hospital emergency room
and mental health care facility as well as in every fertile woman's
medicine cabinet is a tremendous ethical advance. For centuries,
the only option that American women have had to prevent an
unintended pregnancy has been abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency contraception is just that: contraception. By delaying
a woman's ovulation, the odds of pregnancy occurring are greatly
diminished. However one views abortion, the prevention of pregnancy
is ethically better than ending a pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   The real tragedy is that it took so long to get a company to
make this product and for the FDA to approve it. The delay suggests
we are spending too much time worrying about the sex lives of
presidents and celebrities and not nearly enough talking about what
we can do to promote responsibility and safety in our own sex
lives.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Caplan is director of the Center for Bioethics at the
University of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
