<P>
   CLINTON-POLL (Washington) _ A bipartisan poll shows the Monica
Lewinsky matter has taken its toll on President Clinton and
Democrats. Among the findings: ``Moral values'' are now up there
with crime and the economy as leading issues, Clinton's personal
approval has dropped 19 percentage points since the beginning of
the year, and Republicans are up 3 points over Democrats in
congressional races. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SCANDAL (Washington) _ President Clinton scrambles to
shore up support among Democrats amid moves by some members of his
party to distance themselves from the president and the Monica
Lewinsky scandal. Clinton has scheduled a meeting at the White
House early Wednesday with Democratic congressional leaders. By
JOHN C. HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LOTTO-FARMERS (Roby, Texas) _ In the days before state
lotteries, a story regularly made the rounds of the heartland about
a farmer who won the Irish Sweepstakes. Asked what he would do with
the money, he replied, ``I'll just keep farming until it's all
gone.'' It's no longer a joke. Almost two years after 43 people in
this tiny town won a $47 million lottery jackpot, about half the
winners just take their winnings to the bank and pay off their farm
debts. By JIM HENDERSON.
</P>
<P>
   FLOOD-SCHOOLS (Del Rio, Texas) _ More than two weeks after
flooding devastated the Texas border city of Del Rio, 15 public
schools reopen despite concerns that the water supply is not safe.
Meanwhile, some students and their families whose homes were
damaged or destroyed remain in temporary shelters. By JOHN
MacCORMACK.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   YIP-COLUMN (Undated) _ In the wake of the turmoil in the stock
market last week, a colleague made an interesting remark to me
about risk. We always talk about people selling stocks when the
market drops, but who buys those shares and why are they so willing
to buy when the market looks so risky? By PAMELA YIP.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ When Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn,
condemned President Clinton's immoral behavior, he joined a small
band of senators who over the decades have shown the courage and
integrity to defy their party's leaders on a matter of principle.
It's a very small band indeed, but it includes Sens. Mark Hatfield,
Howard Baker, William Fulbright and Margaret Chase Smith, all
heroes worth remembering. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) _ Garry Mauro, still struggling
to get his gubernatorial campaign off the ground, has accused Gov.
George W. Bush of committing a major political sin on taxes _ the
flip-flop. Technically, Mauro is correct. But, politically, the
issue will be debated. By CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
