<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3940 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-CONSUMERS-0909     09-08 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CONSUMERS-0909-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RUSSIANS SHOP, SAVE, WORRY AMID ECONOMIC BREAKDOWN
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-PRICES-0909.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ On one side of this sprawling city, fish-seller Natasha
Ivanova studies her merchandise as it rots in the sun at an outdoor
market in southwestern Moscow. Prices for the mullet she peddles
have risen sevenfold in the past three weeks and there are no
buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's economic crisis has turned an already strapped nation
into a country of anxious survivalists, spending what they can to
horde food that will keep: vegetable oil, flour, sugar, coffee,
pasta and dried beans.
</P>
<P>
   Mullet is not on their shopping lists. Ivanova, 40, and her
family will be eating a lot of unsold fish in the coming days and
nights.
</P>
<P>
   In the city center, next to the Kremlin, 18-year-old Lena
Ruditskaya is bedecked in skintight designer slacks and black
platform boots, trolling for bargains in the exclusive boutiques of
the wealthy New Russians. She proudly clutches her latest catch: an
imported $130 suede jacket from a glitzy shop in the marble-trimmed
Manezh Square mall.
</P>
<P>
   An economics student and the daughter of affluent parents,
Ruditskaya's attitude resembles champagne-sipping on the Titanic:
buy now, the end of high-living is near under the waning era of
President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   A city of some haves and many have-nots since the collapse of
the Soviet Union in 1991, Moscow has been a frenetic theater of
consumerism and fatalism in the three weeks since the country was
crippled by economic turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   Food is disappearing from store shelves. Imports, which make up
the bulk of items in grocery stores, are not making it passed the
border as the paralyzed banking system has frozen payments. Food
prices have risen from 50 to 500 percent in the past three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Russians are conserving their dollars, the main form of savings
in a country whose currency has collapsed three times since
Communist rule disintegrated seven years ago. But still they must
spend to survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where we are going, we don't know. What the politicians are
deciding, we don't know. Maybe we'll wake up from this in the
morning to find it is just a bad dream, or may be we'll be dead,''
Yulia Gladyeshava, 51, a vegetable seller said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow is richer than most of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of Russians are simply struggling to persevere
as they have watched the plummeting ruble effectively cut their
hard-earned salaries, pensions and savings by two-thirds in the
past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Before the crisis hit, most of the 147 million Russians were
caught against the tide of audacious and unfinished capitalism they
were never completely a part of. The few rich got richer, most of
the middle and lower classes did not, living on inert state
salaries and pensions that never rose with the cost of goods after
Soviet-style price controls were removed in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they are nearly wiped out.
</P>
<P>
   The average monthly household income in June was 861 rubles,
about $137. With the ruble's devaluation since Aug. 17, the same
income of 861 rubles withered to a value of about $40 on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The blow is cushioned slightly by the fact that housing and
utilities remain heavily subsidized for most Russians. Yet for
many, a second job is a must, as is a small plot of land somewhere
to grow cucumbers and tomatoes to eat or to sell.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are groceries and clothes to buy. Each month is a
stretch to live.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow the monthly minimum wage set by law before the crisis
was 83 rubles. Now, it buys one liter of vegetable oil, two cans of
meat preserves and one loaf of bread, the Interfax news agency
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hardest hit are the retirees, who lived on fixed incomes.
</P>
<P>
   Nikolai Spronavov, 76, and his wife Claudia, 74, have cut meat
and chicken and cheese from their diet. It is a luxury they can no
longer afford on their combined pension of 1,280 rubles, which was
worth about $210 a month in early August and only $60 on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Economic analysts say the ruble has fallen farther and faster
against the dollar than any other currency in the world except for
Indonesia's. Inflation rose to 15 percent in August, up from 0.2
percent in July, the government announced recently. Forecasters say
the August rate could triple or quadruple by the end of September.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's see Yeltsin live in these conditions. Let's see how he
would fare,'' said Claudia, her bag filled Tuesday with the
couple's evening meal of cucumbers, potatoes and onions.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's small middle class, no more than a few million people,
have seen their bank savings frozen or lost. Moreover, the
prospects of unemployment loom as banks, brokerage houses and
stores that catered to the new class cope with the crisis.
Employment agencies say that in the financial and related services
sector 40,000 to 100,000 jobs might be lost in Moscow over the next
two months.
</P>
<P>
   Looking to sink their remaining rubles somewhere before it falls
farther in value, jewelry sales have skyrocketed, as have purchases
of big-ticket items like washing machines and refrigerators.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have enough money now to buy the things that I want,'' said
the stylish teenager, Ruditskaya, amid the luxury goods. ``I might
as well buy them now. Why wait?''
</P>
<P>
   But for most Russians, the question of waiting or buying was
never an issue because disposable income was never a reality.
Yeltsin's democracy never fully delivered its promises.
</P>
<P>
   They were not part of the system that brought stock markets and
restaurants and cable television and car dealerships and
American-style shopping malls to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   And for the foreseeable future, they never will be as Russia
struggles to settle its political instability and locate a
difficult road to economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
   The fish-seller, Ivanova, was a university-educated laboratory
technician put out of work when her Soviet-era factory closed. She
turned to buying fish from a wholesaler and selling it at a
neighborhood ``rynhok,'' or farmers' market, in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   That was three years ago. At 2 p.m. Tuesday, she had not sold a
single mullet six hours into her workday. But her mind was not so
much on her plight, as that of her troubled nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia was such a mighty country,'' she said, looking into the
distance. ``Now, it is such an embarrassment.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
