<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-FAT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN FRANCE, THE GOOSE IS NOT THE ONLY THING THAT'S GETTING FAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By SUSAN HERRMANN LOOMIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUVIERS, France _ I marvel each time I watch a certain farmer
at our local market spoon rivers of thick, golden creme fraiche
into large fat glass jars for customers who tuck them into
overflowing baskets.
</P>
<P>
   I can almost predict what these guilt-free shoppers will be
having for Sunday lunch _ and it is never lo-cal. Yet they don't
seem to gain a pound. Americans, on the other hand, seem to pile on
the ounces just thinking about buying cream.
</P>
<P>
   In Normandy, my corner of France _ land of rich cheese, richer
cream and the best butter in the nation _ cream-buying market
regulars and all of my friends who eat good, hearty Norman dishes
of local products, are maintaining their shapes and enjoying their
food.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a gray cloud is passing over the traditional French dietary
regimen: the French are gaining weight, if statistics are to be
believed. And if you ask anyone from the country's top
epidemiologists to starred chefs to the local grocer, they all
point to the west, the United States, the country the French love
and hate the most.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Eveline Eschwege, director of epidemiological research at
the Institut National de la Sante et la Recherche Medicale in Paris
(the equivalent of the American National Institutes of Health),
says the French, indeed, are slowly but perceptibly getting
heavier. Eight percent of them now qualify as obese.
</P>
<P>
   She hastened to say that they are far behind most industrial
countries, particularly the United States, with an obesity rate of
at least 20 percent, and Germany, with a 19 percent obesity rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The change is because we follow Americans in everything,'' she
said, ``including the way they eat.'' She points to an increase in
consumption of manufactured foods and sodas, and to the habit of
eating all the time, ``a l'americaine,'' as prime factors.
</P>
<P>
   But how about those classic French menus where everything seems
bathed in butter and cream? They don't put on the pounds the way
fast food does, it seems. According to Dr. Eschwege, the difference
has to do with the ingredients in traditional dishes, which are
pure and closer to their source.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no chemicals, no additives, in foods that go into
traditional dishes like veal with cream sauce or roast chicken and
vegetables,'' she said. ``Also, traditional dishes like those are
eaten at table, calmly, so that satisfaction is gained and no one
is hungry two hours later.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Though we see a definite, if unobtrusive, increase in
weight,'' Dr. Eschwege added, ``at least for now, the French are
still resisting. We haven't completely given up structured meal
times yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bernard Guy-Grand, an international expert on obesity and
the head of medicine and nutrition at the Hotel-Dieu hospital in
Paris, is proud of the shape the French are in, though he
acknowledges obesity as a French public health problem. And he
views trans-Atlantic influence as a culprit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certain the French are eating more and more like
Americans,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   I see it myself. In 10 years of living in France and 20 years of
visiting regularly, I've watched French breakfasts gradually switch
from bakery-fresh bread, butter and coffee to packaged cereals and
commercial hot chocolate. I've seen ``sheeps'' _ potato and corn
chips _ slip into the regular French diet, and packaged pizzas, hot
dogs and frozen dinners become de rigueur.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coca'' (the universal French name for Coca-Cola) is now the
drink most often offered to children at meals on special occasions,
whereas even five years ago it was water, plain or with fruit
syrup; in the old days, they drank wine. ``McDo,'' or McDonald's,
has become the destination of choice for many a family night out.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A friend in Paris, a chef, recently told me about two Parisian
children with full-time working parents who eat dinner every night
at their neighborhood McDo.
</P>
<P>
   Which points to a slightly more disturbing statistic, the
tripling, since the '50s, in the percentage of French children who
are overweight. According to Dr. Marie-Francoise Rolland-Cachera,
an epidemiologist at the Institut Nationale de la Sante et la
Recherche Medicale who specializes in obesity in children, it is up
from 3 percent in 1955, to above 10 percent in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Why has this happened? ``We've got many hypotheses,'' she said.
``But in the case of children it is too easy to say it's the
American style of eating. There are many other reasons, of course,
But a newly sedentary life style is one my colleagues and I have
proven.''
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, the French are as gorgeous and chicly slim as
always. I have lost count of the number of times visiting Americans
ask me how they do it. My analysis has always attributed it to good
diet, regular exercise (no one climbs more steps than the
Metro-taking Parisians, nor carries heavier loads than the French
do coming home from the market, plenty of bread and above all,
specific and honored mealtimes: 12:30 for lunch, and 8 for dinner.
These habits continue, though they appear to be slowly, insidiously
breaking down.
</P>
<P>
   I notice it most at lunchtime in midsize to large French cities,
where instead of the traditional hush as workers stop to eat, the
sidewalks are filled with busy people, phones clapped to one ear as
they munch a sandwich. Of course, the sandwich is made with fresh,
crusty baguette, sweet-cream butter and air-cured ham or raw-milk
Camembert, but it still amounts to eating on the run.
</P>
<P>
   In the countryside, megalithic shopping malls _ complete with
supermarkets, shoe-repair shops, cafes, bakeries, boutiques
offering everything from perfume to shoes, and at least one
fast-food restaurant _ are gradually replacing village centers.
People drive to them, park, rent enormous shopping carts, and
browse the entire day away, eating one if not two meals there.
</P>
<P>
   My 7-year-old son's friends never fail to bring a box of cookies
or candies with them when they come to play: they expect to munch
at will all day long rather than waiting for the traditional 5 p.m.
``gouter,'' or snack time.
</P>
<P>
   These changes disturb me, as an American who has consciously
steeped myself in the country's culinary traditions, more than it
seems to disturb the French. I notice that my French friends are
eager to try the latest American food import, admire McDonald's
because they are so clean, and are happy to feed their children
breakfast cereals because they are so easy.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, I buy fresh bread daily at the local bakery, fresh
butter at the market, fresh coffee from the local roaster, and
fresh milk from the farm. And because I see farmers on a regular
basis at the market, I know exactly who raises my peas, where my
chickens, ducks, and lambs have spent their lives, and the exact
day that the shell beans will be ready to harvest.
</P>
<P>
   A hopeful sign is how easy it still is to eat well _ truly
magnificently well _ in France. Then there is the French national
stubbornness and insistence about doing things in their own
particular way. Diet is one area where a little national chauvinism
might be just what the doctor ordered. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
