<HEADLINE>
TENEMENT HOUSE SETTING FOR DINNER PARTIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You probably do not use mismatched yard-sale plates, glasses and
silverware when entertaining at home, but they are part of the
charm of arranging a dinner party in the tenement kitchen of the
Lower East Side Tenement Museum in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The narrow room, which has uneven floors, bare-bulb lighting, an
old-fashioned stove and sink and is painted a gloomy green, can be
booked for private parties. A modern convenience, air-conditioning,
has been added. A number of vintage enamel-top kitchen tables can
be pushed together to seat 30 guests; there is room in a gallery
space across the dim hallway for a cocktail reception.
</P>
<P>
   The 1863 landmark tenement building, at 97 Orchard Street
(Broome Street) and across the street from the museum's reception
area at 90 Orchard Street, has several apartments decorated to
replicate immigrant experiences from 1878 to 1930.
</P>
<P>
   Parties in the kitchen area, which has a modern, working kitchen
in the next room, include a tour of these apartments. For dinners,
the museum recommends three caterers: Festive Palate, Alison Mesrop
and a kosher company, Simply Divine.
</P>
<P>
   They specialize in menus that evoke the immigrant past. Renting
the kitchen and gallery is $750 to $850, of which $500 is a
contribution to the museum. The caterer's fee is extra. For
information: (212) 431-0233, ext. 214.
</P>
<P>
   For this fall, the museum is planning a series of benefit
dinners with various ethnic themes; they will be open to the
public. On Nov. 14, they are hoping to have an Italian dinner
prepared by Lidia Bastianich of Felidia restaurant. Information:
(212) 431-0233. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Haven for Chilies
</P>
<P>
   Fresh green chilies from Hatch, N.M., which are preferred by
many cooks for Southwestern dishes, are now available at Kitchen
Market, 218 Eighth Avenue (21st Street). They are $3.95 a pound.
</P>
<P>
   The market also sells other fresh chilies, including poblano and
serrano, plus dozens of kinds of dried chilies, along with chili
condiments, beans, grains and dried corn products. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tea From an Artist
</P>
<P>
   Wild Lily Tea Room, a serene oasis with a small pool of water
set into its multilevel stone floor, has opened at 511 West 22nd
Street and will serve tea and light food. Ines Sun all but
abandoned her efforts to make painting a career to devote herself
to the tea room, which is on a gallery-rich block.
</P>
<P>
   More than 40 kinds of tea, plates of scones, pastries and
savories like steamed dumplings are available. The food is $6.75 to
$9.50, including a pot of tea or a glass of iced tea.
</P>
<P>
   Most teas are $4. But for connoisseurs, there are teas like
first-flush Darjeeling for $8. These, the menu advises, are ``best
drunk without adding anything, only your mind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 1616EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3950 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT &LR;      09-08 0694
