u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TALK-NYT &LR;      09-08 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWSLETTER POINTS THE WAY TO RARE BUYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   So you're a wine fanatic whose day is incomplete if it doesn't
include a bottle of some rare California cabernet. Unfortunately,
you have lots of incomplete days, because most shops don't carry
them and those that do are always sold out.
</P>
<P>
   Help is at hand. First Sip, a new monthly wine newsletter, not
only identifies the wines, as do all the other newsletters, but
goes the extra mile and lists where to find them.
</P>
<P>
   For example, should you be a devotee of Etude Pinot Noir, a Napa
Valley wine made by the ultimate cult winemaker, Tony Soter, the
July issue of First Sip lists nine shops where the wine can be
found: two each in California, Missouri and Arizona, and one each
in Massachusetts, Maryland and New Jersey. And a cabernet sauvignon
from the Grace Family Vineyards, also in the Napa Valley and one of
the most difficult American wines to obtain, can be found in two
shops, both in California, First Sip writes.
</P>
<P>
   A tip: these rare wines often turn up where you would least
expect to find them _ in out-of-the-way shops often overlooked by
the big spenders. These shops acquire the wines when they can, but
by no means consistently. This is where First Sips steps in: it
does the searching for you.
</P>
<P>
   Some retailers will sell only one bottle, and others offer only
a vertical selection, which means the buyer must take three
bottles, each from a successive vintage. But most retailers expect
the seekers of these rare wines to fill out their orders with
quantities of other, less exclusive but almost as expensive wines.
</P>
<P>
   First Sip finds rare wines by faxing hundreds of wine shops
nationwide, said Steven Dworman, its publisher, who also publishes
Infomercial Marketing Report, another newsletter. Retailers ``have
made a very specific point that they are not looking for `cherry
pickers,''' he said. ``Appearing in First Sip is worthwhile to them
only if they sell more than just the prized wines.''
</P>
<P>
   The newsletter also lists hard-to-find wines that can be
purchased from wineries. The May issue noted that Dunn Vineyards in
Napa had small quantities of its 1986 and 1987 Howell Mountain
cabernets at $150 and $120 a bottle, respectively. Current vintages
are sold only to clients on a mailing list.
</P>
<P>
   Often, First Sip's reports on the small wineries include useful
tips. An item on the Cain Vineyard and Winery's 1995 vintage
(available this January) noted that with a purchase of a case of
Cain Five, the Napa winery's Bordeaux-style blend, regular
customers can join Club Cain, get 15 percent off wine purchases and
an invitation to a party at the winery.
</P>
<P>
   For the present, much of this information _ and that on many
smaller California wineries _ mostly benefits Californians. Many
states, including New York, in thrall to powerful liquor lobbies,
prohibit the direct interstate shipment from producer to consumer
of wines and spirits.
</P>
<P>
   But East Coast wine enthusiasts who regularly visit California
wine country carry these wines home with them.
</P>
<P>
   Here are First Sip's 10 most-difficult-to-find United States
wines (all of them from California), in order of rarity: 1)
Screaming Eagle Cabernet Sauvignon, Napa Valley; 2) Grace Family
Vineyards Cabernet Sauvignon, Napa Valley; 3) Sine Qua Non the
Bride, Arroyo Grande Valley; 4) Marcassin Winery Chardonnay,
Carneros, Hudson Vineyards E Block; 5) Colgin Cellars Cabernet
Sauvignon, Napa Valley, Herb Lamb Vineyard; 6) Abreu Cabernet
Sauvignon, Napa Valley, Madrona Vineyard; 7) Dalla Valle Maya, Napa
Valley Proprietary Red Wine; 8) Dehlinger Winery Pinot Noir,
Sonoma, Russian River Valley Reserve; 9) Plumpjack Winery Cabernet
Sauvignon, Napa Valley, Mount Eden Vineyard, and 10) Bryant Family
Vineyards Cabernet Sauvignon, Napa Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly household names. Nor do these listings necessarily
represent the very best in California wines. They represent
extremely good wines that are in very short supply. Grace Family
Vineyards makes 300 cases of some of its wines; Screaming Eagle
made 175 cases of its 1994 Cabernet Sauvignon, Napa Valley. The
quirky Sine Qua Non winery, in South Central California, turned out
80 six-packs of a 1995 Rhone blend called Red Handed.
</P>
<P>
   Neither prices nor vintages are supplied for the
most-difficult-to-find list. First Sip assumes that the collectors
of these wines are so dedicated to owning them that neither price
nor vintage matters. Given the care with which the grapes are
selected and the wines made, the product is almost always
excellent. And if it isn't, well, having the bottle is more
important than drinking the wine.
</P>
<P>
   While the early issues of First Sip seemed to concentrate on the
Napa Valley, there have been articles on Oregon and Washington
State, where wineries like Broadley Vineyards (Oregon) and L'Ecole
No. 41 (Washington) might one day qualify for the difficult-to-find
list. No Napa-or-nothing snob, Dworman plans to cover the American
wine scene in depth.
</P>
<P>
   Is his publication, which began in March, a worthy newcomer? For
serious collectors, definitely. For the rest of us, it's great fun
and even informative in an unreal way, like a magazine devoted to
large yachts. Everyone likes to know how the better half lives.
</P>
<P>
   The tone of the newsletter is so enthusiastic it becomes wearing
after a while, but then it's new and trying to be friendly to
everyone. With time, one hopes it will adopt a more measured pace.
</P>
<P>
   Dworman says he will keep his subscription list to 5,000. To
keep out the riffraff, I guess. When the riffraff discover that the
price is $189 a year, they will probably stay away on their own.
(The first year, Dworman is offering a charter subscription for
$99.) First Sip's address is 11533 Thurston Circle, Los Angeles
90049; (800) 523-2727 or (310) 472-5253.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
