<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3953 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KITCHEN-WARES-ART-NYT     09-08 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KITCHEN-WARES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEST KITCHEN AMANDA HESSER 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Grilling is such a familiar cooking technique for Americans that
its particular effect on foods is often overlooked. Take, for
instance, what grilling does to a steak. It browns and sears it in
neat straight lines, so that you get crisp bites of a deep,
caramelized flavor in between more tender parts untouched by the
grill.
</P>
<P>
   When most people think of grilling, though, they think of
barbecue, charcoal and footlong forks. But this time of year, as
backyard cooks start moving back to the kitchen, they have an
indoor alternative _ a grill pan.
</P>
<P>
   It looks much like a saute pan but has ridges rising from the
base. And it can be used with pretty much any food you would grill
outdoors: salmon steaks, vegetables, sausages, even fruit.
</P>
<P>
   But let's make something clear: a grill pan is not a substitute
for an outdoor grill. The similarities pretty much stop at the
grill marks. Food cooks with more moisture in a grill pan because
steam collects between the ridges and the base of the pan. It also
does not get any of the smoky flavor from natural charcoal.
</P>
<P>
   (That isn't to say there is no smoke. On the contrary, if you
have a typical apartment kitchen with no exhaust hood and little
air circulation, a grill pan may not work for you at all.)
</P>
<P>
   In testing five grill pans, I found that almost every one had a
trade-off. A pan either performed just adequately and was easy to
clean up, or it performed well, made a lot of smoke and was
difficult to clean.
</P>
<P>
   I began with All-Clad's 11-inch-square nonstick pan, which costs
$59.99 at the Vinegar Factory, 431 East 91st Street (York Avenue)
in New York City; (212) 987-0885. It is as light as a feather and
very easy to clean, and the square shape makes four steaks an easy
fit.
</P>
<P>
   When I grilled half-inch-thick slices of summer squash brushed
with olive oil, they cooked through at the same rate as they
browned. But with a steak, the rounded ridges in the pan simply
were not deep enough. The browned parts blended together, so the
meat looked as if I had broiled it.
</P>
<P>
   Calphalon makes an almost identical pan, with an anodized
aluminum surface like All-Clad's, but not nonstick. In performance,
it runs laps around the All-Clad. It is exceptionally light, and
its ridges are distinct.
</P>
<P>
   They imprinted the squash and steaks with definite lines and
cooked the food evenly at all points. Its only drawback is that
cleanup is labor-intensive: the manufacturer advises scrubbing it
with an abrasive cleaner.
</P>
<P>
   This pan is also available in a 12-inch round shape. The 11-inch
square is $49.95 at Broadway Panhandler, 477 Broome Street (Wooster
Street); (212) 966-3434.
</P>
<P>
   Then I tried the heavier, more traditional iron grill pans. Le
Creuset's has the brand's traditional shiny enamel coating on the
outside, but a matte coating inside. The pan heated evenly but,
like the All-Clad's, its ridges were too shallow, so the steaks
might as well have been sauteed. It is available in 10- and 12-inch
sizes; the 12-inch is $65.98 at Zabar's, 2245 Broadway (80th
Street); (212) 787-2000.
</P>
<P>
   I went out on a limb and tried a more obscure brand, the
Villaware Sear-Top Grill Pan, which has a slanted cooking surface
so that grease collects at one side. It also has a ridged iron lid
that is heated on a separate burner and placed on top of whatever
you are cooking, to cook the food on both sides at once. I had high
hopes, thinking that perhaps I had uncovered a treasure.
</P>
<P>
   But I was underwhelmed. This pan, which weighs in at 14 pounds
8.2 ounces, is so heavy I had to use both hands to move it around.
But the squash, I am afraid, suffered more than I.
</P>
<P>
   It completely flattened under the weight of the lid. The steak,
on the other hand, cooked beautifully, with dark, caramelized
lines. But because the fat all drips to one side, it began to burn,
throwing off billowing clouds of smoke. (My apartment is still
recovering.)
</P>
<P>
   Though I heated the lid over a high flame for a full five
minutes before cooking, once I placed it on the steak it simply did
not have the heat to brown it, so I had to flip the steak anyway.
</P>
<P>
   If you like cooking to be a workout, you can call Villaware,
(800) 822-1335, for a store location or to order direct. A
rectangular pan, 12} by 9 inches, is $40; an 11-inch square is $40,
and an 11-inch round pan is $35.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, I am still partial to basic cast-iron grill pans.
Many manufacturers make them. I tried one by Lodge that got raging
hot, took hold of the steak and practically branded it with deep
narrow ridges. It smokes like crazy and is ridiculously heavy _
though not nearly as heavy as the Villaware _ but it did the job,
which, frankly, felt more like grilling than what happened with the
lighter, more refined pans.
</P>
<P>
   Cast iron, of course, is not supposed to be washed in soapy
water but heated and rubbed with oil to clean and season it. After
cooking a steak with lots of sticky, juicy bits clinging to the
pan, that's not very much fun.
</P>
<P>
   But as long as you can remember how succulently caramelized the
steak was, then perhaps it is worth the elbow grease. The best
part, though, is the price, a fraction of the others: an 11-inch
Lodge cast-iron grill pan is $17.95 at Broadway Panhandler.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
