A3955 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRAND-JURIES-HNS &LR;      09-08 1247
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAND-JURIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA'S GRAND JURY SYSTEM FACES FLURRY OF CRITICISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VICKI HADDOCK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ They convene as virtual strangers, they meet in
secret, and they can investigate more than 7,000 public agencies in
California. Their mission: to expose local government waste,
mismanagement and wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Civil grand juries issue what inevitably are trumpeted as
``blistering,'' ``scathing'' critiques on the ills of bureaucracy _
be they redundant library branches, overtime abuse or cockroaches
in the jails.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, grand juries in the nine-county San Francisco
Bay area alone have issued dozens of detailed reports at a combined
taxpayer cost of more than $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   There's just one hitch: At best, two-thirds of grand jury
recommendations are rejected or simply ignored. That reality is
fueling a heated debate about how to rescue civil grand juries, or
whether they're worth saving at all.
</P>
<P>
   Defenders argue for strengthening the citizen panels by giving
them larger budgets, more resources, and forcing local officials to
either enact the recommendations or prove why they should not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Citizens watching over the government _ that's something we
need more of, not less,'' said Jim Shultz, executive director of
the San Francisco-based Democracy Center.
</P>
<P>
   Critics, often public officials smarting from a grand jury
report, prefer stripping grand juries of power they say encourages
amateur snoops to run amok. The most prominent convert to their
ranks, San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown, came under fire from San
Francisco's civil grand jury and responded by ridiculing them as
accountable to no one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grand juries have outlived themselves'' and ``ought to be
abolished,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   In the past legislative session, the two sides skirmished over a
host of proposals to reform the system.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over grand juries has failed so far to interest the
public. Notes former San Francisco grand juror Hilda Bernstein:
``Most people simply don't know what the heck it is.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no mention of civil grand juries in school textbooks
and only passing references to them in law schools, notes the
California Grand Jurors Association. Superior Court judges _ those
responsible for civil grand juries _ sometimes don't understand how
they work.
</P>
<P>
   In their zenith a century ago, grand juries held enormous power.
But now the Legislature is rethinking the concept of civil grand
juries amid these concerns:
</P>
<P>
   _ Grand jurors are largely amateurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commitment we ask of grand jurors is absolutely
incredible. They are exposed to huge bureaucracies and expected to
understand the complexities of a school system or sheriff's
department or auditor's department,'' said Scott Thorpe,
California's supervising deputy attorney general who advises grand
juries. ``What I hear from grand juries is they're overwhelmed and
frustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Grand juries have limited resources.
</P>
<P>
   Civil grand juries could hire consultants for needed expertise,
but they rarely have the money to do so. Individual counties would
have to authorize the expense and they usually won't. Sometimes
even the basics are impossible to come by: The headquarters of the
Del Norte County Grand Jury consists of a file cabinet in a
hallway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most grand jury budgets are lower than the annual salary of
the lowest paid staffer in any bureaucracy,'' said Dan Taranto,
president of the California Grand Jurors Association. ``Imagine
ordinary citizens thrown together with no handbook, no phone, no
typewriter, and the county says `Now go do your job.'''
</P>
<P>
   But San Mateo County Supervisor Mike Nevin, a leader of efforts
to curb grand jury power, said the grand juries ``already spending
too much because what they do is so unfocused.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Grand jury reports may contain inaccuracies.
</P>
<P>
   One report about overtime abuses among San Francisco's public
employees found than an airport worker had racked up 4,700 hours of
annual overtime worth $172,880.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem was it was wrong: the figure referred to the
combined overtime of several airport employees. A debate ensued
about who made the error _ the grand jury itself or the airport,
which supplied the data.
</P>
<P>
   _ Grand juries operate in secret.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the panels, which are not subject to the Brown Act
requiring open meetings, often reach wrong conclusions because they
act in secrecy and rarely confirm their findings with affected
officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``They guard their information like gold,'' said Nick Warner,
legislative advocate for the California State Association of
Counties. ``Human nature dictates if you're being investigated and
haven't had a chance to tell your side of the story, and you get a
report that criticizes you or your department, your attitude is
gonna be, `Thanks so much _ now get outta here.'''
</P>
<P>
   The counties association tried to get a state law requiring
grand juries to share details of their investigations with
government agencies before going public, but that provision spurred
protest by former jurors and was weakened.
</P>
<P>
   _ Grand juries lack time for thorough work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system sets grand jurors up for their one moment in the
sun, their lifetime opportunity for power and glory,'' Nevin said.
``There isn't always time to develop what would be a worthwhile
investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevin argues for changing the panel's name from ``grand jury''
to ``citizen review committee'' _ a title he said better conveys
its role without connoting grandiose authority.
</P>
<P>
   But defenders of the grand jury system insist problems are rare.
Moreover, because officials have the power to stonewall
investigations, grand juries need all the authority they can get,
Shultz said. And while their reports often aren't the first to
spotlight problems, ``a grand jury report puts a dose of
credibility on the findings, because they have a formal role.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another problem cited with the grand jury system is that public
officials can ignore grand jury reports that merit action.
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein, forewoman of San Francisco's 1995 Grand Jury, recalls
doing a report that was ``superb, took a lot of time and effort,
and was essentially ignored.''
</P>
<P>
   In some counties, grand juries have persuaded newspapers to
distribute the full text of their reports to subscribers. Even so,
grand juries remain enigmas _ and local officials retain plenty of
wiggle room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at it this way,'' said Deputy Attorney General Thorpe.
``If the public doesn't care enough to rally behind the grand jury
report and hold people accountable, maybe there's a reason. ...
Maybe that particular report is not that important or that
credible.''
</P>
<P>
   Few officials _ save Mayor Brown _ call for the outright
abolition of the grand juries, and by last week even Brown would
only say, ``I don't want to talk about the grand jury.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner argues in a master's thesis that grand juries will have
to be redefined ``as more taxpayer dollars are wasted on unusable
civil grand jury reports.''
</P>
<P>
   But the California Grand Jurors Association insists civil grand
juries save enough by spotlighting government waste to pay for
themselves many times over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that about 30 percent of grand jury reports are
actually implemented ... and in baseball, that's batting pretty
good,'' Taranto said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
