<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRISPY LAMB SHANKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm often confused by the common wisdom of cooking. Why, for
example, do so many recipes have you brown lamb shanks and other
tough meats, when the braising for two or more hours after that to
make them tender breaks down the lovely, crisp crust created by the
browning? The simple truth is that browning creates complex
flavors.
</P>
<P>
   But so does long, slow cooking. And a downside to browning meats
at the beginning of cooking is that it creates hot, flying drops of
fat, often accompanied by minor burns and a huge mess.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a solution: cook lamb shanks (or short ribs, or any other
really tough cut of meat on the bone) for a long time in liquid,
until they are supremely tender. Then grill or broil the shanks,
which will give them their crust. The braising liquid serves as a
succulent sauce.
</P>
<P>
   All this takes, really, is time _ the work is minimal. I find
that a combination of port and garlic provides plenty of flavor,
but if you want to add a few aromatic vegetables to the broth, like
carrots, onions and celery, they'll certainly make a contribution.
</P>
<P>
   Or you can change the character of the dish entirely by braising
the meat in ginger and soy sauce, as in the variation below.
</P>
<P>
   It pays to arrange your schedule to make this slow-cooked dish
in a leisurely fashion. I prefer to braise the shanks the night
before serving them, while I'm cooking something else or even while
I'm out of the kitchen entirely.
</P>
<P>
   They need occasional turning (I suggest every 30 minutes, but 15
minutes more or less between turnings won't matter), but no more
attention than that.
</P>
<P>
   When the shanks are done, refrigerate the meat and sauce
separately; well wrapped, they'll keep perfectly for two or three
days. This allows you to skim the fat from the sauce before
reheating.
</P>
<P>
   The shanks will reheat in the time it takes to brown them. The
sauce needs nothing but salt, pepper and a touch of vinegar or
lemon juice to balance its sweetness. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BRAISED AND GRILLED LAMB SHANKS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: At least 2{ hours &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4 lamb shanks, each about 1 pound
</P>
<P>
   1 cup port or red wine
</P>
<P>
   8 cloves garlic (don't bother to peel them)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon red wine vinegar or lemon juice, or to taste. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Combine lamb shanks, port or other wine and garlic in a
skillet just large enough to hold shanks. Turn heat to high and
bring to a boil; cover, and adjust heat so that the mixture simmers
gently. Cook, turning about every 30 minutes, until shanks are
tender and a lovely mahogany color: 2 hours or, more likely,
longer.
</P>
<P>
   2. Remove shanks and strain the sauce. If time allows,
refrigerate both separately. Skim fat from top of sauce. Heat a
charcoal or gas grill or the broiler; the rack should be 4 to 6
inches from the heat source, and the fire hot.
</P>
<P>
   3. Grill or broil shanks until nicely browned all over,
sprinkling them with salt and pepper, and turning as necessary;
total cooking time will be about 15 minutes. Meanwhile, reheat the
sauce gently; season it with salt and pepper, then add vinegar or
lemon juice. Taste, and add more seasoning if needed. Serve shanks
with sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Variation: For anise-flavor lamb shanks (or short ribs), braise
the meat in a mixture of \ cup soy sauce, 1 cup water, 5 thin
slices of ginger, 5 whole star anises, 4 cloves garlic and 1
tablespoon sugar. Proceed as above, finishing the sauce with rice
vinegar or white-wine vinegar.
</P>
</TEXT>
