<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MADAME-CURRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN INDIAN KITCHEN IN ONE LITTLE PACKAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By AMANDA HESSER 
  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Madame Curry packaged Indian mixes are what foods like
Rice-A-Roni should be. The recipes are authentic, the instructions
are easy to follow and the quality of the ingredients is
exceptional _ the fragrance of the spices practically leaps through
the plastic.
</P>
<P>
   Olena Rajan Murphy, the owner of Miami-based Madame Curry, put
together eight packages, each containing a recipe and any
out-of-the-way ingredients. The orange lentil curry soup mix, for
instance, contains lentils, curry and an aromatic mixture of panch
phoron masala seeds, whole dried chili pepper pods and turmeric.
All you add is chicken stock, vegetable oil, an onion and fresh
cilantro.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Murphy, a cooking teacher, got the idea when taking students
on tours of ethnic markets. ``The question was always, `Why do I
need to buy a whole jar of this when all I need is a teaspoon or an
ounce?''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something my father used to say about Indian cooking was you
can cook a meal if you only had one fire,'' she said. ``So what
I've done is that even if you have a minimum amount of space in
your kitchen, you can cook an interesting array of dishes.''
</P>
<P>
   The shrimp curry would make an impressive dinner party dish. It
takes just 20 minutes to prepare, is flecked with green herbs and
fresh pink shrimp and has a brightly flavored broth. A Basmati rice
and lentil pullao is as intense as it is toothsome, and the Punjabi
chana, or curried chickpea salad, is spicy, fresh-tasting and
delicious.
</P>
<P>
   Other packages are a zesty salmon curry, fragrant Basmati rice,
South Indian chicken curry and South Indian pot roast. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Madame Curry recipe packages cost $4.95 to $6.95 and are sold
via mail order: (800) 656-5303 or www.madamecurry.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
