<HEADLINE>
PARIS GETS A NEW SUBWAY LINE FOR A NEW CENTURY 
</HEADLINE>
 
NEW YORK TIMES CORRESPONDENTS EXPLORE FALL AND WINTER SEASONS IN
EUROPE (For release on Sunday, Sept. 13)  
(jw)  By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
 &HT;    PARIS _ Almost exactly 100 years after Paris began construction
of its famous Metro, the network's first high-speed and fully
automated line will open in Oct. 15 after six years of
construction.
 &HT;    The new underground line, No. 14, is called Meteor, and will run
from the Rue de Tolbiac, near the Francois Mitterrand Library on
the Left Bank, to the Madeleine stop, near the church on the Right
Bank, with connections to parallel Metro and RER rapid-transit
lines at the Gare de Lyon and Chatelet.
 &HT;    The Meteor line, which has cost $1 billion to build, gets its
name for speed, though in the subway everything is relative. The
rubber-wheeled trains will move as fast as 50 mph over the tracks,
a third faster than conventional subway trains.
 &HT;    There will be no drivers or conductors; a central control room
will run the trains like robots. The air-cushioned, six-car trains
will take 11 minutes, with stops, to travel the five-mile route,
and are expected to carry 60 million passengers in the first year,
about the same as the first Metro line did the year after it opened
in 1900.
 &HT;    The original Metro lines had their own distinctive look, many
featuring Art Nouveau stations and stairways designed by Hector
Guimard. The new Meteor stations have a 21st-century aspect like
the monorails at Frankfurt or Newark airports.
 &HT;    Bernard Kohn, whose firm Bernard Kohn &AMP; Associes designed six of
the first eight Meteor stations and drafted the artistic concept
for the line, said: ``Everybody in a big city like this should have
the same right to transport in dignity. So we have beautiful
indirect, nonaggressive lighting and have tried to create an open,
welcoming environment in the stations. Before you get to the
station platforms, you come into a mezzanine that overlooks the
tracks, so you can see where you're going, or even change your mind
and go back up if you want.''
 &HT;    The tracks and trains are inside a glass-and-steel tube, with
see-through doors that slide open simultaneously with those of the
train after the cars come to a stop.
 &HT;    The line, expressly intended to provide relief to the
overcrowded central RER network that it parallels, has come under
criticism for ending at the Madeleine instead of the nearby Gare
St.-Lazare, one of the busiest commuter stations in Paris.
 &HT;    Tunneling will extend the line to St.-Lazare by 2002 or 2003,
according to the Regie Autonome des Transports Parisiens, the Paris
transit authority. Ultimately, the authority plans an extension to
Port de Gennevilliers, in the northwestern suburbs, to Maison
Blanche in the south of Paris, covering 12 miles.
 &HT;    
 UNDERGROUND SHOW OF AN ANCIENT HERITAGE  
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BARCELONA, Spain _ For the best part of the 1990s, Barcelona has
been busily making itself look new. Coinciding with the 1992 Summer
Olympics, it spruced up the ornate buildings of the late
19th-century Modernista movement made famous by Antonio Gaudi and
invited top-flight contemporary architects like Richard Meier,
Norman Foster, Arata Isozaki and Santiago Calatrava to add daring
new shapes to the city's profile. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now the city has decided to look after its ancient past.
Seemingly eager to boast just how old it is, Barcelona has
renovated the History of the City Museum in the heart of the
legendary Gothic Quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The museum itself is not that old. Founded in 1943, it occupies
the 15th-century Casa Padellas, which in 1931 was moved, literally
stone by stone, to its present site to make room for a road. What
is old, however, is the remains of Roman Barcelona, or Barcino, as
it was known, that lie beneath the museum. Unsurprisingly, these
are the museum's principal attractions. And these were the main
focus of the two-year renovation that concluded in late June, when
the ruins were reopened to the public. The museum says it is the
only such institution in Europe with a large archeological site in
its very basement.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to new discoveries during the renovation, the
54,000-square-foot site now reaches farther under the cathedral,
the nearby Plaza del Rey and several adjacent buildings. Scholars
have identified the area as having been commercial and industrial,
with different buildings used for dyeing clothes, cleaning and
packing fish and making wine. At the same time, they have found
traces of a Visigoth church dating back to the early seventh
century. The visitors' path now winds some 650 yards underground
through the ancient city.
</P>
<P>
   To make the museum _ and the city's history _ more accessible,
other improvements were added. A reception area, with signs in
English, makes it easier for visitors to find their way around the
museum. And in a nod to the future, a movie, ``Barcelona: A Virtual
History,'' offers a 28-minute overview of 2,000 years (head sets
provide commentary in English).
</P>
<P>
   The museum's exhibitions concentrate on Barcelona's first
millennium, starting with the first pre-Roman Iberian settlement at
nearby Montjuich and the construction of Barcino in an area now
covered by the Gothic Quarter, but also including the rise of the
Visigothic monarchy and the city's Christianization.
</P>
<P>
   Still, while the city's growth and wealth are illustrated by a
reconstituted interior of a typical Roman home in miniature as well
as by original ceramic pottery, statues, fibulas, jewelry and
remnants of frescoes, it is under ground that the magic of the past
comes alive. Indeed, to emerge from the remains of Barcino into
15th-century Barcelona only underlines the continuity of history.
Today the city is impatient to embrace the 21st century, but it has
not forgotten where it came from.
</P>
<P>
   Hours: Open Tuesday through Saturday 10 a.m. to 8 p.m. June 29
to Sept. 30; 10 a.m. to 2 p.m. and 4 to 8 p.m. the rest of the
year. Open all year on Sunday 10 a.m. to 2 p.m. Closed Monday.
Price: Tuesday through Friday 700 pesetas; Saturday and Sunday, 750
pesetas. Reduced price of 500 pesetas for students and visitors
over 60; free for children under 12.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   FRANKFURT _ Some cities are famous for their cultural life,
others for history or night life. Frankfurt, perhaps unjustly, is
famous primarily for its airport.
</P>
<P>
   Because of this city's central location in Europe and its role
as Germany's financial center, the airport is one Europe's biggest
and busiest airport hubs. It is huge, it is efficient and you can
make a round trip to almost any other city in Europe within one
day, and usually choose among multiple flights. No airport in
Europe except London's Heathrow has so many direct daily
connections to the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Frankfurt airport is expanding its connections.
Deutsche Bahn, the German national railway, is finishing an airport
station for high-speed intercity trains heading for scores of other
European cities.
</P>
<P>
   The new station, which should be completed by the end of this
year, will let air travelers hop directly onto trains rather than
haul their baggage onto a subway to the main train station
downtown.
</P>
<P>
   The railway is also developing an advanced luggage-handling
system that will eventually let people boarding a train in certain
cities, like Munich or Hanover, check their bags straight through
to New York or Paris. In 2002, Deutsche Bahn expects to complete a
new high-speed track between Frankfurt and Cologne. For most
travelers, that will make it far cheaper and almost as fast to
travel by train as by plane from Frankfurt to cities with smaller
airports, like Dusseldorf, Cologne or Stuttgart.
</P>
<P>
   While most travelers come to Frankfurt either for business or
for connections to other European cities, the Frankfurt Ballet has
long been one of this city's genuinely world-class cultural
attractions.
</P>
<P>
   Under the leadership of William Forsythe, the ballet's New
York-born artistic director who has worked in Frankfurt since 1984,
the ballet has become internationally recognized for its
avant-garde productions.
</P>
<P>
   Now Forsythe is expanding his reach. Though he remains artistic
director of the Frankfurt Ballet, he was recently named to head
this city's Teater am Turm, or TAT. Situated in a former
trolley-car station, the TAT has a reputation for experimental
productions under directors like Werner Fassbinder and Claus
Peymann.
</P>
<P>
   Forsythe's goal is to revitalize the theater by blending dance,
drama and musical performances under one roof, and to strengthen
its financing. If he and his associates live up to their track
records, the results will almost certainly be original.
</P>
<P>
   Frankfurt's row of museums along the Main River has got a fresh
boost with the ambitious renovation of the Stadel Art Institute.
After a two-year makeover, the museum recently reopened the wing
that houses its fine collection of old masters. The museum has also
added a new bookshop and lecture hall.
</P>
<P>
   A second phase of the renovation, of the rest of the museum,
will be completed in the summer of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   GENEVA _ The Grand Theatre, a beloved and prestigious Geneva
institution, is about to reopen after a thorough overhaul that kept
it closed for a year. The $13 million renovation project equipped
the old house with state-of-the-art stage machinery and made other
improvements, including the replacement of the nearly 1,500 seats
with ones with red velvet cushions.
</P>
<P>
   The florid ceiling fresco in the foyer, an allegory of ``Joyous
Music'' and ``Tragic Music,'' remains.
</P>
<P>
   The ornate facade of the Grand Theatre, on the Place Neuve,
looking out on the airy Promenade des Bastions, seems a smaller
version of the Paris Opera. To the present director general of the
Geneva house, Renee Auphan, a native of Marseilles, the setting is
familiar: She spent 13 years as a soloist at the Paris Opera.
</P>
<P>
   Geneva's imposing neo-Baroque shrine of the lyrical drama, rich
outside with columns, pediments and statuary, and inside with
marble and crystal chandeliers, was inaugurated 119 years ago with
Rossini's ``Guillaume Tell,'' celebrating the Swiss national hero,
William Tell. Tchaikovsky, Saint-Saens, Massenet and Stravinsky
have conducted their own works here.
</P>
<P>
   The Grand Theatre is sometimes included in lists of the world's
10 best opera houses.
</P>
<P>
   It so happens that each of the three operas to be offered this
fall in the rejuvenated house will be sung in one of the three
principal languages of the Swiss Confederation _ German, Italian
and French.
</P>
<P>
   A new production of Richard Strauss' ``Rosenkavalier'' will be
presented Sept. 21 and reprised Sept. 24, 27 and 29, and Oct. 2 and
5. Phillippe Auguin will conduct; the soprano Tina Kiberg, the
mezzo-soprano Angelika Kirchschlager and Markus Hollop are the
principals.
</P>
<P>
   Rossini's ``Semiramide'' will be performed Oct. 30 and Nov. 2,
5, 8, 10 and 13, with Gianluigi Gelmetti conducting and soprano
Nelly Miricioiu in the title role.
</P>
<P>
   A new production of Massenet's ``Cendrillon'' will be presented
Dec. 9, 11, 13, 15, 17, 19 and 21. Valentin Raymond will conduct,
and soprano Svetla Vassileva appear as Cinderella. Tickets go on
sale Monday for $16 to $103 at the box office, 11 Boulevard du
Theatre, phone (41-22) 418-3130, fax (41-22) 418-3001.
</P>
<P>
   On a contemporary note, the striking new auditorium of the
restructured Batiment des Forces Motrices (now commonly called the
BFM), will open its 1998-99 season on Oct. 6 with ``Soiree de
Ballet Dance en Pieces,'' modern choreography performed by the
Ballet of the Grand Theatre (daily, except Tuesdays, until Oct.
18).
</P>
<P>
   The BFM sits on an island in the Rhone, near the western edge of
Geneva, like a boat anchored in the river.
</P>
<P>
   The low-slung brick-and-concrete building, with its huge steel
rafters, is an abandoned industrial plant that has been converted
into a multipurpose complex, including a 985-seat theater. It still
has a technical air; two inactive turbines grace the spacious
lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Besides being the new home for the ballet, the building will be
used for avant-garde opera and plays.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Even Muscovites, who by now have grown used to the
giant gold onion dome on their horizon, still stop sometimes to
marvel at the Cathedral of Christ the Savior, the enormous church
that has been built anew on the banks of the Moscow River near the
Pushkin Museum for the Fine Arts. More than anything else in this
fast-changing city, the vast cathedral _ whether or not you like
its heavyset grandeur _ has come to symbolize Russia's attempt to
undo the physical damage caused by the hand of Communism.
</P>
<P>
   The cathedral was planned in 1812 in commemoration of Russia's
victory over Napoleon, and construction began in earnest in 1830.
It was finally consecrated in 1883. In 1931, Stalin, in one of his
most spectacular acts of vengeance against the Russian Orthodox
Church, ordered the cathedral's demolition, which began with a
systematic looting of its sumptuous interior.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 5, 1931, the 30-story-high cathedral, topped by a
gigantic copper-covered cupola, was reduced to rubble by a series
of powerful explosions. Plans to build a gargantuan skyscraper in
its place were eventually dropped, and instead, the city used the
site for an Olympic-size swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   A grass-roots plan among Orthodox believers to build a new
cathedral dates back to the 1980s, but the project took off a
decade later with an aggressive fund-raising campaign conducted by
Moscow's politically ambitious Mayor Yuri Luzhkov. The cornerstone
for the new cathedral was laid in January 1995. Three years later,
with a remarkable speed that testifies to a potent mix of political
will and religious faith, the cathedral was virtually finished,
except for the reconstruction of the elaborate interior of the
upper church.
</P>
<P>
   The lower church, with an entrance on Gogol Boulevard, on
Moscow's inner circular road southwest of the Kremlin, has been
open for services almost since the beginning of construction. It is
open every day from 10 a.m. to 8 p.m., and functions as a regular
parish with vigil services on Saturdays at 5 p.m., and services on
Sundays at 10 a.m. On weekday holidays, vigils are at 6 p.m. on the
eve of the feast day, with liturgy held the following morning at 9.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors may have to wait until the end of next year for a
glimpse of the upper church, where workers are still reassembling
and duplicating icons and returning marbled walls and a gilded
iconostasis to their former glory. But a museum is open off the
corridor leading to the simpler lower church, which tells the story
of the church, its tragedy and triumph, in photographs and original
objects salvaged from the rubble. Also on display are works by the
artists involved in the restoration.
</P>
<P>
   The museum, shut briefly this summer, reopened this month. Hours
are 10 a.m. to 6 p.m., and admission is free. English-speaking
guides can be hired.
</P>
<P>
   There is also an observation deck around the belfry, open to
tourists on something of a catch-as-catch-can basis. Requests can
be made at the offices in the lower church, and when a significant
number of visitors has gathered, they are taken up to the deck,
where they can be photographed against the backdrop of the Kremlin.
There is a nominal fee.
</P>
<P>
   The grounds around the cathedral are also open, where visitors
can gaze, at close quarters, upon the sheer scale and scope of the
building, its four belfries and cupola, topped by a giant cross.
</P>
</TEXT>
