<HEADER>
A4003 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-PRIVATE-DINING-ART     09-08 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PRIVATE-DINING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE MIDST OF THE DIN, BUT OUT OF IT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: a photo for use with this story is being sent to NYT
photo clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(See related: NY-CROWDED-RESTAURANTS) 
 (HLW)  
 By WILLIAM GRIMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York is a perverse place. For years, restaurant
owners have invested huge sums to get earsplitting acoustics,
eye-popping interior design and the kind of bustling movement
normally found on a trading floor. Now they are installing tiny
private rooms that let diners tune it all out.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Central Terminal may seem like the last place anyone would
go in search of peace and solitude, but at Michael Jordan's Steak
House, the impossible becomes possible. Off the main dining room, a
maximum of six diners may book a table _ there's only one _ in a
secluded space known as Michael's Dining Room.
</P>
<P>
   Measuring 8 by 12 feet, it's more like a meditation chamber, and
it's an open question whether Jordan could even fit into the space.
The walls, in soothing polished mahogany, block out the sights and
sounds of the restaurant and the surrounding terminal. When the
folding doors are closed, diners can achieve the kind of privacy
normally found in an isolation tank.
</P>
<P>
   At Picholine, not exactly a mosh pit to begin with, a maximum of
eight diners can put a buffer between themselves and the rest of
the crowd by entering a little private room, with a single table,
that looks onto the restaurant's cheese cave. It's a cozy space,
surrounded by floor-to-ceiling wine racks, and visible to the
outside world through a large window that makes the party within
look like a museum exhibit, a late-20th-century version of those
Indian tribes feasting on corn at the American Museum of Natural
History.
</P>
<P>
   The new-style private room fulfills three functions. Business
customers use it to hold confidential meetings, confident that they
will not be overheard. Celebrities can put a wall between them and
any prying eyes. (At Picholine they can sneak in and out by a back
exit.) And diners looking for a romantic evening can shut out the
rest of the world, including, in some cases, the waiter. At the
Park restaurant in the Lombardy Hotel, staff members are under
strict orders not to enter the small private Garden Room until
summoned. Wink, wink.
</P>
<P>
   For all their sense of exclusivity, private rooms are not any
more difficult to reserve than a regular table. A week's notice at
most is usually enough to secure the space.
</P>
<P>
   Not every private room goes for the hermetically sealed
esthetic. At Vong, the Thai Room, an slightly elevated platform in
the main dining room, cleverly lets in air, light and sound while
creating a sense of intimacy with a border of wooden louvers around
a long green marble table that seats 12. It's all very civilized,
in a tropical way. The ambient noise of conversation and dinnerware
clatter floats through the louvers, but the Thai Room itself
maintains a serene, isolated integrity.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the Thai Room in half, shut out the sight and sound, and you
get the Chef's Tasting Room at Union Pacific, where a maximum of
six diners are served the restaurant's tasting menu. The room,
perched on the mezzanine level, has the hushed, textured silence of
a confessional, an impression that's reinforced by the meshed
fabric that foils any attempt to peer in. Diners sit on a black
cloth banquette that runs around three sides of a small copper
table. A star-shaped hanging light casts a small circle of
illumination on the table surface.
</P>
<P>
   For diners who want to be far from the madding crowd, this is
about as far as it gets. Everybody else will be ready to sign up
for an early-release program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 1638EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4005 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CROWDED-RESTAURANT     09-08 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CROWDED-RESTAURANTS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN ELBOW ROOM IS NOT ON THE MENU 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: a photo for use with this story is being sent to NYT
photo clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(See related: NY-PRIVATE-DINING) 
 (HLW)  
 By ERIC ASIMOV   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``So, I don't know, what should I tell him?'' asked
the young woman during dinner at Frank, a crowded little restaurant
in the East Village, after telling the sad tale of her unhappy
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   I had an opinion about her former boyfriend, but I kept it to
myself. After all, I didn't even know her name. I just happened to
be sitting at the next table.
</P>
<P>
   Short of pointing a telescope through your neighbor's window,
few experiences offer better access to the intimate details of
strangers' lives than dining in Manhattan restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Who hasn't had the pleasure of being squeezed onto a narrow
banquette where the tables are too close for comfort? Your mind may
be on your companion across from you, but you cannot avoid being
distracted by the couples sitting on either side. You overhear
their conversations, you inhale their perfume, you can almost taste
their food. And woe betide you if a cellular phone chirps, as
diners dig into their pockets or bags, elbows cocked and ready to
do damage.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to imagine, even five years ago, dining in such
cramped quarters. But today, with rents soaring and restaurants
booming, restaurateurs feel justified squeezing in an extra table
or two _ even if it means the difference between convivial and
claustrophobic. And New Yorkers, who are happy just to get a table
in the first place, are putting up with being packed into dining
rooms with an almost biological efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, that's New York,'' sighed Charles Morris Mount, who has
designed restaurants all over the country. ``It's the battle of the
inch.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, no one accustomed to squeezing into tiny apartments
and crowded subways would expect throne-like accommodations in a
restaurant. You wouldn't even want them in places like Jean Claude
or Balthazar, bustling French bistros where the tight tables
contribute to the air of excitement.
</P>
<P>
   But at restaurants like Frank or Palmetta Plantation House on
the Upper East Side, small, inexpensive places where food may be
worth the discomfort, the jostling and crowding come dangerously
close to ruining the meal.
</P>
<P>
   At the best of Manhattan's midpriced restaurants, from Nick &AMP;
Toni's Cafe near Lincoln Center to Jo Jo on the Upper East Side to
EQ in Greenwich Village, you can expect banged knees and other
close encounters.
</P>
<P>
   At EQ, a chic restaurant where tables are placed like puzzle
pieces to fit in the tiny dining room, a stout man sitting at the
round center table one recent night leaned back in after-dinner
repose and was practically in the lap of a diner against the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big round table, the dimension was made wrong,'' Dennis
Foy, the chef and co-owner, fumed. ``It was supposed to be a
54-inch round, and it's a 60-inch round, which is standard. I lost
six inches of floor space, and that infuriated me.''
</P>
<P>
   And even though you would expect more luxurious restaurants to
be more comfortable, some of the fancier places like Osteria del
Circo lack elbow room.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first question a restaurateur asks is, `How many seats can
I put in?''' said Adam Tihany, who designed Osteria del Circo and
Le Cirque 2000 and who owns the restaurant Remi. ``It's the cost of
real estate _ how much money can you squeeze out per square foot?''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are other considerations. Like the city's fire
and building codes. While the city does not specify the number of
people a restaurant can serve, it does require that restaurants
maintain clear three-foot corridors leading to exits. The city
divides restaurants into two categories, Tihany said. Those that
seat 74 or more people are required to have two exits, with aisles
that are clearly identified. Those with fewer than 74 seats don't
need two exits, but still must have unobstructed aisles.
</P>
<P>
   Before a restaurant opens, it presents its plan for approval to
the city's Buildings Department and Fire Department. Once approved,
said Vincent Falcone, a fire protection plan examiner in the Fire
Department, further inspections are rare, usually only when
somebody complains.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't check to see if tables have enough distance,''
Tihany said. ``They don't care if the operator crams people in as
long as there is a way to get out in case of emergency.''
</P>
<P>
   While that probably is small comfort to diners, it is a good
thing for restaurant owners, because economics often dictate the
need for a higher seating capacity. As uncomfortable as crowded
restaurants may be, they ultimately indicate a healthy industry and
a healthy economy. Where were the crowds 10 years ago, after the
1987 stock market crash, when restaurant after restaurant went
under?
</P>
<P>
   And though there are no figures for restaurants alone,
Garrick-Aug Associates, an agency that specializes in store
leasing, reported that the average retail rent _ including
restaurants _ has risen steadily over the last two years, to $66 a
square foot from $51, while the availability of space has dropped.
``Obviously, the higher the rent, you either have to serve more
meals or raise prices,'' Tihany said. ``If the market won't bear
higher prices, you have to add more people.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   This is especially true of smaller, less-known restaurants,
which, without advertising or high profile, must create a buzz to
attract more customers. Nothing brings in more people like a crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ''Activity is a key to more activity,'' Alan Mannarelli, who
builds and finances downtown restaurants, said. ``Other than
Chanterelle, who doesn't cram in as many tables as they can?''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Frank cannot be accused of neglecting even the
littlest nook or cranny in squeezing 40 or so seats into its tiny,
310-square-foot space. You had better be prepared to enjoy your
neighbor's conversation along with your insalata Caprese, or you
won't enjoy Frank.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to create an intimacy,'' said Roy Docouto, who built
Frank with the owner, Frank Prisinzano. ``At other places, you're
alone at your table. We wanted people to feel as if they were
sitting at the same table together. Strangers have become friends
here. It promotes a sense of, `Say hello to your neighbors.'''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Frank is making a virtue of necessity. But
others do the same by design.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a certain energy to a dining room, and if tables get
too far apart, they lose that energy,'' said David Rockwell, a
designer whose restaurants include Nobu and Payard Patisserie and
Bistro. At Payard, for example, the three dining areas have
distinct seating schemes: Tiny cafe tables and hard chairs packed
into the bakery area, intended for quick bites; a bistro area, with
larger tables, that is lively but cramped and noisy, and a more
spacious, sedate area on the mezzanine.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is a restaurant's concept?'' Tihany asked. `'Is it an
urban bistro? Four-star dining? Relaxed trattoria? Each of these
concepts has a certain energy that dictates the seating.''
</P>
<P>
   While New York restaurateurs _ at all levels _ usually have more
ambition than space, this can inspire creative solutions. EQ is
almost a textbook example of a small downtown restaurant making the
best of a tight space. Foy also designed the dining room, which
needed to seat around 40 people in 400 square feet. EQ's wide
chairs, with their fawn-colored leather seats, are roomy and
luxurious, and the lighting is warm and inviting, showing off the
fish motif of the cloth banquettes and the subtle pattern of the
carpet. But even the finest materials could not extend the
dimensions of the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized that I had to use every square inch,'' Foy said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the rectangular dining room, broken up only by a small
bar near the entrance, feels comfortable, though not quite
spacious. But maintaining that level of comfort requires the stars,
and the diners, to align perfectly. For example, the banquette
along one wall seats 20 people. Banquette tables generally
accommodate groups of two and four. Two tables for two eat up more
space than one table for four because the tables must be separated.
</P>
<P>
   EQ tries to leave about 18 inches between banquette tables, said
its architect, Vincenzo Fressola, roomier than the 6 inches typical
of bistros but not quite the 2 feet of luxury restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, though, fate intervenes, as it did recently when
every table was occupied by a couple. Handbags banged into water
glasses, and it took real maneuvering to get out of the banquette
to go to the rest room.
</P>
<P>
   Opposite the banquette and between the bar and the kitchen is a
cozy alcove that seats 10 along three walls, with a table for six
in the middle of the floor. With each table occupied, a waiter
reciting specials to one must do an intricate pas de deux with
another waiter who arrives with food for the neighboring table.
Their practiced steps allow them to stay out of each other's way,
but trying to follow the waiter's recitation as he dances back and
forth is dizzying.
</P>
<P>
   Designers, Tihany said, begin planning a layout by deciding on
the size of the tables for two. Typically, he said, these are 24
inches wide by 27 inches deep in a bistro or trattoria, and 32
inches wide by 36 inches deep in a luxury restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Fancier restaurants generally require bigger tables for the
simple reason that they have more stuff to fit on their thick white
tablecloths. You may have no use for a fish fork, but there it is,
along with a battalion of wine glasses, butter knives and bread
plates, to say nothing of cellular phones and, of course, the
check. A simpler restaurant doesn't need to accommodate so much
equipment. Bread can sit on the table rather than on its own plate;
the same forks can be used for salad and steak.
</P>
<P>
   Oversize plates, made so popular in the nouvelle cuisine days,
are another enemy of tiny tables, but chefs still seem too willing
to sacrifice table space so they can display their artistic
squiggles of sauce and tossed herbs. Needless to say, simple
arithmetic makes clear that 12-inch luxury plates, to say nothing
of the 14-inch monsters, create a logjam on the tables of a bistro.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how carefully the tables and layout are planned, the
restaurant experience still depends on the characteristics of a
space. Osteria del Circo, which is run by the three sons of Sirio
Maccioni, the owner of Le Cirque 2000, is pretty tightly packed.
``The kids liked it tight,'' Tihany, the designer, said. ``They
wanted to feel the energy.''
</P>
<P>
   When the dining room is half empty, it can be low-key and
pleasant, but as the room gets crowded and the energy bubbles, the
high ceilings seem to throw sound back toward the floor, making
conversations at nearby tables easier to hear than your own.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the new Le Cirque 2000 is more spacious than the
notoriously tight original, but it too can feel cramped, especially
when a series of couples sit elbow to elbow along the banquette in
the rear room near the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   If highly designed restaurants like Le Cirque and Circo
represent one typical New York experience, the tiny restaurants
that line Cornelia Street in Greenwich Village are another. On a
recent Saturday night, restaurants like Le Gigot, Pearl Oyster Bar,
Little Havana, Home and Po seemed as crowded as the sidewalks
outside, where pedestrians in a hurry took to the streets to
squeeze past the masses. As in many New York restaurants, the
design is ultimately decided by the constraints of the space.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ambiance created by the coziness of the space is somehow
related to its success,'' said David Page, an owner of Home, a
stylish little American restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Home can seat 32 people at the handmade varnished wood tables in
its dining room _ make that 32 average-size people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made the booths as big as possible, given the space we
had,'' Page said. ``But if your waist line is bigger than, say, 40
inches, it's impossible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
