<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMILE, YOU ARE BEING WATCHED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News service clients) 
By MONICA ANDERSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the words of that great philosopher, Michael Jackson, lately
``I always feel like somebody's watching me.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's probably because they are watching me ... and you, too.
Has anyone else noticed the incredible number of surveillance
cameras strewn about the ceilings of America? Good grief, a person
can hardly pick their nose or pull out a wedgie without it getting
caught on tape.
</P>
<P>
   How did it all come to this, I ask you? Most of our jails are
bursting at the seams, but there are still enough criminals on the
streets to make our lives one continuous episode of ``Candid
Camera.'' When I was a youngster, ``Jack'' referred to a male human
or a small, metal object used in a children's game. Now, to be
``jacked'' or ``jacked up'' is a slang term for robbery.
</P>
<P>
   One of my favorite anecdotes involves an elderly woman who drove
up and over a curb to avoid being carjacked by several young men
who had used their vehicles to block a city street. Next, we'll all
have surveillance cameras mounted on our rearview mirrors like the
police patrol cars.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, just think about it. There is no way in the world that
anyone who ventures more than a few feet beyond their front door
could ever be without an alibi.
</P>
<P>
   ``Okay, Bill, can you tell us where you were yesterday between 8
a.m. and 4 p.m.?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, let me see. When I left home, I stopped by the
convenience store and got a cup of coffee. I'm sure they had a
camera in there. Then I went to the bank and deposited my check.
They had a bunch of cameras around the cashiers. I arrived at the
department store where I'm the manager in the jewelry department
around 9 a.m. We have a time and date stamp on our tapes if you
want to check it out. Hmmm, during my lunch hour, I went to the
airport to pick up my sister and the attendant took down my license
plate number and videotaped me as I entered and left the airport. I
dropped her off and went back to work. I didn't get off until seven
because Susie, the night manager, was home sick with the flu. You
know, you might want to question her. If the burglar was wearing a
mask, you don't know if it's a male or a female. Yeah, check with
Susie. She's got those beady eyes and she always brings her lunch
to work. I don't know where she was yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   Yep, a gal would have to be mighty reclusive in order not to
leave a neon trail all over town every day. Even your phone records
can peg your location. Now, my husband wants to get some device
called Lo Jack installed on our cars. With Lo Jack, the authorities
can determine the whereabouts of your vehicle 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, I like the theft deterrent and vehicle recovery aspects of
it. However, I do not want my family to know exactly where I am
every minute of the day! Aren't the pager and the cell phone enough
already? No, I'm not doing anything clandestine, but maybe I'm not
at the grocery store for two hours. Maybe I stopped by for a quick
espresso before I returned home. Maybe I got off work a little
early and stopped by the shoe sale at the mall. Is that a crime?
</P>
<P>
   All I need is for my kids to get some homing device so they can
follow me all over town asking for more money. Or my husband. I can
just hear it now, paging me to death with stuff like, ``Honey, it
looks like you're near the sporting goods store. Stop by and get me
some more golf tees on your way home.''
</P>
<P>
   No! Enough is enough already. I've got too many eyes on me as it
is.
</P>
<P>
   Who was that other great philosopher who said, ``It ain't
paranoia if they're really after you?''
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is an Arlington, Texas, wife, mother
and dentist. Write in care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111
W. Abram St., Arlington, TX 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
