<HEADER>
A4024 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-08 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOO FEW POLITICAL HEROES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c. 1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Joseph Lieberman rose on the Senate floor last
week to condemn the immoral behavior of his friend President
Clinton, the Democrat from Connecticut joined an illustrious but
exceedingly small pantheon of political nobility.
</P>
<P>
   Over the decades, very few senators have shown the courage and
integrity to defy their party's leaders in full public view on a
matter of principle. These senators are worth remembering because
of the legacy of independence and the lesson in honorable
government that they leave us.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the bravest were Mark Hatfield of Oregon, Howard Baker
of Tennessee and Margaret Chase Smith _ all Republicans _ plus
Democratic Sen. William Fulbright of Arkansas. Each resisted great
pressure to conform to party policies they could not in good
conscience support or to defend a president they found
indefensible.
</P>
<P>
   First, the case of Mark Hatfield, a respected 30-year
congressional veteran who had risen through seniority to become
chairman of the powerful Senate Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the new GOP congressional majority gave passage of a
constitutional amendment to mandate a balanced federal budget its
highest priority. Every Senate Republican supported it, except
Hatfield.
</P>
<P>
   He objected on principle to tinkering with the Constitution for
an accounting gimmick that could strangle legislative flexibility.
His colleagues leaned on him, lobbyists pressured him; Senate
Majority Leader Bob Dole, then the frontrunner for the 1996 GOP
presidential nomination, lectured him about party loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans couldn't get enough Democratic support to pass
the amendment and it died for want of one vote. Furious GOP
freshmen, still giddy with their new power, demanded that Hatfield
be stripped of his chairmanship. A special GOP caucus was called to
debate Hatfield's future, while he sat isolated in the back of the
room.
</P>
<P>
   Senior members, concerned about the precedent that would be set
if a chairman were fired because of a vote, prevailed over the
hotheads. But Hatfield did not seek re-election the following year.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Howard Baker, whose even-handed conduct as vice
chairman of the Senate Watergate hearings in 1973 helped build a
bipartisan consensus that President Richard M. Nixon had committed
impeachable crimes. The civility and cooperation between Baker and
Democratic chairman Sam Ervin is in sharp contrast to the political
grandstanding and distrust that has characterized the congressional
probes of Clinton's activities.
</P>
<P>
   On the infamous tapes, Nixon can be heard ordering then-Attorney
General John Mitchell to ``hold Baker's hand, baby-sit him''
through the hearings. That didn't have the desired effect, and
Nixon felt Baker's questioning was too soft on White House counsel
John Dean and too harsh on Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon vowed revenge against Baker. ``He'll never be in the White
House again...never, never, never, never,`` Nixon rants on the
tapes. ``He will never be on a presidential plane again...he owes a
great deal to all of us...we've done favors for him. He's not gonna
get away with this now...cut him off. Give him a big freeze...''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon resigned after the House Judiciary Committee recommended
his impeachment. Baker was eventually welcomed back to the White
House after all, as Ronald Reagan's chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   William Fulbright, Senate Foreign Relations Committee chairman,
was among the very first Democrats to protest the Vietnam war _ and
was the most persistent and most influential senatorial critic. He
held crucial hearings into the war's escalation in February 1966,
only seven months after President Lyndon B. Johnson made the major
commitment that foreclosed easy retreat by increasing U.S. combat
troops from 75,000 to 125,000 men.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and Fulbright were long-time buddies and political
allies, as were Clinton and Lieberman. Fulbright originally
supported the war but as it spread and consumed American lives he
concluded that ``we don't belong there'' _ a conclusion Johnson
himself would reach, too late.
</P>
<P>
   Fulbright kept pressing Johnson for peace initiatives, alone at
first but ultimately backed by a majority of both the public and
the politicians. Johnson was furious, calling Fulbright a ``cry
baby'' and complaining that `it's easier to satisfy Ho Chi Minh
than Bill Fulbright.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, after the war ended, Fulbright was accused of devoting
more time to foreign affairs than local problems and was defeated
for re-election in the Democratic primary by Gov. Dale Bumpers.
</P>
<P>
   Reaching back to 1950, we find Margaret Chase Smith making her
first major speech on the Senate floor decrying the anti-Communist
witchhunting tactics of Sen. Joseph McCarthy. She was right about
McCarthy's assault upon individual civil rights but ahead of her
time.
</P>
<P>
   Not until 1954 did McCarthy's subcommittee hold the raucous
hearings into fantasized communist ties of Army officials that
provoked President Dwight D. Eisenhower to finally speak out
against McCarthy. The Senate then condemned him for behavior
``contrary to senatorial traditions.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, the first woman to serve in both chambers of Congress,
was initially elected to the House in 1944 to fill a vacancy caused
by her husband's death, just about the only path to power for a
woman in that era. She was elected to the Senate four years later.
In 1964 she became the first woman to be nominated for president by
a major party, receiving 27 votes at a GOP convention that gave the
nod to Sen. Barry Goldwater.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
