<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4033 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BERNARDIN-BOOK-REVIEW     09-08 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERNARDIN-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LE BERNARDIN: A TALE OUT OF BRITTANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Le Bernardin has dazzled New York and changed the way Americans
think about fish since the day it opened in the winter of 1986. The
restaurant's achievement came not just from talent in the kitchen
or the dining room. It took an unusual brother-sister act.
</P>
<P>
   In the introduction to ``Le Bernardin Cookbook: Four Star
Simplicity'' by Maguy Le Coze and Eric Ripert (Doubleday, $30), Ms.
Le Coze, who founded the restaurant with her brother, Gilbert,
tells the trans-Atlantic tale of how Le Bernardin came to be in
vivid, often surprisingly intimate terms.
</P>
<P>
   It is a story that pays tender homage to the spirit of Le Coze,
who died in 1994 at age 49. He and Maguy, who grew up working in
the family's restaurant and hotel in Brittany, were always close.
</P>
<P>
   They eventually escaped their provincial hometown and their
stern, demanding father to make their way, successfully, in Paris,
and eventually in New York. Ms. Le Coze recalls that as children
just after World War II, she and her brother were often sent to eat
at a neighbor's house when her parents were busy.
</P>
<P>
   They hated it, because the soup and main course were eaten from
the same bowl, then the bowl was flipped over to use the bottom for
dessert. As much as the children loved dessert, they refused to eat
it.
</P>
<P>
   After the sudden death of her alter ego, Ms. Le Coze was able to
continue in business and to keep the four-star flag whipping
triumphantly in the breeze, largely because of the bond that had
developed between Le Coze and Ripert, who joined the restaurant in
1991 as executive chef.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, Ripert enters the picture when it's time to cook.
Useful advice about buying and handling seafood and other
ingredients is followed by a wealth of recipes, most of which are
explained by a bit of written dialogue between Ms. Le Coze and
Ripert.
</P>
<P>
   For example, both reminisce about their childhoods when
discussing a pot-au-feu made with red snapper, and they talk about
how every day at noon, they scarf down toasted bread slathered with
the restaurant's fresh and smoked salmon spread.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the recipes serve four, and many require two large
10-inch skillets or saucepans to prepare. The recipes are easily
divided to serve two, but harder to increase. Because these are
restaurant recipes, they often call for popping something into a
very hot oven for just a minute, a technique familiar to few home
cooks.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the restaurant's tricks, like sprinkling salt, herbs and
lemon juice from several inches above the plate to apply them more
evenly, are revealed. And I was very happy to learn that it was
necessary to butter the bowl when preparing the utterly delicious
sea scallops in chive nage, so that the slices of sea scallops
don't stick to the bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The recipes include the restaurant's classics, like the halibut
in warm vinaigrette, the fricassee of shellfish and the monkfish
with savoy cabbage, as well as some of Ripert's own inspirations,
like grouper with spiced zucchini and red pepper confit.
</P>
<P>
   I tried a number of recipes, both simple, like the irresistible
shrimp broiled with garlic butter, and complex, like the pistou
vegetable soup with mussels.
</P>
<P>
   The only flaw I found in those I tried was the reference to a
sauce in step 4 of the pan-roasted salmon with red wine-lentil
sauce. The only liquid in the recipe was drained from the cooked
lentils. It was thin, and there was far too much of it. So I
reduced it, swirled in some of the butter intended to dress the
lentils, and I had a fine red wine sauce.
</P>
<P>
   There are also plenty of desserts, including a simple bitter
chocolate souffle cake, and the famous variations on caramel, a
signature dessert of Le Bernardin. But Ms. Le Coze has some advice
for readers: ``It's a pain in the neck to make, as you can see. My
suggestion is, don't do it.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FRESH AND SMOKED SALMON SPREAD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 2 hours &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 bottle dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   2 ablespoons chopped shallots
</P>
<P>
   1 easpoon fine sea salt, plus more to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds fresh salmon fillet, fat trimmed, cut in 1-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces smoked salmon, fat trimmed, cut into tiny dice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons thinly sliced fresh chives
</P>
<P>
   \ cup fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 cup mayonnaise, homemade or prepared
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon freshly ground white pepper
</P>
<P>
   Toasted baguette slices, for serving. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Place wine, shallots and 1 teaspoon of the salt in a large
saucepan, and bring to a boil. Add the fresh salmon, and poach for
40 seconds. Drain in a sieve, and run cold water over the fish just
to stop the cooking. Drain well, and refrigerate until cold, at
least 1{ hours. Discard the poaching liquid.
</P>
<P>
   2. Place smoked salmon in a large bowl, and stir in the chives.
Add the poached salmon, and use the side of a wooden spoon to shred
the salmon as you mix. Stir in the lemon juice, mayonnaise and
pepper. Add sea salt to taste.
</P>
<P>
   3. Refrigerate up to 6 hours, then serve with toasted baguettes.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 cups, 8 to 12 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
