<SLUG> BC-WINE-TASTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINE TASTINGS: HINTS OF MELON 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   McDowell Valley Vineyards Marsanne 1997, Mendocino County,
Calif. About $16.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, McDowell Valley Vineyards discovered that a
longstanding block of petite sirah in its vineyards was the real
thing, syrah. Since then, McDowell has concentrated more and more
on grapes of the Rhone Valley, including a plot of marsanne.
</P>
<P>
   Marsanne is a rather overwhelming grape in France, where it
produces white St.-Joseph and white Crozes-Hermitage. And along
with its more refined cousin, roussanne, it is an important
constituent in Hermitage Blanc. In California, while still a
full-bodied wine, marsanne is less aggressive and more perfumed. It
conveys a taste of melons and makes an interesting pairing with
strong-flavored fish and with Chinese and Thai dishes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
