<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4046 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALAMO-DIARY-TEX     09-08 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALAMO-DIARY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS MAY LOSE TREASURED ALAMO DIARY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Texas history buffs are worried that a Mexican officer's
myth-shattering account of Davy Crockett's capture and execution
after the battle of the Alamo may fall into the hands of a dreaded
Yankee.
</P>
<P>
   The diary, which has been privately owned by Texans since 1974,
will be auctioned Nov. 18 in California. It's expected to fetch
$250,000 to $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just afraid it will end up in the Bancroft Library in
California or, worse yet, at Yale,'' complained Stephen L. Hardin,
author of ``Texian Iliad'' and a professor at Victoria College. ``I
don't want the Yankees to have it.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter where the diary ends up, a debate over its
authenticity is likely to continue.
</P>
<P>
   Crockett's diehard fans have denounced it as a 20th century
forgery, an elaborate hoax that disputes their belief that the
coonskin-capped frontiersman went down fighting at the Alamo in
March 1836.
</P>
<P>
   But many academics accept it as a circa 1840 narrative penned or
dictated in Mexico City's Inquisition Prison by Lt. Col. Jose
Enrique de la Pena, who was jailed for backing the wrong
general-politician after the Texas War of Independence.
</P>
<P>
   Only a page of the diary is devoted to Crockett's demise; the
rest of the 200 pages detail de la Pena's complaints about his
superiors' incompetence and cruelty during the war.
</P>
<P>
   But it is that one page that most interests many Texans.
</P>
<P>
   According to de la Pena, Crockett and six others were captured
after the Alamo ``skirmish'' and brought before Gen. Antonio Lopez
de Santa Anna, who immediately ordered them executed. When a unit
of engineers didn't budge, officers aiming to please the general
moved in and hacked the seven to death.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thrust themselves forward, in order to flatter their
commander, and with swords in hand, fell upon these unfortunate,
defenseless men just as a tiger leaps upon his prey,'' the account
says. ``Though tortured before they were killed, these unfortunates
died without complaining and without humiliating themselves before
their torturers.''
</P>
<P>
   The controversial diary has been held until recently at the
University of Texas at San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really hope the document stays in Texas,'' said Hardin, a
Texas history specialist who earned his doctorate at Texas
Christian University in Fort Worth. ``I think it's vitally
important. It's part of our history.''
</P>
<P>
   The papers are owned by Ruby Peace, 74, whose late husband,
former state Democratic Party chairman James Peace, bought them
from a Mexico City rare coin dealer in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're selling it for the money, first of all,'' said her son,
James Peace III, a San Antonio bookseller. ``We'd have been more
receptive to keeping it here, but for all the people calling,
coming by. I've been interviewed about 10 times, been on the BBC.
It's fine for a while, but it's not my avocation to be a Davy
Crockett buff.''
</P>
<P>
   The first report of the diary was in 1955 when a Mexico City
coin dealer, Jesus Sanchez Garza, issued a small Spanish-language
edition, ``La Rebelion de Texas.'' It made few ripples until Texas
A&AMP;M University Press published a 1975 English translation, ``With
Santa Anna in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Another A&AMP;M book based on the diary, the 1978 ``How Did Davy
Die?'' by Dan Kilgore, raised the emotional temperature, leading to
hyperbolic denunciations of the late author as a hero-destroying
communist.
</P>
<P>
   Also spawned was an entire book aimed at exposing the account as
a fraud, the 1994 ``Defense of a Legend: Crockett and the de la
Pena Diary'' by Bill Groneman, a New York City Fire Department
captain and respected Alamo researcher.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as March, CBS-TV anchor and native Texan Dan Rather
criticized a New York Times book reviewer for not seeing de la
Pena's motives as self-serving.
</P>
<P>
   But Groneman concedes that university historians overwhelmingly
accept the diary as real. Only a handful of independent researchers
such as Groneman still question it for lack of ``provenance,'' or
record of ownership, before 1955 and for using 20th century terms
like ``crimes against humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   James Crisp, a North Carolina State University historian who
wrote the introduction to the latest edition of ``With Santa
Anna,'' counts himself among the believers. Yet even he would feel
more assured if costly forensics tests determined just when the ink
was applied to the paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those of us who believe the diary is authentic would be
vindicated,'' Crisp said from Raleigh, N.C. ``We would welcome the
tests.''
</P>
<P>
   No need, says Greg Shaw, director of books and manuscripts at
Butterfield &AMP; Butterfield, which will auction the papers.
</P>
<P>
   Several experts, and his firm, agree that it is real, Shaw said
from Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hardin said $250,000 is a lot for papers with a
questionable pedigree.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is important stuff,'' he said. ``Let's not mess around.
For the money they're asking, before I'd allow my institution to
drop that kind of coin, it should make ... sure it's tested.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
