<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEQUILA-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEQUILA, AN OLD SPIRIT, GETS NEW RESPECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEQUILA, Mexico _ Was it a mirage? In the sultry 95-degree heat,
the fields shimmered along the highway leading west from
Guadalajara, as if the hazy blue sky had tumbled to the earth and
splashed over the hillsides.
</P>
<P>
   But the fields really WERE blue, covered with acres of steely
agave plants, the raw ingredient for one of the world's most
complex spirits _ tequila.
</P>
<P>
   In the Mexican state of Jalisco, the area from the Pacific coast
to the central highlands is tequila country. Like France's cognac,
Mexico's national spirit is also named for a place, the easy-going
colonial town of Tequila, about 30 miles from Guadalajara. All
around it are vast fields of blue agave, a primitive-looking, hardy
succulent that has been rooted in the volcanic soil of the region
for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Even today, the world's entire supply of genuine tequila is
still made from the agave grown in Jalisco (pronounced ha-LEE-sko)
and in a few villages in some nearby states. And fine tequila _ the
herbaceous, subtly sweet, spicy spirit that is finding new
aficionados by the minute _ can be distilled from the juice of the
fine-grained cores, or hearts, of only one kind of agave: the blue
agave, or agave azul.
</P>
<P>
   This is tequila meant for sipping and savoring, instead of
downing as shots at beach bars. Many of the nearly 100 labels of
premium tequila are now available in stores for $10 to $100 and are
displayed in restaurants. The finest tequilas, meant for brandy
snifters, not blender drinks, are listed along with single-malt
scotches and rare cognacs in top restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our tequila sales are way up at Mesa Grill,'' Laurence
Kretchmer said, referring to his restaurant in Manhattan, on lower
Fifth Avenue. ``People still order Cuervo Gold, but they're
starting to understand that there are better tequilas out there,''
added Kretchmer, the author of ``The Mesa Grill Guide to Tequila''
(Black Dog and Leventhal Publishers, 1998).
</P>
<P>
   Cuervo Gold, the colloquial name for Jose Cuervo's Cuervo
Especial, may be the world's most popular tequila, but it is tinted
with caramel and, more importantly, is not 100 percent blue agave.
And in tequila these days, the only passing grade is 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A spirit made from agave was first mentioned in the writings of
Spanish monks in 1621. But long before then, the Aztecs knew that
by hacking off the spiky leaves of the agave plant, they could
expose the core and press the juice from it to make a mildly
alcoholic elixir. Pulque, a milky fermented homemade drink, is
similar.
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish took the process one step further. They learned how
to distill alcohol from the Arabs, the inventors of distillation,
and introduced the technique in Mexico in the 16th century. A new
and highly intoxicating use was found for agave, which already went
into everything from roofing for houses to needles and thread.
</P>
<P>
   No one has figured out how to use machines to harvest agaves,
some of them five-foot-high sunbursts of spikes. Field hands called
jimadores, who know which ones are ready by color, pick them year
round.
</P>
<P>
   Using a coa, a handmade, razor-sharp, rounded blade attached to
a long pole, the jimador slashes off the leaves to expose the
large, pineapple-like core, called a pina, which can weigh from 20
to 100 pounds. Like many jimadores, Ismael Gama, who has worked for
Jose Cuervo for 27 years, is training his son to be a jimador.
</P>
<P>
   In the town of Tequila and in nearby villages, producers like
Jose Cuervo and Herradura cook the starchy white pinas for at least
a day with steam in brick or concrete ovens that can hold 50 tons,
instead of in modern stainless-steel autoclaves. At La Rojena, the
elegant hacienda-like Cuervo distillery, founded more than 200
years ago, workers called horneros still carry the heavy pinas,
each split in half, on their heads to the ovens, or hornos.
</P>
<P>
   Once the pinas have been cooked, they turn deep amber and take
on a soft texture and candylike sweetness hinting of ginger and
citrus. Then they are crushed: the juice, called aguamiel, or honey
water, is separated from the pulp, fermented and then distilled
twice, usually in copper alembics, or pot stills. Tequilas are
often distilled at 110 proof, or 55 percent alcohol by volume, and
then diluted with water.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the spirit is made into one of four types of
tequila:
</P>
<P>
   _ Silver, sometimes called blanco (white), is unaged, clear
tequila. Many connoisseurs prefer it because it has the most
straightforward agave flavor, herbaceous with nuances of citrus,
sweetness and spice. The bright taste of a good silver tequila
makes it the best for mixed drinks. In tequila country, Mexicans
mix it with a lemon-lime soda called Squirt. Fine 100 percent blue
agave silver tequila is delicious chilled and sipped straight up,
like vodka, or on the rocks with a splash of fresh lime.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gold tequila is merely unaged tequila tinted with caramel. Use
it in mixed drinks.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reposado, or rested tequila, is usually a pale straw color
and, by Mexican law, is aged from 2 to 12 months. It is usually
slightly mellower than silver tequila. Some prefer it for cocktails
because the flavor is usually less assertive.
</P>
<P>
   _ Finally, anejo, or aged tequila, which is held in wood
barrels, sometimes French oak, for more than a year, is gold to
amber and usually has a softer, vanilla-tinged flavor that evokes
cognac or armagnac. Anejo is the tequila to sip after dinner. Some
anejos have their color intensified with caramel. Tequila aged for
more than four years tends to lose flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Any of these tequilas can be 100 percent blue agave _ and that
is the best indication of good quality. Mexican law permits tequila
to contain as much as 49 percent sugar (cane sugar is most common).
This ``mixto'' tequila accounts for 80 percent of Mexico's total
annual production of more than 100 million liters, even though the
production of 100 percent blue agave tequila has increased by 20
percent since 1995, according to ``The Book of Tequila'' by Bob
Emmons (Open Court Publishing, 1997).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The label on a bottle of tequila gives at least as much
information as one on a bottle of wine. Here is an example.
</P>
<P>
   TEQUILA: The type of spirit.
</P>
<P>
   RESERVA DE DON JULIO: The brand name.
</P>
<P>
   40 PERCENT ALC./VOL.: The proof; most tequilas sold in the
United States are 80 proof, or 40 percent alcohol by volume.
</P>
<P>
   750 ML: The size of the bottle.
</P>
<P>
   SILVER: The type of tequila. Silver is unaged, clear tequila.
(Gold is unaged tequila tinted with caramel; reposado is aged from
2 to 12 months; anejo is aged in wood for a year or more.)
</P>
<P>
   100 PERCENT BLUE AGAVE: The fact that the tequila was made only
of blue agave; it is the best indication that it is good quality.
(Mixto tequilas are a blend of blue agave and as much as 49 percent
sugar, usually distilled cane sugar.)
</P>
<P>
   NOM 1118: The distillery registration number, which tells which
of the more than 300 distilleries registered by the Mexican
government produced it.
</P>
<P>
   CRT: Production supervised by Consejo Regulador del Tequila
(Tequila Regulatory Council).
</P>
<P>
   DO 84: The denomination of origin number (sometimes called DOT,
denomination of origin tequila), assigned by the Mexican
government, which shows that the tequila was made according to
Mexican regulations and bottled in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCED AND BOTTLED UNDER SUPERVISION OF THE MEXICAN
GOVERNMENT: Because this is a 100 percent blue agave tequila, it
had to be bottled in Mexico, by law.
</P>
<P>
   TEQUILA TRES MAGUEYES, ETC.: The name of the manufacturer and
its address.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCT OF MEXICO: In the United States and in Europe, anything
called tequila must have been produced in Mexico, according to
trade agreements.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
