<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATIN-ROCK-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATIN AMERICAN ROCK GETS ITS GREEN CARD  
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (Repeating for all needing.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISA VALDES-RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Commerce with Latin America, the darling emerging market helped
along by NAFTA, is predicted to dwarf trade with Europe and Asia
combined within 15 years. We give them McDonald's and Windows, they
give us sugar, coffee, bananas, and . . . rock and roll. Say what?
</P>
<P>
   For years, the United States has tossed the cultural Frisbee of
rock music south of the border, cultivating large followings in
places like Mexico City, where a Black Sabbath concert recently
drew thousands of Mexi-metalheads.
</P>
<P>
   That's to be expected. The world's citizens love American rock.
But nowhere do they love it more than in Latin America, where
they've turned it into a boomerang.
</P>
<P>
   Starting about 10 years ago, Latin American rock bands began
hurling their rock back at America -- bigger, brighter, and better,
in many cases. This wasn't the syrupy Spanish pap we were used to
avoiding on AM radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   This was rock: hard-core, complex, virtuosic, experimental. The
lyrics spoke of political and social movements that made Kurt
Cobain's troubles look bo-ring. Where American rock seemed mired in
selfish suburban angst, Latin rock seemed outwardly political,
angry, and pumped. It came out sounding real, and Americans,
especially second- and third-generation Latinos longing for sounds
to define their experience, embraced it.
</P>
<P>
   The rock en espanol movement comes to Boston next week in full
force as two of the hottest acts take to area stages. The Mexican
band Mana (mah-NAH), the top-selling Latin rock band in the world,
originally was to play the Roxy, but is now booked at the larger
Avalon for Wednesday, as part of its 36-city American tour.
Newcomer Bloque (BLO-kay), a Colombian band that describes its own
music as ``psychotropical funk,'' plays tonight at the House of
Blues in Harvard Square and Sept. 19 at the Middle East Cafe in
Central Square, Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   Domestic sales of rock en espanol have increased fivefold in
just five years, according to Maribel Shumacher, vice president of
Warner Music's Latin American division. She credits changing
demographics and boredom with the usual American rock for this.
Tracking sales proves difficult, because organizations such as
Soundscan have not traditionally paid attention to the genre.
Shumacher's claims, however, are backed by preliminary numbers from
the Recording Industry Association of America, and by the creation
of the Latin rock/alternative category for the Grammy Awards last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Shumacher oversaw one of the first Latin rock tour in the States
in 1988, and says interest was minimal. But since that time, it has
become the music of choice for many Americans craving something new
-- and not just Latinos.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Stern -- notoriously critical of Mexican music when
Selena died -- recently featured the Mexican rock-rap group Molotov
(sort of the Mexican Beastie Boys) on his show. Accused by a
conservative Mexican newspaper of ``polluting Mexico'' with its
``harmful and offensive . . . nasty musical production,'' the
controversial Molotov was a natural for Stern.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, many compare America's blossoming affair with rock en
espanol to the British invasion, when bands like the Beatles and
the Rolling Stones dominated the American music scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a commercial standpoint, it's comparable to the British
invasion of the '60s,'' Shumacher said. ``Why? Because people want
to hear something new and fresh. It's fascinating. I'm going to be
bullish about this, but that's because I'm in the thick of it, and
I know. I was at Mana's show in LA a couple of weeks ago, I was
incredibly impressed because it was the first time I saw a 70-30
breakdown. Thirty percent were Anglos -- I mean real Anglos.
</P>
<P>
   What does that say to me? That this stuff is crossing over. It's
slowly catching on.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if there could ever really be a mainstream crossover of
music in a language most Americans can't understand, Shumacher was
prepared with an answer: ``Let me ask you this. Do you enjoy
instrumental music? Do you understand more than half of the words
Green Day sing? No. But do you get the general meaning? Yes. I
mean, I love Alanis Morissette, but I don't understand 50 percent
of what she says. And it doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at some of the artists:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
MANA
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the forefront of the rock en espanol movement is Mana, a
quartet from Mexico with a leonine lead singer named Fehr, whose
vocals are sometimes uncomfortably similar to Sting's. (Don't tell
Fehr. The comparison really upsets him.) Mana's music is melodic,
and draws on Mexican folk music and reggae as often as on the
Police. The group's lyrics speak of social problems such as teen
pregnancy and drug addiction. The band has used earnings to start
its own environmental watchdog group, Selva Negra (Black Forest).
Mana is credited with starting the Latin rock movement. Though
other groups, like heavy metal group Enanitos Verdes and Miguel
Mateos, both from Argentina, have been around since the early
1980s, Mana was the first Latin rock band to land an album on the
Billboard Top 200, where last year's ``Suenos Liquidos'' debuted at
No. 67. It has been certified gold twice in the States, selling
more than 500,000 copies. A previous album, ``Cuando Los Angeles
Lloran,'' also went gold in 1995, and was nominated for a Grammy in
the Spanish pop category; this was before the Latin rock category
was added.
</P>
<P>
   Internationally, Mana has sold more than 10 million records.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
BLOQUE
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bloque is the newest band on the scene; its debut album will not
be in stores until October. Made up of members of Carlos Vives's
Colombian band, Bloque released an announcement explaining that its
music is ``the result of something unique . . . searching.
Searching the garbage can where all Colombian music has been thrown
away for decades . . . Our music fills the immense black hole that
was created by the media revolution in the '60s . . .
</P>
<P>
   while Colombian people were busy trying to learn to dance to the
sound of the (expletive) Beach Boys.''
</P>
<P>
   The resulting music -- political, angry, danceable, brilliant --
is unlike anything yet recorded in the rock genre, a fact that got
the attention of David Byrne, who signed the group to his Luaka Bop
label.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
LOS FABULOSOS CADILLACS &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Buenos Aires band Los Fabulosos Cadillacs last year was the
first band to win the Grammy in the Latin rock/alternative
category. Some say their album, ``Fabulosos Calaveras,'' won
because Mana's ``Suenos Liquidos'' came out two weeks too late to
be considered. But the band's horn-heavy ska-punk could have won
regardless. After all, no one in rock has a high, trembling voice
as imploring as that of lead singer and accordionist Gabriel
``Vincentio'' Fernandez Capello.
</P>
<P>
   Bostonians who frequent Euro clubs will recognize Los Fabulosos
Cadillacs from their hit ``Matador,'' a dancy anthem about Victor
Jara, a young Chilean folk singer who was murdered in a military
coup in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   The Cadillacs, who won an MTV Video Music Award in 1995, have
collaborated with artists from Ruben Blades to Debbie Harry. Spin
magazine said flatly that the Cadillacs were changing ``the future
of rock 'n' roll'' and Rolling Stone has called them ``rock en
espanol's most viable crossover dream.'' They toured this year with
the neo-swing band Cherry Poppin' Daddies.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
