<SLUG> BC-GREECE-ARMENIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMENIAN TREASURES: WHEN ART BECOMES A METAPHOR FOR IDENTITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Greece _ The art of the past is forever being
reinterpreted in terms of the politics of the present. The most
distinctive Armenian sculptures, for example, are heavy stone
crosses called khatchkars. The Armenians, having been driven away
or massacred by the Seljuk Turks, the Turkomans, the Arabs and
others on and off since ancient times, developed khatchkars partly
as a way to leave their mark in the land. Khatchkars are not easily
moved. They suggest the enduring presence of the Christian faith in
Armenia, even in the absence of the Armenians who erected them.
</P>
<P>
   So khatchkars are political symbols. Can they be interpreted in
other ways as well? Obviously, though politics seemed an inevitable
issue in the context of a big and excellent exhibition that was
here recently. Efi Andreadi, who organized the exhibition,
``Treasures of Armenia,'' explained that it was partly because
Greeks and Armenians share a traditional enemy in the Turks that
Armenian officials were inclined to lend to the show in the first
place.
</P>
<P>
   Was the exhibition therefore primarily meant to be a political
statement? No, Mrs. Andreadi insisted, but she did put a certain
spin on the art when she wrote in the preface to the show's catalog
about the Armenians, ``a people of diaspora,'' making, in addition
to khatchkars, small decorative objects ``which in every war,
persecution or exodus could be easily transported and saved from
the hands of the infidels.''
</P>
<P>
   And even if she hadn't said so, the inclination would have been
to see these works through that lens, simply because the show took
place here, meaning not just in Athens but in the arts center
called the Megaron, which itself can be regarded as a local
political symbol.
</P>
<P>
   Art doesn't exist in a vacuum. It can be used to serve almost
any agenda. Caspar David Friedrich's paintings from the early 19th
century came to be linked during the early 20th with a distasteful
sort of German nationalism because they were admired by the Nazis.
Views of Friedrich changed accordingly. Shakespeare's plays were
mainstream entertainment in the 19th century in America, until a
new educated class made them into the theatrical equivalent of
spinach. Today we regard as highbrow what was once presented in the
context of of minstrel shows and magic acts: the perception of
Shakespeare's work has changed along with the context in which it
is performed.
</P>
<P>
   Context often means, more specifically, political context. This
being Greece, an obvious example is the Elgin marbles. Tourist
dollars aside, the Greeks have long said that they want the marbles
back to reunite the Parthenon sculptures on the site where they
came from. This is a matter of artistic integrity but, equally, a
matter of national identity, the Parthenon being the prime emblem
of Greek nationalism. The two ideas, artistic integrity and
national identity, are inextricably linked by the Greeks.
</P>
<P>
   The British have made a similar argument: they point out not
only that they have better preserved the sculptures over the years
than the Greeks, but also that the sculptures have reshaped British
society since the 18th century, fueling a revival of interest in
Classical antiquity that, among other things, even alerted the
Greeks to the value of their own past. Hence the marbles are now
just as integral to British culture and history as they are to
Greek patrimony.
</P>
<P>
   With the show of Armenian art, the Megaron, as the site, helped
to shape a certain kind of interpretation. It is a place where
Greece's recent Spartan past has been replaced by an Athenian
present: construction began on the Megaron decades ago, but stopped
when a junta took control of the country in the late 1960s. The
military commandeered the site for army barracks, then stayed even
after the junta lost power in the mid-'70s. Finally, the barracks
were torn down, and the Megaron was completed several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It has become a sign of the city's cultural aspirations. It is
Athens' version of New York's Lincoln Center, a performing arts
complex, but unlike Lincoln Center it also has an exhibition
program that seems unusually ambitious, considering that Mrs.
Andreadi must make do with a makeshift exhibition space.
``Treasures of Armenia,'' with more than 100 objects, was a major
installment in a series of shows she is planning about the
Byzantine world to be held more or less in the Megaron's lobby.
</P>
<P>
   A large concert hall and a smaller one occupy much of the
building. The plan is to create more performing spaces and
conference rooms (money is raised by renting the place for
conventions) and a bigger music library. There wasn't a decent
music library in this entire region of the Mediterranean world
until the Megaron assembled one from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   Athenians will tell you that the Megaron has entirely changed
the local cultural scene. Major orchestras used to come to Athens,
if at all, for an outdoor festival that took place once a year.
Today because of the Megaron Athens is on the circuit of European
cultural capitals, reflecting, perhaps, on a small scale, Greece's
larger desire to be an equal partner with the bigger nations in the
European Union.
</P>
<P>
   The Megaron, in other words, at least to a visitor, seems a
discreet emblem of a wider effort to impress on the world an image
of Athens as a major capital prepared for the spotlight of the
Summer Olympics in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   In the Armenian exhibition, Mrs. Andreadi made a point of the
fact that, along with khatchkars, medieval ecclesiastical
architecture is at the core of Armenian civilization and identity.
Traditional Armenian churches are thick-walled stone buildings with
a central dome, their outlines usually tall and compressed. A few
stone models of the churches, which were made to decorate the
churches themselves, were in the show.
</P>
<P>
   It is commonly claimed that these churches derive their shape
from Mount Ararat, Mrs. Andreadi said. Later I happened to come
across this passage in ``The Crossing Place: A Journey Among the
Armenians,'' by Philip Marsden:
</P>
<P>
   ``Ararat echoes around things Armenian like a persistent
refrain. It is the name of Armenian journals, Armenian books,
Armenian businesses and restaurants. In the United States there is
an Armenian credit card called Ararat, as is an Armenian nursing
home in California. The national football team is called Ararat.''
</P>
<P>
   Its particular importance, Marsden added, is as a political
symbol of exile, ``staring as it now does into Armenia from across
the Turkish border.''
</P>
<P>
   (This is the last article in a series about how different
cultures interpret and make use of the art of the past. The first
article examined restoration efforts in the old city, or medina, of
Fez, Morocco. The second article discussed the restoration of the
minbar, or pulpit, of the Kutubiyya mosque in Marrakesh.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
