<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATIN-ROCK-2ND </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SORAYA 

</HEADLINE>
   TAKE-BOS  
 (Repeating for all needing.)  
 UNDATED: ... Poppin' Daddies.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A brooding young Colombian guitarist, composer, and singer now
known only by her first name, Soraya is marketed as a Colombian
act. She is a powerful songwriter with introspective, poetic
lyrics, and her acoustic folk-rock sound is something like a
melding of Sarah McLachlan, Bonnie Raitt, and Carole King. Her most
recent album, ``Wall of Smiles'' has been compared with King's
``Tapestry.'' Unlike many Latin rock acts, Soraya has chosen to
release her albums in Spanish and English, making her popular in
England and Germany, and landing her English singles on US rock
radio. Her songs have even been piped over speakers in a Pizzeria
Uno in Dedham. If the Lilith Fair ever sees fit to add a Latina
act, this would be the one.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
CAFE TACUBA &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Mexico's Cafe Tacuba made headlines from the New York
Times to Newsweek when it performed in Central Park. Observed
Newsweek: ``a whole world of music crammed onto one stage . . .
what held this glorious mishmash together was a single, driving
principle: Cafe Tacuba rocked.'' The Miami Herald has called Tacuba
``one of the best bands in rock, period.'' It's true.
</P>
<P>
   This group has mastered the American alternative and hip hop
idioms, and remains fearless about folding in lounge, polka, funk,
and Latin American classics such as ``Ojala Que Llueva Cafe,'' a
merengue made famous by Dominican composer and singer Juan Luis
Guerra. It reached a wider audience in 1992 by playing at the Los
Angeles ``Lollapalooza'' and this year opened for Santana.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
SHAKIRA  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like Soraya, Shakira is a one-name singer, composer, and
guitarist from Colombia. But that's where the similarities end.
</P>
<P>
   Shakira (Isabel Mebarak Ripoll), 21, has been recording
professionally since she was 13. At 19, Shakira released ``Piez
Descalzos,'' an album of sophisticated and mature pop rock songs
reminiscent of Natalie Merchant; it went platinum in Mexico,
Colombia, the States, and Venezuela, selling 900,000 copies in
Brazil alone. Her anguished alto moves across octaves in the style
of Sinead O'Connor and Alanis Morissette, without being as
annoying. Her guitar-playing is deft and determined, and her
compositions experiment with rhythms from Latin America and the
Middle East (her father is Lebanese).
</P>
<P>
   Because of her celebrity, Colombia declared her a goodwill
ambassador to the Vatican, where she met Pope John Paul this year.
He received her warmly, in spite of the lyrics of her song ``Se
Quiere, Se Mata,'' about a woman who dies after an illegal
abortion. Shakira's much-awaited new album, ``Donde Estan los
Ladrones?'', was released this month.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
LA LEY  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Led by a 30-year-old singer, Alberto Cuevas, who spent 10 years
in Montreal, La Ley is the first rock band from Chile to make it
big on the rock en espanol scene, and the first to experiment with
hypnotic techno sounds. La Ley comes at rock from the INXS/Duran
Duran school, with a bit of a Depeche Mode sensibility. Cuevas, a
graphic artist who wears black nail polish and designs the band's
album covers, resents his original band being labeled a ``Latin
American act.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be seen as citizens of the universe, and not be
prejudged because we are Latin Americans,'' he said from Santiago,
where he lives. ``I think all Latin rock bands are hoping to do in
America what American music did in Latin America in the '50s. We
didn't know what you were saying, but it didn't matter. The music
spoke for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
LOS ATERCIOPELADOS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the few woman-fronted rock en espanol bands,
Aterciopelados is quickly gaining on groups like Mana and the
Cadillacs. Lead singer Andrea Echiverri is considered by many
critics to be the best singer in the genre, period. With much of
her body pierced and with in-your-face feminist lyrics, Echiverri
has disproved the former industry assumption that there was no room
for women in the machismo world of Latin rock. Watching her
sold-out shows, it's hard to believe that women were literally
booed from Latin rock stages as recently as the early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   From a wealthy Colombian family, Echiverri comes at her
rebellious stance from a debutante's background. Under her lead,
the band was nominated for the Latin rock Grammy last year, along
with four all-male bands. More than any other female artist to
date, Echiverri has revolutionized the rock en espanol revolution.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
MOLOTOV &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wildly popular throughout Latin America, the rock-rap band
sounds a lot like the Beastie Boys -- and about a million other
American copycats. What sets them apart is language -- Spanish --
and culture -- Mexican. With two bassists who rap, the group is
loud, crude, curses a lot, and, when it attempts to rap in English,
shows its heavy imitation of misogynist American faux-gangstas like
Snoop Dog. In the land musically defined by corny balladeers like
Luis Miguel and Alejandro Fernandez -- who still appear onstage in
velvet mariachi outfits -- these nasty boys with the baggy pants
have caused quite a stir, something like the early days of Madonna,
when the Christian Coalition was out in full protest. Interesting
from a historical but not necessarily musical point of view.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
OTHER BANDS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are literally hundreds of rock en espanol bands. Here are
some of them: Madita Vecindad y Los Hijos del Quinto Patio, famous
for its song ``Pachuco,'' is one of the first Mexican bands to
document the downside of urban life in Mexico City; lead singer
Roco howls through lyrics about police brutality; the group has
used its popularity to raise money for Indians in Chiapas. Julieta
Venegas is a classical pianist from Tijuana who took up the
accordion and then made it rock; as the former keyboardist for the
punk band Tijuana No, Venegas has gone solo in a big, feminist way.
She, along with fellow Mexicana rocker Ely Guerra, have begun a
Mexican version of the Lilith Fair, called De Diva Voz (In the
Diva's Voice).
</P>
<P>
   Argentina's Fito Paez is the only singer on the scene doing
moody rock operas, and has been compared to David Bowie. Andres
Calamaro is another Argentine solo artist; he looks like Bob Dylan
with a stylist, and turned a childhood filled with military horrors
into a successful rock career; his new debut album, called ``Alta
Suciedad,'' is a word play on ``high society'' that comes out
meaning ``high trash.'' Argentina's Soda Stereo was a
U2-sound-alike that broke up recently but still has some nice discs
out there; and Todos Tus Muertos is one of Argentina's top
speed-metal slam bands.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be excluded from the rock en espanol roster are acts from
Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Heroes del Silencio is a pure thrash-metal band whose lead
singer sounds like a thundering Satan on speed.
</P>
<P>
   Several American rockers have come out with their own rock en
espanol projects. Lysa Flores is a guitarist and singer from Los
Angeles who dresses like a mariachi girl and proceeds to crank the
distortion and wail like Janis Joplin; her music and acting were
featured in the film ``Star Maps.'' King Chango is one of the
hottest new Latin rock bands, made up of New Yorkers with
Venezuelan roots. Puerto Rico's best-known rocker is former Menudo
member Robi Draco Rosa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
