<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0187 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4135 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-POLL-HNS &LR;      09-08 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-POLL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BI-PARTISAN POLL PAINTS GRIM PICTURE FOR DEMOCRATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A bi-partisan poll released Tuesday shows President
Clinton's conduct in the Monica Lewinsky matter is taking its toll
on Democratic electoral prospects this November.
</P>
<P>
   Respondents to the ``Battleground '98'' survey conducted jointly
by Ed Goeas, a Republican pollster, and Celinda Lake, a Democrat,
said they favored GOP congressional candidates 43 percent to 40
percent. Among those who say they are very likely to vote, the
margin widened, to 45 percent to 37 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A similar poll by Goeas and Lake last December found voters in a
dead heat, with 40 percent in favor of each party.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also contrasts to a poll late last month after
Clinton's Aug. 17 speech in which he acknowledged not telling the
truth for seven months about a sexual relationship with ex-White
House intern Monica Lewinsky. In that poll, issued by the Pew
Research Center for the People &AMP; the Press, 61 percent of
respondents said Clinton's admission will not affect how they vote
in November.
</P>
<P>
   The Goeas and Lake poll Tuesday measured the responses of 1,000
registered voters nationwide and was conducted Aug. 23-25. Although
it avoided specific questions about Clinton's behavior with
Lewinsky, Goeas and Lake said the Lewinsky matter was behind the
unmistakable erosion of support for Clinton and Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democrats are disenchanted, let down,'' Goeas, president of
The Tarrance Group in Alexandria, Va., told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Lake, president of Washington-based Lake Snell Perry &AMP;
Associates, agreed. ``If the election were held today, it would be
bad for Democrats,'' she said. ``I'm worried, but I get paid to be
worried.''
</P>
<P>
   Respondents most enthusiastic about voting this November tended
to be Republican while those caring less were more likely to be
Democratic, the poll showed.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of ``moral values'' rocketed to the top of the list of
problems facing the nation, according to the poll. Fourteen percent
of respondents identified moral and religious issues as the most
serious, equal with crime and drugs. That's 10 points higher than
in the previous Goeas-Lake poll.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-two percent said restoring moral values should be a top
congressional priority. Forty-two percent said Republicans better
represented their values while 35 percent preferred Democrats.
That's an eight-point gain for Republicans since January.
</P>
<P>
   Ominously for Democrats, support among women was a very narrow 4
percent. Women, a key Democratic constituency, preferred Democrats
to Republicans by 43 percent to 39 percent. The poll showed the
balance was tipped heavily by minority-group women, who favor
Democrats over Republicans by 56 percentage points, 74 percent to
18 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans were ahead among several subgroups of women, the
poll showed. White working women, for instance, favored Republicans
by 2 percentage points. Among white women who stay home, the GOP
margin was 18 points.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's personal standing among voters has plummeted, the poll
found. Last December, the two pollsters reported Clinton's personal
approval at 45 percent, with disapproval at 43 percent _ a 2
percent difference in Clinton's favor.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest survey, 26 percent of respondents approved of
Clinton and 62 percent disapproved _ a 36-point gap against
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Goeas predicted a 15-to-20 seat gain for Republicans in the
House and a four-to-six seat gain in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have controlled both chambers since the 1994
election and now have a five-seat margin in the Senate and an
11-seat margin in the House. On Election Day, Nov. 3, all 435 House
seats and 34 Senate seats are up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   For now, momentum is with the GOP, Goeas said. ``If you control
the football, you score,'' he said. ``If you don't, you die.''
</P>
<P>
   Lake said that while the situation is increasingly grim for
Democrats and Clinton, both have cards they can still play.
Clinton, especially when accompanied by First Lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton, continues to be a prime player in raising money and
motivating the Democratic voting base.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic fortunes this November depend on how successful the
party is in framing the debate around such issues as regulating
managed care health plans, preserving Social Security, and
improving public education, Lake said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democrats need to take this poll as a wake-up call,'' she
said. ``They need to devote more resources to energizing the
base.''
</P>
<P>
   A continued focus on the Lewinsky matter could create a backlash
that favors Democrats, she said, adding: ``If the (Democratic)
agenda continues to be drowned out for seven weeks, voters will be
angry.''
</P>
<P>
   After the poll's release, Rep. Martin Frost, D-Texas, chairman
of the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee, said in a
statement: ``We have always anticipated that 1998 would be a
low-turnout year, and we are prepared to perform well in that
setting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
