<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, Sept. 9, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scattered, intermittent showers and a few thundershowers, some
with small hail, will develop over the interior Northeast as a
cold, upper-level low- pressure system forges slowly east over the
region. Many places will start with partial sunshine in the
morning, but, as air in contact with the warming ground rises into
the lofty cold pool later in the morning and afternoon, billowy
cumulus clouds will burgeon, setting the stage for chilly showers
and thundershowers. Temperatures in the 40s are possible while
showers occur in the mountains. Thus, the tenor of the day over the
interior Northeast will be unsettled and cool, with variable clouds
and sporadic showers. Showers will weaken as they move east toward
the Northeast seaboard, but a few may survive to affect coastal
areas, particularly the northeast New England coast.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, scattered showers and thunderstorms will escort a
front across northern Florida. Farther west, a moisture-laden
tropical disturbance will bring the risk of heavy rains to parts of
the Texas and Louisiana seaboards.
</P>
<P>
   Isolated thunderstorms will develop in Montana and Wyoming as a
cool front slices slowly eastward across the northern Rockies.
Widely separated storms will also flare from the Sierra Nevada of
California to the southern Rockies as the uneven heating of
mountains and valleys promotes rising currents of air.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a rapid warm-up will commence in the western high
Plains as air descending the Rockies into the western Dakotas and
western Nebraska is heated by compression.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Wind Damage
</P>
<P>
   An armada of severe thunderstorms raced east across upstate New
York for two hours starting just before midnight on Monday,
inflicting wind damage in a swath nearly 100 miles long and five to
10 miles wide. Maximum gusts were estimated at 100 miles an hour.
Such a long-lived, organized system of gusty thunderstorms is
called a derecho. In the rear of the arc of storms that outline a
derecho, a stream of very fast winds, called a rear inflow jet,
develops and descends from high altitudes into the storms, arming
them with dangerous and damaging gusts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 1738EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4203 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RECLAIMING-NAZI-ART-N     09-08 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECLAIMING-NAZI-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: HONESTY CAN BE TRICKY, THE LOOT-HOLDERS LEARN  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JUDITH H. DOBRZYNSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the last six months, there has been a notable
change in the art world. It has nothing to do with exhibitions or
acquisitions, but rather with the rhetoric surrounding potential
claims for art plundered during World War II that later found its
way, by various routes through dealers and collectors, into
American museums.
</P>
<P>
   Eager to avoid the kind of outcry that enveloped Swiss banks
that dragged their feet before compensating Jews who lost assets
during the war, museums are no longer denying that there might be
problems in their galleries. They are now pledging to resolve
claims quickly, if they arise, using mediation if necessary. And
they are reviewing their collections to identify artworks tainted
by Nazi looting.
</P>
<P>
   But righting the wrongs of history is never easy. And as a
closely watched case in Seattle is demonstrating, returning a
looted painting or providing compensation for its loss can be
tricky and drawn out _ far more so than the return of bank
accounts, gold or insurance payments lost or stolen during the war.
</P>
<P>
   With those assets, large-scale settlements from big companies
are possible. With art, the cases are individual. No one knows how
many potential cases involve American museums. If the handful that
have occurred are any indication, they often pop up unexpectedly
when a family, sometimes after years of looking, locates a lost
work in a catalog or exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   Further complicating matters, the party or parties who stole the
artwork half a century ago and who profited from trading it are
often long gone, while the current owner of a stolen painting, be
it a museum or an individual, probably had nothing to do with the
theft. The idea of a ``universal solution'' involving a pool of
money that would be used to pay claimants, like the one that Swiss
banks recently agreed to establish, seems attractive theoretically.
But it runs into problems because there is no comparable single
source of money for an art fund.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle case involves the heirs of Paul Rosenberg, a Jewish
art dealer who fled Paris for New York to escape the Nazi invasion,
leaving his collection in a bank vault. Last fall his heirs found
``Odalisque,'' a Matisse painting that had been taken from him by
the Nazis, in the Seattle Art Museum, which had been given the work
a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   On July 31, after negotiations to recover the painting failed,
the Rosenbergs took the museum to court. In refusing to give back
the picture, the museum hinted that it wanted to force a
comprehensive solution involving the Manhattan dealer, Knoedler &AMP;
Co., which brought ``Odalisque'' to the United States. So, late
last month, the museum sued Knoedler, which had bought the painting
in 1954 from a Paris dealer, now defunct, and sold it a few months
later to Virginia and Prentice Bloedel, both now dead, who donated
it to the museum.
</P>
<P>
   The museum says that Knoedler committed fraud, negligent
misrepresentation and breach of warranty of title when it sold the
work to the Bloedels. If the museum has to give up the painting, it
wants compensation for its market value, which may be $2 million or
more, even though it did not pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   Knoedler, which has not yet responded formally, said through its
lawyer that it had nothing to do with the museum dispute because
its dealings were all with the Bloedels, not the museum. ``I don't
know of any case where a museum has gone to someone who never dealt
with them and tried to extract money from them,'' said Lewis B.
Clayton of Paul, Weiss, Rifkind, Wharton &AMP; Garrison in Manhattan.
``The only people who could press a claim are the Bloedels.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum, said its lawyer, John A. Reed of Davis Wright &AMP;
Tremaine in Seattle, has standing in the suit as the Bloedels'
successor.
</P>
<P>
   The wrangling is striking because the Rosenberg case is
relatively straightforward and well documented. Among the many
papers supporting the Rosenberg claim are two exhibition catalogs
from 1937 and 1938 recording the painting as the property of Paul
Rosenberg and an official catalog of looted art published by the
French government in 1947 listing him as the owner. The painting's
whereabouts between 1941 and 1954 are unknown, but Rosenberg and
his family searched constantly for ``Odalisque'' and the many other
paintings looted from his collection.
</P>
<P>
   Facing those facts, which the museum says are supported by its
own research into the painting's provenance, the museum does not
deny the Rosenbergs' claim. ``More likely than not, the Rosenbergs
have superior title,'' Reed said. But the museum refuses to return
the painting until it completes its provenance research and, more
important, presses its claim against Knoedler.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's research does suggest potential problems for
Knoedler. For example, its suit against the dealer asserts that a
Knoedler employee told Mrs. Bloedel in 1954 that Matisse, not
Rosenberg, owned the paintings for the 1937 and '38 exhibitions
even though Knoedler had the exhibition catalogs in its possession
at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The museum said it wanted a court to determine the painting's
ownership because it felt that returning the painting voluntarily
might weaken its case against Knoedler. Without a court ruling,
Reed said, ``Knoedler might look at the same information we have
and say you made a mistake when you gave it back voluntarily.''
</P>
<P>
   In one way, at least, the Seattle museum is fortunate: it has a
gallery to sue. Knoedler celebrated its 150th anniversary in 1996,
although it is no longer a family business. (Armand Hammer, the
late financier, bought the company in 1971 and it is now controlled
by his foundation).
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a heck of a lot of galleries are left that did business''
shortly after the war, particularly in European art, said Richard
Gray, the president of the Art Dealers Association of America. The
dealers' organization, whose members are eager to avoid
debilitating legal costs, recently endorsed a policy urging
third-party mediation of wartime art disputes, following the same
recommendation issued in June by the Association of Art Museum
Directors.
</P>
<P>
   But no one has any idea of how to resolve a case fairly when the
culpable party is no longer in business or alive, and when making
things right for one victim creates another.
</P>
<P>
   That is why the idea of establishing a fund to meet such claims
is being floated by a few art experts and Jewish organizations.
Lacking a credible source of money, however, it is an orphan idea.
When the idea of levying a tax on dealers and auction houses, or
their transactions, has come up at symposiums and conferences, it
has not won resounding support from the art trade, with few people
in the business feeling a responsibility for what happened in the
war.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, the most viable suggestion seems to be voluntary
contributions. ``It might be in the interest of the art community _
auction houses, dealers, museums _ to contribute to the solution,''
said Ori Soltes, who recently stepped down as director of the B'nai
B'rith Klutznick National Jewish Museum in Washington. They could
justify ``communal reasons'' for their participation, he argues,
perhaps the way industry groups sometimes pay into a fund to settle
class-action claims.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 1745EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4207 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRANCE-NEW-SEASON-2TA     09-08 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-NEW-SEASON-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECHARGED FOR FALL: IN FRANCE, THEY CALL IT LA RENTREE 
</HEADLINE>
   (for release Sunday, Sept. 13)  
 (bl)  
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ In the wonderfully strict cycles of life that make the
French seem so predictable, la rentree first announces itself each
year as a reason to postpone things.
</P>
<P>
   From early July, there is little that cannot await the return _
la rentree _ to Paris in September. But, take note, this is not a
symptom of laziness. It is simply part of the French order of
things. Parisians hold parties to say goodbye for the summer in the
knowledge that social, cultural, political and business life will
resume with a vengeance a la rentree.
</P>
<P>
   So now, once again, Parisians are back, hurriedly recovering
control of their city from tourists, adding frowns of impatience to
still-bronzed faces, crowding restaurants that felt no need to stay
open in August to serve foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   In every sense, a new season has arrived _ and all of it
meticulously linked to la rentree. The school year has begun (la
rentree scolaire), government and opposition are again squabbling
(la rentree politique), businessmen are back at their desks (la
rentree economique), new art exhibitions and stage productions are
opening (la rentree culturelle) and hundreds of new books are out
(la rentree litteraire).
</P>
<P>
   True, it could be argued that this phenomenon is no longer
exclusive to Paris or even France. Since most inhabitants of Rome,
Madrid, Amsterdam, Munich, London and beyond now also do major
disappearing acts from their cities in the summer, they too return
en masse. And while New Yorkers may still exhibit a touching
mixture of envy and disapproval of Europe's long vacations, ``after
Labor Day'' has taken on a good number of the attributes of ``apres
la rentree.'' Yet Paris remains the benchmark because this is where
it all began.
</P>
<P>
   What began?
</P>
<P>
   Well, there would be no great rentree without a great depart.
And it is this programmed exodus that the French claim as their own
invention. It began in the 1930s with the introduction of the first
guaranteed paid holidays for workers, and by the 1950s ``dead
August'' had become a celebration of the French art de vivre.
</P>
<P>
   Amusingly, when Germans, Britons, Dutch and other northern
Europeans first decided to imitate the French, they too did it a la
francaise, traipsing to the beaches of the Cote d'Azur or wining
and dining in the bucolic villages of Provence. Today, they also
crowd hilltops and resorts in Italy, Spain and Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   Britain appears to be the latest country to institutionalize
``dead August,'' thanks, it seems, to Prime Minister Tony Blair,
who more or less took the phone off the hook at 10 Downing Street
and spent the entire month in Italy and France (although he was
forced return home briefly after the bombing in Omagh, Northern
Ireland, on Aug. 15).
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, he was merely following in the footsteps of
Britain's well-heeled and chattering classes. But London was
emptier than ever. Last month, with his traditional clientele away,
Sir Terence Conran, the design mogul, was offering $16 fixed-menu
lunches or dinners at five of his glitzy restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   It was even possible to get a table without name-dropping at the
Riverside Cafe and the Pharmacy, two of London's most fashionable
eateries. So now even London is creating the conditions for une
rentree.
</P>
<P>
   The world of culture, though, does not rest. Visitors to Paris
still want to visit the Louvre. American tourists in London still
consider West End theaters to be one of the city's main appeals.
Indeed, three musicals _ ``Whistle Down the Wind,'' ``Dr.
Dolittle'' and ``Oklahoma!'' _ opened in London in July.
</P>
<P>
   But even more important, as residents of major European cities
disperse, artists and performers now increasingly accompany them
thanks to the staggering number of music, theater and other
festivals that have grown up in recent years. Salzburg, Bayreuth,
Avignon, Aix-en-Provence, Edinburgh and Glyndebourne may still have
the best known festivals, but the arts are now well entrenched as a
tourist attraction throughout Europe.
</P>
<P>
   London's cultural rentree can in fact be tagged apres Edinburgh.
``Cultural life in Britain is like water in a bath,'' Robert
Hewison, a British cultural historian, explained. ``The water is
usually in London. Then, for three weeks in August and early
September, it all rushes to Edinburgh for television, film, theater
and music festivals. There's no point in opening anything in London
in August. Only the Promenade concerts at the Albert Hall keep
going. But theater life is planned entirely around the autumn
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Spring and summer in Europe and the United States are, of
course, fall and winter in the Southern Hemisphere, which means
that cultural seasons are also upside-down. For instance, the
season at the Teatro Colon, the legendary opera house in Buenos
Aires, runs from April through December, when seemingly the entire
city moves in a French-like depart to the beach at Punta del Este
in neighboring Uruguay. This calendar has its advantages: when
Europe's opera houses are closed, the Colon can draw big names
(Placido Domingo and Mirella Freni sang Giordano's ``Fedora'' there
last month).
</P>
<P>
   In countries where the weather is warm year-round and neither
depart nor rentree is called for, there is often no cultural season
worth mentioning. Could it be that culture was invented by
Europeans in order to get through the winter? Could it be that
winter resorts were invented to enable them to escape cultural
overdose? Still, as surely as colder weather is approaching, the
Northern Hemisphere's cultural program is going into gear.
</P>
<P>
   Paris jump-starts the season faster than some. In Milan, for
instance, the opera season at La Scala traditionally opens early in
December, while the Royal Shakespeare Company only starts its
London season at the Barbican Center in November.
</P>
<P>
   But in Paris, from the Comedie Francaise to the Paris Opera,
from the Musee d'Orsay to the Folies Bergere, cultural life is now
already stirring. And through early December, a fall festival, the
Festival d'Automne a Paris, is presenting productions and
performers from around the world, with China providing this year's
central theme.
</P>
<P>
   As the days grow shorter, much the same thing is happening in
all the major cities of the Northern Hemisphere, from Vienna to
Chicago. New York's version of the fall festival in Paris, for
example, is the Next Wave Festival at the Brooklyn Academy of
Music.
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere, a sort of bidding war breaks out as new plays,
movies, dance and opera productions, art exhibitions and books
compete for people's time and attention. Suddenly everything has to
be squeezed in _ school life, business life, social life and
cultural life. The rush of energy is tangible.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
