<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 TV NOTES: PRIME-TIME McGWIRE; NEW `ROSEANNE'; `SQUIGGLEVISION'  
 (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clobbering Prime Time
</P>
<P>
   Besides knocking away at baseball's most magical record, Roger
Maris' 61 home runs in a season, Mark McGwire managed to wreak
havoc this week on the Fox network's plans to start up a couple of
its most crucial programs in the fall television season.
</P>
<P>
   But for Fox Broadcasting chairman David Hill, the decision was
easy because of the priority all the networks put now on bringing
national events to the public to meet increasing competition from
cable television and other sources. ``Network television has become
all about event-izing programming,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   Fox spent months and millions of dollars promoting the shift of
its animated comedy hit ``King of the Hill'' to Tuesday, and spent
more months and more millions promoting ``Costello,'' the new
sitcom to follow it.
</P>
<P>
   All that planning was wiped out with one McGwire swing Monday,
his No. 61, setting in motion Fox's contingency plan to pre-empt
its prime-time programming last night for McGwire's assault on No.
62.
</P>
<P>
   Goodbye, ``King of the Hill,'' despite the carefully planned
buildup to an episode tying up the cliffhanger that ended last
season (who will be killed in the propane explosion at the
Mega-Lo-Mart?); goodbye, ``Costello,'' although the new show was
reviewed in Tuesday's newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   But Hill emphasized: ``The future of network television has to
be about bringing events of shared community involvement to the
public. What is everyone in the country talking about? What was on
the front page of every newspaper? McGwire and his son.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill said the man in charge of Fox's prime-time schedule, Peter
Roth, was ``100 percent behind the decision'' and pointed to what
every network is doing this fall. ``Look at what NBC is doing with
the Emmy Awards,'' he said. ``They added an hour to the telecast to
make it more of an event.''
</P>
<P>
   He also cited the way CBS made an event out of the National
Football League's return to the network.
</P>
<P>
   Still, because of the focus on ``King of the Hill'' and
``Costello,'' the decision did represent the worst-case scenario
for Fox's planning, Hill said. Weeks ago, he said, the Fox research
department had predicted that McGwire would be close to the record
starting this week.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Fox, which has a contract with major league
baseball for Sunday games on its network and weekday games on its
Fox Sports Channel and F/X cable channels, announced it would
broadcast McGwire's games on the network starting Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But when his home-run pace picked up, Fox was forced to change
its plans. It became a race of sorts with ESPN, the cable network
with the other national contract. ESPN had Monday's record-tying
game. Fox grabbed Tuesday night, with ESPN lined up for Wednesday
night. Fox would come back Thursday only if McGwire failed to
connect again by then.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, Hill said, the record-breaking home run was all Fox
was interested in. ``If he was still at 60 after Monday we would
have kept `King of the Hill' on and left the game on F/X,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   What of ``King of the Hill'' and ``Costello''? Both will begin
their season next week, after a torrent of promotion during last
night's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will probably cost us money,'' Hill said, referring to the
expense of the promotion. ``One never knows what the effect will
be. Trust me, if it's a disaster, I'll have enough people telling
me about it. Someone will come up and say `King of the Hill' didn't
work because we put it on when Jupiter was in the house of Alpha
Centauri.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   A Carnival? No Way.
</P>
<P>
   A haze of mystery has settled around ``The Roseanne Show,''
which arrives Monday as the latest entry in the daytime television
gabfest listings. No one, not even the star herself, has been able
to say exactly what format her new show will follow _ foggery that
is intended to generate curiosity about the show, no doubt, but
that also arose from necessity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will not have a rigid format,'' her producer, Eddie
October, has said, calling it part comedy and part talk show.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a carnival act,'' said Roseanne, adding that it would
serve as ``a beacon of information.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, she will do serious, family-related segments,'' said Andy
Friendly, president of first-run syndication for King World, which
produces the show and has sold it to more than 150 stations around
the country. (In New York, it will be on Channel 4 weekdays at 3
p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   He cited Rosanne's already-taped profile of an organization
called Children of the Night, which helps runaway teen-agers, a
segment that includes interviews with some of the children on her
set. And Dennis Rodman, a guest in the first week, will have a
surprise reunion with the family of a Texas man dragged to death by
a truck, whose funeral expenses Rodman paid.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes segments will mix the serious with the funny, Friendly
said, as in an installment tentatively titled ``Fatapalooza,'' a
spoof on the rock-and-roll tour called ``Lollapaplooza'' in which
fat women will talk about their problems finding attractive
clothes.
</P>
<P>
   The guest list for the first week's shows includes Whoopi
Goldberg; the star of ``Hollywood Squares,'' another new King World
daytime show that also starts on Monday, and Debbie Reynolds. Nora
Dunn, the former ``Saturday Night Live'' comedian, will play a
regular ``character'' on the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the eclectic format,'' Friendly said. ``It's
unpredictable. It really boils down to one word: Roseanne.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
<P>
   It's Got Squiggle Appeal  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It could be the greatest television show on earth, but
apparently having the word science in its title made children avoid
it like, well, science. That's what the programmers at ABC decided
about the zany but also educational show ``Science Court,'' which
is about to start its second season on ABC's top-rated Saturday
morning cartoon lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Created by Tom Snyder, the animation artist for ``Dr. Katz,
Professional Therapist,'' the children's show is drawn in the same
style, too, called Squigglevision, a term Snyder has trademarked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Science Court'' won praise from educators and parents, and
children liked it in focus groups, but its Nielsen ratings were
poor. ``We wanted to put out the biggest welcome mat possible to
kids this season,'' said Jonathan Barzilay, ABC's senior vice
president for children's programming.
</P>
<P>
   So ABC made two major changes. A math segment (``See You Later
Estimator'') and a vocabulary game have been added to the science
``cases'' argued in court before Judge Stone (with the voice of
comedian Paula Poundstone). And, ABC changed the show's name. The
new title: ``Squigglevision.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
</TEXT>
