<HEADER>
A4223 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT &LR;      09-08 0488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: $8.1 MILLION FOR THE ARTS; CHANGING ROLES; PUCCINI
RAINED OUT;   ISRAELI ART SINCE RABIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Minn., Great Britain, Israel)  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Doris Duke Charitable Foundation is announcing $8.1 million in
grants to the arts Wednesday, including $3.5 million to support
construction of a 10-story complex of the New 42nd Street Inc.,
where theater and dance artists can create, rehearse, perform and
teach. The 199-seat theater in the building, between Seventh and
Eighth Avenues, will be named Duke on 42nd Street. In addition, $2
million will go to the National Dance Project of the New England
Foundation for the Arts for the creation of new work and for its
tours.
</P>
<P>
   The Walker Arts Center in Minneapolis is to receive $1.5
million, including $500,000 to commission work by contemporary jazz
artists; the remaining $1 million is to be matched by the Walker to
establish an endowment for future music and dance projects. And
$1.1 million will go the the National Performance Network, a
grass-roots organization in 40 communities nationwide, for new
work, some 200 one-week residencies, annual meetings and to
underwrite plans to strengthen the network.
</P>
<P>
   New Hat
</P>
<P>
   Not content with writing plays like ``The Judas Kiss,''
``Skylight'' and ``Plenty,'' David Hare, 50, decided to make his
debut on the other side of the footlights. Tuesday night, at the
Duke of York's Theater in London, was opening night for the Royal
Court Theater production of Hare's one-man play, ``Via Dolorosa.''
It is a meditation on Israel and Palestine inspired by a recent
visit.
</P>
<P>
   Stormy Ending
</P>
<P>
   Wearing plastic raincoats over evening clothes, more than 2,000
spectators fled the outdoor theater in Beijing's Forbidden City on
Monday night when hailstones and rain pelted a lavish staging of
Puccini's ``Turandot.'' Many in the audience had flown from Europe
and Asia to see the $15 million production, directed by the
filmmaker Zhang Yimou and conducted by Zubin Mehta. Tickets cost as
much as $1,000. No refunds were available when the performance, one
of a scheduled eight, was halted.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh Visions
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Commemorating Israel's 50th anniversary, the Jewish
Museum in Manhattan will open an exhibition of new Israeli art on
Sunday. The 72 works on display through Jan. 3 include paintings,
photography, performance art and video by 35 artists including Ido
Bar-El, Barry Frydlender, Gideon Gechtman, Moshe Gershuni, Israel
Hershberg, Moshe Kupferman, Lea Nikel and Uri Tzaig.
</P>
<P>
   Running through the works are themes of tension, conflict and
personal concerns. The title of the exhibition, ``After Rabin: New
Art From Israel,'' refers to the show's primary focus: the work of
established and emerging artists created in the three years since
the assassination of Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
