<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4234 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAX-MCGWIRE09-COX     09-08 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-MCGWIRE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HISTORIC BASEBALL WILL BE SAFE FROM TAXES, IRS RULES
 &HT;    300&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (s) sports categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The fortunate fan who comes up with the ball that
breaks baseball's home run record _ and quickly gives it back to
the herculean hitter _ won't have to pay a fortune in gift taxes
for his generosity.
</P>
<P>
   Reversing an earlier call by a subordinate, the top umpire at
Internal Revenue Service ruled Tuesday that the government will
give any fan who catches the historic blast from Mark McGwire or
Sammy Sosa a free pass.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, he or she would be treated the same as any ordinary
taxpayer who immediately declines a valuable prize or returns
unsolicited goods to the sender.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes pieces of the tax code can be as hard to understand
as the infield fly rule,'' IRS Commissioner Charles O. Rossotti
said after his agency was deluged by complaints from Capitol Hill
over an earlier interpretation of the tax law.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is that the fan who gives back the home run ball
deserves a round of applause, not a big tax bill,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   An IRS spokesman had told reporters that any fan who gives back
a valuable ball to McGwire or Sosa could owe gift taxes equal to
nearly 40 percent of the ball's value. Already, a $1 million offer
has been made for the historic horsehide.
</P>
<P>
   Rossotti's reading mollified Senate Finance Chairman William
Roth Jr., R-Del., who has spoken with the IRS chief earlier in the
day and urged him to speedily resolve the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that there was ever even a possibility of Mark
McGwire's historic 62nd home run ball being taxed is a prime
example of what's wrong with our current tax code,'' Roth said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our tax laws are replete with provisions that defy common
sense and are patently unfair,'' the senator added. ``I hope this
event can spur us on to consensus on reforming the tax code.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Gift taxes are owed by the giver _ not the receiver _ of a gift
worth more than $10,000. A lifetime $625,000 exclusion could be
applied, but then the fan would not be able to shield his or her
estate or any future gifts from taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Having the multimillionaire slugger pay the gift tax wouldn't
have saved the day, either, because the payment would then have
been treated as income to the fan.
</P>
<P>
   The results ``may be different if the fan decided to sell the
ball,'' Rossotti warned. Then, ordinary federal and state income
taxes would come into play.
</P>
<P>
   If the ball were sold quickly for $1 million, the new owner of a
baseball ordinarily valued at $9 would become liable for about
$396,000 in federal levies. But if he kept the ball for at least 12
months and then sold it for the same $1 million sum, the
transaction would be treated as a long-term capital gain and
subject to a maximum tax of $280,000.
</P>
<P>
   Under Rossotti's ruling, it's not clear if the fan decides to
keep the ball, and it then winds up in an estate, whether he or she
would become liable for death taxes on its residual value.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear, however, that a fan's decision to give the ball to
a charity would nullify tax liabilities. The charity that benefits
from the gift would be free to sell the ball and the resulting
income also would be tax-free.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
