<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4236 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV15-     09-08 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV15-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINK RIBBON DISEASE CAN ALSO HIT MEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Tuesday Sept. 15)  
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In one week I had lunch with an old friend who told me she's
recovering from breast cancer, heard from two friends that their
mammograms were questionable, and started to hug a woman who winced
and backed off, explaining she'd just had a lumpectomy.
</P>
<P>
   Women are getting accustomed to breast cancer to a degree we
wish we didn't have to, but in an open and active way that makes it
easier for us to talk and worry about it and nag each other to do
self exams and get check-ups.
</P>
<P>
   But we don't have an exclusive on the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Carl's mother had breast cancer. Carl's maternal grandmother had
breast cancer. ``My mother didn't have a daughter to pass it on to,
so she gave it to me,'' says Carl with a crooked smile.
</P>
<P>
   Carl, who lives in Northern California and does fine book
printing, is not his real name. But a man with a breast cancer is
wary about going public.
</P>
<P>
   Carl feels as segregated as women with breast cancer once were.
He's embarrassed. ``If you have breast cancer and you're a man
people look at you strange and seem to question your sexuality.''
</P>
<P>
   Most women have stopped being shy about breast cancer. The
boldest ones walk around without wigs or hats, forego a prosthesis,
even bare the badge of their mastectomy. Others are low profile but
meet in support groups, run races to raise money for breast cancer
research and talk openly of their illness.
</P>
<P>
   Few feel the need anymore to hide and keep it a secret, like it
made them any less of a woman.
</P>
<P>
   That is not the case with men. Breast cancer doesn't fit the
male image. Women have breasts; men have chests. When middle-aged
women start worrying about breast cancer, their men's fears go more
to heart attacks and prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Breast cancer is not on a man's list of major health worries.
Rightfully so. Breast cancer happens 100 more times to women than
men, but it does happen and 300 men die from it each year. When
tumors develop they are not caught early mostly because men don't
go for routine breast x-rays and don't think to check themselves
for lumps. Yet, breast cancer acts the same way in men as it does
in women, is diagnosed and treated the same, and has as many
unknowns as to what causes it.
</P>
<P>
   Carl felt something suspicious while showering.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it wasn't as much a lump as what he calls ``a certain
non-symmetry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I noticed it on a Saturday and I worried all day Sunday and
went to the clinic on Monday.'' Carl had a mammogram and a week
later, surgery to remove the lump and some lymph nodes.
</P>
<P>
   The American Cancer Society estimates that this year 1,600 new
cases of invasive breast cancer will be diagnosed in American men.
</P>
<P>
   His doctor told Carl he knew of only three other men with breast
cancer. His surgeon, only one.
</P>
<P>
   Carl was fairly clueless, himself. ``I didn't know men could get
breast cancer. But it didn't seem like it could be anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Carl is 62. His wife died of pelvic cancer in her late 40s.
Carl's mother had a mastectomy, chemotherapy and radiation
treatments and then lived another 30 years until age 89.
</P>
<P>
   So, cancer was not completely alien to Carl, but in dealing with
breast cancer he felt pretty much alone.
</P>
<P>
   For obvious reasons breast cancer support is decidedly more
female than male based. Mammogram clinics are more apt to have
``Good Housekeeping'' magazines than ``Field and Stream.'' The
advocacy symbol for breast cancer is a pink ribbon.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the breast cancer booklets they gave me were written for
women,'' says Carl. ``That shouldn't make any different because it
works the same way with both of us. But it does.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of that literature for women naturally deals with the
emotional affect of losing a breast. For a man, Carl points out,
``The cosmetological issue isn't the same.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he did mind the loss of his hair after chemotherapy, along
with the beard that he had for 30 years. ``That bothered me more
than I thought it would. Nobody recognized me.''
</P>
<P>
   The worst, however, were the anxiety attacks that followed
chemotherapy, which his doctors didn't warn him about. He described
the attacks as ``feeling threatened by all kinds of nameless
things.''
</P>
<P>
   He's now on an anti-anxiety drug. His hair and beard are back
--thick, curly and more black than gray. ``My oncologist joked,
``Who needs Rogaine?'''
</P>
<P>
   But he still keeps it pretty much to himself. ``I found that I
could easily volunteer that I had cancer. But not that I had breast
cancer. That part can be humiliating. People say they never heard
of it. I think they suspect there is something wrong with my
hormones.''
</P>
<P>
   Carl attended a support group once, but he was the only man
there and he probably won't go back. For now, he prefers to stay
anonymous and simply pass on a warning to other men to be aware.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. Her e-mail address is sfswartz(AT)pressdemo.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
