<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4238 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANCER-SKIN-COX     09-08 0391
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-SKIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Skin cancer victims run a greater risk of catching other forms
of cancer
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   People diagnosed with nonfatal forms of skin cancer have a 25
percent to 30 percent greater chance of ultimately dying from other
cancers, such as of the lung, breast and prostate, new research
shows.
</P>
<P>
   Although researchers with the American Cancer Society and Emory
University(Ga.) deemed the increased risk ``slight'' when compared
with other cancer risks _ such as tobacco and environmental toxins
_ they said it should be a motivator to get people to switch to
known cancer-fighting behaviors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although it sounds like a large number _ 25 to 30 percent _
it's a relatively low risk factor when compared to, say, smoking,
which can put a person at a 300 percent greater risk of dying of
cancer,'' said Dr. Michael Thun, an epidemiologist with the
Atlanta-based American Cancer Society and co-author of the study.
``But it's not a trivial number either. It means people who've
suffered skin cancer should take even more seriously the approaches
we know that reduce cancer risks.''
</P>
<P>
   Released in today's Journal of the American Medical Association,
the study compared 35,000 people who reported having skin cancer in
1982 to 1.1 million people without skin cancer who had enrolled in
a cancer prevention study in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   The study took into account age, race, tobacco smoking, and
other factors known to be associated with cancer risk.
</P>
<P>
   The study did not track patients with melanoma, the most serious
skin cancer that is responsible for about 7,300 annual deaths. It
followed people with nonmelanoma skin cancers, called basal cell or
squamous, that tend to grow slowly and rarely spread to other parts
of the body. More than 95 percent of the 1 million Americans
diagnosed with nomelanoma skin cancers are cured.
</P>
<P>
   This newest study is of great interest to the cancer-research
world as it proves a person is susceptible to other forms of cancer
years after being rid of another cancer, Thun said.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers said it's possible skin cancer can alter a person's
DNA or weaken the body's immune system, making it possible for
another cancer to develop years later.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 1804EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4239 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANCER-SKIN-life-COX     09-08 0392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-SKIN-life-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Skin cancer victims run a greater risk of catching other forms
of cancer
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   People diagnosed with nonfatal forms of skin cancer have a 25
