   Released in today's Journal of the American Medical Association,
the study compared 35,000 people who reported having skin cancer in
1982 to 1.1 million people without skin cancer who had enrolled in
a cancer prevention study in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   The study took into account age, race, tobacco smoking, and
other factors known to be associated with cancer risk.
</P>
<P>
   The study did not track patients with melanoma, the most serious
skin cancer that is responsible for about 7,300 annual deaths. It
followed people with nonmelanoma skin cancers, called basal cell or
squamous, that tend to grow slowly and rarely spread to other parts
of the body. More than 95 percent of the 1 million Americans
diagnosed with nomelanoma skin cancers are cured.
</P>
<P>
   This newest study is of great interest to the cancer-research
world as it proves a person is susceptible to other forms of cancer
years after being rid of another cancer, Thun said.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers said it's possible skin cancer can alter a person's
DNA or weaken the body's immune system, making it possible for
another cancer to develop years later.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
