A4240 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CSIBLEY-COLUMN09-COX     09-08 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CSIBLEY-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Gulf beckons when trouble rears its head
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Flood waters washing in from the Gulf of Mexico covered great
swatches of our island, including the roads, such as were left;
some were washed away. Our back yard was a pond replete with
croaking frogs. The dunes that constitute the front yard had been
sliced in two by the greedy waters, and whole clumps of cedar and
beach golden rod tumbled in the sound waters, a hazard to small
boats.
</P>
<P>
   The electricity was off so there would be no water, no working
bathrooms, no stove on which to prepare supper. But the house
looked sweet and welcoming, a pelican flew over with a friendly
honk, the rickety wooden walk from the front steps had survived _
many didn't _ and we hauled our gear up the steps glad to be there,
no matter what.
</P>
<P>
   We really were lucky. Our house stood _ tattered screens
flapping, sand whooshing grittily over the floors.
</P>
<P>
   We settled on sandwiches for lunch and a front yard grill meal
for supper and finally went off to bed worrying about the neighbors
we heard from. One house on the Gulf side had been swallowed up by
the gigantic green jaws of the storm tides, and a friend who moved
to the island many years ago took comfort that he again had
beachfront property. He has moved his house back from the tide line
twice and felt secure that a shell-topped road stood between him
and the water. This year's hurricane took the road, the water moved
in, and he is once again on the beach. He is, they told me, calm
and philosophical about it.
</P>
<P>
   People who choose to live in hurricane country usually are. Our
friends Dr. and Mrs. Ivan Backerman found their walk to the beach
missing, their steps to the deck crumpled and piled up in the sand
like dirty laundry, and the dunes between them and the water
missing _ so there was a 10- or 15-foot drop from their deck to the
ground. They are already negotiating for a house mover who will
bury new pilings up by the road and set their house on them.
</P>
<P>
   The same thing is true of our friends the Boatenreiters, who
live in one of the oldest and most charming houses on the island.
Storm tides washed the underpinnings from under their deck,
smothered Mary Ruth's pretty little vegetable garden with sand and
left the message that next time, next hurricane, the place they
have loved and cared for might be toppled into the sea.
</P>
<P>
   Why do those of us who were Gulf Coast-reared insist on living _
or at least spending our time _ on the shoals of sure hurricane
visitations? I don't know. I was born not far from the oft-stormy
waters of Santa Rosa Sound. My mother reared me on stories of
preparing for hurricanes, living through them and finally cleaning
up after them. There were always scary moments, particularly that
time of complete deathly quiet when the center passed over us.
</P>
<P>
   You don't forget but you are accepting and appreciative of
whatever the storm leaves. For us, on our first night on the
island, it was bright moonlight and a sweet cool breeze from the
southwest.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
