<HEADER>
A4241 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GETAWAY-ALABAMA-COX     09-08 1449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GETAWAY-ALABAMA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Riding a high tide of revitalization, college town goes way
beyond football to museums, music and lovely homes
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUSCALOOSA, Ala._The ``Roll Tide'' on the water tower was no
surprise. Neither was a certain college football coach's
black-and-white houndstooth check hat on display at a local museum.
</P>
<P>
   But who would have thought that in this quintessential Southern
college town you could also find a masosaur fossil called Sweetie,
a 13th-century stone Buddha, the state's only antebellum garden, a
'30s theater that was one of the last municipal buildings
constructed under the Work Projects Administration and an
archaeological site where the prehistoric metropolis of the South
thrived 800 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Tuscaloosa may be famous as the home of the University of
Alabama, its storied football program and one of college football's
winningest coaches, Paul W. ``Bear'' Bryant. And, yes, there is a
museum dedicated to the Bear and Bama football history _ on Bryant
Drive. No doubt about it, Tuscaloosa is never more crowded than on
those fall Saturdays when 80,000 or so Crimson Tide fanatics
ro-o-oll into town and descend on Bryant-Denny Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But if you think that's all there is to the town on the banks of
the Black Warrior River, you also probably assume Tuscaloosa Blonde
is a euphemism for an Alabama cheerleader (it happens to be one of
the beers at a trendy downtown brewpub).
</P>
<P>
   There's plenty to see and do here year-round. In addition to
historic museums on and off campus, there's a thriving cultural
community anchored by Theatre Tuscaloosa and the Tuscaloosa
Symphony as well as the University's Celebrity Series, which is
bringing in such artists as flutist Jean-Pierre Rampal and
violinist Midori this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Bama, which opened as a moviehouse in 1938 with Cary Grant
and Katharine Hepburn's ``Bringing Up Baby,'' is an important part
of downtown's ongoing revitalization. Fox Theatre-like stars
twinkle in a blue sky above a Spanish-style courtyard setting with
trompe l'oeil paintings on the walls. Renovated in 1981 and placed
on the National Historic Register in 1984, the theater hosts
variety shows, concerts and ballet for school and community
audiences and is planning a classic film series.
</P>
<P>
   In the eclectic mix of downtown bars and restaurants _ from the
Alabama Grill (old-fashioned deviled eggs on the menu) to Javaweb
(a very '90s cyberspace cafe) _ is Barrett's Grillworks and Brewery
in the old Brown's department store at the corner of Greensboro and
University avenues. Here, connoisseurs can take the Brewmaster's
Brew Tour, five 5-ounce glasses of the six in-house brews, for
$4.25.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a marvelous time to be here,'' says Paul Looney,
executive director of Theatre Tuscaloosa, which opens its season
Oct. 16 in a new state-of-the-art theater at the Tuscaloosa Fine
Arts Centre of the campus of Shelton State University. ``You can
see the rhythms of the town changing. Who would have thought that
downtown would be a walking area with pubs, bars and blues clubs?''
</P>
<P>
   Tuscaloosa's vitality is by no means confined to downtown and
the campus area.
</P>
<P>
   More than two dozen Mississippian Indian mounds with ongoing
excavations can be found at Moundville Archaeological Park, a
320-acre National Historic Landmark 13 miles south of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Just across the Black Warrior River to the north is the artsy
little town of Northport, home of the Kentuck Arts Center as well
as a revitalized downtown block with galleries, specialty shops and
the popular Globe restaurant. And 20 miles east of the city is the
Mercedes-Benz Visitor Center and Museum, adjacent to the
German-owned car-making factory.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a quick look at sightseeing highlights:
</P>
<P>
   -- Paul W. Bryant Museum: Here lies the hat. Actually, there are
several versions of coach Bryant's famous checked hat _ even one
crafted in crystal by Waterford in Ireland. Memorabilia, artifacts
and photographs from the beginning of Alabama football in 1892 to
the present are showcased along with interpretive videos about
famous Crimson Tide coaches, players and games. ``I think of this
as a history museum,'' director Kenneth Gaddy says. ``What we are
talking about is the people.'' Open 9 a.m.-4 p.m. daily. $2; $1
children. 300 Bryant Drive (across from the Coliseum).
205-348-4668.
</P>
<P>
   -- Gorgas House: Built in 1829 as a dining hall, this Lowcountry
raised cottage was the first building on the University of Alabama
campus and one of only four to survive a Civil War torching. It was
remodeled as a residence in 1840, which it remained until 1953. Now
a house museum, it is furnished with antiques and memorabilia _
some of which belonged to the family of the university's seventh
president, Josiah Gorgas. 10 a.m.-4 p.m. Tuesdays, Wednesdays and
Fridays; 10 a.m.-4 p.m. Saturdays; 2-4 p.m. Sundays. Free. Capstone
Drive. 205-348-5906.
</P>
<P>
   -- Alabama Museum of Natural History: Historic Smith Hall _ a
neoclassical building at Sixth Street and Capstone Drive in the
heart of campus _ was built 1907-1909. Here, you can see fossils
from as far back as the Ice Age, the horse-drawn wagon used by
Eugene Allen Smith (Alabama state geologist from 1873 to 1927), and
the Hodges Meteorite, which crashed through a roof in Sylacauga in
1954, hitting a woman on her leg. There's a working lab where
research on the masosaur (a marine reptile) named Sweetie is under
way. 8 a.m.-4:30 p.m. weekdays; 1-4 p.m. Saturdays. $1; 50 cents
children. 205-348-7550.
</P>
<P>
   -- The Warner Collection at Gulf States Paper Corp.: Possibly
the city's biggest surprise is this collection of more than 150
American artworks in a 90,000-square-foot corporate headquarters
tucked into the woods above the river. Designed by late Atlanta
architect Cecil Alexander, the sprawling complex, which opened in
1970, evokes a Japanese teahouse with gardens with koi-filled ponds
and exotic caged birds. Retired Gulf States CEO Jack Warner has
amassed one of the world's largest private collections on public
view. Artists include Mary Cassatt, Childe Hassam, John Singer
Sargeant, Winslow Homer, Thomas Hart Benton and all the Wyeths.
Plus, there are totems from the South Pacific, tribal masks from
New Guinea, Japanese campaign chests, a 13th-century Buddha and 95
wild bird portraits by British artist Basil Ede. Tours 5:30 and
6:30 p.m. weekdays and on the hour 10 a.m.-4 p.m. Saturdays and 1-4
p.m. Sundays. Free. 1400 River Road. 205-553-6200.
</P>
<P>
   -- Battle-Friedman House: Wealthy businessman Alfred Battle
built this two-story brick townhouse in 1835, when Tuscaloosa was
still the state capitol. Architectural detailing reflects both
Federal and Greek Revival influences. In 1844, Millicent Battle
employed an English landscape designer, who provided an intricate
design of interlocking diamond-shaped beds and paths. The
antebellum gardens were restored to their original design last
year. Today the home and gardens are maintained by the Tuscaloosa
County Preservation Society. Some of the period furnishings
belonged to the Battles and Friedmans. In the north parlor is a
table that once belonged to Mr. and Mrs. Isidor Straus, owners of
R.H. Macy's, who died on the Titanic. Tours 10 a.m.-noon and 1-4
p.m. Tuesdays-Saturdays and 1-4 p.m. Sundays. $3. 1010 Greensboro
Ave. 205-758-6138.
</P>
<P>
   -- Mercedes-Benz Visitor Center: Tours of the only Mercedes
plant outside Europe are offered Mondays through Fridays by
reservation for ages 12 and older. No shorts, above-the-knee skirts
or sandals allowed in the factory. The exhibition hall, which
traces the history of the car maker from 1886 to the present, is
open 9 a.m.-5 p.m. Mondays-Fridays and 10 a.m.-5 p.m. Saturdays.
$4; $3 senior citizens and children. I-59/20 at Exit 89 in Vance.
1-888-286-8762.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   -- Getting there: It's about 200 miles _ a 3 1/2 hour drive _
from Atlanta via I-20 west.
</P>
<P>
   -- Staying over: The Four Points Sheraton, 320 Bryant Drive,
1-800-477-2222, is on campus. For other options, call the
Tuscaloosa Convention and Visitors Bureau, 1-800-590-9874.
</P>
<P>
   -- Dining: The most inventive eats are at Barrett's Grillworks
and Brewery (and fine dining at Arman's at Barrett's upstairs),
205-366-0380;
</P>
<P>
   Mezzanine, 508 Greensboro Ave., downtown, 205-752-0020; and the
Globe in Northport, 205-391-0949.
</P>
<P>
   -- Information: The Tuscaloosa Visitor Center is at the 1863
Jemison-Van de Graaff Mansion, 1305 Greensboro Ave. Stop by for a
tour and information 8:30 a.m.-5 p.m. weekdays. Call
1-800-538-8696.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
