<HEADER>
A4242 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GETAWAY-FESTIVALS-COX     09-08 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GETAWAY-FESTIVALS-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Alabama: Upcoming events
</P>
<P>
   Eye distant past at native festival
</P>
<P>
   Alabama's earliest residents _ a highly advanced society that
thrived on the highest bluff of the Black Warrior River _ will be
remembered during the 10th Annual Moundville Native American
Festival at Moundville Archaeological Park on Sept. 22-26.
Southeastern tribes will showcase the culture of their ancestors at
the site, where an agrarian community of 3,000 lived around
1,000-1,500 A.D.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the best-preserved sites of its kind in the
country,'' says Betsy Jones, the park's director of education and
festival coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   The five-day event at the national historic landmark features
demonstrations of skills such as basket weaving, beadwork, blowgun
making and flint knapping; preparation of foods and medicines;
stickball games and traditional songs and dances.
</P>
<P>
   An Indian Market offers Native American arts and crafts. Also,
fry bread and other foods will be sold.
</P>
<P>
   A living history camp re-creates the life of Creek Indians and
early settlers in Alabama during the late 18th century and provides
hands-on experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Mississippian Indians constructed the large earthworks topped by
temples, council houses and homes of nobility.
</P>
<P>
   More than 26 of these flat-topped mounds survive, the largest 60
feet tall. Excavation of the ancient artistic and ceremonial center
began in the 1930s as Civilian Conservation Corps workers
discovered some of the most prized artifacts ever found in North
America.
</P>
<P>
   The museum, built by the CCC, contains pottery, stone and clay
pipes, artifacts and a distinctive sandstone disc with rattlesnake
motif.
</P>
<P>
   The festival is 9 a.m.-4 p.m. Sept. 22-25 and 9 a.m.-5 p.m.
Sept. 26. $5; $3 children. A free Lantern Tour of the living
history camp will be 7-9 p.m. Sept. 24 (call 205-348-0050 to
register). Moundville, open 8 a.m.-8 p.m. daily, is 13 miles south
of Tuscaloosa on Ala. 69 south. 205-371-2234.
</P>
<P>
   See folk crafts in their prime
</P>
<P>
   The 27th Kentuck Festival of the Arts in Northport on Oct. 17-18
will once again feature some of the South's best folk art. But
that's not all there is to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kentuck is primarily known as a folk art festival, but we have
a full range of fine art,'' says Kentuck Art Center director Miah
Michaelson. ``We're trying to branch out. We are the largest visual
arts festival in the state.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the works of more than 300 artists (paintings,
sculptures, furniture, pottery, whirligigs _ you name it), the
festival includes two music stages featuring acts such as Iris
DeMent, the gospel trio D'Vine and the banjo-thrashing Bad Livers.
Youngsters can dabble in tie-dye, mold clay, decorate an art car
and craft a corn-shuck doll at a children's area.
</P>
<P>
   Michaelson says part of the festival and art center's mission is
to preserve traditional crafts such as basket making and candle
making _ two of the skills that will be spotlighted.
</P>
<P>
   The Kentuck Art Center, at 503 Main Ave. in Northport, is home
to a museum, two exhibition galleries, a gift shop and seven
artists' studios. Festival hours are 9 a.m.-6 p.m. Oct. 17, 9
a.m.-5 p.m. Oct. 18. $5; $2 children 6-12. From I-20/59 take Exit
71 to Ala. 69 north. Cross the Black Warrior River and take the
first Northport exit. Kentuck Park is 1/2 mile west of Main Avenue.
205-758-1257.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
