<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4272 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICARE09-COX     09-08 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEDICARE PANEL GETS PLENTY OF REFORM SUGGESTIONS
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The bipartisan Medicare commission got an earful of
suggestions Monday on how _ and how not _ to reform the nation's
health care system for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   In a daylong hearing, the commission _ which is scheduled next
March to recommend long-term revisions to Medicare _ received
conflicting suggestions from a broad spectrum of health care
advocacy and interest groups over the wisdom of issuing insurance
vouchers, increasing managed care coverage and expanding the
program to include long-term care.
</P>
<P>
   The panel did not give any indication of what recommendations it
would adopt.
</P>
<P>
   Among the central issues for Medicare, which is scheduled to run
out of money to fully cover hospital costs in about 10 years, is
whether the system should be changed from one in which the
government sets premiums and defines benefits to one in which
people purchase their own federally subsidized coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Several advocacy groups, including the American Medical
Association and the conservative Cato Institute, urged the panel to
shift to private medical savings accounts as the best way of
restraining the cost of Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The tax-free medical savings accounts would be financed by
payroll deductions and employer contributions _ similar to the
current system _ but would be used to purchase private health care
coverage which high deductibles.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Litow, an actuary for the Council for Affordable Health
Insurance, argued that the current system, in which the government
sets premiums and payment rates, results in an ineffective and
costly program.
</P>
<P>
   Using private accounts would give consumers a greater choice of
benefits and force providers to offer more efficient services,
Litow said.
</P>
<P>
   But Paul Rogers, a former Florida congressman, warned that
private medical accounts _ vouchers for a specific amount of money
_ would not adequately coverage the insurance needs of the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers, co-chairman of the National Coalition on Health Care,
warned that as health care costs outpaced vouchers, millions of
poor beneficiaries would be priced out of the insurance market.
</P>
<P>
   ''We urge the commission not to abandon the guarantee of a
minimum benefit package,'' Rogers said, arguing for a system in
which a government voucher would cover a minimum benefit package.
Insurers would bid to provide those benefits, with the government
selecting the lowest bid on a region-by-region basis.
</P>
<P>
   The managed care industry urged the commission to consider
Medicare reforms that would reverse payment limits imposed in last
year's Balanced Budget Act.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Ignagni, president of the American Association of Health
Plans, told the panel that last year's reforms will result in
payments to health maintenance organizations that are
``significantly behind payments under the fee-for-service program.
As a result of these reductions, many plans may have to cut
benefits, raise premiums or both.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Jim McDermott, D-Wash., said he was concerned that HMOs
were advertising extensive benefits in order to attract customers
and then reducing services.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks a little bit like bait-and-switch to me,'' McDermott
said.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Kahn III, representing the Health Insurance Industry of
America, urged the panel to retain the option for seniors to
purchase so-call ``medigap'' insurance to cover benefits not
provided by Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Kahn suggested that the current fee-for-service system would
likely remain a major option for the elderly and that medigap
policies would be necessary to protect them from large
out-of-pocket expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The American Health Care Association, which represents more than
11,000 non-profit assisted living and nursing home facilities,
urged the commission to recommend the creation of a similar panel
to assess the issues of long-term care, which are primarily
financed by the federal-state Medicaid system.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Paul Willig, the association's executive vice president,
noted that two out of five Americans will need long-term care at
some point in their lives, and that three out of four cannot afford
the more than $40,000 annual cost for nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   Since Medicare pays only a small portion of long-term care
costs, Willig said ``hundreds of thousands of aging Americans ...
must impoverish themselves to qualify for Medicaid assistance. It
is a demeaning inequity in our nation's health care system.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
