   POLITE-PATENT _ ATLANTA _ ``Excuse me. After you.'' Robot
welders know nothing about speaking or manners, of course, but
there are times when they need to be ``nice.'' And that's what
Patent No. 5798627 does. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m.
ET.
</P>
<P>
   SPROUT _ ATLANTA _ Sprout, a one-year-old company that sells the
equipment and data to bookstores so they can print a book, on
request, in about 10 minutes. The system, printer and access to a
digital database, starts at about $15,000. (Clothier, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   WEB-MEASURE _ The growing importance of Web measurement. A
comparison of the two top Web measurement firms, Atlanta's Relevant
Knowledge and New York-based Media Metrix. Will include analyst
commentary on Web measurement and if it's developed to a point
where the information is both accurate and useful. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   SUGAR _ The NLRB looks at the U.S. Sugar union vote. (Waresh,
Palm Beach Post) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   DOW _ U.S. stocks surged after Alan Greenspan indicated interest
rates may drop. (Walker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m.
ET.
</P>
<P>
   GM-ISUZU _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Details of the new GM-Izuzu plant are
emerging and it seems that Izuzu will own 60 percent of the new
plant. (Wagner, Dayton Daily News) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   MOTT _ CLEWISTON, Fla. _ Now meet U.S. Sugar's quiet but
important partner, 1,100 miles away in Flint, Mich., the home of
General Motors Corp.'s Buick division. People therehere measure
prosperity not by the cars they drive but by the cars they build.
And much as nearly everything in Clewiston bears the stamp of U.S.
Sugar, nearly everything in Flint bears the stamp of General Motors
and an early G.M. investor named Charles Stewart Mott. (Peltz, Palm
Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CHARLES-MOTT _ Charles Stewart Mott once, the story goes,
changed a 30-watt refrigerator bulb to 15 watts to save
electricity. That might not have been unusual for someone who'd
endured the Great Depression. But Mott, creator of what became the
country's 15th-largest charitable foundation, was then considered
one of the richest men in the United States. Still, he prized
simplicity. (Peltz, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EQUIFAX-CEO _ A lot has changed since Thomas F. Chapman ran into
a brick wall when he went looking for help from Equifax. Now,
Equifax offers the kind of information Chapman needed. And Chapman
is president _ since August 1997 _ and chief executive officer _
since January _ of the Atlanta-based credit reporting and
information services company. (McNaughton, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   EQUIFAX-STRATEGY _ The strategy for Equifax was set with the
arrival in 1987 of C.B. ``Jack'' Rogers Jr. as president and chief
operating officer. His job was to use technology to transform
Equifax's products into more useful and valuable offerings. That's
still the idea: selling information rather than raw data. And it
continues under Thomas F. Chapman, the current president and chief
executive officer. (McNaughton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GEEWAX-COLUMN _ Economists are wondering whether the stock
market's recent gyrations will lead to a significant decline in
consumer spending. As a baby boomer, allow me to make this
prediction: No. (Geewax, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MONEY-TALK _ Pre-retirement planning has gained greater notice
in the last few weeks. The stock market has flayed investors of all
ages. But the scare has been particularly acute for those who are
near retirement and who had been jubilant about the rapidly
increasing value of their investments. (Ezell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
