<P>
   TECH-REPORT _ Hand-held cellular phones have taken another leap
forward in the arena of personal safety. Audiovox has unveiled the
FoneFinder, a hand-held that can be vehicle-mounted and has a
Global Positioning Satellite receiver built in to pinpoint the
location of 911 callers. With a touch of the large 911 button on
the top of the phone, the phone and its GPS receiver are turned on.
A built-in speech chip announces the caller's location to emergency
dispatchers. (Ghirardini, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-MEDIA _ In this age of the Internet and 24-hour news
television, anyone can become a celebrity overnight. Which also
means you can just as quickly become a target for public scrutiny.
``Spin,'' a new book by spin doctor Michael S. Sitrick and
journalist Allan Mayer, talks about this modern phenomenon and how
you can make it work for you. (Haddad, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-KIDS _ Sarah Hutchinson of Marietta is learning about some
popular songs from around the world with a sing-along CD-ROM
program called Children's Songbook. (Davis, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY _ The big news in technology this past week came
from Carnegie Mellon University in Pittsburgh, where researchers
discovered that people who spent hours and hours on the Internet
each night didn't have time left to have any real human
relationships. What a surprise that was. It is roughly equivalent
to discovering that people who walk in the rain get wet and then
long to be dry. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCH _ MTV's Web site seems a prime candidate for teenage
hackers who like to mess with big-time sites. For a while last
week, it looked as if MTV had indeed been hacked. As it turns out,
the defaced start page was actually created by MTV itself as a
promotion for Thursday's ``MTV Video Music Awards.'' (Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MAC-REPORT _ It looks like a gumdrop but is working like a life
saver. Apple Computer's new iMac is not only selling well but
drawing new users to the platform. That was unthinkable just a few
months ago, when most company observers were saying, at best, Apple
Computer would remain a niche player catering to Mac aficionados.
(Haddad, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
