<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4279 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-DEADLOCKED-$AD     09-08 1410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-DEADLOCKED-$ADV13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WHILE PROCESS IS STALLED, ISRAELIS AND PALESTINIANS SEEK
ADVANTAGE IN TALKS
 &HT;    With ISRAEL-SECURITY-$ADV13; ISRAEL-CHRONO-$ADV13; map-graphic
to be placed in the International folder by the Palm Beach Post.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Sept. 13 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Five years ago on the White House lawn(CQ date),
President Bill Clinton gave then-Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak
Rabin a famous nudge, moving him close to Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat so they would shake hands on the Oslo peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Israelis and Palestinians have been vying for position ever
since.
</P>
<P>
   Amid an 18-month freeze in the peace negotiations, both sides
seek leverage over how the process ends and what land, ultimately,
changes hands.
</P>
<P>
   On the rocky hillsides of the West Bank, Jews and Arabs stake
their claims. There is still frequent scenes of violence, featuring
attacks by Palestinian terrorists and stone throwing Palestinian
youth or heavily armed Israeli soldiers and scuffling Jewish
settlers. Meanwhile, political leaders unveil schemes aimed at
getting an edge in the talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we see here is an attempt to maintain bargaining chips
for the end game,'' said Joel Singer, an Israeli author of the Oslo
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, U.S. envoys work to broker the next step in Oslo,
which would be another Israeli withdrawal from part of the West
Bank land it captured in the 1967 war.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty is that this is not the last move in the game.
</P>
<P>
   More important issues come later, such as whether Israel will
share Jerusalem, whether some settlements are dismantled, or
whether there will be a return or compensation of the 3.4 million
Palestinian refugees, and their descendants, who left Israel during
the 1948 war.
</P>
<P>
   The strategies are clear.
</P>
<P>
   If Israel gives up less of the West Bank now, it can give it in
the final talks and resist pressure to give on the other issues.
Conversely, the more land the Palestinians get in their pocket now,
the more they will be able to focus the final talks on Jerusalem,
refugees and settlements.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL THE STRONGER PARTY
</P>
<P>
   Most of the chips are on the Israeli side of the table. Israel
has the land the Palestinians want and populates it with 170,000
settlers. It has an army to hold it and an ally in the de facto
mediator, the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian power relies on a slight upswing in world opinion.
Arafat has accepted a U.S. proposed plan to end the deadlock, but
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, who was a harsh critic
of Oslo when Rabin signed it, has not accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat also has some land now and a police force that Israelis
fear is a budding militia.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly, he has what some call the ``negative power'' -- the
likelihood that if Oslo fails, the 2.5 million Palestinians in the
West Bank and Gaza will, with Arafat's backing, rise up in a bloody
revolt.
</P>
<P>
   Against this background comes the daily thrust and parry.
</P>
<P>
   When two Jewish settlers were killed in a suspected Palestinian
terror attack last month, the leaders of their small Itzhar
neighborhood announced they would build 15 more homes. The message:
Not only aren't they going anywhere, they will grow.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli group Peace Now estimates that in the last 18 months
construction has started on about 3,000 new homes for Jews in the
West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   With these neighborhoods, and the highways that connect them,
come confiscations of long-time Arab lands. According to the
Israeli army, it has destroyed 190 Arab homes so far this year, up
from 180 most years.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. diplomats criticize the moves, saying negotiations, not
bulldozers, must determine who gets the land.
</P>
<P>
   ARABS' CASUALTIES DOWN, ISRAELIS' UP
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the violent ways of asserting power.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Israeli human rights group B'Tselem, Israeli
soldiers or civilians have killed 326 Palestinians since Oslo was
signed through July. Palestinians have killed 226 Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   For Palestinians, that is a huge drop caused by the Israeli
army's withdrawal from almost all populated Palestinian areas.
</P>
<P>
   For Israelis, the figure is a huge increase, due largely to
bombings that many say are attempts by Arafat's rivals to derail
Oslo and create an all-out war between the Jews and Arabs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feared that with the birth of this horrible, nightmare of
an agreement there would be more bloodshed and we've seen it,''
said Yehudit Tayar, a spokesperson for YESHA, which represents
settlements and threatens to use its power to topple Netanyahu's
government if he gives away too much.
</P>
<P>
   Since roughly the time the talks have stalled, 34 Palestinians
and 24 Israelis have been killed.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, the arena for maneuvers range from the United
Nations to city hall.
</P>
<P>
   When the U.N. recently upgraded the observer status of the
Palestinians, that was a step toward Arafat's vow to declare
Palestinian statehood on May 4, 1999, the date the Oslo accords
expire. This is an unsettling threat. Israeli leaders say that
could lead them to re-invade the land they have so far given,
because Oslo relies on any statehood being negotiated, not
declared.
</P>
<P>
   In parallel, Israelis in June proposed widening their authority
over Arab areas near Jerusalem. That angered Palestinians who say
Jerusalem's boundaries should be negotiated, not declared.
</P>
<P>
   Amid all this, tension rises to a dangerous level.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli police are now wary of plots by Jewish extremists to
kill the Israeli defense minister or Netanyahu -- the fate met by
Rabin.
</P>
<P>
   Israelis and Palestinians still support Oslo, according to
polls, but the support has been falling.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of damage has been done in the last 18 months,'' said
Arafat spokesman Marwan Kanafani. ``The damage has hurt the idea of
peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Israeli government spokesman Moshe Fogel sees it differently,
citing the slowing of Palestinian rioting and threats during the
stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are all part of their plan to try to soften up the
Israeli government,'' Fogel said. ``(The stalemate) should have had
a sobering effect on the Palestinians to show them that all these
gimmicks and tactics aren't going to lead them anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   SWISS CHEESE GEOGRAPHY
</P>
<P>
   The Oslo process, in midstream, has created a jumble of
Israeli-Palestinian borders.
</P>
<P>
   In the West Bank, more than 95 percent of the Palestinian
population is now in areas partially or completely controlled by
the Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
   But it makes up only 27 percent of the land and, in most of
that, Palestinians only control civil affairs while Israeli army
jeep patrols still reign.
</P>
<P>
   There is a Swiss cheese geography, with Palestinians living in
more than 100 enclaves surrounded by Israeli checkpoints.
</P>
<P>
   On the hilltops are 127 Jewish settlements, often resembling
condominiums. They pose a problem for Oslo because they were
scattered in a pattern designed to interrupt any solid block of
Palestinian land.
</P>
<P>
   American officials want Israel to give up another 13 percent of
the West Bank to keep the process moving. Netanyahu said he needs
more security assurances.
</P>
<P>
   He demands that Arafat fulfill a promise to convene the leaders
of the international Palestine Liberation Organization and revoke
the many parts of its charter that call for war against Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The group has voted once to amend its charter generally for
Oslo, however, the specific revisions were never made.
</P>
<P>
   The CIA recently restarted Israeli-Palestinian talks on an
anti-terrorism security agreement that Netanyahu rejected several
months ago. An agreement could give him political cover for backing
to grant more land.
</P>
<P>
   There has not been a suicide bombing in Israel in over a year,
which experts attribute to a leadership crisis in the extremist
group Hamas and probably extra vigilance by Arafat -- whose own
fate is now linked to preserving the Oslo agreement he signed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an improvement, but it is not optimum,'' said Carmi
Gillon, former head of Israel's internal security force, Shin Bet.
``Nowadays, Arafat realizes that terrorist acts are against his
interests.''
</P>
<P>
   While most Israelis oppose giving up more land until Arafat
improves security, Palestinian leaders frequently attribute
terrorism to frustration caused by Israel's reluctance to turn over
land.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
