<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4280 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-SECURITY-$ADV1     09-08 0451
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-SECURITY-$ADV13-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   SOME GAINS SEEN IN ARAFAT'S SECURITY, IS IT ENOUGH FOR PEACE?
</P>
<P>
   With ISRAEL-DEADLOCKED-$ADV13.
</P>
<P>
   For Use Sunday, Sept. 13 And Thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   By LARRY KAPLOW &QC;
</P>
<P>
   c. 998 Cox News Service &QC;
</P>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ He has heard the demands from the Israeli government
and received training from the CIA, but is Palestinian Authority
President Yasser Arafat fighting terrorism?
</P>
<P>
   It is a year since the last time suicide bombers sent nails and
terror ripping through an Israeli crowd, though several individual
murders have occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``Operations have come down because of the huge crackdown (from
Arafat),'' said Ibrihim Gosheh, a spokesman in Jordan for the Hamas
extremist group that often takes credit for the bombings.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, opinions of Arafat's record vary widely.
</P>
<P>
   His police force is several thousand officers over what is
allowed under the Oslo accords, but analysts say that may help him
keep peace. He refuses to extradite terrorists to Israel, but
observers point out that he would not be required to if the
terrorists were tried by his authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Hamas is Arafat's political rival. If the peace process fails,
Hamas is vindicated and Arafat will be seen as having misled his
people.
</P>
<P>
   Ghassan Khatib, director of a Palestinian research group, said
that contrary to some claims, Arafat would not use Hamas bombings
to influence peace negotiations with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will never allow himself to become dependent on his
opponents,'' Khatib said.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians note that Israelis could not stop terror when they
controlled all the land.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat has jailed some Hamas leaders, but Carmi Gillon, former
head of Israel's internal security force, said mostly he fights
terror by pressuring the families of the extremists. Arafat's
record has improved, he said, but it is not how Israelis fight
terror.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (Palestinians) think that if you put a Hamas member in
the police it will convince him not to be a terrorist,'' Gillon
said.
</P>
<P>
   The CIA trains Palestinian police in anti-terrorism and even on
securing its phone lines from Israeli listening devices, according
to Menachem Klein, a political scientist at Bar Ilan University.
</P>
<P>
   Klein said one of Arafat's security chiefs recently met with a
top terrorist leader -- a friend from their time in Israeli jails
-- and told him he would face stiff punishment if any terror was
committed.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has said Arafat
responds to specific threats, but does not break the terrorist
network -- he spears the fish one by one, rather than casting a
net.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
