<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0223 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4297 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-DELAY09     09-08 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DELAY09 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    HOUSE WHIP JUGGLES GOP ROLES
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Christi Harlan
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Thanks to House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, House
Republicans learned that they can expect to vote today to create
two commemorative coins and name five post offices after deserving
individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Also thanks to DeLay, they were given a point-by-point rebuttal
to the request from President Clinton's lawyer that he be given an
early peek at any report from independent counsel Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   The two advisories were a reflection of the dual jobs that the
Texas Republican is juggling as both the top Republican in charge
of rounding up House votes and as the self-designated source of
information about impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Information ... is what we're providing,'' said DeLay's
spokesman, Michael Scanlon. The whip's staff is providing ``just
about anything under the sun you could need research on,'' from how
special counsel Leon Jaworski of Houston handled his investigation
of President Nixon to the special oath that senators must take
before trying a president on articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having this sort of information is useful for answering
constituents' questions,'' Scanlon said.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay has been the most outspoken of the House leaders about
Clinton's affair with Monica Lewinsky, calling for the president's
resignation within a day of his admission that he lied about the
affair. DeLay has also suggested that Starr's full report be made
public as soon as it arrives at the Capitol and that the House stay
in session past early October to deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom believes the guy is not fit to be president,'' Scanlon
said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite DeLay's strong feelings, his staff insists that the
impeachment-information service they're running isn't what critics
claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``This information we give to members is not intended for them
to run out and start calling for the president's impeachment,''
Scanlon said. ``It serves other purposes. One is information, one
is background, and third is to be involved in the public debate on
this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The public debate Tuesday, as suggested by DeLay's office, was a
refutation of assertions made by Clinton's lawyer in a letter sent
Monday to Starr. David Kendall asked Starr for an advance copy of
any report going to Congress and hinted that he may mount a legal
challenge to Starr's authority to report directly to Congress.
Kendall also faxed copies of the letter to various reporters in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay, as congressman, responded with a press release blasting
Kendall for ``trying to grab headlines.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Kendall's actions reek of politics,'' he said in his press
statement. ``This request is nothing more than a PR move, and it
may backfire on him.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLay, as information resource, provided House Republicans with
``talking points'' on the Kendall letter that include comparisons
of the Watergate investigation with Starr's investigation and note
changes in federal law that would allow Starr to report to
Congress:
</P>
<P>
   ``Kendall claims that the IC (independent counsel) may not even
have legal grounds for submitting a report. How does he want him to
do it? A phone call? (Actually, what they want is for Starr to come
up and testify so they can try and make him look like a fool.) It
is ridiculous to say that Starr cannot or should not submit a
report. This is a desperate attempt by the White House to keep the
American people and Congress from finding out the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Scanlon insisted the advisories being created by DeLay's staff
are just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were pumping out press releases and talking points on
why Bill Clinton is a bad person, then that would be partisan,'' he
said. Providing information on the censure or impeachment of the
president, he said, ``that's not partisan.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
