<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-TOBACCO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENAMED TOBACCO COMPANY LEADS BRITAIN'S BLUE CHIPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Shares in the renamed British American Tobacco PLC
soared far ahead of the rest of London's lackluster stock market
Tuesday in the first day's trading since the company sold its
financial services arm to the Zurich Group.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the newly merged Allied Zurich PLC lost
ground, reflecting stock analysts' pessimism about the combined
financial unit. Analysts said the rise in British American Tobacco
stock sent a clear message that investors, who had widely seen
BAT's tobacco operations as undervalued because of the effect of
the financial business, were expecting tobacco price increases in
the United States in coming years.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to spin off the financial operations of what had
been BAT Industries PLC was interpreted by some analysts as an
effort to court investors who had been troubled by tobacco-related
litigation in the United States. But Michael Prideaux, a spokesman
for British American Tobacco, based here, dismissed those
assessments as ``the sort of battle cry'' of the tobacco industry's
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at what we were doing,'' Prideaux said, ``it was
to merge the financial services with a very strong partner to
enable them to grow more rapidly.'' American tobacco-related
settlements ``did not play a role at all,'' he said, although ``we
kept an eye on it.''
</P>
<P>
   British American Tobacco led Britain's blue chips Tuesday,
rising 1.285 pounds, or 38 percent, to 4.66 pounds, while the
benchmark British stock index closed slightly lower, in contrast to
gains around 3 percent in Paris and Frankfurt and around 5 percent
on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts ascribed BAT's surge to the end of uncertainty over the
spinoff of the financial services business. ``The market was just
waiting for tangible proof that the de-merger would take place,''
said Tim Young, an analyst with SG Securities. Shares in the
company's financial units, which have merged with the Zurich Group
to form Allied Zurich, closed down 30.5 pence at 7.86 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal with the Zurich Group, investors in BAT
Industries split their old stock equally between British American
Tobacco PLC and Allied Zurich.
</P>
<P>
   BAT Industries went ahead with its asset sale including the
insurers Allied Dunbar and Eagle Star after a British High Court
judge rejected efforts by 48 Blue Cross and Blue Shield health
plans in the United States last week to block the $18.7 billion
deal with the Zurich Group.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the health plans argued that the court should
protect BAT creditors in settlements intended to cover the cost of
treating people with smoking-related illnesses. But BAT maintained
that it was not possible to forecast the outcome of future
litigation. Lord Justice David Neuberger ruled in favor of BAT
Industries, which suspended trading in its stock on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   British American Tobacco, which makes Lucky Strike cigarettes,
is the world's second-largest cigarette producer after Philip
Morris. Its principal unit in the United States is Brown &AMP;
Williamson, a wholly owned subsidiary that has been a defendant in
litigation in Florida, Texas and Mississippi. BAT ascribed falling
tobacco profit last year to settlement costs in the United States
of $431 million and rising American legal fees totaling $144
million.
</P>
<P>
   However, the parent company's direct exposure to American
litigation is limited, according to Prideaux, the spokesman,
because of what he called a ``pretty consistent track record in the
United States of courts' finding that the holding company was
outside their jurisdiction.''
</P>
<P>
   Any ramifications for American tobacco concerns that might
consider spinning off non-tobacco interests were thus uncertain.
``It was probably slightly easier for us to do because we are a
U.K.-based company,'' Prideaux said.
</P>
</TEXT>
