<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW SLIDE MAY RENEW SOME VISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HOYE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Are you a person with vision?
</P>
<P>
   If so, you have my sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   It's nearly impossible these days to have vision, or to think
long term. Nobody's interested. The whole world wants results, and
they want them now, thank you very much.
</P>
<P>
   We live in a world of five-minute doctor visits, drive-through
restaurants and instant gratification. ``Long-term planning'' in
most companies means next week, not next year.
</P>
<P>
   So it has been rather interesting to watch the craziness
surrounding Internet start-up companies. Now here's an industry
where ``long term'' is everything.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody's making money yet, except, perhaps, Yahoo!. Yet
investors have flocked to such companies, flooding them with cash
on the expectation that there's money to be made down the road, as
millions of consumers begin using the new online medium.
</P>
<P>
   There is money to be made. But it ain't happening yet.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet Stock Index, for example, tracks about 50 top
Internet-related stocks. Two-thirds of the companies on the list
operate in the red or just break even.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Wolff's new book, ``Burn Rate,'' details the absurdity
of it all, beginning with the title. ``Burn Rate,'' the former
journalist and entrepreneur points out, refers to the amount of
money a promising start-up company consumes each month in excess of
its income.
</P>
<P>
   It's all so bizarre that even the comic strip ``Doonesbury'' has
gotten into the act, making fun of Internet companies that operate
in the red, yet keep attracting millions of dollars in investment
capital.
</P>
<P>
   But is the tide turning?
</P>
<P>
   The Aug. 31 market crash hit technology stocks hard.
Internet-related stocks took the brunt of it. Stock in Amazon.com,
a hugely successful online book seller, lost 21 percent of its
value Monday, and 4.5 percent more on Sept. 1. Yahoo! sank 17
percent Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Such stocks may have made up their losses by the time you read
this, but many in the industry are wondering whether the honeymoon
is over. Could it be that investors have turned a corner, and from
now on will require a bit more in return for their cash?
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't surprise me. After all, investing in the future
requires vision. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Seniors page debuts &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo! has produced another one of its trademark specialty
areas. This time, the special area is devoted to senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   It's called Yahoo! Senior's Guide, seniors.yahoo.com. (Note:
There is no ``www'' at the beginning of that Web address.)
</P>
<P>
   The site takes all the Web has to offer and filters it, leaving
only those resources that might be interesting to older Americans.
</P>
<P>
   There are familiar categories _ computers, entertainment,
travel, etc. . . . But when you click on them, you're treated to a
group of Web sites and other resources that apply to seniors.
</P>
<P>
   Click on Computers, for example, and you get subcategories
including links to other Web sites for seniors and links to topics
of interest to seniors, such as genealogy.
</P>
<P>
   There also are links to senior-oriented live chats and a host of
message boards on topics ranging from health care to personal
finance. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now, something funny &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Owen Whetzel, a fine gentleman I once worked with in California,
keeps in occasional touch with me via e-mail. And I appreciate
that, too, as he often forwards humorous postings he runs across in
cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   His latest electronic dispatch began:
</P>
<P>
   ``If lawyers can be disbarred, and clergymen defrocked, doesn't
it follow that . . .
</P>
<P>
   - Electricians can be delighted.
</P>
<P>
   - Cowboys can be deranged
</P>
<P>
   - Models can be deposed
</P>
<P>
   - Organ donors can be delivered
</P>
<P>
   - Musicians can be denoted.
</P>
<P>
   - Bedmakers can be debunked.
</P>
<P>
   Hmm. I guess so. Thanks for pointing that out, Owen! &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Hoye is an online editor and covers computer- and
Internet-related issues for Arizona Central, the Web site of The
Arizona Republic. He can be reached at dhoye(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
