<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BALLOT WITHOUT A LEWINSKY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - It's primary election day in Arizona and, once again,
the so-called news media in our community has failed to provide us
with the facts we need to make informed choices.
</P>
<P>
   As a member of the working press, I'm embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   As a member of the voting public, I'm outraged.
</P>
<P>
   How are we supposed to differentiate between good politicians
and bad when all we know about the candidates are their party
affiliations, their qualifications and their positions on the
issues?
</P>
<P>
   Excuse me, but didn't a single hack in this backwater burb think
to ask political hopefuls the basic ``who, what, when, where and
why'' questions?
</P>
<P>
   As in, Whom are you sleeping with?
</P>
<P>
   What exactly do you do?
</P>
<P>
   When do you do it?
</P>
<P>
   Where?
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   OK, maybe we can guess why. But, as for the rest, how can we be
expected to make intelligent decisions about leadership without the
kind of vital information voters receive in cities like Washington,
D.C.?
</P>
<P>
   The candidates say they want to lower taxes. So? What voters
need to know is, did these people ever lie on their tax returns?
</P>
<P>
   Not once? Not on a single deduction? An inflated expense
account? A long shot that came in at the track?
</P>
<P>
   What about health care?
</P>
<P>
   Did any of the folks running for office ever call in ``sick'' on
a really nice day? &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did the dog do it? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then, there's education.
</P>
<P>
   Have our political candidates ever told a teacher the dog ate
their homework?
</P>
<P>
   Did they ever tell a cop they really (begin ital) did (end ital)
come to a complete stop at the intersection? Or that it was their
``index'' finger being used to give directions to another driver?
</P>
<P>
   All political candidates say honesty is important. They all
promise to be truthful.
</P>
<P>
   But, would telephone solicitors agree?
</P>
<P>
   Were the politicians on the line really ``about to sit down for
dinner,'' ``in the middle of changing a diaper'' or ``hard of
hearing.''
</P>
<P>
   And was it true when they told the Jehovah's Witnesses at the
door, ``We don't speakie da English?''
</P>
<P>
   What's wrong with the reporters here?
</P>
<P>
   What's wrong with voters?
</P>
<P>
   All politicians promise to take criminals off the streets,
reduce the number of government regulations and encourage business.
</P>
<P>
   What about (begin ital) their (end ital) business?
</P>
<P>
   Do they eat their broccoli?
</P>
<P>
   Do they drink right out of the milk carton?
</P>
<P>
   Do they brush between meals?
</P>
<P>
   Do they leave the toilet seat up?
</P>
<P>
   Do they cry at Hallmark commercials? &QL; 
 &QL; 
Important questions &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I've watched the national news and read big-city papers. These
things are important. They must be.
</P>
<P>
   Have any of the candidates ever watched ``Jerry Springer''?
</P>
<P>
   Appeared on ``Jerry Springer''?
</P>
<P>
   Invested in an Arkansas real estate deal with Jerry Springer?
</P>
<P>
   Here in Arizona, voters simply haven't been presented with the
kind of data citizens in the rest of the United States seem to
consider essential.
</P>
<P>
   There are occasional flashes.
</P>
<P>
   Like when one candidate for state attorney general produced a TV
commercial calling another candidate a criminal.
</P>
<P>
   Or when a third attorney general candidate went out of her way
to say she is not gay.
</P>
<P>
   But, why aren't reporters asking what would seem to be the
obvious follow-up questions?
</P>
<P>
   Do they dye their hair?
</P>
<P>
   Do they cheat at solitaire?
</P>
<P>
   Have they ever torn the tab from a mattress or pillow?
</P>
<P>
   I don't know what's wrong with us _ lack of savoir-faire, maybe
_ but not a single candidate in our state has been asked to respond
to the one-word inquiry that seems to preoccupy voters everywhere
else:
</P>
<P>
   Intern? &QL; 
 &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
