<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET'S `PAUSE' REFRESHING TO ANALYST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RUSS WILES  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - The recent stock market plunge has been called a lot
of things, some of which can't be printed in a family newspaper.
But Peter Lynch views this summer's decline as a ``pause that
refreshes.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynch, the famed former manager of the Fidelity Magellan Fund in
Boston, said he was hoping earlier this year for the market to
tread water for a while so that corporate profit growth could catch
up to investors' high expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Profit growth, after all, is the main determinant of stock
market performance over the long haul, Lynch said. Yet prices
during 1998's first half vaulted much more dramatically than
earnings themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was rooting for the market not to go up as much so that
earnings could catch up,'' he said in an interview Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch said he wouldn't mind seeing the Dow Jones industrial
average hover between 7,500 and 8,000 for a year or two. The Dow
started 1998 near 7,900 but has dropped below that during the
recent retreat.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, stocks tend to rise roughly in line with profit
growth, Lynch said. From 1945 through 1997, the market advanced
sixtyfold, compared to a fiftyfourfold increase for corporate
profits. But during the first half of 1998, it surged 18 percent
while earnings were unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   ``That (gap) can't last for very long,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch advises people to take market slides in stride as a normal
part of the investment cycle. Since 1970, for instance, stocks have
dropped 10 percent or more on 13 occasions _ about once every two
years. Such declines can't be predicted, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch is spearheading a new Fidelity drive to encourage
investors to gain a better understanding of what they own. He
recently wrote a pamphlet, ``Key Things Every Investor Should
Know,'' that offers tips and a quiz for figuring out the stock
market and related investment topics. The pamphlet is available for
free by calling 800-544-8888.
</P>
<P>
   To underscore his message, Lynch also will appear in Fidelity
television commercials with actress Lily Tomlin starting Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Tomlin will help ``cut through the clutter and deliver what we
think investors need: Peter Lynch's timeless, invaluable principles
of investing,'' said Stephen Cone, president of a Fidelity
marketing department.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch, who is vice chairman of Fidelity's money-management arm
and a trustee for the group's mutual funds, also thinks market
drops are good opportunities for investors to learn a bit more
about themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch cautioned investors to anticipate more modest returns from
stocks in the years ahead compared with what they've seen in the
recent past. Corporate profits have grown at roughly an 8 percent
annual clip since 1945 and aren't likely to deviate much from that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But even at 8 percent a year, you get very powerful
compounding,'' Lynch said. ``At that rate, your money will double
every nine years.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Russ Wiles can be reached at russ.wiles(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 1836EDT &QL; 
