<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4312 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROGERMARIS-AZR &LR;      09-08 1320
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROGERMARIS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE (WITH MARIS AROUND) WAS NOT FAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (Duplication warning: Story also moved in ``A'' category)  
 By SAM LOWE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FARGO, N.D. _ We sat as strangers, sharing space and watching TV
because Mark McGwire might hit a baseball beyond the confines of
Busch Stadium. My companions were all young people who cheered
every time the St. Louis first baseman came to the plate in the
hope that he'd hear them and knock one out of the park.
</P>
<P>
   Although I wished McGwire well, I did not share the enthusiasm
of my temporary associates. Every time McGwire hits a home run, it
diminishes my personal claim to fame.
</P>
<P>
   This goes back to the summer of 1950, when I played baseball
against Roger Maris. I was considerably younger then, and the
passing years have clouded my memory somewhat, but there are things
that stick with you forever.
</P>
<P>
   And Roger Maris was one of those things.
</P>
<P>
   He played for the Fargo American Legion team; I played for
Jamestown, 100 miles to the west. We faced each other twice that
summer. His team won both games by lopsided scores and eventually
went on to capture the state championship.
</P>
<P>
   He was Roger Maras then, (I'll explain that later), a
15-year-old who commanded so much respect that we put on the Maras
Shift every time he came to the plate. He batted left-handed, so in
what we considered a clever display in skill and cunning, we moved
all our infielders and outfielders to the right side of the
diamond, so we could catch the ball when he hit it toward us.
</P>
<P>
   Realistically, however, it was a case of seven players putting
up a brave front while secretly hoping that if he did whack the
ball it would go toward someone else. Even at that tender age,
Maras hit line shots that would have drilled a hole right through
us if we were dumb enough to get in front of one. And we'd be left
standing there with a big cavity in our chest and feeling as stupid
as Wile E. Coyote in the Roadrunner cartoons. We loved baseball,
but none of us was so enamored with the game that we were willing
to sacrifice our bodies for an out, even if it was against Roger
Maras.
</P>
<P>
   The shift was a futile gesture anyway _ we never got him out. He
hit the ball and our infielders ducked, then hollered instructions
to our second line of defense _ the outfielders. A small band of
hearty souls, we had positioned ourselves against the outfield
fences so we could see the ball as it sped toward us. This reduced
the possibility of getting hit on the back of the head by a line
drive.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, it wasn't Roger Maras who was supposed to be doing
this to us. His brother, Rudy, was the original reason for the
Maras Shift because we had played against him the previous year and
he had been very unkind to our pitching staff. But now we also had
to deal with his brother, who was just as talented, even though he
was only 15. It was one of our first exposures to the theory that
life is not fair.
</P>
<P>
   So we played the two games against Fargo, got creamed by what
seemed like a total of 50 runs, and tried to put it all behind us
by joking that we'd been beaten by worse teams, which was true. We
finished the season with a 4-16 record. Roger Maras was selected as
the most valuable player for the Fargo team after it won the state
title. The honor came shortly before his 16th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   I graduated from the American Legion program after that season,
but Roger continued his assault on our family for another year. In
the summer of 1951, my brother Jim pitched against him in a game in
Jamestown. They faced each other four times. My brother struck him
out in their first three encounters, something that still comes up
regularly at family reunions. But on his fourth trip to the plate,
Maras hit the ball so hard that those who witnessed it swear it was
still climbing when it cleared the right-field fence.
</P>
<P>
   They never found the ball. The assumption was that it landed in
the river across the road from the ballpark. That meant it was
airborne for about 400 feet. Understandably, this is still not a
popular discussion topic when our family convenes.
</P>
<P>
   I saw him in person only once more, in 1953. He was 19, playing
with the Fargo-Moorhead Twins, a Cleveland Indians farm team in the
Class C Northern League. His brother and I were teammates on the
North Dakota State Baseball Squad, and Rudy got us free tickets to
the Twins games. One night I yelled at Roger as he ran in from the
outfield. Without breaking stride he waved and said, ``Hey,
Jamestown.'' The gesture not only eased some of the grief he had
caused me and my family, but also elevated my stature in the eyes
of my classmates. ``You know him?'' they asked. ``Yup,'' I replied.
``Played against him a couple times.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time I ever uttered the phrase, and it earned
me so much respect that it has been a standard in my conversational
English since then.
</P>
<P>
   Maras played 114 games with the Twins that summer, hitting .325
with nine homers and earning the league's Rookie of the Year award.
</P>
<P>
   The change in the spelling occurred in 1955, said Sid Cichyi,
who coached the brothers when they attended Shanley High School in
Fargo. ``Roger was playing with Keokuk, Iowa, and some of the fans
began taunting him by emphasizing the last syllable of his name,''
Cichyi said. ``This upset his dad so much that he had the family
name legally changed to Maris.''
</P>
<P>
   Both spellings appear in the Maris memorabilia on display at the
Roger Maris museum, located in the West Acres shopping mall in
Fargo. The museum, actually a large glass enclosure in one of the
walkways, tracks Maris' baseball career from his American Legion
days until he retired in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   A steady trickle of fans stopped to look and comment Saturday.
``He had such a sweet swing,'' said Bev Grande of Fargo, who
watched him many years ago. ``I hate to see his record broken,
because it means something to me personally. But at least the
attention is getting him some favorable publicity. When he was
chasing Babe Ruth's record, the sportswriters didn't like him,
because Ruth was such a hero.''
</P>
<P>
   An elderly man who refused to give his name was more emphatic.
``I'd like to break McGwire's kneecap,'' he growled. ``Now
everybody will forget about Maris, and he was a great ballplayer.''
</P>
<P>
   The attitude was different in the watering hole where dozens of
us watched McGwire's pursuit of the home run record over the
weekend. Whenever McGwire came to bat, everyone cheered except me.
And when he hit No. 60 on Saturday, a few of the younger people
showed unrestrained exuberance. I questioned this show of
non-support for the hometown hero who is immortalized a couple of
miles south of where we sat and buried just a few miles north.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Lewis, 27, gave me a plausible explanation. ``The older
people don't want the record broken because they associate with
Maris,'' he said. ``But he had his time. McGwire is our generation.
Let him have his glory now.''
</P>
<P>
   So, I guess that makes me old. And I realized that I've also
been rather selfish in this matter. For 37 years, I have been using
my playing time against Roger Maris as one of those little
eyebrow-lifters tossed into a conversation to get attention. But my
position as a minor sports celebrity is on shaky ground and will
diminish now that McGwire tied Maris with his 61st home run, then
surpasses it with his 62nd. I firmly believe he will do it. And
that will reduce my bragging rights to a mere whisper of what they
used to be. It will still be important to me, but overall, my niche
in sports history just got a lot smaller.
</P>
<P>
   I don't climb down from my self-constructed pedestal willingly,
however. Even as I write this, I am thinking about Darin Erstad, a
rising star with the Anaheim Angels. He's from Jamestown. There's
got to be some tie-in between me and him . . . &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
