<HEADLINE>
MURDOCH MOVE FOR MANCHESTER UNITED UNSETTLES BRITISH FANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Given that most British people think baseball is an
unfathomable American bastardization of cricket, few here batted an
eye last year when media mogul Rupert Murdoch bought the Los
Angeles Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   But now that the Australian-born tycoon has set his sights on
Manchester United, England's most famous and financially successful
soccer team, all hell has broken loose. It is suddenly the biggest
story in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   There are few things that arouse the passions of the English
like soccer, or what they call football. But one thing that comes
close is anything that the ambitious, controversial tycoon touches.
Put together, soccer and Murdoch are a volatile mix, politically
and culturally, in England and the rest of Britain.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Murdoch's BSkyB cable network confirmed that it was
trying to buy venerable Man United, an announcement that sent the
team's stock value soaring about $190 million in a day.
</P>
<P>
   Outraged fans plan to picket at Wednesday night's game at Old
Trafford, Man United's hallowed stadium. They are convinced that
Murdoch wants to corner the television market on the team, making
its games exclusive to his cable network, which already has a
virtual monopoly on Premier League games. As Sky prepares to launch
a 200-channel digital network, landing the games of the New York
Yankees of English soccer would be an enticing lure for potential
subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch's initial offer of about $900 million for the team has
spawned interest from other corporations, including Enic, an
entertainment conglomerate which has financial backing from the US
giant Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   It is not just Man United fans who are lamenting the bidding war
that Murdoch has started. Fans of the 19 other Premier League clubs
fear that if Murdoch acquires the team, his network will show Man
United games at the exclusion of others.
</P>
<P>
   Soccer fans here take their game seriously, and consider it
beneath the purely bottom-line thinking that dominates most
professional sports in the rest of Europe and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   There is a growing fear that soccer, one of the few things that
provides common ground for all classes and races in a society often
divided by class and race, will become just another commodity to be
bought and sold by the highest bidder.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in his shop in North London, Nick Marcos, an elderly
tailor, shrugged as he bemoaned the growing commercialization of a
game he played as a child in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about money today,'' he said. ``The game has become
secondary.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the threat that Murdoch's sudden interest in Man United
poses to English football, it refocuses attention on the
relationship between Murdoch and British Prime Minister Tony Blair,
whose government must approve the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Since his May 1997 landslide election, Blair has enjoyed an
extended honeymoon with the press, especially Murdoch's holdings.
But Blair's alleged coziness with Murdoch continues to surface as a
sore point, a welcome development for political opponents who have
little else to beat him up with.
</P>
<P>
   Conscious of that, Blair's closest adviser, Peter Mandelson, the
trade and industry secretary who can approve or veto the deal,
swiftly announced that Murdoch's bid would be given intense
scrutiny to make sure it does not pose an undue threat to
consumers. Fans are not reassured by Mandelson's close friendship
with Murdoch's daughter, Elisabeth, Sky's CEO.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers say there is probably little the government can do to
stop Murdoch from buying Man United, but politically it must be
seen to be doing all it can to stop him. If the government blocks
Murdoch, it will score points with fans everywhere but risk
incurring the wrath of Murdoch's extensive media empire.
</P>
<P>
   All this bother over a soccer team leaves some people puzzled.
As London's Evening Standard observed in an editorial, ``It says
much about national priorities that there has been far more public
anguish about Mr. Rupert Murdoch's threatened bid for Manchester
United than ever there was about the creation of his dominant media
empire in Britain.''
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch controls about 40 percent of the British media, from
racy tabloids that showcase naked women to the more upmarket
broadsheet, The Times of London. If he succeeds in his latest
acquisition bid, he will own just one soccer team.
</P>
<P>
   But, for millions of people, it's the only team that matters.
</P>
</TEXT>
