<P>
   DROUGHT-TEXAS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Old farm joke: What happens when you bet the
farm and lose? Answer: You just make another enemy. Otto Wagner
Jr., 43, who farms 3,600 acres in the Lower Rio Grande Valley,
retells the joke. But, frankly, there's little laughter in his
region, or in other parts of Texas, where the Drought of '98
lingers. The drought came as the great leveler this year. Many
farmers are on the brink of failure, agricultural economists warn.
And August's rains in some parts of the state came too late to do
much good for this year's crops. The Fort Worth Star-Telegram
recently visited farmers in three regions _ Ellis County south of
Dallas, Gaines and Dawson counties in Northwest Texas, and the
Lower Rio Grande Valley _ for a closer look at the drought's
impact. Some said they were considering leaving the business.
Others vowed to survive on the farm. By WORTH WREN JR. Story will
move in ``a'' general news category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THEFT RING &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TOLAR, Texas _ From behind the closed gate of the Lawhon Exotic
Ranch, officials say, the tentacles of a theft ring reached out to
five states, to Costa Rica, and even to a deceased witness in the
Whitewater investigation. Now there are only metal barns, some emus
and the occasional donkey on a well-kept patch of land just outside
Tolar. But this year authorities discovered a huge collection of
stolen vehicles _ pickups, front-end loaders and earth-moving
machines _ on the property. The Department of Public Safety says it
was the most expensive collection of stolen vehicles it has
uncovered. Since January, when the ranch's owner, Charles W.
Lawhon, 48, was accused of stealing a Johnson County earthmover,
authorities have found more than 120 stolen vehicles valued at more
than $3 million. They were scattered across Arkansas, Missouri,
Oklahoma, Minnesota and North Dakota, and the DPS says that some
vehicles may even have been shipped to Costa Rica. By BILL HANNA.
Story will move in ``a'' general news category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
