<HEADLINE>
DON'T TAKE RISKS IF YOU CAN'T AFFORD IT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAMELA YIP 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the wake of the turmoil in the stock market last week, a
colleague made an interesting remark to me about risk.
</P>
<P>
   We always talk about people selling stocks when the market
drops, but who buys those shares and why are they so willing to buy
when the market looks so risky?
</P>
<P>
   Part of the answer is lower stock prices, but that's not all of
it.
</P>
<P>
   Much has been said in the aftermath of the market's carnage
about whether you'd be nuts to buy into stocks now.
</P>
<P>
   I'm a big believer in buying on the dips, but I also believe you
need to put risk in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   There's no doubt that the stocks of some high-quality companies
have fallen to tempting prices. But the reward for picking up these
battered stocks will only go to the patient. Unless you're able to
part with your money for as long as five years, you shouldn't be in
stocks, especially now, when the market's so volatile.
</P>
<P>
   ``If investors are going in with the idea of trying to make some
money on the short term, they may or may not win because of that,''
said Henry Lartigue, chief investment officer of Chase Bank of
Texas. ``Market movements over the short term tend to be random,
but over the long term, the stock market rises.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if you're a long-term investor, you may be running just
as much risk being out of the market now as you would going in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The history of the market shows over time, those who bought on
dips were rewarded at some point in the future,'' said David Lapin,
president of Lapin &AMP; Wigginton Asset Management in Houston, a money
management firm.
</P>
<P>
   With stock prices as low as they are, you actually would be
taking on less risk if you buy in now because stock prices have
fallen so sharply.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's market turmoil brought stock prices down about 20
percent off their 52-week highs, Lartigue said.
</P>
<P>
   Don't shop for a stock just on the basis of how far it has
fallen. It's not a bargain unless the company also has good
management and the likelihood for steady earnings growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are buying a good-quality company and your intention is
to hold it for the long term, then I don't think you're assuming
too much risk,'' said Lynn Bernard Jr., executive vice president of
global investment strategies at Pinnacle Management &AMP; Trust in
Houston, money managers. ``Over the long term, there are plenty of
companies that you could argue could do quite well.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether you buy in up or down markets, there's no avoiding risk.
But you can take steps to limit the dangers.
</P>
<P>
   First, ask yourself what's the potential return on an investment
vs. the potential loss. Look at the price/earnings ratio of the
stock, which is a measure of how much investors are willing to pay
for a company's earning power.
</P>
<P>
   How does the ratio compare with that of the overall market and
the price/earnings ratios of other companies in the industry? Is it
too high or too low relative to the company's earnings?
</P>
<P>
   If you find a stock you like, take it in small bites. Don't bank
your entire retirement nest egg on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should buy stocks in unemotional quantities,'' said money
manager Richard J. Fruth of Richard J. Fruth &AMP; Associates. ``Buy
small amounts and if it goes lower, you can add to it. This is not
an all-or-nothing business. You don't go from zero-invested to
fully invested.''
</P>
<P>
   Spread your money among different types of investments because
diversification will save you in a down market.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the recent market shakeout saw the stocks of
Houston companies getting hit harder and sooner than the rest of
the market because of the city's heavy concentration of energy
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Diversification doesn't mean going to the other extreme. You
could be asking for trouble if you bail out of stocks in favor of
cash investments.
</P>
<P>
   Certificates of deposits and savings accounts may shelter you
from day-to-day fluctuations, but can't protect your spending power
from the ravages of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   If you think you have too much money invested in stocks,
gradually reduce your stock holdings and move your money into less
risky investments such as bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, trust your gut. You ultimately are the best person to
gauge how much risk you're comfortable with.
</P>
<P>
   ``When things start to decline _ there are bad headlines in the
papers and on television _ will you have the stomach for the market
volatility and the broad-based pessimism that tends to come with
it?'' Peter Lynch, Fidelity Investments' famed money manager, asked
in a new education campaign aimed at investors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pamela Yip can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to pamela.yip(at)chron.com, or call
(713) 220-2000 and enter access code 1003. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
