<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEATRICE'S DISAPPEARING ACT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: A few years ago, you couldn't turn on the TV without seeing a
``We're Beatrice'' commercial. I haven't seen one in years. Did the
company fold?
</P>
<P>
   _ T.F.F., via the Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: The ``We're Beatrice'' campaign was the brainchild of former
chief executive James Dutt, who wanted to identify the company's
diverse consumer and food products more strongly with the Beatrice
name.
</P>
<P>
   After Dutt was forced to resign in 1985, the Chicago company was
taken private in an $8.2 billion leveraged buyout. The new owners
immediately launched an effort to pay debts by selling off Beatrice
holdings, including Avis, Playtex and Tropicana.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the company's nonfood.MDNM/ operations were reorganized
as a new company, E-II Holdings, which was later sold to American
Brands.
</P>
<P>
   After the buyout, the huge promotional campaign was not resumed
and the Beatrice logo was removed from company products. In 1986,
then-chief executive Donald Kelly told Fortune what the new slogan
should be: ```We're Beatrice, now you'll have to find us.''' The
last Beatrice holdings were sold to ConAgra in 1990 for $1.36
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm a big fan of ``Good Will Hunting'' star Minnie Driver.
Where can I contact her?
</P>
<P>
   _ B.K., Oakland, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A: Amelia ``Minnie'' Driver can be contacted in care of Creative
Artists Agency, 9830 Wilshire Blvd., Beverly Hills, CA 90212.
</P>
<P>
   Driver, 27, is a 1991 graduate of the Webber-Douglas Academy of
Dramatic Art in London. As she built a career on British
television, Driver made ends meet by performing as a jazz vocalist
and guitarist at London clubs.
</P>
<P>
   The first chance for many U.S. moviegoers to see her was the
1995 film ``Circle of Friends.'' She was nominated for a Best
Supporting Actress Oscar for ``Good Will Hunting.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Driver has been promoting ``The Governess,'' a
historical drama set in 1840s London.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is Barbara Bel Geddes using her real name? Also, where was
she born and raised?
</P>
<P>
   _ E.T.H., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: The longtime ``Dallas'' star was born on Oct. 31, 1922, in
New York. Her father, Norman Bel Geddes, was a stage and industrial
designer who used a professional name slightly different from his
birth name _ Norman Melancton Geddes.
</P>
<P>
   Bel Geddes, who missed one season of ``Dallas'' because of
health problems, has been retired since the series went off the air
in 1990. Fans can write to her in care of Shapira and Associates,
15301 Ventura Blvd., Suite 345, Sherman Oaks, CA 91403.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
