<SLUG> BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PRODIGY MURDERED IN HIS PRIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One thing leads to another. We were talking about movies
generally, then movie stars in particular, and finally Debbie
Reynolds specifically. Reference was made to the song ``Tammy,''
which a very young Debbie recorded quite successfully after
appearing opposite a very young Peter Fonda in ``Tammy and the
Bachelor'' so long ago.
</P>
<P>
   One thing leads to another. Wasn't that movie based on a popular
novel? Indeed it was, and I offered the information that the novel
title was ``Tammy Out of Time'' and that the author, a woman named
Cyd Ricketts Sumner, was the victim in an unsolved murder.
</P>
<P>
   One thing leads to another. We talked about authors known to
have been murdered, or believed to have been murdered in cases of
official suicides. That enabled me to talk about David Graham
Phillips, author of the great novel ``Susan Lenox, Her Fall and
Rise,'' of which I may have more to say soon, in print. Then
someone _ indeed, a professor _ mentioned a name I had almost
forgotten completely; and I really was surprised to hear the name
of Paul Leicester Ford from someone else's lips.
</P>
<P>
   Back there in high school English, junior year, we read two
historical novels, both published around the century's turn. One
was set in a Missouri embattled and divided during the Civil War
period. Its author was Winston Churchill _ the ``other'' one, an
American of reliable bestsellerdom well before his distant British
cousin attained a higher glory.
</P>
<P>
   The other work was ``Janice Meredith,'' an often pulsating
narrative of the American Revolution. Its author was Paul Leicester
Ford, of whom I then knew nothing; nor, I believe, did the teacher,
although she certainly knew about Churchill and rated him the
better author. She was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Some years later, I learned some things about Paul Leicester
Ford that to me were quite interesting.
</P>
<P>
   In historical scholarship, Paul Ford was a child prodigy almost
as amazing as little Amadeus Mozart in music. He was well-born, and
his father was a literatus with an extensive private library that
was exploited by the boy's precociousness.
</P>
<P>
   Paul, at age 8, was author of a patriotic essay addressed to an
adult readership, printed in a newspaper. At age 10, he undertook
what he said would be his life's work, that of collecting and
editing for posterity many historical accounts that were sliding
into obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   His heroes were Thomas Jefferson and George Washington. From
1892 to 1894, Ford issued incrementally in 10 volumes ``The
Writings of Thomas Jefferson,'' still recognized as authoritative
and the basis for the Jefferson volume in the Library of America
series.
</P>
<P>
   Then Ford yielded to that well-known agent, popular demand, and
became a historical novelist. ``The Honorable Peter Stirling''
appeared in 1895, when he was 29, and made him famous. In 1896 he
was a sales leader in nonfiction, as his ``The True George
Washington'' humanized an almost mythical Washington, presenting
his flaws without diminishing his greatness.
</P>
<P>
   Ford labored several years on the manuscript of ``Janice
Meredith,'' ultimately the popular sensation of 1899. It brought
the American historical novel into heady vogue. Mary Johnston's
``To Have and to Hold'' was the nation's top seller in 1900, as was
Churchill's ``The Crisis'' in 1901.
</P>
<P>
   After all these years, ``Janice Meredith'' remains the
definitive novel of the American Revolution. Walter Edmonds'
``Drums Along the Mohawk'' and some of Kenneth Roberts' works
surely are better; but they deal with fragments of the Revolution,
where Ford did the whole number _ Paul Revere's ride; the Boston
Tea Party; Patrick Henry's impassioned address to the Virginia
House of Burgesses; the winter at Valley Forge; Washington crossing
the Delaware; the battles of Yorktown, Lexington and Saratoga; and
the surrender of Cornwallis. Washington and Jefferson are major
characters in the novel.
</P>
<P>
   A heroine was needed, and Janice Meredith was Ford's entirely
fictional creation; but his historical fidelity gave the narrative
great validity. It's easy to believe that the novel would still be
famous today, as likely also would other historical novels Ford
might have written, if ...
</P>
<P>
   If he hadn't been murdered. As a shining success in life and
literature, Paul Leicester Ford inherited his father's considerable
estate. His older brother, Malcolm, a dissolute failure, was
disinherited. The jealous Malcolm shot and killed his brother in
1902 when Paul Ford was only 36.
</P>
<P>
   Talk swung back to movies when someone suggested that ``Janice
Meredith'' might be an apt property for one. Well, it ``was''
filmed, rather elaborately, back in the silent era as a Marion
Davies vehicle. Sure enough, it marked the feature-film debut of
W.C. Fields, in a comical cameo as a British soldier.
</P>
<P>
   That got us talking about William Claude Fields, and Robert
Lewis Taylor's book about him, and Rod Steiger's portrayal ... one
thing leads to another.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Swindell is books editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7731. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
