<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-SERIES-SEASON-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVENTURES, ALL IN A ROW  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 13) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many of us in New York complain yearly about pandering repertory
and incoherent programs, but solutions are arriving from every
side. I hope the public responds, because music this season is
being served with a sense of adventure unusual to the decade.
</P>
<P>
   The watchword is ``series,'' and there are a lot of them:
coherent looks at either individuals or ideas.
</P>
<P>
   A series from Great Performers at Lincoln Center asks whether
important music should be seen as well as heard. Peter Sellars
stages Bach cantatas sung by Lorraine Hunt in March. Theatrical
treatment is also given to Schoenberg's ``Pierrot Lunaire'' (John
Kelly, Sarah Rothenberg and colleagues) in January and Mahler's
``Kindertotenlieder'' (Robert Lepage and Rebecca Blankenship) in
February.
</P>
<P>
   Jessye Norman and Bill T. Jones have a similar project in May,
and the Brooklyn Academy of Music chimes in with Schubert's
``Winterreise'' as dramatized by Jurgen Tamchina in November.
Should we just listen? Should stage people leave well enough alone?
We shall see.
</P>
<P>
   Also from Great Performers come six Elgar events in January,
four of which bravely pair the composer with Beethoven. Colin Davis
conducts the London Symphony Orchestra in three of the programs at
Avery Fisher Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Although we must wade through another Beethoven cycle at the New
York Philharmonic this fall (something neither an already lazy
public nor Beethoven needs), there are signs of life at this
cautious and conservative institution. A composer-as-theme event
remembers Gershwin's centennial in December, with the pianist Andre
Previn moving between the concert Gershwin and his jazz
counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   Sofia Gubaidulina will come and stay as well, her weeklong
residence in the spring offering a newly commissioned concerto for
two violas.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly Haydn is getting the attention he deserves. The
Orchestra of St. Luke's explores symphonic and operatic repertory
in three concerts led by Franz Bruggen, Charles Mackerras and Roger
Norrington. St. Lukes's chamber players add three more concerts of
their own. Haydn is best heard surrounded by more Haydn, not as an
isolated throat-clearer in mixed programs.
</P>
<P>
   Four Cleveland Orchestra concerts at Carnegie Hall in May
constitute a double theme: Debussy and Ravel (led by Pierre
Boulez), and Mahler (led by Christoph von Dohnanyi). Here are
sustained looks by a great orchestra and two great conductors well
suited to the repertories.
</P>
<P>
   As the 20th century ends, a better idea of the period in
retrospect is now with us, and interesting examples arrive this
season from every side. Bernd Alois Zimmermann's ``Requiem for a
Young Poet'' crosses the Atlantic for the first time, when Michael
Gielen conducts the Southwest Radio Symphony Orchestra of Freiburg
at Carnegie Hall in April.
</P>
<P>
   Operas like Thomas Ades's ``Powder Her Face'' (the Brooklyn
Philharmonic), ``Moses und Aron'' and ``Wozzeck'' (the Metropolitan
Opera) and Astor Piazzolla's ``Maria de Buenos Aires,'' Steve
Reich's ``Hindenburg'' and the Philip Glass-Robert Wilson
``Monsters of Grace'' (all at the Brooklyn Academy of Music) offer
substance and variety.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott Carter will be everywhere this season. James Levine and
the Met Chamber Ensemble look at 20th-century Central Europe in
three Carnegie Hall concerts of unusual richness: Ligeti,
Schoenberg, Poulenc, Berg and Webern. Note, too, the Met
Orchestra's premiere of Milton Babbitt's Piano Concerto No. 2 with
Robert Taub.
</P>
<P>
   Another series of note has a man as a theme, and he will be
doing nearly everything but selling tickets. In the spring at
Carnegie Hall, Alfred Brendel appears as recitalist, concerto
soloist, accompanist, chamber player and poet. (Brendel will read
his own work at Weill Recital Hall.)
</P>
<P>
   It all looks too good to be true: Schoenberg and Berg in the
same Met season, the return of Reich's ``Music for 18 Musicians''
in the Brooklyn program, the rare look at Zimmermann's big vocal
piece, the proffering of styles as varied as Piazzolla and
Gubaidulina. There is much to look forward to.
</P>
</TEXT>
