   MARKET (New York) _ Stock prices continue their wild ride, but
the vertiginous swings leave investors cheering, as the Dow Jones
industrial average rises 380.53 points, its biggest point gain
ever. Broader market averages also record hefty gains, partly
reversing their recent steep declines. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   KENYA-RECONSTRUCT (Nairobi, Kenya) _ A reconstruction of the
Nairobi bombing, based on interviews with guards and other
witnesses, shows that the embassy was left vulnerable to the most
rudimentary attack. By James C. McKinley Jr. With graphic. 2,500
words.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-MIDDLECLASS (Moscow) _ Until recent weeks, Moscow's
professional elite had been insulated from Russia's economic ills,
but now all that has changed. Russia's financial turmoil is taking
a big toll on the small but visible middle class, working for
banks, real estate and advertising agencies, start-up companies and
Western firms. It has also cut a swath through the class of foreign
bankers, brokers, traders, technicians and adventurers who came
here to cash in. By Celestine Bohlen. With graphic. 1,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   BABY-SEXCHOICE (Undated) _ With an announcement that is
producing applause and handwringing, doctors at a fertility center
near Washington say that they can substantially stack the odds that
a couple can have a baby of the sex they choose. The report is to
be published Wednesday in the Journal Human Reproduction. By Gina
Kolata. 1,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   Reefer:
</P>
<P>
   AFFIRM-IMPACT (Undated) _ A major new study of the records and
experiences of tens of thousands of students over 20 years at the
nation's elite colleges concludes that the colleges' affirmative
action policies created the backbone of the black middle class and
taught white classmates the value of integration. By Ethan Bronner.
2,000 words.
</P>
