<SLUG> BC-NIVOLA-FILMS-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM A FAMILY OF PAINTERS, A QUICK-CHANGE ARTIST 
</HEADLINE>
   Justine Elias writes about theater, television and film from New
York.  
(bl) 
 By JUSTINE ELIAS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Few actors, however successful, can say that they
have a museum in the family, but Alessandro Nivola can boast of
two: one, devoted to his grandfather, Italian sculptor Constantino
Nivola, is situated in the artist's hometown in Sardinia, and a
second, a far more modest and decidedly unofficial archive in
Manhattan, is devoted to the actor himself.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Nivola, then a rising Broadway performer who had
done a few small film and television roles, landed the part of
Nicolas Cage's villainous younger brother and partner in crime in
the thriller ``Face/Off.'' Packing only a single suitcase, the
actor traveled to Los Angeles, expecting to work a few months and
then return to New York. But while he was on the West Coast, he was
evicted from his Greenwich Village apartment, and had to ask
friends to retrieve his belongings before they were tossed into the
garbage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a bin in Manhattan Mini Storage with my former life in
it, everything that was once me,'' said Nivola, 26. He added
mischievously, ``I hope my old landlord reads this and feels very
guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the actor decided then to find a new home in Los
Angeles, and earned rave reviews for his performance as the
eccentric, anti-social bomb maker in ``Face/Off,'' his career has
not followed a conventional Hollywood path.
</P>
<P>
   In his next movie, ``Best Laid Plans,'' a drama starring Reese
Witherspoon and Josh Brolin that is to be released next spring, he
plays a graduate student turned con artist, and in ``I Want You,''
a forthcoming British film by Michael Winterbottom that is set in
the seaside town of Hastings, Nivola plays a paroled murderer
seeking to rekindle a forbidden love affair _ a role he researched
by spending three days in Brixton prison in South London.
</P>
<P>
   Winterbottom said the actor's regional British working-class
accent and manner became so convincing that members of the film's
crew were later startled to hear him speak in his normal voice.
They knew all along, objectively, that he was American, said the
director, but he's the kind of actor who can become completely
hidden in a role.
</P>
<P>
   Nivola's former co-star Cage, who has seen ``I Want You,''
agreed. ``Alessandro's a chameleon,'' said Cage, who added that he
was amused and inspired by his colleague's ideas as they created
their twisted, symbiotic screen relationship in ``Face/Off.''
</P>
<P>
   Nivola's facility with accents is coming in handy in his next
movie, a new adaptation of Jane Austen's ``Mansfield Park,'' now
filming in Britain. He plays the aristocratic Henry Crawford, whom
the actor describes as one of Austen's ``more ambiguous cads.''
</P>
<P>
   For Nivola, who was born in Boston and reared in several
Northeastern college towns, this international career has been a
welcome surprise. Though he grew up in a family of visual artists _
his mother, a grandmother, an aunt and younger brother are all
painters _ he became interested in performing at an early age, and
asked to be enrolled in summer drama courses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a mimic, an imitator, and like my father, who is a
university professor, the only non-artist in the family,'' he said.
``I was always doing impressions of people. Later, I did lots of
tortured monologues where I had to cry, dredging up whatever tragic
history I could think of at age 12.''
</P>
<P>
   As an English literature student at Yale University, Nivola
worked in regional theater, even skipping a few weeks of classes to
perform in a Seattle production of an Athol Fugard play. Though
Nivola longed to try out for film and television roles, his first
agent advised him to wait. The strategy paid off when Nivola won a
key role in the 1995 Roundabout Theater production of Turgenev's
``Month in the Country,'' starring Helen Mirren.
</P>
<P>
   Though he has already tackled an impressive range of roles,
Nivola still contends with a certain degree of misapprehension
about who he really is. ``Early on in New York, because of my name,
I was constantly being called in to audition for roles as
bricklayers,'' said the actor, who resembles a Northern Italian
version of James Dean.
</P>
<P>
   ``And after `Face/Off,' people knew me as this strange fellow I
played. My agents would submit my name and people would say, `Well,
isn't he _ I mean, he's like Rain Man!' I went through a period
where I had to meet everyone in town, look them in the eye and show
them that I am a functional human being. Now, though, I think
people can alter that first impression.''
</P>
</TEXT>
