<SLUG> BC-CAMBODIA-UNREST-350&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMBODIAN TROOPS DESTROY TENT CITY, ROUT PROTESTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By SETH MYDANS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia _ Without warning Cambodian troops ripped
down a two-week-old protest campsite just after noon Tuesday and
spent the rest of the day chasing stone-throwing mobs through the
streets, flailing at them with sticks and firing automatic weapons
in the air.
</P>
<P>
   A number of people were injured, but no deaths or gunshot wounds
were reported, although officers said their troops were firing live
ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   The destruction of the tent city, which had become home to
hundreds of people who were supporting the losers in a
parliamentary election in July, appeared to break an agreement
reached hours earlier that would have produced a peaceful end to
the sit-in.
</P>
<P>
   The government, led by the incumbent strongman and official
winner of the election, Hun Sen, had also promised that the leader
of the protest, Sam Rainsy, would not be arrested. But Sam Rainsy
remained under the protection of the United Nations in the
Cambodiana Hotel, where he prepared to spend a second night Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   After two hand grenades exploded at his residence early Monday,
Hun Sen ordered the arrest of his opponents and barred them from
leaving the country. But the arrest order was later delayed. One
person was killed and several others were wounded on Monday when
soldiers fired into crowds outside the Cambodiana.
</P>
<P>
   Hun Sen made no official statement Tuesday, and there was a
sense of anarchy in the streets of the capital six weeks after an
election that had been intended to cement a frail democracy and
bring new stability.
</P>
<P>
   The scene included shooting, beating, running and shouting from
one street to the next as packs of young men with motorbikes
taunted soldiers and families leaned from balconies to watch. But
there was no clear aim to the protests.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sam Rainsy and the royalist party leader, Prince
Norodom Ranariddh, have raised hundreds of complaints about fraud
and intimidation, most assessments by foreign and Cambodian
political analysts agree that such irregularities were probably not
enough to have changed the overall outcome.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The anger that was evident in the streets Tuesday, both among
demonstrators and security forces, appeared to be less a reflection
of electoral loyalties than of the frustrations and brutalities and
poverty brought on by unending violence and political feuding.
</P>
<P>
   There was hatred in the eyes of the young man who pulled his
T-shirt up to his neck and dared soldiers to shoot him, and there
was hatred in the eyes of the soldiers who chased him, brandishing
iron bars and sticks with nails in them.
</P>
<P>
   The sun was at its hottest and people were dozing on straw mats
after a midday meal when 100 soldiers and riot police officers with
helmets, plastic shields and electric-shock batons advanced into
the campsite that Sam Rainsy called Democracy Square.
</P>
<P>
   The troops shot in the air, and a fire truck turned a high-power
hose on the blue plastic lean-tos. Whacking at the squatters with
the rifle butts and kicking over cooking pots, the soldiers drove
1,000 or so people from the makeshift campground.
</P>
<P>
   Some people carried small children as they fled. Some balanced
sleeping mats and pots on their heads like war refugees.
</P>
<P>
   As the troops began ripping down the site, looting motorbikes
and other belongings as they went, many of those who had been
evicted formed a crowd outside the nearby royal palace. They were
augmented by hundreds of the jobless young men who loiter about the
city committing petty crimes and making a few pennies giving rides
on their motorbikes.
</P>
<P>
   The running battles began under the mustard-yellow walls of the
palace with their white crenelated ornaments. Helmeted officers
charged, swinging their staves at the stands of fruit sellers. A
pyramid of coconuts bounced into the street.
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers began to beat a man dressed all in yellow but released
him when the rioters hurled a volley of stones at them. The
soldiers advanced, batting aside the stones with their plastic
shields like hockey goalies.
</P>
<P>
   The rioters threw bottles filled with gasoline. But they were
plastic water bottles and simply started small brief fires on the
asphalt.
</P>
<P>
   Then a volley of automatic gunfire broke out. A U.N. official
raised his arms, shouting: ``Hold it! Stop! Stop it!''
</P>
<P>
   Instead the soldiers began running toward the rioters, some
firing their weapons from their hips. Troops chased rioters down
alleyways and toward the Tonle Sap River, where two buses with
tourists from Hong Kong were parked.
</P>
<P>
   Soon the mobs had spread through the city, near the ancient Wat
Phnom pagoda, in front of the railway station, outside the
Information Ministry, around the central market and across the
street from the Cambodiana.
</P>
<P>
   As the sun set the mobs began to disperse, and the streets fell
silent as scavengers picked among the discarded plastic bags and
soiled sleeping mats of the abandoned campsite.
</P>
</TEXT>
