</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-TERROR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP BEHIND OMAGH BOMBING DECLARES CEASE-FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JAMES F. CLARITY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ A splinter group of the Irish
Republican Army that killed 29 people in a bomb attack in the town
of Omagh three weeks ago said in a statement Tuesday that it had
permanently ended its campaign of violence.
</P>
<P>
   The statement, by the Real IRA, means that with one exception
all paramilitary groups in Northern Ireland, Roman Catholic and
Protestant, are now observing cease-fires.
</P>
<P>
   The curtailment of violence improved the atmosphere in which the
politicians of this British province will try to enact the
provisions of a peace agreement approved last spring by the
Catholic minority and the Protestant majority. The agreement, which
was overwhelmingly approved in referendums here and in the Irish
Republic, envisions reforms that will give the minority more
political power and the Irish Republic more influence in northern
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The 14-month cease-fire by the IRA has allowed the peace effort
to move forward. But smaller groups, like the Real IRA, continued
their violence, charging that the agreement was a sellout of
republican principles since it did not establish a united Ireland,
free of British control, run from Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that this is now a complete end to all our violence,''
said John Hume, the mainstream Catholic leader who started the
peace effort six years ago in talks with Gerry Adams, the president
of the IRA's political arm, Sinn Fein.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us involved in the political process,'' Hume said,
``must now dedicate all our energies toward building new political
institutions which will be an eternal monument to the victims of
our troubles.''
</P>
<P>
   Hume, who has reduced his personal role in the peace effort for
health reasons, has been nominated for the Nobel Peace Prize.
</P>
<P>
   Officials here and in Dublin welcomed the Real IRA statement.
The group is made up of about 50 operatives, including men who were
bomb experts for the IRA.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Continuity IRA, another splinter group, has not
declared a cease-fire. Security officials say it has not been
active in recent months and the police denied a claim by the group
that it attacked a police car last week.
</P>
<P>
   Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern said of the Real IRA
cease-fire, ``This does nothing for the people who who were killed
in Omagh or for the relatives of the victims.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the Irish government would continue to search for those
who planted the 500-pound bomb in Omagh, in the center of the
province, on Aug. 15. And he suggested that the government would be
helped by the package of new laws approved by the parliament last
week, which are intended to make it easier for the police and
courts to imprison suspects in terrorist cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the cease-fire is to do with the new legislation and
the outcry of the people over the atrocity,'' Ahern said.
Parliamentary opposition members in Dublin had asked why, if new
laws were needed to control terrorism, they had not been proposed
until after the Omagh attack. The new laws change the rules of
evidence in favor of prosecutors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
