<SLUG> BC-CHINA-RUSSIAN-MARKET-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUBLE'S PLUNGE DARKENS RUSSIAN MARKET IN BEIJING 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: RUSSIA-MARKETPLACE, RUSSIA-POLITICS) 
(nk) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Normally the Yabao Road market here is a bustling
place, with more than 2,000 bountiful stalls crammed full of gaudy
fur coats, bejeweled fuzzy sweaters, lavish blond wigs and
formidable lacy bras _ reflecting the latest fashion trends not of
Beijing, but of Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Here, throngs of independent Russian traders buy cheap Chinese
goods in bulk for sale back home, providing a brisk business for
the market's Chinese stall-owners, many former government employees
who have gone into business for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But the ruble's plunge over the last two weeks has transformed
this once-prosperous market into something of a ghost town. The
Russians can no longer afford to buy here. So, on this steamy
summer day, on the block that begins at the Moscow Restaurant, the
only residents of the vast outdoor market are anxious store owners,
drawing on cigarettes or playing chess, and idle freight company
employees watching television and playing cards.
</P>
<P>
   Business is off by 80 or 90 percent, they say, now that the
Russians are gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money I've made in the last two weeks is not enough for
food, let alone the rent,'' Liu Zhanguo, 22, said, looking up from
a newspaper in a room full of lifeless furs. ``All our business is
from Russia, so we are finished if the ruble doesn't rebound.''
</P>
<P>
   At stall nine, which sells up-market children's snowsuits, a man
named Sun sits glumly on a wooden chair. He said he had made a lot
of money here since he quit his job in the Public Security Bureau
of Anhui Province five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never imagined it could get this bad,'' said Sun, who said
he was embarrassed to give his full name. ``Last year this time I
could sell 1,000 garments in an afternoon. Now I haven't sold a
single item in the last three days.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yabao Road market, also known as the Russian market, is one
small piece in what has been a thriving trade between Russia and
China, sustaining thousands of businesses small and large, private
and public in both countries.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the official value of China's trade with Russia was
$6.2 billion, including $2 billion in exports from China, mostly
textiles, food and garments, said Lu Nankuan, vice director of the
Center for Russian Studies at the Chinese Academy of Social
Science.
</P>
<P>
   But he said that statistic does not include the unofficial
export trade from places like Yabao Road: Officially, the Russians
who buy thousands of wigs and coats are not businessmen, but
tourists or dao ye (that is a derogatory term for itinerant traders
who wander from place to place selling wares).
</P>
<P>
   This unofficial trade is estimated to be worth $3 billion
annually, Lu said, adding, ``The devaluation of the ruble will
definitely affect China's exports this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the ruble's nose dive is not nearly as disastrous for
China as the fall of the Japanese yen, said Li Guobin, an economist
at the State Information Center, which is associated with China's
State Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
   China has export and import trade with Russia, so while a
falling ruble means that Russians buy fewer Chinese goods, it also
means that China can buy less expensive cement and power-station
parts, for example. ``For China, there are good and bad things
about the ruble's devaluation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the last two weeks have been a disaster for thousands of
small-business owners who have left the security of state-owned
enterprises to live or die financially by Russian trade. Business
at wholesale markets like Yabao Road is conducted in American
dollars. And, with the ruble worth a third of what it was a month
ago, Russians do not have dollars to spend.
</P>
<P>
   As Westerners walk down the market aisles, bored vendors sitting
on small wooden stools look up hopefully from Nintendo games. ``Are
you Russian?'' they ask.
</P>
<P>
   In a small store that sells Chicago Bulls hats, Zhao Xianhan now
drinks tea and plays solitaire. Zhao, who came here two years ago
from rural Hebei, shares the stall with a woman who sells
hairpieces and and wigs, but nothing much is selling now _ only an
occasional Afghan or Romanian customer wanders in.
</P>
<P>
   Zhao said that he used to make a profit of 20,000 yuan a year,
about double the average income for Beijing. But he and his wife
can no longer send money home to his parents and their child _ they
can not even afford their 4,500 yuan a month rent. ``When the
season is good we sell thousands of hats a day, but there are few
customers now.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Li Hongyang, who manages a Beijing coat-factory's store in the
market said he had sold only four coats in the last two weeks, down
from 10 a day in July and hundreds or thousands a day this time
last year.
</P>
<P>
   A number of stalls have decided to close temporarily. The
hotels, restaurants and other service businesses that cater to the
traders are hurting as well.
</P>
<P>
   In a vast hanger-like packing station, small clusters of men who
are paid to pack purchases for air shipment to Moscow sit on the
empty cement floor around a flickering black and white television.
Co-workers play cards or nap on broken cardboard boxes, which in
better times carried clothes and shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Yu Ruijun, who said he worked for a Moscow air transport
company, fiddled with the antenna of the jury-rigged set. ``We
packed four boxes today,'' he said. ``It should be more than 600.
We have nothing to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 1854EDT &QL; 
