<HEADER>
A4345 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR &LR;      09-08 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; THE PROFESSOR AND THE MADMAN &QL; 
 &UR; Simon Winchester (HarperCollins, $22)
</P>
<P>
   One autumn day in 1896, James Murray, editor of the ``Oxford
English Dictionary,'' traveled by train to the village of
Crowthorne, England, to see a man with whom he had corresponded for
nearly 20 years. W.C. Minor was one of many volunteers who had
helped Murray assemble the dictionary (he had contributed more than
10,000 neat, handwritten definitions). The two never had met _
Minor had declined to do so, without explanation. Now, in
Crowthorne, Murray found a carriage waiting, and he was taken to a
forbidding mansion at the end of a long drive. It was, he was
stunned to learn, England's harshest asylum for the criminally
insane, and W.C. Minor was a murderer who was profoundly and
irreversibly mad. His work with Murray had been his medicine for
two decades, his link with sanity. Winchester tells the story of
the two men with an arch, spare tone that emphasizes its Victorian
roots, its eccentricities and the sad life of W.C. Minor. ``One
must feel a strange gratitude,'' he writes, ``that his treatment
was never good enough to divert him from his work. The agonies that
he must have suffered in those terrible asylum nights have granted
us a benefit, for all time. He was mad, and for that, we have
reason to be glad. A truly savage irony, on which it is
discomfiting to dwell.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; NO SAFE PLACE &QL; 
 &UR; Richard North Patterson (Knopf, $25.95)
</P>
<P>
   Here's something new and different, a novel about a sexual
affair that threatens the career of a powerful politician. Kerry
Kilcannon hasn't reached the presidency yet but he's running for
it, and the woman involved is not an intern, but Lara Costello, a
network news reporter who met Kilcannon when she was working for
the ``New York Times.'' Patterson packs so much around this core
plot that it's dizzying. There's the candidate's background, which
includes a bad marriage, a mother who brutally was beaten by
Kilcannon's father, a law career during which Kilcannon was shot by
the husband of a client, and a brother, also a politician, who was
assassinated on the campaign trail. There's a cast of advisers who
meet for arduous discussions on political strategy and damage
control. There's the press corps, with its competitive sniping and
black humor. And there's an anti-abortion zealot who shot three
people at an abortion clinic and now is stalking Kilcannon. It
takes 500 pages to carry it all. The dialogue sounds authentic
despite the many roles Patterson portrays, and the sex-and-politics
angle is not as wearying as you expect it to be. This is the kind
of affair you wouldn't mind your politicians having, with love
outweighing the scandal and no dresses left behind. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; PURE DRIVEL &QL; 
 &UR; Steve Martin (Hyperion, $19.95)
</P>
<P>
   We have complained about the recent spate of books written (a
term loosely applied) by comedians, but none of them had the
audacity to refer to Marcel Proust by his initials, to rewrite a
paragraph by Milan Kundera or to mention the Booker Prize without
explaining what it is. Steve Martin thinks he's talking to  &UR; smart
people, here, and flattery will get him everywhere, or at least put
him out ahead of the competition. We must warn you that this is a
slight book (just over 100 small pages), and, therefore, pricey,
and Martin admits that the essays in it are ``little candy kisses,
after-dinner mints to the big meal of literature.'' But it's fluff
with thought behind it, by a man who uses the word ``antecedent''
and still makes you laugh. David Mamet read it and said, ``This is
a ril, ril funny book.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; LASSO THE WIND &QL; 
 &UR; Timothy Egan (Knopf, $25)
</P>
<P>
   With all due respect to Terry Tempest Williams, a wonderful
writer who has contributed an admiring blurb for the jacket, we
suggest that this book was written for people in the East. Closer
to home, you might have had your fill of writers who set out to
explore the grand question of what has happened to ``the West.''
From the start, there's swagger in Egan's tone (hiking in the Grand
Tetons, he complains that ``I had heard too many lies about the
`Real West,' flimflam and fraud retold as gilded narrative by
people whose grandparents took the land by force and have been
draining the public trough ever since to keep it locked in a
peculiar time warp of history. I needed a land without filter or
interpretation _ the West, unplugged.''). We couldn't help thinking
that he had been beaten to the punch by writers with truer hearts
and less lofty book proposals. He quotes many of them as he visits
Western states and profiles issues, people and places. Included are
Supai and Lake Havasu City, with mention of Phoenix and the cotton
farms ``outside Mesa and Glenwood.'' Egan is the Pacific Northwest
correspondent for the ``New York Times.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; TAKING CHARGE &QL; 
 &UR; Michael Beschloss (Touchstone, $16)
</P>
<P>
   New in paperback is this look at Lyndon Johnson through secret
recordings of conversations he had during his presidency. The
transcripts cover from November of 1963 to August of 1964, and
include a touching passage in which Johnson expresses anguish over
sending American soldiers to Vietnam. Beschloss, who transcribed
and edited the tapes, acknowledges the ``earthy, vulnerable,
suspicious, affectionate, devious, explosive, funny, domineering,
sometimes threatening private man who strides across the pages of
this book. That the tapes might one day offer later generations a
sustained look at the more primal Lyndon Johnson may have bothered
him. But it is safe to assume that one thing would bother him more
_ being forgotten.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Anne Stephenson can be contacted at
amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 1854EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
