<SLUG> BC-BOOK-FOREIGN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELF-ASSURED AUTHOR AVOIDS PITFALLS OF ROOKIE NOVELISTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Foreign Student 
Susan Choi (HarperFlamingo, $23) 
 
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is an anecdote that Eudora Welty once told, about when she
was young and just beginning her career as a writer and she thought
that the moon rose in the western sky. She described it that way in
one of her stories, and a critic informed her that she had
misplaced it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He offered valuable words to me about my profession,'' she
said later. ``Always be sure you get the moon in the right part of
the sky.''
</P>
<P>
   I thought of this as I read ``The Foreign Student'' by Susan
Choi, a writer who knows exactly where the moon should be, and a
good many other things besides. So many first novelists write books
full of saved-up images and earnest performance, but Choi seems to
have put self-interest aside and made a pact with the story about
how it wanted to be told. Her allegiance to it is absolute, her
prose elegant and self-assured. If this is the first step in her
writing life, there's no telling where she might go.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Foreign Student'' opens with the arrival of a young Korean
man named Chang Ahn _ in America, he will be called ``Chuck'' _ at
a college in Sewanee, Tenn. He is to be a student there, but we do
not know why or through what means. It is 1955, just after the end
of the war in Korea. We learn that things did not go well for Chuck
there, and so he exists now in a state of transience.
</P>
<P>
   He was a translator for the Americans, but had no ties to them
beyond his grasp of English. He has lost his best friend, Kim, a
Communist who fled to North Korea after the war. His relationship
with his once-aristocratic parents is now distant. Indeed, Chuck's
strongest link to his homeland is buried in the nightmares he has
each night, the terrible, violent dreams that will not go away.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this, Chuck is very appealing without ever seeming
especially admirable. Choi captures perfectly his faulty English,
which was a great skill in Korea but in America makes him seem
vulnerable and even ingratiating. His delicate courtesy is offset
by his presence in a country that is alive with anti-Communist
sentiment. Away from the familiar world of the university, people
stare openly at him. Chuck absorbs it almost dutifully. There are
no traumas here that can compare with those he knew at home.
</P>
<P>
   Two people come to play important roles in Chuck's new life. One
is Charles Addison, a charismatic professor who helps Chuck with
his English. The other is Katherine Monroe, the young woman who has
been Addison's mistress since she was 14.
</P>
<P>
   Katherine is adrift, troubled by her long estrangement from her
wealthy mother and by the emotional confusion of her relationship
with Addison. She, like Chuck, is a refugee from a troubled past,
and soon after they meet, a quiet awareness rises between them. We
spend the rest of the novel waiting out a sense of pending romance
that is no less appealing because it exists between the most
unlikely of people.
</P>
<P>
   Choi sees her characters through this story with great control
and attention to detail. She describes the arc of water that rises
from a vase hurled through the air by an angry Katherine, the
shreds of eraser that fall to the floor beneath Chuck's math
equations, the smell of an old woman's perfume as it clings to
everything ``shyly, like an apology.''
</P>
<P>
   She also has a way with dialogue, especially when Katherine and
her mother, Glee, reunite after years of silence. Their exchanges
are gritty and wary and full of venom, but they push toward
reconciliation and love. In the end, it is Glee who grants
acceptance to Katherine's new path in life, even as she had
condemned long ago her daughter's choice of Charles Addison.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a weakness in ``The Foreign Student'' it is that the
sections about Chuck's life in Korea seem flat compared with those
that take place in Sewanee and at Katherine's family home in New
Orleans (the exception is a wrenching chapter about Chuck's flight
from Seoul and his torture by Korean police _ it is one of the most
harrowing war stories you will ever read). Choi also withholds
information unnecessarily _ only in the final pages do we learn the
details of how Chuck ended up in Tennessee, and it was not worth
wondering about for so long.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe there are reasons for these things. Choi suggests that
Chuck was never as foreign as we thought him to be, that his life
in Korea did not define him. In coming to Tennessee _ to Katherine
_ he claimed his freedom. He was, in a way, coming home.
</P>
<P>
   Here is all I know about Susan Choi: She is 29. She is a
fact-checker at the ``New Yorker.'' And she is a very promising
writer who knows that the moon has its place in the sky, and that
the truth of a story lies in the strength and elegance of its
telling. &QL; 
Anne Stephenson can be reached at
amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
