<HEADLINE>
`POINT OF ORIGIN' SUCCUMBS TO WEAK PLOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
Point of Origin 
Patricia Cornwell (G.P. Putnam's Sons, $25.95) 
 
 By MONTY PHAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since her first novel, 1990's ``Postmortem,'' Patricia Cornwell
has shown just how much detective work a medical examiner can
accomplish armed with a scalpel and a microscope.
</P>
<P>
   The suspense tale won Cornwell several awards and introduced
readers to Dr. Kay Scarpetta, chief medical examiner for the
commonwealth of Virginia. The novel showed the more passive side of
detective work as Scarpetta, using microscopic clues found on the
bodies of the victims, was able to help track down the killer.
</P>
<P>
   Cornwell followed with eight more novels involving Scarpetta,
including the latest, ``Point of Origin.'' Not much has changed in
Scarpetta's world, and that's the problem. If anything, the plots
have become thinner and the characters flatter.
</P>
<P>
   And now, in ``Point of Origin,'' they're getting old, too.
Scarpetta is seemingly always tired. There are numerous references
to the thinning hair and advancing age of police Capt. Pete Marino,
Scarpetta's partner in crime-solving. Even Benton Wesley,
Scarpetta's lover and the fittest of the group, complains about how
old he has gotten.
</P>
<P>
   The story starts off with a mysterious letter that Scarpetta
receives from Carrie Grethren, a convicted serial killer imprisoned
in a hospital for the criminally insane whom Scarpetta and Wesley
helped track down in an earlier novel. To complicate matters,
Grethren had an affair with Scarpetta's niece, Lucy, while the two
were working for the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   When Grethren escapes, Wesley is called in by the FBI to assist.
He and Scarpetta, working with Lucy, now with the Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms, and Marino, who amazingly has no
other cases to work on, investigate a series of mysterious fires to
which they believe Grethren is somehow linked.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, the characters seem to have evolved, but they
haven't. Scarpetta still has too much work to do. She and Wesley
still have to keep their relationship secret because of
conflict-of-interest issues. Marino's still ornery. Lucy's still
angry.
</P>
<P>
   To her credit, Cornwell does take a risk with a central
character in this novel, which results in a side of Scarpetta
rarely seen in earlier novels. But the events that follow the plot
twist are predictable, too.
</P>
<P>
   And even the plot, which had driven the author's previous
novels, is noticeably thin. It relies too heavily on knowledge from
earlier books, as if Cornwell wanted to tie ends left loose years
ago (or it's a not-so-subtle nudge for new readers to buy the older
works). The ending is hurried, contrived and unrealistic, the clues
put together in a rush of sudden epiphanies.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, fans will continue to buy Cornwell's books
regardless. That's the benefit of a good first impression. But
perhaps Cornwell should examine her own point of origin and start
over from there. Let Scarpetta retire. After all, she isn't getting
any younger. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
