<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELECTION YEAR MAKES DIFFERENCE IN TAX TALK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush returned to Texas from
``nonpresidential'' campaign stops in other states last week to
propose modest tax cuts for the home folks, and Garry Mauro, his
Democratic re-election challenger, yelled, ``Gotcha!''
</P>
<P>
   No, not in the polls. Not quite.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro, still struggling to get his one campaign off the ground
while Bush is able to fly two at the same time, accused the
governor of committing a major political sin on taxes _ the
flip-flop.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, Mauro is correct. But, politically, the issue will
be debated.
</P>
<P>
   Bush now wants to repeal the state sales tax on nonprescription
drugs, diapers and most health aids and declare a limited,
back-to-school tax holiday on inexpensive clothing for children.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Bush asked the Legislature to raise the same sales
tax by a half cent per dollar on nonprescription drugs, diapers,
health aids and all the other hundreds of goods and services that
the tax covers.
</P>
<P>
   If lawmakers enact Bush's new tax-cut proposal, the average
Texas family will save about $35 a year, depending on how many
children a family has, how often they get sick, etc., etc.
</P>
<P>
   If legislators had enacted Bush's tax plan last year, which they
didn't, that same average family would have paid $71 a year in
higher sales taxes, according to the governor's own estimate.
</P>
<P>
   What a difference an election year can make.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness to Bush, however, the sales tax increase he proposed
last year would have been part of a tradeoff for lower school
property taxes. The higher sales taxes under that more far-reaching
plan, according to the governor's estimate at the time, would have
been more than offset by an average savings of $333 a year in
property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature rejected the proposal, because it also included
a controversial change in business taxes and many lawmakers didn't
have the stomach to raise the sales tax or any other tax in a year
when state government had a budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   So legislators gave taxpayers less than half of the property tax
relief the governor had requested _ about $140 a year _ by merely
raising the homestead exemption on school taxes. Lawmakers paid for
it by taking $1 billion of the budget surplus for this biennium and
giving it to school districts, which also had been part of Bush's
plan.
</P>
<P>
   With an even larger surplus forecast for the next budget period,
tax cut fever is more prevalent than ever among political
candidates this year.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro wants to use a large chunk of the surplus, which could
grow to as much as $6 billion, to pay for a $6,000-a-year teacher
pay raise. But he also has proposed eliminating the sales tax on
motor vehicles and paying for it by doubling the ``sin'' taxes on
alcohol and tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Most Texans don't buy new cars very often, but when they did the
several hundred dollars they would save under Mauro's proposal
would be much more noticeable than the few pennies they would save
on a bottle of pain reliever under Bush's new plan.
</P>
<P>
   You could even argue, just for the fun of it, that Mauro, the
Democratic nominee, has the Republican tax-cut plan, and Bush is
promoting a Democratic tax-cut option.
</P>
<P>
   A Republican would save a lot more tax money on a new Cadillac
or Lexus than a Democrat would on an old, beat-up Chevy. Since the
auto sales tax is 6.25 percent of the vehicle's price, the more
expensive the car, the greater the savings.
</P>
<P>
   But Mauro would argue that that old, beat-up Chevy and whatever
taxes are saved on it may be worth their weight in gold to a
working-class Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   For most Texans, meanwhile, the $35 a year they could expect to
save under Bush's limited sales tax cut would hardly scratch their
budget. Low-income Texans, however, would benefit the most because
they pay a higher proportion of their income in taxes than
middle-income and wealthy people do.
</P>
<P>
   The heavy reliance on the sales tax is one reason Texas has one
of the most regressive tax systems in the country. Bush didn't seem
concerned about that fact when he proposed an increase in the sales
tax last year, but, as noted earlier, this is an election year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite last year's property tax cut, which Bush calls the
largest (collectively) in Texas history, the governor may fear he
still needs to strengthen his tax-cut record for his anticipated
White House race.
</P>
<P>
   He is on record during the 1997 session proposing a new business
tax and a general sales tax increase, something other presidential
contenders may try to make an issue.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes, another likely contender for the GOP presidential
nomination in 2000, already has called Bush the ``tax man in
Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes also has challenged Bush and other governors to outlaw
taxes on Internet services. And guess what? Bush's new tax relief
plan also proposes a sales tax exemption for Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
