<SLUG> BC-KIDSBOOKHELP-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPINIONATED DUO SERVE UP BEST SELECTIONS FOR YOUNG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BEVERLY MEDLYN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Buying a book for a child can be an intimidating process, with
an overwhelming number to choose from, uncertainties about what is
age-appropriate, and chagrin over price tags. Even choosing a free
library book can be a daunting experience.
</P>
<P>
   Help has arrived. Valerie V. Lewis and Walter M. Mayes have
narrowed the possibilities to a mere 2,000 titles in their new
``Valerie &AMP; Walter's Best Books for Children: A Lively, Opinionated
Guide,'' published by Avon Books for $15.
</P>
<P>
   Their selections neatly are cataloged for easy reference,
according to age and reading and listening levels. An index even
groups titles according to topics and themes, such as trains,
stepfamilies, emotions, fear of the dark and woodchucks.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a section called ``tricky situations and frequently
asked questions.'' Sidebars and inspirational tips on such subjects
as choosing a book, series fiction, exceptional authors and
literary classics are interspersed.
</P>
<P>
   The one-paragraph book summaries are done in an amusing style.
When Valerie and Walter agree that a book is the best of the best,
a star is printed next to the title. When they disagree, each one
weighs in with a few comments, a la Siskel and Ebert.
</P>
<P>
   Although the selections aren't included in the guide unless
Valerie and Walter believe in their merit, every now and then they
raise an eyebrow, as in this passage about H.A. Rey's ``Curious
George'':
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not wish to be curmudgeonly, but we need to say that
much of George's appeal is lost on us as adults. Oh, we read them
as children and later to our own children, and we acknowledge the
fact that they delight. But we are at a loss to explain why they
are popular. Is it just that George embodies curiosity so well? Is
it a nostalgia for simpler times, perhaps, when a man in a big
yellow hat taking a monkey from the jungle could be looked upon
fondly and not as a poacher? Or is it that George is simply
beloved, period, and we just don't get it? Do not let us stop you
from making up your own mind, as there is certainly plenty of
George to go around.''
</P>
<P>
   After a while, you feel like you know and trust the two
knowledgeable characters who tackled this massive project (their
original list of titles topped 8,000).
</P>
<P>
   Mayes, also known as Walter the Giant Storyteller, is a
book-sales representative who talks nationwide with parents and
kids about books. Lewis, owner of Hickelbee's children's bookstore
in San Jose, is children's book correspondent for ``CBS This
Morning.'' They've worked together since 1981, and their
comfortable writing style reflects the friendship. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 1857EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0257 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4355 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-GA-TECH09-COX     09-08 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GA-TECH09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    O'Leary gets defensive after loss to BC
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The weather was cool during Georgia Tech's football
practice Monday, but coach George O'Leary was hot and sweaty after
the workout.
</P>
<P>
   Not sweaty from nervousness, which easily could have been the
case two days after watching Tech's defensive debacle in a 41-31
loss to Boston College. He was sweaty from trying to do something
about it. After a preseason of watching the defense practice from
20 yards back, with a clipboard in hand, the former defensive line
coach has rolled up his sleeves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking in the mirror,'' said O'Leary, whose defense
allowed 491 yards to the Eagles. ``I'm taking responsibility. We
need to get tougher, more aggressive at the point of attack. If the
guys out there aren't getting it done, we'll get someone out there
who will.''
</P>
<P>
   He practically participated in some of the defensive drills,
disappearing into the middle of the defensive line after one play
and reappearing with his hands on a scout-team offensive lineman to
show defensive lineman John Grantham what he wanted. The next play
Grantham, a reserve defensive lineman, put that same lineman on his
back.
</P>
<P>
   Since the surprising loss to Boston College, practice has had
``a little bit more focus, attention, a sense of urgency,''
first-year defensive coordinator Randy Edsall said. ``If there
isn't, there's something wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, (the game) was embarrassing. . . . It was a poor
performance. No sugarcoating, no nothing. Basically, I'm the guy
that's responsible. It's my job to make sure I go out and make
these kids better.''
</P>
<P>
   While the personnel changes O'Leary is trying this week aren't
exactly wholesale, they are significant. He has replaced two
seniors _ linebacker Justin Robertson and end Roderrick Roberts _
with younger players who have shown more promise. Redshirt freshman
Matt Uremovich is getting a shot at weakside linebacker and
sophomore Tony Robinson has moved in at defensive tackle. Senior
Nate Stimson has moved from tackle to end.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary will use Saturday's game against New Mexico State to
decide if these changes are right.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question we have to get a lot more aggressive and a
lot tougher with our assignments on defense,'' O'Leary said.
``That's all coachable.''
</P>
<P>
   Other factors contributed to Saturday's performance, including
inexperience. Delaunta Cameron, the only returning linebacker,
missed the first two weeks of preseason camp with a shoulder
injury. Five of the other seven players up front were playing as
full-time starters for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Tech's best defensive player _ free safety Travares
Tillman _ went down with a neck sprain in the second quarter and
missed the rest of the game. And Boston College had a strong
offense led by Scott Mutryn, a fifth-year senior quarterback, and
running back Mike Cloud, the third-leading rusher in the Big East
last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it was just a lack of experience or maybe some players
were just tired,'' Cameron said. ``But there are no excuses. We're
just going to have to make the plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Edsall, the former secondary coach of the Jacksonville Jaguars,
watched the game film four times Sunday and decided that the
defensive scheme and the calls were proper, although it appeared
that Jacket defenders were out of place on several big plays by
Boston College. Tech coaches and players seem to agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not a star-studded outfit on defense,'' Edsall said.
``For us to be a good defense, each guy has to play to his
potential and beyond. If we don't do that, you see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   This defense was supposed to be better than the one that
couldn't stop Georgia and Virginia when it had to last year and
finished last in the ACC in total defense. But on Saturday, the
defense looked worse, giving up 271 yards rushing and another 220
yards passing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things I was concerned about showed up,'' Edsall said.
``That's not to say we're throwing the towel in. We're going to be
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech's defenders still believe in themselves, senior defensive
end Jesse Tarplin said. They've just got to correct their mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that our mistakes were so big and horrible; (they
were) just simple stuff,'' Tarplin said. ``Being physical is
simple.''
</P>
<P>
   The top two tacklers for the Yellow Jackets against Boston
College were the safeties _ Jerry Caldwell with nine tackles and
Tillman with seven. Tech will have a tough time winning if that
trend continues, and both Tarplin and Cameron know it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm anxious, (and) I know other people on defense are anxious
to show Tech fans and people in the community this is a good
defense,'' Cameron said. ``People say this will be the same defense
as last year, not aggressive. We're going to go out and show people
this weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
