u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAWORKERS-HEALTH-COX     09-08 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAWORKERS-HEALTH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Questions raised about Blue Cross, Blue Shield advantage
 &HT;    By Andy Miller
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia's biggest health-care prize is up for grabs _
and debate _ as about 400,000 state employees and dependents are
moved to a managed care network next year.
</P>
<P>
   Weeks before bids are due, a group of legislators and industry
officials are questioning whether Blue Cross and Blue Shield of
Georgia, the state's largest health insurer, has a built-in
advantage to land that business.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Nadine Thomas (D-Atlanta), chair of a legislative
panel studying the bid process, recently noted Blue Cross, or a
company connected to it, have ongoing contracts to handle the
claims and other administrative functions for the Georgia Merit
System.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems Blue Cross and Blue Shield's hands are all over the
Merit System,'' Thomas said. ``I have concerns about this not being
a fair (bidding) process.''
</P>
<P>
   But Blue Cross on Tuesday countered that hospital-doctor
networks _ potential bid competitors _ have an edge in regions
where they have virtual medical monopolies. They can refuse to join
Blue Cross' network, or can price their bid below the insurer's,
said Neil Vannoy, a Blue Cross vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know a lot more about us than we know about them,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, State Merit covers about 263,000 employees, which,
along with dependents, amounts to 546,000 Georgians. Of that total,
about 138,000 are members of HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   The state is moving non-HMO employees from a traditional
insurance plan to a preferred provider organization, a form of
managed care that allows patients to choose a doctor or hospital
outside a network. But they must pay more for that choice.
</P>
<P>
   The Merit System has divided the state into nine regions. Along
with Blue Cross, other possible bidders include Georgia First,
Principal/SouthCare, and Humana, as well as local hospital-doctor
systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without question, it's the largest health-care contract
available in the state of Georgia,'' said Brent Layton of
consulting firm Layton &AMP; Associates.
</P>
<P>
   Without the change, the Merit System will deplete its financial
reserve and run up a huge deficit, a consultant's report said.
</P>
<P>
   The state health benefits plan lost about $32.4 million in
fiscal year 1998, after a $21 million loss the previous year. The
Merit System, if unchanged, is projected to lose $83.5 million in
fiscal 1999, according to consulting firm PricewaterhouseCoopers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became clear to us that something major had to be done,''
Dana Russell, Merit System commissioner, told a recent legislative
hearing. ``This is not painless,'' he said. ``But it is better than
the alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   When using network doctors and hospitals, employees will still
get 80 percent or 90 percent of the charges paid for them, after
meeting a deductible. But for out-of-network care, those
percentages would drop to 60 percent or 70 percent. Premiums and
deductibles may also rise, Russell said, citing the projected
losses.
</P>
<P>
   Final bids for the nine regions are due in October, with the
selections done in December. Startup is July 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Russell, too, has insisted that Blue Cross doesn't hold a
competitive advantage.
</P>
<P>
   But Thomas and others pointed to Blue Cross' existing contracts
with State Merit as a potential conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Medical necessity decisions for the state plan are made by a
subsidiary of WellPoint Health Networks. WellPoint, which also does
consulting work on the Merit System's drug formulary, plans to
acquire Blue Cross in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   And Blue Cross also holds a multiyear contract to handle claims
administration for State Merit, providing customer service as well.
That contract, which won't expire till 2001, is worth $29 million
annually to Blue Cross.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of doctor and hospital groups also have raised
questions on confidentiality of future information about a PPO,
with Blue Cross, a competitor, being the claims administrator.
</P>
<P>
   The State Employees Union pointed out that some of the bid
evaluation concerns a PPO's computer compatibility with the
administrator, Blue Cross.
</P>
<P>
   Russell acknowledged a part of the bid application deals with
that information interface. ``Perhaps there is a slight benefit''
to Blue Cross, Russell said. But ``it's such a small percentage''
of the overall evaluation, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Vannoy said the Blue Cross information connection is a standard
in the industry. The firm has agreed not to use any information on
other PPOs gained through claims handling, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
