<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Beck makes his first cut in 18 months
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The last time Chip Beck had made a cut, on March 14,
1997, Tiger Woods was still a month away from winning the Masters.
Fuzzy Zoeller was still politically correct. Mark McGwire was still
with the Oakland A's.
</P>
<P>
   That it happened to one of golf's truly nice guys only made it
more difficult to watch. But finally, that excruciating struggle is
over for Beck.
</P>
<P>
   After 47 tournaments without making a cut _ or a paycheck _ the
former University of Georgia player qualified Friday for weekend
play at the Greater Milwaukee Open. Two days later Beck, who turns
42 Saturday, earned the most beautiful $6,300 of his career and
tied for 42nd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy, it's about time,'' Beck said. ``You never realize how
difficult something like this is until it happens to you. . . .
It's only one made cut, but when you've missed as many as I have,
it has a great impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Until Milwaukee, Beck had posted only three rounds in the 60s
since the Honda Classic in March 1997. Last week, he managed three
in four rounds, shooting 69-68-73-68 for a 72-hole total of 6-under
278. In an ironic twist, Beck tied with PGA champion Vijay Singh,
whose streak of 53 made cuts was snapped at this year's Masters.
</P>
<P>
   The ordeal had stretched so long, Beck had begun to research
other means of employment. Having extended himself financially
during his prolonged slump, Beck and his wife, Karen, who have four
children, have put their $6 million home in Lake Forest, Ill., near
Chicago, on the market. Beck also has two children from his first
marriage who live in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've actually tried to use this time, in a way, to broaden
myself,'' Beck said, ``because I feel I'm too young and I have too
many hopes and dreams for my future to just kind of die on the golf
course.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Beck had given clues to the turnaround. After
shooting an opening 69 at Milwaukee, he pledged, ``You're going to
see a new Chip Beck. I'm driving the ball better than I have in
years.'' But even the final hurdle Friday did not come without
adversity. While Beck eventually would qualify easily at 5-under,
he temporarily faltered toward the end, bogeying Brown Deer's sixth
and seventh holes, on his final nine. Righting himself, Beck split
the fairway with a drive at the eighth, then birdied the ninth,
sinking a 12-footer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was huge,'' Beck said. ``In the past, I would have let
the bogeys bother me, but this time I put it behind me.''
</P>
<P>
   Beck's voice was cracking when he pondered the pain of the past
two seasons. ``I've felt close in the last month or two, but I've
had such disappointments. I didn't know if I'd really be able to
come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
