<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLF-NOTES09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NELSON RETURNING TO SENIOR TOUR
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Larry Nelson, off the Senior PGA Tour for six weeks
because of a herniated disk in his neck, is returning for Friday's
Comfort Classic at the Brickyard Crossing Golf Club in
Indianapolis. After a scary period a few weeks ago, when the pain
returned to Nelson's right arm and shoulder to resurrect fears of
surgery, he found relief the last two weeks. On Monday, Nelson
declared his strength 85 percent to 90 percent returned. ``It's
exciting for me to go back to play,'' Nelson told The Golf Channel.
``I don't know what kind of factor I'll be in the tournament.'' One
thing hasn't changed since Nelson withdrew from the U.S. Senior
Open July 24. He's still third on the money list behind Hale Irwin
and Gil Morgan. But Irwin ($2,302,350) has more than doubled
Nelson's $1,087,753. Dominating his sport in stunning fashion,
Irwin has not finished out of the top five in his 16 tournaments,
has won six times and been runner-up five times. ``It's
phenomenal,'' Nelson said about Irwin. ``I don't care where you're
playing. He could be playing with the Atlanta Junior Golf
Association and it would be remarkable.''
</P>
<P>
   Calcavecchia will try anything
</P>
<P>
   Mark Calcavecchia, who will defend his Subaru Sarazen World Open
title in November, has passed $1 million in earnings for the second
straight year. Imagine what kind of year he could be having with a
trustworthy putter. Frustrated, he went to a cross-handed grip on
the 12th hole of his Friday round at the NEC World Series of Golf
two weeks ago and has decided to stick with it. For Calcavecchia,
though, that's a relative term. ``I've had quite a few rounds this
summer where I've used three or four grips in one round,'' he said.
Although Calc moved from 120th to 100th in the putting stats last
week, he's says, ``It's not like I'm standing over a 10-footer and
saying, 'Oh, this is in.' . . . I guarantee you, nobody ahead of me
on the money list has putted any worse than I have. Nobody else
with a million dollars is ranked in the hundreds.'' Not true.
There's three of them _ Vijay Singh (124th), Billy Mayfair (129th)
and Tiger Woods (132nd).
</P>
<P>
   Ammaccapane looking like her old self
</P>
<P>
   Her resurgence didn't come in time to make her one of captain
Judy Rankin's picks for the Solheim Cup team, but Danielle
Ammaccapane has moved to 10th on the LPGA money list ($417,507)
with her second win of the season Sunday at the Safeway
Championship in Portland, Ore. After finishing ninth, sixth and
third on the money list in 1990-92, Ammaccapane has not cracked the
top 25 since, falling to 84th in 1996. Her father, Ralph, a
co-owner in their Phoenix sports bar, was in tears Sunday after
Danielle's win despite a closing 72. His other daughter, Dina,
finished third.
</P>
<P>
   Chip shots
</P>
<P>
   Since winning three tournaments in four weeks, including the
U.S. Women's Open, rookie Se Ri Pak has cooled off. She has tied
for 10th in her last two events and is second on the money list
($800,076), behind Annika Sorenstam ($806,188). . . . England's
Justin Rose, 18, who needs to earn 55,000 pounds for an exemption
on the European Tour in 1999, has not yet made a cut. He has two
events remaining out of his seven sponsor exemptions, but he seems
headed for qualifying school. . . . President Clinton played
Ballybunion in Ireland last week, missing some lurking headstones
that border the first tee and robbing assembled reporters of some
potential symbolism. . . . U.S. Amateur champion Hank Kuehne and
last year's champion, Georgia Tech's Matt Kuchar, head the four-man
team that will represent the U.S. at the World Amateur Team
Championship in Chile Nov. 19-22. Also named were 1998 U.S. Amateur
runnerup Tom McKnight of Galax, Va., and Joel Kribel of Pleasanton,
Calif., who lost to Kuchar in 1997. . . . Jeff Sluman's
neighborhood cleaned up at the Greater Milwaukee Open. Rick Bruder,
Sluman's Chicago neighbor, agreed to caddie for him at the last
minute. ``He probably kept me relaxed,'' Sluman said about Bruder,
who is not a golfer himself. ``I was kind of laughing inside at how
nervous he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
