<HEADER>
A4360 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTH-INFORMATION-CO     09-08 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-INFORMATION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Trio of companies help medical industry cut costs, coordinate
care, enter Information Age
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It was not until April that the Information Age dawned
in the examination rooms of Evanston (Ill.) Obstetrics and
Gynecological Associates.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, when the four doctors saw patients, questions were
asked, notes were scrawled and paper was filed. Same as it ever
was. Norman Rockwell could have painted that picture.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Dr. Ned Wagner sits at a PC before and after exams. He
types what he's learned into a database readable by each doctor at
each office. Within a year, that information will be available to
all 81 doctors in the Illinois Evanston Hospital pre-natal group.
</P>
<P>
   And now, when a patient's sample comes back from the lab, a
software program prompts Wagner to make sure the results are
normal, asks whether the patient has been told the results and
whether follow-ups are necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wealth and the power of the tool of electronic records is
shared information in the community of physicians that care for a
patient,'' Wagner said. ``The repetitive nature of what we do makes
it possible to streamline some of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Information Age is also the era of corporate medicine. Under
managed care, doctors are becoming subsidiaries, turning their
practices from mom-and-pop shops into sophisticated small
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Industry consolidation is forcing doctors to share information
outside the walls of their office with others in their health care
groups.
</P>
<P>
   A trio of Atlanta companies are helping meet the need, making
hundreds of millions of dollars supplying the health care field
with easier ways to swap those facts.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, health care groups, hospitals and doctors offices
are expected buy $17 billion worth of information technology this
year.
</P>
<P>
   HBO &AMP; Co. is the industry leader, taking in $1.2 billion last
year selling ways to reduce the paper trail in offices like
Wagner's in Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Medaphis had revenue of $573 million last year selling, among
other things, computer systems that automate billing, scheduling
and patient admitting.
</P>
<P>
   National Data Corp.'s health care division took in $358 million
in 1997 automating things such as billing records and prescription
forms. NDC started as a processor of prescriptions for the
military.
</P>
<P>
   A few years back, Americans started clamoring for lower health
care costs. The amount Americans spent for health care shot from
about 9 percent of the U.S. gross domestic product in 1980 to 13.6
percent in 1996, an increase of $450 billion, according to the
Employee Benefit Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Mergers further increased the need for technology, putting more
pressure on those running the new companies, said Steve Ely,
Medaphis' vice president of marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone who has been then CEO of a $200 million company
suddenly becomes, through acquisition, the head of a $1.5 billion
company,'' Ely said. ``There's more information to deal with. They
start looking at how they can improve their information technology
infrastructure to get a better handle on their business systems.''
</P>
<P>
   Managed care also has been a factor, forcing doctors to be
concerned about insurance coverage and what it does or does not pay
for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doctors can't make arbitrary choices anymore,'' Ely said.
``Automating some of the coverage issues increases their efficiency
and increase the time they can focus on their patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Medaphis' revenues have hovered in the $500 million to $600
million range for the last three years. Its stock traded at $50 as
recently as April 1996, but has sat below $12 the last 18 months.
Problems with one of the technology companies Medaphis acquired in
1994 led to lower-than-expected earnings, which dropped share
prices 60 percent in August of 1996 and 38 percent in October of
that year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are slowly emerging from a turnaround, and the new
management team is what people are betting on going forward,'' said
Steve Fitzgibbons, an analyst with Hambrecht &AMP; Quist.
</P>
<P>
   HBO &AMP;Co. became the industry leader, in part, by buying its
competition: 17 companies since 1993, plus two announced this
summer that await stockholder approval.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgibbons said HBO &AMP; Co. has no real weak spot. Its stock has
appreciated almost 1,400 percent since 1997. Its management is
respected. Integrating software from the newly acquired companies
is one of its few challenges, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan James, vice president of marketing for HBO &AMP; Co., said
the company spends between $50 million and $60 million a year
integrating software.
</P>
<P>
   NDC President Robert Yellowlees said the growth information
technology in health care is still a relatively untapped market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the largest segment of the economy with a relatively low
level of automation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For doctors' offices, systems start at $100,000 and can run as
high as $750,000, depending on size of the group and power of the
hardware. Systems for hospitals start at $500,000, HBO &AMP; Co.'s
James said.
</P>
<P>
   James said the key is to make the computer systems easy to use
and powerful. ``Doctors see 25 to 40 patients a day,'' he said.
``Anything that slows them down they will reject.''
</P>
<P>
   James said the health care industry is moving toward systemwide
computer systems _ admitting to scheduling to CAT scans to home
health care visits to billing, all from one source.
</P>
<P>
   When it came to learning new technology, Evanston's Wagner had
an edge. He designed a software program his hospital group has used
for years to manage the treatment of patients with abnormal pap
smears. The rest of his office was less receptive, more like
doctors in general, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The toughest hurdle for doctors is that it's a change in
behavior,'' Wagner said. ``Using paper and charts to accumulate
data is a time-honored and well-honed tool. Everyone has a pen in
their pocket, not everyone has a terminal at their fingertips. The
low-hanging fruit is to show them how it makes the tedious
easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
