<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITE-PATENT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bring on the era of robot etiquette
 &HT;    By Gene Tharpe
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Excuse me. After you.'' Robot welders know nothing about
speaking or manners, of course, but there are times when they need
to be ``nice.'' And that's what Patent No. 5798627 does.
</P>
<P>
   Recently issued to Malcom Gilliland of Marietta and Kenneth
Gilliland of Atlanta, the patent protects a method for preventing
collisions of two or more robot welders operating close together.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to preventing wrecks on the robot highway, the
patent also covers technology that protects objects being welded
from overheating and distortion.
</P>
<P>
   The robot welders are programmed to perform certain tasks and to
stop at specified points in the job. Then, via electronic
communication with a central controller, they are directed to their
next tasks.
</P>
<P>
   The controller might direct one robot to pause so that a second
robot can pass by without collision, or perform a specified welding
operation that is best done when the first robot is not working.
Several robots can be directed by the controller.
</P>
<P>
   Once the pause or operation is completed, the robots resume
their programmed tasks when the controller determines they are in
the correct positions.
</P>
<P>
   Welding can cause excessive heating of the welded object if two
or more operations are performed closely together in space or time.
The heat can cause distortion of the object, a problem prevented by
Patent No. 5798627.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Gilliland said the controlled robots were developed for
welding metal panels of Navy ships, but they could be adapted to
other welding jobs, such as auto manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   One day when you apply for a loan, approval or disapproval might
be ``automatic,'' thanks to a new patent that protects a data
method for the ``automatic determination of the approval status of
a potential borrower of a loan.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Patent No. 5797133 was issued Aug. 18 and assigned to
Strategic Solutions Group Inc. of Atlanta, which is now known as
Bisys Creative Solutions Inc., according to a Bisys spokesman, who
also said the firm did not grant interviews about its patents or
technology.
</P>
<P>
   According to the U.S. Patent Office, however, the patent
involves an automated telephone and processing system used by a
data firm or lender to take loan-application calls.
</P>
<P>
   Recorded messages give instructions and ask questions, which
callers answer by pressing buttons on their phone. The data thus
gathered is translated into numerical values and stored in a data
processor and, along with credit bureau information and criteria
provided by the lender, is used to automatically determine ``the
approval status and credit limit of the potential borrower.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
