<HEADER>
A4362 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORISSETTE-ALBUM-$ADV     09-08 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORISSETTE-ALBUM-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALANIS MORISSETTE: A JAGGED VOICE COMES BACK A STAR  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 13) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The aftershocks from Alanis Morissette's ``Jagged Little Pill''
haven't subsided since the album was released in 1995. In one
pop-culture masterstroke, the album introduced a mainstream
audience to what punks, post-punks, riot grrrls and alternative
rockers had been shouting for more than a decade: that women were
angry, intelligent, carnal, sick of being victims and ready to
speak for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Morissette wasn't afraid to let her voice break or shriek;
her tunes were clear-cut while the arrangements had a raw,
distorted edge, and her words whiplashed from avenging
righteousness to self-help.
</P>
<P>
   As the album swept the Grammy Awards and went on to sell 16
million copies in the United States and an estimated 28 million
worldwide, it ushered in imitators from Tracy Bonham to Meredith
Brooks to Natalie Imbruglia.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Morissette's new album is due for release on Nov. 3, and
advance information is scarce; she has not even revealed the
album's title. But she has held on to the combination that worked
on ``Jagged Little Pill.''
</P>
<P>
   As on that album, she is writing songs with Glen Ballard, and
she is producing them with him. The album's reception will test
whether Morissette, now a star, can still connect with the longings
and frustrations of a mass audience, particularly the young women
who came to her concerts and sang along on every verse of every
song.
</P>
<P>
   The album will also test the music business itself, which in its
zeal for quick hits and niche marketing has virtually lost the
ability to build loyal audiences or follow through on blockbusters.
</P>
<P>
   The 1990s have been an era of one-hit wonders, as the music
business has promoted songs rather than careers. Yet Ms. Morissette
galvanized rock in the mid-1990s, arousing intense devotion and the
kind of equally intense antipathy that shows she struck a nerve.
</P>
<P>
   No one expects Ms. Morissette's new album to out-sell ``Jagged
Little Pill''; such worldbeating albums are exceedingly rare
conjunctions of individual talent and the Zeitgeist. But if anyone
can hold on to a mass audience that has shown a rapidly diminishing
attention span, Ms. Morissette should be the one.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Morissette is by no means the only forthright woman who will
be releasing an album in the next few months. From folk-rock to
hard rock to hip-hop to pop, many of the fall's major releases are
by women.
</P>
<P>
   Among them are Sheryl Crow, adding a new Celtic tinge to her
California folk-pop on ``The Globe Sessions''; Joni Mitchell, who
denounces the music business on ``Taming the Tiger,'' and P.J.
Harvey, whose blues-haunted songs are laced with eerie electronica
on ``Is This Desire?'' Jewel, on a new album this fall, will show
whether she has moved beyond platitudes, while the rapper and
empire-builder Missy Elliott has been working on a new album.
</P>
<P>
   The unclassifiable Bjork, who has been known to deploy anything
from dance rhythms to orchestral strings, may also release an album
before the end of 1998; Bette Midler's ``Bathhouse Betty'' is due
this week, perhaps bringing back some of the vulgar energy that
disappeared with her sappy 1990s hits. Hole, Courtney Love's band,
is likely to tour in conjunction with the album it released earlier
this month. Acknowledging the inevitable, Rolling Stone magazine
will release an anthology of women in rock.
</P>
<P>
   While women make artistic strides, men will be making a racket
this season, serving the eternal teen-age need for sonic mayhem and
taboo-tweaking. Marilyn Manson's latest provocation, ``Mechanical
Animals,'' is due this week, no doubt to howls of protest from some
faction he has taken pains to offend. Music fans demonstrated
through buying patterns that hard-rock's fondness for blunt impact,
its disdain for propriety and its indifference to melody linked it
to hip-hop; now bands have caught up, and a metal-rap bandwagon is
well under way.
</P>
<P>
   Rage Against the Machine, the metal-rap band whose music
harnesses free-floating teen aggression for what it hopes are
political motives, is due to release an album in November.
</P>
<P>
   Korn, another metal-rap band, whose songs agonize over the
wrongs heaped on misfits and the powerless, released ``Follow the
Leader'' in August; during the fall, it is to headline what it
calls the ``Family Values Tour,'' a caravan of loud rockers
including Monster Magnet and Fear Factory. While fans find
catharsis, adults are expected to cower.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
