<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOOD-SCHOOLS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOLS MARK A SOMBER REOPENING IN FLOOD-RAVAGED TEXAS TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEL RIO, Texas _ The drawings, in crayon and pencil, show
fantastic scenes of raging blue oceans, insect-like helicopters,
and humanoid figures in various states of peril.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grandma Concha died. The water took away her home,'' was the
creation of one kindergarten student at Travis Elementary.
</P>
<P>
   Each drawing included the child's narration as taken down by the
classroom teacher. Some dealt with less tragic themes.
</P>
<P>
   ``My toys were all covered up with water,'' read one. Another
said simply, ``A wire burned me.''
</P>
<P>
   After a two-week unscheduled vacation prompted by the floods
from Tropical Storm Charley on Aug. 23, about 10,000 Del Rio
children went back to school Tuesday. The deluge devastated parts
of this border city of 31,000, killing nine people and leaving
hundreds homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Other than having to drink bottled water, most children had not
been directly affected by the flooding, which ravaged a
lower-income neighborhood called San Felipe.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of students from the flood area, however, are now
living in motels, shelters or with relatives.
</P>
<P>
   At midday Tuesday, the district's top administrator reported no
significant problems at any of the 15 school campuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really going along quite smoothly. I've had people
standing by to resolve any situations at the campuses, and they
really haven't gotten any calls,'' Superintendent JoAnne Ackermann
said.
</P>
<P>
   For students in the San Felipe area, the flood was very personal
and very costly.
</P>
<P>
   They needed only look at the debris of their old neighborhood on
the way to school Tuesday to be reminded.
</P>
<P>
   Now, heavy equipment operators, Texas Army National Guardsmen
and state prison inmates on work details have replaced familiar
friends and neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   At Travis Elementary, which serves about 400 kindergarten
students, about 20 were absent Tuesday, a bit higher than normal.
</P>
<P>
   The school, like the neighborhood just to the south, had been
flooded when the San Felipe Creek left its banks after more than a
foot of rain fell.
</P>
<P>
   And on the first day back at school, the curriculum was modified
a bit to allow everyone to examine the disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all the classes, we're allowing the kids to express
themselves,'' Principal Linda Guanajuato said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And all the cafeteria walls will be covered with their
illustrations. It's one way for them to tell what they saw and
felt,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In each class, teachers also gave lessons from the, ``After the
Flood Coloring Book,'' which was distributed by the Red Cross after
the deluge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about the weather and how it affects us every day
and how some of their houses got flooded,'' said Veronica Guerrero,
a teacher whose class had almost perfect attendance Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had all but one today, and I called the mom,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said he was too traumatized to come back. They were
rescued in the fire truck, and he's just not ready,'' Guerrero
said.
</P>
<P>
   The nearby Lamar Elementary escaped flooding, but a great many
of its 430 students did not.
</P>
<P>
   Three staff members also lost their homes, said Principal Maria
Ramirez, who grew up nearby and whose aging parents had to be
carried to safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``About a third of our students were affected, and we have quite
a few that lost everything,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez said that during the two-week flood break, teachers and
administrators tracked down and contacted each family to offer
comfort and assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message was we had heard about what happened and we're
here to help you in any way that we can. The children living at the
Civic Center were so excited to see someone from school,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the water fountains were all taped shut because the
water remains undrinkable, balloons and posters with cheerful
messages brightened the Lamar campus.
</P>
<P>
   One poster read, ``Welcome, Survivors.'' Another: ``We missed
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Marian Casillas, the counselor at Lamar, said the effects of the
disaster for some children may last throughout the school year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt the need right away to attend to the children crying in
the classrooms,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Several other counselors have been assigned to the campus, and a
storage room has been cleaned out and converted to a counseling
room.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're meeting right now with mental health professionals ...
to deal with the long-range effects,'' Casillas said. ``We're
talking about parents' meetings, classroom presentations, talking
to students in groups and individual counseling.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
