<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEFTRING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXOTIC RANCH HID THEFT RING, OFFICIALS SAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL HANNA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOLAR, Texas _ From behind the closed gate of the Lawhon Exotic
Ranch, officials say, the tentacles of a theft ring reached out to
five states, to Costa Rica, and even to a deceased witness in the
Whitewater investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Now there are only metal barns, some emus and the occasional
donkey on a well-kept patch of land just outside Tolar. But this
year authorities discovered a huge collection of stolen vehicles _
pickups, front-end loaders and earth-moving machines _ on the
property. The Department of Public Safety says it was the most
expensive collection of stolen vehicles it has uncovered.
</P>
<P>
   Since January, when the ranch's owner, Charles W. Lawhon, 48,
was accused of stealing a Johnson County earthmover, authorities
have found more than 120 stolen vehicles valued at more than $3
million. They were scattered across Arkansas, Missouri, Oklahoma,
Minnesota and North Dakota, and the DPS says that some vehicles may
even have been shipped to Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
   Inside Lawhon's barn, investigators found such gee-whiz touches
as movable walls and vehicles hidden behind hay bales.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say they believe that the ring had drivers who moved
vehicles and heavy equipment between Texas and the other five
states.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators say they have learned that the theft ring was
able to pluck brand-new pickups from dealerships and heavy pieces
of machinery from businesses without being detected. Some vehicles
found on Lawhon's ranch were stolen as long ago as 1988.
</P>
<P>
   The ring might still be thriving if Johnson County Commissioner
R.C. McFall had not stumbled upon Lawhon apparently trying to steal
a county-owned 38,000-pound back-end loader that had been parked
along the road, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   McFall said he is still dumbfounded by Lawhon's aplomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``He acted like he was a cool cucumber,'' McFall said. ``After I
had caught him, he told my foreman, `I can't believe he thinks I
was trying to steal that.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The DPS says Lawhon was one of four principal members of the
ring, although investigators aren't certain that he was the
mastermind. Although he has been indicted in Hood and ]Johnson
counties, he is expected to go through the federal judicial system.
Don Carter, Lawhon's attorney, said his client is expected to plead
soon to federal charges, most likely interstate transportation of
stolen property.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has accepted full responsibility,'' Carter said. ``He
certainly wasn't the mastermind. I think that fact will bear itself
out later, after he pleads in federal court.''
</P>
<P>
   Three others, including Lawhon's 29-year-old nephew, Johnny
Lawhon Jr. of Mabelvale, Ark., are believed to be major players,
investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Lawhon, who gained notoriety after finding Whitewater
documents and a cashier's check made out to President Clinton in
the trunk of a car, died March 29 in an auto accident. Internet
reports of his death were circulated on anti-Clinton Web sites
under such headings as ``Clinton Witness Life Expectancy Hits All
Time Low.''
</P>
<P>
   But investigators now say they believe that Johnny Lawhon was
also part of the theft ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were four main characters _ one now deceased,'' said DPS
Sgt. Mike Ditto. ``All I can say is he was from Arkansas and some
vehicles came from Arkansas. So he had some kind of involvement.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other men who have not been charged have been identified as
being involved. One has ties to Costa Rica, which prompted
investigators to look for stolen goods in that Central American
nation.
</P>
<P>
   The theft ring used a variety of methods to steal vehicles. Law
enforcement agencies speculate that some vehicles were simply
driven off of dealer lots by people posing as employees. Others
vanished at night or were simply moved from businesses or
construction sites before anyone noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people knew what they were doing,'' Ditto said. ``They
knew how these dealers worked and how to move large pieces of
equipment quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Lawhon owns C&AMP;S Trailer World, a custom-trailer
business, and has also owned a front-end-loader business in south
Fort Worth. His nephew worked at a transmission shop in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   After Charles Lawhon was caught in Johnson County, McFall was
concerned that Lawhon would smooth-talk his way out of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then you saw his spread and it was unreal,'' McFall said.
``He had those movable walls and that James Bond loft, where the
ramp comes down. You could not believe that stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   One matter that authorities say is puzzling is why Lawhon kept
some of the property so long.
</P>
<P>
   ``His statement was he was going to have a big sale one day,''
DPS Sgt. Jimmy Towe said. ``We don't know if he really was, but
that's what he said.''
</P>
<P>
   Hood County Sheriff Allen Hardin, who stowed much of the stolen
property at the Sheriff's Department until the owners could be
found, said Lawhon's real motive may have been the thrill of
stealing _ and then holding the property.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
