</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRAIGHT FROM CENTRAL CASTING: MARK MCGWIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ He's Central Casting's first and only choice to be
the Babe Ruth of our time.
</P>
<P>
   This home run stuff isn't exactly new to Mark McGwire. He hit a
home run his first time up as a Claremont, Calif., Little Leaguer
and he has been hitting them at a regular rate ever since. And for
the past four years, he has been hitting home runs at a greater
pace than any other man in history.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire will soon hold the record for most home runs in a major
league baseball season by himself. And why not? He entered Tuesday
night's game with the Cubs as the record-holder for most home runs
in two (120), three (172), and four (210) consecutive seasons _ and
he was tied with Roger Maris for one-year honors with 61.
</P>
<P>
   Hitting home runs is his craft, and it involves far more than
just sheer strength. The McGwire mind and the McGwire body are in
perfect synchronization, and they have been for a lot longer than
the past six months. McGwire has been building toward this moment
for at least six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk about it to our players all the time,'' said Cardinals
manager Tony La Russa, who was McGwire's first big league manager
when both were employed by the Oakland A's. ``He had the infamous
'91 (.201, with 22 home runs), and then the comeback in '92 (42
homers, 104 RBIs). But when he came to spring training in '93, you
could see he had improved his body and his conditioning. From the
first time he took BP that year, you could see he was quicker and
stronger. You ask any coach who was with our club that year. We
were saying, `Holy smokes! He's just gotten better and better.'''
</P>
<P>
   There was only one problem. While the top 98 percent of him was
just fine, the bottom 2 percent was not. After getting off to a
torrid start in '93 (15 extra-base hits and 24 runs batted in
during his first 25 games), he was sidelined with a heel injury
that would eventually require surgery. He had nine home runs in his
first 82 at-bats but he made only two pinch-hitting appearances
after May 14.
</P>
<P>
   He had problems with both his left heel and his back in 1994,
the result being that in two seasons, he was restricted to 74 games
and 219 at-bats. He spent more time on the disabled list in 1995,
but he very quietly became one of only seven major league players
to hit 30 homers in fewer than 400 at-bats. In fact, he narrowly
missed joining Hank Aaron (40/392 in 1973) as the only players to
hit 40 in fewer than 400 at-bats, finishing with a whopping 39 in
just 317.
</P>
<P>
   So when he was able to play 130 games in 1996, should anyone
have been surprised when he smashed 52 home runs? Or 58 in 156
games last year? Or whatever it is he will wind up with this
season? He is a swatmeister supreme; that's all there is to it.
</P>
<P>
   The more anyone looks at what McGwire is doing, the more
awe-inspiring it is. Start with the fact that he plays half his
games in Busch Stadium, which has always been a distinctly
pitcher-friendly park. The Cardinals felt so defeated by the
dimensions and ball-carrying capabilities of the stadium during the
first 25 years or so of the park's existence (it opened in 1966)
that St. Louis teams were always built on pitching and defense, and
not just because of the football-inspired artifical turf that
wasn't removed until 1996. With the exception of Jack Clark, a St.
Louis cleanup batter might hit 15 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, La Russa was managing the A's. He had been a
lifelong American Leaguer, but as a mainstream baseball guy, he was
well aware of the reputation enjoyed by Busch Stadium. Now suppose
someone had suggested to him back then that in the following
decade, Roger Maris's record would be eclipsed by a man playing for
the St. Louis Cardinals. What would he have thought?
</P>
<P>
   ``I had watched enough TV games there to see the ball come off
the bat and say, `Wow, they always seem to die at the warning
track,''' said La Russa. ``So my answer is, you can never tell
about baseball, but I would have said that it's possible but the
odds are way down there.''
</P>
<P>
   Now La Russa is being asked if this assault on the record is a
unique happening or perhaps the first of many years in which the
34-year-old McGwire will threaten to raise the bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be,'' he said. ``I have great respect for amazing
talent, and if I were to say to you I'd be surprised if he were to
do it again, that would mean I had underestimated his amazing
talent.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's not merely the talent that impresses La Russa. ``Mark
has superhuman powers of concentration,'' maintained the skipper.
``He has been locked in all year long. That's his greatest
strength, his strength of mind, not his strength of body.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long, long season,'' La Russa continued. ``This is
the sixth month of the season. He has had pressure on him to
perform since the first batting practice in Jupiter (Fla.). He had
a great spring training. He hit a grand slam on Opening Day and he
had a great April. He had a great May, a great June, a great July,
and a great August. There have been no hiccups. Of his first 61
home runs, I'd say at least 40 of them have been meaningful in some
way. I believe this is one of the great clutch performances of all
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Where will it end? Sixty-two will come and go. Once he owns the
record, he is likely to transcend relaxation and head directly to
serenity, without passing Go or collecting $200. Did someone say
70?
</P>
<P>
   We are witnessing the greatest regular-season achievement in the
history of American sport. ``There are times in life to
celebrate,'' said an ebullient Bud Selig, a commissioner who
happens to love the game as few do. ``This is a time to
celebrate.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
