<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YELTSIN'S SILENCE ON PRIME MINISTER HAS MOSCOW BUZZING 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: RUSSIA-MIDDLECLASS, CHINA-RUSSIA-MARKET.) 
(nk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The big news in Russia on Tuesday was what did not
happen.
</P>
<P>
   After the Communist-led parliament, in a stormy debate on
Monday, again rejected President Boris Yeltsin's choice for prime
minister, he did not rush to renominate Viktor Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Yeltsin was holed up with his advisers at his residence
just outside Moscow, pondering his hand. The silence out of
Yeltsin's headquarters underscored his dilemma and nourished
speculation that he was considering other candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is now the president's turn to have his say,'' said Gennady
Zyuganov, the Communist leader.
</P>
<P>
   None of Yeltsin's choices are good. Yeltsin could press ahead
with Chernomyrdin's nomination and dare the Communist-led
parliament to vote down his choice for a third time, a move that
would force the dissolution of the legislature.
</P>
<P>
   That would enable Yeltsin to stand firm against the Communists,
but it would turn the political battles over the past two weeks
into an all-out war. The Communists warned the president Tuesday
against disbanding the parliament and trying to rule by decree,
invoking the specter of huge social unrest.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin could settle on a compromise candidate. That would spare
the nation a prolonged political squabble as the Russian economy is
reeling. That, however, could also mean ceding influence and
prestige to the Communists and perhaps backing away from market
reforms.
</P>
<P>
   As the president weighed his options, the potential replacements
for Chernomyrdin were piously hiding their ambition under a cloak
of humility and statesmanship.
</P>
<P>
   Yegor Stroyev, the 61-year-old leader of the upper house of
parliament, has often been mentioned as a compromise choice. A
Yeltsin ally, he also serves as the head of the administration in
Oryol, an agricultural area south of Moscow that tends to be
pro-Communist and was the birthplace of Zyuganov.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Stroyev urged Yeltsin to think long and hard before
re-entering the political fray, but insisted he had no interest in
being prime minister. He endorsed Yevgeny Primakov, the hard-line
foreign minister whose candidacy has also been promoted by Gregory
Yavlinsky, the leader of the liberal Yabloko Party.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov, however, was not to be outdone in disclaiming any
interest in higher office. Tuesday afternoon he issued a statement
stressing how happy he was in his current job and asserting that he
had not encouraged Yavlinsky to propose him as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot consent to this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The canny foreign minister, however, seemed to leave the door
open a crack. ``It is my consistent belief,'' he said, ``that a way
must be found out of the current political crisis within the
shortest possible time by means of consensus.''
</P>
<P>
   That left the mayor of Moscow, Yuri Luzhkov, who has been waging
an entirely unsubtle campaign to position himself as a likely
successor to Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   Luzhkov raised eyebrows the other day by criticizing
Chernomyrdin. But Tuesday he insisted that he had not talked to
Yeltsin about taking Chernomyrdin's place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am already head of the Moscow government,'' he said. ``Isn't
that enough?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As Moscow speculated about just who might be nominated,
Chernomyrdin sought to demonstrate that it was too soon to write
his political obituary.
</P>
<P>
   His aides Tuesday issued a blizzard of decrees and statements
intended to show that their man was on the job and in control.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin, they announced, had signed decrees on customs
duties, bank policy and personnel. He ordered a reduction of the
excise tax on oil production, a measure dearly sought by the oil
industry.
</P>
<P>
   All told, Chernomyrdin has signed 67 resolutions and 58
directives since he was appointed acting prime minister last month,
his spokesman boasted.
</P>
<P>
   As Russia's leaders jockeyed for power, however, the economic
collapse continued. The exchange rate slipped to 23 rubles to the
dollar, a far cry from the rate of 6.2 rubles in mid-August. There
was talk of postponing the last major privatization of a state oil
company for lack of buyers.
</P>
<P>
   The enclave of Kaliningrad declared a state of emergency.
Workers struck in the closed nuclear cities of Chelyabinsk and
Arzamus over wage arrears and even picketed in front of the Atomic
Energy Ministry building in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   As the politicians caught their breath before another round of
wrangling and intrigue, even they agreed Russia would pay a heavy
price for allowing the political circus to go on for much longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is impossible to calculate the budget in these
conditions,'' said Aleksandr Zhukov, the chairman of the
parliament's budget committee. ``If in the next three to four days
the situation with the prime minister is not resolved, the economic
conditions will deteriorate and it will be very difficult to get
out of the economic whirlpool.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
