<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-MOWLAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOWLAM WELCOMES BC EFFORT TO ASSIST NORTHERN IRELAND LEADERSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DORIS SUE WONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ More than two decades have elapsed since Northern
Ireland had a parliament.
</P>
<P>
   So it's not surprising that many of the 108 elected members of
the new Northern Ireland Assembly, a cornerstone of the Good Friday
peace agreement, have had no experience as legislators.
</P>
<P>
   To help prepare them for the task ahead of them, Boston
College's Irish Institute this fall and next year will hold a
series of comprehensive seminars in Boston for assembly members
from all eight Northern Ireland's political parties, as well as
civil servants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to very positive outcomes,'' said Mo
Mowlam, the British minister for Northern Ireland who was at the
college Tuesday for the launching of the political leadership
program. ``It enables people to be together and that trust and
confidence are central'' to making the peace agreement work.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Ireland was placed under direct British rule in 1972,
after its parliament collapsed amid rioting and sectarian violence
by the Irish Republican Army and Loyalist groups. Earlier this
year, voters in Northern Ireland and the Republic of Ireland
approved a historic peace accord calling for the creation of an
assembly, which for the first time would include leaders of Sinn
Fein, the political arm of the IRA.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Landry, chairman of BC's political science department, will
travel to Northern Ireland late next month to brief assembly
members on the upcoming seminars in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Landry said Tuesday that until recently, the political parties
have been accustomed to dealing with each other primarily on a
``conflictual'' and ``symbolic'' level.
</P>
<P>
   The seminars, Landry said, will help assembly members make the
transition to ``nuts and bolts'' legislative governance.
</P>
<P>
   This fall's programs will include meetings with Massachusetts
legislators and city councilors and the use of projects such as the
Deer Island sewage treatment plant as case studies in effective
government.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, seminars will focus primarily on specific topics such
as education and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   The program at BC, initiated by Mowlam, is being funded by BC
and the United States Information Agency.
</P>
<P>
   The program comes as an IRA splinter group, which has claimed
responsibility for the Aug. 15 car bombing in Omagh that killed 29
people and wounded more than 330, called for a complete cease fire.
</P>
<P>
   Mowlam Tuesday said she was suspicious of the cease fire call by
the the Real IRA.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad it had to happen after Omagh rather than before,''
said Mowlam. ``We will need alot more evidence than what has been
said in the last 24 hours'' to believe the Real IRA is sincere.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the carnage they have brought, Mowlam asserted that
``evil'' splinter groups such as the Real IRA would fail in their
attempts to sabotage the peace agreement because the people of
Northern Ireland want the accord to work.
</P>
<P>
   During her three-day stay in Boston, Mowlam was also laying the
groundwork for a 11-city tour in the United States next month to
woo investors for Northern Ireland. Jobs, she said, would help
cement the peace process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 1923EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0276 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4392 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-ASIAN-ANTIQUES-     09-08 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-ASIAN-ANTIQUES-ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASTING AN EYE ON ARTFUL BOOKS AND ASIAN ART  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 13) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn.)  (af) 
 By RITA REIF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget that books are endangered by the computer and that Asian
art is collected mostly by Asians. Both are on the minds of the
nation's curators, who have assembled some of the strongest and
most diverse selections of such works ever shown in this country.
And both have the power to inspire responses ranging from simmering
excitement to deep serenity.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the pleasures of browsing through the pages of
century-old maps of America in the atlases that will go on view in
October at the New York Public Library, or perusing the zany
comic-strip images and revealing portraits in the late 20th-century
books that will be shown in November at the Museum of Contemporary
Art in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   And a rare opportunity awaits the bibliophile in each of us when
one of the world's great medieval manuscripts, the lavishly
illustrated ``Housebook,'' goes on view at the National Gallery of
Art in Washington in November. The book was recently unbound, and a
selection of its finest images, 35 sparsely colored pen and ink
drawings ranging from the size of a postcard to that of a miniature
poster, will be the centerpiece of ``Love and War: A Manual for
Life in the Middle Ages.'' (The pages, being shown for the first
time in America, will move in May to the Frick Collection in New
York.)
</P>
<P>
   The 15th-century ``Housebook,'' owned by Count Johannes of
Waldburg-Wolfegg in Germany, presents a starkly different view of
medieval life than the more familiar romanticized reinventions of
the period seen in the Victorian paintings of Edward Burne-Jones.
</P>
<P>
   A curious blend of a cookbook and a how-to manual, ``Housebook''
is a veritable encyclopedia of secular life that presents images of
offbeat machines like the first pedal-operated spinning wheel and,
for astrology buffs, personifications of the planets. But most of
the images are of people.
</P>
<P>
   The drawings in ``Housebook'' are refreshingly candid and
occasionally funny, depicting all strata of society. They show men
fishing, mining, jousting, as soldiers and acrobats.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most engaging images are those of elegantly dressed
aristocrats dancing, playing cards, flirting and bathing,
juxtaposed with scenes of peasants jitterbugging in the Morris
dance and making love in the bushes.
</P>
<P>
   The artist, called the Housebook painter, even injects humor
into a traditional view of the Holy Family, showing the Madonna and
Child and Joseph rolling a ball to the baby Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   The witty way in which an old story is given a new twist plays
to a contemporary sense of irony. ``The response to these drawings
is not nostalgia but delight,'' said Andrew Robison, a senior
curator at the National Gallery. ``The images make you smile. And
you will not need a magnifying glass to study them.''
</P>
<P>
   In museums and galleries, on the fashion runways of New York and
Paris, in films and in restaurants, Asian artifacts elicit somewhat
different reactions: curiosity and wonder. The more we see them,
the more we are drawn to contemporary objects that reflect ancient
crafts, especially in works from Japan like the baskets coming to
the Asia Society next spring and the computer-designed fabrics
favored by Tokyo's high-fashion houses, which will be seen at the
Museum of Modern Art in November.
</P>
<P>
   But what most of us yearn to see more of these days are the
masterpieces _ centuries-old works from Asian lands, the types of
bronzes, porcelains, jades, lacquerwares and furniture that once
adorned temples and palaces throughout the East.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly though, Chinese furniture, one of the most influential
areas of Asian decorative arts, has been underrepresented in
American and European museums.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Minneapolis Institute of Arts is trying to correct that
oversight in the most ambitious exhibition of Ming and Ching
furniture ever held in this country. The show is installed in the
museum's new Asian art complex of 22 galleries, which will have its
grand opening on Sept. 27.
</P>
<P>
   The stars of the show are two glorious architectural treasures:
a soaring 17th-century reception hall from a Ming mansion and a
lattice-framed 18th-century scholar's study with an adjoining rock
garden. Both were brought from China _ eaves and all _ and
painstakingly reassembled in two galleries in the new complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``You walk into the Ming room and your blood pressure drops,''
said Robert D. Jacobsen, the museum's Asian-art curator. ``It's a
calming, centering experience to be in there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 1926EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
