<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4397 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TANZANIA-STITH-BOS &LR;      09-08 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TANZANIA-STITH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON MINISTER TAKES OATH AS AMBASSADOR TO TANZANIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w, i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Several Massachusetts neighborhoods converged in a
gold-toned reception room overlooking the capital Tuesday as the
Rev. Charles R. Stith was sworn in as US ambassador to Tanzania
with pledges to increase trade and fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   The occasion was tinged by somber reminders that Monday marked
one month since the twin bombings of US embassies in Tanzania and
Kenya. At the opening of his speech, Stith read the names of the 10
embassy employees, all Tanzanians, who were killed in the Dar es
Salaam bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Not that anyone needed reminders. Outside, in a semi-circular
driveway that has long welcomed visitors to the State Department,
workers Tuesday finished installing 26 metal posts to keep out
cars. To add another layer of protection, the driveway was also
blocked by three government-owned Dodge Ram trucks, so new that the
price stickers were still on the windows.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the State Department, on once-bustling
Virginia Avenue, police waved away cars.
</P>
<P>
   Stith's determination to go to his post and supervise the
reconstruction of the embassy is a sign ``the United States will
not let terrorism scare us away from protecting out interests
overseas,'' said Susan Rice, the assistant secretary of state for
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the bombings, which killed 263 people and wounded
more than 5,000, Stith said, ``We were devastated by the loss, but
let the message go forth. ... We will never be intimidated by
terrorist thugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind him stood Edith Bartley, 25, an American whose father and
brother were killed in the Kenya explosion, and to his side was
John Lang, the top-ranking State Department official, who
coordinated the rescue effort in Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   Before the bombings, career diplomats considered Tanzania a
quiet, out-of-the way posting. The country of 29 million is a
democracy with free elections and a government that echoes
Washington's talk of free trade. Stith, though, will have the added
duties of overseeing reconstruction of the embassy and repairs on
the ambassador's residence while consulting with the FBI and other
agencies on the bombing investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In a rousing speech to nearly 400 friends _ mostly from Boston's
religious, academic and business communities _ Stith spoke about
the path from the segregated St. Louis neighborhood where he grew
up to his new assignment in East Africa as a US diplomat.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have risen from the cusp of poverty to become a
representative of this country and an adviser to its president is
an honor, and it is humbling,'' Stith said to applause in the
ornate Benjamin Franlin room atop the State Department. The
late-afternoon swearing-in ceremony had the air of a testimonial
dinner. The audience included retired Superior Court Judge Harry J.
Elam, former Boston schools superintendent Robert ``Bud'' Spillane,
Oak Bluff's Police Chief Joseph Carter, and Harvard University
professor Cornel West.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the bombings, the job in Tanzania ``is no longer a
pretty inconspicuous post,'' said Roxbury District Court Judge
Edward R. Redd. ``It's going to require extra vigilance and extra
prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Stith will be joined in Tanzania by his wife, Deborah
Prothrow-Stith, an associate dean at Harvard's School of Public
Health; their son Percy; their daughter Mildred, known as ``Mimi,''
and his mother-in-law, Mildred Prothrow, 80, who has plans to
volunteer at a school or hospital..
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing tapes to learn how to speak Swahili _ not that
I've learned anything,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Percy, 19, will take a year off from Bates College to work for
his father at the embassy. ``After the bombing, I had some friends
in college ask me, `Do still want to go there?' '' he said. ``We
definitely do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 1928EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0279 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4398 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KENYA-RECONSTRUCT-ART     09-08 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENYA-RECONSTRUCT-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOMENTS OF TERROR: SPECIAL REPORT ON THE KENYA EMBASSY BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic updating the Kenya bombing story is being sent to
NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individul purchase
by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JAMES C. McKINLEY Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya _ The American Embassy here was an easy target
for terrorists. Its perimeter was patrolled by unarmed guards
earning about $100 a month. The embassy's parking lot, shared with
a local bank, had an exit lane protected by neither guards nor
barricades.
</P>
<P>
   On August 7, attackers driving a truck packed with explosives
turned off Haile Selassie Avenue and roared up that road, flashing
past an uninstalled security barrier that the local bank was
planning to erect to protect the lot.
</P>
<P>
   The truck reached the edge of the building, where it was
confronted by several unarmed private security guards, who
scattered after the attackers threw a grenade-like device at them.
</P>
<P>
   A reconstruction of the Nairobi bombing, based on interviews
with guards and other witnesses, shows that the embassy was left
vulnerable to the most rudimentary attack.
</P>
<P>
   A decade after the State Department vowed to tighten the
security of its embassies around the world, the interviews show
that the Nairobi post had failed to achieve a basic aspect of
security: control of buildings.
</P>
<P>
   And Nairobi is not alone. An administration official in
Washington said it was common for embassies to be near private
property with security precautions left to the local owners. In
Malaysia, the embassy was next door to a gas station. After the
bombings in Africa, the official said, the U.S. government bought
the gas station and immediately emptied its tanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a typical problem for us,'' the official said. ``We
have a number of situations in which we share commercial parking
lots.''
</P>
<P>
   The House International Relations Committee plans to hold
hearings later this month on the embassy bombings, and will examine
a number of security issues, including why the exit lane was left
vulnerable to terrorist attack.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past 18 months, the U.S. ambassador to Kenya, Prudence
Bushnell, repeatedly complained to her superiors in Washington
about the lack of security at her embassy, and the committee wants
to know whether she specifically raised questions about access to
the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   An administration official said the embassy in Nairobi did not
request any money to secure the road leading out of the parking
lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously it would have made a difference,'' said one embassy
official, who like most of the U.S. officials interviewed for this
article spoke on the condition of anonymity. ``If we had had
control of that outside parking lot and more guardposts, they would
have gone somewhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Most U.S. embassies around the world employ unarmed guards from
private security companies rather than armed guards or soldiers to
handle day-to-day security outside the building. U.S. Marines
normally control access to embassy buildings and protect classified
documents, and handle security problems within the embassy itself.
But external security is often handled by private companies.
</P>
<P>
   After the explosion here on Aug. 7, U.S. officials initially
praised the guard company, United International Investigative
Services, which is based in Anaheim, Calif. The officials pointed
out that the two Kenyan guards at the rear gate of the embassy's
underground garage had refused to allow the van carrying the bomb
to enter the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the vehicle had gotten down that parking ramp, none of us
would be talking to you,'' said one high-ranking embassy official.
</P>
<P>
   But the initial praise for the guards, who all survived the
blast, did not address why the terrorists had such an easy time
driving up to the barrier at the top of the ramp leading into the
embassy garage, coming close enough to gut the embassy building and
kill three dozen people inside.
</P>
<P>
   According to several witnesses, the Mitsubishi Canter van
carrying the bomb entered the parking lot through an exit lane
leading out to Haile Selassie Avenue. There was no barrier there to
stop the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   The embassy shared the rear parking lot with the adjacent
Cooperative Bank, U.S. officials said. The bank employed guards
from Wells Fargo Co., who controlled a barrier at the entrance of
the parking lot 50 yards to the north. The entrance was on an
access road that ran parallel to the avenue.
</P>
<P>
   The bank had hired a contractor to install a cantilevered bar
barrier, like those used at railroad crossings, across the exit
lane, but the work had not yet been completed, U.S. officials said.
The useless barrier was laying on the ground the day of the attack,
several guards said. State Department officials said they had no
plan to build a security barrier controlling access to the rear of
the embassy.
</P>
<P>
   Even without a barrier, the exit ramp was supposed to be guarded
by one of the embassy's private security guards in the parking lot,
the guards said in interviews. But the guard on duty that day near
the mouth of the exit lane, Jomo Matike Boke, did nothing to stop
the van from entering, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Boke's failure was not surprising, since he was filling in for a
sick colleague and had never performed the assignment before, the
guards said.
</P>
<P>
   A few days after the bombing, William Guidice, president of
United International Investigative Services, said the truck
carrying the bomb had first tried to enter a parking lot at the
front of the building, claiming to have a delivery for the embassy.
</P>
<P>
   Guidice maintained that the guard turned the truck away from the
front lot and told the men inside to go around to the back gate to
make the delivery. The guard, Francis Emomeri, declined to be
interviewed for this article.
</P>
<P>
   But FBI investigators and embassy officials now say they doubt
that story. No witnesses have been found who saw the truck come to
the front of the embassy, law-enforcement officials said, though at
least one witness has told investigators he saw a second car
leading the van toward the embassy before the blast.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
