<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4399 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-MURDOCH-BOS &LR;      09-08 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-MURDOCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURDOCH MOVE FOR MANCHESTER UNITED UNSETTLES BRITISH FANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Given that most British people think baseball is an
unfathomable American bastardization of cricket, few here batted an
eye last year when media mogul Rupert Murdoch bought the Los
Angeles Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   But now that the Australian-born tycoon has set his sights on
Manchester United, England's most famous and financially successful
soccer team, all hell has broken loose. It is suddenly the biggest
story in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   There are few things that arouse the passions of the English
like soccer, or what they call football. But one thing that comes
close is anything that the ambitious, controversial tycoon touches.
Put together, soccer and Murdoch are a volatile mix, politically
and culturally, in England and the rest of Britain.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Murdoch's BSkyB cable network confirmed that it was
trying to buy venerable Man United, an announcement that sent the
team's stock value soaring about $190 million in a day.
</P>
<P>
   Outraged fans plan to picket at Wednesday night's game at Old
Trafford, Man United's hallowed stadium. They are convinced that
Murdoch wants to corner the television market on the team, making
its games exclusive to his cable network, which already has a
virtual monopoly on Premier League games. As Sky prepares to launch
a 200-channel digital network, landing the games of the New York
Yankees of English soccer would be an enticing lure for potential
subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch's initial offer of about $900 million for the team has
spawned interest from other corporations, including Enic, an
entertainment conglomerate which has financial backing from the US
giant Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   It is not just Man United fans who are lamenting the bidding war
that Murdoch has started. Fans of the 19 other Premier League clubs
fear that if Murdoch acquires the team, his network will show Man
United games at the exclusion of others.
</P>
<P>
   Soccer fans here take their game seriously, and consider it
beneath the purely bottom-line thinking that dominates most
professional sports in the rest of Europe and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   There is a growing fear that soccer, one of the few things that
provides common ground for all classes and races in a society often
divided by class and race, will become just another commodity to be
bought and sold by the highest bidder.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in his shop in North London, Nick Marcos, an elderly
tailor, shrugged as he bemoaned the growing commercialization of a
game he played as a child in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about money today,'' he said. ``The game has become
secondary.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the threat that Murdoch's sudden interest in Man United
poses to English football, it refocuses attention on the
relationship between Murdoch and British Prime Minister Tony Blair,
whose government must approve the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Since his May 1997 landslide election, Blair has enjoyed an
extended honeymoon with the press, especially Murdoch's holdings.
But Blair's alleged coziness with Murdoch continues to surface as a
sore point, a welcome development for political opponents who have
little else to beat him up with.
</P>
<P>
   Conscious of that, Blair's closest adviser, Peter Mandelson, the
trade and industry secretary who can approve or veto the deal,
swiftly announced that Murdoch's bid would be given intense
scrutiny to make sure it does not pose an undue threat to
consumers. Fans are not reassured by Mandelson's close friendship
with Murdoch's daughter, Elisabeth, Sky's CEO.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers say there is probably little the government can do to
stop Murdoch from buying Man United, but politically it must be
seen to be doing all it can to stop him. If the government blocks
Murdoch, it will score points with fans everywhere but risk
incurring the wrath of Murdoch's extensive media empire.
</P>
<P>
   All this bother over a soccer team leaves some people puzzled.
As London's Evening Standard observed in an editorial, ``It says
much about national priorities that there has been far more public
anguish about Mr. Rupert Murdoch's threatened bid for Manchester
United than ever there was about the creation of his dominant media
empire in Britain.''
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch controls about 40 percent of the British media, from
racy tabloids that showcase naked women to the more upmarket
broadsheet, The Times of London. If he succeeds in his latest
acquisition bid, he will own just one soccer team.
</P>
<P>
   But, for millions of people, it's the only team that matters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 1930EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0281 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4400 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KENYA-RECONSTRUCT-ART     09-08 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENYA-RECONSTRUCT-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NAIROBI, Kenya: the blast. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What is certain is that the van was headed east on Haile
Selassie Avenue when it abruptly made a hard left turn, bounced
over a curb, then slipped through the exit lane and into the
parking lot, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   It was 10:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Benson Okuku Bwaku was the guard manning the barrier leading
into the underground garage. He said he saw the 3.5-ton Mitsubishi
Canter truck with a covered cargo bay turn off the avenue and speed
toward him.
</P>
<P>
   The barrier was up, Okuku Bwaku said, because he had just
allowed a three-wheeled mail cart, driven by an embassy worker
named Francis Kile, to pass out of the embassy's garage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just feel something in my blood that the van was unusual,''
he recalled. ``I asked Kile to move his cart quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   The truck would have reached the barrier in seconds had a white
sedan not pulled out of another parking garage under the
Cooperative Bank Building across the lot from the embassy, he said.
The sedan ended up nose to nose with the van and for a minute
neither could move.
</P>
<P>
   Okuku Bwaku said he saw a man jump from the passenger side of
the van. Feeling panicked, the guard pushed the barrier down and
fastened it to the post. When he looked up, the man was next to
him, about six feet away, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The man was black-skinned with Arab features, long sideburns and
fine, straight black hair that hung down to the middle of his neck,
the guard said. He wore a plaid shirt and grey, denim cargo pants
with large pockets on the thighs. His hands were in his pockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he said was: `Open the gate.' Not loud. Not soft,'' Okuku
Bwaku recalled. ``I did not talk to him. The barrier was down. He
pulled his hands out of his pockets. In his left hand he had what
looked like a hand grenade. In his right hand he had three objects
with three strings falling from them.''
</P>
<P>
   The man hurled the grenade-like device at Okuku Bwaku's head
with his left hand, the guard said. He ducked. The grenade landed a
few yards behind him and exploded near a car in the compound.
</P>
<P>
   Okuku Bwaku ran about 25 feet toward Haile Selassie Avenue and
stopped. He said he desperately tried to radio the Marine guard at
post one, a bulletproof control room in the reception area of the
embassy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Break! Base! Terrorism! Terrorism!'' he said he shouted into
the radio. The attacker threw a second device at him. It sailed
over him and exploded in a paved plaza surrounding the embassy, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the drop barrier there was an iron fence and a pair of
heavy steel gates, through which cars had to pass to enter the
garage. As Okuku Bwaku ran toward the avenue, a second guard, Joash
Okindo, locked the steel gates with a padlock. He was critically
injured in the blast that followed.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the embassy, Cpl. Samuel Gonite was on guard in the post
one control room. Like the other six Marines at the embassy that
day, he declined through a military spokeswoman to be interviewed
for this article.
</P>
<P>
   But the spokeswoman, Maj. Mary Baldwin, said the corporal was
not aware of the fracas at the back gate until the first grenade
exploded. She said he immediately checked the monitors connected to
cameras on the roof but saw nothing unusual. He told his superiors
he looked outside to see if the noise might have been a car
accident.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Baldwin said the corporal was trying to make one of the
roof-top cameras pan around to the rear parking lot when the second
car bomb exploded. He either did not receive or did not hear Okuku
Bwaku's frantic radio transmission.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that time, his focus was not on the radio, but on getting
the embassy secure,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, Okuku Bwaku was running for his life. He ran around the
corner of the embassy, intending, he says, to sprint to the
post-one control room and alert the Marines. He had gone about 15
yards when the car bomb exploded, sending him flying to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Baldwin said Gonite recalled a 10-second delay between the
first grenade and the big explosion.
</P>
<P>
   A seismograph at the University of Nairobi Geology Department
registered a small tremor at 10:39 and 20 seconds. Eight seconds
later, it registered a shockwave from the explosion that measured
3.4 on the Richter scale.
</P>
<P>
   Though Okuku Bwaku never saw the truck move closer to the
parking lot ramp, another guard on duty nearby did.
</P>
<P>
   The guard, who asked not to be identified, said he was standing
near the outlet ramp of the parking lot, when the delivery truck
made a sharp turn off Haile Selassie and into the parking lot,
moving fast.
</P>
<P>
   He described the truck as a late model, cream-colored one with a
Dubai license plate on the back fender. He saw the truck squeeze
past the sedan and approach the barrier just after the man who had
leaped from the passenger side threw a grenade at Okuku Bwaku.
Law-enforcement officials say the driver of the truck was killed in
the explosion. It is unclear how many other terrorists were present
when the bomb went off or how many were involved in the bombing
conspiracy, they said. Some witnesses have reported seeing another
man climb out of the back of the van.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Richardson, a former military policeman who is one of
the partners in the guard company, said the guards receive about 80
hours of classroom training and 40 hours of practical training
before being put on the job. The company also gives frequent
refresher courses, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We teach them about terrorism and the things they should look
for,'' Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
   But Richardson acknowledged it was virtually impossible for
unarmed guards to stop armed men from driving a car filled with
explosives up to the rear of the embassy, especially given the lack
of physical barriers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not in that location,'' he said. ``You get very little
forewarning about what's taking place or what's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In that particular area, with unarmed security officers, it's
hard to protect something like that, or even to put a lot of fear
into anyone,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
