<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN CONSUMERS DENIED CAR LOANS, MORTGAGES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Inside the lobby at Taxquena Motors Tuesday, &UR;  &LR; four
new Volkswagens sat like sparkling jewels behind a panel of
floor-to-ceiling windows. And a half-dozen salesmen paced the
white-tiled floor waiting for anyone to come in and take a closer
look.
</P>
<P>
   But there were hardly any takers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's lots of demand for our cars,'' said one salesman who
was back at his desk trying to keep busy. ``But it's hard to get
credit these days and the interest rates are incredibly high.''
</P>
<P>
   In an early sign that the anxieties sweeping across Latin
American markets are &UR;  &LR;  affecting the lives of ordinary citizens,
volatile interest rates have forced several Mexican banks to
temporarily stop lending money to borrowers for mortgages and cars.
Many car dealers and manufacturers have also suspended most of
their financing and leasing programs.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the country's biggest banks announced on Friday that
they were halting most of their consumer credit programs because of
rapidly rising interest rates and a plummeting currency. Late last
week, the Mexican peso hit a record 10.2 to the dollar, and
short-term interbank interest rates surged to 39 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory G. Tallas, director general of First Chicago Bank
Mexico, attributed the tighter credit policies to the losses many
Mexican banks have suffered recently in mutual fund investments,
particularly in emerging markets in Asia and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   ``The losses on the market have hit the banks' capital ratios,
leaving these guys in tough shape,'' Tallas said. ``This is
affecting the amount of money they can lend to business enterprises
and the amount of credit available for the average Joe in the
street is completely dried up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The suspension of credit depends on the (stock) market,'' said
Yolanda Miranda, a Mexico City branch manager for Inverlat Bank.
``We don't know how long this could last because at this moment we
don't have a strong market. It could last months.''
</P>
<P>
   The banks' decisions affect nearly all consumer loans for buying
homes, cars, personal computers, televisions and stereos. It will
also make it harder for businesses to secure lines of credit.
</P>
<P>
   Bancomer and Banamex, two of Mexico's largest banks, said they
suspended credit as an ``act of responsibility.'' Bancomer will not
issue new credit cards during &UR;  &LR; September and those who already hold
cards will see increases in their annual interest rates of between
15 and 20 percent, said a bank official.
</P>
<P>
   Obtaining credit is generally more difficult and more expensive
in Mexico and other Latin American countries than in the United
States. Car financing programs typically require a minimum down
payment of 35 percent to 40 percent with monthly installments
stretched out over just two to three years. Bank-issued credit
cards carry annual interest rates ranging anywhere from 35 percent
to 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Most bank officials said they would loosen their credit policies
when interest rates stabilized and demand for new loans went up
again. Meanwhile, as concerns have grown over rising interest
rates, so have warnings from government officials and radio and
television announcers who tell Mexican citizens not to accumulate
too much debt.
</P>
<P>
   The move by the banks came only two days after Mexico's finance
minister, Jose Angel Gurria, joined his Latin American counterparts
last week in stressing that their economies are sound. After
meeting with officials from the International Monetary Fund in
Washington, D.C., Gurria said that recent drops in Latin American
stock markets were the result of overreaction by investors.
</P>
<P>
   But a survey released Monday by the Bank of Mexico shows that
confidence in the economy among analysts &UR;  &LR; has fallen dramatically
over the last month. Only 17 percent of the analysts surveyed by
the central bank in August had a favorable outlook for the economy,
compared with 77 percent in July.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican banks are not alone in tightening their credit policies.
The Buenos Aires newspaper Clarin reported Monday that most
Argentine banks have also suspended new construction loans because
of the country's dwindling cash supply as investors have fled that
economy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe researcher Lorena Zarate contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 1931EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0284 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4404 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TANZANIA-STITH-BOS &LR;      09-08 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TANZANIA-STITH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON MINISTER TAKES OATH AS AMBASSADOR TO TANZANIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w, i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Several Massachusetts neighborhoods converged in a
gold-toned reception room overlooking the capital Tuesday as the
Rev. Charles R. Stith was sworn in as US ambassador to Tanzania
with pledges to increase trade and fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   The occasion was tinged by somber reminders that Monday marked
one month since the twin bombings of US embassies in Tanzania and
Kenya. At the opening of his speech, Stith read the names of the 10
embassy employees, all Tanzanians, who were killed in the Dar es
Salaam bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Not that anyone needed reminders. Outside, in a semi-circular
driveway that has long welcomed visitors to the State Department,
workers Tuesday finished installing 26 metal posts to keep out
cars. To add another layer of protection, the driveway was also
blocked by three government-owned Dodge Ram trucks, so new that the
price stickers were still on the windows.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the State Department, on once-bustling
Virginia Avenue, police waved away cars.
</P>
<P>
   Stith's determination to go to his post and supervise the
reconstruction of the embassy is a sign ``the United States will
not let terrorism scare us away from protecting out interests
overseas,'' said Susan Rice, the assistant secretary of state for
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the bombings, which killed 263 people and wounded
more than 5,000, Stith said, ``We were devastated by the loss, but
let the message go forth. ... We will never be intimidated by
terrorist thugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind him stood Edith Bartley, 25, an American whose father and
brother were killed in the Kenya explosion, and to his side was
John Lang, the top-ranking State Department official, who
coordinated the rescue effort in Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   Before the bombings, career diplomats considered Tanzania a
quiet, out-of-the way posting. The country of 29 million is a
democracy with free elections and a government that echoes
Washington's talk of free trade. Stith, though, will have the added
duties of overseeing reconstruction of the embassy and repairs on
the ambassador's residence while consulting with the FBI and other
agencies on the bombing investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In a rousing speech to nearly 400 friends _ mostly from Boston's
religious, academic and business communities _ Stith spoke about
the path from the segregated St. Louis neighborhood where he grew
up to his new assignment in East Africa as a US diplomat.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have risen from the cusp of poverty to become a
representative of this country and an adviser to its president is
an honor, and it is humbling,'' Stith said to applause in the
ornate Benjamin Franlin room atop the State Department. The
late-afternoon swearing-in ceremony had the air of a testimonial
dinner. The audience included retired Superior Court Judge Harry J.
Elam, former Boston schools superintendent Robert ``Bud'' Spillane,
Oak Bluff's Police Chief Joseph Carter, and Harvard University
professor Cornel West.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the bombings, the job in Tanzania ``is no longer a
pretty inconspicuous post,'' said Roxbury District Court Judge
Edward R. Redd. ``It's going to require extra vigilance and extra
prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Stith will be joined in Tanzania by his wife, Deborah
Prothrow-Stith, an associate dean at Harvard's School of Public
Health; their son Percy; their daughter Mildred, known as ``Mimi,''
and his mother-in-law, Mildred Prothrow, 80, who has plans to
volunteer at a school or hospital..
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing tapes to learn how to speak Swahili _ not that
I've learned anything,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Percy, 19, will take a year off from Bates College to work for
his father at the embassy. ``After the bombing, I had some friends
in college ask me, `Do still want to go there?' '' he said. ``We
definitely do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
