<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-GOVERNMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMID FISCAL CRISIS, NO INTEREST IN PRIME MINISTER'S JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Wanted: Russian prime minister nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Job description: Save country from certain collapse. Applicant
must be aging former Soviet Communist Party member. Relevant work
experience a plus.
</P>
<P>
   With its economy unravelling by the day, its currency falling
fast, and its outlying regions growing increasingly restive over
the power vacuum in Moscow, Russia badly needs a new government.
</P>
<P>
   But no one seems to want the job of putting one together except
Viktor S. Chernomyrdin, the acting prime minister whose nomination
by President Boris N. Yeltsin was emphatically rejected a second
time by lawmakers on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, three men whom the Communist-dominated State Duma, the
lower house of parliament, would rather see as premier _ acting
Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov, Moscow Mayor Yury Luzhkov, and
Yegor Stroyev, speaker of the upper house of parliament _ all said
thanks, but no thanks.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to see why. As the ruble dropped another 10 percent
to 20.82 to the dollar amid soaring prices, panic-buying, and
growing shortages in stores, several Russian regions announced they
would try to tackle the crisis on their own.
</P>
<P>
   In Kaliningrad, a tiny Russian enclave tucked between Poland and
Lithuania, Governor Leonid Gorbenko declared a ``state of
emergency'' that amounted to an effort to control prices and
restrict hoarding. Siberia's Omsk province has announced strict
price controls of its own, as has the tiny semi-autonomous ethnic
Republic of Chuvashia on the river Volga, home to 1.2 million
people.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, an interim government spokesman said Russia had
plenty of food stocked up. But Russia looks increasingly likely to
default on its foreign debt obligations, which would make it harder
than it already is for Russian firms to get letters of credit to
buy products abroad. The food imports upon which the country
depends for an estimated 50 to 75 percent of its diet have dried
up. The only things in ample supply are dire predictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This crisis is very dangerous,'' said former acting prime
minister Yegor Gaidar, who freed prices in 1992 to kick off
Russia's post-Soviet transformation, as well as the price increases
that drove him out of office in less than a year. Tuesday, Gaidar
predicted a new round of hyperinflation if the government does what
the Duma and most other people in Russia want and prints money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have serious consequences and could end with the
formation of a Nazi regime,'' Gaidar told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin, who replaced Gaidar and was prime minister for
five years before Yeltsin fired him in March, says he can put
Russia together again, but the Duma looks poised to reject him a
third time. That would allow Yeltsin to dismiss the Duma, and push
Russia into a constitutional crisis that would make pulling the
economy out of its tailspin even more impossible than the task
seems now.
</P>
<P>
   The Duma has moved to prevent that from happening. If Yeltsin
reappoints Chernomyrdin, the house will begin impeachment
proceedings, senior lawmakers said Tuesday. While it is difficult
to actually remove the Russian president from office, during an
impeachment investigation Yeltsin would lose his right to dissolve
the Duma _ assuming he decides to obey the rules laid off in
Russia's much trampled-upon 1993 Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Hinting darkly that Yeltsin may be considering a military
solution to the standoff, Communist leader Gennady Zyuganov said
Tuesday that Russia's poorly fed army was not ready to back the
president. Yeltsin ended a power struggle with his parliament in
1993 by sending tanks to shell the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   But the Duma's stiff resistance to Chernomyrdin has caused
Yeltsin to pause. Tuesday, the Duma waited all day for Yeltsin to
either name a new candidate or reappoint Chernomyrdin. Instead, the
president remained holed up in his suburban residence south of
Moscow, huddling with advisers, according to the Kremlin press
service. As the Duma waited in vain for an answer, its supply of
imported fresh-ground coffee ran out, bringing the crisis home to
the entrenched lower house. Yeltsin is expected to name his
candidate Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Gaidar said Russia now needed a government with ``a clearly
defined reformist reputation'' willing to cut spending, raise and
simplify taxes, and win back battered international confidence,
Reuters reported. Yeltsin forced the Duma to accept a government
like that in April, under Sergei Kiriyenko, the 35-year-old premier
the president sacked after the ruble collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   This time, lawmakers have made it clear they want the next
government led by someone like most of them: aging former Communist
Party officials who reject Gaidar's monetarist solutions to
Russia's problems.
</P>
<P>
   Luzhkov, the 60-year-old mayor of Moscow, fits that bill, and
enjoys a reputation in Russia and abroad as a can-do manager,
thanks to his efforts to clean up Moscow. A lot of people charge
that Luzhkov is a crook, too, but the mayor has fought and won
dozens of libel lawsuits against anyone willing to put that in
print.
</P>
<P>
   Luzhkov is also openly ambitious, but the job he covets is
Yeltsin's, not Chernomyrdin's. The mayor has been putting together
a formidable war chest, a media empire, and a chauvinistic foreign
policy in preparations for scheduled presidential elections in
2000. But Luzhkov Tuesday denied having ambitions to become prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am already a prime minister _ of the government of Moscow,''
Luzhkov told reporters. ``There are no discussions about that and
none are planned.''
</P>
<P>
   Stroyev, too, has the sympathies of many Duma members. The
former Soviet Communist Party secretary of Oryol, an agricultural
region 200 miles south of Moscow, Stroyev stayed on as governor
after the Soviet collapse. His 1997 reelection, in which he won
over 95 percent of the vote, was panned as unfair and undemocratic
by most observers, but praised as a victory for reform by Yeltsin.
As the speaker of the upper house of parliament, the Federation
Council, which is made up of regional leaders, Stroyev, 61, has
been a loyal supporter of Yeltsin while talking about things the
Communists like to hear, like the need for greater state support
for agriculture and industry.
</P>
<P>
   But Stroyev Tuesday declined to be considered for the job of
prime minister, instead offering his support to Primakov, the
acting foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov's candidacy was suggested by the reformist leader
Grigory Yavlinsky. This may have come as a surprise to American
commentators who see the gruff 68-year-old Primakov as an
entrenched enemy of the West and Yavlinsky as reform's last best
hope. But in Russia, Primakov is seen as the consummate pragmatist
and a true patriot, and thus one of the few people in the country
who can sign songs from ``West Side Story'' with Secretary of State
Madeleine K. Albright, as the two did in Manila in July, and not be
slammed as a turncoat.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov also Tuesday refused to be considered a candidate,
saying he would gladly accept an invitation to continue as foreign
minister.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential candidate, Communist lawmaker and the former
head of the Soviet State Planning Agency, Yury Maslyukov, was out
of town and presumably out of the running.
</P>
<P>
   It could be that none of the prime minister candiates wants to
anger Yeltsin by appearing to want the job too much. Like the czars
he jokingly compares himself to, Yeltsin has set up a system in
which all power is concentrated in his office. Luzhkov, Primakov,
and Stroyev have been careful in recent years to avoid appearing
anything less than loyal supporters. But to do the job of prime
minister, they will need more autonomy than any of their
predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   The key condition any candidate for the job will demand of
Yeltsin, according to former Kremlin political adviser Vyacheslav
Nikonov, is that the president give up some of his power.
</P>
<P>
   The question remains: Is Yeltsin ready to accept that?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
