<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLLOCK-MONET-ART-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLLOCK AND MONET: DISTANT KINSHIP  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 13) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   He was dubbed the ``young man from Wyoming'' in the publicity
for his first show 55 years ago. Never mind that he actually spent
less than a year in Cody, a turn-of-the-century tract development
cooked up by William (Buffalo Bill) Cody, or that he went to high
school in Los Angeles until he dropped out to move to New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   The notion stuck of Jackson Pollock as a kind of cowboy, and
therefore a quintessentially American artist, the paradox being
that much of the American public vilified him, his work epitomizing
to them the sort of nonsensical art that Europe was always foisting
on the United States.
</P>
<P>
   How specifically ``American'' were Pollock's pictures? It's
fitting that two of the big shows this fall are the Pollock
retrospective at the Museum of Modern Art in November and the late
Monet show at the Museum of Fine Arts in Boston this month.
</P>
<P>
   For a long time critics regarded Monet's last years, at Giverny,
as irrelevant and anachronistic against the backdrop of movements
like Cubism and Constructivism. Most of the works stayed in Monet's
studio at his death, unsigned. He didn't even try to sell or
exhibit them, nor did his heir, his son Michel, who let them remain
in the studio for nearly 30 years, hoping opinion might shift in
their favor.
</P>
<P>
   It finally did. Artists like Andre Masson wrote admiringly of
the pictures in the early '50s. Big collectors like Walter Chrysler
Jr. and institutions like the Modern bought some of them,
justifying their value specifically in terms of what was going on
in art then: Monet's late works were called near-abstract
precursors of Abstract Expressionists' paintings. Pollock became a
kind of retroactive stamp of approval for Monet.
</P>
<P>
   As the critic Tom Hess put it at the time: ``In the past decade
paintings by such artists as Pollock, Rothko, Still, Reinhardt,
Tobey, and writings by such artists as Andre Masson and Barnett
Newman, have made us see in Monet's huge late pictures, and in the
smaller, wilder sketches he made for them, a purity of image and
concept of pictorial space that we now can recognize as greatly
daring poetry.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Pollock's supporters helped to establish his bona
fides by relating his art to late European modernism, which
included Monet. Popular books like John Canaday's ``Mainstreams of
Modern Art'' juxtaposed Monet with Pollock, giving credence to one
through the other. And Hess, writing about ``a web of hues'' and
``handwriting loops and swirls,'' used language associated with
Pollock to describe Monet.
</P>
<P>
   The coincidence of the two shows this season may therefore tell
us not just what sets Monet and Pollock apart, but, at least
implicitly, what connects them.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, popularity isn't a link. No matter what the
critics said, the public never needed any excuse to like Monet's
late Waterlilies. On the other hand, Pollock's paintings probably
continue to mystify and annoy people for whom even Duchamp's urinal
is, by now, a comprehensible, if not necessarily agreeable, act of
cultural insubordination.
</P>
<P>
   The persistent difficulty of Pollock's art perhaps partly
explains why this exhibition is the first full-dress retrospective
of his work in this country in more than three decades.
</P>
<P>
   It will be especially interesting to see how art experts react
to it. Pollock as much as any artist has been through the ringer of
critical opinion since he died in a car wreck 43 years ago. He has
been a lightning rod for Pop painters, feminists and just about
everyone else who has wanted to rewrite the story of postwar
American art, proof among other things of his unshakable
importance.
</P>
<P>
   Will this engender a certain feeling that he is old news by now?
His abstractions, exemplars of the 1950s, may seem unrelated to
what artists are doing in the '90s _ until, that is, you realize
the impact they have had on everyone from Richard Serra to Sue
Williams to Jason Rhoades to Terry Winters; and the list goes on.
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't be surprised if his work comes as a revelation to
many people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
