<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON SUMMONS DEMOCRATS FOR WHITE HOUSE MEETING
 &HT;    600&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton summoned House Democratic leaders
for an urgent White House meeting Wednesday morning amid signs that
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr was nearing completion of a
massive report to Congress on possible impeachable offenses.
</P>
<P>
   With fresh polls suggesting that Clinton's troubles could badly
hurt Democrats in November elections, the president decided to
postpone his departure for a brief trip to Florida on Wednesday so
he could meet over coffee in the White House residence with some of
his party's most prominent members.
</P>
<P>
   ''They've got a lot to talk about,'' said White House spokesman
Michael McCurry.
</P>
<P>
   He said the session would cover legislative matters as well as
the Clinton's relationship with former intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said the White House was trying to schedule a second
meeting Thursday involving Democratic and Republican leaders from
both the House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., and Minority
Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., were scheduled to meet Wednesday to
discuss possible procedures for impeachment proceedings against
Clinton. That meeting also is to include Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill.,
chairman of the House Judiciary Committee, and the panel's ranking
Democrat, John Conyers of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Committee staff members from both parties met Tuesday afternoon
in an attempt to resolve disputes over how to handle Starr's report
and conduct hearings on its findings. Those details are expected to
be put in the form of a resolution, which will be taken up by the
Rules Committee as soon as Starr notifies Gingrich that the report
is finished.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's political activity was unfolding as anticipation grew
of a report from Starr's office, which has been investigating for
eight months charges that Clinton had an affair with Lewinsky and
later urged her to lie about it under oath.
</P>
<P>
   After denying the affair in January, Clinton admitted to it in a
televised address Aug. 17, but he has continued to insist that he
did not counsel her to lie about it.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., told reporters he
expected Starr to deliver his report to Congress ``this week or
next.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's personal attorney, David Kendall, asked Starr in a
letter Monday that Clinton be allowed to have a week to review the
report and prepare a rebuttal before it is sent to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Starr rejected the request Tuesday, saying in a letter that ``no
barrier should intervene between the House of Representatives and
its prompt receipt of impeachment-related information.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's political position appeared to slip further Tuesday as
veteran Sen. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C., joined Democrats who have
publicly denounced the president's behavior in the Lewinsky
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're fed up,'' said Hollings, who is in a tough battle for
re-election. ``The behavior, the dishonesty of the president is
unacceptable, and we'll see with the report what course the
Congress will take.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, a moderate Republican group called Women in the Senate and
House urged Clinton to resign, saying he has ''tarnished the
presidency, crippled his effectiveness and shattered the trust of
the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   That came two days after Paige Patterson, president of the
Southern Baptist Convention, Clinton's own denomination, called
Sunday for Clinton to resign ''for the good of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said Tuesday, ''There are a variety of leaders in the
religious community, and some have taken a contrary point of view.
But they need to speak for themselves, out of their own conscience
and their own spirituality.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Even Clinton's efforts to direct attention to national
priorities yielded more embarrassment for him Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland Gov. Parris Glendening, a Democrat, snubbed the
president by refusing to attend an event at an elementary school in
nearby Silver Spring, Md., in which Clinton called for increased
federal resources for badly needed repairs to the nation's crowded
public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Glendening had announced Saturday that he wouldn't show up out
of concern that Clinton's troubles over Lewinsky could hurt
Glendening's own re-election chances this November.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said Glendening's views represented those of one
governor and not a national trend, adding that Clinton ''probably
understands why the governor feels the way he does.''
</P>
<P>
   Glendening's fears could be well-founded, suggest the findings
of a bipartisan poll released Tuesday that showed Clinton's
popularity declining and voters deeply disturbed by the Lewinsky
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, conducted by Democratic pollster Celinda Lake and
Republican pollster Ed Goeas, showed Clinton's job approval rating
at 56 percent, compared to ratings of 62 percent or higher in
similar polls late last month. The new poll found Clinton's
personal approval rating, a measure of how people regard him as a
person, at 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The pollsters said there were indications ``that Democratic
voters, demoralized by President Clinton's problems and seeing
little incentive to vote for politicians and a system teetering on
the brink of moral bankruptcy, may choose to stay home'' on
Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   Goeas was more direct.
</P>
<P>
   ''The president has lost the trust of a large segment of the
American people,'' Goeas wrote, ''and he suffers from a diminished
moral authority to lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Lake and Goeas jointly surveyed 1,001 registered voters around
the country between Aug. 24 through Aug. 26. The poll has a margin
of error of plus or minus 3.1 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Carr and Mark Sherman of the Atlanta Journal and
Constitution contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
