<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SENATE CAMPAIGN DEBATE REOPENS WEDNESDAY
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate's two-day countdown toward the year's
climactic vote on campaign finance reform will start Wednesday
morning, supporters of tighter restrictions said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Under an arrangement with Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss.,
Sens. John McCain, R-Ariz., and Russell Feingold, D-Wis., agreed to
offer their bipartisan bill late Tuesday as an amendment to the
Interior Department appropriations bill. Revived after a similar
bill was passed by the House in early August, their bipartisan bill
would ban big, unregulated gifts to political parties and tighten
rules for pre-election ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be having two full days of debate'' on Wednesday and
Thursday, McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   The key vote will be Thursday night. At that time, Republicans
expect to show that they have the votes to conduct a bill-killing
filibuster. Under Senate rules, McCain and Feingold will need votes
from 60 of the 100 senators in order to stop the filibuster.
</P>
<P>
   Though McCain has ``no new head counts,'' he is ``cautiously
optimistic that the uphill battle'' for the measure will be
successful, said his press secretary, Nancy Ives.
</P>
<P>
   In a similar test last winter, supporters were eight votes
short. Seven Republicans and all 45 Democrats sided with McCain and
Feingold, while 48 Republicans voted against.
</P>
<P>
   None of the 48 holdouts has announced a change of position,
although eight have been targeted in newspaper ads placed in their
home states by Public Campaign. Ellen Miller, executive director of
the pro-reform advocacy group, said, ``It's about time that the
senators follow the will of the people they were elected to
represent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I will vote to table it,'' Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., one of
eight GOP targets, said Tuesday. ``I think it's an ineffective bill
and probably has First Amendment problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Other ads are aimed at swaying Lott, Lauch Faircloth of North
Carolina, Judd Gregg of New Hampshire, Ben Nighthorse Campbell of
Colorado, Alfonse D'Amato of New York, Mike DeWine of Ohio and
Christopher ``Kit'' Bond of Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
