<HEADLINE>
APARTHEID ASSASSINS CONFESS KILLINGS IN OTHER LANDS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRETORIA, South Africa _ Some of the apartheid era's worst
assassins began confessing to the Truth and Reconciliation
Commission on Tuesday about murders and bombings they committed
outside South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Although the assassins, all former policemen, hope to get
amnesty against prosecution in South Africa for planning an
explosion that went off in the heart of London and for mailing
letter bombs that killed women and children in Angola and
Mozambique, they are, by confessing, opening themselves up to
charges and possible extradition requests from the countries where
the crimes were committed.
</P>
<P>
   An observer from Scotland Yard was in the audience Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The hearings are scheduled to take three weeks. The only person
to testify Tuesday before microphone problems cut the hearings
short was Johan Coetzee, commander of the national police Security
Branch from 1980 to 1983 and commissioner from 1983 to 1987.
</P>
<P>
   In his application for amnesty from the commission, which
investigates apartheid-era crimes, Coetzee outlined the plot behind
the bombing of the London headquarters of the outlawed African
National Congress on March 14, 1982. He described how bomb parts
were sent to London in a diplomatic pouch _ other reports have said
they were inside a cookie tin in the pouch _ and assembled inside
the South African Embassy. The bomb killed no one but damaged the
building.
</P>
<P>
   The attack was intended, Coetzee testified, both to scare the
ANC and to ``demonstrate our government's disenchantment'' that the
British government was letting the ANC and its ally, the South
African Communist Party, maintain public London offices.
</P>
<P>
   The Pretoria government was also incensed because it had
evidence that a 1981 rocket attack by five black guerrillas on
Voortrekkerhoogte _ South Africa's equivalent of the Pentagon _ had
been aided by two white British sympathizers who rented the house
in Pretoria where the guerrillas hid, and concealed their rockets
for them.
</P>
<P>
   The London bombing was ordered, repeatedly and adamantly, by the
late Louis le Grange, then minister of police, Coetzee testified.
He said he had not been told if anyone above le Grange _ including
President P.W. Botha _ gave the order. However, he was assured that
Pretoria was ``prepared to face severe diplomatic consequences''
with the British if the bombers were caught.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe,'' he added, ``that le Grange would have
decided on such an operation on his own.''
</P>
<P>
   In coming weeks, the hearings are expected to go into other
crimes, including letter bombs that killed Ruth First, wife of Joe
Slovo, then head of the South African Communist Party, in
Mozambique, and Jeanette Schoon, wife of Marius Schoon, an ANC
activist, and their 7-year-old daughter, Katryn, in Angola. Mrs.
First's three grown daughters were in the hearing room Tuesday, as
were Schoon and his 15-year-old son, Fritz, who was 2 years old and
in the room with his mother and sister when they were killed. Both
families oppose amnesty.
</P>
<P>
   Schoon, speaking in a hallway after the hearing, said he once
pressed Angola to arrest Williamson, who frequently travels there
to run a vegetable-import business. ``They didn't do anything,'' he
said, somewhat bitterly.
</P>
<P>
   Schoon said that this is the second time since his wife and
daughter were killed that he has been in the same room with the man
who confessed to their murder. Asked his feelings about the
commission, he said: ``I think it's going to bring national
reconciliation. In my case, it's not going to bring about personal
reconciliation. But on the whole, I'm in favor _ the really big
maggots are beginning to come out from beneath the stones.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Coetzee mentioned other ``extraterritorial operations'' he was
involved in planning: commando raids on ANC sites in Maseru,
Lesotho, and Gabarone, Botswana, and a bombing raid on Maputo,
Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
   Other people expected to testify include Craig Williamson, the
ex-policeman sometimes referred to as ``Super-spy'' in the South
African newspapers, who has already confessed to mailing the letter
bombs and overseeing the London bombers, and Eugene de Kock, known
as ``Prime Evil'' for his command of an assassination squad. He is
serving two life sentences and more than 200 years in prison for
his crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Whether these men are ever prosecuted by the countries where the
bombs exploded ``depends on whether they ever choose to leave the
country,'' said John Allen, chief spokesman for the commission.
</P>
<P>
   Theoretically, any ex-policeman who confesses to taking part in
the London bombing could be arrested if he appeared at an airport
of a European Union country. The Mozambican and Angolan justice
systems barely function, but Botswana is capable of effecting
arrests, and army generals who planned the Gabarone raid have
resisted confessing it to the commission because they still enjoy
hunting trips into Botswana, Allen said. He added that there were
no agreements he knew of with any country to ignore the crimes if
the amnesty applicants here confessed.
</P>
<P>
   Williamson's lawyer, Allan Levin, said he had asked Justice
Minister Dullah Omar for assurances that, if Williamson is granted
South African amnesty, he would fight any extradition request by
Britain or any other country. ``The minister has refused,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Counseling his client to testify was therefore a calculated
risk, Levin said. Williamson, who is well-known and easily
recognizable because he is obese and bearded, poses readily for
photographs and repeatedly talks about his crimes to journalists,
faced almost certain criminal prosecution in South Africa and a
$500,000 civil suit by Schoon. Amnesty will remove those threats
even if it opens him up to the possibility of pursuit by Britain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
