</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TANZANIA-STITH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON MINISTER TAKES OATH AS AMBASSADOR TO TANZANIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w, i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Several Massachusetts neighborhoods converged in a
gold-toned reception room overlooking the capital Tuesday as the
Rev. Charles R. Stith was sworn in as US ambassador to Tanzania
with pledges to increase trade and fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   The occasion was tinged by somber reminders that Monday marked
one month since the twin bombings of US embassies in Tanzania and
Kenya. At the opening of his speech, Stith read the names of the 10
embassy employees, all Tanzanians, who were killed in the Dar es
Salaam bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Not that anyone needed reminders. Outside, in a semi-circular
driveway that has long welcomed visitors to the State Department,
workers Tuesday finished installing 26 metal posts to keep out
cars. To add another layer of protection, the driveway was also
blocked by three government-owned Dodge Ram trucks, so new that the
price stickers were still on the windows.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the State Department, on once-bustling
Virginia Avenue, police waved away cars.
</P>
<P>
   Stith's determination to go to his post and supervise the
reconstruction of the embassy is a sign ``the United States will
not let terrorism scare us away from protecting out interests
overseas,'' said Susan Rice, the assistant secretary of state for
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the bombings, which killed 263 people and wounded
more than 5,000, Stith said, ``We were devastated by the loss, but
let the message go forth. ... We will never be intimidated by
terrorist thugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind him stood Edith Bartley, 25, an American whose father and
brother were killed in the Kenya explosion, and to his side was
John Lang, the top-ranking State Department official, who
coordinated the rescue effort in Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   Before the bombings, career diplomats considered Tanzania a
quiet, out-of-the way posting. The country of 29 million is a
democracy with free elections and a government that echoes
Washington's talk of free trade. Stith, though, will have the added
duties of overseeing reconstruction of the embassy and repairs on
the ambassador's residence while consulting with the FBI and other
agencies on the bombing investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In a rousing speech to nearly 400 friends _ mostly from Boston's
religious, academic and business communities _ Stith spoke about
the path from the segregated St. Louis neighborhood where he grew
up to his new assignment in East Africa as a US diplomat.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have risen from the cusp of poverty to become a
representative of this country and an adviser to its president is
an honor, and it is humbling,'' Stith said to applause in the
ornate Benjamin Franlin room atop the State Department. The
late-afternoon swearing-in ceremony had the air of a testimonial
dinner. The audience included retired Superior Court Judge Harry J.
Elam, former Boston schools superintendent Robert ``Bud'' Spillane,
Oak Bluff's Police Chief Joseph Carter, and Harvard University
professor Cornel West.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the bombings, the job in Tanzania ``is no longer a
pretty inconspicuous post,'' said Roxbury District Court Judge
Edward R. Redd. ``It's going to require extra vigilance and extra
prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Stith will be joined in Tanzania by his wife, Deborah
Prothrow-Stith, an associate dean at Harvard's School of Public
Health; their son Percy; their daughter Mildred, known as ``Mimi,''
and his mother-in-law, Mildred Prothrow, 80, who has plans to
volunteer at a school or hospital..
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing tapes to learn how to speak Swahili _ not that
I've learned anything,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Percy, 19, will take a year off from Bates College to work for
his father at the embassy. ``After the bombing, I had some friends
in college ask me, `Do still want to go there?' '' he said. ``We
definitely do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
