<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0298 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4437 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-BALL-BOS &LR;      09-08 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-BALL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALUE OF HOME RUN BALLS COULD EXCEED $1 MILLION EACH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Budgeted as MCGWIRE-SOSA; attn.: Ill.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The baseball that Mark McGwire hits for his 62d home
run will have a retail market value of around $9. But the minute
somebody catches it, the value will skyrocket to $1 million or
more.
</P>
<P>
   At least that was the contention of Steve Ray, a memorabilia
dealer who came to Busch Stadium intending to make just such an
offer to whoever winds up with the historic souvenir.
</P>
<P>
   There is no guarantee he will get a chance. The previous six
homer balls _ including the 61st, which tied Roger Maris's
single-season record _ were caught by fans who returned them to
McGwire. All professed a love for the game and agreed with McGwire
that the balls belonged either in his possession or in the Baseball
Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   But while Ray doesn't necessarily disagree with that notion, the
bottom line is that the market value of the 62d home run ball is
unlimited. With that in mind, his company, North Shore Sports LLC
of Northbrook, Ill., has combined with two New York memorabilia
dealers for a $1 million offer. The dealers will also shell out $1
million for the last home run ball of the season by McGwire or
Sammy Sosa, depending on who holds the record at the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   If Ray's company gets the ball, it will have the option of
marketing it or selling it to the highest bidder at auction. If the
company retains the ball, it would be loaned to the Hall of Fame,
much like a priceless painting for a museum exhibit. Each way, the
company would get some free publicity and a leg up on the
television shopping market, which reportedly has put in a bid of
$200,000.
</P>
<P>
   The bidding frenzy is no surprise. The selling of rings,
jerseys, bats, and baseballs is big business, Ray said. The lid
came off when Wal-Mart purchased a Honus Wagner baseball card from
Wayne Gretzky for $600,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they did was use it in a promotion,'' he said. ``They set
it up with packs of cards. If you bought one, you got an entry
blank. From what I heard, they gave away the $600,000 card in a
raffle, but they did $180 million in business from it. That's the
promotional value of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray, who stands 6 feet 6 inches, said he had a seat in the
left-field bleachers at Busch and planned to bring his glove
Tuesday night. He would love to catch the ball himself and cut out
the middle man. But he doubts that will happen. When the ball is
caught, he will try to make a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``One million is a great number,'' said Ray. ``It's a lot of
money. Do we think the ball is worth more? We don't know yet. This
piece is known across the entire world, not just the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally think the piece should be given back to Mark
McGwire. But we're not the first people to make an offer on this _
and I don't think we will be the last. We're in the business. This
is my industry. This is why we do what we do. That guy (Mike
Davidson, who caught No. 61 Monday) was offered $100,000 for the
ball and it didn't affect him. You think $1 million will affect
him? Yes, that much changes your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray acknowledged that the person catching the ball may have
staggering tax considerations _ though one of the burdens was
lifted Tuesday when the Internal Revenue Service, under
congressional pressure, ruled that gift tax laws will not apply to
the person who donates the ball to McGwire immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The sports memorabilia business is unique, said Ray.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like you're going to a mom-and-pop store and buy a
pack of cards,'' he said. ``It's a real business today. You can
display stuff and it brings you back to your childhood. It's not
like coins, which sit in a safety deposit box. This is fun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
