   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   Here are Tuesday night's columns:
</P>
<P>
   CONSOLIDATE-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ Two giant advertisers said on
Tuesday that they would consolidate portions of their accounts. The
announcements by the H.J. Heinz Co. and the Hewlett-Packard Co. are
indicative of the constant consolidations of agency assignments
that have been remaking Madison Avenue for most of the decade. They
are also emblematic of the continuing efforts by large marketers to
focus on brand-building campaigns. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stock prices continued their wild ride, but
on Tuesday the vertiginous swings left investors cheering, as the
Dow Jones industrial average rose 380.53 points, its biggest point
gain ever. Broader market averages also recorded hefty gains,
partly reversing their recent steep declines. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
