<HEADER>
A4441 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-LAND-ART-600&AMP;A     09-08 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-LAND-ART-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATCH OF DESERT IS KEY TO NEXT STEP IN MIDEAST TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   IN THE JUDEAN DESERT, WEST BANK _ Here is the parcel of land
that has been mired in the most recent stalemate between the
Israelis and the Palestinians: undulating dunes laced with scrub,
starkly beautiful if desolate, and barren but for the lizards and
an occasional Bedouin encampment.
</P>
<P>
   Southeast of Hebron and barely more than an hour from Jerusalem,
this is the latest 3 percent of the West Bank that the Israelis
have been loath to surrender and the Palestinians hesitant to
accept.
</P>
<P>
   It is expected to become a so-called nature reserve within the
13 percent of territory that Israel would turn over to the
Palestinians if the long-stalled second withdrawal were to move
forward.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Ross, the U.S. special envoy to the Middle East, is to
arrive in Jerusalem on Wednesday, his first trip since May, when
not only the size and location but the very notion of a final
parcel of land was a deal-breaking issue.
</P>
<P>
   Over the summer the Israelis have quietly agreed to surrender 13
percent of the West Bank, provided that they retain security
control over the last parcel. The Palestinians have tentatively
agreed to accept, although they have balked at Israel's demand for
zoning control over the nature reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Not even two weeks before the Jewish High Holy Days, when
Israeli diplomacy effectively shuts down for a month, Ross' trip
comes at a critical moment for all parties to the peace
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans are eager for a foreign policy success, or at
least eager to avert failure. Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is
feeling new political pressure as serious talk of a secular
centrist party has arisen. And Yasser Arafat is eager to gain
formal ownership of more land before next May, when the interim
peace accord expires and he says he intends to declare a
Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   While some Palestinians and some Israelis alike believe that
neither leader truly wants an accord, advisers to both insist that
they do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bibi feels pretty close, pretty confident that the whole thing
could move forward now,'' said David Bar-Illan, a spokesman, using
Netanyahu's nickname.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed Abdel-Rahman, a close adviser to Arafat, said: ``He has
depression. I tell him, `You are like Job. In your place I would
destroy the whole peace process.' But he says, `Fortunately I am
not like you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat has been facing an increasingly outspoken Palestinian
National Council, with some members quite critical of his
allegiance to two ministers accused of corruption. And he must also
massage tense relations with Hamas, the militant Islamic movement.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in his home in Gaza City, the spiritual leader
of Hamas, Sheik Ahmed Yassin, described the peace talks as a ``kind
of entertainment for people, just a waste of time, like a pretty
balloon waiting to be punctured.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, every time Ross and his negotiating team check into the
Laromme Hotel in Jerusalem, both sides turn hopeful. A
knowledgeable but skeptical Israeli observer put at 55 percent
their chances of making concrete progress.
</P>
<P>
   Since Ross' last visit, the primary channel for negotiations has
been between a personal confidant of Netanyahu, Yitzhak Molcho, an
urbane and almost apolitical lawyer, and Ahmed Qurei, better known
as Abu Ala, the senior Palestinian negotiator, who is also
considered the most skillful.
</P>
<P>
   This time, though, Israeli and Palestinian politicians have
questioned the Clinton administration's clout. ``America is weak,
so Arafat must wonder whether they can deliver, and that affects
their role here,'' said Natan Sharansky, the minister of industry
and trade.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ross' challenge is to work out a package that addresses, among
other things:
</P>
<P>
   _ Israel's demands for a Palestinian crackdown on illegal
weapons and for a large police force, possibly using the local CIA
station for inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   _ Israel's demand that Arafat convene the Palestine Liberation
Organization leadership _ or some part of it _ to eliminate from
the Palestinian Covenant a call for Israel's destruction.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Palestinian Authority's demands for a timetable for
Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank, and for the setting up of a
committee that would address the third redeployment of Israeli
troops.
</P>
<P>
   This land itself is still an issue within Israel. The land to be
handed over has not been publicly identified by the Israeli
government. It has been referred to only abstractly as the 3
percent, or the nature reserve. It would be declared a nature
reserve so that there could be no construction, but it is unlikely
to be a park.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli army, which uses this area as a firing zone, and
Ariel Sharon, the former defense minister who is now minister of
infrastructures, say it is of critical strategic importance, since
it is close to the Dead Sea and Israel's eastern border.
</P>
<P>
   But the only other option would be to hand over a piece of land
much closer to the Jewish settlements near Mount Hebron.
</P>
<P>
   Here there are few residents. With harsh sun and dryness during
the summer and severe flooding in the winter, it is inhospitable
terrain, even for animals. It is home to a species of lizard with a
thick, spiked tail and to the eagle. Several Bedouin families and
their goats live in the hills, but mostly above the parcel in
question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing would change here under the Palestinian Authority,''
said Salaam Jahaleen, a Bedouin man. ``There is no electricity, no
water, and there will be no electricity, no water. No TV, no
teachers. It's land that nobody wants to invest in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
