<SLUG> BC-CHILDREN-STRANGLED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHER CHARGED IN STRANGULATION DEATHS OF HER 6 CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PAUL _ A wisp of a woman, not quite five feet tall and
wearing a hospital gown to court, was charged Tuesday with six
counts of second-degree murder for the strangulation deaths of her
children.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, an organization that provides services for battered
Asian women began planning a defense fund for Khoua Her, based on
their belief that her actions were the byproduct of domestic
violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see this as the response of a woman who was abused and
exposed to violence,'' said Pacyinz Lyfoung, executive director of
Asian Women United of Minnesota. ``We are not condoning what was
done, but we are supporting Khoua Her in this difficult time in her
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Her was a sad-eyed, silent presence at her brief arraignment, at
which a judge ordered her held on $1 million bail pending a
psychiatric evaluation. No pleas were entered on her behalf, but
her court-appointed public defender said he would enter innocent
pleas at the earliest opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-year-old woman, married at 13 and a mother six times
before age 20, stood with a frown fixed on her face. She showed no
other emotion as a translator relayed the proceedings to her. She
smoothed her hair once, glanced briefly at spectators in the small
courtroom, and at one point rested her cheek on her hand.
</P>
<P>
   She seemed dazed at times, and moved gingerly in and out of the
courtroom. Her lawyer, Bruce C. Wenger, said afterward she had hurt
her back last Thursday night, apparently in a suicide attempt on
the night of the children's deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Wenger did not elaborate on Her's injuries, but a complaint
released Tuesday by St. Paul police added new details to the grim
discovery five days earlier at the McDonough Homes public housing
project.
</P>
<P>
   Police and paramedics arrived at the family's townhouse around 7
p.m., having been summoned by a ``suicide in progress'' call that
Her made to 911. Forcing open a locked screen door and pushing open
an unlocked inner door, the officers found a semiconscious Her on
the floor, a brown extension cord draped loosely around her neck
and a red mark on her skin beneath it.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Her, in the living room, police found a small girl, lying
face down with a piece of black material tied tightly around her
neck. The girl was still warm, the officers said, but attempts to
revive her failed.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of the stairway in the two-story home, a second
officer found an older boy, a strip of black material near his head
and an abrasion on his neck. A second boy was found in an upstairs
bedroom, also with a strip of material near his head.
</P>
<P>
   A third boy and a girl were found dead in the basement, and
shortly after, the sixth child, the youngest girl, was found dead
in the first-floor bathroom. The children were identified as boys
Kouaeai, 11, Samson, two weeks shy of his 10th birthday, and Tang
Lung, 7; and girls Nali, 9, Aee, 6, and Tung Ke, 5.
</P>
<P>
   While on the phone with the 911 dispatcher, Her allegedly spoke
at first only about suicide, but later stated, ``Well, I killed the
kids.'' She also allegedly told the dispatcher she tried to kill
herself about an hour before calling 911 and was having trouble
breathing. Police have not released the 911 tape.
</P>
<P>
   She offered no motive, the complaint says, saying, ``I don't
know why I killed my kids.'' Police found only Her and the children
in the home.
</P>
<P>
   Her's supporters pointed to what by all indications was a
combative relationship between Her and her estranged husband, Kong
``Tou'' Hang, who identified the children and told police he had
last spoken with his wife about a month ago. The two had been
brought together by Hang's mother in a Thai refugee camp.
</P>
<P>
   Police had been called to their home 17 times since February
1996, with husband and wife trading accusations of abuse. Hang told
police Her had threatened him with a shotgun in June 1997, but it
was Her who received a protective order against Hang.
</P>
<P>
   Police earlier had said they wanted to question Her's boyfriend,
with whom she had been living, but Tuesday homicide investigators
said he had been ruled out as a suspect.
</P>
</TEXT>
