<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROADWAY-SEASON-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BROADWAY, HIGH HOPES FOR THREE CHAMELEONS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 13) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Broadway seems to have chosen to dress like a wary,
much-married bride this season. There's plenty of something old and
something borrowed (from vintage movies and, of course, England)
and very little of something new.
</P>
<P>
   (For something blue, there's always the salty-mouthed Sandra
Bernhard, who is returning with her one-woman show ``I'm Still Here
... Damn It!'')
</P>
<P>
   Theater traditionally confounds handicappers, and at moments
like this it's a consolation to think that there are no guarantees
of what will run wire-to-wire. Did you really predict that a rock
operetta about AIDS and heroin addiction would break out of a small
downtown theater and go on to a robust life on Broadway and beyond?
</P>
<P>
   Still, I admit there are a few things I am looking forward to
with the sort of hopes that are usually dangerous. These are
centered on three actors who, though none have been on Broadway
recently, arrive with sterling pedigrees and in roles that would
seem to fit them like wet suits.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Short, the comedian of a thousand professional
alter-egos, will appropriately be playing not one but a number of
roles in the Roundabout Theater Company's revival of the 1962
musical ``Little Me'' this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Judi Dench, the great English actress who recently won American
hearts as a startlingly human Queen Victoria in the movie ``Mrs.
Brown,'' returns to New York this spring in David Hare's London hit
``Amy's View.''
</P>
<P>
   And Kevin Spacey, the Academy- and Tony Award-winning actor who
defies the casting director's notions of ``type,'' is also due this
spring as Eugene O'Neill's dream-smashing salesman in ``The Iceman
Cometh,'' a role he played to feverish acclaim in London.
</P>
<P>
   None of this trio gives off the megawatt glamour or Personality
with a capital P usually associated with stars. They are all, by
self-definition, chameleons, and anyone who knows their work has
marveled at the different colorings they seem to assume so
reflexively.
</P>
<P>
   They have technique to spare, for sure, but they are also
propelled by something far more potent: the fierce, fluid will to
become someone else.
</P>
<P>
   Short, who first claimed attention as a quick-sketch artist on
the Canadian comedy show ``SCTV'' and on ``Saturday Night Live,''
has always invested his oddball personae (remember the albino
show-biz baby Jackie Rogers Jr.?) with an energy and detail that
transcend cartoonishness.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood has never quite figured out how to harness that force.
Nor, to date, has the stage, even though Short brought a winning
flair to the singing schlemiels of the ill-fated musical adaptation
of ``The Goodbye Girl'' and the Encores concert production of
``Promises, Promises.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Little Me,'' which (like ``The Goodbye Girl'' and
``Promises, Promises'') has a book by Neil Simon, with songs by Cy
Coleman and Carolyn Leigh, this morph master may finally have the
opportunity he deserves. Short will be playing the doomed men in
the life of Belle Poitrine (an auspiciously cast Faith Prince), the
all-American femme fatale.
</P>
<P>
   Sid Caesar, a spiritual ancestor of Short's, created the parts.
Personally, I can't wait to see what Short does with the Maurice
Chevalier-like music hall performer who goes down with a
Titanic-like ship.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dench (aka Dame Judi) is a short, round-faced woman who
soared to majesty on the London stage long before she took on
Victoria. Many critics believe her Cleopatra, for the Royal
National Theater opposite Anthony Hopkins, may be the best of the
century. (``She's 5-foot-nothing, yet she's got sex and wit, wit
and sex,'' said the director Peter Hall.)
</P>
<P>
   In ``Amy's View,'' she plays, most suitably, an eminent actress
for whom the stage is, quite simply, a religion.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dench, after all, has repeatedly said she prefers theater to
movies because a film performance is fixed; she can't keep growing.
``Layers, I play a lot of layers,'' says her character in ``Amy's
View,'' later observing that true artistry ``comes with the passage
of time: you go deeper _ right down to the core.'' Any time Ms.
Dench goes exploring for that core, you would be well-advised to
accompany her.
</P>
<P>
   Spacey also knows from layers. Think about how he piled them on
and then peeled them away as a furtive, compulsively chatty felon
in ``The Usual Suspects.'' Indeed, trying to find the actor beneath
the layers of characterization has become a cottage industry for
celebrity profilers.
</P>
<P>
   None has been successful. ``Nobody knows who I am yet,'' he once
said, ``and I want to keep it that way.'' But you never doubt that
you know his characters intimately, whether Spacey is playing a
nice Jewish gangster in ``Lost in Yonkers'' on Broadway or a
murderous Southern antiquary in the movie ``Midnight in the Garden
of Good and Evil.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Iceman,'' he portrays a spiel spouter who is campaigning
against the illusions that people live by and who, in the play's
final act, divests himself of his own. This could turn out to be
the most provocative striptease of the season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
