<HEADLINE>
FRANK DISCOUNTS GAY INSULT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS BLACK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Representative Barney Frank Tuesday shrugged off a
crude remark made by a California congressman over the weekend as
part of the price of being a well-known, openly gay politician.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Randy ``Duke'' Cunningham, a Republican,
apologized afterward for the remark, made at a San Diego
appearance, in which he mocked Frank and gay sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Tuesday about Cunningham's comment, Frank, a Massachusetts
Democrat, said, ``He seems to be more obsessed with homosexuality
than most homosexuals.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank said his high visibility made criticism and comments about
his sexuality and personal life inevitable. ``It comes with the
territory,'' he said. ``I get involved in controversy so I have to
expect it.''
</P>
<P>
   Julie Pope, a spokeswoman for Cunningham, said her boss would
have no further comment. ``He said he was out of line and
apologized and that is it,'' she said. She said she did not know
whether Cunningham intends to apologize to Frank. Frank said he had
not heard from him Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
