<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4451 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RENO-FUNDRAISING-BOS &LR;      09-08 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENO-FUNDRAISING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO LAUNCHES NEW EVALUATION OF DEMOCRATIC FUND RAISING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Budgeted as Reno-Gore)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno Tuesday began a
preliminary investigation into whether President Clinton or his
campaign was involved in an illegal effort to use Democratic Party
``soft money'' to pay for 1996 reelection campaign ads, Justice
Department officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Reno is slated to decide at the end of 90 days whether to seek
the appointment of an independent counsel, whose work would be
separate from the probe being conducted by Kenneth W. Starr.
</P>
<P>
   As news of Reno's decision emerged in the late afternoon, White
House officials privately expressed exasperation that Starr's probe
could be followed by yet another investigation by another
independent counsel whose work could go on for years.
</P>
<P>
   Reno's decision to conduct a preliminary review into Democratic
fund-raising comes nearly two years after reports first surfaced
about a string of alleged irregularities in the party's
fund-raising operation.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a step she has long resisted, Reno announced her move in
a letter to the three-judge panel that could &UR;  &LR; decide whether to
appoint an independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have commenced a preliminary investigation,'' Reno wrote,
``involving President of the United States William Jefferson
Clinton concerning political advertisements during the 1996
election cycle.''
</P>
<P>
   A Republican-authored Senate report issued last year concluded
that Clinton oversaw an elaborate enterprise in which millions of
dollars in unregulated soft money _ raised for the Democrats'
party-building efforts _ was used to pay for Clinton's reelection
ads. Such ads are supposed to be financed only with regulated
``hard money,'' which is more restricted and regulated than soft
money.
</P>
<P>
   Reno has previously launched 90-day reviews to examine whether
an independent counsel should be appointed to examine if Clinton
and Vice President Al Gore illegally solicited campaign funds in
telephone calls from the White House. Reno decided last year
against seeking a counsel to examine the phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   But on Aug. 26, Reno said she had received new information about
Gore's calls that warranted another 90-day review. On Sept. 1, Reno
also ordered a 90-day preliminary review to determine if former
White House deputy chief of staff Harold Ickes violated campaign
finance laws.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, in making her third decision in a month to start a
preliminary review of fund-raising matters, Reno again cited new
information as she decided to open the 90-day review into whether
the Clinton-Gore campaign illegally used Democratic Party soft
money. While Justice Department officials declined to describe the
new information, it apparently involved a Federal Election
Commission audit that turned up new questions about the ads.
</P>
<P>
   The FEC audit reportedly recommended that the Clinton-Gore
reelection campaign repay $13.4 million in federal matching funds.
The Clinton-Gore campaign agreed to a $37 million spending limit in
the primaries in return for getting matching funds, and it would
have to repay an unspecified amount of money if it broke the limit
by using party soft money.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1996 campaign, both the Clinton and Bob Dole
campaigns benefited from millions of dollars worth of ``issue
advocacy'' ads broadcast by their respective parties. The ads were
supposed to help ``party-building'' efforts, but many of them left
the impression that they were election ads for Clinton or Dole. At
the time, officials of both parties said they were allowed to run
the ads as long as they didn't directly call for the election of a
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Common Cause, the self-styled citizen's lobby that
has long sought an investigation of the ads, Tuesday said they were
pleased with Reno's announcement. But the organization's president
said Reno should have expanded the 90-day probe to include an
examination of similar ads by the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is long overdue,'' Common Cause president Ann McBride
said. ``However, we believe that what happened in the 1996 election
happened in the Clinton campaign and Dole campaign. It is very
important this be a bipartisan investigation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 2000EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
