</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-JUSTICE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITING NETSCAPE LETTER, MICROSOFT AGAIN SEEKS DISMISSAL OF
ANTITRUST CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a document that Microsoft says undermines the
government's case against it, a Netscape attorney wrote to the
Justice Department in March and admitted that the Internet browsing
function cannot be removed from Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft filed the letter with a 48-page brief Tuesday renewing
the company's call that the government's antitrust case should be
dismissed. U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson is scheduled
to hear arguments on that question Friday. If he does not dismiss
the case, the trial is scheduled to begin Sept. 23.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's brief continued the recent escalation in rhetoric
used by the warring sides in the highly publicized legal battle.
Microsoft accused the government of ``blatant misrepresentation,''
``a smear tactic,'' ``vague and constantly changing allegations,''
``a profound lack of confidence in the case they filed in May,''
and ``a baseless personal attack on the credibility of Microsoft's
CEO.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They attempt to distract the court from the fatal defects in
their claims by slinging as much mud as they can at the defendant
(Microsoft) and by giving prominence to numerous irrelevant facts
in a desperate attempt to cloud the issues,'' Microsoft said in its
brief. ``Plaintiffs (the federal and state governments) apparently
hope that a combination of overblown rhetoric and the sheer volume
of paper they have submitted in opposition to Microsoft's motion
will lead the court to throw up its hands in frustration, conclude
there must be disputed issues of fact and deny Microsoft's motion
(for dismissal) without seriously considering the sufficiency of
plaintiffs' claims.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department shrugged off the latest filing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft's reply is nothing new,'' said Justice Department
spokeswoman Gina Talamona. ``We look forward to proving at the
upcoming trial that Microsoft engaged in a series of
anti-competitive acts to maintain its operating system monopoly and
to extend that monopoly to Internet browsers.''
</P>
<P>
   In its case against Microsoft, the Justice Department and the
attorneys general of 20 states and the District of Columbia accuse
the Redmond-based software giant of illegally seeking to extend a
monopoly on computer operating systems into the market for Internet
browsers. The illegally anti-competitive acts allegedly included
forcing consumers to use Microsoft's Internet browser by
integrating the browser into the ubiquitous Windows operating
system, and forcing computer manufacturers, Internet service
providers, Internet content providers and online service providers
to promote Microsoft's Internet browser through various licensing
deals.
</P>
<P>
   In its brief yesterday, Microsoft said there is no evidence to
support any of those claims, and cited the letter from Netscape
Communications Corp. attorney Allen Snyder to Justice Department
antitrust chief Joel Klein.
</P>
<P>
   In the letter, Snyder said ``we are totally unable to provide
examples of files that can or can not be deleted from Windows 98
since ... it is our understanding that it simply is not possible to
delete any portion of IE (Internet Explorer), or of browser
functionality, from Windows 98 as presently configured without
severely interfering with the operating system.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft said the letter shows the browser is an integral part
of the operating system, and not an add-on inserted for
anti-competitive reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft also claimed that it has canceled all of the offending
licensing deals to answer any concerns about Netscape's ability to
distribute its own competitor browser to consumers. Microsoft said
it dropped controversial licensing deals with Internet service and
content providers ``because they were generating negative publicity
and because Microsoft determined that they were not commercially
significant.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft also said it is discontinuing the controversial
``channel bar,'' a feature that allowed consumers to move easily to
World Wide Web sites of Microsoft's paying partners, such as
Disney. The feature was unpopular among Microsoft critics, who
worried the company was starting to control what types of content
consumers would see on the Internet. More importantly, the feature
also proved unpopular with consumers, Microsoft said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft said it does not expect to include the ``Channel Bar''
in upgrades or future versions of Windows 98.
</P>
</TEXT>
