<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEIBOWITZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE STARR REPORT AS CINEMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID LEIBOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - They say the report from Ken Starr may run a thousand
pages long, not counting the brown-paper wrapper and anatomy
charts. We are talking ``Gone With the Wind'' in length and in
scope, just as we'll be saying ``gone with the wind'' to the
presidency of Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The report should be ready for Congressional eyes this week or
next. The salient questions number three, by my reckoning:
</P>
<P>
   - Was that ``Newsweek'' source _ the one who said ``When people
read (this) report, they'll want to throw up?'' _ right on the
money?
</P>
<P>
   - How long until the impeachment hearings start?
</P>
<P>
   - How much scratch are we talking if we option Starr's findings
to Hollywood?
</P>
<P>
   This last question is key, because it represents the American
public's only chance to recoup the $40 million Starr has frittered
away. Plus _ let's be honest _ entertainment value may be the only
legacy left for President Number 42.
</P>
<P>
   Bill's always loved Hollywood; Hollywood's always loved Bill.
Adapting the Starr report might be a natural. Think silver screen,
big stars, Oscars:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Full Monica'' _ Fresh out of job offers from Revlon, a
group of unemployed former White House interns decides to take it
all off to, uh, make ends meet. Starring presidential
adviser/career counselor Vernon Jordan as himself and, in a cameo,
Phoenix Mayor Skip Rimsza as the &UR; political hack who demands the
interns stop dancing at 1 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The flick would be rated R for nasty imagery, but it could've
been worse. We could've sold to the pornmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Line of Fire''? ``Air Force One''?
</P>
<P>
   Excuse me while I go take a shower.
</P>
<P>
   Which isn't to say we couldn't sell Starr's goods to television.
Again, there's limitless possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four Years'' _ Modeled after ``60 Minutes,'' this
investigative news hour stars Starr himself! Finished with Clinton,
the special prosecutor rids the country of some other overhyped
public figures: The pilot reveals that Ellen DeGeneres once kissed
men and that Mark McGwire doesn't wear a cup. He might be slow,
obsessed and pricy, but Ken Starr always gets his man.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this would work better as a comedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Allewinsky McBeal'' _ The fact that the ``Big Creep'' won't
call sends our heroine running to a shrink. While on the couch, she
finally gets to the bottom of her irrational fear of dry cleaners.
</P>
<P>
   And, hey, forget that Bob Saget. He's got nothing on our newest
reality TV show.
</P>
<P>
   ``America's Funniest Home Videos and Audios'' _ Linda Tripp
hosts this half-hour laughfest. Now you can actually hear the men
getting hit in the groin with errant golf balls.
</P>
<P>
   Nor should we leave out the cable networks. No way Lifetime, the
chick channel, could possibly resist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hillary!'' _ You go girl! She gives investment advice _ stay
away from land in Arkansas! She gives fashion tips _ black works
best at resignation ceremonies! And she knows what life's like as
the other woman _ mortifying! She's the First Lady, and if half the
village tunes in, she's got herself a ratings winner.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there's the President himself. Mr. Televised Town Hall
seems a natural as a talk-show host, where he could feel your pain
_ among other things. The trouble is, gabbing's a crowded field,
and Bill Clinton may be the only man in America with less
credibility than Jerry Springer.
</P>
<P>
   I hate to typecast the guy, but I think he's stuck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spin City'' _ A politician in trouble tries to lie his way
clear, with absolutely no luck at all.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, I have to admit it _ even to me, that sounds like
dullsville. Clinton's sitcom would probably be cancelled midway
through its run.
</P>
<P>
   So it goes in America as we wait for the special prosecutor to
weave his thousand-page tale. Life mirrors art. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Leibowitz can be reached at david.leibowitz(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 2010EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
