<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0311 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4466 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGO-TALKS-NYT &LR;      09-08 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGO-TALKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEACE GETS LIP SERVICE AS TALKS ON CONGO END 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VICTORIA FALLS, Zimbabwe _ Despite the official announcement
Monday night of a cease-fire agreement in the Congo, the latest
peace negotiations ended Tuesday much like the others in recent
weeks _ with nothing more than a joint statement endorsing peace as
an ultimate goal.
</P>
<P>
   The talks did succeed in bringing together all the parties
involved in the conflict, including the presidents of Congo,
Zimbabwe, Namibia, Angola, Uganda and Rwanda. But apparently
several issues left the participants deeply divided and at times,
officials acknowledged, there were heated exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the rebel forces also attended, but they were
kept separate from the heads of state and complained that they had
been badly treated and had been forced to spend four hours in a
stifling room without windows.
</P>
<P>
   As the presidents gathered for a news conference late Tuesday
morning, the rebels left for the airport, saying they did not feel
bound by anything the presidents had signed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We very much support a cease-fire,'' said Bizima Karaha, one
of the leaders of the rebel group, the Congolese Democratic
Coalition. ``But because we have been excluded from it, we are not
bound by it.''.
</P>
<P>
   The presidents had little to show for their hours of discussion.
They issued a communique saying that ``the Congo needs peace'' and
that ``there must be a cessation of hostilities.'' They also said
their defense ministers would meet in two days in Ethiopia for
further talks.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting broke out in Congo in July as rebel forces, backed by
Rwanda and Uganda, attacked the government of Laurent Kabila, who
had himself been in power less than 18 months. Kabila toppled the
former regime in the Congo, then known as Zaire, with the help of
Rwanda and Uganda but then had a falling-out with his former
allies.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels are accusing Kabila of corruption, nepotism and
stirring ethnic hatred, particularly against Tutsi, the ethnic
group that dominates the leadership of Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   At first the rebels appeared to be gaining ground quickly, and
even seemed poised to march into Kinshasa, the capital. But Kabila
was able to rally new allies _ Angola, Zimbabwe and Namibia _ and
has managed to turn the tide.
</P>
<P>
   Government forces appear to have pushed the rebels back to the
eastern part of the country. Fighting was reported to be continuing
even as the heads of state issued their statement.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the summit meeting, President Frederick Chiluba
of Zambia, admitted that much work had to be done before any
concrete peace proposals could be agreed upon.
</P>
<P>
   The most heated exchanges were apparently between Kabila and
Rwanda's president, Pasteur Bizimungu. One sticking point has been
that Rwanda continues to assert that it has no troops in Congo, and
therefore it cannot withdraw them. Uganda has admitted to having 50
troops in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The way the rebels should be treated during talks was also in
dispute.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
