<HEADER>
A4469 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOW-09-COX     09-08 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW-09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stocks soar after Greenspan announcement
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Did Chicken Little get it wrong again?
</P>
<P>
   You'd think so, judging by the stock market's stunning surge on
Tuesday, when three stock market averages posted their biggest
one-day point gains ever.
</P>
<P>
   The technology-loaded Nasdaq composite index jumped 6 percent,
reflecting the intense demand for technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The blue chip Dow Jones industrial average rose 5 percent and
the Russell 2000 index of smaller stocks was up 4.3 percent, all on
strong volume.
</P>
<P>
   Many Wall Street analysts were already saying late last week the
worst of the late summer sell-off might be over, though market
weakness could continue.
</P>
<P>
   That was before Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan buoyed
investor spirits with a speech Friday suggesting the Fed's next
move might be to cut short-term interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Long-term Treasury yields, which are set by the marketplace,
have already trended down to historic lows.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan didn't promise a rate cut, but that was the spin that
the market put on his comment that inflation is no longer the Fed's
No. 1 problem.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's next policy meeting is Sept. 29.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan's comments were followed by a three-day holiday
weekend of relative calm on world economic fronts, which primed
investors to be in a buying mood on Tuesday. Stocks surged and
stayed there all day, adding to their gains at the end of the
session.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts think this signals the end of the worst sell-off
on Wall Street since the 1990 bear market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not issuing an all-clear because we never told people to
duck and cover,'' said Alan Skrainka, chief market strategist for
Edward Jones in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   He noted a cut in interest rates would be a stimulus to business
spending that would also help the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy drives the stock market. Any move that helps the
economy would definitely be good news for profits and for stocks,''
said Skrainka.
</P>
<P>
   But other analysts are more cautious about what Tuesday's buying
means, pointing out that historically, markets often rally as much
as 50 percent from a big slump, only to dip again.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow fell 19.3 percent from its July 17 high of 9,337.97 to
its Aug. 31 low. Tuesday's close represented a 6.4 percent rebound
from that low. If the Dow recaptures 50 percent of its recent loss,
it would be back above 8,400.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of technical damage has been done to the market and it
would be a surprising situation for it to come roaring back,'' said
Interstate/Johnson Lane technical analyst Ricky Harrington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be more logical for the market to rebuild a base. I
wouldn't be surpsied to see market sell-off Wednesday,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington said the Dow is still trading at a price-to-earnings
ratio of about 20 despite the index's recent drop of almost 1,800
points, which means there is still a lot of ``froth'' in share
prices. The Dow's historic P/E is about 15.
</P>
<P>
   The next most frequent scenario from analysts is that stocks
will continue to trade within a 100-point range for the rest of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   By then, analysts say the full impact of another factor that is
getting increased attention on Wall Street _ President Clinton's
White House problems _ will likely have been resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
