<HEADER>
A4472 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NC-CLINTON-COX     09-08 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NC-CLINTON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Opinions vary in town that bears president's name
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLINTON, N.C. _ Retired state trooper William Pate gets so angry
thinking about President Clinton these days that he wants his rural
Carolina hometown to change it's name.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want nothing to do with the man,'' said Pate. ``I
think it's a disgrace.''
</P>
<P>
   The president has never set foot in his Carolina namesake _ it
was named for a Revolutionary War hero 180 years ago _ but his sex
scandal and independent counsel Kenneth Starr's investigation stir
up plenty of strong feelings among residents here, with many ready
to forgive and forget and others so upset they say they would run
him out of town.
</P>
<P>
   Located about 60 miles south of the state capital of Raleigh and
the hometown of Sen. Lauch Faircloth (R-N.C.), Clinton may not be
Middletown, USA, but residents here sum up the president's travails
in much the same way as the rest of the country outside of
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   For folks here, Clinton's statements about former White House
intern Monica Lewinsky and his relationship with her aren't about
legal semantics _ whether or not what he said was misleading but
``legally accurate.'' It's about sex in high places, telling the
truth and the nation's priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Some, like Mayor Emsley Kennedy, think Starr has ``wasted the
taxpayers' money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A person's private life ought to be his private life, whether
it's the president of the United States or the person on the
street,'' Kennedy said. ``By gosh, what's it been _ four or five or
six years now? It's just ridiculous, I think. If they've got some
charges bring them forward and get it over with. Decide what you
are going to do and get on with the country's business.''
</P>
<P>
   Others such Pate get so bothered talking about the president
they loose their breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was told when I was a youngin' to tell the truth,'' said
Pate. ``He stood up there and looked in a million peoples' faces
and said I did not do it. And then he come back and said I did do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This country would be a lot better with (him) out of there,''
Pate continued, working up a full head of steam. ``If he'll lie
once, he'll lie again. He's never told this country he's sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, the town of Clinton was named for Lt. Col.
Richard Clinton, militiaman in the revolutionary war, whose land
now holds the Sampson County courthouse. Albert Kaleel, a member of
the Clinton City Council, said no one has asked to have the town's
name changed since the Clinton scandal broke.
</P>
<P>
   In fact Kaleel, who's been serving hot dogs and hamburgers from
his lunch counter on the town square since 1932, said he thinks the
president ought to be left alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made a mistake,'' said Kaleel between serving customers on
a recent afternoon. ``He'd been better off if he'd owned up to it
to start with, but after all he did own up to it eventually. How
many men wouldn't deny this if their wives were around?''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Kaleel, his own wife, Jane Kaleel, was around
to hear his final comment and issued a derisive snort.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very, very careless and a liar,'' Mrs. Kaleel said of the
president. ``I would hate for him to be my husband.''
</P>
<P>
   James Colwell, clipping hair at Colwell's Barber Shop just down
the street, was more forgiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just a man,'' said Colwell. ``I can't expect no more of
him than I can expect of myself. I don't hold anything against him
_ I've got my own problems to keep straight.''
</P>
<P>
   Andy Shaffer, with the local Farm Bureau, said he expects more
from politicians, especially presidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we ought to have leaders who have bad morals,''
said Shaffer, who belongs to the men's religious organization known
as Promise Keepers. ``If he's a government leader he ought to have
a little integrity. I don't think he has any. You are talking about
someone who's supposed to be an example to my family and my
children. I don't think he's setting a very good example.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether supportive or critical of the president, residents here
said the president's problems haven't occasioned nearly the amount
of discussion and debate as they have in Washington, where Congress
is paralyzed in anticipation of Starr's report and pundits can talk
of nothing else.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Warren, owner of Just Nailz, said her customers don't talk
about the president that much, or if they do, it's ``comments like,
'They should leave him alone, let him run the country.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``His personal problems are his own business,'' said Warren.
``If his wife can live with him then I can, too. He's not the only
one who has done that. He is probably the only one who has been
exposed. It's just a character trait in high places.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
