<HEADER>
A4476 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOREA-ANALYSIS-COX     09-08 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-ANALYSIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    North Korea: An analysis
 &HT;    By Han S. Park
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   After some four years of waiting, Kim Jong Il, the son of
deceased leader Kim Il Sung, has finally been officially elected as
leader of North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   That was not a big surprise:
</P>
<P>
   Kim has been the defacto leader of the country since his
father's death, even though the succession _ the first instance of
hereditary succession in a communist system _ was only now made
official.
</P>
<P>
   But, for Korea watchers, the arrangements under which he took
control were quite surprising.
</P>
<P>
   First, the position of president has been eternally reserved for
the deceased leader, Kim Il Sung. Second, the chairman of the
Military Commission, the position to which Kim Jong Il was
re-elected, assumes the function of head of state. Finally, the
chairman of the Supreme People's Assembly (Parliament) performs the
ceremonial functions of representing the country internationally.
</P>
<P>
   These arrangements have great symbolic meaning in North Korea
and might provide some insight into future behavior on the part of
the regime.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement eternally reserving the position of president
for Kim Il Sung, rather than abolishing it, supports the
often-heard pronouncement from North Korea that ``the Great Leader
is living with the people forever.'' This move is consistent with
the theological tone emerging in ``Juche,'' the guiding ideology of
North Korea, which frequently mentions the concept of eternal life.
The moves also signal that Kim Jong Il can never be independent of
his father and that the two will always be perceived as one in the
eyes of the people.
</P>
<P>
   Since it is unclear whether the younger Kim has ever achieved
the level of support achieved by his father, he should be able to
benefit from this linkage to his father's charismatic leadership
and legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Also of significance is the promotion of the position of
chairman of the Military Commission to the head of state. This
sends a signal that the military clearly occupies a central
position in the government. There will be no civilian-military
strife and there should be no ambiguity as to where the ultimate
authority rests.
</P>
<P>
   This combination of extreme nationalism and militarism can be
explosive and is causing concern around the world. North Korea has
a strong military possessing weapons of mass destruction, and, as
evidenced last week with the launching of the Taepo Dong missile
over Japan, now has improved delivery capabilities. Even in the
face of impossible odds, North Korea has never been timid about
standing up to the rest of the world, behavior that often causes
jitters around the region. This transition will do nothing to calm
these fears.
</P>
<P>
   Another significant factor in this succession is that although
Kim Jong Il has officially assumed the position as head of state,
it is clear that he will rarely be seen in public and will avoid
excessive media exposure or exposure to foreign leaders. These
functions will be handled primarily by the chairman of the Supreme
People's Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   This will enable the North Koreans to construct for Kim Jong Il
the charismatic, almost mythical, leadership qualities held by his
father without much, if any, public scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   All of these arrangements signal that the world should not
expect any dramatic leadership changes or policy shifts from North
Korea. Kim Jong Il's power will remain absolute as the chief of
state and the commander of the military. His authority will be
unquestioned and unshakable as it is supported by the eternal
authority of his father.
</P>
<P>
   Now that North Korea has officially completed the process of
succession, it is the obligation of the new government, if it is to
maintain its legitimacy and support of the people, to develop
policies to overcome the critical food shortage in the country and
to rehabilitate the health of its people.
</P>
<P>
   While North Korea is clearly the most unpredictable system on
the planet, the dire conditions in which its people now live make
it at least in part the responsibility of the community of nations
to find a way to work with, not alienate, the North Korean
leadership. This will require wisdom and empathy on the part of all
parties concerned, including especially North Korea itself.
</P>
<P>
   Han S. Park, one of the nation's leading experts on North Korea,
directs the Center for the Study of Global Issues at the University
of Georgia. He has traveled to North Korea frequently and is a
consultant for ABC News.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
