<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4479 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-MCGWIRE-BALL-TAX-     09-08 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MCGWIRE-BALL-TAX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRS NOW SAYS NO TAX ON RECORD-BREAKING BASEBALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also BBO-McGWIRE, BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN.) 
(nk) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It ain't so, the IRS said Tuesday. The fan who
grabs the home run that breaks Roger Maris' record will not face a
huge tax bill if he or she turns the ball over to the player who
hits it.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with a public relations debacle, the tax-collection agency
put out a statement Tuesday afternoon explaining the ``basic income
and gift tax principles'' that would apply to a fan who ends up
with the historic ball and returns it. Its interpretation of those
principles Tuesday was far more favorable to such a fan than the
more literal-minded interpretation that the IRS had previously said
might apply.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, the fan in these circumstances would not have
taxable income,'' the agency said, deflating legions of IRS bashers
who had already worked themselves into a high dudgeon over reports
that the lucky fan could face a tax bill of hundreds of thousands
of dollars just for turning the ball over to Mark McGwire of the
St. Louis Cardinals or Sammy Sosa of the Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS said snagging the ball and giving it back would, for
legal purposes, be like winning a sweepstakes but declining the
prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``There would likewise be no gift tax in these circumstances,''
the agency said, adding that the tax consequences would be
different if the fan tried to cash in by selling the ball. By some
estimates, the ball could be worth $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes pieces of the tax code can be as hard to understand
as the infield fly rule,'' said IRS Commissioner Charles Rossotti.
``All I know is that the fan who gives back the home run ball
deserves a round of applause, not a big tax bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Rossotti, who has been trying to reshape the agency into a
customer-friendly service center for taxpayers, acted after members
of both parties in Washington took turns Tuesday mocking and
criticizing the IRS for even allowing the issue to come up.
</P>
<P>
   Although the IRS has said all along that it will have to look at
all the circumstances before determining the tax implications of
the ball that breaks the single-season record of 61 home runs, it
had done little until Tuesday to dispel the impression that it
would apply the laws and regulations strictly. Treating the
baseball like any other valuable gift would have meant slapping a
tax of as much as 40 percent of the ball's value, although the
donor could have chosen to reduce his or her liability by using the
$625,000 lifetime exemption on gifts available to all taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking before the IRS made its announcement Tuesday, White
House spokesman Mike McCurry said the possibility of the agency's
stepping into a moment in baseball history was ``about the dumbest
thing I've ever heard in my life.'' House Minority Leader Richard
Gephardt of Missouri said that ``only the IRS could turn a
once-in-a-lifetime catch into a once-in-a-lifetime Catch-22.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. William Roth, R-Del., who led hearings over the last year
into abuses of taxpayers by the IRS, said he had called Rossotti
Tuesday to urge him to avoid invoking tax provisions ``that defy
common sense and are patently unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that there was ever even the possibility of Mark
McGwire's historical 62nd home run baseball being taxed,'' Roth
said, ``is a prime example of what is wrong with our current tax
code.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 2014EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0319 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4486 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BO     09-08 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGASSI DEFEAT LEAVES OPEN FLAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Night and day,'' as Sinatra used to croon, ``you
are the one.'' But the ``you'' the folks at Flushing Meadow wanted
so badly _ Andre Agassi _ was not the one after a night and day of
tennis.
</P>
<P>
   In the roaring traffic boom, in the silence of their lonely
room, they thought of him. But those plaintive and positive
thoughts went the way of so many love affairs, dashed on the rocks,
breaking up Tuesday on the green hardrock rectangle within Louis
Armstrong Stadium where he had won their hearts and the title four
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tournament is over,'' a woman lamented as Andre plopped a
last feckless backhand into the net. She was far from alone in her
sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   Karol Kucera, a gangling 6-foot-3-inch blond who couldn't get
out of the first round in Boston a couple of weeks ago, didn't
quite see it that way after his triumph in two acts, 6-3, 6-3, 6-7
(5-7), 1-6, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   In Bratislava, Slovakia, where he originated 24 years ago, it
appears to the good burghers that their favorite son is in the
quarterfinals of the US Open against Pete Sampras (whom he beat at
the Australian Open) and that business here will be conducted
through Sunday _ even though Andre is over.
</P>
<P>
   It took Monday night and Tuesday afternoon to determine how over
Andre is.
</P>
<P>
   Andre was over in the third game of the last set. He and Karol
agreed on that. He let a floundering Kucera escape from two break
points (15-40) that would have given Agassi a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no confidence when I was down there, 0-2, 15-40. I
needed a couple of points to get my confidence back,'' Kucera said.
Agassi _ ``I needed that game to keep control'' _ helped with a
couple of sloppy backhands, and Karol anted a big forehand and an
ace.
</P>
<P>
   For the pigeon-toed, balding, yet unquestionably appealing
husband of actress Brooke Shields, plus the 9,600 Agassians
cramming the arena, it was a two-act tragedy. Probably also for his
smooshy shoemaking crowd, suffering at long distance in Beaverton,
Ore. (even though Kucera works for the same haberdasher).
</P>
<P>
   Act I, Monday night, had a suspenseful scenario during which the
hero tried every playground scuffle to psyche out Kucera _
moonballs, mimicking his foe, some stalling _ all to the audience's
joy. Possibly, it was a rewrite of ``Winning Ugly,'' a primer by
his coach, Brad Gilbert. It worked. Two points from defeat in the
tie-breaker, Agassi steadied and grabbed the set, then a 3-0 edge
in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   But the curtain came down too soon in a Charlton Heston special
effect. Like Moses, Kucera was saved by water. ``I was a little bit
lucky that it was rain coming,'' he said. ``It was very tough when
Andre turned the match around, tough for me to stay concentrated.''
</P>
<P>
   He felt like Moses among the Egyptians. ``I was fighting against
the crowd. I was very nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   Act II, a dry, sunny Tuesday afternoon, promised salvation as
Agassi banged out five straight games to within one point of making
it all come true. However, there was to be no happy ending.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Andre's fight from two sets behind a yellow 8-ball and
persistent delaying of defeat until the foozled fifth set, his
``Wait till next year!'' claque will have to comfort themselves
with a 1998 campaign in which Agassi phoenixed his way out of the
ash heap and flapped from No. 141 back to the Top 10.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, though, it was back to steerage when you consider how
he futilely performed on the first-class occasions: Australian,
fourth round to Alberto Berasategui; French, first round to
qualifier Marat Safin; Wimbledon, second round to Tommy Haas. Now
Kucera. Pinned by not exactly pinup boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about how you play at the right times vs. my game,''
said Andre straightforwardly. ``By my normal standards, it's
certainly been a bad year. I've got to keep it in context because
of how long it's been since I've been competitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The year has gone to set me up for what I'm hoping to be now,
the next level in my game _ I'm talking a few years of great
tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   Everybody hopes so. But it was shocking that he couldn't take
advantage of Kucera's serve when it went wobbly. Karol missed 20 of
27 first balls at one stretch in the fifth and decided just to put
the ball in play at speeds that wouldn't get you arrested in a
school zone.
</P>
<P>
   They took turns getting tight in the fifth, and Agassi won that
phase as the big Slovak outhit and outran him right out of town.
</P>
<P>
   Still, night and day, Andre's the one, the male tennis passion
for his countryfolk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
