<HEADLINE>
RAFTER, NOVOTNA ADVANCE WITH WORKMANLIKE WINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ While Andre Agassi was playing to a full house in a
side stadium, Patrick Rafter and Jana Novotna were workmanlike on
the main stage.
</P>
<P>
   No moonballs. No mimicking the ball tosses of opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Just cool confidence born of tennis titles. Major titles.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter won his first, and thus far only, Grand Slam crown here
last year. Novotna, long known as a player who had trouble
finishing off big matches, took care of that reputation with her
first at Wimbledon in July.
</P>
<P>
   Both, not surprisingly, liked the feeling. And both are on track
to feel it again.
</P>
<P>
   While Agassi lost to Karol Kucera, 6-3, 6-3, 6-7 (7-5), 1-6,
6-3, and messed up a quarterfinal marquee matchup with Pete
Sampras, Rafter eliminated Goran Ivanisevic, 6-3, 6-4, 4-6, 6-1. He
plays Jonas Bjorkman, a 6-4, 2-6, 6-2, 6-2 winner over Jan
Siemerink.
</P>
<P>
   In other fourth-round matches, unseeded Thomas Johansson and
Mark Philipoussis advanced with upsets and will meet in a
quarterfinal. Johansson beat No. 11 Yevgeny Kafelnikov, 3-6, 6-3,
6-3, 7-6 (9-7), and Philippoussis took out No. 13 Tim Henman, 7-5,
0-6, 6-4, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   Magnus Larsson beat Oliver Gross, 6-4, 7-5, 5-7, 6-2, to make it
three unseeded players in the bottom half of the draw. Larsson
plays the winner of last night's match between No. 7 Alex Corretja
and No. 10 Carlos Moya.
</P>
<P>
   Novotna, seeded third, crushed the No. 11 seed, Steffi
Graf-slayer Patty Schnyder, 6-2, 6-3. Novotna plays the winner of
Tuesday night's match between two-time winner Monica Seles and
defending champion Martina Hingis.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter welcomed the Monday night storm that suspended his match
until Tuesday. On Monday night, the huge-serving Ivanisevic seemed
to be heating up, Rafter said.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for Ivanisevic was that any serving success was
fleeting.
</P>
<P>
   His answer when asked the difference in the match was blunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serve,'' Ivanisevic said. ``Yeah, I had maybe 40 percent first
serves in. I cannot play on the junior girls with that kind of
percentage.''
</P>
<P>
   He had the numbers right. He put in 40 percent of his first
serves for the match and had only 25 percent in the fourth set.
Rafter put in 75 percent of his first serves in the match.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's confident,'' Ivanisevic said. ``He's hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year Rafter came here after a summer of getting to five
tournament finals and losing them all. This summer he won all three
finals he made, including two last month.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, he's riding his serve-and-volley game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm probably serving just a little bit smarter than
what I was last year,'' he said. ``I was serving very well last
year. But this year I can maintain that with consistency and just
sort of mixing it up a lot better, volleying really well, moving
well, just playing a smart game when I need to.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivanisevic will attest to that.
</P>
<P>
   Novotna, who turns 30 next month, is on the top of her game,
too, and is putting together a career year. She went to the
quarterfinals at the French Open and then won three straight
titles, including Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, you know, winning a Grand Slam gives you confidence,
not only for the next couple of weeks, but it gives you confidence
for life,'' Novotna said. ``You know, not too many people can do
something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   No longer, Novotna said, is she hearing herself referred to as a
choker.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the first time I hear it in six weeks,'' she said. ``I
didn't hear it for such a long time and it really felt good. Every
time I do a press conference or I'm recognized by somebody,
(there's) not a word about anything in the past, only the present
time, which is great. I have been waiting a long time to change
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Experience and age, Novotna felt, didn't hurt at all against
Schnyder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected a much harder match, there's no question about
it,'' she said. ``But I also knew that after beating Steffi, she
may have a letdown a little bit because she's not as experienced.
She's still very young. In the future, she will be a great player.
But at this moment, she just simply didn't know how to handle the
whole situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Novotna, by the way, didn't mind at all that Schnyder ousted
Graf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very pleased, I must say, when I heard the news that she
beat Steffi,'' she said. ``There's no question about it. I mean,
playing Steffi today in these weather conditions would be really
difficult because she hits really hard and she's very overpowering.
It would be much harder for me to create my game.''
</P>
<P>
   She had little problem doing that Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
