<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4496 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRASH-RDP-ART-375&AMP;ADD     09-08 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-RDP-ART-375&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLIGHT 111 BLACK BOX RECORDED PLANE'S SYSTEMS BREAKING DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: a 1stLd-Writethru is scheduled to move by 9:30 p.m. ET) 
(ART ADV: a graphic for use with this story is being sent to NYT
graphics clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(HLW) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Nova Scotia _ Well before Swissair Flight 111 hit the
water last Wednesday night, a computerized black box that tracks
dozens of functions on the big MD-11 recorded system after system
breaking down, the chief investigator said on Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   While the box, the flight data recorder, sat near the tail and
silently tracked over 250 different characteristics, up front, in
the smoke-filled cockpit, the two pilots were striving to find
their problem and simultaneously prepare for an unexpected approach
to an unfamiliar airport. A transcript released on Tuesday shows at
least a touch of frantic confusion slipping in. At one point, the
pilots broadcast a conversation between the two of them, in German,
to a puzzled air traffic controller on the ground; and, at another
point, both decided to talk to the controller at once.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are still hoping to recover the other black box,
the cockpit voice recorder, but rough weather kept divers out of
the water on Tuesday. But with enough analysis, said the chief
investigator, Vic Gerden, of Canada's Transportation Safety Board,
the details from the box that Canadian navy divers brought up on
Sunday may reveal where the plane's problem began, even if the box
quit six minutes before the plane crashed five miles off the coast
near here. But Gerden said that investigators in his
data-processing laboratory in Ottawa were working backwards from
the end of the data and had not yet determined where, on the
25-hour record (a period that could cover three previous flights)
the problems began.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Tuesday, Gerden confirmed that fire-damaged parts that
were collected along the shoreline here are from the airplane; in
fact, they are ``heat-damaged'' parts from the cockpit, he said.
</P>
<P>
   While a transcript released by the board of the last 27 minutes
of communication between the Geneva-bound jet and air traffic
controllers shows some confusion on both sides of the conversation,
it was not immediately evident if the errors made any difference to
the outcome of the flight. All 229 people on the plane were killed.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The portion of the air traffic control communications released
on Tuesday begins with the plane, about half an hour out of Kennedy
International Airport in New York, using standard language to
introduce itself to a controller at a high-altitude control center
in Moncton, New Brunswick, as ``Swissair one-eleven heavy.'' Heavy
means any plane over 300,000 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   The plane reports in at 58 minutes after midnight, Greenwich
mean time, or just before 10 p.m. here, and just before 9 p.m. in
New York. All proceeds normally until a pilot says the flight is
``declaring Pan Pan Pan,'' the call sign for an urgent problem, 16
minutes later. The pilot _ no one knows yet if it was the captain
or the first officer _ says he wants to go to ``a convenient place,
I guess Boston.'' Controllers limit each altitude to planes going
in a single direction, and the controller clears the Swissair
flight to descend from 33,000 feet to 31,000, an altitude
appropriate for traffic headed to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty seconds after Swissair's initial call, the controller,
with a much better idea of the MD-11's location, says, ``uh, would
you prefer to go into Halifax,'' which is about as close to an
order as an air traffic controller gives a plane in trouble; thirty
seconds later, Swissair accepts the suggestion. ``Speedbird,'' a
call sign for a supersonic Concorde, is listening in, and the
British Air crew supplies Swissair with weather conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Amid what is undoubtedly a very heavy workload in the cockpit,
the Swissair pilot has to ask twice for the wind direction and the
radio frequency for the instrument landing system at Halifax.
</P>
<P>
   An open question for investigators _ and armchair accident
analysts _ is whether the plane could have begun dumping fuel
earlier, to get the plane's weight down to the manufacturer's
recommended maximum for landing, or should have bothered dumping at
all, if it delayed a landing. In Canada, Gerden said on Tuesday
evening, planes may dump fuel if they are above 2,000 feet above
ground level, and the plane need not have circled the water to do
this.
</P>
<P>
   When the pilot asks, at 1:21:30, ``we, uh, must dump some fuel.
May we do that in this area during descent?'' the controller does
not immediately answer, but asks if the plane can turn left or
right for a previously-discussed circle to lose altitude. The pilot
says, ``we are able for a left or right turn towards the south to
dump,'' a course that will take them out to sea. The controller
tells them they will be over the coast in 10 miles, and that they
should advise him when they are ready to dump. The pilot does not
say he is beginning dumping until 1:24:56, almost three minutes
later, at which time the controller tells him, `just a couple of
miles I'll be right with you,'' and thirty seconds after that, the
controller tells the crew to begin dumping.
</P>
<P>
   Another telling moment is when (at 1:22:36) a pilot has
evidently keyed the microphone for transmission to the ground while
discussing with the other pilot, in German, whether they are
performing the emergency checklist for smoke, a confusion
equivalent to trying to carry on two telephone conversations
simultaneously and putting the wrong one on hold.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
