<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0329 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4507 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SCHOOL-ART-57     09-08 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCHOOL-ART-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEERS AND JEERS GREET CLINTON IN SUBURBS
</HEADLINE>
   (See also CLINTON-CONGRESS, CLINTON-STARR) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SILVER SPRING, Md. _ Standing on her sun-dappled lawn, Celia
Winter politely dismissed President Clinton as ``a farce'' as his
motorcade arrived from the White House on a mission of preaching
education in this bastion of suburban values.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just disgusted with him,'' Mrs. Winter said. ``This is a
man who campaigned with his family, with Hillary, on the theme of
family values. And now it's all shot to hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Winter spoke more in sadness than anger, but her neighbor
down the block, Maureen Callahan, took the more demonstrative step
of tacking a hand-lettered, black-and-white announcement on her
neat picket fence: ``Embarrassed. Disheartened. Disgusted by Our
President.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He shouldn't be here with young children,'' Mrs. Callahan, who
has a young child, said as she stared disapprovingly toward
Pinecrest Elementary school, where students were assembled to cheer
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thrilled Mr. Glendening chose not to come,'' she said of
Maryland Gov. Parris Glendening, a Democrat seeking re-election who
shunned the event in protest of Clinton's behavior in the Lewinsky
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats rallied to the president's side, but with never
a word of the Lewinsky inquiry nor of a possible impeachment
inquiry in two hours of speechifying about education five miles to
the south inside the Washington Beltway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very pleased to have the president here to talk about one
of the real issues,'' said Rep. Albert Wynn, D-Md., who led the
applause for Clinton. In an interview, the congressman insisted
that it was ``time to move on'' from the Lewinsky scandal. ``In my
district, folks are not interested in hype, they are not interested
in scandal.''
</P>
<P>
   The president, energetically working the scene of cheering
students as if it were a stop in some vital new political campaign,
beamed before his invited audience of 120 teachers, parents and
other advocates for improvements in education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes when things are going really, really well for
people, they get a little self-indulgent and basically just want to
kick back and relax,'' Clinton declared in warning against the
neglect of education needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congressman Wynn committed the truth up here when he said that
the first time we talked, he was hitting on me for more federal
funds for education,'' Clinton added.
</P>
<P>
   The event amounted to a respite from the investigatory travail
of Washington. But for every bit of encouragement _ ``We love
you!'' shouted one supporter as the president stepped up to speak _
there was a disapproving word or a blunt sign being offered by
surrounding residents. ``Liar! Liar!'' one homeowner announced to
the motorcade in a sign propped up by a statue of St. Anthony.
</P>
<P>
   A half-dozen pro-impeachment pickets who have been dogging the
president in Washington journeyed here to hold up a sign
proclaiming, ``Mr. President, stay away from our daughters.'' But
other outsiders came to express support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of his critics come across as puritanical,'' said Susan
Rohrer of Beltsville, watching the motorcade route with her two
daughters, ages 3 and 5. ``What they're doing is negating all the
good he's done.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the school, Maureen Hanley, a local resident, said
flatly: ``He's here because of spin control. He's got to win the
public back again. Forgive me, but I think he's a liar, and you can
watch it in his facial expressions, trying to get this to blow
over. But it's not blowing over.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Inside the school, the president received repeated rounds of
applause as he spoke up for higher spending on school construction
and teacher training and warned children about hollow promises.
</P>
<P>
   ``The child will turn on the television and hear every
politician like me saying children are the most important things to
our future, education is the most important issue,'' Clinton said.
``The actions that the child sees walking up the steps to school
every day are louder than all the words to the contrary of the
politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Winter, watching as the presidential caravan glided through
this sylvan tableau of family value politicking, contended that the
president was violating his own action-over-words caution. ``He's
just here in a continuation of his latest marketing scheme,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the president was obviously cheered by the meticulously
planned journey beyond the Beltway, spending extra time to meet the
children assembled at his departure. In his speech, he related
their needs to a wide variety of pending issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Senate is going to get another chance to do the right
thing on campaign finance reform,'' he said. ``I wish they would.
I'd like to see all my successors be able to spend less time
raising money and more time helping you raise your kids.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
