<SLUG> BC-DROUGHT-TEXAS-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN TEXAS'S HEARTLAND, NOT ALL WILL SURVIVE RELENTLESS DROUGHT OF
'98
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WORTH WREN JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Old farm joke: What happens when you bet the
farm and lose?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: You just make another enemy.
</P>
<P>
   Otto Wagner Jr., 43, who farms 3,600 acres in the Lower Rio
Grande Valley, retells the joke. But, frankly, there's little
laughter in his region, or in other parts of Texas, where the
Drought of '98 lingers.
</P>
<P>
   The drought came as the great leveler this year. Many farmers
are on the brink of failure, agricultural economists warn. And
August's rains in some parts of the state came too late to do much
good for this year's crops.
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Worth Star-Telegram recently visited farmers in three
regions _ Ellis County south of Dallas, Gaines and Dawson counties
in Northwest Texas, and the Lower Rio Grande Valley _ for a closer
look at the drought's impact.
</P>
<P>
   Some said they were considering leaving the business. Others
vowed to survive on the farm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it even in the worst times,'' said B.J. Simpson, 73,
who grew up in the 1930s Dust Bowl days in northwest Texas and now
farms in the Rio Grande Valley. ``I love it at the worst. I always
will. It's a way of life. And it's a good life, even though it's
tough.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Ellis County, North Central Texas
</P>
<P>
   WAXAHACHIE _ Across Ellis County, only the best farmers have
survived until now _ primarily 125 full-time operators earning
livelihoods from crops and livestock.
</P>
<P>
   That's how Gary Stanford, Ellis County agent for the Texas
Agricultural Extension Service, sees it. Now, he says, their debt
loads are rising beyond their control and their banks' tight
standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of this elite population, we're probably going to lose a
third of them out of agriculture,'' Stanford predicted recently.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Wilson, 49, is one farmer who is wondering whether he can be
back in the business next year _ or whether he wants to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen cotton die from no water,'' he remarked
recently. ``This year, some of it did.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, who grew up on a farm near Waxahachie that's been in his
family for more than 100 years, returned to the farm in 1976 after
college, military service and eight years with Texas Instruments in
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   He was just in time for the 1978 drought and interest rates
topping 15 percent on operating loans. Then came 1980's dry heat
wave, slashing his cotton yield by 25 percent, but he survived the
1982-86 farm recession.
</P>
<P>
   By the late 1980s, he was enjoying mostly good times before a
1991 flood and persistent rain delayed his harvest for months,
inflicting severe crop losses. After some federal aid and a
rebound, the 1996 drought brought more losses.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Wilson's 744 acres of corn produced 12 to 34 bushels
an acre, down from annual averages of 75 to 80 bushels in decent
weather. His 610 acres of cotton might yield half of the farm's
400-pound average.
</P>
<P>
   The only bright spot was the 120 acres of winter wheat. Its high
yields came in ahead of the drought. They baled much of it for hay,
a wise move because half of the state's hay crop has been
devastated this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we're in hock,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley and Ann Praslicka, farmers near Waxahachie since 1955,
are another farm family that has weathered the drought. Through the
years, the couple, who reared five children, have minimized their
risk by farming a small acreage they own for cotton, corn and
grain.
</P>
<P>
   They farm 200 dryland acres, and they say their venture will
survive despite a loss of nearly $30,000. They were helped by
insurance payments on a 100 percent corn loss, said Stanley
Praslicka, 70.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll make it,'' he said. ``It'll be hard,'' noting that late
rains could further damage his cotton with stains that hurt fiber
quality before harvest.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1960s, the Praslickas rented an additional 100 acres
for three years. Ann Praslicka said they could see no added rewards
from the 300-acre venture, while adding more costs, risks, worries
and labor. So they fell back to their 200 acres.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could do all the labor ourselves,'' Stanley Praslicka said,
adding that the farm has provided them with a modest living while
allowing them to set aside college funds for their children.
</P>
<P>
   The family's cotton yields this year, at maybe 200 to 240 pounds
an acre, are among the county's best, despite being down from about
600 pounds an acre in decent weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we just hadn't done anything this year and kept our money
in the bank, we'd be better off,'' Ann Praslicka said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Gaines and Dawson counties, Northwest Texas
</P>
<P>
   SEMINOLE and DENVER CITY _ Here among the bumper crop of
oilfield pumpjacks, Anderson Upton has been in a tight water race.
</P>
<P>
   He's trying to grow profitable yields of cotton, peanuts and
grain sorghum, but has been losing to rainless, windy days and
temperatures of between 100 and 108 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   One recent day, Upton jockeyed his pickup from well to well _ 26
in all _ to keep the water pressure high enough to supply 14
irrigation systems serving about 1,600 leased and owned acres.
Peanuts get top priority for water because they have the potential
to produce the best revenue and profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're running out of water,'' said Upton, 37, who must
constantly watch his irrigation systems to ensure they're not
pumping air, leaking or breaking down.
</P>
<P>
   Like others across his region, he has been working virtually
nonstop, logging 14-hour workdays and longer since early May. The
irrigation, though, has been around-the-clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm committed to get the best I can; otherwise, I lose more,''
Upton said. He abandoned watering two 120-acre fields of sorghum
about 45 days ago to have more water for his peanuts and cotton.
Now the sorghum looks like a loss. He also cut his watering time on
some cotton to boost the water flow to peanuts.
</P>
<P>
   Upton estimates cotton and peanut yields are declining by 20
percent to 50 percent in some spots. Yet the farmwide averages are
likely to be too high to draw on his crop insurance coverage.
</P>
<P>
   In July, his irrigation electricity and gas costs alone tripled
to about $18,000 for the month, from $6,000 a month the previous
year. Unfortunately, he doesn't share royalties from any of the oil
and gas pumpers to offset his rising costs.
</P>
<P>
   While his banker was telling him to curb expenses, he delayed
laying off one of his two hired workers for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not to blame for this weather, and they've got
families to feed, too,'' Upton said.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, he's projecting his seven-year-old farming operation
will lose about $60,000 this year, meaning he'll carry operating
debt into next year. He'll probably have to tie up his 40 percent
equity in a 320-acre tract to get refinancing to operate next year
</P>
<P>
   For now, he mostly keeps his worries to himself, said Anderson's
wife, Tamara Upton, a Seminole schoolteacher. They have 2- and
8-year-old sons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe once or twice a month is the only time we sit down at
the table together for a meal,'' she said, citing his long
workdays.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Lower Rio Grande Valley
</P>
<P>
   WESLACO, RIO HONDO and McALLEN _ Lower Rio Grande Valley farmers
were staring into a water-shortage nightmare going into August.
</P>
<P>
   They feared their 27 water districts _ seven of which were
already denying water to farmers and reserving it for the urban
centers' needs _ would be forced to shut off irrigation water for
months or years. The Rio Grande is their tap.
</P>
<P>
   With the drought, Mexican competition, urban sprawl and other
contributing factors, acreage planted in vegetables across the
four-county valley plunged about 50 percent during the past five
years.
</P>
<P>
   Between 25 percent and 30 percent of the acreage in grapefruit
and orange groves and sugar cane went without irrigation from four
to 10 weeks this summer, when the crops needed water the most. Some
cotton and grain also didn't get enough irrigation.
</P>
<P>
   Rio Grande water-rights holders not using their supplies found a
seller's market. Water, which sold for $10 to $15 per acre foot in
the early '90s, reached a peak of $75 to more than $100 per acre
foot.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, while missing the Lower Valley, Tropical Storm Charley
struck at points up the Rio Grande. Its runoff rushed into the
river's Amistad and Falcon reservoirs, which supply down-river
irrigation and urban water needs in the Lower Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Valley is not dead,'' said Darrell Duda, general manager
of Duda Texas and its Duda Valley Onions division, a McAllen-based
fresh produce company.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing the drought already looming over the Rio Grande watershed
three years ago, Duda Texas cut its planted vegetable acreage by
about 50 percent. Instead of 3,000 irrigated acres of vegetables,
sugar cane and grain crops, Duda Texas cut back to 1,500 irrigated
acres of vegetables and sugar cane _ plus dryland grain on parts of
the other 1,500 acres.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gotta manage that risk factor,'' said Duda, 36, a
fourth-generation family management-team member for A. Duda &AMP; Sons,
the Oviedo, Fla.-based parent.
</P>
<P>
   Across the Lower Valley, meanwhile, farm debts are running high
due to a string of disasters that have hit cotton, corn, sorghum,
vegetable, citrus and sugar cane growers since 1989, said Jason
Johnson, the Lower Valley's extension economist in Weslaco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now even the big farms are losing money,'' Johnson said,
predicting a further consolidation into fewer and larger farms. He
expects a significant reduction of land being farmed.
</P>
<P>
   Otto Wagner Jr., who farms northwest of McAllen, figures his
out-of-pocket cash losses on his drought-wrecked corn crop this
year, after insurance, will exceed $40,000. And that conservative
forecast may just be wishful thinking, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may consider us, especially dryland farmers, to be taking
a big risk, and it's a big gamble,'' he said. ``Yes it is, but what
is not a gamble in our life? ... It just takes timely rains.''
</P>
<P>
   Billie Mack Simpson, a farmer in Rio Hondo in the eastern Lower
Valley, figures cotton and grain losses at about $300,000 this year
on the 4,600 leased and 400 owned acres that he farms with his dad,
B.J. Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   That's not the final tab, which could be lowered significantly
by beef cattle sales this fall and the final crop insurance
proceeds. The family also ranches about 1,200 cows on nearly 45,000
leased and about 100 owned acres.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything we do depends on Mother Nature, the Good Lord up
there,'' said Billie Mack Simpson, 44, whose sugar cane is dying on
630 acres denied irrigation water since late June. ``I'm in limbo
every day of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
