</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWISSAIR-CRASH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PILOT COULD HAVE DUMPED FUEL OVER LAND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Nova Scotia -- The pilot of Swissair 111 chose not to
dump fuel over land in Nova Scotia, permitted under Canadian
regulations, but instead made a 180-degree turn to head back to sea
in the precious final moments of the doomed flight.
</P>
<P>
   Expanded excerpts of communication between the pilots and
air-traffic controllers showed Tuesday that the Swissair crew was
considering a fuel dump over land on its emergency approach to
Halifax International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   The crew, however, chose to reverse course only 25 miles from
the airport, in an effort to lighten their load. The aircraft never
returned, crashing violently into the Atlantic with the loss of 229
lives.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to head back to sea was made more than 7 minutes
after the crew first alerted air-traffic controllers that they had
smoke in the cockpit, and less than 3 minutes before electrical
problems forced the crew to fly the plane manually.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian flight regulations allow fuel to be dumped at altitudes
above 2,000 feet. The MD-11 aircraft was higher than 10,000 feet
when it turned back toward the Atlantic with 229 people aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Vic Gerden, chief investigator of the crash, declined Tuesday to
speculate why the pilot did not choose to dump his fuel over land
on its approach to the Halifax airport. But Joachim Maitre, a
Boston University professor of journalism and international
relations who trained as an East German military pilot, assailed
the pilot's judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can fly an aircraft from 33,000 feet to the runway in a
very quick time,'' said Maitre, who has written extensively on
defense technology.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Maitre said, the pilot may not have realized that the
aircraft was equipped with Kapton, an electrical insulator that had
been banned by the US Air Force after a series of F-16 crashes and
later by the US Navy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The material has the quality of magnesium,'' Maitre said. ``It
burns quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Kapton had been stripped from the US military aircraft
because of reported burning when subjected to chafing and friction.
Officials for Boeing, which bought MD-11 manufacturer
McDonnell-Douglas last year, confirmed this week that the aircraft
was equipped with the material.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot, Maitre said, apparently misinterpreted the cause of
the cockpit smoke, which forced the crew to don oxygen masks. ``His
mind was focused on something non-lethal,'' Maitre said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I knew as a pilot that I had this material, I would not
have wasted time attempting to dump fuel,'' Maitre said.
</P>
<P>
   Aviation officials in the United States and Canada, however,
have said that landing at 30 tons over the maximum weight -- which
Swissair 111 carried -- could have caused the aircraft to barrel
off the runway or erupt in fire from a hard impact.
</P>
<P>
   However, flames may have begun to plague the plane during
flight. Gerden said Tuesday that retrieved pieces of cockpit
wreckage show signs of ``heat stress.''
</P>
<P>
   The presence of smoky conditions, at least, are reinforced by
the expanded excerpts released Tuesday. In them, one crew member
asks the other if he is proceeding through the ``emergency
checklist for air-conditioning smoke.''
</P>
<P>
   The question, overheard because the pilots had not disconnected
their radio link with controllers, was one stage of
trouble-shooting to pinpoint the problem, said Jim Harris of the
Canadian Transportation Safety Board. The question does not mean
that the air-conditioning system was smoking, Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the revelation of ``heat stress'' in the cockpit,
Gerden said that the flight-data recorder has shown ``anomalies''
in the aircraft's operating systems. He declined to specify what
systems were affected.
</P>
<P>
   Harris said it was unknown if the problems occurred late in the
flight or even extended back to engine startup for the scheduled
New York-to-Geneva trip.
</P>
<P>
   Gerden said he believes that information retrieved from the
flight-data recorder, which lost power during the flight's final 6
minutes, will be more helpful in determining the cause of the crash
than what occurred in the last stages.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of power to the flight-data recorder also ``does not
necessarily indicate that the aircraft had total electrical
failure,'' Gerden said. The plane had three sources of electricity,
he added.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are hopeful that the cockpit voice recorder, which
may be retrieved today, continued to tape the pilots during the
final six minutes when ground controllers lost radio contact.
</P>
<P>
   Besides that recorder, military divers are expected to retrieve
more bodies from the ocean Wednesday. Rough weather Tuesday
restricted diving to relatively shallow waters closer to shore.
</P>
<P>
   US military assistance has begun to arrive. Newly developed
underwater sensors, which can provide detailed maps of the bottom,
have been loaned for the operation.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the salvage ship USS Grapple is expected in Halifax
today, where it will refuel and put to sea Friday for use off
Peggy's Cove. The ship, used in the investigation of the TWA Flight
800 crash two years ago, can lift 300-ton objects.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 33 US military divers -- whose experience includes
the TWA crash, the explosion of the space shuttle Challenger, and a
Haitian ferry sinking -- will help provide relief for the 75
Canadian divers who have labored on the scene since Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
