<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4518 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-ART-490&AMP;ADD-NY     09-08 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-ART-490&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW SURGES 380.53, BIGGEST POINT GAIN EVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also GREENSPAN-MARKETPLACE) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices continued their wild ride Tuesday, but
the vertiginous swings left investors cheering, as the Dow Jones
industrial average vaulted 380.53 points, or just under 5 percent.
Broader market averages also recorded hefty gains, partly reversing
their recent steep declines.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to explain the big jump in equity prices, market
analysts and traders said that comments last Friday by Alan
Greenspan, chairman of the Federal Reserve Board, gave investors
hope that a coordinated response might be forthcoming from the Fed
and other central banks to crises in Asian and Russian markets.
</P>
<P>
   They said investors were encouraged by Monday's vigorous rally
in foreign stock markets, an advance that continued Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow's rise in percentage terms was the biggest percentage
gain since the crash of 1987 but well below the record 15.34
percent rise of March 15, 1933, when the average climbed 8.26
points, to 62.10.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 21, 1987, it gained 10.15 percent, or 186.84 points, to
2,027.85
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's surge was the biggest point gain ever. Still, the
close, at 8,020.78, was 14 percent below the record of 9,337.97 set
July 17.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts' said the fact that most stocks were trading at deep
discounts to their 52-week highs _ 44 percent on average _ was
another factor in Tuesday's climb.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we were oversold,'' said Charles Clough, chief
investment strategist at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. ``And I don't think it
takes much of a change in psychology to spark something of a
rally.''
</P>
<P>
   In a speech delivered at the University of California at
Berkeley last Friday, Greenspan suggested the Fed was less
concerned than previously about an inflationary threat, and might
be prepared to lower interest rates if sagging overseas economies
threatened domestic economic growth. Later, a dinner meeting the
Fed chairman attended with U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin and
Japanese Finance Minister Keichi Miyazawa led to speculation that,
after months of jawboning by U.S. officials, Japan might be about
to implement policies to reform its banking systems and to reflate
its economy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Clough and others said they did not view the mere
prospect of action by the United States and other industrialized
nations, most importantly Japan, as sufficient to send stock prices
soaring again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't over yet,'' said Byron Wien, U.S. investment
strategist at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, referring to the market's
recent unsettled state.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't the start of another bull leg,'' he continued.
``First of all, none of the structural problems that caused people
to rethink things last month have been overcome. The typical action
in a down market is for stocks to get deeply oversold, to rally,
and then to retest the lows.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, few analysts expected gains as broad or as sharp as were
made Tuesday. Four stocks rose for every one that fell on the New
York Stock Exchange on Tuesday. In addition to the Dow, the broader
market averages also soared.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index jumped 49.57 points, or just
over 5 percent, to 1,023.46. The Nasdaq composite index registered
its biggest point gain ever, soaring 94.34 points, or more than 6
percent, to 1,660.86; that was its second largest in percentage
terms, behind the 7.34 percent advance recorded on Oct. 21, 1987.
And the Russell 2000 index, made up of mostly small and
medium-sized stocks, increased by 14.86 points, or 4.28 percent, to
361.93.
</P>
<P>
   Big institutions like pension funds, which typically trade in
big blocks of 10,000 or more shares, did a preponderantly large
amount of the buying Tuesday, in contrast to their recent tendency
to be heavy net sellers of stock.
</P>
<P>
   Near the close of trading, just under $700 million worth of
stock was purchased in lots of less than 10,000 shares, according
to Laszlo Birinyi, whose firm, Birinyi &AMP; Associates, tracks market
developments. Individual or retail traders seldom buy or sell as
many as 10,000 shares at a time. By comparison, more than $2.2
billion worth of stock was bought big blocks, Birinyi said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big difference today is that the professionals were coming
back,'' into stocks, he said.
</P>
<P>
   For a second day buying was heavy on a number of foreign
markets, especially in Asi. In Japan, the Nikkei 225 index was up
just under 1 percent, after surging 5 percent Monday. Hong Kong's
Hang Seng index rose 1.4 percent, following Monday's 7.1 percent
surge. In Europe, Germany's DAX index rose 3.7 percent, and the
Paris CAC-40 rose 2.9 percent. But London's FT-SE 100 slipped 0.1
percent after strong gains Monday.
</P>
<P>
   On the Big Board, all 30 Dow industrial stocks rose.
</P>
<P>
   American Express, which along with most other financial stocks
has been battered recently, climbed $6.38 a share, to $80. General
Electric gained $6.25, to 81.88, after its engine unit said it
expected sales this year to rise 42 percent, to $10 billion. And
McDonald's shares jumped $6.31, to $64.44.
</P>
<P>
   The day's gain in the Dow surpassed the record 337-point advance
set last Oct. 28. Volume on the Big Board was the tenth-heaviest
ever, at 810.6 million shares. Nine of the exchange's 10 busiest
days have come in the last month, and four of those have happened
since the beginning of September.
</P>
<P>
   ``The volatility in the market shows nervousness and anxiety on
the part of institutional investors,'' said Thomas Galvin, chief
investment officer at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, ``while time
and again individual investors have shown more restraint and more
of a longer-term horizon than many professionals give them credit
for.''
</P>
<P>
   Clough, the Merrill Lynch strategist, said Americans had not
significantly changed the amount of money they were putting into
401-k retirement plans and equity mutual funds. ``What has changed
are foreign inflows,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   In the second and third quarter of last year, he said,
foreigners were putting $100 billion into American equities at an
annual rate, about four times as high as previously. In the first
quarter of 1998, that number accelerated to $125 billion, he said.
``These are massive, manic liquidity flows,'' he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
