u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-NORTHWEST-STR     09-08 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-NORTHWEST-STRIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SENDS TOP AIDE TO ASSESS NORTHWEST STRIKE DEADLOCK  
(HLW)
</HEADLINE>
   By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ President Clinton dispatched one of his closest aides
to Minneapolis on Tuesday to try to break the deadlock between
Northwest Airlines and its striking pilots, which has grounded the
carrier for 11 days and disrupted travel in the much of the Midwest
and South.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Lindsey, the deputy White House counsel and one of
Clinton's most trusted lieutenants, flew aboard a government jet to
Minneapolis, where a federal mediator is meeting with the two
sides. He was joined by Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater.
</P>
<P>
   The two men did not arrive until late in the day, and it was
unclear precisely what role they would play. A White House
spokesman, Barry Toiv, would say only that the two men planned to
``assess the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The involvement of Lindsey reflects the increasing political
pressure on Clinton since the pilots walked out on Aug. 29.
Republicans and officials in states hurt by the strike have been
urging the president to use his executive powers to order the
pilots back to work, as he did last year in the case of American
Airlines. But leading Democrats and labor leaders have called just
as loudly for him not to intervene.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has said that Clinton has not ruled out
intervening but that he would prefer to see a negotiated
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   After taking a break for Labor Day, the mediator resumed
meetings with representatives of the union and the airline on
Tuesday in an effort to restart negotiations. Similar discussions
in Chicago over the weekend accomplished little, participants said.
The two sides have not returned to the bargaining table since the
strike began.
</P>
<P>
   The strike is now the longest against an airline since
machinists walked out at Eastern Airlines in 1989. The pilots are
asking for greater job security and a 15 percent raise over three
years. The company has offered them a 9 percent raise over four
years. The average pilot earns $120,000 a year, according to the
union; the company says the average is $133,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Compromise is difficult for both sides because the pilots, who
agreed to wage concessions in 1993 to help save the airline from
bankruptcy, resent that Northwest has resisted their demands after
posting four years of record profits. The company says it cannot
sweeten its offer to the pilots because it is also negotiating
contracts with other unions representing workers who took salary
cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The union and many Wall Street analysts say that Northwest's
strategy is to hold out until the president is forced to intervene.
Clinton has the power to order the pilots back to work for 60 days
while an emergency board tries to find a resolution acceptable to
both sides. Northwest has said that it is not advocating
presidential intervention, though it has promoted the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsey, who has served as an aide to Clinton since his early
days in politics, has more clout than anyone previously involved in
the dispute to press both sides to compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is somebody who I think both sides can talk to and know
that they are talking to a direct emissary of the president,'' Toiv
said.
</P>
<P>
   But by becoming more directly involved, he can also better
advise the president as to whether he needs to intervene.
</P>
<P>
   Slater has already exerted some pressure on Northwest by
ordering two commuter affiliates who halted operations during the
strike to resume flights to 17 communities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
