<HEADER>
A4526 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-GOP-COX     09-08 0467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GOP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Republican warns against focus on Clinton
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans could undermine their chances for large
gains in the November elections if they focus on President
Clinton's problems, Rep. John Linder (R-Ga.) warned Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Turning the campaign into a national referendum on Clinton
needlessly risks creating the perception that Republicans are
piling on, said Linder, chairman of House Republicans' campaign
committee, in a conference call with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the character issue could pop up in the final days
of the fall campaign in Republican ads urging voters to continue
GOP leadership of the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be surprised if we close with some kind of
commercial that said, `Who's going to keep an eye on him if we have
a Democratic Congress?''' Linder said in a later interview.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Republican said opinion polls that show an erosion
of trust in Clinton also indicate that voters see a GOP Congress as
a bulwark against the president.
</P>
<P>
   A new bipartisan poll released Tuesday shows that Clinton's
admittedly inappropriate relationship with Monica Lewinsky is
threatening to cut into Democrats' usual advantage among women and
senior citizens and could dim voter turnout.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Martin Frost of Texas, chairman of the Democratic
Congressional Campaign Committee, said in a statement that
Democratic candidates continue to do well in district-by-district
polling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always anticipated that 1998 would be a low-turnout
year,'' Frost said.
</P>
<P>
   But Linder said the Battleground Poll shows that Democrats
``have a serious problem.''
</P>
<P>
   While Linder held fast to his prediction of a Republican gain of
12 to 15 seats in the House, he said Republicans are in a position
to ``catch an October wave, if there is one,'' and possibly gain
more than 30 seats.
</P>
<P>
   The wave would be the release of damaging details from
independent counsel Kenneth Starr's widely anticipated report to
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Linder said he doubted that hearings on the report could take
place before the elections.
</P>
<P>
   He briefed reporters on the launch of a second round of issue
advertising that Republicans are running in key congressional
districts. So far, the GOP has run ads in Las Vegas and
southwestern Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In both districts, well-financed Democrats are trying to win
seats that are held by Republicans who are running for the U.S.
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Shelley Berkley, a University of Nevada regent and former
lobbyist, is the Democratic candidate in Nevada's 1st Congressional
District. Brian Baird is trying to avenge his 1996 defeat in
Washington's 3rd Congressional District.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
