<HEADER>
A4529 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWISSAIR-DELTA-COX     09-08 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWISSAIR-DELTA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta execs to attend funeral for victims of Swissair crash
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The top executive at Delta Air Lines, which booked 53
of the passengers on Swissair Flight 111 and had a flight attendant
aboard the plane, will attend memorial services for the victims
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Leo Mullin, president and chief executive of Atlanta-based
Delta, will travel to Halifax, Nova Scotia, for a service this
evening and then to New York for another memorial Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Mullin's presence reflects Delta's quiet but considerable
involvement in the aftermath of the Sept. 2 crash.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the crash, Delta employees notified most of
the relatives of the 131 American passengers _ not just those it
had booked. The toll-free information number published by Swissair
actually was answered by Delta employees in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was logical for us to do that because Swissair is not
heavily staffed in the U.S., and we had more people ready to
respond quickly,'' Delta spokesman Bill Berry said.
</P>
<P>
   Delta also assigned specially trained employees to the families
of American victims. The employees help with travel arrangements,
coordinate with other relatives, answer questions and try to
provide solace. The relationship can last for months.
</P>
<P>
   Delta has a team in Halifax to provide family support services
and assist Swissair officials and investigators. Delta is keenly
interested in what caused the Swissair MD-11 to crash because it
also flies the three-engine jet.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, investigators said there are signs of heating on some
small pieces of wreckage from the cockpit area, which could help
them determine the source of smoke reported by pilots before the
jet plunged into the ocean near Halifax. They declined to speculate
on the cause of the damage.
</P>
<P>
   Bad weather halted attempts to salvage the plane's cockpit voice
recorder, still on the sea bottom. Work is expected to resume
today. The MD-11's flight data recorder has been recovered but
contains no data from the last six minutes of flight, fueling
speculation about an electrical failure.
</P>
<P>
   Delta and Swissair are longtime marketing partners and routinely
book passengers on each others' trans-Atlantic flights. Walter
Vollenweider, Swissair's vice president for North America, said the
marketing pact outlines post-accident cooperation. But he added,
``What Delta has done goes far beyond what was spelled out, no
questions asked.''
</P>
<P>
   Berry said that, had the airlines' roles been reversed, Delta
would have sought similar assistance from Swissair.
</P>
<P>
   The New York-Geneva flight that crashed was among the most
popular of the two airlines' jointly booked flights. Patricia
Eberhart, a New York-based Delta flight attendant, was working
Flight 111 under a cross-utilization program. Eberhart, 51, was a
30-year veteran who previously worked for Pan Am.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Swissair has been lauded for the attention paid to
the needs of grieving families. It's provided charter flights,
chauffeured minivans and police protection to ensure privacy. The
airline has offered families a $20,000 payment for immediate needs,
and its executives have been visible.
</P>
<P>
   That response is in contrast to TWA's seemingly aloof stance
after the Flight 800 disaster in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Down the road, Delta's involvement could include defending
itself against legal claims. Berry said Swissair has primary
liability, but lawyers say that probably won't shield Delta.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they acted as an agent and referred people to a defective
aircraft they will be open to claims,'' predicted Atlanta liability
lawyer Guerry Thornton.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
