<HEADER>
A4530 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VENTURECAPITAL-Q&AMP;A-CO     09-08 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENTURECAPITAL-Q&AMP;A-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q and A with Charles Mosely, Jr.
 &HT;    By Michael Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Charles Moseley Jr. is general partner in Noro-Moseley
Partners, metro Atlanta's largest venture capital company.
Noro-Moseley earlier this year put together its fourth venture
capital fund. That money will be invested in a number of small
high-tech companies in exchange for partial ownership. Should the
companies prosper, Noro-Moseley investors will also gain as their
investments reap large returns when the company's interests are
sold. Of course, companies can fail, too. Moseley spoke with the
Atlanta Journal-Constitution about the pearls and perils of venture
capital.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How has Atlanta's technology sector changed?
</P>
<P>
   A: We have been in business for 15 years. The activity we see
today vs. that of 15 years ago is just substantially different. The
long-anticipated Silicon Valley of the South that the Chamber of
Commerce has been promoting for years _ it really is finally here.
Oh, it's not on the scale of California, but compared to the rest
of the country, it is really happening. Two places really stand
out. Research Triangle Park and metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What caused the change?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's not any one thing. Things just take time to develop.
There's Scientific-Atlanta since the 1950s. There have been
national companies that have moved operations here. There is a
growing infrastructure that has produced entrepreneurs who were
young people in those companies. Also, many if not most of the
companies that we see here have some connection to Georgia Tech.
And the stock market boom really helped. The kind of wealth that
has been created as encouragement to people to go try their hand at
it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where are Noro-Moseley's investments?
</P>
<P>
   A: We have seven or eight investments in Research Triangle out
of about 25 during our most recent fund (started earlier this
year). Then there is one in Tennessee, and I think the rest are in
Atlanta. About 85 percent of our investments overall have been in
the Southeast. What's new is our involvement in Research Triangle
Park, but that has not come at the expense of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the difference between now and then?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think the opportunities are much better. There are more of
them and they are better quality. The Internet didn't exist then.
... It's a dramatic development that will change the way people do
business and communicate. There's a lot of medical-related stuff,
much of it coming out of Emory. And in Atlanta we are seeing
better, more experienced management teams.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How many proposals do you get, entrepreneurs asking for
money?
</P>
<P>
   A: On average, we probably get 10 or so a week of what I'd call
serious proposals. That means 500 to 700 in a year. Maybe 100 to
200 are really serious proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Q: After you've studied them and their business plans, looked at
their potential market and made up your minds, how many are going
to end up with your money?
</P>
<P>
   A: We have made seven investments in the past six months. We'll
make 10 to 15 deals in a year. We have done some early stage
investing. But typically, the company we invest in already has some
revenue and they are looking to expand. And we've done some
late-round investing too. The average investment time in a company
is five or six years.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the average size of an investment?
</P>
<P>
   A: Our average size has gone up because our fund has gotten
larger. The average in the future will be close to $3 million a
deal. We generally have been the lead investor, but not the only
investor. The max, at any one time, will probably be 20 to 25
investments, and we have six people. We spend a lot of time with
the companies. But we are not in the business of managing
companies. We are in the business of managing investments. What we
try to do is make sure we have the best team possible in those
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How much of a gamble is it? How often do things turn out the
way you expect and you make a great return?
</P>
<P>
   A: Most of the time, things take longer than you expected.
Things probably take more money than you expected to spend, too.
Twenty percent of our investments turn out to be losers, and 80
percent range from mediocre to very good. It's not as risky as you
would think. But most of the time it's not great or nothing _ there
is a lot in-between. ... Our effort is to maximize the return of
our investors.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What do you consider a good return?
</P>
<P>
   A: The fact is we never really know what's going to happen. It
lies in the future. The reality is these entrepreneurs don't know
either.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What you do is really different from how others make money...
</P>
<P>
   A: I think we all get some satisfaction from building things. We
don't make money by cutting things up and closing things down. The
last 10 or 15 years has really been the golden age of
entrepreneurs, and we are part of that. It is about growing things,
and it is hard work. Entrepreneurs have taken the path less
traveled and it's not easy to do.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
