<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERRILL-LYNCH-LOSS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERRILL LYNCH'S OVERSEAS LOSS IS $135 MILLION  
(HLW)
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER TRUELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. said on Tuesday that it lost $135
million in July and August from its business with Russia and other
emerging markets, and is now preparing to cut costs after the
recent turmoil in financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   The losses are expected to reduce the brokerage firm's net
income for July and August to an estimated $102 million, according
to Merrill, which made its announcement after the stock market
closed. In the third quarter ended Sept. 30, 1997, Merrill earned
$493 million.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill has never before made such an interim announcement of
its earnings, David H. Komansky, its chairman and chief executive
said in an interview on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A succession of other big American and European financial
companies, including Citicorp, Bank of America, Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter &AMP; Co. and the Bankers Trust Corp., have announced hundreds
of millions of dollars of losses in the last two weeks after Russia
effectively defaulted on some debt, sending prices tumbling for the
securities of developing nations and causing interest margins to
widen rapidly for less creditworthy borrowers around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden reversal of fortune for financial services companies,
some of the most successful companies of recent years, has been
stunning. ``It's impressive that so many big and smart institutions
were on the wrong side of this trade,'' said John Keefe, president
of Keefe Worldwide, a financial services consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for Merrill have said often in the last couple of
weeks that their company did not report financial results
``intra-quarter,'' implying that it would wait until it announced
its results for the three months ended Sept. 30 before revealing
its losses from Russia and other emerging markets.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill said on Tuesday that it was making an exception to this
policy ``because of the intensive public focus on deteriorating
conditions in the emerging markets, and the fact that most major
international financial institutions have made some form of
disclosure.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrill said that the emerging markets' losses it announced on
Tuesday included the cost of marking down its inventories of
securities to market value, allowances for its own exposure to
third parties with losses in emerging markets, and losses from its
own trading. Merrill said that its cash earnings in July and August
_ excluding the effect of goodwill, most of it from its recent
$5.3-billion acquisition of Mercury Asset Management, the British
money manager _ totaled $138 million.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill's top executives declined to specify what expenses, or
how much, they might seek to cut. ``We're reviewing our
alternatives now,'' said Komansky, Merrill's chairman and chief
executive officer. ``Discretionary spending, what can be
eliminated, what can be deferred. We have a wide range of
alternatives. How quickly to expand. We are in the midst of
evaluating all that.''
</P>
<P>
   Guy Moszkowski, a managing director and brokerage analyst at
Salomon Smith Barney, a subsidiary of the Travelers Group, said:
``They clearly had, as they said, $135 million of emerging markets
fixed income trading losses in the quarter. But it's also clear
from their other remarks that in order to get to only $100 million
or so of profits for July and August there must be substantial
additional losses with other credit-oriented bond products.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a very unusual series of events in the credit
markets,'' Moszkowski added. ``But there will be some questioning
of their credit controls.''
</P>
<P>
   Some other firms, including Salomon Smith Barney and Bankers
Trust have reported worse losses than Merrill. ``It's obviously not
good news, but considering what some others have reported it could
have been worse,'' Raphael Soifer, an analyst at Brown Brothers
Harriman &AMP; Co., said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
