A4535 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWISSAIR-CRASH-BOS &LR;      09-08 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWISSAIR-CRASH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PILOT COULD HAVE DUMPED FUEL OVER LAND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Nova Scotia -- The pilot of Swissair 111 chose not to
dump fuel over land in Nova Scotia, permitted under Canadian
regulations, but instead made a 180-degree turn to head back to sea
in the precious final moments of the doomed flight.
</P>
<P>
   Expanded excerpts of communication between the pilots and
air-traffic controllers showed Tuesday that the Swissair crew was
considering a fuel dump over land on its emergency approach to
Halifax International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   The crew, however, chose to reverse course only 25 miles from
the airport, in an effort to lighten their load. The aircraft never
returned, crashing violently into the Atlantic with the loss of 229
lives.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to head back to sea was made more than 7 minutes
after the crew first alerted air-traffic controllers that they had
smoke in the cockpit, and less than 3 minutes before electrical
problems forced the crew to fly the plane manually.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian flight regulations allow fuel to be dumped at altitudes
above 2,000 feet. The MD-11 aircraft was higher than 10,000 feet
when it turned back toward the Atlantic with 229 people aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Vic Gerden, chief investigator of the crash, declined Tuesday to
speculate why the pilot did not choose to dump his fuel over land
on its approach to the Halifax airport. But Joachim Maitre, a
Boston University professor of journalism and international
relations who trained as an East German military pilot, assailed
the pilot's judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can fly an aircraft from 33,000 feet to the runway in a
very quick time,'' said Maitre, who has written extensively on
defense technology.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Maitre said, the pilot may not have realized that the
aircraft was equipped with Kapton, an electrical insulator that had
been banned by the US Air Force after a series of F-16 crashes and
later by the US Navy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The material has the quality of magnesium,'' Maitre said. ``It
burns quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Kapton had been stripped from the US military aircraft
because of reported burning when subjected to chafing and friction.
Officials for Boeing, which bought MD-11 manufacturer
McDonnell-Douglas last year, confirmed this week that the aircraft
was equipped with the material.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot, Maitre said, apparently misinterpreted the cause of
the cockpit smoke, which forced the crew to don oxygen masks. ``His
mind was focused on something non-lethal,'' Maitre said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I knew as a pilot that I had this material, I would not
have wasted time attempting to dump fuel,'' Maitre said.
</P>
<P>
   Aviation officials in the United States and Canada, however,
have said that landing at 30 tons over the maximum weight -- which
Swissair 111 carried -- could have caused the aircraft to barrel
off the runway or erupt in fire from a hard impact.
</P>
<P>
   However, flames may have begun to plague the plane during
flight. Gerden said Tuesday that retrieved pieces of cockpit
wreckage show signs of ``heat stress.''
</P>
<P>
   The presence of smoky conditions, at least, are reinforced by
the expanded excerpts released Tuesday. In them, one crew member
asks the other if he is proceeding through the ``emergency
checklist for air-conditioning smoke.''
</P>
<P>
   The question, overheard because the pilots had not disconnected
their radio link with controllers, was one stage of
trouble-shooting to pinpoint the problem, said Jim Harris of the
Canadian Transportation Safety Board. The question does not mean
that the air-conditioning system was smoking, Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the revelation of ``heat stress'' in the cockpit,
Gerden said that the flight-data recorder has shown ``anomalies''
in the aircraft's operating systems. He declined to specify what
systems were affected.
</P>
<P>
   Harris said it was unknown if the problems occurred late in the
flight or even extended back to engine startup for the scheduled
New York-to-Geneva trip.
</P>
<P>
   Gerden said he believes that information retrieved from the
flight-data recorder, which lost power during the flight's final 6
minutes, will be more helpful in determining the cause of the crash
than what occurred in the last stages.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of power to the flight-data recorder also ``does not
necessarily indicate that the aircraft had total electrical
failure,'' Gerden said. The plane had three sources of electricity,
he added.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are hopeful that the cockpit voice recorder, which
may be retrieved today, continued to tape the pilots during the
final six minutes when ground controllers lost radio contact.
</P>
<P>
   Besides that recorder, military divers are expected to retrieve
more bodies from the ocean Wednesday. Rough weather Tuesday
restricted diving to relatively shallow waters closer to shore.
</P>
<P>
   US military assistance has begun to arrive. Newly developed
underwater sensors, which can provide detailed maps of the bottom,
have been loaned for the operation.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the salvage ship USS Grapple is expected in Halifax
today, where it will refuel and put to sea Friday for use off
Peggy's Cove. The ship, used in the investigation of the TWA Flight
800 crash two years ago, can lift 300-ton objects.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 33 US military divers -- whose experience includes
the TWA crash, the explosion of the space shuttle Challenger, and a
Haitian ferry sinking -- will help provide relief for the 75
Canadian divers who have labored on the scene since Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 2045EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0344 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4536 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-CRASH-RDP-ART-375&AMP;A     09-08 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CRASH-RDP-ART-375&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLIGHT 111 BLACK BOX RECORDED PLANE'S SYSTEMS BREAKING DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: a 1stLd-Writethru is scheduled to move by 9:30 p.m. ET; also
moved in `a' category) 
(ART ADV: a graphic for use with this story is being sent to NYT
graphics clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(HLW) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Nova Scotia _ Well before Swissair Flight 111 hit the
water last Wednesday night, a computerized black box that tracks
dozens of functions on the big MD-11 recorded system after system
breaking down, the chief investigator said on Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   While the box, the flight data recorder, sat near the tail and
silently tracked over 250 different characteristics, up front, in
the smoke-filled cockpit, the two pilots were striving to find
their problem and simultaneously prepare for an unexpected approach
to an unfamiliar airport. A transcript released on Tuesday shows at
least a touch of frantic confusion slipping in. At one point, the
pilots broadcast a conversation between the two of them, in German,
to a puzzled air traffic controller on the ground; and, at another
point, both decided to talk to the controller at once.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are still hoping to recover the other black box,
the cockpit voice recorder, but rough weather kept divers out of
the water on Tuesday. But with enough analysis, said the chief
investigator, Vic Gerden, of Canada's Transportation Safety Board,
the details from the box that Canadian navy divers brought up on
Sunday may reveal where the plane's problem began, even if the box
quit six minutes before the plane crashed five miles off the coast
near here. But Gerden said that investigators in his
data-processing laboratory in Ottawa were working backwards from
the end of the data and had not yet determined where, on the
25-hour record (a period that could cover three previous flights)
the problems began.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Tuesday, Gerden confirmed that fire-damaged parts that
were collected along the shoreline here are from the airplane; in
fact, they are ``heat-damaged'' parts from the cockpit, he said.
</P>
<P>
   While a transcript released by the board of the last 27 minutes
of communication between the Geneva-bound jet and air traffic
controllers shows some confusion on both sides of the conversation,
it was not immediately evident if the errors made any difference to
the outcome of the flight. All 229 people on the plane were killed.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The portion of the air traffic control communications released
on Tuesday begins with the plane, about half an hour out of Kennedy
International Airport in New York, using standard language to
introduce itself to a controller at a high-altitude control center
in Moncton, New Brunswick, as ``Swissair one-eleven heavy.'' Heavy
means any plane over 300,000 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   The plane reports in at 58 minutes after midnight, Greenwich
mean time, or just before 10 p.m. here, and just before 9 p.m. in
New York. All proceeds normally until a pilot says the flight is
``declaring Pan Pan Pan,'' the call sign for an urgent problem, 16
minutes later. The pilot _ no one knows yet if it was the captain
or the first officer _ says he wants to go to ``a convenient place,
I guess Boston.'' Controllers limit each altitude to planes going
in a single direction, and the controller clears the Swissair
flight to descend from 33,000 feet to 31,000, an altitude
appropriate for traffic headed to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty seconds after Swissair's initial call, the controller,
with a much better idea of the MD-11's location, says, ``uh, would
you prefer to go into Halifax,'' which is about as close to an
order as an air traffic controller gives a plane in trouble; thirty
seconds later, Swissair accepts the suggestion. ``Speedbird,'' a
call sign for a supersonic Concorde, is listening in, and the
British Air crew supplies Swissair with weather conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Amid what is undoubtedly a very heavy workload in the cockpit,
the Swissair pilot has to ask twice for the wind direction and the
radio frequency for the instrument landing system at Halifax.
</P>
<P>
   An open question for investigators _ and armchair accident
analysts _ is whether the plane could have begun dumping fuel
earlier, to get the plane's weight down to the manufacturer's
recommended maximum for landing, or should have bothered dumping at
all, if it delayed a landing. In Canada, Gerden said on Tuesday
evening, planes may dump fuel if they are above 2,000 feet above
ground level, and the plane need not have circled the water to do
this.
</P>
<P>
   When the pilot asks, at 1:21:30, ``we, uh, must dump some fuel.
May we do that in this area during descent?'' the controller does
not immediately answer, but asks if the plane can turn left or
right for a previously-discussed circle to lose altitude. The pilot
says, ``we are able for a left or right turn towards the south to
dump,'' a course that will take them out to sea. The controller
tells them they will be over the coast in 10 miles, and that they
should advise him when they are ready to dump. The pilot does not
say he is beginning dumping until 1:24:56, almost three minutes
later, at which time the controller tells him, `just a couple of
miles I'll be right with you,'' and thirty seconds after that, the
controller tells the crew to begin dumping.
</P>
<P>
   Another telling moment is when (at 1:22:36) a pilot has
evidently keyed the microphone for transmission to the ground while
discussing with the other pilot, in German, whether they are
performing the emergency checklist for smoke, a confusion
equivalent to trying to carry on two telephone conversations
simultaneously and putting the wrong one on hold.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 2045EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
