<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0345 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4537 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STRATEGY-BOS &LR;      09-08 1270
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STRATEGY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR SAID TO REFUSE CLINTON AN EARLY LOOK AT REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr Tuesday
rejected a White House request for an advance look at his report of
possible impeachable offenses by President Clinton before sending
it to the House of Representatives, setting the stage for a
possible showdown over the report's contents.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's report is expected to reach the House ``this week or
next,'' Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott said Tuesday. Lott
suggested the written request from Clinton's private attorney,
David Kendall, to preview the report was a stalling tactic. ``I
wouldn't be surprised if they go to court to try to block it,''
Lott said about administration officials.
</P>
<P>
   The back-and-forth over Starr's report comes as Clinton, worried
that Democrats are beginning to openly criticize his admission of
an affair with former White House intern Monica S. Lewinsky, plans
to meet Wednesday morning with House Democratic leaders, who will
have a lot to say about how the report is handled.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting, according to White House officials and Democratic
strategists, is designed to persuade congressional leaders to
support the president at a time some Democrats are publically
signaling their disapproval of Clinton. Adding to his problems is
Attorney General Janet Reno's decision Tuesday to order a 90-day
preliminary investigation of funding for the 1996 Clinton-Gore
campaign ads, a review that could lead to another independent
counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the president needs to repair his relationship with
Congress,to the extent that he can,'' a Democratic strategist close
to the White House said. ``There are obviously a lot of distraught,
angry and upset people. They are going to be deciding his fate, so
he has a particular interest in calming their distress.''
</P>
<P>
   Kendall on Monday had asked Starr to allow him and Clinton's
White House lawyers a week to review the independent counsel's
report and provide a response before sending it to Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's aides and advisers said the request was fair, since
Kendall was not allowed to cross-examine grand jury witnessess,
including Lewinsky. The aides also view Starr as being under no
obligation to include exculpatory information about Clinton in his
report.
</P>
<P>
   ``We make this request to ensure that this first step in the
most serious process contemplated by our Constitution is taken with
due consideration for fundamental fairness,'' Kendall wrote to
Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Starr, in his response to Kendall, said, ``As a matter of legal
interpretation, I respectfully disagree with your analysis. My
conclusion is that you are mistaken in your views ... and right to
review a `report' before it is transmitted to Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr concluded, ``If you believe it is appropriate for your
client to be allowed to review that information ... before that
information is made public, I suggest that you address your
concerns to the House of Representatives where such a decision
might be made.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Starr refused to confirm that his office is preparing a
report, his four-page letter detailed his legal right to provide
Congress with information and analysis that may constitute grounds
for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Starr also noted Clinton refused several invitations to testify
before the grand jury. On April 3, after the sixth refusal, Starr
wrote to Kendall: ``If the President chooses again not give his
testimony, so that the grand jury may at least receive some of his
evidence, please provide this Office with any and all exculpatory
evidence you may have.''
</P>
<P>
   Kendall is still expected to submit a simultaneous report to
Congress that interprets the evidence against Clinton in a more
favorable light than the White house expects from Starr's report.
</P>
<P>
   One person familiar with the White House's strategy said Kendall
probably not pursue a court fight to review the report because that
might appear the president has something to hide. More likely, said
another source, the White House would use Starr's rejection to
galvanize the president's supporters to criticize the fairness of
the report.
</P>
<P>
   Robert B. Reich, former labor secretary under Clinton and now
professor of social and economic policy at Brandeis University,
said, ``The White House will obviously do whatever it can to
confirm the public's deep suspicion that Ken Starr is playing
politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they can make the issue Ken Starr, as they almost succeeded
in doing before the president was pushed into a corner two weeks
ago at the time of his grand jury apperance, they can succeed in
deflecting attention off the issue of presidential judgment and
veracity,'' Reich said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House is scrambling to develop a legal and political
strategy for handling the fallout from the president's
acknowledgement on Aug. 17 of an inappropriate relationship with
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   After that admission, Clinton left for a two-week vacation on
Martha's Vineyard and a weeklong visit to Russia and Ireland. He
returned Sunday to a more hostile political atmosphere that
included members of his own party.
</P>
<P>
   During his first full day back at work in Washington in three
weeks, Clinton visited a Maryland school Tuesday, made significant
because Democratic Governor Parris Glendening snubbed him by not
attending.
</P>
<P>
   Also, two Democratic senators, Ernest ``Fritz'' Hollings of
South Carolina and Barbara Boxer of California, strongly criticized
Clinton's relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fed up,'' said Hollings. ``The behavior, the dishonesty
of the president is unacceptable, and we'll see with the report
what course the Congress will take.''
</P>
<P>
   Boxer, whose daughter married Hillary Rodham Clinton's younger
brother in the White House in 1994, described the president's
behavior as ``wrong,'' ``indefensible'' and ``immoral.''
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Michael D. McCurry said that in
addition Wednesday's meeting with House Democrats, the president is
trying to arrange to meet Thursday with Republican and Democratic
congressional leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's got a number of things he wants to say to them, a
number of things he wants to ask them about,'' McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic strategist who spoke on the condition of
anonomity put it this way: ``Bill Clinton has a lot more to fear
from Congress than he does from the public. . . . The political
community is on the verge of panic, and the public is aghast at the
panic they're seeing from the political community.''
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, aides have scheduled a busy week for the
president to showcase him as focused on the people's work. After
meeting with Democratic leaders, Clinton will fly to Florida to
promote his education agenda and to attend Democratic Party
fund-raisers. Later in the week, he will promote auto safety, host
a breakfast for religious leaders and attend a memorial service for
victims of the US embassy bombings in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides have left open the possibility that Clinton
will add to his public comments about the Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you'll see are a lot of small tactical moves designed day
by day to keep the situation from deteriorating further,'' said
Reich.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many different views right now about what needs to
be done, a lot of confusion, not panic, but real uncertainty,'' he
said. ``They are waiting for the other shoe to drop, until they
know what a clunker that shoe is going to be, they are very
uncertain about how to proceed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
