A4544 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPROUT-COX     09-08 0399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPROUT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Close-up on Sprout
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   What: Sprout, a one-year-old company, sells equipment and data
to bookstores so they can print a book, on request, in about 10
minutes. The system, printer and access to a digital database,
start at about $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   Who: Henry Topping, 29, and Pat Brannan, 34. Before attending
grad school at the University of Virginia, Topping worked in asset
management. Brannan was a Navy pilot and Gulf War veteran who later
worked as an emulsion processing consultant in the oil refinery
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue: None. Yet. Topping said they are one to two months away
from earning revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Current location: The Advanced Technology Development Center at
Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Web address: http://www.sproutinfo.com
</P>
<P>
   Beginnings: The company began as a second-year grad school class
contest. Topping and Brannan won the contest and graduated from
U.Va. in May 1997. Sprout started in Atlanta the next month.
</P>
<P>
   They chose Atlanta over New York, a more logical choice for a
company dependent upon relationships with publishing companies,
partly because Brannan's wife took a job with Coca-Cola and, in
part, because Atlanta was a better place for a small business,
Topping said.
</P>
<P>
   Inspiration: Expensive, hard-to-find books.
</P>
<P>
   While pursuing their MBA degrees, Topping and Brannan were
struck by how expensive the textbooks they needed for class were.
Most were about $65 and hard to come by.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a combination of sticker shock and an inability to
deliver books when they were needed,'' Topping said.
</P>
<P>
   Customer response: Pat Cunningham is vice president of
operations and one of the owners of the Engineer's Bookstore, on
Marietta Street near Georgia Tech. Sprout will use the Marietta
Street (in downtown Atlanta) store as a test site.
</P>
<P>
   ``It keeps bookstores vibrant in the changing marketplace,''
Cunningham said. ``You can look online and decide if you want to
buy. It keeps bookstores in the supply chain.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham's store carries a lot of high-priced textbooks,
averaging about $60, which can drive up inventory costs. ``With an
idea like Sprout, I don't have to have a product on my shelf to be
able to sell it. It's another channel to deliver product.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
