<HEADER>
A4556 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-YOUTH-RALLY-NYT &LR;      09-08 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-YOUTH-RALLY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE RUSHED RALLY STAGE AFTER BEING ATTACKED, CHIEF SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Police Commissioner Howard Safir, offering a new
explanation for why his officers stormed the stage at the end of
Saturday's youth rally in Harlem, said Tuesday that they rushed
forward only after they were pelted by bricks, bottles, metal
barriers and other objects, many of them hurled from the speaking
platform itself.
</P>
<P>
   Safir and Chief of Patrol John Scanlon, the ranking commander at
the scene Saturday, said that a phalanx of officers in riot helmets
first began moving toward a set of generators, which were located
behind and to the right of the platform, to cut power to the sound
system being used by keynote speaker Khallid Abdul Muhammad.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani had said police took over the
stage because Muhammad began urging the crowd to fight and even
shoot officers if provoked. Earlier, the mayor had said that the
officers moved in to enforce a strict timetable that called for the
rally to be shut down promptly at 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   In the account offered Tuesday, Scanlon said: ``When we moved,
our objective was the generator, to cut the sound. We only went to
the stage to secure our safety and the safety of other civilians in
the area because debris continued to come off the stage.''
</P>
<P>
   The Police Department's more detailed account came as Manhattan
District Attorney Robert Morgenthau announced that he had begun a
grand jury investigation of the events at the end of the rally,
called the Million Youth March. Morgenthau said the investigation
would be certain to include any assaults on police officers. In
addition, he said, investigators would consider possible charges of
incitement to riot, a misdemeanor, against Muhammad. Safir and
Giuliani have urged that he face such charges.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, scattered calls for community healing were drowned
out Tuesday by the growing recriminations, threats of civil rights
lawsuits, and calls for investigations by everyone from the U.S.
Justice Department to the New York Civilian Complaint Review Board.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the antagonists in this continuing saga showed no sign of
tiring, trading strikingly similar barbs from a distance of 230
miles. Safir, to the approbation of Giuliani, called Muhammad a
``black Hitler,'' while in Washington, Malik Zulu Shabazz,
Muhammad's top aide, likened Giuliani to a tyrant sitting back in a
``fascist, Adolf Hitler-type tower,'' sending the police ``out to
do evil work against the community.''
</P>
<P>
   At his news conference Tuesday, Safir angrily defended his
department's actions, saying the police had ensured ``that a
hate-monger who came here to cause trouble was not allowed to do
that, and the citizens of this city were protected from people who
wanted a riot and did not have one.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that it was necessary for the officers to wear riot
gear, for their own protection. ``Somebody said to me, `How come
they were wearing helmets and riot gear?''' Safir said. ``Well,
thank God they were wearing helmets, because one of our police
officers was hit in the head with a brick and probably would have
been dead or severely brain-injured had she not been wearing her
helmet.''
</P>
<P>
   Safir refused to discuss the reasons for some of the Police
Department's actions, however, such as the decision to send a
helicopter flying low over the crowd on Malcolm X Boulevard. ``I'm
setting the record straight on the facts of what occurred,'' he
said. ``I'm not going into specific tactics.''
</P>
<P>
   Explaining the move toward the stage, Scanlon said that at about
3:45 p.m., one of the event promoters promised to cut off the
generators promptly at 4 p.m.. ``I asked him as a sign of good
faith to move the gentleman who was standing in front of the
generator, and he said he would,'' the chief recalled. ``He not
only didn't do that, he reinforced it with large numbers of
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Police photographers videotaped the rally and the demonstration
at its close from several angles. Saturday, the department shared
with reporters some of that tape, of Muhammad's remarks. Tuesday, a
spokeswoman for Safir refused to allow a reporter to view the
department's videotape of the melee behind the stage, saying that
those images were being forwarded to the district attorney's office
and had thus become evidence in the criminal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview Tuesday, Morgenthau said he had decided
to begin the grand jury investigation based largely on accounts of
the clash provided by several of his own investigators, including
Leroy Frazier, who oversees Morgenthau's Harlem office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought there was a serious chance of confrontations and
difficulty, so we had three or four people there,'' Morgenthau
said. Frazier, who also heads the district attorney's special
prosecutions bureau, will direct the grand jury investigation,
Morgenthau said.
</P>
<P>
   Morgenthau said that the inquiry would extend to any criminal
activity, whether by demonstrators, speakers or police. He added,
however, that he had yet to hear of any crime committed by an
officer at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, he said, ``there are certain things that we know
happened.'' Among them, he said, Officer Julie McNichols of the
Bronx Task Force was struck in the helmet by a brick and knocked
unconscious, and Officer Christopher Williams of the Manhattan
South Task Force was stabbed in the hand and hit with a metal
chair.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, investigators said they have identified just one
alleged assailant, using the police videotapes. The man, James
Washington of Brooklyn, who is also known as Shaheed Muhammad, was
expected to surrender Tuesday. Morgenthau said the man had hurled a
brick at the rally Saturday and had also assaulted a police
community affairs officer who was sitting outside a news conference
held by the rally organizers in Brooklyn on Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
