<HEADER>
A4558 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-ONDECK09-C     09-08 0273
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-ONDECK09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves on deck: Montreal Expos
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ When: 7:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _ Where: Olympic Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   _ TV: Fox Sports South.
</P>
<P>
   _ Probable starting pitchers: LHP Tom Glavine (18-6, 2.61 ERA;
15-11, 3.55 lifetime vs. Expos) vs. RHP Dustin Hermanson (13-10,
3.08; 1-2, 3.50 lifetime vs. Braves).
</P>
<P>
   _ Notes: Glavine gets his second shot at his 19th victory. He's
coming off a tough 2-1 loss to the Mets last Friday in New York.
Although he allowed just five hits in seven innings, one was
decisive: Mike Piazza's monstrous two-run homer in the fourth
inning. Glavine can still become the NL's first 19-game winner
against the Expos, who bombed him early in his career but whom
Glavine has owned in recent years. In his lone start against
Montreal this season, he went 6 2/3 innings in Atlanta on June 13
and, despite allowing 11 hits and six runs (earned), got the win in
the Braves' 9-7 victory. Javy Lopez and Andruw Jones homered
back-to-back off Mike Johnson, then back-to-back again in their
next at-bats. Once a reliever with San Diego, Hermanson is thriving
in his second season as a starter with Montreal. He's won nine of
his last 13 decisions, beginning with a 4-1 win over the Braves in
the Big O on June 21. That day, the hard-throwing right-hander went
eight strong innings, giving up five hits and one run on Michael
Tucker's seventh-inning solo homer. His ERA dropped that day to
2.96; now at 3.08, it's still sixth-best in the NL (Glavine's
fourth at 2.61).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
