<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kucera outlasts Agassi in match of mind games
 &HT;    By Todd Holcomb
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If Karol Kucera felt Andre Agassi had done him wrong,
then winning was the best revenge.
</P>
<P>
   After losing five straight games to trail 2-0 in the fifth set
Tuesday, the ninth-seeded Kucera saved two break points and won
6-3, 6-3, 6-7 (7-5), 1-6, 6-3 to reach his first-ever quarterfinal
in a U.S. Open. It was a rain-delayed match contested over two days
and enlivened by some Agassi gamesmanship that went over well with
a partisan full house of 9,500 at Louis Armstrong Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's day one, Agassi was down two sets and a service
break in the third when he began protesting the Slovak's habit of
stopping his service motion to catch his errant tosses. After
Kucera's fifth false-start in one game and about 12 for the match,
Agassi stopped play to complain to chair umpire Norm Chryst.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many times is he allowed to do that?'' Agassi asked
Chryst. When told it was legal, Agassi left Chryst with, ``So I can
do it on every serve, right?''
</P>
<P>
   Chryst didn't answer. ``He just gave me that stupid look he
gives,'' Agassi said.
</P>
<P>
   A few points later, Agassi called for time just as Kucera was
serving against a break point at 3-1. Made to serve again, Kucera
missed his first serve, and Agassi drove his second into the
backhand corner, unreturnable, further inciting the crowd to his
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some stage, after 15, 16, 18, whether he meant it or not,
it's unacceptable,'' Agassi said of Kucera's interrupted serves.
``It's asking a lot of a player to put up with that.''
</P>
<P>
   After the changeover, Agassi mocked Kucera by catching his own
service tosses prior to four different points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a little bit unfair from Andre,'' Kucera said,
``because I didn't do this on purpose. My ball toss was not good,
especially when you are under pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the set, Agassi began looping moon balls at Kucera.
Agassi said he did it to help him refocus on constructing points
and improving shot selection, but Kucera thought Agassi was playing
mind games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough for me to stay concentrated,'' Kucera said.
``When somebody is doing something bad to you, then you're thinking
about what he's doing and you don't think about the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi led 3-0 in the fourth set when rain ended the night. On
Tuesday, Agassi had two break points for 3-0 lead in the fifth.
Agassi credited Kucera for stepping up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, it was all about tennis,'' Agassi said. ``Last night,
it just got to the point where it was so competitive, we could've
put on boxing golves, thrown darts, anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Kucera called it ``the most interesting match I've ever
played.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
