<HEADLINE>
BOEING, AIRBUS SPLIT ORDERS WORTH $7 BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Splitting what some analysts say could be parts of
largest pot of business remaining in this economic cycle, The
Boeing Co. and Airbus Industrie Tuesday announced airplane orders
worth a combined $7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus won orders totaling about $4.3 billion to sell up to 10
long-range A340-500 jets and six A320 short-haul planes to
International Lease Finance Corp., an airplane leasing company, and
as many as 16 A340s to Emirates Airlines. The orders are a setback
for Boeing, which was hoping to sell ILFC and Emirates on
longer-range, higher-performance versions of the 777 that would
have greater range and more performance than current models.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Dennis, vice president of Boeing's commercial group, said
Boeing continues to actively market the new versions of the 777.
``I would say we are very close to launching,'' he said. ``As a
marketing guy, I'd like to see it happen immediately, but I think
we are very close.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing won an order from the Brazilian carrier Varig, the
largest airline in Latin America, worth about $2.7 billion. It is
for the sale of four 777s, 10 next generation 737-800s, four next
generation 737-700s, six extended range 767-300s, plus options for
four 777-200s and 11 737-700s. The Varig sale helped take some of
the sting out of Airbus's $3.5 billion order, announced in March,
from a group of airlines in Brazil, Chile and Central America.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing President Harry Stonecipher made an appearance for the
Varig announcement, saying, ``We have not left the field of
battle.''
</P>
<P>
   But as if to underline the uncertainty in the aircraft market,
Brazil was in the midst of a currency crisis of its own. Its
central bank had just put up the interbank lending rate from 19
percent to 29.75 percent in an effort to defend its currency, the
real.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing spokesman Fernando Vivanco said airlines such as Varig
``typically make major purchase decisions every 10, 15 or 20
years,'' and that a short-term crisis would not affect the decision
or the quality of the order.
</P>
<P>
   John Plueger, chief operating officer of International Lease
Finance Corp., was asked whether this is a wise time to be buying
this many planes, which would be delivered from 2002 to 2006.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry has certainly reached a crescendo and it's
possible there will be some softening in the next few years,'' he
said. ``But our own internal estimates are that time period between
2002 and 2006 is going to be very, very robust.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``And actually we are actually quite bullish about a
strong recovery in Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   Asia is the key that divides the industry bulls from the bears.
Boeing's ``1998 Current Market Outlook'' forecasts an annual growth
rate for short-haul flights within Asia of 7.6 percent through 2007
_ a figure higher than Europe or North America _ and a 6.8 percent
annual growth in Asia-to-Europe flights.
</P>
<P>
   Safeco Corp. money manager Bill Whitlow, who has followed Boeing
for years, says it's fairly clear that Boeing's production will hit
a cyclical peak next year. ``The question is how much it
declines,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Aseritis of Credit Suisse First Boston forecasts a
drop-off from about 610 planes next year to about 500 a year for
the next few years after that. Ed Greenslet of The Airline Monitor
forecasts a drop to 320 planes by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number one question is Asia, and in Asia, the number one
question is Japan,'' Whitlow says. The more optimistic forecasts
assume that Japan's economy finally recovers. The pessimists assume
a global recession.
</P>
<P>
   Post-Intelligencer reporter Bruce Ramsey and Bloomberg News
contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 2103EDT &QL; 
