u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAZIL-ECON-625&AMP;ADD-N     09-08 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-ECON-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL ACTS TO SPUR EXPORTS, LIMIT SPENDING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ Caught between the urgency of stanching
a near-hemorrhage of hard currency from the country and the demands
of approaching presidential elections, the Brazilian government
announced modest measures Tuesday to stimulate exports and contain
spending.
</P>
<P>
   The government said it would simplify cumbersome bureaucratic
procedures for exports worth less than $10,000, and would allow
foreigners to pay for Brazilian exports with international credit
cards. The plan's goal is to increase exports 15 percent a year, in
the hope that they will reach $100 billion a year by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The government also announced a 20 percent across-the-board
budget cut for national agencies for the rest of 1998. The step
represented an about-face as capital for emerging markets grows
scarcer. Three months ago, officials had lifted more modest
spending limits on federal agencies, as President Fernando Henrique
Cardoso prepared to start his campaign for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   But investors saw Tuesday's steps as perhaps too modest. ``They
affect the domestic debt, but the market has not interpreted them
as a way to reduce our crisis,'' said Rafael Cardoso, vice
president of Sudameris Bank. ``The government's trying to reduce
spending, but there's not much margin for maneuver,'' added
Cardoso, who is not related to the Brazilian president.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, after starting the day with strong gains, the nation's
benchmark stock index ended slightly lower, losing steam in
afternoon trading after the government measures were announced.
Indeed, despite a 5 percent surge on Wall Street Tuesday, most
Latin American stock markets seemed to reflect the uncertainty over
Brazil, closing off or, in the case of Mexico, with modest gains.
In the bond market, the Brazilian government was able to sell $510
million worth Tuesday, roughly a fifth of the total it had offered.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that the government's measures came across as
tepid. James Barrineau of Salomon Smith Barney said the steps to
curtail spending would do little more than offset the higher costs
associated with an interest rate increase last week. ``There's
still a lot of uncertainty in terms of whether this will be
enough,'' Barrineau said. ``The perception is, it's not what people
were looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   Chile, too, sought some relief from economic troubles by
focusing on commercial trade. Officials in Santiago announced plans
to cut down on so-called exchange dumping, by restricting imports
from countries that had devalued their currencies. At the same time
it is moving to lower general tariffs to 6 percent from 11 percent.
With the fall in prices for copper, a third of Chile's exports, and
the troubles in Asia, Chile's commercial deficit has reached $3
billion, about $1 billion more than economists forecast.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two weeks, Brazil has been spending about $1
billion a day in foreign reserves to shore up its currency, the
real, which economists say is overvalued by 10 to 20 percent. On
Friday, it lost $2.7 billion in reserves, as Latin American finance
ministers ended a meeting with the International Monetary Fund with
no solid pledge of assistance for their floundering economies. On
Thursday, Moody's Investors Service downgraded Brazilian bonds to
the debt levels of Nicaragua and Paraguay.
</P>
<P>
   The losses prompted the government to effectively raise
Brazilian interest rates to 29.75 percent after markets closed
Friday, just as the Federal Reserve chairman, Alan Greenspan,
indicated that he was increasingly concerned about a spreading
danger to world markets _ a statement many interpreted as an
openness at the Fed to lowering U.S. interest rates. In Washington
last week, Latin American finance ministers had been clamoring for
just such help.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The increase in the central bank's assistance rate for banks,
called the T-Ban, was expected to cost the Brazilian government
$1.3 billion more a month in interest payments on its debt,
Barrineau said, but it was seen as an essential step in slowing the
flight of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   While the government has labored to project calm, orderly
preparation for the financial storm that threatens to strike here
after devastating economies in Asia and Russia, it has been
speaking with somewhat conflicting voices.
</P>
<P>
   It raised interest rates just two days after lowering them. In
announcing the increase, Francisco Lopes, the director of the
central bank, warned that ``the government now has to work in the
fiscal area to help defend the real.'' But Cardoso, who is running
for re-election on Oct. 4, chided reporters for suggesting that ``a
package'' of spending cuts was in the works.
</P>
<P>
   ``Package is a disagreeable phrase that gives the impression you
are going to pass a set of measures that will take the country by
surprise,'' he said on Monday. ``We are not going to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The conflicting voices coming from Brasilia, the capital, are a
mirror of officials' conflicting needs. Cardoso, who wants to be
re-elected, wishes to cause as little economic pain as possible. At
the same time, Brazil must convince lenders and the markets that
its economic plans and economy are credible.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardoso administration has largely avoided effective
measures to balance expenses over the last four years, making it
more vulnerable to shortages in dollar reserves. Brazil is expected
to end the year with a deficit of 8 percent, and expectations for
growth are running under 2 percent. J.P. Morgan predicted last week
that the economy would shrink 2 percent, and forecasts for next
year are not much better.
</P>
<P>
   The government did not bolster its credibility by releasing a
1999 budget that relied on projections of 4 percent growth.
Brazil's unemployment, at 8 percent, is up by almost half over last
year, and at the worst levels since the debt crisis of the early
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The government said Tuesday that stimulating exports would
create 500,000 jobs. And it predicted that the restrictions on
spending would create a ``primary surplus'' of $5 billion in 1998
and $8.7 billion in 1999. The figure do not include interest
payments on debt. Brazil's budget deficit, given the government's
projections, would drop to about 5 percent of the gross domestic
product. The country faces a current account deficit of $40
billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
