<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4577 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BASEBALL-HEROES-COX     09-08 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASEBALL-HEROES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How we mark our milestones
 &HT;    By Paul Reid
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A kid should catch the ball.
</P>
<P>
   It's only appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Because, like it or not, the future begins with home run No. 62.
</P>
<P>
   Like it or not, the Maris era is boxed, wrapped and archived as
soon as 62 leaves Mark McGwire's bat. As Jim Lovell said when
Apollo 13 lifted off, the clock is running.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time before baseball, before the impersonal
constraints of clock time and calendar time, when the king's reign,
floods or plague marked passages in human lives.
</P>
<P>
   Now we mark time with records. Baseball is our way of keeping
score. Baseball heroes and their deeds define cultural epochs. Home
run records are just rare enough to offer the same perspective a
mountain peak offers _ an unobstructed view back across the valley
to other peaks.
</P>
<P>
   When old records die, something dies in us. Mortality whispers.
</P>
<P>
   If you were 10 in 1961, you're middle-aged today, and you can
take the measure of your life from Maris to McGwire. It's a nice,
simple calibrating device, more effective, more emotional, more
personal than a calendar. Sit back, close your eyes, and follow
your life's story from those days of big cars, JFK and Mercury
space capsules. When McGwire launches 62, the chapter ends.
</P>
<P>
   If you were a kid back in 1961, Babe Ruth's 1927 record was, for
you, a distant, prehistoric event, like World War I and Al Capone.
Maris brought baseball, and you, into the modern era. It was a
beginning, like Sputnik, the transistor, jet flight. Grunts in
Vietnamese rice paddies debated whether Mickey Mantle was the
better hero than Maris, whether Dustin Hoffman could act, whether
Janis Joplin could sing. Babe Ruth was history.
</P>
<P>
   For your uncles in Normandy foxholes who talked of the Babe and
Greta Garbo and Ty Cobb, Maris came to mark the end. Their giant
Emerson radios went to the garage. The '38 Dodge went to the scrap
pile. Their pinup girls got old. The Babe died.
</P>
<P>
   If you're 40 today and think Roger Maris and his record have no
personal meaning for you, you're wrong. Your kids will talk about
the McGwire era, and they'll remember you in terms of Before and
After No. 62. You, and Roger Maris, will be part of the last era.
</P>
<P>
   And if you remember George Herman Ruth sending No. 60 skyward,
you know you have lived a long life. Mark McGwire's feat cannot
help but fill you with a sense of loss, of remembrances of old
friends, hopes realized, dreams dashed. You've been here for most
of the century, and the century is ending.
</P>
<P>
   A kid should catch the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire belongs to all of us, but the ball belongs to the
future and the future belongs to the kid.
</P>
<P>
   The Babe took America into a new age: the Hero as Everyman.
</P>
<P>
   Other icons of his era:
</P>
<P>
   FDR
</P>
<P>
   The Depression
</P>
<P>
   Will Rogers
</P>
<P>
   Al Jolson
</P>
<P>
   Charles Lindbergh
</P>
<P>
   Lou Gehrig
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Roosevelt
</P>
<P>
   Buster Keaton
</P>
<P>
   Hitler
</P>
<P>
   Prohibition
</P>
<P>
   Al Capone
</P>
<P>
   John D. Rockefeller
</P>
<P>
   Frank Sinatra
</P>
<P>
   Bruno Hauptmann
</P>
<P>
   Mary Pickford
</P>
<P>
   Empire State Building
</P>
<P>
   1927 Chevrolet. A car for all Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Iwo Jima. Real heroes.
</P>
<P>
   Maris competed for coverage with manned space flight, the
transistor and the computer.
</P>
<P>
   Other icons of his era:
</P>
<P>
   Davy Crockett, as done by Disney
</P>
<P>
   JFK and Jackie
</P>
<P>
   Cuban missile crisis
</P>
<P>
   The Beatles
</P>
<P>
   Bay of Pigs
</P>
<P>
   Mickey Mantle
</P>
<P>
   I Love Lucy
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Lewis
</P>
<P>
   The Cold War
</P>
<P>
   Civil rights
</P>
<P>
   J. Paul Getty
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Monroe
</P>
<P>
   Mercury 7 astronauts
</P>
<P>
   McGwire fits our image of the hero: big, humble, generous.
</P>
<P>
   The way America ought to be.
</P>
<P>
   Other icons of his era:
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton
</P>
<P>
   Titanic
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan
</P>
<P>
   Jim Carrey
</P>
<P>
   Beanie Babies
</P>
<P>
   O.J. Simpson
</P>
<P>
   The Internet
</P>
<P>
   and who knows what the future holds?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
