<HEADER>
A4581 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     09-08 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODWARD ADMIRATION SOCIETY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back in London after being convicted of involuntary manslaughter
of an 8-month-old baby in her care,  &UR; Louise Woodward &LR;  told the
Sunday Times that she has received about 50 proposals of marriage,
and many gifts, since her return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tend to get a lot of gifts from them, Valentine things like
flowers and chocolates,'' said the 20-year-old Woodward. ``You
always get people who see a picture or your face on TV and fall in
love with it. They tend to keep my photograph by their bed. ...
I've got lots of friends out there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LAY DOWN THAT SWORD AND SHIELD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A monumental art installation using recycled parts from nuclear
attack submarines built in the '60s has been installed at Magnuson
Park in north Seattle. ``The Fin Project: From Swords Into
Plowshares'' is the work of  &UR; John Young &LR; , a professor of public art
and sculpture at the University of Washington in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The design magazine Metropolis describes the outdoor sculpture
as ``22 submarine fins placed at various angles and heights to
resemble the dorsal fins of a large pod of orca whales.'' Each fin,
painted black, weighs 10,000 pounds; the whole installation, on the
site of a former Navy base, is 500 feet long.
</P>
<P>
   This commemoration of the end of the Cold War was built with
$150,000 in private money raised by  &UR; Max Gurvich &LR; , a Seattle
philanthropist. ``We spent millions of dollars on a war machine,''
he told Metropolis. ``Now it has become an object of art.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Earl Spencer &LR; ,  &UR; Princess Diana &LR; 's brother, is bored with
South Africa and plans to return to England permanently, said a
report in the Telegraph of London. Spencer's four children live
with their mother in South Africa. An aide said that the devoted
family man plans to ``keep a base'' there, to use when he visits
the kids.
</P>
<P>
   _ The biggest indoor high, literally, in sport climbing today is
silo climbing. Upper Limits in Bloomington, Ind., the nation's
first silo climbing gym, features challenges twice as high as those
in traditional rock climbing gyms, says Shape magazine. The silos
used were once storage places for soybeans.
</P>
<P>
   _ The journey of  &UR; Keiko &LR; , the ``Free Willy'' whale, from a pool
in Newport, Ore., to a UPS flatbed truck, &LR;  to an Air Force cargo
plane and then to a sea pen in an Icelandic bay, will be covered
live on the Internet beginning Wednesday at 1:30 p.m. at
www.keiko.org. The Web cast is the product of a partnership between
the Free Willy Foundation, the telecommunications supplier Ericsson
and RealNetworks.
</P>
<P>
   _ Is the New York Times losing its blue-blood credentials? A
correction in Monday's paper said that an obituary for a Times
executive the day before had called the Yale secret society Skull
and Crossbones instead of Skull and Bones. This is a gaffe that
would be comparable to calling the Junior League the Junior Legion.
</P>
<P>
   _ A study at Cardiff University found that the sound of
neighbors making love can be stressful. The findings will be
discussed at a housing research conference at the university.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOW TO BARGAIN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   City Edition, a new biweekly published in Beijing for
English-speaking expatriates, provides a series of globally useful
tips for bargaining. ``Treat the transaction as a game,'' writes
 &UR; Lucy Mui &LR; . ``Keep a poker face, &LR; '' and tell the vendor the ``white
lie'' (Mui's distinction) that the merchandise you want at the
price you want is available elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, set your own  &LR; price before you begin bargaining.
``Do not reveal this figure: When the vendor asks how much you are
willing to pay, counteroffer a price slightly less than your ideal
one. ... Setting your price serves the dual purpose of giving you a
negotiating goal and giving you peace of mind when you attain it.
You may learn later that a friend bought the same item for half the
price, but you, at least, paid an amount you were willing to part
with.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with journalists (is) they think that their
opinions matter. That's the problem with most rock stars and
musicians; they think that their opinions REALLY matter. They
don't. They're there for you to enjoy or throw out. That's why ears
have holes in 'em; music can go in and out.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Steven Tyler of Aerosmith in Music Choice.
</P>
</TEXT>
