<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4584 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STARR-820&AMP;ADD     09-08 1330
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-820&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR EXPECTED TO SUBMIT REPORT TO CONGRESS IN NEXT FEW DAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CLINTON-CONGRESS, CLINTON-SCHOOL) 
(sw) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr. and JAMES BENNET   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Dismissing objections from the White House, Kenneth
Starr, the Whitewater independent counsel, plans to deliver a
report to Congress, as early as the end of this week, summarizing
his eight-month inquiry into President Clinton's relationship with
Monica Lewinsky, allies of Starr said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Starr intends to alert House Speaker Newt Gingrich in a letter
on Wednesday that he will submit his report containing substantial
and credible evidence that may be the grounds for impeachment of
the president, according to lawyers familiar with Starr's plans.
Prosecutors are also planning to convene the grand jury here on
Thursday, in a signal that it will continue its criminal inquiry
even after a report is sent to the House of Representatives, the
lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   The report is expected to accuse the president of perjury in a
civil deposition, obstruction of justice, lying to a grand jury,
witness tampering and abuse of power, the lawyers said. It is
likely to include an embarrassing description of Clinton's conduct
with Ms. Lewinsky and a scorching appraisal of his use of White
House lawyers and claims of privilege in response to the inquiry
this year.
</P>
<P>
   In a prickly four-page letter incongruously addressed ``Dear
David,'' Starr on Tuesday rejected a request from David Kendall,
the president's private lawyer, for an advance review of the
report.
</P>
<P>
   Struggling to gain his political footing as Democratic senators
continued to pummel him on Tuesday for his behavior, Clinton
hastily set up a meeting for 8:30 a.m. Wednesday with House
Democratic leaders. Advisers to Clinton said he planned to address
the Lewinsky matter, apologizing and asking forgiveness for
misleading the legislators and the nation, and for potentially
damaging the party's prospects in elections this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton may offer another public apology later this week,
perhaps at a prayer breakfast at the White House on Friday morning,
advisers said. Clinton has made a series of increasingly direct
statements of regret since he acknowledged the relationship with
Ms. Lewinsky in a brief, defiant address on Aug. 17, after seven
months of denials.
</P>
<P>
   The House is scheduled to come back into session on Wednesday
afternoon, and the White House is anxious to smother the Democratic
criticism that began rising in the Senate last Thursday, when Sen.
Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut, trailed by other Democrats, took
to the floor to denounce Clinton's behavior.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, previously reluctant Democrats, including Sen.
Barbara Boxer of California, joined the chorus of criticism. Ms.
Boxer, whose daughter married a brother of Hillary Rodham Clinton,
called Clinton's behavior ``immoral'' and ``indefensible,'' while
defending his agenda and accomplishments in a speech on the Senate
floor.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall argued in a letter to Starr on Monday that the special
prosecutor had no legal authority to write a report analyzing his
findings _ but that if he chose to do so, he had an obligation out
of ``fundamental fairness'' to permit an advance review by
Clinton's defenders.
</P>
<P>
   But Starr wrote on Tuesday that he had a legal responsibility to
issue a report to Congress analyzing the evidence, and no authority
to provide a preview to the White House. He refused to acknowledge
that he was preparing a report, but as he cited sources from the
Constitution to Webster's dictionary, he left little doubt as to
how high he considers the stakes in his inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my view,'' he wrote, ``it is for Congress, the repository
of impeachment power, to decide if and when such information should
be provided to your client.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr also made it clear that he believes his prosecutors have
wide latitude in the preparation of a report. He quoted Alexander
Hamilton, who wrote in The Federalist papers that impeachment
proceedings should not ``be tied down to ... strict rules, either
in the delineation of the offence by the prosecutors, or in the
construction of it by the Judges.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican congressional leaders also scorned Kendall's request
on Tuesday. ``Why should they get special treatment?'' Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott said to reporters. ``I presume they'll
get it when the House gets it. They'll have a chance to respond.''
</P>
<P>
   One Clinton adviser outside the White House said that the
president's lawyers might go to court to try to force Starr to
permit them to review the report, perhaps delaying its delivery.
</P>
<P>
   But another senior adviser said that Clinton's lawyers had not
expected Starr to agree to Kendall's request. He said that in
discussions last week, legal and political advisers came to a
consensus that the primary purpose of Kendall's letter was
political, to suggest that Starr was unfair.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the White House meeting Wednesday, Rep.
Richard Gephardt, the House minority leader, is scheduled to sit
down with Gingrich and the Republican and Democratic leaders of the
House Judiciary Committee to discuss how to handle the Starr report
when it is delivered.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Close advisers of Clinton had not expected Starr to deliver his
report so soon, and some of them are concerned that the White House
is not prepared to respond to it. Kendall asked in his letter to
review the report at least a week before delivery, unsuspecting
that Starr might deliver it to Congress within a week of the letter
itself.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides said that they expect the report to include
graphic sexual details of the intimate relationship Clinton has
acknowledged with Ms. Lewinsky, whom he met in 1995 when she was a
21-year-old unpaid White House intern. It is the prospect that such
seamy material will be disclosed, these aides said, that has scared
congressional Democrats and prompted them to back away from the
president.
</P>
<P>
   The precise contents of the report remain closely held. But
prosecutors have been drafting sections that accuse Clinton of a
variety of crimes, including obstruction of justice and encouraging
others to lie under oath, lawyers familiar with Starr's plans have
said. Prosecutors are also considering whether to accuse Clinton of
perjuring himself in his deposition in January in the Paula Jones
sexual misconduct lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton denied a sexual relationship with Ms. Lewinsky in that
deposition. But he said in his address to the nation on Aug. 17
that his reponse was ``legally accurate,'' basing that claim, his
advisers have said, on a definition of sexual relations used by
Mrs. Jones' lawyers. Clinton made a similar claim in grand jury
testimony on the same day.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility that Starr's team might challenge Clinton's
interpretation, and accuse him of perjury before the grand jury,
raises the specter of a tawdry debate over what kind of intimate
contact constitutes sex.
</P>
<P>
   In their exchange of letters, Starr and Kendall quarreled over
everything from the intent of the Founding Fathers to the meaning
of the word ``information.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Starr was permitted by law to provide Congress with
``substantial and credible information,'' Kendall argued that the
prosecutor could not go past that authority to summarize or analyze
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   But Starr wrote that his dictionary defined information in part
as ``[k)nowledge derived from study,'' which, he said, left room
for analysis of facts. He wrote that the law also suggested that
prosecutors must use their judgment to determine if evidence is
``substantial and credible'' and whether it ``may constitute
grounds for impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In truth,'' he wrote, ``the independent counsel is duty bound
to provide Congress with his analysis of the information so that
Congress can make its own informed decision.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
