<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCK MARKET GAUGES SOAR AS INVESTORS SEEM HOPEFUL
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average jumped nearly 5 percent, or
380.53 points, to 8,020.78, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index rose 49.57 points, or 5 percent, to 1.023.46. The Nasdaq
composite index registered its biggest point gain ever, 94.34
points, or 6 percent, closing at 1,660.86, and the Russell 2000
index of small and medium-sized stocks increased 14.86 points, or
4.28 percent, to 361.93.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts attributed the turnaround in stocks to comments last
Friday by the chairman of the Federal Reserve, Alan Greenspan, who
gave investors hope that the Fed and other central banks might
jointly respond to crises in Asian and Russian markets.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the 30-year Treasury bond fell sharply. The yield,
which moves in the opposite direction, increased to 5.36 percent,
from 5.28 percent on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   YELTSIN PONDERING NEXT MOVE
</P>
<P>
   President Boris Yeltsin of Russia was considering his options to
calm the economic turmoil in that country after Parliament's second
rejection of his choice for prime minister, Viktor Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDMAN VETERAN TO LEAVE FIRM
</P>
<P>
   J. Christopher Flowers, a founder of Goldman, Sachs's lucrative
financial institutions merger practice, plans to leave the firm at
the end of November. The move comes the same day the firm
reaffirmed its intention to end its private partnership and issue
shares to the public in November.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL PLANS SPENDING REDUCTIONS
</P>
<P>
   The president of Brazil, Fernando Henrique Cardoso, announced
measures to stimulate exports and contain spending. The plan's goal
is to increase exports 15 percent a year, in the hope that they
will reach $100 billion a year by 2002. The government also
announced a 20 percent across-the-board budget cut for national
agencies for the rest of this year.
</P>
<P>
   WHEELCHAIR-FRIENDLY BUS CONCERN
</P>
<P>
   Greyhound Lines plans to announce that it will make all 4,000
stops on its nationwide bus system accessible to wheelchair users
by October 1999. But groups representing those users said Greyhound
planned to equip too few buses with lifts to deliver on the
company's promises.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN EXPRESS' EURO CHECKS
</P>
<P>
   American Express will issue euro-denominated traveler's checks
in time for sales to start on Jan. 1, 1999, the beginning of the
European Monetary Union.
</P>
<P>
   BRITISH AMERICAN TOBACCO UP 38%
</P>
<P>
   Shares in British American Tobacco soared 38 percent in London
on the first day of trading since the company sold its financial
services arm to the Zurich Group.
</P>
<P>
   A SMALLER DISK DRIVE FROM IBM
</P>
<P>
   IBM plans to announce that it has developed an ultra-small,
one-inch disk drive aimed at the market for hand-held computers and
consumer appliances.
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMER BORROWING JUMPED IN JULY
</P>
<P>
   Borrowing by consumers grew at a faster-than-expected pace in
July as auto and other personal loans surged, offsetting a drop in
credit card debt. Borrowing in July rose by $5.3 billion, to $1.266
trillion.
</P>
<P>
   ORDERS FOR NEW JETS AT $5.7 BILLION
</P>
<P>
   In the first two days of the Farnborough International Air Show,
the aerospace industry's top event of the year, Boeing has received
orders with a list price of around $3 billion and the European
consortium Airbus Industrie has received orders valued at $2.7
billion.
</P>
<P>
   EQUITY INNS CANCELS RFS ACQUISITION
</P>
<P>
   Equity Inns has canceled plans to acquire RFS Hotel Investors
for $660 million in stock because of the decline in the stock price
of Equity Inns.
</P>
</TEXT>
