<HEADER>
A4598 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-McGWIRE-PROFILE-A     09-08 1331
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-McGWIRE-PROFILE-ART-850&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BBO-MCGWIRE-SCENE)
</HEADLINE>
  
 MARK DAVID McGWIRE: RELUCTANT SLUGGER, RELUCTANT HERO  
(See also BBO-MCGWIRE, BBO-MCGWIRE-VECSEY-COLUMN,(ART ADV: Photo of McGwire is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the time he began playing baseball as an 8-year-old in
Claremont, Calif., Mark McGwire has been a reluctant home run
hitter and a reluctant hero. McGwire wanted to be a pitcher, not a
hitter, and he remained on the mound until college. He has always
wanted to avoid being the primary focus in a team sport.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how reluctant McGwire is to be the slugger in the
spotlight, his thunderous swings produce the sort of prodigious
home runs that have turned him into a larger-than-life figure.
Every fan loves watching baseballs rocket out of stadiums, so every
fan has reveled in McGwire's prowess as he has slipped into his
crouch, uncoiled and crushed another pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Especially this season.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's captivating run to history culminated Tuesday night
when he belted his 62nd homer to eclipse Roger Maris' hallowed
37-year-old record for the most in one season. McGwire, whose
reluctance abated as he glided toward this moment, broke the record
in the St. Louis Cardinals' 145th game. He instantly became the
most successful home run hitter for one season and a modern
baseball hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never dreamed of being in this position,'' the 34-year-old
McGwire said last month. ``I dreamed about being a big leaguer.
Things happen for a reason. Hard work pays off.''
</P>
<P>
   Listen to the people who watched McGwire develop from a robust
teen-ager who played golf and soccer before baseball, and they
inevitably discuss his work habits. Although his tantalizing story
sometimes seems predestined _ he homered in his first at bat for
the Claremont Little League Athletics _ McGwire did not wake up as
a 17-year-old with a 90-mile-an-hour fastball and a mighty
uppercut.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Carroll, who coached McGwire at Damien High School in La
Verne, Calif., has a vision of him that swims in his mind. It is
McGwire on the field or in the dugout with his red hair drenched,
his face sweating. That is how McGwire always looked to Carroll:
working or poised to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark was not afraid to work,'' Carroll said. ``God gave him
talent, but he worked hard, and that set him apart. God gives
everyone talents. Mark did something with his.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark David McGwire, born Oct. 1, 1963, was the second oldest in
a sports-oriented family of five boys whose cul-de-sac was a field
for all seasons. When he was 5, he caddied for his father, John,
and became intrigued by golf. But John McGwire, a dentist, and his
wife, Ginger, did not allow Mark and Dan, the younger brother who
went on to play quarterback for the Seahawks and the Dolphins, to
become egocentric about sports.
</P>
<P>
   John McGwire never told Mark about the coaches who predicted a
major league career for him, and Ginger believed that Mark never
became adversely affected by success because he was schooled to
respect others. He disliked receiving extra attention, and even
last month McGwire said: ``I don't know anyone who plays this game
to get the attention. I know I don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Rod Dedeaux, McGwire's baseball coach at the University of
Southern California, recalled how the burly young man was a
``natural leader'' through his quiet, blue-collar approach. When
McGwire first arrived at Southern Cal, he filled out a form for the
media guide and left the section about athletic accomplishments
blank.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very unselfish, very disciplined and was a great
teammate, and that comes from having wonderful parents,'' Dedeaux
said. ``You learn all of that from your parents.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire learned even more. His career has been hampered by foot
and back injuries, and he pondered retirement after a 1991 season
in which he batted .201. But then McGwire thought about his
father's lifelong fight. John McGwire learned as a 7-year-old that
he had polio, and he walks with a cane because one of his legs is
much shorter than the other. Now, at 61, he is an avid golfer and
cyclist, once biking 400 miles from San Francisco to Santa Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   How could he quit, Mark reasoned, if his father never did?
</P>
<P>
   Like everyone, McGwire has had his share of problems. He
underwent therapy for four years because, he said, he was an
emotional wreck after his baseball struggles in 1991. He faltered
as a husband, was divorced after four years of marriage and has
said he wishes he could do it all over. He is immersed in
controversy for using androstenedione, a testosterone-inducing
supplement that is legal in baseball but banned in professional
football and the Olympics. He was once asked if he is near-sighted
or far-sighted and he responded, ``blind.'' Without contact lenses,
that is.
</P>
<P>
   But McGwire is a devoted father to Matthew, his 10-year old son
whose pictures line his locker and who has been a bat boy during
the home run chase. He gives $1 million a year from his three-year,
$28.5 million contract with St. Louis to charities for physically
and sexually abused children. And he is one of the most popular
players of his era.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people love him so much that he can't go anywhere or do
anything,'' said Pat Kelly, a teammate. ``Everybody wants a piece
of him. At dinner, at a movie. The guy gets mobbed.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Montreal Expos drafted McGwire in the eighth round out of
Damien High in 1981 but offered him a signing bonus of only $8,500.
So he accepted a baseball scholarship to Southern Cal with an eye
toward becoming a major league pitcher. By his sophomore year,
McGwire wanted to play first base.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would see the balls jumping off the bat every day in
batting practice,'' Dedeaux said. ``You didn't have to see a game
to realize he had to play a real position. When you saw him hit the
ball nine miles, that was enough.''
</P>
<P>
   While at Southern Cal, McGwire met Kathy, one of the bat girls,
and they married in 1984. The Oakland Athletics drafted McGwire in
the first round that year, signing him for $125,000, and he
catapulted to stardom in 1987 by bashing a rookie record of 49
homers. McGwire had the chance for a 50th on the final day of the
season, but he left the A's in Chicago to return to California to
be with his wife as she gave birth to Matthew.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a tough decision to make,'' McGwire said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, the A's trampled opponents while winning 104 games and
were favored to win the World Series, but they lost to Kirk Gibson
and the Dodgers. It was also a difficult personal year for McGwire,
who went through a divorce. He and his ex-wife share custody of
Matthew, who lives in California with his mother and stepfather.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire played in two more World Series with the A's, winning
one from San Francisco in the earthquake-interrupted series of 1989
and losing to the Reds in 1990. After a dreary 1991, McGwire
rebounded with 42 homers in 1992 and then missed virtually all of
1993 and 1994 because of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire hit 39 homers in 1995, erupted for 52 in 1996 and had 34
by July 31 in 1997, but the rebuilding A's traded him to St. Louis
instead of trying to re-sign him. He left having hit 363 homers for
the Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals have underachieved this season, but McGwire's
pursuit of Maris helped rekindle interest in the sport and helped
recapture a legion of fans. Reluctant hero or not, McGwire's
fantasy season will be remembered as one of the best and the most
exciting in baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like apple pie,'' McGwire said. ``Every child, boy or
girl, has picked up a ball, a bat or a glove. Everybody can relate
to this sport. That's why I think all Americans can relate to this
sport.''
</P>
<P>
   And, now, to Mark McGwire and his new home run record.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
