<HEADLINE>
GORE COMBINES SCHOOL APPEARANCE, POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MERIDEN, Conn. _ Vice President Al Gore went on the road Tuesday
to sell the Clinton administration's proposals for hiring more
teachers, building new schools and renovating old ones.
</P>
<P>
   In the first of a series of town hall meetings that he plans to
hold nearly weekly through the fall, Gore flew into this
hard-pressed former factory town and went to Lincoln Middle School
_ where one-fourth of the 800 students have to be taught in a
double-wide trailer or at the high school across the street _ to
lead a discussion on crowding.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the state of the area's politics, as much as of its
schools, that appeared to lure Gore: The trip provided first-term
Rep. Jim Maloney, D-Conn., who faces a difficult race for
re-election this fall, the opportunity to make a campaign
appearance with him. Gore's aides said that each of the town-hall
discussions he has planned for this fall would be paired with a
political stop.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president is viewed in some quarters as a safer choice
to campaign for Democratic candidates than is Clinton, who has been
shunned by some in his party because of the Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Gore made no direct reference Tuesday to the president's
troubles, and took no questions. But in his remarks at a
fund-raising luncheon with Maloney, he alluded to the fears of
Democratic leaders that the party's voters would stay home in
November because of disillusionment caused by the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Gore declared that the Republican right wing was ``willing to
work hard for a bunch of crazy ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They work at it,'' he said, ``and as a result they sometimes
win elections which by all rights they have no business winning.
And so the question comes down to this: Are you willing to match
their intensity with even more of your own?''
</P>
</TEXT>
