<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, Sept. 13,
1998. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM AND VIDEO
</P>
<P>
   HAPPINESS-FILM (Undated) _ At a time when the news media are
awash in the gory details of presidential sexual hijinks, the
public is supposedly beyond shock when it comes to revelations of
bad behavior. Or is it? The acid test will come with the first
public American screenings of Todd Solondz's pitch-black comedy
``Happiness,'' at the New York Film Festival. ``Happiness,'' which
will be released in theaters on Oct. 16 by Good Machine, is a
gleeful, systematic demolition of the myth of the suburban idyll.
By Stephen Holden. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   JONATHAN-MYERS-FILMS (Undated) _ Once upon a time, the talk was
of the It Girl. These days, Jonathan Rhys Meyers has filmmakers
extolling what one might call the A Boy. The A, of course, stands
for androgynous, which is one quality _ an infectious smile and raw
talent are others _ that has the 21-year-old Irishman leading the
latest Anglo-Irish thespian wave. ``Johnny's fabulous to look at,''
said Ang Lee, who cast Rhys Meyers as a long-haired
villain-with-a-difference in his Civil War film, ``Ride With the
Devil,'' which is expected to be released in the spring,
co-starring Tobey Maguire and Jewel. By Matt Wolf. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   NIVOLA-FILMS (Los Angeles) _ Few actors, however successful, can
say that they have a museum in the family, but Alessandro Nivola,
26, can boast of two: one, devoted to his grandfather, the Italian
sculptor Constantino Nivola, is situated in the artist's hometown
in Sardinia, and a second, a far more modest and decidedly
unofficial archive in Manhattan, is devoted to the actor himself.
In his next movie, ``Best Laid Plans,'' a drama starring Reese
Witherspoon and Josh Brolin that is to be released next spring, he
plays a graduate student turned con artist, and in ``I Want You,''
a forthcoming British film by Michael Winterbottom that is set in
the seaside town of Hastings, Nivola plays a paroled murderer
seeking to rekindle a forbidden love affair _ a role he researched
by spending three days in Brixton prison in South London. By
Justine Elias. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   CIVIL-ACTION-FILM (Boston) _ Nonfiction books and films always
dance cheek to cheek with real life, of course. But ``A Civil
Action,'' a Disney movie that is to open on Dec. 25, based on the
acclaimed 1995 book by Jonathan Harr, has an unusually, uncannily
intimate relationship with reality. Perhaps the most intriguing
aspect of the success of the book and potential success of the
movie is this: In their depiction of a cluster of leukemia deaths
among children in the Boston suburb of Woburn and the large-scale
1986 legal battle that ensued over whether industrial pollution was
to blame, the reality they convey is not a comfortable or a simple
one. By Carey Goldberg. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   SAM-ROCKWELL-FILMS (Undated) _ Sam Rockwell is a master of the
quick change. The 29-year-old actor showed his range in January at
the Sundance Film Festival, where he was featured in not one but
three films. He appeared as the romantic, James Dean-like outcast
who mows lawns in John Duigan's ``Lawn Dogs,'' which opened in May;
he slouched across the screen as a hilariously inept safecracker in
John Hamburg's ``Safe Men,'' which opened in July, and he delivered
a chilling performance as a car-salesman-turned-hitman in Saul
Rubinek's dark comedy ``Jerry and Tom,'' which will also be shown
this month at the Toronto Film Festival. By Laura Winters. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   THEATER
</P>
<P>
   BROADWAY-SEASON (New York) _ There are a few things I am looking
forward to this season with the sort of hopes that are usually
dangerous. These are centered on three actors who, though none have
been on Broadway recently, arrive with sterling pedigrees and in
roles that would seem to fit them like wet suits. Martin Short, the
comedian of a thousand professional alter-egos, will appropriately
be playing not one but a number of roles in the Roundabout Theater
Company's revival of the 1962 musical ``Little Me'' this fall. Judi
Dench, the great English actress who recently won American hearts
as a startlingly human Queen Victoria in the movie ``Mrs. Brown,''
returns to New York this spring in David Hare's London hit ``Amy's
View.'' And Kevin Spacey, the Academy- and Tony Award-winning actor
who defies the casting director's notions of ``type,'' is also due
this spring as Eugene O'Neill's dream-smashing salesman in ``The
Iceman Cometh,'' a role he played to feverish acclaim in London. By
Ben Brantley. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   DANCE
</P>
<P>
   EIFMAN-BALLET (Undated) _ Boris Eifman's choreography, like his
dancers, is passionate and intense: his Eifman Ballet of St.
Petersburg gave audiences a jolt when this 21-year-old Russian
troupe made its New York debut in April with provocative
psychodramas about Tchaikovsky and the ballerina Olga Spessivtseva.
When the Eifman Ballet returns to City Center Jan. 19 through 31,
it will be easier to see why Eifman's highly expressive use of the
ballet idiom is so dramatic and stunning. ``The Karamazovs,'' his
two-act treatment of Dostoyevsky's ``Brothers Karamazov'' is a
distilled if graphic essay on the novel's themes. By Anna
Kisselgoff. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   CLASSICAL MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-SERIES-SEASON (New York) _ Many of us in New York complain
yearly about pandering repertory and incoherent programs, but
solutions are arriving from every side. I hope the public responds,
because music this season is being served with a sense of adventure
unusual to the decade. The watchword is ``series,'' and there are a
lot of them: coherent looks at either individuals or ideas. By
Bernard Holland. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   POP MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   MORISSETTE-ALBUM (Undated) _ The aftershocks from Alanis
Morissette's ``Jagged Little Pill'' haven't subsided since the
album was released in 1995. In one pop-culture masterstroke, the
album introduced a mainstream audience to what punks, post-punks,
riot grrrls and alternative rockers had been shouting for more than
a decade: that women were angry, intelligent, carnal, sick of being
victims and ready to speak for themselves. Ms. Morissette's new
album is due for release on Nov. 3, and advance information is
scarce; she has not even revealed the album's title. By Jon
Pareles. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   ART
</P>
<P>
   ARCHITECTS-SEASON (Undated) _ Money, movies, missiles, malls and
madness: the time approaches when these may be the only first-rate
items the United States will continue to turn out for international
consumption. There will be nothing but one vast continental sprawl
anchored by two buildings, one on either coast: the Pentagon, and
the new theater for the Academy Awards on Hollywood Boulevard,
which breaks ground this fall. By Herbert Muschamp. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   POLLOCK-MONET-ART (Undated) _ How specifically ``American'' were
Jackson Pollock's pictures? It's fitting that two of the big shows
this fall are the Pollock retrospective at the Museum of Modern Art
in New York City in November and the late Monet show at the Museum
of Fine Arts in Boston this month. By Michael Kimmelman. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   ANTIQUES
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-ASIAN-ANTIQUES (Undated) _ Forget that books are
endangered by the computer and that Asian art is collected mostly
by Asians. Both are on the minds of the nation's curators, who have
assembled some of the strongest and most diverse selections of such
works ever shown in this country. By Rita Reif. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   PAPERBACKS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (`t' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-EUROPE-SEASON (London) _ A new train to the plane is a
traveler's dream. By Sarah Lyall. (Vienna) _ A change of pace from
chandeliers and Strauss. By Jane Perlez. (Amsterdam, Netherlands) _
An old master's house adds masterly touches. By Marlise Simons.
(Paris) _ Paris gets a new subway line for a new century. By Craig
R. Whitney. (All Moved).
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER (Undated) _ Euro translates currency babel.
By Roger Collis. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Monet, with a mint on the pillow, in
