<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: AVOIDING THE DREADED ASTERISK
</HEADLINE>
   (See also BBO-MCGWIRE, BBO-MCGWIRE-PROFILE, BBO-MCGWIRE-SCENE,
BBO-MCGWIRE-BALL-TAX) 
(nk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Just keep belting the ball out of the park, early
and often. This was the way to exorcise all the ghosts and the
shadows, the doubts and the quibbles, the parenthetical clauses and
the modifying phrases.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire has politely kept Babe Ruth and Roger Maris on
their pedestals, but he caught them quickly, before anybody could
drag out charts and theories to diminish what the big boy has done.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night against the Cubs, McGwire, in his second at-bat,
hit his 62nd homer in his team's 145th game _ giving him more
homers in a season than anybody who ever played major league
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody can say they put an asterisk on it,'' McGwire said
after launching No. 61 on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   It was only a matter of time before McGwire crushed another. And
in a way, that took away from the drama. There has been no autumnal
chill, no pennant-race jitters, no sense of urgency, not like the
haunted Maris trudging around the bases with his head half down in
the Oct. 1 shadows of Yankee Stadium, doing it on the last day.
</P>
<P>
   After stultifying heat and humidity on the Labor Day weekend,
there was finally a brisk September feel to Busch Stadium Tuesday
night, but until now McGwire and his buddy Sammy Sosa have been
playing in an endless summer. Impervious to major slump or serious
injury or pressure, McGwire made it easier for himself by roaring
past 50, hitting 60 and setting his sights on 70. That's the way to
do it.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Roger Maris hit 61 homers in 162 Yankee games in
1961, and Babe Ruth hit 60 homers in 154 Yankee games in 1927, when
the schedule went to only 154 games. Sosa, the laughing cavalier,
went into last night's game with 58 homers in the Cubs' first 144
games.
</P>
<P>
   These were remarkable performances by both McGwire and Sosa,
that cannot be even partly diminished by citing friendly ball
parks, expansion pitching, helpful supplements, weight machines and
jet-age balls.
</P>
<P>
   These two men, along with Ken Griffey Jr. of Seattle, who went
into Tuesday with 50 home runs, are the next generation of
world-level athlete: McGwire, bulked up at 34 but more agile than
he was in his 20s; Sosa, powerful and compact; and Griffey, lithe
and airborne, pulling home runs back over the fences on defense,
laughing his way past the weight room and the pharmacy.
</P>
<P>
   There was a flicker of an asterisk a few weeks back when an
astute reporter noticed, in plain sight, a container of
androstenedione in McGwire's locker. The slugger admitted he was
using the over-the-counter substance to help build his body, but
baseball had no rule against the supplement.
</P>
<P>
   In taking androstenedione, McGwire has done nothing illegal _
dangerous, maybe, but not illegal. With his eye, with his hands,
with his acquired hitter's reflexes, he has deflected even a
potential symbolic asterisk, unlike poor Maris in 1961, the first
year of the 162-game schedule. Commissioner Ford C. Frick, formerly
Babe Ruth's ghost writer, tagged a mostly unseen asterisk on Maris,
who had 59 homers through the first 154 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a great admirer of Ford Frick,'' said the new
commissioner, Bud Selig, ``but that was not one of his greatest
moments.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire has cited the sentiments for Ruth and Mickey Mantle
during Maris' bittersweet year: ``You have two strikes against you
in the huge city of New York. I mean, that is not good. There
again, there are people being negative out there that just didn't
want to see somebody do history. The fact is, he did it. The fact
is that everybody should be happy for Roger Maris and his family.
Records are meant to be broken. It just happens that we are close
to it right now, and it is going to be broken.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, McGwire said of Maris: ``It was not fair to criticize
him. Is it his fault that he played when they changed it to 162
games?''
</P>
<P>
   Roger Maris Jr. has watched the home run derby of 1998 with a
twinge of sadness. ``Everybody knows who Mark McGwire is,'' he
said. ``Everyone is pulling for Mark McGwire and they want to see
him do this and I think that would be just an outstanding feeling
for my father. And, yeah, I wished that would have happened for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Roger Maris felt saddled with an asterisk, for all
time. By crushing so many home runs, so early, McGwire and Sosa are
knocking the asterisk out of the ball park.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
