<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4616 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRASH-RDP-1STLD-WRITE     09-08 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-RDP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLIGHT 111 BLACK BOX RECORDED PLANE'S SYSTEMS BREAKING DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to expand by approx. 400 words, and refine)  (ART ADV: a graphic for use with this story is being sent to NYT
graphics clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(HLW) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Nova Scotia _ As the pilots of Swissair Flight 111 were
struggling to prepare their jumbo jet for an emergency landing last
Wednesday night, a series of vital operating systems on the plane
were gradually breaking down, the chief investigator said on
Tuesday evening after a preliminary examination of the plane's
flight data recorder.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, on Tuesday, investigators also released a full
transcript of conversations between air traffic controllers and the
pilots, who were simultaneously striving to locate the source of
smoke streaming into their cockpit and to prepare for an unexpected
approach to an unfamiliar airport in a plane brimming with fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Though the conversations are largely calm and technical, at
least a touch of frantic confusion occasionally slipped in. At one
point, the pilots broadcast a conversation between the two of them,
in German, to a puzzled air controller on the ground, and, at
another point, both decided to talk to the controller at once.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Tuesday, investigators said that they had recovered
parts from the cockpit that showed signs of heat damage. The pilots
had reported smoke in the cockpit at the beginning of the incident,
but it is not clear yet whether there was a fire there.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are still hoping to recover the other ``black
box,'' the cockpit voice recorder, but rough weather kept divers
out of the water on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But with enough analysis, said the chief investigator, Vic
Gerden of Canada's Transportation Safety Board, the details from
the box that Canadian navy divers brought up on Sunday may reveal
where the plane's problem began, even though the recorder quit six
minutes before the plane crashed five miles off the coast near
here.
</P>
<P>
   Gerden said that investigators in his data-processing laboratory
in Ottawa were working backwards from the end of the data and had
not yet determined where on the 25-hour record (a period that could
cover three previous flights) the problems began.
</P>
<P>
   Gerden said that they did not want to say more about the
information from the flight data recorder until they had time to
assess its meaning and integrate the information with radar tapes
and other evidence.
</P>
<P>
   But another indication of the plane's growing distress came from
the tape of conversations between the controllers and the pilots.
Investigators said that they could hear in the background at one
point the warbling warning sound that the plane's autopilot makes
when it disconnects itself. If an autopilot cannot follow its
instructions, be they for altitude, speed, heading, or pitch, it
flips itself off and lets the pilots know it has done so.
Investigators say they do not yet know which failure made the
autopilot quit.
</P>
<P>
   The transcript of communications between the Geneva-bound jet
and air traffic controllers shows some confusion on both sides of
the conversation, although it was not immediately evident if the
errors made any difference to the outcome of the flight. All 229
people on the plane were killed.
</P>
<P>
   The part of the air traffic control communications that was
released on Tuesday begins with the pilots, about half an hour out
of Kennedy International Airport in New York, using standard
language to introduce the aircraft to a controller at a
high-altitude control center in Moncton, New Brunswick, as Swissair
one-eleven heavy. (Heavy means any plane over 300,000 pounds, and
warns the controller not to put a following plane in the heavy
plane's wake.)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Everything proceeds normally until one of the pilots says the
flight is ``declaring Pan Pan Pan,'' sign of an urgent problem,
about 10:14 p.m. local time. The pilot _ no one knows yet if it was
the captain or the first officer _ says he wants to go to ``a
convenient place, I guess Boston.'' Controllers limit each altitude
to planes going in a single direction, and the controller clears
the Swissair flight to descend from 33,000 feet to 31,000, an
altitude appropriate for traffic headed to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty seconds after Swissair's initial call, the controller,
with a much better idea of the MD-11's location, says, ``Uh, would
you prefer to go into Halifax,'' which is about as close to an
order as an air traffic controller gives a plane in trouble, and
thirty seconds later, Swissair accepts the suggestion.
``Speedbird,'' a call sign for a supersonic Concorde, is listening
in, and the British Air crew supplies Swissair with weather
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Amid what is undoubtedly a very heavy workload in the cockpit,
the Swissair pilot has to ask twice for the wind direction and the
radio frequency for the instrument landing system at Halifax.
</P>
<P>
   An open question for investigators is whether the plane could
have begun dumping fuel earlier, to get the plane's weight down to
the recommended maximum for landing, or should have bothered
dumping at all, if it delayed a landing. In Canada, Gerden said on
Tuesday evening, planes may dump fuel if they are above 2,000 feet
above ground level, and the plane need not have circled the water
to do this.
</P>
<P>
   In a moment of apparent miscommunication, the pilot gets an
answer, but not to his question. When the pilot asks, ``We, uh,
must dump some fuel. May we do that in this area during descent?''
the controller does not immediately answer, but asks if the plane
can turn left or right for a previously-discussed circle to lose
altitude. The pilot says, ``we are able for a left or right turn
towards the south to dump,'' a course that will take them out to
sea.
</P>
<P>
   The controller tells them they will be over the coast in 10
miles, and that they should advise him when they are ready to dump.
The pilot does not say he is beginning dumping until almost three
minutes later, at which time the controller tells him, ``Just a
couple of miles I'll be right with you,'' and thirty seconds after
that, the controller tells the crew to begin dumping.
</P>
<P>
   Another telling moment is when a pilot has evidently keyed the
microphone for transmission to the ground while discussing with the
other pilot, in German, whether they are performing the emergency
checklist for smoke, a confusion equivalent to trying to carry on
two telephone conversations simultaneously and putting the wrong
one on hold.
</P>
<P>
   While they were conducting these communications with the ground,
the crew had a choice of detailed checklists for dealing with
smoke. The procedure they discussed among themselves was for smoke
from an air-conditioning system, and the procedure is to increase
the airflow rate to maximum. If that does not help, the crew is
supposed to turn off one air-conditioning pack and run the other,
and if that does not solve the problem, reverse the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   For removing smoke of unknown origin, the procedure is to turn
off the galley equipment, and if that does not help, rotate a
switch to turn off one third of the plane's circuits at a time.
</P>
<P>
   To remove fumes from a cockpit, the procedure is to increase
ventilation, descend to 12,000 feet, slow down and depressurize the
aircraft. Then the pilots are supposed to open one of their two
cockpit windows. In the MD-11 cockpit, those slide sideways on a
track, and are big enough for a pilot to crawl through, as happened
in an accident last year at Newark International Airport in which a
plane flipped upside down on the runway.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the instructions are to land at the nearest suitable
airport.
</P>
<P>
   The cockpit voice recorder, whose pings were still heard on
Tuesday, is likely to give investigators more information on the
plane's condition. And the cockpit itself is a crucial goal for the
investigators. They are expecting the arrival of the U.S. Navy
salvage ship Grapple on Wednesday; a veteran of the TWA 800
recovery effort, it should begin work later this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
