<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4621 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-FUNDRAISING-     09-08 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FUNDRAISING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO ORDERS 90-DAY INQUIRY INTO WHETHER CAMPAIGN ADS ILLEGALLY
AIDED CLINTON
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Incorporates previous copy; subs top for rewriting)   (sw) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Advancing a pivotal step toward the possible
appointment of an independent prosecutor to investigate campaign
finance abuses, Attorney General Janet Reno ordered a 90-day
inquiry on Tuesday into whether President Clinton circumvented
federal election laws in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Reno's decision marked the third time in less than two weeks
that the Justice Department has begun a 90-day independent-counsel
inquiry into allegations of possible election improprieties _ this
one into whether Clinton illegally benefited from Democratic
advertisements during the presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the other two investigations, this one named Clinton
as the subject of the inquiry, and is potentially the most
far-reaching because it goes to the heart of the Democrats'
fund-raising strategy.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement to the three-judge panel that supervises
independent counsel matters, Reno said that she had begun a
preliminary investigation ``involving President of the United
States William Jefferson Clinton concerning political
advertisements during the 1996 election cycle.''
</P>
<P>
   The new inquiry centers on whether Clinton and White House aides
coordinated an advertising campaign to benefit Clinton's
re-election, in an improper effort to violate federal spending
limits that he agreed to follow when he accepted taxpayer financing
for his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Reno initiated the 90-day review based on the preliminary
findings of an Federal Election Commission audit last month. The
audit concluded that the Democratic National Committee evaded
federal spending limits by funneling $42 million dollars to state
parties for ads that were thinly-veiled messages on behalf of the
Clinton-Gore re-election campaign. The audit determined that the
ads, commonly called issue ads, should have been counted under
spending limits imposed on the president's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The other two outstanding inquiries focus on Vice President Al
Gore's statements about his telephone fund-raising calls and on
possible perjury by Harold Ickes, a former deputy White House chief
of staff, concerning his dealings with the Teamsters union. By the
end of the 90-day period for each investigation, Reno is required
by law to decide whether to seek the appointment of an outside
counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's lawyer, David Kendall, said on Tuesday that the
Democrats' ads were lawful. ``Each Clinton-Gore ad was reviewed by
counsel at the president's request, to assure the ad's legality,
and approved prior to broadcast,'' he said. ``When the Department
of Justice's review process finally concludes, it will determine
that the Clinton-Gore ads were entirely proper.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Sandler, the general counsel for the Democratic National
Committee, said the ads were legal and no different in tone than
ads financed by Republicans for their party. ``We expect that this
fuller examination will demonstrate conclusively that the DNC
followed the letter and spirit of the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno has reviewed the legality of the issue ads on at least
three separate occasions over the last two years, but each time
went no further than a 30-day initial review of the allegations,
which were first raised in late 1996 by Common Cause, the public
interest group.
</P>
<P>
   In each instance, Reno found no wrongdoing, saying she lacked
specific and credible of evidence that a crime had been committed
by any of the high-level officials, like the president, who are
covered by the law.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials said on Tuesday that the audit report
provided few new facts about the conduct of Clinton or any other
official but was highly significant in persuading Reno to launch
the inquiry. The agency's audit marked the first time that the
Federal Election Commission investigators had ever questioned the
legality of the content of the ads in a manner that allowed the
Justice Department to assert its criminal jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some government officials, including those who favor an
independent prosecutor, said that it could be difficult to define a
specific prosecutable offense in this area. And they added,
Clinton's campaign embarked on the issue ads on the basis of
extensive legal advice that the activities were legal _ a
potentially strong defense that could quickly thwart any effort to
consider a prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   In her action on Tuesday, Reno moved to a stage of deliberations
that could lead her to seek the appointment of an independent
prosecutor. Her decision on Tuesday gives the Justice Department
three months to determine whether there are reasonable grounds to
believe that Clinton broke the law. If so, Reno has no choice but
to refer the case to an independent prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly nervous in recent days, Democrats have expressed
fears about what an investigation of the issue ads might mean. An
independent counsel investigation of Clinton's role in the
advertisements, which were a central thrust of the president's
campaign, could evolve into exactly the kind of wide-ranging
criminal inquiry that Republican lawmakers have demanded from the
outset and which, thus far, Reno has resisted.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Reno has seemed willing to reconsider her
position, based on what her aides said was newly unearthed
information or in the case of the issue ads, information that was
recently provided by another agency.
</P>
<P>
   Some of her Republican critics suggested that the attorney
general had reversed herself because of an outcry after Charles La
Bella, the former head of the Justice Department's campaign finance
unit, sent her a report urging her to seek the appointment of an
independent prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, and chairman of the Senate Judiciary
Committee, said Reno's action was a positive, but incomplete step.
``Until we have a broad-based independent counsel investigation, we
will only be looking at the loose threads of the scandal and not
the most serious alleged violations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., and chairman of the Governmental
Affairs Committee, which investigated campaign finance issues last
year, said Reno should ask the three-judge panel to appoint an
independent prosecutor immediately. ``While it appears the attorney
general is inching toward doing what she should've done almost two
years ago, there is no reason to take another 90 days to further
belabor the obvious,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
