<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4623 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-PROFILE-C     09-08 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-PROFILE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mark McGwire: A profile
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Mark McGwire is physically imposing _ 6 feet 5, 250
pounds, with huge hands, a large trunk and powerful arms. Add the
scruffy red beard and the fact that he doesn't smile a lot, and
it's easy to imagine McGwire as a major-league baseball ruffian.
</P>
<P>
   Looks can be deceiving.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's sensitive side has caused his emotions to overflow on
numerous occasions during his historic chase. He cries when he
talks about family. He cries when he talks about Babe Ruth and
Roger Maris. He cries when he talks about the St. Louis fans, who
welcomed him with open arms last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what people know now is just how great a guy he is,''
said Mike Shannon, a Cardinals announcer and former player. ``He is
so genuine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What you see with Mark is what you get,'' teammate Ron Gant
said. ``There is no show there, no trying to say and do the right
things. As soon as he came over here, we all knew how he would fit
in. He's like a brother.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire might be the most modest of all sports heroes. While
Michael Jordan constantly sells himself off the court and
appreciates the limelight, McGwire would rather sit at home with
his 10-year-old son, Matt. McGwire, nicknamed Big Mac, has turned
his back on most endorsements, most notably McDonald's, which would
be a natural fit. McGwire doesn't eat the sandwich, and he thinks
it would be hypocritical to endorse it.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire gives $1 million a year to the cause of abused children
and constantly participates in public-service advertisements. He
was doing just that on Thursday, when the Cardinals had one of
their rare off days. Most players involved in such a
pressure-cooker probably would have relaxed at home.
</P>
<P>
   He is extremely close to his son, who often serves as the
Cardinals' batboy. McGwire's contract stipulates that his son can
travel with the Cardinals any time he wishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk all the time,'' McGwire told Sports Illustrated. ``We
talk about everything. If there's one thing I have learned, you
have to talk. We talk so much that sometimes we don't even use
words. We just look at each other and know what the other is
thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire is divorced from Matt's mother, Kathy, and Matt does not
live with his father. But in the offseason, Mark returns to his
home in Orange County, Calif., five minutes from his son. In fact,
McGwire has become good friends with his ex-wife's new husband, Tom
Williamson, and on many days in the offseason Mark, Tom and Matt
can be seen together on the golf course.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask me, `How do you compete with a guy like that?'
Williamson told Sports Illustrated. ``I always answer, `You don't.'
I don't have to. Mark's such a great guy.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire also has been a great ambassador for baseball. He gives
away jerseys, caps and gloves. When he goes into each town, he
spends time signing for players from the other clubhouse. When he
was in Atlanta last month, he faced a roomful of memorabilia to
sign. He signed everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is always asking Mark for stuff,'' Gant said.
``That's just the nature of this business. If you play for the
Cardinals, people ask you, `Can you get McGwire to sign something?'
He always does it.''
</P>
<P>
   And this city loves him for it. Not since the days of Stan
Musial has St. Louis adored a player as much as it does McGwire. He
probably will finish his career here, after signing a new contract
before the season. Even Musial looks up to McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been great for this city,'' said Musial, who spends a
lot of time at the ballpark. ``What he has done for St. Louis and
the rest of this country has been incredible. And he hasn't changed
at all through it. Years from now, people will talk about Mark
being one of the greatest.''
</P>
<P>
   On and off the field.
</P>
<P>
   PERSONAL
</P>
<P>
   _ Born: Oct. 1, 1963 in Pomona, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   _ Personal: Divorced with one son, Matt, 10. One of his four
brothers, Dan, played quarterback in the NFL with Seahawks and
Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   _ Size: 6 feet 5, 250 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   _ High school: Damien in Claremont, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   _ College: Southern California, where he was named college
player of year in 1984 after hitting 32 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Olympics: Member of U.S. team in 1984 Games in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   _ Draft: Taken by Oakland A's in first round of 1984 draft (10th
pick overall).
</P>
<P>
   _ Honors: American League Rookie of the Year in 1987 with
Oakland. Won AL Gold Glove in 1990. Named Sportsman of the Year by
the Sporting News in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   _ All-Star Games: Selected to AL team nine times and National
League team once.
</P>
<P>
   _ World Series: Played with Oakland in three straight World
Series (1988-90).
</P>
<P>
   _ Transactions: Traded from Oakland to St. Louis for pitchers
T.J. Mathews, Eric Ludwick and Blake Stein on July 31, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
