<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0373 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4624 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-SEASON-CO     09-08 1766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-SEASON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    After long-running battle with Sosa, McGwire finally won race to
62
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The chase is over: Someone finally hit 62.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-seven seasons after Roger Maris passed Babe Ruth, Mark
McGwire is the new single-season home run king.
</P>
<P>
   In a magical season that transfixed baseball, McGwire started
fast, then found himself in a home-run duel with Sammy Sosa, before
finally claiming the stage for himself.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's magic homer came Tuesday, one day after he tied the
record. Now he looks to set his own standard. Could it be 65, or
even 70?
</P>
<P>
   But first, a look back.
</P>
<P>
   The homer on Monday that tied Maris was almost as special as the
one that broke the record. It was a blistering first-inning shot
off Cubs veteran Mike Morgan that crashed off the restaurant window
just inside the left-field pole and landed some 430 feet from the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   Legendary baseball voice Jack Buck, the Cardinals' radio
announcer, made the call:
</P>
<P>
   ``Swing and look at there! Look-a there! Look-a there! McGwire's
No. 61! McGwire's Flight 61 headed for Planet Maris.''
</P>
<P>
   After McGwire hit it, he threw both arms into the air as he
watched the ball land. He rounded first and bumped forearms with
Cubs first baseman Mark Grace and did the same at third with former
teammate Gary Gaetti. Sosa stood in right field, smiling and
clapping. After rounding third, McGwire pointed at the the sky, at
what he calls ``The Man Upstairs,'' then crossed home plate. He
popped on-deck hitter Ray Lankford in the stomach and lifted his
son Mathew, serving as a batboy, and hugged him.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't finished. He pointed to the fans, to his father, John,
who had turned 61 that day, and to the family of Maris, thumping
his heart and saying, ``Roger's with me.'' Then he saluted his
team's owners and took a curtain call.
</P>
<P>
   In the left-field stands, a 28-year-old catering worker
retrieved the ball. The man, who attended the game only because his
brother-in-law had to work, gave the ball to McGwire without asking
for any money.
</P>
<P>
   With the record-tying homer in the books, the dream became
complete the next night with No. 62. And more than two weeks remain
in the magical season.
</P>
<P>
   THE BEGINNING
</P>
<P>
   The season opened with McGwire as the focus. He had slugged 58
homers the season before, and many experts and fans thought he
could be the one to break Maris' record, especially in an expansion
year, when pitching would be diluted.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't waste any time. On Opening Day, the last day of March,
he hit a grand slam, the first for a Cardinal in a season opener.
At 360 feet, it was not a typical McGwire shot; only three all
season would be shorter.
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, no special attention went to Sammy Sosa. The Cubs
rightfielder had hit 36 homers in 1997, and most baseball people
thought that if anyone would chase Maris along with McGwire it
would be Seattle's Ken Griffey Jr., who hit 56 homers last season.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire hit 10 home runs in April. Three came against the
expansion Arizona Diamondbacks on April 14, the third time in his
career that he had hit three in a game. Eight of his opening-month
homers came with the team tied or behind. His 32 RBIs in April tied
the NL record set by Barry Bonds in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa's first homer came on April 4, one of six for the month.
Griffey hit 10. The race was on.
</P>
<P>
   A BIG MAC MAY
</P>
<P>
   McGwire kept turning heads in May. His 545-foot home run on May
16 against the Marlins was the longest ever hit at Busch Stadium in
St. Louis. The next night they put a giant Band-Aid over the dent
in the sign in center field. ``That was the best ball I've ever
hit,'' McGwire said. ``I don't think I could have hit it better.''
Marlins coach Rich Donnelly said, ``I saw people in the upper deck
ducking.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire also hit his 400th career homer, becoming the fastest of
26 players to reach that milestone. He went deep eight times in
seven days, hit 16 homers in the month and finished May with 27.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa continued to hit homers on his usual pace. His seven in May
gave him 13 for the first two months but left him 14 behind
McGwire. Griffey had 18.
</P>
<P>
   As in the season before, it was McGwire and Griffey. But Sosa
was about to get hot. Very hot.
</P>
<P>
   HERE COMES SAMMY
</P>
<P>
   McGwire remained consistent in June. On the 27th of the month,
he hit his 36th homer in the club's 79th game. It put him 31 games
ahead of Babe Ruth's pace to 60 in 1927 and 13 games ahead of
Maris' 61 in 1961. McGwire hit another on the 30th, but it would be
his last homer for 11 days.
</P>
<P>
   The media attention was growing daily, and the Cardinals set up
special press conferences for McGwire. The strain was beginning to
show, and McGwire refused to answer questions about his homers on
nights that the Cardinals lost.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa hit two homers on June 2nd after sitting out the previous
three games with a swollen thumb. Then he homered in five straight
games, giving him 11 in his last 10 games and 20 for the season. On
the 15th, he smashed three, and on June 20 he hit his 20th homer in
his last 21 games.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa finished with 20 home runs in June, a major-league record
for any month, and drove in 40 runs. He was back in the home-run
chase with 33, just three behind McGwire. But Sosa said, ``It's
McGwire who's going to break the record. He's the man.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey also had a good June, hitting 14 to give him 32. It was
a three-man race, but not for long.
</P>
<P>
   ALL STAR BLUES
</P>
<P>
   In July, baseball wondered how
</P>
<P>
   McGwire would be affected by his failure in the Home Run Derby
at the All-Star Game. With millions watching, he was eliminated in
the first round, and as the second half started, some people
thought it might affect his swing. It didn't.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's first July homer came four days after the game. He hit
two the next day, including his 40th. Five days later, he hit his
42nd, setting a record for the most homers by the end of July,
sending him past Jimmie Foxx and Babe Ruth. McGwire finished July
with 45 homers.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa trailed McGwire by five home runs most of the month. But he
made a run at McGwire beginning on the 28th. After a nine-year
grand slam drought, he hit the first two of his career on
consecutive nights. He finished the month with 42, three behind
McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey, however, was struggling. He hit just eight in July to
drop out of the race and would get only six in August.
</P>
<P>
   A WILD AUGUST
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, coming on hard, hit six homers in 11 games. When the Cubs
and Cardinals met on the 8th, McGwire led off the fifth inning with
his 46th of the season, but Sosa later tied the game with his 44th.
</P>
<P>
   On the 11th against the Giants, Sosa actually caught McGwire
with his 46th. But a few innings later, McGwire hit his 47th,
against the Mets, breaking Hack Wilson's record for the most home
runs before Sept. 1. With the Cubs and Cardinals playing on Aug.
19, Sosa tied McGwire again and actually led the race for a few
innings after he hit his 48th. But McGwire came back less then an
hour later and tied him.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 20 in New York, McGwire became the first player in
major-league history to connect for 50 or more homers three seasons
in a row. Setting that record and reaching that milestone seemed to
relax McGwire: ``I can eat. I can sleep. I am having a great
time,'' he said. ``I wish everyone could experience what I am going
through.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa hit his 50th and 51st homers on the 23rd. Three days later
he hit his 52nd, his third-inning homer leaving him two behind
McGwire and giving him a streak of 13 consecutive series with a
homer.
</P>
<P>
   Then McGwire had to face his biggest off-the-field controversy
of the season. He acknowledged that he had been taking
Androstenedione, an over-the-counter supplement. Some people said
they thought the drug usage, while legal in baseball, would tarnish
the record if McGwire reached it. But McGwire said, ``Making
something out of nothing -- that has been my statement the whole
time. There are people across America laughing at what the media
has done with this thing. It's absolutely nothing. It's a
supplement.''
</P>
<P>
   A bigger problem for McGwire's home-run total was running into
the Braves. Atlanta pitching had shut down McGwire for most of the
season, and starting on the 27th, he was having problems again. On
the 29th, he was thrown out in the first inning for arguing a
called third strike. Fans at Busch Stadium went crazy, throwing
baseballs and debris on the field and booing for several innings.
</P>
<P>
   But the next night, McGwire started his final assault on Maris.
Against 244-game-winner Dennis Martinez, he drove a 500-foot shot
over the center field wall at Busch. It would be the first of five
homers in his next 12 at-bats. He and Sosa both ended the month at
55.
</P>
<P>
   REACHING MARIS AND BEYOND
</P>
<P>
   McGwire started off September with a pair of two-homer games in
Florida. On the first day of the month, he tied and then broke
Wilson's 68-year-old National League record with this 56th and
57th. On the 2nd, Sosa was able to get within one with a home run
against the Reds, but later that night, McGwire poked two -- to get
within one of Ruth -- and said, ``Quite amazing, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   Both teams were off the next day, preparing for the holiday
weekend. A television-shopping network offered $250,000 to the fan
catching the record-breaking ball.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire came home for a three-game weekend series against the
Reds. Seats in the left-field bleachers were the hot ticket, with
fans wanting a chance to catch history.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire seemed a little tense going into Friday night's game,
canceling his pregame press conference with the media ``to get his
head straight.'' It was a long night. Sosa fared better in
Pittsburgh, hitting his 57th.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday was better for Mcwire. In the first inning, he tied
Babe Ruth with No. 60 on a fastball from the Reds' Dennis Reyes and
pulled within one swing of Roger Maris. McGwire spent most of the
postgame news conference talking about Ruth. ``I wish I could go
back in time and meet him,'' he said. ``When I pass away, I want to
meet him and find out what he was really like.'' Later that night
in Pittsburgh, Sosa climbed to No. 58 with a sixth-inning shot off
the Pirates Sean Lawrence.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, neither went deep, although McGwire came very close,
missing by just 7 feet on a foul ball hit in his third at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, however, with McGwire and Sosa on the same field,
McGwire would tie Maris and his 37-year-old record.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
