</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ILLINOIS-MOSELEY-BRAUN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMBATTLED SENATOR ACCUSES CRITIC OF RACISM 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Sen. Carol Moseley-Braun's re-election bid took an
emotional turn when she angrily lost her composure during a Labor
Day event and used a racial epithet to characterize herself as a
target of racism.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to criticism of her personal and political conduct in
a nationally syndicated column written by George Will,
Moseley-Braun said, ``I think because he could not say `nigger,' he
said the word `corrupt.''' (The word ``corrupt'' never actually
appeared in the column.)
</P>
<P>
   She also said, ``George Will can just take his hood and go back
to wherever he came from.''
</P>
<P>
   The senator apologized for the outburst several hours later.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my anger, I lost my temper and used language that was not
appropriate,'' she said in a statement. ``I am sorry. For more than
five years, I've endured baseless charges and reckless insinuations
that were intended to divert attention from my solid record of
accomplishment as a United States Senator.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an episode that seemed to underscore how sensitive
Moseley-Braun is to ethical questions that have been raised for
years about her financial practices before and during her 1992
campaign and about a 1996 meeting she had with Nigeria's brutal
dictator, Sani Abacha, who died this year.
</P>
<P>
   And it comes during a tough re-election battle for
Moseley-Braun, the first African-American woman in the Senate, as
she tries to hold on to what Democratic leaders consider one of the
party's most vulnerable Senate seats.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls have suggested that Moseley-Braun, who was swept
into office in 1992, is in an insecure position for an incumbent,
especially in a year when many incumbents are expected to do well.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a poll conducted by The Chicago Tribune found
Moseley-Braun trailing her opponent, State Sen. Peter Fitzgerald,
39 percent to 46 percent, with a margin of error of four percentage
points. It also showed that women, who supported her overwhelmingly
in 1992, were sharply divided about her.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, a poll published in The St. Louis Post-Dispatch
showed Fitzgerald leading by 46 percent to 35 percent with a margin
of error of four points.
</P>
<P>
   There are other reasons why Moseley-Braun has a tough fight
ahead of her. One is expected low turnout, made potentially lower
by President Clinton's problems. Another is money.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald, a conservative from a wealthy banking family in the
northern suburbs of Chicago with an estimated net worth of $40
million, spent $6 million on the Republican primary and recently
embarked on a television advertising campaign expected to cost as
much as $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Moseley-Braun, on the other hand, pulled out of debt for the
first time last year. Her latest campaign filing shows her war
chest at $1 million, although her campaign consultant, Eric
Adelstein, said more was coming in.
</P>
<P>
   Will's column included a reprise of accusations that
Moseley-Braun and her former fiance and 1992 campaign manager,
Kgosie Matthews, spent tens of thousands of dollars on travel,
clothes, jewelry and stereo equipment. The Federal Election
Commission dropped its investigation of those accusations last
year, saying the reputed violations were not as serious as those in
other cases before the commission, that staff time was scarce and
that the statute of limitations might have run out.
</P>
<P>
   The column mentioned Moseley-Braun's trip, with Matthews, to
Nigeria to meet with Abacha, a visit that was criticized by the
State Department and members of her own party.
</P>
<P>
   Moseley-Braun has acknowledged in the past that she made
mistakes. She attributes some of her actions to naivete about the
scrutiny and attention a senator attracts.
</P>
<P>
   Some commentators suggested that Moseley-Braun deliberately
tried to draw attention to her race. Others said the remarks were
too emotional to be calculated. Tuesday, Moseley-Braun made further
efforts to diffuse the attention over her statements. She faxed a
letter of apology to Will saying, ``I should not have called your
motives into question.''
</P>
<P>
   Will responded with a hand-written note that referred to
something that has Chicago natives brimming with pride: the home
run crusade of Sammy Sosa of the Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apology accepted,'' Will wrote. ``Go Sammy!''
</P>
</TEXT>
