<SLUG> BC-BOXER-CLINTON-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOXER REBUKES CLINTON ON LEWINSKY MATTER 
</HEADLINE>
   By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ California Sen. Barbara Boxer, one of President
Clinton's staunchest allies, joined the growing ranks of Democrats
Tuesday to publicly denounce the president for his relationship
with Monica Lewinsky, calling it ``wrong and indefensible'' and
``immoral.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Boxer stopped short of calling for Clinton to resign or
be impeached, her comments on the Senate floor offered more
troubling evidence for Clinton that Democratic support is
collapsing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``The president has now agreed,'' said Boxer, whose daughter
was married to Hillary Rodham Clinton's brother in a White House
ceremony four years ago. ``I fervently wish he had seen it that way
before the relationship started, and in any case, he should have
taken responsibility much earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   Boxer's statement followed a stern rebuke issued in the same
venue last week by Sen. Joseph Lieberman, a Connecticut Democrat
and longtime Clinton confidant, that was supported by Daniel
Patrick Moynihan of New York and Bob Kerrey of Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   ``It demonstrates two things,'' said Larry Sabato, a political
scientist at the University of Virginia. ``How much trouble Barbara
Boxer is in, and how much trouble Bill Clinton is in.''
</P>
<P>
   Boxer is in dead-even race to hold her Senate seat this November
against Republican challenger Matt Fong. Political analysts now
rank Boxer as one of the two most vulnerable Democratic incumbents
in the Senate this November, along with Carol Moseley-Braun of
Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   The Lewinsky affair put Boxer in a particularly tight spot. She
won election to the Senate six years ago largely as a champion of
women's rights and has made it a centerpiece of political career.
In comparison to her high-profile role during the confirmation
hearings of Supreme Court Justice Clarence Thomas and the move to
oust former Oregon Sen. Bob Packwood, a Republican, her subdued
reaction to the Clinton matter has not gone unnoticed by her
critics.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Boxer tried to walk a fine line, drawing a distinction
between personal morality and what she called ``public policy
morality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I will always be grateful to (Clinton) for his visionary
public policies in so many areas, and so will the people of
California,'' said Boxer, who signaled her support for Lieberman's
speech, as well as the president's response to it, at a campaign
stop in California on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe there are differences in this body about the
immorality of the president's relationship with an intern,'' but
the Senate's agenda should also ``deal with public policy
morality,'' she said, citing proposed legislation on health
maintenance organizations, after-school programs and other
Democratic issues.
</P>
<P>
   Fong swiftly issued a press release cataloging a long list of
Boxer's public statements on sexual harassment, contrasting her
strident tone during the Thomas hearings and the Navy's
``Tailhook'' scandal to her reaction to Paula Jones' allegations
against Clinton, which Boxer said should be handled by the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer said she decided to come forward after supporters on the
campaign trail told her they understood she needed to address the
Lewinsky matter while expressing concern that no one was addressing
public policy issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this shows is we need to allow the process to move
forward and be very clear in our disapproval, and yet work with
this president for the good of the people,'' said Boxer. ``That's
the message.''
</P>
<P>
   As more details of the impending report by independent counsel
Kenneth Starr continue to leak out, Boxer's statement was among the
many signs that discontent among Democrats is snowballing.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina Sen. Fritz Hollings, another Democrat in a
difficult re-election bid, joined Boxer Tuesday. ``We're fed up,''
Hollings said. ``The behavior, the dishonesty of the president is
unacceptable, and we'll see with the report what course the
Congress will take.''
</P>
<P>
   And over the weekend, Maryland Governor Parris Glendening, also
in a tight re-election bid, canceled an Oct. 2 fund-raiser with
Clinton, turning down what originally was hoped to be a boost of
hundreds of thousands of dollars to his campaign coffers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are starting to focus on the details (of the report),''
Sabato said, ``and whatever your views of Bill Clinton, the details
are truly disgusting.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has called for a closed-door meeting with congressional
Democrats Wednesday, but the impending Starr report, coming on the
heels of Clinton's combative televised apology, is making it
difficult for members to rally to his defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Folks want to see what's in the Starr report as quickly as
possible, but what they hear about what's in the report only
amplifies their worst nightmares,'' said a Senate Republican
leadership aide. ``No one up for re-election wants to stand before
the public every day and every night between now and November and
be faced with one of three choices: defending the president,
condemning the president, or the worst of all worlds, which Barbara
Boxer tried to live in for three weeks, which is essentially to say
nothing and try to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   California Field Poll director Mark DiCamillo said Boxer has
lost support from Republican women from six years ago, when she ran
as a fighter for women's rights. ``That has given way to a much
more partisan view of Boxer,'' DiCamillo said. ``It doesn't seem
she's able to attract females across the aisle.''
</P>
<P>
   But California Democratic Party campaign adviser Bob Mulholland
scoffed at the notion that the Lewinsky scandal is having any
repercussions in California.
</P>
<P>
   The fallout is ``zero'' Mulholland said, citing polls that say
76 percent of the public thinks Clinton should serve out his term.
``Only the Republicans who are spinning it and most of the
reporters who can't help themselves think there's a fallout from an
American president being a human with mistakes,'' Mulholland said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
