<HEADLINE>
LERNER WINS OWNERSHIP OF CLEVELAND BROWNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Lerner, the favorite from day one to end up with the NFL
expansion franchise, made the Cleveland Browns the most exepensive
team in the sports history Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Lerner, who made billions in the credit card business, withstood
four ballots before the NFL owners finally voted him into their
exclusive club.
</P>
<P>
   The battle for ownership of the Cleveland franchise, which will
field a team in 1999 in the AFC, came down to Lerner and Chuck
Dolan, who made his fortune in cable television.
</P>
<P>
   The owners met in Chicago Tuesday afternoon and were informed by
the New York investment firm of Goldman Sachs that Lerner and Dolan
were the two top bidders in a field that originally numbered seven.
Three dropped out last week, including Jerry Jacobs, onwer of the
Boston Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining four submitted their final offers over the
weekend. By rule, 23 of the 30 owners needed to vote in favor of
the franchise recipient. Even though Lerner was the high man with a
bid of $530 million, it took four ballots for him to win the day.
In the end, Art Modell, the former Cleveland owner, asked his
fellow owners to make Lerner a unanimous choice. All voted in
favor, except Oakland's Al Davis.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that Modell was the most anti-Lerner owner in the
room. But once it became obvious that his candidate, Dolan, could
not win, Modell moved for Lerner.
</P>
<P>
   Lerner's victory _ for a price that dwarfs the previous sports
franchise record, the $350 million Rupert Murdoch paid for the Los
Angeles Dodgers this year _ means that Carmen Policy, former
president and general manager of the San Francisco 49ers, will
assume the top team management role under Lerner. Policy left the
Niners last month in a dispute with owner Eddie DeBartolo and cast
his lot with Lerner.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, when the NFL expanded to Carolina and
Jacksonville, the cost for those two teams was about $200 million.
Tampa Bay later sold for about the same price.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay owner Malcolm Glazier, along with Davis and Jerry
Jones of Dallas, had all said publicly that the Browns should sell
for $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   However, last week the guessing was that the final price would
be $500 milllion-$600 million. Some $54 million of this money will
go toward paying for cost overruns in the construction of the
football stadium being completed in downtown Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Lerner is not a popular choice in Cleveland. He is considered a
traitor by many Browns fans because he helped Modell move the
former NFL franchise out of town to Baltimore three years ago.
Later Modell and Lerner had a falling out, but this still did not
appease many of the Cleveland fans.
</P>
<P>
   But he is the man now, and with Policy, a proven winner at the
helm, a very generous draft package (two players in every round for
two yeras) and some $33 million to spend on free agents, the new
Browns should have a good team in quick order.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 2151EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0379 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4634 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FED-ANALYSIS-BOS &LR;      09-08 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS LATCH ONTO FED'S HINT OF RATE CUTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER G. GOSSELIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If global investors had their way, Alan Greenspan
would head a planetary central bank, not just an American one.
</P>
<P>
   In a measure of their desparation for economic leadership in a
newly treacherous world, investors from Tokyo to New York have sent
stock prices flying in the wake of a Friday speech by the Federal
Reserve chairman suggesting that the US central bank is now deeply
concerned about financial troubles aboard, and might cut US
interest rates if problems persist.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that investors' reaction is especially striking
because of how little Greenspan actually said; how little most
expect him to do quickly, and how little difference whatever he
does is likely to make beyond US borders.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are reading too much into the speech,'' said Edgar E.
Peters, chief investment strategist for PanAgora Asset Management
in Boston, which manages $17 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, suggested Peters and others, the global rally Monday
and Tuesday _ which was already being dubbed ``the Greenspan
rebound'' _ was less a measure of the Fed's awesome powers than it
was a gauge of the near total lack of leadership by the world's
major economies in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time, there's a government policy group that
seems to be watching out for trouble before it happens, and that's
the Fed,'' said Peters. ``That kind of vigilence is a rare
commodity in this crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Alan Greenspan is the world's economic leadership at the
moment,'' added Mickey D. Levy, chief economist with Nationsbanc
Montgomery Securities in New York.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the surge in stock markets worldwide makes some
sense given what Greenspan said. An interest rate cut by the Fed
would spur the US economy and, along with it, US imports. Greater
imports could help damaged economies in Asia and elsewhere sell
their way out of their problems.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts said that the dimensions of the runup went far
beyond what the central banker's remarks warrant. For example, in
Toyko, the bellwether Nikkei 225 stock average jumped 747.15
points, or 5.3 percent Monday, and was on the rise again last
night. Stocks soared 23 percent in Maylasia. With the exception of
London, virtually every European market was up.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the most complex financial crisis that we've
seen since the Cold War'' and there is only so much the Fed can do
about it, said Richard B. Berner, chief economist with Mellon Bank
in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Greenspan warned that the United States could not
continue growing in the face of global troubles, and said that the
central bank is now as concerned about those troubles as it is
about its traditonal foe, inflation. He hinted that the Fed might
cut interest rates to ensure continued US growth.
</P>
<P>
   But most analysts said Tuesday that they do not expect an
interest rate reduction until later this year at the earliest, and
even then only if the global crisis has clearly spilled over into
the United States. To date, most effects of the crisis here have
been two-edged, for example, hurting US exporters, but helping
consumers with cheaper imports and lower market interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``If investors are looking for instant gratification, they're
not going to get it,'' said Edward F. McKelvey, a senior economist
with Goldman Sachs in New York.
</P>
<P>
   If and when, the Fed does cut rates, the reduction is likely to
be modest and aimed at protecting US growth, not repairing global
economic damage. ``I don't know whether they can insulate the US
from all of the major risks, but they certainly can't insulate the
world,'' McKelvey said.
</P>
<P>
   A Fed rate cut ``is not going to solve very many of the world's
problems,'' said Lyle Gramley, a former governor of the central
bank who is now a senior economist with the Mortgage Bankers
Association in Washington, D.C. ``It's not going to help Russia.
It's not going to help Japan,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the fact that financial markets reacted so
enthusiastically to Greenspan's remarks despite the limits of Fed
powers signals how much investors and ordinary citizens around the
world are looking for economic leadership, but have yet to find it.
</P>
<P>
   Although the major economies offered some leadership in the
early stages of the Asian crisis last year, their chief instrument
of influence, the International Monetary Fund, is widely seen as
discredited after its austerity policies failed to stem the spread
of trouble. Since then, a series of unrelated political upheavals,
including the Monica Lewinksy scandals here, have sapped Western
leaders of much of their ability to act.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
