u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MARIS-Q&AMP;A-COX     09-08 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MARIS-Q&AMP;A-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Maris liked to keep low profile
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   His son, Kevin, said Roger Maris would be looking down and
``watching every swing'' as St. Louis Cardinals' first baseman Mark
McGwire broke his father's single-season home run record of 61.
Maris, an outfielder with the New York Yankees, set the record
during the 1961 season. Here are some facts about Maris:
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who was Roger Maris?
</P>
<P>
   A: Maris played in the major leagues with four teams,1957-68 and
was the American League's Most Valuable Player in 1960 and '61, his
first two years with the New York Yankees. He played his last two
seasons with the St. Louis Cardinals. Maris, who was born in
Hibbing, Minn., and grew up in Fargo, N.D., signed with the
Cleveland Indians after graduating from high school, where he also
had been a football standout.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How old was he when he broke Babe Ruth's record?
</P>
<P>
   A: Maris was 27.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is Maris in the Hall of Fame?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. Most baseball writers say that they think that Maris had
a Hall of Fame season in 1961 but not a Hall of Fame career. In 12
seasons, Maris compiled a .260 batting average. He hit 275 home
runs. Although Maris is not in the Hall of Fame, both the ball he
hit for No. 61 and the bat he used are in Cooperstown.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How close was he to the end of the season when he hit No. 61?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. 61 came in the fourth inning on the final day of the 1961
regular season. His homer off rookie Tracy Stallard gave the
Yankees a 1-0 victory over the Boston Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did he hit a lot of home runs before the '61 season?
</P>
<P>
   A: Maris had hit 28 home runs in 1958 while playing for
Cleveland and Kansas City and 39 homers during the 1960 season with
the Yankees. He followed with 33 homers in 1962. The fence in
Yankee Stadium during Maris' playing days was 296 feet down the
right-field line. And Maris, a left-handed hitter, was a dead pull
hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How did the nation respond to his record-breaking season?
</P>
<P>
   A: Many baseball fans, and writers, did not want to see Babe
Ruth's record fall. If the record had to fall, most rooted for
Maris' teammate, Mickey Mantle. Maris was booed on the road and
sometimes at home.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was the deal with the asterisk?
</P>
<P>
   A: Ruth hit 60 homers when the length of the baseball season was
154 games. Maris hit 61 the first year baseball expanded to a
10-team American League and a 162-game schedule. Baseball
commissioner Ford Frick ruled in late July that Ruth's record would
stand unless it was broken during the first 154 games. The
figurative asterisk was removed in 1991 by then-commissioner Fay
Vincent. Maris, however, was not around to see it; he died Dec. 14,
1985, at the age of 51.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What kind of man was Maris?
</P>
<P>
   A: Maris, who was married and had six children, preferred to
keep a low profile and was comfortable playing in the shadows of
his more-famous teammates, including Mickey Mantle. ``I just want
to be a good ballplayer,'' Maris said. ``I just wanted to be one of
the guys.'' It was painful for Maris when he became the focus
during the run at Ruth's record. He often complained about the
pressure of being in the limelight.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
