<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4643 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-McGWIRE-COLLECTOR     09-08 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-McGWIRE-COLLECTOR-ART-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECORD ADDS VALUE TO A CARD COLLECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: BBO-MCGWIRE, BBO-McGWIRE-PROFILE, BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN,
BBO-McGWIRE-BALL-TAX.) 
(ART ADV: Photo of Wendy Levy Jackson being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Wendy Levy Jackson is a successful real estate broker,
but you can't blame her for tuning in every night for the latest on
Mark McGwire's quest to surpass Roger Maris as baseball's
single-season home run king.
</P>
<P>
   After all, she has about 3,000 McGwire baseball cards, part of
an unusual inheritance from her late husband, Stanley Jackson. And
she has another 500 or so of McGwire posing with Jose Canseco when
they were with the Oakland A's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time he'd hit another one, my friends would call and
congratulate me,'' said Jackson, who is 51. ``We were all rooting
for him. One of my friends said, `You would think he's my relative
or something.'''
</P>
<P>
   Knowing how Stanley Jackson, who died in March 1997, would have
reveled in McGwire's home run success this season, Wendy went to
the Mount Nebo-Levitt Weinstein Cemetery in South Miami-Dade, where
her late husband is buried, after McGwire had hit four out of Pro
Player Stadium last week in two games against the Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   She was there about four minutes when she heard someone softly
call her name. It was Howard Rosen, her husband's longtime friend,
who had gone to the cemetery for the same reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``We both appreciated how much he would have just loved this,''
Jackson said Tuesday, looking around her South Miami-Dade townhouse
at the impact McGwire had on her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Jackson had adopted McGwire as one of his favorite
players in a three-year frenzy of baseball-card collecting that
began in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a veterinarian by day and he did baseball cards by
night and weekends,'' she said. ``I watched him do it for a while,
then I figured I might as well get involved, and I'd go with him to
some of the card shows.''
</P>
<P>
   Through her husband, she became known in local baseball card
show circles as ``Ms. Mint,'' for having an abundance of mint
condition cards.
</P>
<P>
   Her most valuable cards now are squirreled away in safe-deposit
boxes, and her lesser ones fill a storeroom. She has cards of
McGwire in a variety of hitting poses, as well as him on defense.
She initially thought she had just 2,487 of McGwire, until she
found a 500-card album of him during various stages of his career
in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   His most valuable card, according to Rheal McMullen, owner of
Sports Cards USA in Sunrise, Fla., is No. 401 _ a 1985 Topps of
McGwire with the United States Olympic team before his first season
with the Oakland A's. This is McGwire's official rookie card.
</P>
<P>
   A rare mint condition card of that variety can bring $1,400,
according to McMullen. Lesser quality Topps '85's can bring between
$200 and $300, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said she has 148 of those cards, most of which are in
excellent condition. Ron Tannenbaum, who puts on baseball card
shows in South Florida, said the new rates are coming out later
this week, and he expects McGwire's cards to be ``about 50 percent
higher.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything with McGwire is going up,'' McMullen said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Waldo Rodriguez, who owns the Sports Card Center in the Little
Havana section of Miami, said most of his customers seek out
McGwire memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as cards, the rookie card is what everybody is looking
for,'' Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said she never asked her husband why he liked McGwire so
much, but he did leave a clue as to why he accumulated nearly
100,000 sports cards, 90 percent of them in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   A University of Florida journalism alumnus, he wrote this in an
alumni publication:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mick is middle-aged, The Duke of Flatbush has gray hair,
Stan The Man from St. Louis owns restaurants . . . and Billy Martin
is dead. How come, then, I still collect baseball cards? Because my
young son rekindled a former passion. Because I grew up with
baseball and I'll die with baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire was not the only player who was popular with Stanley
Jackson. He has about 3,000 of Wally Joyner's cards, because of his
son David's fondness for the current San Diego first baseman. He
also has ``untold boxes'' of Reggie Jackson, the former Oakland and
Yankees slugger.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson now would like to sell the whole collection at one time,
and has set up a separate phone number _ 305-981-7672 _ to do so.
She estimates that her husband invested between $50,000 and $60,000
in the cards, plus a big chunk of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything I do, I am going to be careful about it,'' she said.
``Stanley put his heart and soul into this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
