<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4646 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-HOWMANY-C     09-08 0484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-HOWMANY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    So, how many CAN he hit? Baseball writers wager guesses
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ When Roger Maris passed Babe Ruth for the
single-season home run record, he hit No. 61 on the last day of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire passed Maris on Tuesday during his club's 145th
game, leaving him 17 games and a host of chances to add to his
total.
</P>
<P>
   In asampling of baseball writers covering the event, some think
McGwire could hit as many as 70. At the current rate, based on a
162-game season, McGwire would finish with 69; Chicago's Sammy Sosa
would have 65, and Seattle's Ken Griffey Jr. would hit 56.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't see him hitting 70, but he could get to 68,'' said
Jerry Crasnick of the Bloomberg News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Sherman of the New York Post also thinks 68 is a reasonable
number. ``That means we can give him the goal of 70 next year,''
Sherman said.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa said he thinks McGwire can reach 70, which would be an
incredible standard considering that the most hit in the first 129
years of professional baseball was 61.
</P>
<P>
   The schedule favors McGwire. Houston is the only team remaining
on St. Louis' schedule that is involved in a playoff race. The
Cardinals have five games against the Astros. St. Louis ends its
season at home against Montreal, a team that continues to pitch a
very young rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like McGwire will be facing a lot of clubs where
Craig McMurtry would be their No. 1 starter,'' said Bud Shaw of the
Cleveland Plain Dealer. Shaw refers to the former Braves starter,
who was 9-17 for Atlanta in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Those surveyed also think Sosa will have no chance of catching
McGwire down the stretch. The Cubs are in the middle of an intense
wild card race, and Sosa cannot afford to swing for the fences
during every at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   Former Oakland teammate Jose Canseco, who plays for Toronto,
said he thinks McGwire has a good chance to break his own record
before his career ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to know him,'' Canseco said. ``He will come out next
season working as hard as he did this year and try to hit more.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no reason to think McGwire's numbers will drop. At age
34, he appears to be in the best shape of his career. This season,
he has played in his most games since 1991, when he appeared in 154
for the A's, and his production level has improved. He hit 39
homers in 1995, 52 in '96 and 58 last season.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Aaron hit 245 more homers after his 35th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire also wants to hit 500 home runs during his career. He is
at 448.
</P>
<P>
   But what may push McGwire the most is McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a lot of years left and he is in great shape,'' said
Cardinals manager Tony La Russa, who has been with McGwire since
his days in Oakland. ``He is going to hit a lot more homers.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
