<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BACK-TO-SCHOOL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYC SCHOOL YEAR BEGINS WITHOUT THE USUAL SENSE OF CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By JACQUES STEINBERG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The city's 1.1 million public school children begin
trudging back to class Wednesday to a system preoccupied with fewer
opening-day distractions than in any September in at least five
years but facing new pressures to convert this moment of relative
calm into lasting student achievement.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since 1983, the nation's largest school
district _ a system that has had 10 leaders in 15 years _ will open
its doors with a schools chancellor, Dr. Rudy Crew, who has made it
to his fourth school year.
</P>
<P>
   Crew pledged Tuesday that this year's first day would bear
little resemblance to those of the past, with new classrooms
actually completed and free of workmen before students arrive, a
teacher assigned to virtually every class, a desk reserved for
virtually every student (a function, in part, of slowing enrollment
growth) and an absence of the outside political rancor that drove
out Crew's two immediate predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   Whether class sizes will grow cannot be determined until the
year is under way, school officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But once the first-day jitters have come and gone, Crew said,
students, teachers and principals, as well as he himself, must push
themselves to meet standards higher than those of the past.
</P>
<P>
   High-school freshmen will have to start preparing now for a new
battery of stiff Regents exams that they will be required to pass
before they can graduate. Beginning this winter, fourth and eighth
graders will sit for new state standardized tests in reading and
mathematics.
</P>
<P>
   And everyone has been put on notice that the system intends to
begin holding back failing students in the fourth and seventh
grades in the next school year. (For the last two decades, only a
fraction of failing students have had to repeat a grade.)
</P>
<P>
   Threatening to undermine those efforts, however, are potentially
inflammatory tensions simmering below the surface.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, Crew and City Hall reached a tentative agreement to
expand the role of police in maintaining the safety of schools,
raising a host of unanswered questions about where the school
system's responsibility will end and the Police Department's will
begin, as well as whether the number of arrests in school buildings
will rise.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the very foundation of the system _ its buildings _
continues to crumble, with hundreds of schools in need of
long-delayed repairs to roofs, walls, floors and boilers, and a
capital budget that addresses only a fraction of the work.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis over the buildings' deterioration has been compounded
this year by a state mandate to find room for 14,000 4-year-olds
who have been enrolled in new prekindergarten programs. Tuesday,
school officials said that in the scramble for seats, they had yet
to find room for nearly 700 but hoped to do so by next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the first day of school for the nation's
largest district has been thick with an air of crisis, often real
and sometimes imagined _ the scouring of schools for asbestos in
September 1993, which delayed the start of the school year 11 days;
the bitter search for a new chancellor in the summer of 1995, which
spilled over into the first month of school; the desperate quest
for classroom space in the fall of 1996, when some students
streamed into newly constructed schools only to find carpenters
still installing windows and doors, and the sniping over school
conditions that was a central issue in last fall's mayoral
election.
</P>
<P>
   While some degree of opening-day chaos is almost inevitable in
any school system, let alone one comprising 1,100 schools, Crew
spoke Tuesday of several steps that had been taken to minimize the
disruptions of the past.
</P>
<P>
   After years of treating the hiring of qualified teachers with
the last-minute efficiency of a student cramming for an exam, the
Board of Education planned far ahead this year. A result, school
officials say, is that they hired 5,000 new teachers, many as early
as last spring. That, they say, should be enough to fill virtually
all classrooms by Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   And, under pressure from the chancellor, the School Construction
Authority said that for the second straight year it had been able
to deliver all the new seats that it had promised the board _ about
10,000 _ in advance of opening day. They include two new schools,
Gateway Health and Sciences High School in Jamaica, Queens, with
605 seats, and Public School 56 on Staten Island, with 955 seats.
</P>
<P>
   The remainder of new classrooms will be in temporary trailers,
building additions and spaces partitioned from existing classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Though enrollment is projected to grow by only about 5,000 this
year, compared with increases of nearly 20,000 in recent years, the
system is still working its way out of a hole created in the 1980s
and '90s, with tens of thousands more students than its buildings
were intended to house.
</P>
<P>
   Crew said that undertaking long-term repairs would be a priority
this year. He said that he had recently met with Gov. George Pataki
and would soon visit Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver to make the
case for more money.
</P>
<P>
   Crew would not specify how much he had requested, but the need
is estimated in the billions of dollars by the board and by city
officials. By November, the board is to submit a five-year capital
plan mapping out the board's priorities and strategy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
