<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAPPINESS-FILM-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HAPPINESS': SHOUTS OF RAGE AT THE WAY WE ARE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 13) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At a time when the news media are awash in the gory
details of presidential sexual hijinks, the public is supposedly
beyond shock when it comes to revelations of bad behavior. Or is
it?
</P>
<P>
   The acid test will come with the first public American
screenings of Todd Solondz's pitch-black comedy ``Happiness,'' at
the New York Film Festival. The film was shown at the Cannes Film
Festival last spring and picked up for distribution by October
Films, but October had to back out under pressure from its parent,
Universal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Happiness,'' which will be released in theaters on Oct. 16 by
Good Machine, is a gleeful, systematic demolition of the myth of
the suburban idyll. Set in a well-heeled New Jersey suburb, it
eviscerates the relationships among three sisters and their
extended family, finding bitterness, boredom, sexual dysfunction
and vicious sibling rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   The most controversial scenes involve a respected local
psychotherapist who pursues a secret life as a pedophile (he's
married to one of the sisters, who smugly prates on about ``having
it all''). Though not graphic, the scenes centering on this deeply
troubled character are all the more disturbing because he is almost
sympathetic and because the boys he molests are his 11-year-old
son's classmates.
</P>
<P>
   This is a film that feels as if it was conceived in a rage
against the forced cheer and phony togetherness promoted by
television sitcoms and feel-good Hollywood romances. In one scene
after another, the characters, several of whom are physically
unattractive and self-hating, voice their anger and disappointment
with one another in language that is stunning in its bluntness and
cruelty.
</P>
<P>
   The only truly likable character is one of the sisters, a
Candide-like do-gooder named Joy, who is the butt of her siblings'
contempt and is presented as living proof that no good deed goes
unpunished.
</P>
<P>
   Suspicion of the family and disgust with the status quo are
palpable in several other movies opening this fall. ``Lolita,''
Adrian Lynes' powerful, sad-hearted adaptation of the classic
Nabokov novel, which opens in theaters on Sept. 25, also evokes
pedophilia as the secret American vice.
</P>
<P>
   And Dominique Swain's extraordinary Lolita, a woman-child at
once brazenly seductive and painfully vulnerable, is one of the
year's most disquieting screen performances.
</P>
<P>
   Another film that punctures the sitcom-perfect vision of
American life is Gary Ross' elegant science-fiction fable
``Pleasantville,'' in which two contemporary teen-agers dive
through the looking glass, so to speak, and find themselves trapped
in a black-and-white television show that suggests a hybrid of
``Leave It to Beaver,'' ``Father Knows Best'' and an Archie comic
book.
</P>
<P>
   As the two refugees from the 1990s bring sex and rock-and-roll
into this eerily sanitized world, Pleasantville's perky cardboard
characters learn to cry and, losing their innocence, change from
black and white to living color.
</P>
<P>
   Much harsher is Peter Berg's contemporary comedy, ``Very Bad
Things,'' whose misanthropy and loathing of suburbia nearly match
those of ``Happiness.'' During a wild bachelor party in a Las Vegas
hotel room, one of five friends accidentally kills a prostitute.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of calling the police, they decide to dispose of the
body, but not before a nosy hotel security guard interrupts them
and is murdered. After returning to their sterile Southern
California housing development in time for the wedding, rampant
paranoia and backstabbing lead to more killings (including a
fratricide), several of them engineered by Christian Slater as a
cool-headed real-estate salesman spouting the platitudes of a
television self-help guru. ``Very Bad Things'' has the courage to
be unabashedly hateful.
</P>
<P>
   The trashing of family values isn't limited to American films.
In ``The Celebration,'' the Danish filmmaker Thomas Vinterberg has
created a viciously funny satire set at the elegant 60th birthday
bash of a pompous patriarch.
</P>
<P>
   During the ceremonial toasts, his eldest son shocks the guests
by accusing his father of having raped him and his now-dead twin
sister when they were children. Another son turns out to be a
raving neo-Fascist.
</P>
<P>
   When the black boyfriend of a surviving daughter shows up
unexpectedly, the entire gathering joins in singing a crude racist
ditty. The film's message is inescapable: under a surface gloss of
``civilized'' bonhomie, human beings are vile.
</P>
<P>
   In all of these films you can sense a reckless millennial
fervor, an urgency to tear down everything and expose the
rottenness so that civilization can start all over again with a
clean slate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
