<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4667 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCDOUGAL-TRIAL-NYT &LR;      09-08 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDOUGAL-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCDOUGAL'S TRIAL STARTS WITH CHRONICLE OF FINANCES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA MONICA, Calif. _ After months of delay, opening arguments
began here Tuesday in the embezzlement trial of Susan McDougal,
with a prosecutor telling jurors that President Clinton's onetime
partner in the Whitewater deal stole more than $150,000 from the
conductor Zubin Mehta and his wife in a ``crime of passion'' born
of frustration at her financial reverses in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   For years with her former husband, the late James McDougal, Mrs.
McDougal ``became accustomed to having lots of money, spending lots
of money and living a very high style of life,'' the prosecutor,
Jeffrey Semow, said. But with her marriage over and the couple's
finances ruined, Mrs. McDougal took a job in 1989 as assistant and
later bookkeeper for Nancy Mehta, and ``even though that money had
run out, the passion for it still survived,'' Semow added.
</P>
<P>
   As Mrs. McDougal listened impassively, Semow also accused her of
a crime of opportunity, like ``taking candy from a baby,'' because
Mrs. Mehta trusted her so completely to manage the couple's
financial affairs, signing complete books of personal checks, which
the prosecution says Mrs. McDougal then used for her own expenses.
Mrs. McDougal is also charged with forging Mrs. Mehta's signature
on checks and a credit card application, using her automatic teller
card without authorization and charging credit card purchases
without her consent.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. McDougal's lawyer, Mark Geragos, began his opening
statement late Tuesday afternoon by arguing that it was all a
misunderstanding and that most of the spending had gone to benefit
the Mehtas.
</P>
<P>
   Geragos began to detail the 32-year history of the Mehtas'
marriage, but Judge Leslie W. Light of Superior Court cut him off
sharply and cleared the courtroom of jurors and reporters for a
closed hearing, apparently concerned about whatever line of
argument the lawyer intended to pursue. For months, in interviews,
Geragos has contended that the charges against Mrs. McDougal were
political, brought in collusion with the Whitewater special
prosecutor, Kenneth Starr, who held Mrs. McDougal in jail for
nearly two years on a contempt citation in an effort to induce her
to testify about Clinton's financial dealings in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   But Light issued a pretrial ruling barring Geragos from making
that argument in the trial, and the judge reacted angrily when Mrs.
McDougal returned from a break in the ladies room and her lawyer
gave the court what appeared to be photocopies of articles she
reported finding tucked by the mirror about Richard Mellon Scaife,
a conservative millionaire who has been harshly critical of Clinton
and is under investigation for possibly influencing a major witness
in the Whitewater case. ''They have absolutely nothing to do with
the issues of this trial,'' Light said sharply. Apart from those
flashes of fire, the day was mostly given over to a detailed
chronicle by the prosecution of Mrs. McDougal's financial records.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, Mrs. McDougal could face up to seven years in
prison. She is already on probation from her 1996 conviction by
Starr for her role in fraudulently obtaining a $300,000 loan, some
of which later went to pay debts of Whitewater Development Co., in
which she and her husband were partners with Clinton and his wife,
Hillary. She also faces up to 12 years in prison if convicted of a
still-pending charge of criminal contempt for her refusal to
testify before Starr's grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   In the current case, Mrs. McDougal has contended that she
operated with the Mehtas' approval and her lawyer has said Mrs.
Mehta knew about the credit card, and had agreed to the arrangement
as a way of providing extra compensation for Mrs. McDougal, who was
supposedly paid $3,200 a month as a personal assistant, plus $30 an
hour for bookkeeping work.
</P>
<P>
   But Semow said that as Mrs. McDougal's illicit spending grew out
of control, she had created false financial records in an effort to
explain her use of the credit card as payment for bookkeeping work
by a phony company she created, Paradise Bookkeeping. ``She went
back into the database, and as they say, cooked the books,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, even if Mrs. McDougal's claim is true, prosecutors
say, she failed to report use of the credit card as income, and as
a result she is also charged with three counts of state income tax
fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Semow portrayed Mehta, the former conductor of the Los Angeles
Philharmonic and the New York Philharmonic, as a musical genius
with no interest in his financial affairs, and described his wife,
Nancy, as ``a bit better,'' but still ``essentially clueless''
about business matters, which she delegated to others. Mrs.
McDougal went to work for them in 1989 after her boyfriend, Pat
Harris, left a job with them to go to law school.
</P>
<P>
   Despite warnings from some other employees that Mrs. McDougal
appeared to be making unauthorized purchases, Semow said, Mrs.
Mehta continued to trust her until the summer of 1992 when she
returned from a trip to Italy and received an unexpected call from
the Bank of America asking whether she wanted to increase the
credit limit on a Mastercard held in her name, with Mrs. McDougal
listed as an alternate user.
</P>
<P>
   This was the first that Mrs. Mehta knew of such a card, Semow
said, though he acknowledged that she apparently used it herself a
few times, and when Mrs. McDougal could not provide adequate
explanation, she was dismissed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
