<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4669 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NORTHEAST-STORM-ART-N     09-08 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORTHEAST-STORM-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMERGENCIES DECLARED AS STORM CLEANUP STARTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAHWAY, N.J. _ There was oak all over Oak Street on Tuesday,
literally. And at the intersection of Maple and Elm, the mammoth
branch of a Norway maple that had once arched overhead, graceful
and leafy, had been rendered so much cordwood and leaf piles at the
curb in front of William Papirnik's house.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, said Papirnik, the city's former civil defense
director, it was one of those times when living on a tree-lined
street is more a curse than a blessing.
</P>
<P>
   Downed tree limbs and power lines were the most visible signs of
destruction left by a line of violent squalls that swept through
this city, much of New Jersey north of Camden, and Nassau and
Suffolk counties on New York's Long Island on Monday. The storms
cut electricity to nearly 300,000 customers, but power had been
restored to all but 55,000 by late Tuesday, said utility spokesmen
in New Jersey and on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   The storms were blamed for one death in the Bronx, fatal boating
accidents off Long Island and Sandy Hook, and two other deaths
early Monday morning near Syracuse. Matthew D. Bernius Jr., 52, was
killed when his 19-foot sailboat capsized in the Atlantic Ocean
near Tanner Park in Copiague, N.Y. On the Jersey Shore, Joseph
Kaplaka, 56, of Newton was washed overboard while trying to return
his rented 12-foot motorboat to shore, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   But for most people in the metropolitan area, the storms were
notable for their speed and ferocity and for the tangle of debris,
school closings and rush-hour detours they left in their wake.
</P>
<P>
   Surveys taken by the National Weather Service on Tuesday
determined that at least two tornadoes spawned by the system
touched down briefly in New Jersey and that one struck Lynbrook in
Nassau County.
</P>
<P>
   Middlesex County Emergency Services Manager Bill Fortier said
five towns _ Dunellen, Edison, Middlesex, South Plainfield and
Woodbridge _ had declared states of emergency because of widespread
power failures that knocked out traffic lights. The declaration
allows the towns to impose curfews to speed cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone through 200 boxes of flares, thousands of
barricades and traffic cones,'' he said. ``But we're happy to say
that no shelters had to be opened. No one was put out of their
house.''
</P>
<P>
   Schools in more than half a dozen towns in Union and Middlesex
Counties, in central New Jersey, as well as those in Lynbrook were
closed Tuesday because buses could not negotiate streets littered
with tree limbs and power lines. And the guidance equipment that
helps pilots land at Teterboro Airport remained out of commission
after being struck by lightning during the storms.
</P>
<P>
   A downed tree knocked out power lines serving a 10-mile stretch
of railroad track between Red Bank and Matawan, said Steve Coleman,
a spokesman for the New Jersey Transit commuter line. The power
failure caused delays for about 14,000 morning commuters, who
boarded shuttle buses to detour around the stretch of dead track.
Coleman said New Jersey Transit expected to restore power by
Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   In and around Syracuse, more than 120,000 Niagara Mohawk Power
Corporation customers remained without power Tuesday as utility
crews worked to repair the damage caused by winds as high as 90
miles per hour that swept through the area early Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   While much of the damage in New Jersey and on Long Island was to
power lines and connections serving blocks or single-family houses,
the upstate storms brought down bulk transmission lines over nine
counties, said Nick Ashooh, a Niagara Mohawk spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Eberwine, a meteorologist at the National Weather Service
station in Mount Holly, said that while most Syracuse-area
residents were asleep when the storm hit at 1 a.m. Monday, people
in the New York area had some warning as the skies darkened with
ominous, black clouds between 2 and 3 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The squall line that swept through the area originated in
Pennsylvania and stretched about 100 miles from the Poconos south
to Philadelphia, he said. The fast-moving system traveled east
about 55 mph, and 15-mile-long storm cells had winds approaching 70
mph, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Eberwine said most of the storm's effects were the result of
``straight-line wind damage,'' although meteorologists had found
evidence of an F-1 tornado, capable of causing moderate damage from
swirling winds up to 112 m.p.h., at Clark, just north of Rahway.
They also detected an F-0 tornado, which has winds of up to 72
m.p.h. and could cause light damage, in Plainfield. The rankings
are based on the Fujita scale developed by a University of Chicago
scientist.
</P>
<P>
   The damage ranged from the extreme and frightening to the minor
and merely puzzling. At the home of Joseph and Mary Peter on Oak
Street in Rahway, an uprooted oak tree crushed the enclosed sun
porch minutes after Peter had closed the windows and returned to
the parlor, 10 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   The Papirniks, on the other hand, had only a broken attic
window, some missing latticework and a damaged downspout.
</P>
<P>
   In North Plainfield, Hermina Sevilla's shiny red station wagon
lay crushed beneath an uprooted tree, while barely 50 feet away,
Walter Jones' spindly hibiscus plants and delicate Japanese maple
were left untouched.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't even disturb the trash can tops,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in North Plainfield, traffic was barred from a stretch
of Somerset Avenue where power lines lay in the street and trees
rested against buildings. For Owais Choudharino, owner of the
Washington Avenue Deli and International Catering, business was bad
Monday and Tuesday as barricades diverted foot and automobile
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   But the storm meant more business for Anthony Cortese's Somerset
Sideline Bar, just across the street. When power was restored at 8
p.m. Monday, he saw a wave of customers eager to watch Monday night
football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the only bar for four towns where you could get a
beer,'' Cortese said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
