s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARCHITECTS-SEASON-$AD     09-08 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCHITECTS-SEASON-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESIGNS FOR STUDENTS, STARS AND TRAVELERS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 13) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By HERBERT MUSCHAMP   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Naisbitt, the futurist, put it this way: When Asians like
something, they call it modern. When they don't, they call it
western. Since discouraging words are officially frowned upon in
Singapore today, it is fair to predict that the new campus of
Singapore's Nanyang Polytechnic will be received as modern through
and through.
</P>
<P>
   It is also a safe bet that the crisp design of the campus will
not soon be marred by unsightly wads of chewing gum.
</P>
<P>
   Designed by the New York firm Gwathmey Siegel &AMP; Associates, the
75-acre campus promises to be one of the most important of the many
works by American architects in southeast Asia in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The campus, designed entirely from scratch, occupies a suburban
location, and up to 12,000 students, all commuters, are expected to
be registered in the next few years. The fields of academic
concentration include engineering, health care, business, and
communications technology.
</P>
<P>
   Gwathmey Siegel has approached this project with the concept
that buildings, too, play a pedagogical role. Campus architecture
is not just a container for classrooms, but is itself a vital form
of education.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson the architects intend to impart to Singapore students
is the value of community, a classical ideal extending from the
Greek gymnasium to the University of Virginia and beyond. Is it
possible to have modern architecture without western freedom? A
project important for the cross-cultural issues it raises and for
its lucid design.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Eisenman's new design for the University of Arkansas
Football Stadium comes with built-in architectural pom-poms, huge
lollipop red ramps that leap into space and curl around the
stadium's rim.
</P>
<P>
   The project enlarges the existing stadium from 46,000 to 65,000
seats. The ramps, rising to 3,500 feet, are designed to unite the
stadium with a new student center.
</P>
<P>
   The associate architect is HNTB Sports Architecture. Eisenman,
who is not known to set great store by function, states that the
red superstructure will help cool the stadium by providing shade
and directing air currents. But they also show that his efforts to
undermine classicism often have the opposite effect.
</P>
<P>
   Like Charles Gwathmey, Eisenman was once part of the Whites, a
group of architects who sought to uphold the formal rigor of
European modernism. Their antagonists, known as the Grays (Charles
Moore, Robert A.M. Stern), followed Robert Venturi in arguing for
more accommodation of popular American taste.
</P>
<P>
   Both faced the breakdown of the Modern movement's solidarity.
Both grasped that with the collapse of Modernism, architects were
confronted with the loss of political leverage and esthetic
meaning.
</P>
<P>
   And both movements responded with essentially Baroque maneuvers
designed, like the architecture of the Counter-Reformation, to
demonstrate architecture's enduring relevance as a serious art
form.
</P>
<P>
   Gray Baroque took up historical pastiche and pop motifs, White
Baroque went with increasingly complex geometric abstraction. In
Arkansas, Eisenman's skyward ramps update Bernini, himself a great
cheerleader of an earlier day.
</P>
<P>
   Money, movies, missiles, malls and madness: the time approaches
when these may be the only first-rate items the United States will
continue to turn out for international consumption. There will be
nothing but one vast continental sprawl anchored by two buildings,
one on either coast: the Pentagon, and the new theater for the
Academy Awards on Hollywood Boulevard, which breaks ground this
fall. The missile mall and the movie mall, mad money-makers both.
</P>
<P>
   The new 3,500-seat theater, two blocks south of the Chinese
Theater, has been designed by David Rockwell in association with
Ehrencrantz Eckstut &AMP; Kuhn, and Altoon &AMP; Porter.
</P>
<P>
   There are lots of entertainment architects out there, but
Rockwell is one of the few whose heart is in the right place. He is
madly in love with theater, and he has a strong and quirky vision
of the city's theatrical dimension.
</P>
<P>
   His Academy Awards theater features a facade of glass curtains,
a long promenade of a lobby and a three-tiered auditorium and
featuring glass boxes. The design, still in development, could
benefit from some noir Nathanael West effects: darker glass,
perhaps, a deeper chiaroscuro, for a city whose undercurrent of
menace, with luck, will never run dry.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the season belongs to Warren &AMP; Wetmore, architects
of Grand Central Terminal, and Beyer Blinder Belle, the firm that
has renovated and partly remodeled this classic chunk of New York,
which officially reopens on Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   It will be swell, it will be mobbed, but, as we walk through the
Concourse, the throngs may set some of us to humming the tune Fred
Astaire sings in ``The Band Wagon'' as he saunters along the
platform to board the 20th Century: ``I'll go my way by myself,
just I myself, alone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 2218EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0399 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4672 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-SUN-NYT &LR;      09-08 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-SUN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUN AND MICROSOFT FACE OFF AT HEARING ON '96 JAVA PACT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST) 
(bl) 
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ On the morning of March 12, 1996, after
all-night negotiations to hammer out final details, principals from
Sun Microsystems Inc. and Microsoft Corp. signed a deal under which
Sun licensed its promising Java technology to Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the two companies, rivals again, squared off for a
three-day hearing in federal court to determine just what that
agreement meant. The resolution of the dispute could have
far-reaching implications for software makers and users.
</P>
<P>
   Sun contends that Microsoft has manipulated the Java programming
language to promote its stranglehold on the operating system
market. Microsoft, in turn, counters that Sun is using the
courtroom to accomplish what it cannot in the marketplace _ namely,
compete with Microsoft's Windows operating system.
</P>
<P>
   While the case is highly technical and esoteric, it could have a
wide impact. Sun has asked the government for a preliminary
injunction to prevent Microsoft from selling Windows 98 and the
Internet Explorer until it modifies the products to be Java
compatible.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the first day of testimony, a Microsoft executive told
Judge Ronald Whyte of U.S. District Court in San Jose that a
preliminary injunction could impact ``thousands, if not tens of
thousands'' of software developers. ``If there was an injunction,
it would impact worldwide shipments,'' said Robert Muglia, senior
vice president of Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Java is a programming language that can be used to develop
software for use across different operating systems. Java permits
users of these different operating systems to share and gain access
to the same programs.
</P>
<P>
   Sun contends that in 1996, Microsoft agreed it would create
versions of Java that maintained this essence of widespread
compatibility. Instead, Sun said that very soon after the agreement
was reached, Microsoft began releasing versions of Java to be used
to develop software exclusively for use on Microsoft operating
systems. Sun sued on Oct. 7, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Last May, in light of the imminent release by Microsoft of
Windows 98, Sun asked the court to grant a preliminary injunction
that would be satisfied with one of three conditions: that Windows
98 include a fully compatible version of Java; that Microsoft
bundle Sun's version of Java with Windows 98, or that Microsoft
remove any incompatible programs from Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   Sun officials declined to comment today, noting that they were
scheduled to present evidence on Wednesday. In its motion filed on
May 14 seeking a preliminary injunction, Sun argued that
``Microsoft is drawing on its vastly superior distribution channels
for desktop operating systems and browsers to inundate the market
for desktop computers with an unlicensed, incompatible version of
Sun's Java environment,'' according to a statement by the company.
</P>
<P>
   The motion called the attempt, ``a blatant effort to devalue
Sun's technology and establish its own, corrupted version as a de
facto industry standard.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft said in court today that it understood its agreement
with Sun to mean Microsoft would be allowed to effectively create
two versions of Java, one that passes Sun's test for widespread
compatibility, and one intended for use with Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   Muglia, the Microsoft executive, said Sun was unfairly trying to
control programming language that was essential to the Windows
operating system and that was outside the purview of the agreement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
