<HEADER>
A4675 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EIFMAN-BALLET-$ADV13-     09-08 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EIFMAN-BALLET-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN PSYCHODRAMAS MADE OF MOVEMENT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 13) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Boris Eifman's choreography, like his dancers, is
passionate and intense: his Eifman Ballet of St. Petersburg gave
audiences a jolt when this 21-year-old Russian troupe made its New
York debut in April with provocative psychodramas about Tchaikovsky
and the ballerina Olga Spessivtseva.
</P>
<P>
   When the Eifman Ballet returns to City Center Jan. 19 through
31, it will be easier to see why Eifman's highly expressive use of
the ballet idiom is so dramatic and stunning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Karamazovs,'' his two-act treatment of Dostoyevsky's
``Brothers Karamazov'' is a distilled if graphic essay on the
novel's themes. The second new program is a double bill that
wrestles with life's mysteries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Requiem,'' the first work, is set to Mozart's ``Requiem'' and
meditates on birth, maturity and death while the second ballet ``My
Jerusalem,'' was inspired by that city's places of worship.
</P>
<P>
   In Eifman's vision, colored by his use of percussive techno-rock
music, three religions (Judaism, Christianity and Islam) are
distinct but reconciled.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike ``Red Giselle,'' his work about Spessivtseva, and
``Tchaikovsky,'' (both will be performed again), ``Requiem'' and
`My Jerusalem'' are plotless. I saw them in June, along with ``The
Karamazovs,'' when the Eifman Ballet, which uses various theaters
in St. Petersburg, performed there for the first time at the
Maryinsky (Kirov) Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Contemporary choreography has certainly been seen on that
hallowed stage, but the Eifman company is not the kind of official
opera-house troupe Americans usually see, like the Bolshoi and the
Kirov.
</P>
<P>
   The Maryinsky itself presented experimental productions at the
turn of the century and through the 1920s until Soviet officialdom
clamped down on artistic freedom. American impresarios like Sol
Hurok had similar conservative tastes. It was safer box office to
import 19th-century classics and occasional Soviet heroic-style
ballets.
</P>
<P>
   That Eifman, now 52, was part of a new generation of Russian
choreographers trying to express themselves with individuality was
unknown to Americans. Esthetically, that generation owed much to
Leonid Yakobson, an older choreographer who was often on the outs
with the Soviet cultural authorities but who taught at the
Leningrad Conservatory's choreography department.
</P>
<P>
   Eifman, a 1972 graduate, freelanced while choreographing for the
Kirov school. His present company is an outgrowth of a group
affiliated with the Leningrad Philharmonic.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, he has been inspired by literature. I also saw
his ``Don Quixote,'' in which the Don lives in an insane asylum.
``For many years,'' Eifman said, ``I felt I lived in a madhouse,
the Soviet Union. I was told, `You don't do Soviet ballets, why
don't you go away?' ''
</P>
<P>
   As a ballet, this ``Don Quixote'' lacks coherence. But like the
pieces to be seen at the City Center, it suggests that spiritual
quest is a prime Eifman theme.
</P>
<P>
   The sexual images in some of Eifman's narrative productions
(tame by Kenneth MacMillan's standards) are not surprising. ``The
Karamazovs'' is a dark, powerful ballet, focused on the duel
between the flesh and the spirit.
</P>
<P>
   An orgy opens the work as the patriarch of the Karamazov clan
staggers from a striking two-tiered set toward the three cursed
brothers, who are entangled in a cat's cradle type of net.
</P>
<P>
   The saintly Aleksei is portrayed by Igor Markov, who ends by
climbing up toward a cross, seeking God. Earlier, he plays Jesus
opposite Albert Galichanin's Grand Inquisitor, in Eifman's symbolic
translation of Dostoyevsky's celebrated debate about God and
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   To boil down philosophical discourse to a duet is a risk. But
Eifman makes his point through the expressiveness of his
choreography. Duets are his forte, and his two ballerinas, Vera
Arbuzova and Yelena Kuzmina, are especially fluent within a
marvelous group of dancers.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, it is ensemble work that comes to the fore in the
double bill. The whole stage seems to tilt in the swiftly changing
patterns of ``Requiem.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``My Jerusalem,'' the soloists symbolizing the three
religions are absorbed into a commune that sails away on a rocking
gyroscope: part space ship, part Noah's ark.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
