<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4677 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIVIL-ACTION-FILM-2TA     09-08 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIVIL-ACTION-FILM-2TAKES-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`A CIVIL ACTION': THE STRESSES OF DISTILLING DRAMA FROM LIFE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 13) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CAREY GOLDBERG 
  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ On the wintry, weedy grounds of an abandoned
psychiatric hospital outside Boston, John Travolta and Robert
Duvall locked bright blue gaze with pale blue gaze, breath steaming
in the cold as they engaged in a verbal dogfight befitting the two
lawyers they were playing in the film version of ``A Civil
Action.''
</P>
<P>
   A few feet away on this day last December, the real-life Jerome
Facher, the wily, wise corporate litigator played by Duvall,
watched as the screen version of himself bit off a powdery chunk of
jelly doughnut and tried to intimidate Travolta's younger and
brasher character, Jan Schlichtmann, into settling his case.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does it much better than I would,'' Facher observed of
Duvall. ``He's a way better actor.''
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, joking with the actor, he put it, ``You're a
better me than (italics)me!''(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   Disconcerting, isn't it? Art not only imitating life but besting
it, in the opinion of the subject who has been doing the actual
living.
</P>
<P>
   Nonfiction books and films always dance cheek to cheek with real
life, of course. But ``A Civil Action,'' a Disney movie that is to
open on Dec. 25, based on the acclaimed 1995 book by Jonathan Harr,
has an unusually, uncannily intimate relationship with reality.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most intriguing aspect of the success of the book
and potential success of the movie is this: In their depiction of a
cluster of leukemia deaths among children in the Boston suburb of
Woburn and the large-scale 1986 legal battle that ensued over
whether industrial pollution was to blame, the reality they convey
is not a comfortable or a simple one.
</P>
<P>
   There are no obvious, flawless heroes, though there are many
obvious victims; causes are complex, and mistakes are made by good
people. And the legal system emerges in shades of gray, somewhere
between justice and injustice.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the book has been on the best-seller list for about two
years, and the movie, with a budget of more than $60 million, is so
promising that it is already being mentioned in
entertainment-industry publications as a strong contender for
various Academy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   Harr recalls that the book, which took him an excruciating nine
years and repeated extensions on his contract with Random House to
write, was a hard sell at first. ``It was a book about toxic waste
and a lawsuit that drags on and dead children,'' he said. ``And who
wants to read that?''
</P>
<P>
   Once the book was done, however, the movie rights were not a
hard sell at all. When Harr's agent began to offer the book around,
before it was even published, it set off a bidding war, and the
screen rights ended up being bought for $1.25 million.
</P>
<P>
   Rachel Pfeffer, who was then president of Wildwood Enterprises,
Robert Redford's production company, started reading the book and
couldn't put it down. She ultimately left the company to commit
herself wholly to producing ``A Civil Action.''
</P>
<P>
   Some colleagues told her that she was crazy, that the story was
too dark and complex. But, she said, ``I think people want what
this book had, and what the movie has as well, which is great guts,
great American guts _ emotion, passion, finally hubris. Like Jan's
partners, you go on this incredible roller-coaster ride.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, she added, just the fact that Schlictmann ``gave up what
he gave up, that these families went through what they went through
_ it touches on so many different things.''
</P>
<P>
   To Travolta, the movie ``means a lot to everyone on different
levels.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly the backdrop, which is the environment, is a very
important issue,'' he continued, ``and it's also about characters
that arc and go through transitions. It could be a comment on a lot
of different things _ materialism, success, power, what one does
when that's taken away.''
</P>
<P>
   Distilling that multilayered meaning into a two-hour movie fell
largely to Steven Zaillian, who wrote the screenplay for
``Schindler's List'' among other movies and was the director of the
successful 1993 film ``Searching for Bobby Fischer.''
</P>
<P>
   On ``A Civil Action,'' he is not only the writer and the
director but also one of the producers. Getting the script right
took two years, he said, and he purposely did not meet the
real-life characters until it was done.
</P>
<P>
   But the movie captures the spirit of reality so closely, he
said, that it sometimes even seems to blur with the principals'
memories of what happened. At one point, Zaillian said, he was
filming a scene in which Schlichtmann won a big case and did a
gleeful little dance outside a Boston courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   For stronger visual appeal, the scene was shot in Boston's
Public Garden rather than near the downtown courthouse where it had
really occurred.
</P>
<P>
   As Schlichtmann watched the filming, he said, ``This is exactly
what really happened,'' Zaillian recalled. ``And I said, `No, it's
not, Jan; I know what really happened.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The real Schlichtmann is unabashedly pleased at the shape of the
movie, which he consulted on for a reported fee of about $200,000.
He sees nothing too reality-bending in the fact that he is being
played by Travolta, even if the two are nothing alike physically.
</P>
<P>
   Travolta tends slightly to heft while Schlichtmann is all
narrow, rangy ectomorph. Schlichtmann has brown eyes that in the
book are described as earning him the nickname Spaniel Eyes;
Travolta's eyes are perhaps the bluest in the business.
</P>
<P>
   Travolta has a fascinating languor to him; Schlichtmann, even
now in a much mellower, silver-haired, 47-year-old model, seems
kinetic and a bit turbulent, even when he talks about meditating.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But Schlichtmann sees Travolta as capturing the spirit of his
younger self. ``I was awed at how he became a lawyer like I was,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Schlichtmann has changed a great deal since he was the
Porsche-driving, Italian-suit-wearing, all-or-nothing lawyer whose
colorful personality convinced Harr that there was, indeed, a book
in the Woburn case, and who ended up bankrupt and battered and
lost.
</P>
<P>
   Now married and the father of two toddler sons, he divides his
time among several pursuits: starting up production companies,
making environment-oriented radio and television shows and working
on Woburn-like cases in New Jersey, Massachusetts and elsewhere.
Perhaps the most striking change, though, is that he now sees the
kind of take-no-prisoners litigation he practiced in the Woburn
case as a great mistake, and says as much at public speaking
engagements.
</P>
<P>
   It may make great drama, but such litigation is like war, he
said in an interview at his house on a seaside peninsula in the
Boston suburb of Beverly, where he cultivates an elaborate water
garden and works from a shingled studio just steps from the main
house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just came to appreciate how wasteful and destructive
litigation can be,'' he said. Now, he encourages ``problem
solving,'' through less confrontational, more peaceable, more
realistic talks between sides in a dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Schlichtmann seems to have grown philosophical about many other
things as well _ for instance, the fact of being a public figure
who is about to become even more public but has had no direct
editorial control over how he was portrayed, either in the book or
the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're passed around as property for others to examine
and analyze,'' he said, ``it forces you to accept yourself in all
your aspects. And when you lose your privacy over that, it's a
learning experience and it can give you many insights and also
great pain in learning those insights.''
</P>
<P>
   The transformation of real, relatively private lives into film
material did create a knotty problem for the makers of ``A Civil
Action,'' however.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, with filming set to start in Boston in the fall,
several members of the bereaved families who had sold the rights to
their story to another team of producers _ for a movie project that
never came to fruition _ complained that Disney was not involving
them in the production or compensating them.
</P>
<P>
   Such disputes over rights to real-life stories have arisen
before: notably, Geoffrey F. Bowers, a lawyer with AIDS who fought
his dismissal from work, accused the makers of the 1993 movie
``Philadelphia'' of stealing his story. Such conflicts seem likely
to become ever more common as enterprises seeking ``synergy''
between journalism and movies multiply.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, the issue became so hot that legislators
passed a bill saying that filmmakers could not make movies about
people's lives without their permission. Advocates for Hollywood
protested loudly that such a law limited freedom of expression.
Massachusetts boosters like the acting governor, Argeo Paul
Cellucci, warned that filmmakers would stay away.
</P>
<P>
   The measure ultimately died, but Disney agreed to pay the
families several hundred thousand dollars, and to consult them more
in the production, though it stopped short of giving them any
editorial control.
</P>
<P>
   Although the dispute died down, it highlighted the unfortunate
effect even sensitively made books and movies can have in renewing
the pain for their real-life subjects. On one hand, the eight
Woburn families had badly wanted their story told, and that was why
they gave such full access to Harr, and to journalists in general.
And for many, that is still the main thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, people will continue to just be aware of what's
going on in their cities or towns or farmland,'' said Donna
Robbins, a nurse whose 9-year-old son Robbie died of leukemia.
``Because it's everywhere, it's not just in Woburn.''
</P>
<P>
   But Anne Anderson, whose son Jimmy was 12 when he died of
leukemia, said that the success of the book and the making of the
film have served to reopen her wounds and remind her of her lack of
control over how she, and especially her son, have been depicted.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Anderson, who is played in the movie by Kathleen Quinlan,
said she thought her son was portrayed as ``weak and whiny'' in the
book, and ``that just wasn't so.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just waiting to see what the movie focuses on,'' she said.
``It's frightening. I don't own the story; I don't own anything
they're going to do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Pfeffer, the movie's producer, said that Jimmy would not be
featured at all because the story starts after his death. But she
and Zaillian had no simple answers for the anxieties of the
subjects of such nonfiction films, other than their own commitment
to treat their characters right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the only control they have is having the material in
the right hands,'' Ms. Pfeffer said, referring to the families. ``I
really don't think there is anyone who will feel they were not
treated with dignity, respect and just a lot of thought.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Facher did not seem to mind when Duvall
affectionately derided him as ``an animal _ an animal! _ in the
courtroom.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, playing again with the idea of having a cinematic
doppelganger, he sounded grateful just to be allowed to hang around
the set and watch himself be portrayed by a gifted actor. ``I
wouldn't let me near me, if I were playing me,'' he declared.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 2224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
