<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0406 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4683 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KENYA-RECONSTRUCT-ART     09-08 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENYA-RECONSTRUCT-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOMENTS OF TERROR: SPECIAL REPORT ON THE KENYA EMBASSY BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for light rewrite of 1st 9 grafs)  (ART ADV: Graphic updating the Kenya bombing story is being sent to
NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase
by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JAMES C. McKINLEY Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya _ The American Embassy here was an easy target
for terrorists. Its perimeter was patrolled by unarmed guards
earning about $100 a month. The embassy's parking lot, shared with
a bank, had an exit lane protected by neither guards nor
barricades.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 7, attackers in a truck packed with explosives turned
off Haile Selassie Avenue and roared up that lane, flashing past an
uninstalled security barrier that the bank was planning to erect to
protect the lot.
</P>
<P>
   The truck managed to drive close to the building, where it was
stopped by an unarmed private security guard at a barrier at the
entrance to an underground garage. The guard ran when the attackers
threw a grenade-like device at him.
</P>
<P>
   A reconstruction of the Nairobi bombing, based on interviews
with guards and other witnesses, shows that the embassy was
vulnerable to the most rudimentary attack.
</P>
<P>
   A decade after the State Department vowed to tighten the
security of its embassies around the world, the interviews suggest
that the Nairobi mission failed to meet what appears to be a basic
security requirement: controlling access to the parking lot behind
its building.
</P>
<P>
   And Nairobi is not alone. An administration official in
Washington said it was common for embassies to be near private
property with security precautions left to the local owners. In
Malaysia, the embassy was next to a gas station. After the bombings
in Africa, the official said, the U.S. government bought the gas
station and immediately emptied its tanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a typical problem for us,'' the official said. ``We
have a number of situations in which we share commercial parking
lots.''
</P>
<P>
   The House International Relations Committee plans to hold
hearings this month on the Nairobi car bombing and the simultaneous
bombing of the American Embassy in Dar es Salaam, Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   The committee will examine a number of security issues,
including why the exit lane was left vulnerable to terrorist
attack.
</P>
<P>
   During the last 18 months, the American ambassador to Kenya,
Prudence Bushnell, repeatedly complained to her superiors in
Washington about the lack of security at her embassy, and the
committee wants to know whether she specifically raised questions
about access to the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   An administration official said the embassy in Nairobi did not
request any money to secure the road leading out of the parking
lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously it would have made a difference,'' said one embassy
official, who like most of the U.S. officials interviewed for this
article spoke on the condition of anonymity. ``If we had had
control of that outside parking lot and more guardposts, they would
have gone somewhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Most U.S. embassies around the world employ unarmed guards from
private security companies rather than armed guards or soldiers to
handle day-to-day security outside the building. U.S. Marines
normally control access to embassy buildings and protect classified
documents, and handle security problems within the embassy itself.
But external security is often handled by private companies.
</P>
<P>
   After the explosion here on Aug. 7, U.S. officials initially
praised the guard company, United International Investigative
Services, which is based in Anaheim, Calif. The officials pointed
out that the two Kenyan guards at the rear gate of the embassy's
underground garage had refused to allow the van carrying the bomb
to enter the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the vehicle had gotten down that parking ramp, none of us
would be talking to you,'' said one high-ranking embassy official.
</P>
<P>
   But the initial praise for the guards, who all survived the
blast, did not address why the terrorists had such an easy time
driving up to the barrier at the top of the ramp leading into the
embassy garage, coming close enough to gut the embassy building and
kill three dozen people inside.
</P>
<P>
   According to several witnesses, the Mitsubishi Canter van
carrying the bomb entered the parking lot through an exit lane
leading out to Haile Selassie Avenue. There was no barrier there to
stop the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   The embassy shared the rear parking lot with the adjacent
Cooperative Bank, U.S. officials said. The bank employed guards
from Wells Fargo Co., who controlled a barrier at the entrance of
the parking lot 50 yards to the north. The entrance was on an
access road that ran parallel to the avenue.
</P>
<P>
   The bank had hired a contractor to install a cantilevered bar
barrier, like those used at railroad crossings, across the exit
lane, but the work had not yet been completed, U.S. officials said.
The useless barrier was laying on the ground the day of the attack,
several guards said. State Department officials said they had no
plan to build a security barrier controlling access to the rear of
the embassy.
</P>
<P>
   Even without a barrier, the exit ramp was supposed to be guarded
by one of the embassy's private security guards in the parking lot,
the guards said in interviews. But the guard on duty that day near
the mouth of the exit lane, Jomo Matike Boke, did nothing to stop
the van from entering, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Boke's failure was not surprising, since he was filling in for a
sick colleague and had never performed the assignment before, the
guards said.
</P>
<P>
   A few days after the bombing, William Guidice, president of
United International Investigative Services, said the truck
carrying the bomb had first tried to enter a parking lot at the
front of the building, claiming to have a delivery for the embassy.
</P>
<P>
   Guidice maintained that the guard turned the truck away from the
front lot and told the men inside to go around to the back gate to
make the delivery. The guard, Francis Emomeri, declined to be
interviewed for this article.
</P>
<P>
   But FBI investigators and embassy officials now say they doubt
that story. No witnesses have been found who saw the truck come to
the front of the embassy, law-enforcement officials said, though at
least one witness has told investigators he saw a second car
leading the van toward the embassy before the blast.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   What is certain is that the van was headed east on Haile
Selassie Avenue when it abruptly made a hard left turn, bounced
over a curb, then slipped through the exit lane and into the
parking lot, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   It was 10:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Benson Okuku Bwaku was the guard manning the barrier leading
into the underground garage. He said he saw the 3.5-ton Mitsubishi
Canter truck with a covered cargo bay turn off the avenue and speed
toward him.
</P>
<P>
   The barrier was up, Okuku Bwaku said, because he had just
allowed a three-wheeled mail cart, driven by an embassy worker
named Francis Kile, to pass out of the embassy's garage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just feel something in my blood that the van was unusual,''
he recalled. ``I asked Kile to move his cart quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   The truck would have reached the barrier in seconds had a white
sedan not pulled out of another parking garage under the
Cooperative Bank Building across the lot from the embassy, he said.
The sedan ended up nose to nose with the van and for a minute
neither could move.
</P>
<P>
   Okuku Bwaku said he saw a man jump from the passenger side of
the van. Feeling panicked, the guard pushed the barrier down and
fastened it to the post. When he looked up, the man was next to
him, about six feet away, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The man was black-skinned with Arab features, long sideburns and
fine, straight black hair that hung down to the middle of his neck,
the guard said. He wore a plaid shirt and grey, denim cargo pants
with large pockets on the thighs. His hands were in his pockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he said was: `Open the gate.' Not loud. Not soft,'' Okuku
Bwaku recalled. ``I did not talk to him. The barrier was down. He
pulled his hands out of his pockets. In his left hand he had what
looked like a hand grenade. In his right hand he had three objects
with three strings falling from them.''
</P>
<P>
   The man hurled the grenade-like device at Okuku Bwaku's head
with his left hand, the guard said. He ducked. The grenade landed a
few yards behind him and exploded near a car in the compound.
</P>
<P>
   Okuku Bwaku ran about 25 feet toward Haile Selassie Avenue and
stopped. He said he desperately tried to radio the Marine guard at
post one, a bulletproof control room in the reception area of the
embassy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Break! Base! Terrorism! Terrorism!'' he said he shouted into
the radio. The attacker threw a second device at him. It sailed
over him and exploded in a paved plaza surrounding the embassy, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the drop barrier there was an iron fence and a pair of
heavy steel gates, through which cars had to pass to enter the
garage. As Okuku Bwaku ran toward the avenue, a second guard, Joash
Okindo, locked the steel gates with a padlock. He was critically
injured in the blast that followed.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the embassy, Cpl. Samuel Gonite was on guard in the post
one control room. Like the other six Marines at the embassy that
day, he declined through a military spokeswoman to be interviewed
for this article.
</P>
<P>
   But the spokeswoman, Maj. Mary Baldwin, said the corporal was
not aware of the fracas at the back gate until the first grenade
exploded. She said he immediately checked the monitors connected to
cameras on the roof but saw nothing unusual. He told his superiors
he looked outside to see if the noise might have been a car
accident.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Baldwin said the corporal was trying to make one of the
roof-top cameras pan around to the rear parking lot when the second
car bomb exploded. He either did not receive or did not hear Okuku
Bwaku's frantic radio transmission.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that time, his focus was not on the radio, but on getting
the embassy secure,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, Okuku Bwaku was running for his life. He ran around the
corner of the embassy, intending, he says, to sprint to the
post-one control room and alert the Marines. He had gone about 15
yards when the car bomb exploded, sending him flying to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Baldwin said Gonite recalled a 10-second delay between the
first grenade and the big explosion.
</P>
<P>
   A seismograph at the University of Nairobi Geology Department
registered a small tremor at 10:39 and 20 seconds. Eight seconds
later, it registered a shockwave from the explosion that measured
3.4 on the Richter scale.
</P>
<P>
   Though Okuku Bwaku never saw the truck move closer to the
parking lot ramp, another guard on duty nearby did.
</P>
<P>
   The guard, who asked not to be identified, said he was standing
near the outlet ramp of the parking lot, when the delivery truck
made a sharp turn off Haile Selassie and into the parking lot,
moving fast.
</P>
<P>
   He described the truck as a late model, cream-colored one with a
Dubai license plate on the back fender. He saw the truck squeeze
past the sedan and approach the barrier just after the man who had
leaped from the passenger side threw a grenade at Okuku Bwaku.
Law-enforcement officials say the driver of the truck was killed in
the explosion. It is unclear how many other terrorists were present
when the bomb went off or how many were involved in the bombing
conspiracy, they said. Some witnesses have reported seeing another
man climb out of the back of the van.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Richardson, a former military policeman who is one of
the partners in the guard company, said the guards receive about 80
hours of classroom training and 40 hours of practical training
before being put on the job. The company also gives frequent
refresher courses, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We teach them about terrorism and the things they should look
for,'' Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
   But Richardson acknowledged it was virtually impossible for
unarmed guards to stop armed men from driving a car filled with
explosives up to the rear of the embassy, especially given the lack
of physical barriers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not in that location,'' he said. ``You get very little
forewarning about what's taking place or what's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In that particular area, with unarmed security officers, it's
hard to protect something like that, or even to put a lot of fear
into anyone,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said he and his partners had applied for permission
to start an armed-guard service last year, but the Kenyan
government had turned them down.
</P>
<P>
   Embassy officials said it would have been possible to employ
armed guards at the embassy _ several banks in the neighborhood do
_ but until the attack last month, the potential threat to the
embassy did not seem high enough to warrant armed patrols.
</P>
<P>
   A security official at the embassy, who asked not to be
identified, said even with better-trained guards, the embassy would
be difficult to protect because of its location.
</P>
<P>
   The five-story chancery sits at the corner of the city's two
busiest avenues and heavy pedestrian traffic flows around it
constantly, like water over a stone in a creek.
</P>
<P>
   The building has precious little setback on any side, and the
parking lots at the front and rear come up within a few meters of
the walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The location of that building from a security standpoint is a
nightmare,'' the official said. ``It should have been moved.''
</P>
<P>
   Embassy officials said the U.S. ambassador, Ms. Bushnell,
renewed her complaints several times about the lack of security,
recommending at least twice in writing that the chancery be moved
to a new location.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the year and a half that she's been here she's been
fighting with Washington to get us out of that building,'' a close
aide to Ms. Bushnell said. But the answer came back from Washington
that there was no money available for a new embassy, and the old
building would be remodeled instead, embassy officials said. It
remains unclear whether the security system in the rear parking lot
was to have been changed in the planned renovation, the officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't anything that wasn't brought to Washington's
attention,'' another embassy official said. ``They told us to be
quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, several guards from the United International
Investigative Services said they had not received adequate training
to counter a terrorist attack like the one on August 7.
</P>
<P>
   Some said their training had lasted only two weeks, rather than
a month as Richardson maintained. Bombs were covered, they said,
but only in a cursory way. In essence, they were taught to clear
the area when a suspicious package or suspected bomb is found, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   First hired in November 1996, the company receives about $1
million a year from the State Department to provide full-time
security at the embassy and about 180 official residences. The
contract requires 540 guards, who make about $83 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Forced to live in slums without water or electricity, several
guards said the salary did not encourage them to risk their live
for the embassy, they said. What's more, their salaries were cut
recently, along with health benefits for their families and a daily
meal allowance, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are getting is too little,'' said one guard, who asked
not to be named.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
