<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4695 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-McGWIRE-ART-550&AMP;A     09-08 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-McGWIRE-ART-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG BANG: MCGWIRE BREAKS BASEBALL'S HOMER RECORD
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo of McGwire and two graphics are being sent to NYT
photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Mark McGwire made the most out of the least Tuesday
night, setting major league baseball's home run record by hitting
his 62nd and shortest home run of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Swinging at the first pitch from Steve Trachsel of the Chicago
Cubs with two outs in the fourth inning, McGwire lined a low-flying
shot that just cleared the left-field fence near the corner where
the stands meet the foul line. The drive, hit at 8:18 Central
Daylight Time, was estimated at 341 feet, 6 feet shorter than
McGwire's previous shortest this season. He has hit five home runs
longer than 500 feet.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, a 34-year-old right-handed-hitting first baseman for
the St. Louis Cardinals, broke the tie with Roger Maris that he had
forged only the day before. In 1961, Maris hit his 61st home run in
the Yankees' 163rd and last game of the season. This was the
Cardinals' 145th game.
</P>
<P>
   The home run set off a wild scene at Busch Stadium, starting
with McGwire's dance to first base on which he missed the base and
had to be told by Dave McKay, the Cardinals' first-base coach, to
touch it. As McGwire rounded the bases, the Cubs infielders
congratulated him, and when he reached home plate, Scott Servais,
the Cubs' catcher, shook his hand and then they embraced. Minutes
later, Sammy Sosa, who has been challenging McGwire in the home run
record chase, ran in from right field and went to McGwire, who
picked him up before they embraced.
</P>
<P>
   One home run away from breaking the record, McGwire on Tuesday
picked up the bat that Maris used to hit his record-breaking homer
in 1961, rubbed the barrel of the bat across his broad chest and
said, ``Roger, you're with me.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, who has spoken in recent days of communicating with
Maris and Babe Ruth after he dies, came together with Maris' bat
two hours before the start of the Cardinals-Cubs game. McGwire tied
Maris' record by clubbing his 61st home run on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire entered Tuesday's game leading Sosa by three. The Cubs'
right fielder had not hit a home run since he reached 58 Saturday
night in Pittsburgh. In the Cardinal clubhouse before Tuesday's
game, Delino DeShields, their second baseman, walked over to the
mirror where the lineup card was posted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this the Hall of Fame card?'' he asked no one in
particular.
</P>
<P>
   The card had been made out by Rene Lachemann, the team's
third-base coach, in the absence of Manager Tony La Russa, who was
on his way back from his mother's funeral. La Russa was in the
dugout by the time the two rivals batted in the first inning.
Facing Kent Mercker after Mark Grace singled home a run, Sosa
rapped a single past third base, leading to a second Cubs run.
</P>
<P>
   In McGwire's turn at bat in the Cardinals' half of the inning,
Steve Trachsel threw the first three pitches out of the strike
zone, much to the noisy consternation of the fans in a sold-out
Busch Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   With camera flashes exploding all over the park, McGwire, given
a green light instead of the take sign usually signaled on a 3-0
count, swung at the pitch and hit a grounder to shortstop Jose
Hernandez, who threw him out.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa batted again in the third inning and again hit a grounder
toward third. But this time, Fernando Tatis scooped up the ball and
started an inning-ending double play.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Before the game, Sosa and McGwire met separately with two
officials from the Hall of Fame, Donald Marr Jr., the president,
and Jeff Idelson, the executive director of communications and
education. Marr and Idelson explained to the players what sort of
items they would be interested in obtaining for the Hall's display
on the greatest home run race in history.
</P>
<P>
   Marr and Idelson brought with them the bat with which Maris hit
his 61st home run against Tracy Stallard on Oct. 1, 1961, the last
day of that season. Both players, Idelson said, took the bat and
swung it. ``We wanted to share it with them,'' Marr said.
</P>
<P>
   After McGwire swung it, Idelson related, he went one step more,
rubbing it on his chest and putting into words the sentiment he
expressed Monday after he tied Maris.
</P>
<P>
   After hitting his 61st homer on Monday, McGwire pointed to the
Maris children, who were sitting in the stands near the St. Louis
dugout, pointed skyward and tapped his heart, letting them know
that their father, who died in 1985 at the age of 51, was in his
heart.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, Idelson said, did not act as demonstratively with the bat
as McGwire did, but he was surprised to learn that Maris' bat was
the same weight, 32 ounces, and the same length, 34{ inches, as
his. McGwire uses the same weight bat, but his is half an inch
longer.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the conversations with the players, Marr and Idelson
were confident they would have a solid representation for the Hall
in Cooperstown, N.Y. ``Mark said what he has been saying publicly
all along,'' Idelson said after a seven-minute meeting with
McGwire. ``He would be generous. He is certainly cognizant of his
role in history, and he'd like to see his achievements documented
where they should be, at the Hall of Fame. We're very pleased.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire did not give the Hall officials any items at the
meeting. He said earlier in the week that he uses the same bat
until he breaks it, and the one he took into Tuesday night's game
had been responsible for his last six home runs, Nos. 56 through
61.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, on the other hand, turned over the bat he used in hitting
his 57th home run, the one that broke Hack Wilson's club record.
Sosa previously gave the Hall the bat he used to break the record
for the most home runs hit in the month of June.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, Idelson said, was like McGwire in being aware of the
significance of his role in the chase for the home run record and
wanted it to be documented as well.
</P>
<P>
   In handling Maris' bat, Sosa was surprised, Idelson said, that
it was in such good condition for a 37-year-old bat. The Hall
received the bat and the ball Maris hit for No. 61 from Maris in
1973. The Hall also has the bat and ball from Ruth's 60th home run
in 1927. Ruth's bat was much bigger than the others, 40 ounces and
35\ inches.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire and Sosa reached this juncture after a spirited contest
to see who could get to the record first. McGwire held the lead
except for two and two-third innings in a game between the
Cardinals and the Cubs on Aug. 19. Sosa hit his 48th in the fifth
inning of that game, but McGwire matched him in the eighth and went
ahead with a game-winning home run in the 10th. Sosa had not caught
up since.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa was new this season to the home run stratosphere of the
50s, having hit a career high of 40 in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
