<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4699 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-McGWIRE-ART-550&AMP;A     09-08 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-McGWIRE-ART-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG BANG: MCGWIRE BREAKS BASEBALL'S HOMER RECORD
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: BBO-McGWIRE-PROFILE, BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN,
BBO-McGWIRE-BALL-TAX, BBO-MCGWIRE-COLLECTOR and EDIT-MCGWIRE.) 
(ART ADV: Photo of McGwire and two graphics are being sent to NYT
photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Mark McGwire made the most out of the least Tuesday
night, setting major league baseball's home run record by hitting
his 62nd and shortest home run of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Swinging at the first pitch from Steve Trachsel of the Chicago
Cubs with two outs in the fourth inning, McGwire lined a low-flying
shot that just cleared the left-field fence near the corner where
the stands meet the foul line. The drive, hit at 8:18 Central
Daylight Time, was estimated at 341 feet, 6 feet shorter than
McGwire's previous shortest this season. He has hit five home runs
longer than 500 feet.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, a 34-year-old right-handed-hitting first baseman for
the St. Louis Cardinals, broke the tie with Roger Maris that he had
forged only the day before. In 1961, Maris hit his 61st home run in
the Yankees' 163rd and last game of the season. This was the
Cardinals' 145th game.
</P>
<P>
   The home run set off a wild scene at Busch Stadium, starting
with McGwire's dance to first base on which he missed the base and
had to be told by Dave McKay, the Cardinals' first-base coach, to
touch it. As McGwire rounded the bases, the Cubs infielders
congratulated him, and when he reached home plate, Scott Servais,
the Cubs' catcher, shook his hand and then they embraced. Minutes
later, Sammy Sosa, who has been challenging McGwire in the home run
record chase, ran in from right field and went to McGwire, who
picked him up before they embraced.
</P>
<P>
   One home run away from breaking the record, McGwire on Tuesday
picked up the bat that Maris used to hit his record-breaking homer
in 1961, rubbed the barrel of the bat across his broad chest and
said, ``Roger, you're with me.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, who has spoken in recent days of communicating with
Maris and Babe Ruth after he dies, came together with Maris' bat
two hours before the start of the Cardinals-Cubs game. McGwire tied
Maris' record by clubbing his 61st home run on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire entered Tuesday's game leading Sosa by three. The Cubs'
right fielder had not hit a home run since he reached 58 Saturday
night in Pittsburgh. In the Cardinal clubhouse before Tuesday's
game, Delino DeShields, their second baseman, walked over to the
mirror where the lineup card was posted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this the Hall of Fame card?'' he asked no one in
particular.
</P>
<P>
   The card had been made out by Rene Lachemann, the team's
third-base coach, in the absence of Manager Tony La Russa, who was
on his way back from his mother's funeral. La Russa was in the
dugout by the time the two rivals batted in the first inning.
Facing Kent Mercker after Mark Grace singled home a run, Sosa
rapped a single past third base, leading to a second Cubs run.
</P>
<P>
   In McGwire's turn at bat in the Cardinals' half of the inning,
Steve Trachsel threw the first three pitches out of the strike
zone, much to the noisy consternation of the fans in a sold-out
Busch Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   With camera flashes exploding all over the park, McGwire, given
a green light instead of the take sign usually signaled on a 3-0
count, swung at the pitch and hit a grounder to shortstop Jose
Hernandez, who threw him out.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa batted again in the third inning and again hit a grounder
toward third. But this time, Fernando Tatis scooped up the ball and
started an inning-ending double play.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Before the game, Sosa and McGwire met separately with two
officials from the Hall of Fame, Donald Marr Jr., the president,
and Jeff Idelson, the executive director of communications and
education. Marr and Idelson explained to the players what sort of
items they would be interested in obtaining for the Hall's display
on the greatest home run race in history.
</P>
<P>
   Marr and Idelson brought with them the bat with which Maris hit
his 61st home run against Tracy Stallard on Oct. 1, 1961, the last
day of that season. Both players, Idelson said, took the bat and
swung it. ``We wanted to share it with them,'' Marr said.
</P>
<P>
   After McGwire swung it, Idelson related, he went one step more,
rubbing it on his chest and putting into words the sentiment he
expressed Monday after he tied Maris.
</P>
<P>
   After hitting his 61st homer on Monday, McGwire pointed to the
Maris children, who were sitting in the stands near the St. Louis
dugout, pointed skyward and tapped his heart, letting them know
that their father, who died in 1985 at the age of 51, was in his
heart.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, Idelson said, did not act as demonstratively with the bat
as McGwire did, but he was surprised to learn that Maris' bat was
the same weight, 32 ounces, and the same length, 34{ inches, as
his. McGwire uses the same weight bat, but his is half an inch
longer.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the conversations with the players, Marr and Idelson
were confident they would have a solid representation for the Hall
in Cooperstown, N.Y. ``Mark said what he has been saying publicly
all along,'' Idelson said after a seven-minute meeting with
McGwire. ``He would be generous. He is certainly cognizant of his
role in history, and he'd like to see his achievements documented
where they should be, at the Hall of Fame. We're very pleased.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire did not give the Hall officials any items at the
meeting. He said earlier in the week that he uses the same bat
until he breaks it, and the one he took into Tuesday night's game
had been responsible for his last six home runs, Nos. 56 through
61.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, on the other hand, turned over the bat he used in hitting
his 57th home run, the one that broke Hack Wilson's club record.
Sosa previously gave the Hall the bat he used to break the record
for the most home runs hit in the month of June.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, Idelson said, was like McGwire in being aware of the
significance of his role in the chase for the home run record and
wanted it to be documented as well.
</P>
<P>
   In handling Maris' bat, Sosa was surprised, Idelson said, that
it was in such good condition for a 37-year-old bat. The Hall
received the bat and the ball Maris hit for No. 61 from Maris in
1973. The Hall also has the bat and ball from Ruth's 60th home run
in 1927. Ruth's bat was much bigger than the others, 40 ounces and
35\ inches.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire and Sosa reached this juncture after a spirited contest
to see who could get to the record first. McGwire held the lead
except for two and two-third innings in a game between the
Cardinals and the Cubs on Aug. 19. Sosa hit his 48th in the fifth
inning of that game, but McGwire matched him in the eighth and went
ahead with a game-winning home run in the 10th. Sosa had not caught
up since.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa was new this season to the home run stratosphere of the
50s, having hit a career high of 40 in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 2238EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0415 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4700 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-1STL     09-08 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 MORE PROMINENT DEMOCRATS REPRIMAND CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to modify the quoted matter in 2nd graf)  (Eds: See also CLINTON-STARR) 
(mk) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two more Senate Democrats Tuesday delivered
stinging rebukes of President Clinton, condemning what they said
was his ``dishonesty'' and ``immoral'' behavior. The chorus of
critics within the president's own party has gained volume as
lawmakers return to Washington anticipating a report from the
independent counsel investigating Clinton any day now.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., who is related to Clinton by
marriage and who is locked in a tough Senate race, took to the
Senate floor Tuesday morning and chastised the president for
failing to take responsibility ``much earlier,'' calling his
behavior wrong, indefensible and immoral.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer's daughter married Hillary Rodham Clinton's brother in the
White House in 1994. But Boxer's press spokesman, David Sandretti,
said Tuesday that the senator, who made a point of defending
Clinton's leadership on policy issues, had no conversation with
anyone in the White House or any Clinton relative before making her
speech Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A short while later, another Democrat who also faces a tough
re-election bid, Sen. Ernest ``Fritz'' Hollings of South Carolina,
took aim at Clinton Tuesday in his home state, saying: ``We're fed
up. The behavior, the dishonesty of the president is
unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   The two lawmakers delivered their remarks one day before the
House returns to session to face the daunting task of reviewing a
report by independent counsel Kenneth Starr. The report on possibly
impeachable offenses could arrive in the House as early as this
week, House Republican and Democratic aides said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   House leaders are preparing to hold a series of meetings on
Wednesday on how to grapple with the inquiry, including one between
Democrats and the president.
</P>
<P>
   And in an apparent change of heart, a number of key Democrats
said Tuesday that Starr's report should immediately be made public
in its entirety, a position that breaks with prior calls to keep it
secret. A host of Republicans, including Majority Whip Tom DeLay,
of Texas, have also demanded that the report be made public,
arguing that the public has the right to see and know more than may
be offered in a simple ``executive summary.''
</P>
<P>
   The call for full and prompt disclosure of the report _ perhaps
with some names redacted for privacy reasons _ appears to be
gaining momentum, Republican and Democratic aides close to the
inquiry said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a growing and legitimate school of thought that says
let's go ahead and put the whole thing out, sink or swim,'' said
one high-ranking Democratic leadership aide.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., was the first to call for full
disclosure in an Aug. 27 letter to Speaker Newt Gingrich. Since
then, others, including Reps. Charles Rangel of New York and Robert
Wexler of Florida, have added their voices. Both say that sensitive
grand jury testimony and names should be redacted from the report
before its release.
</P>
<P>
   House Judiciary Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., and ranking member
Rep. John Conyers Jr., D-Mich., both agree that an executive
summary of the report should be released to all members of
Congress, with the full report going only to committee members.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``This should not be done in secret, or by suppressing
something,'' Dingell said. ``The people need to know. This is a
judgment we're making on their behalf. Taxpayers spent $40 million
on this document. They have a right to know what's in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangel added Tuesday, ``There is no question that the substance
of the accusations have to be made public because it's going to get
leaked anyway and everyone between now and election will be putting
their spin on it. I don't see that we have an option.''
</P>
<P>
   One House Democratic aide said some Democrats simply fear being
``blindsided'' by the White House before the November elections if
the report is not made available to them.
</P>
<P>
   Wexler argued that making the document public could allow
Clinton to respond, if his request to review the report before it
is sent to Congress is rejected by Starr.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president needs to have an opportunity to respond to Ken
Starr's allegations and conclusions to the extent that they are
contained in the report,'' Wexler said.
</P>
<P>
   Bracing themselves for the inquiry, Republicans and Democrats
have scheduled an important series of meetings on Wednesday to
begin planning how best to handle the report, both procedurally and
politically.
</P>
<P>
   The president, who is deeply concerned about the erosion of
support among Democrats in Congress, plans to meet Wednesday
morning with the senior eight members of the House Democratic
leadership at the White House. Members are expecting an apology
from the president for deceiving them, House Democratic aides said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Mike McCurry described the meeting as
focusing on the congressional agenda as well as the impeachment
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Republican leaders will huddle at a ``retreat'' in
the afternoon to sort out their strategies. And in the morning
House leaders from both parties, including Hyde and Conyers, are
expected to come together to discuss House procedures for handling
Starr's report. Democrats are opposed to a bid by Hyde to garner
what aides call ``unprecedented powers'' for his committee, such as
the ability to subpoena witnesses and cite witnesses for contempt
without a full House vote, Democratic aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich and Hyde have both said that it is important the
process be bipartisan. And Rep. Gerald Solomon, R-N.Y., chairman of
the House Rules Committee, has said he wants to grant only a few
exceptions to existing House procedures.
</P>
<P>
   But on Tuesday a House Republican aide described the matter as
``fluid,'' while the Democrats' chief counsel on the Judiciary
Committee described the two sides as being ``a long way off on
substance.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the whole inquiry could be wrapped up before the
election, as some Democrats and Republicans are hoping, Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott said he didn't think so.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 2239EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
