<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0421 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4708 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-COLUMN-CO     09-08 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baseball resurrected with McGwire
 &HT;    By Terence Moore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Baseball officially rose all the way from the dead
Tuesday night inside the loudest of tombs called Busch Stadium.
There, Roger Maris joined Babe Ruth as just another guy behind Mark
McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   This wonderful crusade to a 62nd home run ended with a screamer
just over the fence in left field in the fourth inning. It was
McGwire's shortest homer of the year at 341 feet, but it was the
biggest. Such was true, not only for McGwire, but for a suffering
game that needed every bit of what eventually turned this ballpark
into the loveliest madhouse you'll ever see after McGwire's shot
curled about five feet away from the foul pole into history.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, everything on this side of the universe was so loud,
so glorious, so unbelievable that McGwire nearly forgot to touch
first base on his home run trot. What followed was exactly 10
minutes of McGwire hugging the world. It started with his
10-year-old son Matthew, and it ended with the rest of us, still
rubbing our eyes after watching McGwire spend the last four days
conquering Ruth, Maris and fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   This is among the greatest feel-good stories of our time. No, of
any time, and you can tell as much by the way much of the universe
ceased to function recently until McGwire left a batter's box.
</P>
<P>
   Now we can breathe again, and then we can search for ways to
keep our hearts from pounding so much.
</P>
<P>
   Among those with chills the size of an average McGwire blast was
an Atlanta columnist who has felt this way only twice before in
baseball. I was in Cincinnati that September night in 1985 when
Pete Rose turned his hometown into Disney World along the Ohio by
passing Ty Cobb for most career hits. Then, 10 Septembers later, I
saw Cal Ripken Jr. take his electric victory lap around Baltimore's
Camden Yards under a full moon after he surpassed Lou Gehrig's
streak of consecutive games played.
</P>
<P>
   Now this. This was the best of them all. The feats of Rose and
Ripken were amazing, but they primarily involved longevity. In
contrast, there was no sense of inevitability that McGwire would
slam enough homers before the end of this season to catch Ruth or
Maris. Plus, McGwire had his two legends to battle, while Rose and
Ripken had their one.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the biggest reason why McGwire's ongoing moments surpass
those of Rose and Ripken is that McGwire's moments slam an
exclamation point on baseball's recovery from the brutal strike of
1994 and 1995. We're not referring as much here to McGwire's march
to Nos. 60, 61 and 62 as we are to the class with which he has
achieved them.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, McGwire has signed eternal autographs and
answered eternal questions. He's been a loving father by squeezing
his son with his arms or his words whenever possible. He's kicked
Charles Barkley in the teeth by saying that he is a role model.
He's even shown as much by donating $1 million each year to battle
child abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Said John McGwire, Mark's father, whose 61st birthday present on
Monday was Mark's 61st homer: ``He's a man of faith. He's a father
who loves his son. He's a good citizen. He loves this country like
we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, McGwire likes to acknowledge that he has been
blessed with an impressive supporting cast, starting with Chicago
Cubs slugger Sammy Sosa, McGwire's closest pursuer with 58 homers
and biggest cheerleader. When they aren't pushing each other on the
field (they've homered 20 times on the same day), they're
suggesting the other is the greatest thing to happen to the game
since the invention of home plate.
</P>
<P>
   During those 10 minutes of absolute bedlam after No. 62, Sosa
raced in from right field to smash fists with McGwire and exchange
punches to the gut. Then McGwire grabbed Sosa in the biggest of
hugs.
</P>
<P>
   Good for them. Good for baseball. Good for the universe, because
we definitely need it.
</P>
<P>
   Terence Moore is a sports columnist for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. E-mail him at tlmajc(AT)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
