<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0424 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4712 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-MCGWIRE-SCENE-250     09-08 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MCGWIRE-SCENE-250&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOSA SHOWS RESPECT; MCGWIRE RETURNS IT 
</HEADLINE>
  (DUPLICATION WARNING: Also moving in ``a'' news file.) 
(th) 
 By JACK CURRY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Sammy Sosa kept saying that he wanted Mark McGwire
to break Roger Maris' home run record and kept insisting that
McGwire would do it. Over and over, Sosa stayed consistent and
often seemed like McGwire's biggest fan instead of his biggest
competitor. He remained true to his words with his actions Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   After McGwire drilled a bullet that hugged the left field line
and barely cleared the left field fence in the fourth inning, Sosa
smiled from right field. He watched a delirious McGwire stumble
around the bases, watched him celebrate his 62nd homer in animated
fashion and could not resist congratulating him. Sosa hustled in
from right field and actually joined the party.
</P>
<P>
   It was an amazing scene involving McGwire and Sosa, a scene for
baseball history and a scene that crossed barriers and spoke of
brotherhood. McGwire embraced Sosa and lifted him, like he was a
package of groceries.
</P>
<P>
   Then McGwire and Sosa touched their fists high and then stopped
just short of punching each other in the stomach, which has become
McGwire's trademark following homers during this memorable season.
</P>
<P>
   Before Sosa returned to right, McGwire also paid tribute to him
by performing his routine following homers. McGwire touched his
lips and kissed them twice and pointed to the skies. McGwire then
hugged Sosa one more time and later thanked him when he spoke
briefly with the fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sammy Sosa,'' McGwire said, gazing out toward right at Busch
Stadium, ``you're unbelievable.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Before the game, Sosa could not even pull on his uniform pants
without having a media relations official shadowing him and waving
off a group of reporters who tried to speak with the happiest of
Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not right now, thank you,'' Sosa said politely as reporters
descended upon him. ``We'll do this later, OK?''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the Cubs, a team that is trying to reach the
post-season for the first time since 1989, were alone and
available. Rod Beck sipped a drink and read a newspaper in front of
his locker. Mark Grace smoked a cigarette and jokingly wondered if
McGwire would take a rest after blasting his 61st homer on Monday.
Mickey Morandini fiddled with a fresh bat and stared at the
starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   If a person from another country with no sports knowledge had
stumbled into the clubhouse, it would have taken about 10 seconds
to realize that Sosa is the most wanted Cub. No one else had a
bodyguard. No one else had 20 reporters waiting for him to utter a
few syllables.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that has been a silent blessing for the Cubs because they
have not been overly burdened with fielding questions about the
organization's ignominious history of not winning a World Series
title since 1908 and not even appearing in one since 1945.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' said Grace, ``Sammy is the main story on this
team. There's only one guy whose ever had a better season than him,
and that's McGwire. As long as he handles it well, we all feed off
it and enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Cubs conceded that the attention given to Sosa's pursuit
of McGwire and of their pursuit of Roger Maris has sometimes
overshadowed the type of season that the loyalists at Wrigley Field
have long prayed for.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the players emphasized that their focus has remained
on winning the wild card, they admitted it has not been the central
theme for fans and most of the news media. The Cubs and Mets
entered Tuesday night tied at 80-64 for the National League wild
card (the Mets lost their game with the Philadelphia Phillies
16-4), but that race is secondary to most of the world fascinated
with homers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think it's the home run thing,'' said Morandini.
``They're eating it up. It's consuming everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Grace said: ``We're focused on the chase. It's our only focus.
It might not be the fan's focus. In baseball, there's the Yankees,
McGwire and Sammy Sosa, Kerry Wood and the playoff chase. We're
part of it. Sammy, Kerry and ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   While Sosa has handled the tenuous situation with aplomb by
constantly repeating that the post-season is his ``main concern,''
at least one Cub expressed disgust with the ongoing publicity about
the long balls.
</P>
<P>
   When two reporters approached Beck and requested an interview,
he asked them what it would entail. When he was told the wild card
would be the subject, he agreed to talk. But once Beck was asked if
the carnival surrounding Sosa had allowed the Cubs to play in more
anonymity, he responded, ``A little bit,'' and then turned ornery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to talk about winning baseball games,'' said Beck.
``I'm sick and tired of this home run stuff. It does take second
fiddle. It's what the media wants to talk about. The only thing we
want to talk about is the wild card and winning baseball games.''
</P>
<P>
   The post-season is Sosa's priority, too, and the focus might
shift to that now that McGwire has eclipsed the record. Sosa, who
began the night with 58 homers, always said he hoped that McGwire
would get the record and that the Cubs would get the chance to play
games in October. So far, half his wishes have come true.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark McGwire,'' Sosa has said, ``is the man.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 2252EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0425 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4713 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-HOMER-COX     09-08 0378
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-HOMER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baseball, America ushers in new hero
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ For a few seconds Tuesday night the baseball world
stopped and stared. From their television sets, from their seats at
Busch Stadium, through the eyes of radio announcers, they peered
down a third-base line, adrenaline flowing, stomach aching, and
prayed that a baseball hit by Mark McGwire had enough to get it
over a 10-foot wall.
</P>
<P>
   The moment seemed to last forever.
</P>
<P>
   Then the ball disappeared; McGwire's arms went toward the
heavens, and the fans in attendance began screaming, stomping,
crying and relishing their moment in history.
</P>
<P>
   The chase has ended. McGwire's 62nd homer, off Cubs pitcher
Steve Traschel, broke the single-season record for home runs set by
Roger Maris in 1961. The line drive down the left-field line,
measured at 341 feet, barely cleared the fence.
</P>
<P>
   It was McGwire's shortest home run of the season, but it was
good enough to go into the history books.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire reached down to golf the ball and had trouble following
its path. He was halfway down the first-base line when he realized
the ball cleared the fence. He became so wrapped up in the moment
that he missed first base while being congratulated by coach Dave
McKay, who steered McGwire back to touch the base.
</P>
<P>
   He then continued around the bases, slapping every player. When
he finally got around third base, with flashbulbs going off
everywhere, he stepped on the plate, and the real celebration
began.
</P>
<P>
   Like he did the day before when he hit No. 61, he picked up his
10-year-old son, Matt, a bat boy, and gave him a kiss he will never
forget. He then grabbed and hugged teammates and members of the
Maris family, who were sitting near the Cardinals' dugout. When he
climbed back on the field, he was greeted by Cubs outfielder Sammy
Sosa, who was his nearest pursuer during the chase for 62.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire then grabbed a microphone hooked up for the occasion,
and said: ``Sammy Sosa is unbelievable.'' He then thanked the
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   When play resumed, they were dancing in the streets of St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball has a new hero.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
