   ``Of course,'' said Grace, ``Sammy is the main story on this
team. There's only one guy whose ever had a better season than him,
and that's McGwire. As long as he handles it well, we all feed off
it and enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Cubs conceded that the attention given to Sosa's pursuit
of McGwire and of their pursuit of Roger Maris has sometimes
overshadowed the type of season that the loyalists at Wrigley Field
have long prayed for.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the players emphasized that their focus has remained
on winning the wild card, they admitted it has not been the central
theme for fans and most of the news media. The Cubs and Mets
entered Tuesday night tied at 80-64 for the National League wild
card (the Mets lost their game with the Philadelphia Phillies
16-4), but that race is secondary to most of the world fascinated
with homers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think it's the home run thing,'' said Morandini.
``They're eating it up. It's consuming everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Grace said: ``We're focused on the chase. It's our only focus.
It might not be the fan's focus. In baseball, there's the Yankees,
McGwire and Sammy Sosa, Kerry Wood and the playoff chase. We're
part of it. Sammy, Kerry and ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   While Sosa has handled the tenuous situation with aplomb by
constantly repeating that the post-season is his ``main concern,''
at least one Cub expressed disgust with the ongoing publicity about
the long balls.
</P>
<P>
   When two reporters approached Beck and requested an interview,
he asked them what it would entail. When he was told the wild card
would be the subject, he agreed to talk. But once Beck was asked if
the carnival surrounding Sosa had allowed the Cubs to play in more
anonymity, he responded, ``A little bit,'' and then turned ornery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to talk about winning baseball games,'' said Beck.
``I'm sick and tired of this home run stuff. It does take second
fiddle. It's what the media wants to talk about. The only thing we
want to talk about is the wild card and winning baseball games.''
</P>
<P>
   The post-season is Sosa's priority, too, and the focus might
shift to that now that McGwire has eclipsed the record. Sosa, who
began the night with 58 homers, always said he hoped that McGwire
would get the record and that the Cubs would get the chance to play
games in October. So far, half his wishes have come true.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark McGwire,'' Sosa has said, ``is the man.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
