<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4715 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-GOV-MALONE-BOS &LR;      09-08 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-GOV-MALONE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANK PROBING RELEASE OF CELLUCCI DEBT REPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH   AND FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Acting Governor Paul Cellucci's personal debt Tuesday
took center stage in an increasingly acrimonious gubernatorial
campaign, with Cellucci accusing his Republican rival Joseph D.
Malone of complicity in illegally obtaining his private credit
reports.
</P>
<P>
   The issue flared up when the Chase Manhattan Bank, of New York,
confirmed Tuesday it is investigating whether someone at the bank
illegally released credit information on Cellucci that has been
circulating among the Boston media for several months.
</P>
<P>
   A bank spokeswoman said an internal investigation was launched
two months ago after Cellucci's personal attorney called Chase with
evidence that someone at the bank had retrieved Cellucci's credit
history on at least two occasions _ March 28 and May 29 _ without
authorization.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Cellucci has told the bank that credit reports for
his wife, Jan, and his father, Argeo Cellucci, a Hudson
businessman, were also obtained through the bank on two other days
in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our investigation so far has not determined we requested or
received the reports,'' said Charlotte Gilbert-Biro, vice-president
for corporate communications. ``I can say that if the reports were
accessed illegally, the person would be terminated.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, in the wake of a WHDH-TV (Channel 7) report that
focused new attention on Cellucci's debt, estimated at more than
$700,000, Cellucci and his campaign aides laid the blame on the
leak at Malone's doorstep.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Joe Malone has an obligation to talk to all of his
consultants, all of the people helping him on his campaign, and
let's find out who broke state law, who broke federal law, and who
brought campaigning and dirty tricks to a new low in
Massachusetts,'' Cellucci said.
</P>
<P>
   John Brockelman, Cellucci's deputy campaign manager, pointed an
accusatory finger at Manhattan private investigator Richard ``Bo''
Dietl, a Malone friend and fund-raiser. ``Given that last week Joe
Malone announced he was going to continue to attack Paul Cellucci's
personal finances, his close relationship with private investigator
Bo Dietl, who specializes in accessing credit reports, it raises
serious questions that deserve to be answered,'' Brockelman said.
``I smell a rat.''
</P>
<P>
   Reached in New York, Dietl, who has been quoted in news reports
boasting about his ability to obtain confidential credit reports,
denied any involvement in obtaining the records.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course not,'' he said when asked if he had played any role
in getting Cellucci's credit report. ``I think the governor is
hallucinating a little bit on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Dietl said his role with Malone had been limited to raising
$60,000 at a New York City fundraiser and arranging for his
appearance on Don Imus's nationally syndicated radio show.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Tuesday about the Cellucci campaign charge, Eric
Fehrnstrom, Malone's deputy campaign manager, accused Cellucci of
trying to divert attention away from his personal debt problems.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Fehrnstrom refused to answer the question directly when
asked if the Malone campaign was in any way involved in the leak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not going to respond to Paul Cellucci's ridiculous
allegations,'' Fehrnstrom said. ``I am just not going to dignify it
with a response except to say he is employing Bill Clinton-like
tactics to divert attention from his own problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrongfully obtaining and circulating someone's credit report is
a federal crime punishable by a stiff fine and a prison sentence of
up to two years.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday evening, Channel 7 aired a segment on Cellucci's debt
but the reporter, Andy Hiller, said he did not have a copy of the
actual credit report.
</P>
<P>
   ``I relied on information obtained from a confidential source,''
said Hiller, who said the acting governor had neither confirmed nor
denied the accuracy of the figures he used. ``If he had said the
numbers were wrong, we would not have had a story.''
</P>
<P>
   Several months ago, a source gave the Globe a purported summary
of Cellucci's personal credit report, but the newspaper declined to
use the material.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of Cellucci's debt has flared just as the two
candidates are preparing to meet Wednesday night in Worcester for
their last debate before the Sept. 15 primary. With polls showing
him lagging far behind the acting governor, Malone last week said
Cellucci's personal debt is on the table for debate in the closing
days of the Republican primary.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci has said he accumulated the debt partly as a result of
a paycut when he gave up his law practice in 1991 to become
lieutenant governor. He said also his bills mounted as he paid for
his two daughters' college education and made additions to his
Hudson home.
</P>
<P>
   Malone contends it was Cellucci's recent TV ad that attacks his
record as treasurer that led to his decision to make Cellucci's
heavy personal debt a campaign issue.
</P>
<P>
   But in fact, the Malone campaign has been engaged in a quiet
effort to plant damaging stories about Cellucci's personal finances
for months _ even back when the treasurer was publicly insisting he
wouldn't touch the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been peddling it to news organization for quite
awhile,'' said a GOP strategist, who speculates that the real
reason Malone decided to drive the issue himself is that the
campaign has concluded that it won't receive enough attention
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   In the most striking example of the Malone campaign's effort to
draw attention on the debt, Charles Manning, a close Malone friend
and paid consultant to the campaign, last spring faxed a memo to
reporters outlining discrepancies in Cellucci's various
explanations for the debt and suggesting areas for the news media
to investigate. Manning declined comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Another individual close to the campaign says a volunteer from
the Malone camp inspected the building permits on the acting
governor's Hudson home to investigate Cellucci's explanation that
renovation expenses had contributed substantially to the debt.
Until last week, however, Malone's public position was that while
Cellucci should offer a fuller explanation, he himself wouldn't
exploit Cellucci's personal financial woes as a campaign issue.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the debt issue during a June 12, 1997, meeting with
Globe editors and reporters, Malone said then he would not raise
the matter, though he stopped short of ruling the issue out of
bounds.
</P>
<P>
   In July of last year, when Globe columnist David Nyhan wrote
about Malone, Malone's stance was the same. ``Malone vows not to
make an issue of Cellucci's personal debt level,'' wrote Nyhan, who
quoted Malone saying: ``I'll let other people decide that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe staff writer Jill Zuckman contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
