<SLUG> BC-R-BBO-MCGWIRE-BALL-TAX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRS NOW SAYS NO TAX ON RECORD-BREAKING BASEBALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Also moved in `s' category) 
(nk) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It ain't so, the IRS said Tuesday. The fan who
grabs the home run that breaks Roger Maris' record will not face a
huge tax bill if he or she turns the ball over to the player who
hits it.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with a public relations debacle, the tax-collection agency
put out a statement Tuesday afternoon explaining the ``basic income
and gift tax principles'' that would apply to a fan who ends up
with the historic ball and returns it. Its interpretation of those
principles Tuesday was far more favorable to such a fan than the
more literal-minded interpretation that the IRS had previously said
might apply.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, the fan in these circumstances would not have
taxable income,'' the agency said, deflating legions of IRS bashers
who had already worked themselves into a high dudgeon over reports
that the lucky fan could face a tax bill of hundreds of thousands
of dollars just for turning the ball over to Mark McGwire of the
St. Louis Cardinals or Sammy Sosa of the Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS said snagging the ball and giving it back would, for
legal purposes, be like winning a sweepstakes but declining the
prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``There would likewise be no gift tax in these circumstances,''
the agency said, adding that the tax consequences would be
different if the fan tried to cash in by selling the ball. By some
estimates, the ball could be worth $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes pieces of the tax code can be as hard to understand
as the infield fly rule,'' said IRS Commissioner Charles Rossotti.
``All I know is that the fan who gives back the home run ball
deserves a round of applause, not a big tax bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Rossotti, who has been trying to reshape the agency into a
customer-friendly service center for taxpayers, acted after members
of both parties in Washington took turns Tuesday mocking and
criticizing the IRS for even allowing the issue to come up.
</P>
<P>
   Although the IRS has said all along that it will have to look at
all the circumstances before determining the tax implications of
the ball that breaks the single-season record of 61 home runs, it
had done little until Tuesday to dispel the impression that it
would apply the laws and regulations strictly. Treating the
baseball like any other valuable gift would have meant slapping a
tax of as much as 40 percent of the ball's value, although the
donor could have chosen to reduce his or her liability by using the
$625,000 lifetime exemption on gifts available to all taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking before the IRS made its announcement Tuesday, White
House spokesman Mike McCurry said the possibility of the agency's
stepping into a moment in baseball history was ``about the dumbest
thing I've ever heard in my life.'' House Minority Leader Richard
Gephardt of Missouri said that ``only the IRS could turn a
once-in-a-lifetime catch into a once-in-a-lifetime Catch-22.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. William Roth, R-Del., who led hearings over the last year
into abuses of taxpayers by the IRS, said he had called Rossotti
Tuesday to urge him to avoid invoking tax provisions ``that defy
common sense and are patently unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that there was ever even the possibility of Mark
McGwire's historical 62nd home run baseball being taxed,'' Roth
said, ``is a prime example of what is wrong with our current tax
code.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
