<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Neagle expected to miss next start
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ The news from the medical front back home was OK
Tuesday. No, Denny Neagle doesn't have a tear in his left rotator
cuff. Yes, the left-hander has some bursitis in his pitching
shoulder. It will probably cause Neagle to miss a second straight
start Saturday, but he should be able to resume his spot in the
rotation next week. And, more important, on into October.
</P>
<P>
   All that was determined Tuesday when Neagle, who was scratched
from his scheduled start Monday against the Mets, was examined in
Atlanta by Braves orthopedist Joe Chandler. While an MRI showed no
damage to Neagle's rotator cuff, Chandler did give him a cortisone
shot to help ease the stiffness that has plagued Neagle for a
couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The MRI was good,'' said Braves trainer Dave Pursley. ``He had
a little injection in his labrum.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a little bursitis, inflammation of the bursa sac,''
said Bobby Cox. The manager isn't sure if Neagle, who's won his
last three starts, will be able to start Saturday at home against
Florida. If not, rookie Bruce Chen _ who made his major-league
debut Monday in Neagle's stead _ will start again. If so, Neagle
would take his next regular turn Sept. 16 against Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   With pride
</P>
<P>
   With Michael Tucker stuck in a 6-for-31 slump
(24-for-his-last-127, .189) and now hitting a season-low .249,
Curtis Pride started in right field against Expos right-hander
Miguel Batista, Pride's first start since being recalled from
Richmond Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to,'' Cox said of Pride. He has a chance to be on our
(postseason) roster. We need to get him some at-bats.''
</P>
<P>
   Pride was 0-for-1 as a pinch hitter over the weekend in New
York, grounding out on Monday. That lowered his pinch-hitting
average to .206 (7-for-34). But in his first 16 starts before
Tuesday, Pride hit .321 (17-for-53) as a starter.
</P>
<P>
   Home run for Jones
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire isn't the only guy hitting lots of homers lately.
</P>
<P>
   On the first pitch Andruw Jones saw from Batista in the second
inning Tuesday night, he lofted his 29th home run of the season,
just over the wall in the left. It was his fifth homer in six
games, and his eighth in the last 16.
</P>
<P>
   All this from a kid who didn't hit his first homer until April
14, finished that month with four and had just 12 at the All-Star
break. On Sunday, he became the third-youngest player (21 years,
four months) to reach 50 career homers. The youngest? Hall of Famer
Mel Ott (20 years, four months), then Tony Conigliaro (20 years,
seven months).
</P>
<P>
   Why the late surge? ``I don't know,'' said Jones. ``I've been
really patient and waiting for pitchers to make a mistake. I think
the last three games (in New York), the pitchers made a mistake,
left it over the plate and high.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
