<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 9/8/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) ST. LOUIS -- Sept. 8, 1998 -- BBO-MCGWIRE-2, 9-8 -- His
teammates ready to receive him, Mark McGwire points skyward after
breaking Roger Maris' home run record Tuesday night with No. 62 - a
lined 341-foot shot to left which was the shortest of the season
for the Cardinal slugger. The home run triggered an 11-minute
delay, baseball's biggest midgame celebration since Cal Ripken
broke Lou Gehrig's consecutive games record in 1995. (G. Paul
Burnett/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) ST. LOUIS -- Sept. 8, 1998 -- BBO-MCGWIRE, 9-8 -- Mark
McGwire hugs his son, Matt, after breaking Roger Maris' home run
record Tuesday night with No. 62 - a lined 341-foot shot to left
which was the shortest of the season for the Cardinal slugger. ``To
all my family, my son, the Cubs, Sammy Sosa. It's unbelievable,''
he says. ``Thank you, St. Louis.'' The home run triggered an
11-minute delay, baseball's biggest midgame celebration since Cal
Ripken broke Lou Gehrig's consecutive games record in 1995. (G.
Paul Burnett/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- Sept. 8, 1998 -- NY-SOCIAL-SEASON, 9-8 --
Kristina Stewart became the editor of Quest, a society magazine,
just under one year ago. In her view, which now matters in certain
pockets of the Upper East Side, New York society is ``a fascinating
sandbox'' with ``its own vocabulary,'' but is still welcoming of
new languages. ``If it wasn't, it would be like Latin, says Ms.
Stewart. (Librado Romero/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) AURORA, Colo. -- Sept. 8, 1998 -- COLO-SHOOTING, 9-8 --
Juan Morales, left, and his father, Anibal Morales, the uncle of
Eddie Morales, one of six people killed in a Labor Day shooting
rampage in Aurora. Police and witnesses said the suspect, Alexander
Pagosian, and a friend, Michael Martinez, 18, were carrying
shotguns and had pulled bandanas over their faces when they entered
two houses in the suburbs of Aurora, east of Denver, on Monday.
(Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) HURST, Texas -- Sept. 8, 1998 -- TEXAS-FROST, 9-8 --
Rep. Martin Frost at a union's Labor Day barbecue in a Fort Worth
suburb. As chairman of the Democratic Congressional Campaign
Committee, he finds himself facing two months of campaigning over
uncertain ground for a party whose leader is up to his eyeballs in
scandal. ``All I can say is that the situation is impossible to
gauge,'' says Frost, a 10-term congressman. ``But I think it's
going to be a very late-developing election.'' (Mark Graham/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) MIAMI -- Sept. 8, 1998 -- BBO-MCGWIRE-COLLECTOR, 9-8 --
Wendy Levy Jackson of South Miami-Dade has a collection of about
3,000 Mark McGwire baseball cards. The most valuable McGwire card
is his official rookie card, a 1985 Topps featuring him with the
United States Olympic team. ``Every time he'd hit another one, my
friends would call and congratulate me,'' says Jackson, a
51-year-old real estate broker for Coldwell Banker. ``One of my
friends said, 'You would think he's my relative or something.' ``
(Gary I. Rothstein/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) DALLAS -- Sept. 8, 1998 -- GREYHOUND-HANDICAPPED, 9-8 --
A Greyhound driver, Ralph Jackson Jr. uses a lift Tuesday for
Thomas Thompson in Dallas. A company plan to make all of its stops
accessible to wheelchair users drew skepticism from some advocates.
(Mark Graham/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) UNDATED -- Sept. 8, 1998 -- BBO-MCGWIRE-PROFILE, 9-8 --
Caricature of Mark McGwire. Without a doubt or an asterisk, McGwire
and his mighty swing broke Roger Maris' home run record Tuesday
night with plenty of games to spare. Historic No. 62 was a lined
shot to left, punctuating a chase that reinvigorated the sport and
captivated the nation. (Michelle Hazelwood/NYTRENG Graphics
Network)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 8, 1998 -- CLINTON-SCHOOL-2, 9-8 --
President Clinton appeared at the Pine Crest Elementary School in
Silver Spring, along with Rep. Albert Wynn, D-Md., left, and
Education Secretary Richard Riley, to talk about education needs.
``I'm very pleased to have the president here to talk about one of
the real issues,'' says Wynn, who insists that it is ``time to move
on'' from the Lewinsky scandal. ``In my district, folks are not
interested in hype, they are not interested in scandal.'' (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) SILVER SPRING, Md. -- Sept. 8, 1998 -- CLINTON-SCHOOL-1,
9-8 -- President Clinton's car passes demonstrators Tuesday as it
leaves Pine Crest Elementary School in Silver Spring. The president
appeared at the school to talk about education needs. (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Sept. 8, 1998 -- AFFIRM-IMPACT, 9-8 -- Derek
Bok, left, and William Bowen have completed a study that challenges
much of the conservative thinking about affirmative action. The
study is to be released Wednesday by Princeton University Press in
a book titled ``The Shape of the River: Long-Term Consequences of
Considering Race in College and University Admissions.'' (Joyce
Dopkeen/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Sept. 8, 1998 -- TEN-USOPEN-4, 9-8 -- Third
seed Jana Novotna during her 6-2, 6-3 quarterfinal demolition of
Patty Schnyder, the 19-year-old 11th seed from Switzerland, to
advance to the final four for only the second time in 12 U.S. Open
campaigns. ``I had expected a much, much harder match,'' the Czech
veteran says of the 61-minute romp. (Barton Silverman/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Sept. 8, 1998 -- TEN-USOPEN-3, 9-8 --
Defending champion and third seed Patrick Rafter of Australia
during his fourth round, 6-3, 6-4, 4-6, 6-1, victory over Wimbledon
finalist Goran Ivanisevic at the U.S. Open on Tuesday. Rafter wil
face Jonas Bjorkman of Sweden in the quarterfinals. (Barton
Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Sept. 8, 1998 -- TEN-USOPEN-2, 9-8 -- Ninth
seed Karol Kucera sending eighth seed Andre Agassi crashing out of
the fourth round of the U.S. Open on Tuesday. Following an
overnight rain delay, the 24-year-old from Bratislava, trailed 0-2
down in the fifth set before fighting back to post a 6-3, 6-3, 6-7
(5-7), 1-6, 6-3 victory. (Barton Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Sept. 8, 1998 -- TEN-USOPEN-1, 9-8 -- ``By my
normal standards it's certainly been a bad year,'' eighth seed
Andre Agassi says of his Tuesday loss in the fourth round of the
U.S. Open to ninth seed Karol Kucera, 3-6, 3-6, 7-6 (7-5), 6-1,
3-6. ``I've got to keep it all in context because of how long it's
been since I've even been competitive'' Agassi has won three-time
Grand Slam titles - 1994 U.S. Open, 1992 Wimbledon and 1995
Australian Open. (Barton Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) IN THE JUDEAN DESERT, West Bank -- Sept. 8, 1998 --
ISRAEL-LAND, 9-8 -- Bedouin nomads are the only residents of a
portion of desert that Israel has offered to turn over to the
Palestinian Authority under certain conditions. An American
mediator is to resume talks this week. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) FANWOOD, N.J. -- Sept. 8, 1998 -- NORTHEAST-STORM, 9-8 --
Kathy Westervelt and Jeff Wohlgarth look over the damage caused by
a tree that crushed her car during Monday night's storm. Downed
trees and tree limbs that in turn pulled down overhead wires
delivering power to nearly 300,000 customers in the metropolitan
area were the major and most visible legacices of the line of
violent squalls that swept eastward from Pennsylvania and rapidly
through the tri-state area. (Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) MOSCOW -- Sept. 8, 1998 -- RUSSIA-MIDDLECLASS, 9-8 --
Three weeks into Russia's latest crisis, the good times at the
Chesterfield Cafe - a popular watering hole for Moscow's
high-living young professionals - are already running on empty.
``This is the quietest night of the quietest week,'' says manager
Martin Bainbridge, center, who left London's night club business
two and a half years ago to take part in Moscow's giddy expansion.
(James Hill/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Sept. 8, 1998 -- NY-PRIVATE-DINING, 9-8 --
Michael's Dining Room at Michael Jordan's Steak House in Grand
Central. Off the main dining room, a maximum of six diners may book
a table - there's only one - in a space that, at 8 by 12 feet, is
more like a meditation chamber. The walls, in soothing polished
mahogany, block out the sights and sounds. When the folding doors
are closed, diners can achieve the kind of privacy normally found
in an isolation tank. (Nancy Siesel/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Sept. 8, 1998 -- NY-CROWDED-RESTAURANTS, 9-8
-- Diners at Osteria del Circo squeeze around tables as the
waitstaff attempts to work around them. ``The first question a
restaurateur asks is, 'How many seats can I put in?''' says Adam
Tihany, who designed Osteria del Circo, Le Cirque 2000 and who owns
the restaurant Remi. ``It's the cost of real estate - how much
money can you squeeze out per square foot?'' (Boyd Hagen/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Sept. 8, 1998 -- KITCHEN-WARES, 9-8 -- When
most people think of grilling they think of barbecue, charcoal and
footlong forks. But this time of year, as backyard cooks start
moving back to the kitchen, they have an indoor alternative - a
grill pan. Clockwise from top center: Villaware's Sear-Top pan with
lid, All-Clad's square nonstick pan, 12-inch round iron pan by Le
Creuset, Calphalon's pan with anodized-aluminum surface and a
cast-iron pan by Lodge. (Michael Rogol/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
