<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 23:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4789 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BROWNS-375&AMP;ADD-NY     09-08 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BROWNS-375&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LERNER, WHO HELPED BROWNS LEAVE, IS AWARDED FRANCHISE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Al Lerner, a Brooklyn-born credit card magnate who
helped Art Modell move the old Cleveland Browns to Baltimore in
1996, was chosen unanimously Tuesday by National Football League
owners to buy the new Browns franchise for $530 million, a record
sum for a North American sports franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Lerner defeated a $500 million offer from Charles Dolan, the
chairman of Cablevision Systems, and his brother, Lawrence, a
Cleveland-area lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ask me how it feels to write a check for a pair of
shoes, I could tell you,'' said Lerner, the chairman of MBNA Corp.,
a giant credit card issuer, who is worth a reported $2.5 billion.
``But at this level, it's a unique experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Lerner will make a lump-sum payment for the team, which will be
shared equally by 29 of the other teams, except for Modell's
Baltimore Ravens.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I haven't written the check yet,'' Lerner said in a
conference call from Cleveland after the vote.
</P>
<P>
   In the third ballot of the 30 owners, Lerner was one vote short
of the 23 required for approval. Seven teams were aligned with the
Dolan group, including the Jets, Giants and Ravens. But on a motion
by Modell, the naysayers switched to Lerner. The Oakland Raiders
abstained.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting, in the same airport hotel ballroom where NFL owners
voted to let Modell move to Baltimore, seemed to go on without
resolution as it stretched into the evening. Inside the room,
owners lobbied to continue discussion Wednesday or even next week,
as the focus of their talks centered on the Lerner and Dolan bids.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were very respectful, positive and thoughtful
discussions, based on the positive aspects of both groups,'' said
Paul Tagliabue, the NFL commissioner. ``There was no negative
campaigning.''
</P>
<P>
   Modell, a former friend of Lerner's but now estranged from him,
was expected to speak against Lerner, but did not.
</P>
<P>
   Going into Tuesday's meeting, the league's seven-member
expansion committee considered bids from Lerner, Dolan and Howard
Milstein, the New York-based real estate developer and banker.
</P>
<P>
   But the committee decided early Tuesday not to bring Milstein's
offer, estimated to be at $450 million, before the full ownership.
A fourth bidder, Bart Wolstein, a Cleveland-area real estate
developer, was eliminated Monday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The vote to make Lerner the owner culminates a nearly six-month
process during which the NFL fulfilled its promise to Cleveland to
bring a team back to the city by vote agreeing to bring in an
expansion team, not one relocated from another city.
</P>
<P>
   Seven bidders were originally attracted to the process, but
three dropped out last week before they submitted ``final'' bids to
the league. Since last week, the bids by the Lerner and Dolan
groups were cajoled upward by between $20 million and $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   Of the $530 million Lerner will pay, $54 million will go to the
cost of the $280 million stadium being built on the site of old
Cleveland Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The selection culminated a process that began nearly three years
ago, after Modell announced that he was moving the old Browns to
Baltimore for a revenue-rich deal at a new stadium. Soon after, the
NFL agreed to place a new team in Cleveland, but decided only last
March to make it an expansion team, not one moved from another
city.
</P>
<P>
   It would not be the largest price paid for a team if a reported
$950 million bid by Rupert Murdoch for Manchester United, the
popular English soccer team, is true.
</P>
<P>
   Lerner was a heavy favorite to win a vote Tuesday largely
because of his willingness to pay all or most of the cost of the
Browns in cash. A former bidder for an expansion franchise in
Baltimore, he had the backing of Cleveland Mayor Michael White.
</P>
<P>
   Milstein said he had not thought about whether he would pursue
buying the Washington Redskins if he lost his bid for the Browns. A
$450 million bid was recently made to buy the team and its year-old
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Wolstein was the least well-heeled of the competition, and was
essentially out of the sweepstakes before Tuesday's meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the other bidders, who were in Cleveland or New York,
Wolstein was in Italy. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
