<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4848 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONSOLIDATE-AD-COLUMN     09-08 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSOLIDATE-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: 2 BIG MARKETERS WILL CONSOLIDATE PORTIONS OF THEIR
ACCOUNTS. 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two giant advertisers said Tuesday that they would consolidate
portions of their accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The announcements by H.J. Heinz Co. and Hewlett-Packard Co. are
indicative of the constant consolidations of agency assignments
that have been remaking Madison Avenue for most of the decade. They
are also emblematic of the continuing efforts by large marketers to
focus on brand-building.
</P>
<P>
   Heinz, which has renewed a commitment to spend on advertising
for its grocery products, is looking to consolidate worldwide brand
duties for its Heinz ketchup at one agency. Though billings on the
account, now divided among a dozen shops, were not disclosed, they
were estimated at $150 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``This new initiative will focus our worldwide advertising
behind our flagship icon brand,'' said William Johnson, president
and chief executive at Heinz in Pittsburgh, by developing what he
described as ``a single global brand positioning that generates
excitement and growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Johnson assumed the duties of chief executive last year
from Anthony O'Reilly, he has pressed Heinz to return to its
longtime practice of supporting brands like Heinz ketchup,
Star-Kist tuna and 9-Lives cat food with consumer ad campaigns.
Under O'Reilly, Heinz had reduced ad budgets to pay for promotions
like cents-off coupons and payments to retailers. For instance,
Heinz ketchup was advertised during Super Bowl XXXII in January,
the first time the brand appeared on national TV in almost five
years.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said they believed that the company's strategy of
spending cost savings on consumer campaigns was bearing fruit _ or
vegetables, depending on what you consider the tomato to be.
</P>
<P>
   As part of that renewed emphasis on advertising, Heinz is
unexpectedly consolidating the global ketchup account, a decision
not known publicly until the trade publications Advertising Age and
Adweek reported the move in front-page articles published Monday.
Five agencies were being considered, they reported; Heinz named two
of them as finalists Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The finalists are Leo Burnett Co. in Chicago and the TBWA
Worldwide unit of Omnicom Group in New York. Burnett had long been
Heinz's primary American agency, creating characters like Charlie
the tuna for Star-Kist and Morris the cat for 9-Lives. But Burnett
and Heinz parted ways on American assignments in 1994 after
domestic ad spending had dwindled to $8 million from $65 million in
1988. Burnett has continued as a Heinz agency in Europe and Latin
America on products like seafood.
</P>
<P>
   TBWA, parent of TBWA Chiat/Day, has not worked directly for
Heinz; its newly reorganized British agency, TBWA GGT Simons Palmer
in London, creates campaigns or Heinz/Farley's infant feeding
products in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   The three agencies eliminated from the ketchup review were:
Bates Worldwide in New York, part of Cordiant Communications Group
PLC; DDB Needham Worldwide in New York, a unit of Omnicom, and Euro
RSCG Worldwide in Paris, owned by Havas Advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The Bates British agency, Bates Dorland in London, handles Heinz
ketchup there. The Chicago office of DDB Needham handles Heinz
ketchup in the United States as well as brands like Heinz gravy and
Ore-Ida frozen foods; a sibling, DDB Needham San Francisco, was
named last month as the agency for the Smart Ones line of frozen
entrees and desserts sold by Heinz's Weight Watchers Gourmet Food
Co.
</P>
<P>
   The Euro RSCG office in London was recently awarded a
pan-European assignment to advertise Heinz ketchup. Those
commercials, carrying the theme ``All the world says Heinz,'' began
running last week as the review got under way.
</P>
<P>
   A decision on the ketchup account could come in two or three
weeks, said Ted Smyth, a spokesman for Heinz. Asked whether it
augured similar steps for other important worldwide Heinz brands,
he replied: ``It's too early to say. We are moving to category
management of our big brands, in tuna and weight control. That's
part of this process.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard named Publicis &AMP; Hal Riney in San Francisco, a
unit of Publicis SA in Paris, to handle a consolidated worldwide
branding assignment for personal computers and PC servers. Though
billings for the campaign, to appear in Europe and North America,
have not been determined, Advertising Age estimated them at as much
as $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to crank up the volume on PC's and be a little more
competitive and aggressive,'' said Jan McDaniel, marketing
communications manager for North America at Hewlett-Packard in
Cupertino, Calif. ``Advertising is one of the weapons we'll use.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal reported Tuesday that Hewlett-Packard
would consolidate worldwide duties for PCs and servers, with
billings estimated at more than $200 million, at Publicis, which
handles the PC product account in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McDaniel labeled the report inaccurate because of
suggestions that another Hewlett-Packard agency, the Saatchi &AMP;
Saatchi unit of Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi PLC, would lose all its
assignments to Publicis. Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi San Francisco will
continue working for Hewlett-Packard on such accounts as Unix
servers, she said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the billings estimate, Ms. McDaniel said, laughing, ``If
it is a $200 million account, I need to have a very big promotion
and a raise.''
</P>
<P>
   Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi San Francisco also handles the PC product
account in North America. That assignment, Advertising Age
reported, was likely to move to Riney at some point.
</P>
<P>
   Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi PLC issued a statement Tuesday describing the
loss to Publicis as ``less than 10 percent of Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi
worldwide Hewlett-Packard billings, which are in excess of $100
million.''
</P>
<P>
   Publicis has been aggressively publicizing account gains and
acquisitions to raise its profile among worldwide agency companies.
In this instance, though, the confusion over the Hewlett-Packard
assignment may have been counterproductive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
