<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: AMERICAN EXPRESS CHECKS TO BE ISSUED IN EUROS 
</HEADLINE>
  (duplication warning: also sent with `t' code) 
(bl) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   American Express said Tuesday that it would print
euro-denominated traveler's checks in time for sales to start on
Jan. 1, 1999, the beginning of the European Monetary Union. While
the euro becomes the official currency of the 11-nation euro-zone
Jan. 1, with national currency exchange rates fixed to the euro,
the circulation of euro notes and coins will not begin until Jan.
1, 2002.
</P>
<P>
   During the three-year transition, consumers will be able to use
the American Express euro traveler's checks _ in denominations of
50, 100 and 200 euro _ to pay for goods and services while
merchants begin to convert to euro pricing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect the euro-denominated traveler's checks to be
accepted by local merchants as soon as they begin pricing their
products in euros,'' said Victoria Handwerk, an American Express
spokeswoman. ``But during the transition, American Express
traveler's checks, as always, can be cashed for local currency if
desired at our travel service offices within the euro-zone.''
</P>
<P>
   She also said the euro traveler's checks would enable purchasers
to travel anywhere in the euro-zone without having to worry about
multiple currencies. The euro-zone countries are Germany, France,
Italy, Belgium, the Netherlands, Luxembourg, Austria, Spain,
Portugal, Ireland and Finland.
</P>
<P>
   The new traveler's checks will have a pastel-colored world map
on the front and acceptance instructions in English, French and
German on the back. They will include security features like those
on dollar-denominated checks.
</P>
<P>
   The euro-denominated checks will be available worldwide
beginning Jan. 1, 1999, at American Express travel service offices,
at some financial institutions, exchange bureaus and travel
agencies, including the American and Canadian Automobile
Associations. In the United States, American Express card holders
will be able to order the euro checks by telephone (800 221-7282)
for delivery by mail after the new year.
</P>
<P>
   During the transition, American Express traveler's checks will
also be available in local currencies, and will be valid
indefinitely. But national currencies and national-currency
traveler's checks will not be sold after June 30, 2002, when the
euro will become the only legal currency used in the participating
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Coping With the Strike
</P>
<P>
   While the strike against Northwest Airlines continues to
inconvenience travelers in the Midwest, business travelers appear
to be taking it more or less in stride.
</P>
<P>
   A survey conducted last Wednesday through Friday among corporate
travel managers by the National Business Travel Association found
that 63 percent of those surveyed had been affected by the strike,
but that more than 77 percent had rebooked on other major carriers
in anticipation of the strike.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, 22 percent of corporate travel managers surveyed said
that during the strike they had turned to low-fare carriers, niche
carriers or new-entrant carriers. And of those, more than 65
percent said they would consider moving the rebooked travel
permanently to alternate carriers.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, 57 percent of the travel managers do not want
President Clinton to intervene formally in the strike.
</P>
<P>
   No-Paper Ticketing Abroad
</P>
<P>
   Over the next three months United Airlines plans to extend its
electronic ticketing service to Singapore; three cities in China
(Beijing, Shanghai and Hong Kong); Belgium; France; Germany; Italy,
and the Netherlands. The addition of those 7 nations will bring to
12 the number of foreign countries using United e-mail. Australia,
Canada, Japan and New Zealand were added this year, while Britain
was put on line last October.
</P>
<P>
   United said that the use of its E-tickets, which allow
passengers to board planes without paper tickets, reached an
all-time industry high of 3.4 million last month. During that
month, 56 percent of eligible itineraries were ticketed
electronically, an increase of almost 11 percent over August 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines are reluctant to disclose the exact amount of money
they save with E-tickets compared with paper tickets, because
estimated savings per E-ticket range all over the tarmac. But it is
generally believed that the major airlines save about $10 million a
month each, which of course explains their eagerness to expand
electronic ticketing as far and as fast as possible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
