<HEADLINE>
WORLDLY MANNER A HEAVY FAVORITE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Worldly Manner, a five-length winner in the Best Pal Stakes
earlier in the season, will be a heavy favorite to win the $250,000
Del Mar Futurity for 2-year-olds today, closing day at Del Mar.
</P>
<P>
   If Worldly Manner succeeds, he'll be joined in the winner's
circle by some familiar faces. Owners John and Betty Mabee of
Golden Eagle Farm have won the Futurity four times in the 1990s,
with Best Pal (1990), River Special (1992), Winning Pact (1993) and
Souvenir Copy (1997). Trainer Bob Baffert won the race with Silver
Charm (1996) and Souvenir Copy. Jockey Kent Desormeaux rode winner
Future Quest in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Desormeaux replaces Gary Stevens, who is sidelined following
knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert tries to clinch his second straight Del Mar training
title. With 16 winners, he leads Barry Abrams by one and Bob Hess
Jr. by two. Corey Nakatani has wrapped up his second Del Mar riding
title.
</P>
<P>
   Worldly Manner, a son of Riverman, has won two of his three
starts. He'll be joined in a Golden Eagle-owned entry with unbeaten
Daring General. The seven-horse field for the 7-furlong race
includes D. Wayne Lukas-trained Hidden City, winner of the Ellis
Park Juvenile in Kentucky, and rider Pat Day.
</P>
<P>
   The Del Mar Futurity has sent three of its winners on to
Kentucky Derby victories: Tomy Lee (1958), Gato del Sol (1981) and
Silver Charm.
</P>
<P>
   Fairplex Park opens its Los Angeles County Fair season Thursday
for 18 straight days of racing. First post will be 12:30 p.m. each
day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
