<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NECE NOT FOLLOWING IN DAD'S FOOTSTEPS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ First, Ronnie Lott's son picked UCLA over USC.
Now, he's playing linebacker instead of safety.
</P>
<P>
   Like father, unlike son.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, my dad was kind of surprised,'' Bruins freshman Ryan
Nece said of the reaction to his offseason move from safety to
linebacker. ``The whole family was surprised. Everybody had this
stereotypical picture in their heads about what an inside
linebacker should look like: Dick Butkus.
</P>
<P>
   ``But once I explained what (defense) UCLA ran and why I
switched, they felt it was a good move.''
</P>
<P>
   Nece, an honor roll student, realized playing time was scarce
behind All-American strong safety Larry Atkins and agreed to try
inside linebacker. He was UCLA's most-improved defensive player in
training camp and is currently second-string, behind junior Ramogi
Huma.
</P>
<P>
   What Nece lacks in size _ at 210 pounds, he's tiny for the
position _ he makes up for in quickness and smarts. One of his
first moves was to ask dad for advice, and Lott, the legendary USC
and San Francisco 49ers safety, was happy to oblige.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave me a few tips,'' said Nece, a San Bernardino native
who chose UCLA over Washington because he felt comfortable with the
coaching staff. (USC did not recruit him.)
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing he told me to do was sit on my knees and practice
hitting a wall with my hands (in an upward thrusting motion). That
helped me learn to stay low when I tackle.''
</P>
<P>
   Nece, who uses his mother's maiden name, learned the position
quickly and added 10 pounds of muscle in the offseason. He'll get
plenty of playing time Saturday against Texas, as the Bruins will
rotate nine linebackers in the heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really pleased with Ryan,'' inside linebackers coach
Marc Dove said. ``He keeps elevating his performance with every
practice.''
</P>
<P>
   And if Lott has any complaints, he can take them to his former
position coach at USC _ Bob Toledo.
</P>
<P>
   Injury update: Second-string nose guard Ken Kocher, one of
UCLA's top freshmen, has recovered from a sprained ankle and will
play against Texas. How much _ and when _ will depend on the ankle
and game circumstance.
</P>
<P>
   Low numbers: Don't count on quarterback Cade McNown matching the
numbers posted Saturday by his Heisman competitors. UCLA's run-pass
balance does not allow for 50 attempts, and Toledo won't permit
seven touchdowns (ie: Kentucky's Tim Couch).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to (pad McNown's stats) at the expense of him
getting hurt,'' Toledo said. ``And I'm not going to do it at the
expense of running up the score.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding a spark?: The punt and kick returners have been
established. Freddie Mitchell will handle punt return duties, while
Mitchell, Jermaine Lewis and DeShaun Foster will share the kickoff
returns.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA ranked seventh in the Pacific-10 in kickoff returns last
year and last in punt returns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes down to people,'' Toledo said. ``Great return teams
have great returners.''
</P>
<P>
   Pregame walk: In following a Toledo-era tradition, the Bruins
will arrive at the Rose Bowl at 10:30 a.m. Saturday and immediately
walk through the crowd gathered near the Food Zone in area H.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets our players emotional and gets fans into the game,''
Toledo said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 2313EDT &QL; 
