<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-WOMEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HINGIS MAKES QUICK WORK OF SELES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also TEN-USOPEN) 
(mk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's not that she is jaded: Martina Hingis delights
in winning matches. Any matches, anywhere. But it takes a special
occasion like Tuesday night's 6-4, 6-4 defeat of Monica Seles in
their windblown U.S. Open quarterfinal to provoke the 17-year-old
sophisticate to leap with joy as punctuation to a soul-satisfying
victory.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner had Hingis _ who wore her hair scraped into the
customized Samurai topknot favored by the Open's other defending
champion, Patrick Rafter _ cranked out an ace on her first match
point than she jumped into the air as if she intended to ride a
pogo stick out of Arthur Ashe Stadium. Had a horse been handy, the
avid rider would have leaped aboard it as well.
</P>
<P>
   Just two rounds from a victory that would make her the youngest
U.S. Open champion to mount a successful title defense, Hingis was
in a mood to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   The victory also halted Hingis' two-match losing streak to
Seles, a tiny streak of futility that caused no shortage of
irritation to Hingis, who considers it inexcusable to drop a match
to the same person twice. After absorbing semifinal defeats at both
Roland Garros and Wimbledon this year, a development she terms a
setback when compared to her acquisition of three of the four Grand
Slam crowns in 1997, Hingis has been particularly keen on defending
her turf at this Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I haven't done as well as last year, but life goes on,
and now I'm in the semifinals same as last year,'' said Hingis, who
immediately set her sights on using this semifinal, where she will
face the Wimbledon champion, Jana Novotna, to exact revenge for her
loss to Novotna in that semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   Played in autumnal conditions, the quarterfinal took just 72
minutes and was nudged toward its brisk conclusion by 26 unforced
errors from Seles. Seles had trouble keeping her forehands _
whether she was using her traditional two-fisted technique or the
more flexible but less reliable one-hander she has worked into her
repertory _ within bounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some points where it was hard to control the
ball,'' Seles said of the navigational problems caused by the wind.
``I felt lost this entire tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Seles netted forehands at set point of the opening set and at
break point of the first game of the second set. Though she
reflexively broke right back to put the second set back on serve at
1-1, Hingis broke her again for a 4-3 lead, then held at love for
5-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew coming in that she wanted to win this match really
badly,'' Seles said. ``She raised her level, I went down a notch.''
</P>
<P>
   Not known for her merciful side, Hingis didn't let her childhood
idolization of Seles interfere with her professional domination of
the former No. 1 when their rivalry began in the 1996 Oakland
final.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis ran up her career mastery over Seles to 5-0 before Seles
finally picked a pivotal spot, their 1998 French Open semifinal, to
break out of her slump against the savvy Swiss teenager, who
continues to count the French Open as the only Grand Slam title to
evade her.
</P>
<P>
   Seles, owner of the Roland Garros title from 1990-92, walloped
Hingis by 6-3, 6-2 to end Hingis' winning streak against her, and
when they met two weeks ago in the Canadian Open final, Seles
prevailed in a 4-6, 6-3, 6-2 comeback that trimmed her deficit to
5-2.
</P>
<P>
   According to Seles, whose sixth-seeded position was her lowest
at the Open since she made her debut in 1989, Hingis is a hard
player to knock off course, especially at a Grand Slam where she
has a title defense to inspire her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's really psyched up for it,'' Seles said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
