<SLUG> BC-FBN-CLEVELAND09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lerner awarded Browns; Policy CEO after $530 million bid
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Only two months after he resigned as president of the San
Francisco 49ers to pursue a role with a resurrected Cleveland
Browns franchise, Carmen Policy is back in the NFL. His proven
acumen, perhaps more than the record revenues the Browns are
expected to generate and the additional draft choices they will
receive in their first two years of existence, could translate into
quick success in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was just the first step,'' said credit card magnate Al
Lerner, after he was chosen Tuesday night as the Browns owner.
``But in Carmen, we've got a CEO who has scaled all those other
steps pretty successfully.''
</P>
<P>
   Policy will serve as president and chief executive officer of
the Browns and will own a 10-percent stake in the team. When he
joined the Lerner bid following his departure from the 49ers, the
pair immediately became the unofficial favorites to land the team.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't hurt that Lerner, who once owned 5 percent of the old
Browns, already had put money in NFL owners' coffers by placing
team logos on credit cards. More significant on Tuesday was that
Lerner, 65, also outbid the other suitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning the Super Bowls was tremendous, but this rates right
with them,'' Policy said.
</P>
<P>
   Including a $54 million subsidy for Cleveland's new stadium, the
Lerner bid was worth $530 million. Although far shy of the $1
billion price tag urged by owners Al Davis of Oakland, Jerry Jones
of Dallas and Tampa Bay's Malcolm Glazer, the fee still represents
the most ever paid for a professional sports franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Lerner was the unanimous recommendation of the finance
committee, which considered the bids of three groups.
</P>
<P>
   Brothers Larry and Charles Dolan, whose group included Hall of
Fame coach Don Shula, bid $500 million. The bid of Howard Milstein
was believed to be $450 million.
</P>
<P>
   Owners met for nearly six hours and it took four ballots for
Lerner-Policy to get the 23 votes necessary for approval.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 2315EDT &QL; 
