<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-SWEDES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEDES CARRY CAMARADERIE INTO QUARTERFINAL ROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Bjorn Borg was gliding ruthlessly and quietly
along the baseline, the U.S. Open was the brash and rambunctious
place where Swedes could not win. But Mats Wilander broke the mold
in 1988; Stefan Edberg grinded it into small pieces in 1991 and
1992 and now a new generation of Swedish men is doing more damage
on the hardcourts of the National Tennis Center in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Three of them reached the quarterfinals Tuesday: Jonas Bjorkman,
Magnus Larsson and, most surprisingly, Thomas Johansson. The last
time three Swedes made it this far at Flushing Meadows was in 1985,
when Wilander, Edberg and Joakim Nystrom reached the final eight.
</P>
<P>
   Professional tennis can be a relentlessly individualistic
enterprise, but the Swedes approach it differently. They break
bread together, break down opponents' strengths and weaknesses
together and, on occasion, break training together. Such closeness
is the product of a culture that emphasizes cooperation and
egalitarianism, and it also stems from the fact that it is nice to
speak your own language and understand all the jokes during dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to help each other as good as we can; I mean we're very
good friends, both on the court and off,'' said Johansson, who
upset 11th-seeded Yevgeny Kafelnikov of Russia, 3-6, 6-3, 6-3, 7-6
(8-6), to reach his first quarterfinal in a Grand Slam event.
</P>
<P>
   Bjorkman and Larsson, the pivotal figures in Sweden's 5-0 rout
of the United States in last year's Davis Cup final, are no
strangers to the later stages of their sport's premier events. The
tightly wound and remarkably quick Bjorkman reached the semifinals
here last year, his finest year as a professional, and was also a
quarterfinalist in 1994. According to Goran Ivanisevic, he is best
returner in the game, and Ivanisevic serves hard enough to know.
</P>
<P>
   Bjorkman is unusually extroverted for a Swedish tennis star, and
is one of the star acts at the players' annual talent show in Monte
Carlo because of his ability to imitate service motions. Bjorkman
can rock like Boris Becker and twitch like John McEnroe, and
Tuesday he put on another fine performance, winning by 6-4, 2-6,
6-2, 6-2 over Jan Siemerink, the net-charging Dutchman, who had
beaten him at Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   After soaring to No. 4 in the world last season, Bjorkman had
struggled since reaching the Australian Open quarterfinals in
January, but he has found his form at Flushing Meadows.
</P>
<P>
   So has the absent-minded Larsson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Magnus is the kind of guy who can walk out of the house
wearing two left shoes,'' Bjorkman said.
</P>
<P>
   With his powerful forehand and serve and deceptively lumbering
gait, the 6-foot-4-inch Larsson reached the quarterfinals here in
1993 and again last year. But after celebrating Sweden's Davis Cup
victory in December, his luck began to turn. Shortly after he
returned home to Vaxjo, Sweden, the car he had rented and parked in
front of his house was destroyed by a small bomb. Swedish police
have been unable to determine who planted it, but Larsson's coach,
Carl-Axel Hageskog, believes it was a prank.
</P>
<P>
   Then in January, Larsson fell ill with what he thought was a
virus after playing in a tournament in Qatar. While doctors kept
taking blood tests and finding little that was conclusive, it took
Larsson four months to regain full health and strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``His stomach kept saying no to food,'' Hageskog said. ``He went
into the French Open with no training behind him.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Larsson is on his game, he is one of the opponents that
seeded players least like to face. After upsetting No. 2 Marcelo
Rios in the third round, he kept his concentration in the fourth
round Tuesday against 92d-ranked Oliver Gross of Germany, winning
by 6-4, 7-5, 5-7, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   Bjorkman and Larsson both live in tax-free Monaco, but they both
keep close ties to Vaxjo. Bjorkman grew up there, and Larsson moved
there as a teen-ager. Vaxjo is also Wilander's hometown, and it is
Wilander, not Borg, who has had the biggest influence on this new
generation of Swedes. Bjorkman played at the same club and was 10
when Wilander won the French Open in 1982. Johansson was 7 and came
from a different city, Linkoping, but the impact was the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always been my idol,'' the 23-year-old Johansson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 2316EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
