<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0451 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 23:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4867 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-STEELERS-SHERMAN-     09-08 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-STEELERS-SHERMAN-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COORDINATOR KEEPS PANIC OUT OF THE GAME PLAN
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It would have been easy for Ray Sherman to fall into the trap,
the one that grabs a new coach by the throat and makes him do
things he does not want to do. The one that creates pressure to
make a splash.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knows that Chan Gailey, the new Dallas head coach, used
to be Pittsburgh's offensive coordinator. Few know that Ray Sherman
_ 46 years old, a nine-year National Football League assistant
coach, a former receiver at Fresno State _ replaced Gailey in
Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   It was Sherman's debut on Sunday when Pittsburgh visited the
Baltimore Ravens. The game was a knockdown showdown early, a 3-3
tie at halftime. There Pittsburgh sat with all of those
silky-smooth offensive weapons, sparked by quarterback Kordell
Stewart, and no touchdowns to show for it. The temptation for
Sherman could have been to wing it, to try to bust the game open,
to throw the football and throw it some more and let loose with his
imagination and playbook. Through his coach's headset, to attempt
to create the winning spark with big-play-calling overkill.
</P>
<P>
   But like the Steelers, Sherman stayed cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``We struggled running the ball in the first half, but in the
second half we wanted to keep running it because that's what we are
and that's what we do,'' Sherman said. ``I know that when you get
away from your identity that bad things can happen. The Steelers
had a system intact when I came here, and we want to continue that
system. It's one of those physical offenses where running the ball
takes care of the passing game and helps create it. This team on
offense and defense is just going to hit you in the mouth. That's
our game.''
</P>
<P>
   Hit 'em in the mouth. And that's how Pittsburgh won it, 20-13,
spoiling the Ravens' debut in their new stadium. Of course, they
had plenty of help from the Ravens, especially a botched snap of a
punt that gave Pittsburgh the ball at the Ravens' 5-yard line and
helped set up the game's first touchdown, a 1-yard run by Stewart
that gave Pittsburgh a 13-3 lead with 2 minutes 6 seconds left in
the third quarter. But it was Sherman's steady hand with the
offense that helped the Steelers continue to build momentum.
</P>
<P>
   The Steelers passed 19 times and ran 11 times in the first half.
In the second half, they ran 18 times and passed only 8 times. And
that run-first mentality helped the Steelers set up the Ravens. It
set up a play-action pass _ Stewart faking to Jerome Bettis and
then completing a 20-yard strike into the end zone to receiver
Charles Johnson with 10 minutes left _ that provided the winning
points.
</P>
<P>
   The call was timely. A first-and-10 pass from the Ravens' 20
after three consecutive, powerful Bettis runs of 9, 0 and 1 yards.
The run set up the pass.
</P>
<P>
   Purely the Steelers' way.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were having some success stopping our running game, but
we kept at it with the idea that we could suck them up into the run
and take a shot somewhere along the way,'' Sherman said. ``On that
play, Charles Johnson did a good job of getting free and getting to
the ball and holding on. That game could have easily gone either
way, but it went the right way for us. I learned a long time ago in
this league that you've got to appreciate every victory and cherish
them because they do not come easily. On the road, too, in the
opener? It was special.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It was that way on Sunday, too, for Gailey, as Dallas beat
Arizona by 38-10; for Kippy Brown, as Miami beat Indianapolis by
24-15, and for Jimmy Raye as Kansas City beat Oakland by 28-8.
Gailey calls the plays for Dallas. Brown and Raye are offensive
coordinators calling the plays for their teams. They were among the
newcomers, like Sherman, who won in their debuts while calling the
offensive shots. Each made an impact.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman was the offensive coordinator with the Jets under Pete
Carroll in 1994. His resume includes stops as an offensive coach
with Houston, Atlanta, San Francisco and Minnesota. He came to
Pittsburgh from Minnesota, where for the last three seasons he was
the quarterbacks coach.
</P>
<P>
   When Gailey left for Dallas, Bill Cowher, the Steelers' head
coach, called the Vikings and asked for permission to interview
Sherman. Often in the NFL, head coaches hire assistants whom they
know personally. Something about Sherman intrigued Cowher even
though he did not know him well.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was Sherman's cool, even then.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh is at home against Chicago on Sunday. Another chance
for Sherman to tinker, not toy. ``When I played receiver, I wasn't
a finesse receiver,'' Sherman said, laughing. ``I had to block. I
had to hit 'em in the mouth. I feel right at home here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
