<HEADER>
A4877 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-TV-COX     09-08 0400
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-TV-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fox, WGN also a part of history
 &HT;    By Prentis Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fox wasn't on the air for Mark McGwire's historic 61st homer,
but the network will have its baseball logo on footage of No. 62.
WGN will also have clips with its logo included.
</P>
<P>
   But because Fox was the carrier of the game on ``free TV,'' the
majority of viewers in America heard Joe Buck exclaim: ``Down the
left field line! Is it enough? Gone! There it is! Sixty-two! Touch
first, Mark! You are the new single-season home run king.''
</P>
<P>
   And with that declaration, Buck and his partners Tim McCarver
and Bob Brenly smartly zipped their lips and let the pictures tell
the story for the next four minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes in television you have to lay out, and if ever there
was a time to lay out, that was it,'' McCarver said later in the
telecast. ``When he went to hug Roger Maris' family, Bob and I both
nearly lost it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox certainly captured all the appropriate shots: McGwire having
to go back and touch first base on his historic home-run trot;
getting a hug from Cubs catcher Scott Servais at the plate; picking
up his 10-year-old son Matt and being mobbed by his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   There were the reaction shots of the gracious Sammy Sosa,
including the Cubs slugger leaving his position in right field to
come over and hug McGwire. In fact, about the only shot of
significance that escaped Fox's coverage was the reaction of Cubs
pitcher Steve Trachsel, which should have been shown on replay like
that of Cardinals' manager Tony LaRussa as the ball cleared the
fence.
</P>
<P>
   When the announcers resumed speaking, Buck marked the time as
8:18 p.m. Central Time and said it couldn't happen to a better man;
McCarver noted it did not have the typical height of a McGwire home
run; while Brenly pointed out baseball did not want the homer to
stop the game, ``but the emotion of the moment was too much.''
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth inning, McCarver likened the night to ``the
seventh game of the World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   Reporter Steve Lyons also did his part by interviewing Tim
Forneris, a member of the Cardinals ground crew who retrieved the
ball and commissioner Bud Selig. Buck also gave viewers a reason to
stay tuned by announcing several times McGwire would be interviewed
after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
