<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 23:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4882 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-MAIN09-COX     09-08 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-MAIN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Another un-Madduxlike performance; Braves lose to Expos 6-3
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ For both the Braves and Greg Maddux, life got worse
Tuesday. On a cold, rain-delayed evening in Olympic Stadium, Maddux
gave up four first-inning runs and Atlanta never recovered, losing
6-3 to the Expos.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' fifth loss in six games (and seven of nine) dropped
Maddux's record since the All-Star break to 5-6. His ERA in that
span: 3.34, after giving up six hits and six runs (five earned) in
seven innings Tuesday. While Maddux (17-8) struck out nine and
passed the 2,000 mark in career strikeouts, he also walked four as
Atlanta's September swoon worsened to 2-5.
</P>
<P>
   After a lost weekend in New York, the Braves were determined to
get themselves, and Greg Maddux, back on track. At the All-Star
break, Maddux was 12-2 with a 1.54 ERA, named the NL's starting
pitcher in the All-Star Game and seemed destined for his fifth Cy
Young Award.
</P>
<P>
   But since the break, Maddux had gone just 5-5, with an ERA of
3.06. In two of his last three starts (Aug. 23 against Los Angeles,
last Wednesday against Houston), he'd allowed three homers _ the
first three-homer games of his career. This night, against the
lowly Expos, at least Maddux kept the ball in the park.
</P>
<P>
   He was staked to a quick 1-0 lead on walks to Marty Malloy and
Chipper Jones, a passed ball and Andres Galarraga's grounder which
scored Malloy. Maddux had retired the first Expo before giving up a
single to Terry Jones. He was ahead of Shane Andrews 0-1 when the
drizzle in which the game began became a downpour. Another game,
another rain delay, this one for an hour and 14 minutes. When
Maddux came back out, the chill (game-time temperature: 63, and
falling rapidly), the mound (muddy and slick, later coated with new
dirt) and the Expos all conspired against Maddux.
</P>
<P>
   He walked Andrews. After Chipper Jones let a tough-hop grounder
go beneath his glove for a run-scoring error, Maddux walked Brad
Fullmer. Maddux, two walks in one inning? It got worse. Chris
Widger singled in a run. Maddux forced in a run when, on a 1-2
pitch, he hit F.P. Santangelo in the upper left arm. When Orlando
Cabrera lined another hard single to right, it was 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux finally got out of the inning when he got Expos starter
Miguel Batista looking _ the 2,000th strikeout of Maddux's career _
and Wilton Guerrero on a groundout.
</P>
<P>
   When Andruw Jones' high fly ball kept going and dropped just
over the left field wall in the second, it was the fourth straight
game in which he'd homered. His 29th homer was also his fifth in 18
at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Although Maddux retired the side in order in the second, he had
problems again in the third. He appeared to have trouble with his
footing on the mound. A leadoff walk, two more singles and another
walk scored two Expos for a 6-2 Montreal lead. The rain returned,
worsened, then let up before Ryan Klesko doubled leading off the
sixth and scored on Ozzie Guillen's two-out single to cut it to
6-3.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
