<HEADER>
A4884 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-62-COX     09-08 0235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-62-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McGwire makes home run history
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (a) general news and (s) sports categories.)
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ On a dreamy night in a steamy baseball city, the
sport whose tradition is built largely on numbers introduced
perhaps its grandest Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   No. 62.
</P>
<P>
   Soak it up, America: The mighty McGwire has gone deep one more
time.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis Cardinals first baseman Mark McGwire ripped a fastball
over the left-field fence at Busch Stadium and became the
single-season home run leader, breaking Roger Maris' 37-year-old
record of 61 that most of the baseball world thought would never be
touched.
</P>
<P>
   The homer came off Chicago Cubs right-hander Steve Trachsel in
the fourth inning. It was measured at 341 feet, McGwire's shortest
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The home run and McGwire's pursuit of the record will be
remembered forever. The excitement captured the nation and provided
a rebirth for the sport.
</P>
<P>
   The ball landed in an area underneath the stands and never made
it into the seats. It was quickly picked up by a Cardinals'
groundskeeper and brought to McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   The homer touched off a wild celebration at Busch Stadium.
McGwire pointed to the crowd and hugged his son Matt, his teammates
and members of the Maris family.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
