<SLUG> BC-NJ-TEACHER-STRIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL BOARD ASKS JUDGE TO DISMISS STRIKING TEACHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ROBERT HANLEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREEHOLD, N.J. _ With a New Jersey judge seemingly poised to
start jailing striking teachers in Middletown Township at the
urging of school officials, the school board abandoned that request
Tuesday and instead asked that teachers lose their jobs if the
walkout persists.
</P>
<P>
   After the board shifted its strategy, Judge Clarkson Fisher Jr.
of State Superior Court recessed a contempt-of-court hearing until
Thursday morning, effectively giving the board and the teachers'
union, the Middletown Township Education Association, more time to
resolve a long and bitter contract dispute that prompted the
teachers to walk out on the first day of school last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher seemed ready Tuesday to begin imposing jail terms to
those who have violated a back-to-work order he issued last
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   He rejected arguments by the union's lawyer, Sandy Oxfeld, that
his order was improper and that he had no jurisdiction because the
union had filed an unfair labor practice complaint with the state's
Public Employment Relations Commission.
</P>
<P>
   After a recess, the board's lawyer, Douglas Kovats, disavowed
any jail terms. ''In all candor,'' he said, ``I'm not particularly
concerned with putting anybody in jail.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Kovats asked the judge to order that teachers would
forfeit their jobs by continuing to defy the back-to-work order
once the judge sets a deadline for a return to the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   After Oxfeld asked for more time to prepare a response to that
proposal, Fisher ordered the hearing continued on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the hearing, Diane Swaim, president of the
striking union, told about 500 teachers gathered outside Monmouth
County's Hall of Records here that she was prepared to resume
bargaining Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Other union officials said that night-long talks that preceded
the court session had narrowed differences on a new contract to
replace one that expired in 1996. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
