<SLUG> BC-GOLDMAN-IPO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERT ON BANKING MERGERS AT GOLDMAN, SACHS PLANS TO RETIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON and JOSEPH KAHN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ J. Christopher Flowers, a founder of Goldman, Sachs &AMP;
Co.'s lucrative financial institutions merger practice, said
Tuesday that he was leaving the firm at the end of November.
</P>
<P>
   Flowers' retirement comes at a sensitive time for Goldman: The
firm reaffirmed Tuesday its intention to end its private
partnership and issue shares to the public in November.
</P>
<P>
   Flowers not only counseled Goldman regarding its offering, but
the group he helped build is also one of its most successful. So
far this year his team served as advisers on $197 billion of
domestic banking mergers, nearly half all announced.
</P>
<P>
   Flowers, a 20-year Goldman veteran, not only counseled Norwest
in its planned $34 billion acquisition of Wells Fargo this year,
but he helped defend Mellon Bank when the Bank of New York
announced an unsolicited offer to buy the company.
</P>
<P>
   Flowers' announcement caught some Goldman bankers by surprise,
executives close to the company say. In an interview in July,
Flowers said then that he was not considering retirement, but
indicated he would be interested in other responsibilities at the
firm. ``I've done so many deals that doing the next deal isn't that
important to me,'' he said at that time.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Flowers hoped to be named one of three chief
operating officers responsible for running the investment-banking
unit on a day-to-day basis, several Goldman executives said. But by
early August it became clear that Flowers would not be picked.
</P>
<P>
   The jobs instead went to Mac Heller, Goldman's global mergers
and acquisitions chief, Robert Kaplan, head of corporate finance
for the Americas, and Peter Weinberg, head of global
telecommunications, media and technology banking. Flowers would
also not be named to Goldman's management committee, one of the two
governing entities to be created after the offering.
</P>
<P>
   It was in light of those two decisions by Goldman management
that Flowers, 40, told the executive committee he would retire. The
decision was disclosed Tuesday in a memo to all employees, after
certain clients and employees were told over the Labor Day holiday,
a person close to Goldman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty years is a long time to be at any one place,'' Flowers
said in an interview Tuesday. He did not disclose his plans, but
said he was considering several opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   The firm's co-chief executives and chairmen, Jon Corzine and
Henry Paulson Jr., meanwhile, reaffirmed Tuesday their intention to
pursue the public offering in the fall despite the recent
turbulence in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IPO process is still on track,'' Paulson said in a
broadcast to Goldman employees worldwide, according to people who
watched it. He said that Goldman's decision to go public was
prompted by the need to overhaul the company's ownership structure
and solidify its capital base, a need that was not directly
affected by short-term rises and falls in stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine and Paulson also reiterated earlier statements that
trading losses in volatile emerging markets had a relatively small
effect on the firm's bottom line. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-98 2357EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0465 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4895 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-HUDSON-PARK-600&AMP;AD     09-08 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HUDSON-PARK-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI SIGNS LAW CREATING PARK ON HUDSON 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DOUGLAS MARTIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Saying Manhattan's western waterfront has been an
embarrassment since his days as a young lawyer on Wall Street, Gov.
George Pataki signed a law Tuesday to create a park nearly five
miles long, from Battery Park City to 59th Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``How proud I am,'' Pataki said at a signing ceremony at Pier 25
in TriBeCa that was also attended by Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, State
Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver and community advocates on both
sides.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said that the park was ``one of the very best things we
can do during our period of time in government.''
</P>
<P>
   Construction of the park, which is expected to cost up to $390
million, is scheduled to begin in October and to be finished in
2003.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the work is already under way. A bike path is to run the
length of the park, and the part that passes through Greenwich
Village is already under construction. And Pier 40 is also to be
part of the park, and on Sunday, the governor is to dedicate two
soccer fields on the pier's roof.
</P>
<P>
   The law protects the stretch of riverfront as a park, a status
it never had before, said Marcia Reiss, policy director for the
Parks Council, a research and advocacy group. ``It was a plan
before,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   The project includes the renovation of 14 piers for public use,
the construction of a 4.5-mile waterfront esplanade and swaths of
green space along the river. It also protects river habitat by
creating a sanctuary under the oversight of state conservation
officials. Many kinds of commercial development _ including hotels,
offices and gambling and cruise ships _ are banned. Pataki received
sustained applause when he promised that the park would include a
beach in Greenwich Village.
</P>
<P>
   But there are still significant problems facing the park, which
grew out of a failed plan in the 1970s called Westway, a sunken
freeway that would have run along the Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   The Army Corps of Engineers must issue a permit for any
construction done in the river, and plans now call for rebuilding
some rotting piers and replacing a bulkhead at the river's edge
along the length of the park. Three federal agencies and numerous
opponents of the park have testified that those plans could
endanger fish and other wildlife. One possibility is that their
opposition could result in a lengthy environmental impact
statement.
</P>
<P>
   One of the agencies, the Environmental Protection Agency, said
in a letter to the Corps of Engineers, ``Based upon our review of
the available information, we cannot conclude that the overall
project will avoid adverse effects on the Hudson River.''
</P>
<P>
   Foes of the project were passing out copies of the letter at the
signing ceremony Tuesday, as they pressed their argument that the
law cedes too much authority to what they fear will become an
uncontrollable new public authority bent on commercial development.
They waved signs saying, ``The Bill's a Trick,'' and ``Park Not
Pork.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcy Benstock, who heads the Clean Air Campaign, a longtime foe
of the park, noted that Westway was defeated when it failed to win
approval from the Corps of Engineers, which was worried about the
survival of striped bass. Of New York state's law, she said, ``The
protections are flimsy and riddled with loopholes.''
</P>
<P>
   James Haggery, who supervises permits issued by the Corps of
Engineers for the eastern United States, said there is no timetable
for a decision on the permit. He said the agency would pass along
the concerns of the agencies and critics to the new Hudson River
Park Trust for answers before making a decision.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Albert Butzel, chairman of the Hudson River Park Alliance, a
coalition of 35 environmental and civic groups in favor of the
park, said the issues were considerably different from those
presented by Westway, which involved plans for 200 acres of
landfill in the Hudson. The new park involves none. A leading
opponent of the freeway, Butzel also maintained that the governing
structure of the trust would be far more democratic than most state
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The new trust is to manage the park. It will have 13 board
members, five appointed by the governor and five by the mayor. The
remaining three will be appointed by the Manhattan borough
president in consultation with Community Boards 1, 2 and 4, which
abut the park. Only two of the three community representatives will
be allowed to vote at any one time. To make sure that neither the
mayor nor the governor can push through a measure unacceptable to
the other, eight votes are required to make major decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The trust is also not allowed to issue bonds or condemn
property. The law stipulates that any commercial use of parkland
must go through normal city zoning procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Another hurdle for the park is financing. Although the city and
state have each pledged $100 million to build the park, that is
just a little more than half of the estimated cost.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Fox, who has served as president of the Hudson River Park
Conservancy, the agency in charge of park planning until the trust
takes over, suggests a number of fund-raising possibilities. Among
these are surcharges on property taxes paid by nearby owners, on
the theory that the park will increase the value of their real
estate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
