<DOCNO> NYT19980908.0466 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4897 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SOCIETY-EDITOR-ART     09-08 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SOCIETY-EDITOR-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SOCIETY GROUPIE FINDS THE PERFECT NICHE 
</HEADLINE>
  (duplication warning: also sent with `L' code) 
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What's a nice Mormon girl who grew up in Huntington
Beach, Calif. _ home of shopping centers and surfers _ doing as the
editor of Quest, the Manhattan society magazine that lovingly
chronicles the 10021 set?
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely think there is an irony going on with California
surfer culture and Mormon baggage,'' said Kristina Stewart, the
editor in question, addressing the early influences in her life.
``But that irony was set in motion long before I got here.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ms. Stewart did respond to a request for an interview
with a startled, ``But I'm just a dork from California!''
</P>
<P>
   She is a 31-year-old disarming and nervous workaholic who has
been reading French Vogue since she was 16. So here she is in the
big city, at the dawn of the fall social season, having a very good
time.
</P>
<P>
   There was a party Tuesday night for Bill Blass. There is a party
Wednesday night at Saks for British designers. Thursday there's a
New York City Opera dinner-dance, a Dolce &AMP; Gabbana perfume party,
a Moschino store opening and an art-meets-fashion event at
Bendel's. ``It's a four-fer,'' said Ms. Stewart, who plans to go to
all of them.
</P>
<P>
   In her view, which now matters in certain pockets of the Upper
East Side, New York society is ``a fascinating sandbox'' with ``its
own vocabulary'' but is still welcoming of new languages. ``If it
wasn't,'' Ms. Stewart said, ``it would be like Latin.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stewart talked for a couple of hours the other day in her
downtown office at Meigher Communications, which owns Quest and its
well-dressed sisters, Garden Design and Saveur.
</P>
<P>
   Quest, a 10-year-old monthly, prints 85,000 copies and
distributes the bulk of them free to apartment buildings in the
epicenter of its universe: Fifth and Park Avenues from 60th to 90th
Streets. It also goes free to the Knickerbocker Club, the Harvard
Club and so on. It is sold on newsstands, and some people actually
pay for a subscription.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stewart is just completing her first year as editor, with a
mission to feature hatching socialites. The magazine has no teeth _
Chris Meigher, the chairman of Meigher Communications, describes it
as ``a celebration of New York'' _ but it has generated buzz among
the pretty young things it pays attention to. People like to look
at Quest's real estate ads, the bedrock of its advertising, and the
party pictures.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Ms. Stewart put the young socialite and designer
Alexandra Lind on the cover, posing her at East Hampton's Maidstone
Club, which caused the club to throw a fit because it said Ms. Lind
was using the institution to promote her clothes. Shocking! In
March Ms. Stewart reached into the safer stratosphere when she put
Brooke Astor on the cover of an issue featuring the 400 New York
socialites Ms. Stewart considered the ``Quest 400,'' which people
on the list read avidly.
</P>
<P>
   Now, who is the most interesting person Ms. Stewart left off the
list?
</P>
<P>
   ``Mmmm,'' she said. ``Who can I afford to alienate?'' She
thought for a moment. ``Ivana Trump,'' she finally said, ``did not
find herself here.''
</P>
<P>
   Because?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think she illustrates the best of what society is
about,'' Ms. Stewart said, a tad haughtily. ``There is a
graciousness and a sense of responsibility that comes with having a
high-profile position in society.''
</P>
<P>
   But wait. Donald Trump is on the list.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stewart seemed ready for that. ``He has an interesting
profession and a position in the New York community you can't
ignore,'' she said. And, she pointed out, ``everyone has redeeming
qualities.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stewart, who likes to dance, ice-skate and wear Lilly
Pulitzer and Pucci, described herself as ``definitely a
card-carrying Mormon'' who does not believe in drinking, smoking or
premarital sex. Her religion, she said, ``means a lot to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends say she never touches alcohol on the social circuit, and
that it keeps her vision clear. She agrees, especially when it came
to running around to the clubs with friends when she first came to
New York a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just gave me a little perspective,'' Ms. Stewart said, ``to
be in the environment but not totally of it.''
</P>
<P>
   She was happy to get out of Huntington Beach. ``I think there
was a weather-induced lethargy that hung over the area,'' Ms.
Stewart said. ``I was at odds with the collective psyche.'' She
went to Brigham Young University, her mother's choice, but spent
two summers working at British Vogue, first under Anna Wintour,
then Liz Tilberis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I negotiated this pact with my mom that I would go to BYU if I
could do fun things in the summer,'' Ms. Stewart said. (Ms.
Stewart's mother, a former city planner, now works in private land
development. Her stepfather is the former city manager of Baldwin
Park in Los Angeles County. Her father, a banker, died 12 years
ago.) After college, Ms. Stewart wrote freelance articles, then
spent three summers editing the exceptionally glossy Hamptons
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   She said she knows well the ``ugly aspects'' of society _ ``I'm
aware of bigotry, and that there are women of dependent means and
that there are meal tickets waiting to find them'' _ but won't
dwell on them in Quest. One reason she likes covering the young
rich of the Upper East Side, she said, is because the community is
``conservative and responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stewart adores old society photographs, especially one of
the socialite C.Z. Guest taken by Slim Aarons at a pool in Palm
Beach in the 1950s. It's hanging behind her desk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't get any better than that,'' Ms. Stewart said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
